<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-16 00:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0615 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PARTY-ANIMAL-LADN     04-16 0932
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARTY-ANIMAL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITICS COMPLAIN PROPOSED ROSE BOWL FLOAT WOULD GIVE WRONG IDEA OF
GLENDALE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY LEE CONDON  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   GLENDALE, Calif. _ It's just a basset hound wearing a party hat,
but to Glendale's civic leaders, it's one hot dog.
</P>
<P>
   A battle has erupted over the city's float for the 2000 Pasadena
Tournament of Roses parade.
</P>
<P>
   A majority on Glendale's Rose Float Committee wants a float
dubbed ``Party Animal,'' featuring a sad-eyed basset hound in a
field of flowers.
</P>
<P>
   But a renegade minority on the panel, led by the committee's
president, say it presents the wrong image for the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``The party animal part of it just doesn't reflect what Glendale
stands for,'' Marilyne Wiechmann, president of the Glendale Rose
Float Association and chief opponent of the dog, said Thursday.
``One of the parks commissioners said we'd be the butt of Jay Leno
jokes.''
</P>
<P>
   But Councilman David Weaver, a longtime member of the float
committee, loves the basset hound.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fun. It's a float people will look at and start
smiling,'' Weaver said. ``You need a float that catches the judges'
eyes. I can't imagine someone will look at that float and say
Glendale is going to the dogs.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday the opposition group scored a major victory,
convincing the city's Park and Recreation Commission that the
basset hound float should be junked in favor of something more
appropriate. Getting the city's blessing is, of course, important
because Glendale once again will provide $60,000 of the float's
$90,000 budget.
</P>
<P>
   Weaver is placing discussion of the issue on the City Council's
April 27 agenda. He said the council already has voted to fund the
float and that he does not believe it has the power to overrule the
float committee, which is an independent organization.
</P>
<P>
   City Attorney Scott Howard could not be reached to comment on
the issue.
</P>
<P>
   But Mayor Ginger Bremberg said she is certain the City Council
will have the final say on the float choice because the city is
footing the bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the city's determination which float should be put in
the parade,'' Bremberg said.
</P>
<P>
   Although she's a dog lover with two of her own at home, Bremberg
admits to an anti-``Party Animal'' bias.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't think it suits the dignity of our community,''
Bremberg said.
</P>
<P>
   Weaver said this would be the 88th entry for the city of
Glendale, which is second only to the city of Los Angeles in terms
of entering floats in the parade.
</P>
<P>
   Ann Ransford, a member of the parks commission, called the
basset hound design ``darling.'' Still, she voted against the
float. She said the city pays for the float each year as a way to
promote the city to everyone around the world who watches the
parade.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we're using this as an opportunity to market ourselves to
the world, I'm not sure Glendale wants to say we are a party-animal
city,'' Ransford said.
</P>
<P>
   But she thinks there could be an easy compromise: Keep the dog,
but drop the ``party animal'' title.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's the best solution,'' Ransford said.
</P>
<P>
   Some have argued that the party dog doesn't fit with the
parade's theme &UR;  &LR; _ ``Celebration 2000: Vision of the Future.'' But
Weaver said the dog fits with the celebration part of the theme
even if it's lacking in visions of the future. He said organizers
of the parade already have announced that they have too many
science fiction and outer space floats.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone is doing the next millennium thing. They won't even
accept any more floats that have an outer space theme,'' Weaver
said. ``Everyone is getting hung up on the vision of the future.''
</P>
<P>
   The dog was chosen over 10 other possible floats presented to
the selection committee of the float panel, said Bill Lofthouse,
president of Pasadena-based Phoenix Decorating, which has created
the city's floats for the past 21 years.
</P>
<P>
   Lofthouse said the dog is ``definitely a potential
prize-winner.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be competing with a lot of other more expensive
floats and you don't want it to get lost in the shuffle,''
Lofthouse said. ``You need a hook or a schtick.''
</P>
<P>
   However, he is so frustrated by the current situation that he
might not agree to build the float if the minority on the Glendale
float committee is successful in killing ``Party Animal.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd have to question whether I'd be involved if this
democratic process didn't work,'' Lofthouse said.
</P>
<P>
   He too suggested compromising by changing the name of the float,
perhaps from ``Party Animal'' to something like ``Where's the
Party?''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Leland, director of sponsorship and marketing for the
Pasadena Tournament of Roses, said the dog was one of 300 designs
pre-approved by the tournament officials for the New Year's Day
parade.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tournament has already blessed it,'' Leland said, noting
that the float is consistent with the celebration theme.
</P>
<P>
   Before designs are even pitched at cities and corporations by
outfits like Phoenix Decorating, they have to pass muster with
tournament officials. ``Party Animal'' not only made the cut but
was deemed ``cute'' by the tournament's president.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tournament is a fairly conservative organization,'' Leland
said, adding that the parade does not accept alcohol or cigarette
advertising.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Party Animal'' float was not offensive by their standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't rule it out thinking it was too provocative or unfit
for family viewing,'' Leland said. ``It's a basset hound wearing a
party hat. It's cute!''
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
