u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-RANGERS-GRETZKY-N     04-16 1070
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-RANGERS-GRETZKY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRETZKY INDICATES RETIREMENT IS NEAR
</HEADLINE>
   (sw) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   OTTAWA _ Wayne Gretzky, one of Canada's best-known natural
resources and the subject of great debate, both within his mind and
among those all around him, was saluted on Thursday night in what
may be his last game in his native land.
</P>
<P>
   Gretzky is strongly considering retiring after completing this,
his 20th season in the National Hockey League and his 21st as a
professional. His announcement could come as early as Friday
afternoon at a news conference scheduled at Madison Square Garden.
The New York Rangers will play their season finale on Sunday at
home against the Pittsburgh Penguins.
</P>
<P>
   After Thursday night's 2-2 tie with the Senators, Gretzky
strongly hinted that retirement was close.
</P>
<P>
   ``All indications are obviously pointing that direction,'' he
said. When someone asked if this was his last game in Canada, he
said, ``I'd be lying to you if I said I wasn't close.''
</P>
<P>
   Gretzky spoke at length in a large news conference, with members
of his family present. His blue eyes turned moist a few times, but
he frequently flashed a toothy smile. When the game ended and he
was selected the star of the game, he skated back onto the ice to
take a bow and was called back twice for curtain calls.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a weak decision, believe me,'' Gretzky said.
``I've thought about this for a long time. Unless a miracle happens
either tomorrow or Saturday morning, I'll probably go make it
official.''
</P>
<P>
   When Gretzky added that his decision was ``not 100 percent,''
many reporters responded in chorus with ``99 percent?'' in
reference to the number he wears on his jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Gretzky said he would meet Friday morning with Charles Dolan,
whose Cablevision company owns Madison Square Garden. ``Let's put
it this way, it's going to take a miracle,'' Gretzky said.
</P>
<P>
   Late in the third period, during a television timeout, many in
the crowd of 18,500 began to chant: ``One More Year! One More
Year!''
</P>
<P>
   The public address system then played ``Nobody Does It Better''
while Gretzky skated alone from the Ranger bench, under a bright
spotlight, to the face-off circle while his teammates remained a
respectable distance away. Players from both teams tapped their
sticks on the ice in tribute.
</P>
<P>
   He raised his stick and waved his hand as the fans rose to their
feet for a long, loud ovation. In the stands, fans held signs that
said ``Gretzky Is Hockey'' and ``The Greatest One Forever'' and
``Wayne Please Don't Retire.''
</P>
<P>
   His Rangers teammates seemed pretty certain that the
announcement would involve the word goodbye.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knows how important he is to the game,'' said Kevin
Stevens, one of the older New York players who is closest to
Gretzky. ``As a player, we all know what he has meant to the game.
He is a great ambassador. It's a big blow to hockey. You're losing
a guy who has pretty much put this game where it is at right now.
He probably will play his last game on Sunday.''
</P>
<P>
   When Gretzky took the ice for warm-ups and, later, for the
opening face-off, he was greeted with warm applause but no intense
emotional outpouring. Some spectators wore team jerseys with
Gretzky's name and his 99, from various stops in his career.
</P>
<P>
   The sweaters, as they say in Canada, represented the Edmonton
Oilers, the Los Angeles Kings, the St. Louis Blues and the Rangers.
Several fans also wore the jersey of Team Canada, for which Gretzky
played in several international tournaments, including the 1998
Winter Olympics in Nagano, Japan. During a timeout in the first
period, the television screen on the scoreboard showed Gretzky
sitting on the bench as the speaker system played a song called
``Simply the Best.''
</P>
<P>
   Gretzky's parents, wife and children were here, and so was Gary
Bettman, commissioner of the National Hockey League. One news
report suggested that Gretzky was under pressure from Canada's
prime minister, Jean Chretien, to make his announcement in Canada,
not the United States, where he has played since Edmonton dealt him
to Los Angeles in 1988. Gretzky's face on Thursday adorned the
front pages of most newspapers here, and television stations
carried videotapes of his words and deeds.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's bigger than the prime minister, to be honest,'' said Todd
Harvey, a Ranger forward from Hamilton, Ontario. ``If you were to
have the prime minister go and make a speech and Gretz go and make
a speech, there would be more people at Gretz's speech.''
</P>
<P>
   Chretien could not attend Thursday night's game because he was
attending a state dinner. But he, like most Canadians, discussed
the possibility of the Great One's retiring at 38, with most of his
sport's scoring records and a page in his nation's history book.
The prime minister said Gretzky should play another season.
</P>
<P>
   John MacLean, a veteran player, put it in professional
perspective. ``He has had such an impact, he has done so much for
everybody as far as exposure of the game and bringing salaries
up,'' MacLean said.
</P>
<P>
   In his best season, 1981-82, Gretzky scored 92 goals, but he has
only 9 this season. He has been slowed by age and by a bothersome
injury to a disk in his neck that caused him to miss 12 games.
During his absence, the Rangers went 6-3-3 and played some of their
most spirited games.
</P>
<P>
   When he could play, Gretzky was hit harder and more often by
opposing checkers than was common in his best seasons. Gretzky's
rating of minus-23 in the plus/minus ratio is the worst on the
team. It measures a player's presence on ice when goals are scored
for and against his team, excluding his team's power-play goals.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Brantford, Ontario, on Jan. 26, 1961, Gretzky was a
nationally known athlete in Canada long before he turned
professional, with Indianapolis of the World Hockey Association, in
1978. He, Gordie Howe and Bobby Orr are considered the best players
ever to play in the NHL. All are from Canada, which takes a large
part of its national self-image from the sport.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about his anticipation for Thursday night's game,
Gretzky said: ``I'm going to enjoy it, no question. I'm very proud
of Canada. I love Canada. I'm Canadian.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Among the signs held by the fans was one that showed his No. 99
superimposed over the red maple leaf of the Canadian flag.
</P>
<P>
   Hockey, Gretzky said, is ``everything in this country.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
