<SLUG> BC-FBC-USC-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOWARD GETS PRESEASON HONOR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   USC wide receiver R. Jay Soward has been selected to Playboy's
preseason All-American team as a kick returner. Soward is the only
Trojan selected to the squad, and first since Daylon McCutcheon and
Jim Wren made the team in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was happy I made it,'' Soward said. ``It's a great
accomplishment. I'm a little on the downside because I'm only a
kick returner.''
</P>
<P>
   Soward will travel to Phoenix next month to spend time with the
rest of the All-American team.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll be real fun,'' Soward said. ``I'll be with the top
prospects.''
</P>
<P>
   Grade problems: Freshman tailback Sultan McCullough had his last
practice Thursday after becoming academically ineligible because he
needs to drop a class today.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's done,'' USC coach Paul Hackett said. ``He's going to zero
in and focus on finishing the year the way he needs to finish. I
don't want any guys to be behind the eight ball.''
</P>
<P>
   McCullough, who is already one of the nation's top sprinters,
will miss the USC-UCLA dual meet in May but will be eligible for
the Pacific-10 and NCAA track championships if he enrolls in summer
school.
</P>
<P>
   He had emerged as one of the pleasant surprises of spring
practice, after gaining 99 yards in last weekend's scrimmage.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is one guy that's improved, it's Sultan,'' Hackett
said. ``Can he develop into a first-class runner? All the signs
point yes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I showed them a little bit, but I can do much better,''
McCullough added. ``Right now, I'm not in that great football shape
because I was running track.''
</P>
<P>
   Hackett said about five other players will probably have their
last practices this weekend _ either because they will be
ineligible or because Hackett wants them to concentrate on
academics. At least two of the players are starters.
</P>
<P>
   Soward, Frank Strong and Jason Steen were among those who sat
out practice, but Hackett said Soward would not miss any more
spring practices.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
