<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-MARINERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS SWEEP AS HELLING EXCELS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The Rangers won a game yesterday without Aaron Sele
pitching and without flogging the opposing pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they gutted one out with timely hitting, steady defense
and a hard-nosed pitching performance from starter Rick Helling.
The combination was good enough to give the Rangers their first
sweep at the Kingdome since 1992 in a 4-3 victory in 10 innings
against the Seattle Mariners.
</P>
<P>
   Helling and relievers Tim Crabtree and John Wetteland held the
Mariners to five hits and no walks over 10 innings; the Rangers
played their fourth consecutive game without committing an error;
and they made the most of their nine hits _ six singles and three
doubles.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just can't flog people,'' Rangers manager Johnny Oates
said. ``It's tough to flog people every day and win by flogging
alone. To be considered a good baseball club, it takes two things,
pitching and defense. It's nice to score runs, but you can't do it
day in and day out.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pitching we've got the past few days, the whole team can
feed off that. It's what we've been waiting for. This was a great
series for our pitchers.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers had lost 26 of their past 34 games at the Kingdome
before this series. But the Mariners were without all-star
shortstop Alex Rodriguez for the series, and center fielder Ken
Griffey Jr. missed yesterday's game with an upset stomach.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now Texas is the better ballclub,'' Seattle manager Lou
Piniella said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have a good ballclub, too. It has been tough for us to
win in here,'' outfielder Rusty Greer said. ``It's been tough to
beat them at our place. Hopefully, we can start playing a little
better against these guys because to win your division, you have to
play good against all three division opponents.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers took most comfort in Helling's performance. Their
20-game winner from last season had given up 13 runs in his first
two starts, setting off a tremor that seemed to unsettle both the
rest of the rotation and the entire team.
</P>
<P>
   Helling, the first Rangers pitcher this season besides Sele to
allow fewer than four runs in a start, had some early trouble
yesterday, giving up a two-run home run to David Bell in the third
and a run-scoring double to Butch Huskey in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   But Huskey was the last Mariners batter to reach base. Helling
retired the last 14 batters he faced in getting through the eighth
inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to go a long way to put those first two games
behind me,'' Helling said. ``After my first two starts, I really
wanted to come out and pitch a good game, keep it close and give us
a chance to win. To do it in the Kingdome against a good lineup
like they had reassures me in my mind that those first two games
are behind me.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers' offense also went dormant after taking a 3-0 lead
in the third inning against Mariners starter Jeff Fassero. Mariners
pitchers retired 18 of 22 batters they faced after that until the
Rangers broke through in the 10th.
</P>
<P>
   Lee Stevens lined a single to center off reliever John Halama;
Royce Clayton bunted pinch-runner Tom Goodwin to second; and Luis
Alicea, the offensive hero of the day, brought him home with a
double to right center.
</P>
<P>
   Alicea was a late addition to the lineup after second baseman
Mark McLemore was scratched with a strained leg muscle. He
responded by going 3-for-5 with two runs scored and two runs batted
in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found out right after batting practice I was playing,''
Alicea said. ``I kind of had an idea because Mac was complaining
yesterday about his leg, and he mentioned to me he might not be
able to play. It's a tough role to be in, but you just have to
prepare for it as best you can.''
</P>
<P>
   He did, helping the Rangers come away with what Oates and his
players said was their best all-around game of the season.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
