<SLUG> BC-BBA-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWEEP OF MARINERS HUGE FOR STRUGGLING RANGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ From the manager's office, to the trainer's room and
in most precincts in the visiting clubhouse, the cliched company
line rolled forth in all its majesty after the Rangers completed a
three-game sweep of the Mariners with a 4-3, 10-inning victory at
the Kingdome yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   No, they weren't at all worried about a shaky 3-4 start in their
season-opening homestand.
</P>
<P>
   They knew, without a doubt, that they'd eventually get better
pitching.
</P>
<P>
   No (insert stifled yawns here), a sweep over the Mariners in
this concrete hellhole is really nothing special.
</P>
<P>
   Liar, liar, pants on fire.
</P>
<P>
   Don't let the Rangers kid you. This three-game tourniquet was
huge for a number of reasons. Just ask closer John Wetteland, who
tells the truth, even when it doesn't hurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was real big,'' Wetteland said after striking out two of
the three hitters he faced in a perfect 10th for his third save of
the season. ``Especially since we just don't play well here. I
don't know a team that does.
</P>
<P>
   ``We proved to ourselves that this ballpark can't hold us
either.''
</P>
<P>
   By sweeping the Mariners to open this four-city, 12-game road
trip, the Rangers put that disastrous first week in their rearview
mirror, beat up on a key division rival and found a way to stop the
bleeding, both in their starting rotation and the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   Wounded pysches are healed. Confidence soars. Fans relax. The
sun comes out again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I admit it,'' manager Johnny Oates said. ``I probably let
losing affect me too much, and I don't enjoy the wins as much as I
should.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just know you can't make too much of three wins in a row any
more than you can three losses in a row. You can't get giddy or
you'll get the rug yanked out from under you just like that.''
</P>
<P>
   A lot of good things happened for the Rangers in this series:
the 9 RBI-night for Pudge Rodriguez; outstanding production from
the bottom of the order and the bench; eight solid innings
yesterday from No. 1 starter Rick Helling.
</P>
<P>
   But do not underestimate the part played in all this by the
call-up of little-known reliever Jeff Zimmerman.
</P>
<P>
   Zimmerman got the day off yesterday after pitching four shutout
innings in the first two games of the series. His youthful
enthusiasm, his competitive nature and, most important, his
above-average ability, has been like a Vitamin B-12 shot for a team
desperate for a psychological lift.
</P>
<P>
   ``Immeasureable,'' is how Wetteland sees it. ``When he got
called in that first night \RTuesday\S, we're all sitting there,
remembering our first appearances.
</P>
<P>
   ``He responded so well in his first two games, we had to bring
him up in \Rkangaroo\S court on a case of making the rest of us
look like idiots.''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing has put a smile on Oates' face like the way Zimmerman
pitched Tuesday and Wednesday nights.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing what somebody who comes in and pitches just four
innings can do for a team,'' Oates said. ``It's not just what I
see. I hear the talk in the clubhouse and how it's changed since he
arrived. I heard it when we left Texas, and it definitely has a
different tone now.''
</P>
<P>
   Oates' biggest challenge _ other than to resist the temptation
to overuse Zimmerman _ may be in juggling his bullpen to be sure
the former TCU right-hander is in the right role.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't write it in stone that he's going to be pitching middle
innings all season,'' Oates raved after Zimmerman had worked 22/3
innings of perfect relief of John Burkett for the win Wednesday
night. ``He's too valuable for that role.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way he's throwing the ball right now, I can't be using him
as a long man. I want him to be available for the seventh and
eighth innings. Somebody else may have to take the long-man role.
He's passing some people right now.''
</P>
<P>
   It's fine for a team to believe it's good. At some point, it has
to actually prove it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the atmosphere ever actually got heavy,'' said
Mark McLemore, who sat out yesterday's game with an aching tendon
behind his knee. ``I just think we're starting to come together,
starting to execute.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a lot of road games ahead of us, and we need to play
well.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe to the Rangers, this was just another series (don't
believe it).
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, to them, winning three in a row in the Kingdome really is
nothing special (of course it is).
</P>
<P>
   But back in Texas, where fans were watching anxiously for signs
of life, I have a feeling this little sweep couldn't have come at a
better time.
</P>
<P>
   Now we can settle in and get on with the season.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
