<SLUG> BC-RAC-LONE-STAR-OPENS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESERT AIR CAPS TEXAS-SIZED NIGHT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY MOSS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAND PRAIRIE, Texas _ It was a Texas beginning to a Texas-sized
celebration last night at Lone Star Park at Grand Prairie.
</P>
<P>
   The track began its third thoroughbred season with perhaps the
fastest Texas-bred in training, 4-year-old colt Desert Air, winning
the Premiere Stakes for his Texas owners. Seven of the next eight
races also went to horses owned by Texas residents. And that
followed Charley Pride's rendition of the national anthem in his
decidedly Texas style, and the on-track unfurling of the University
of Texas' giant state flag.
</P>
<P>
   The state celebration went off theme only once _ and for a
dachshund instead of a racehorse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not quite sure where Brutus The Skydiving Dog fit in
there,'' Lone Star general manager Corey Johnsen said of one of the
pre-race promotions, ``because I'm fairly certain he's not a
Texas-bred.''
</P>
<P>
   On-track attendance (13,171) and betting ($1.1 million) on Lone
Star races were down more than 10 percent from opening day a year
ago. Johnsen said he isn't concerned that will be a trend. He
believes some fans stayed home to do taxes, or opted to attend the
races on Sunday to watch 1998 Kentucky Derby winner Real Quiet
compete in the Texas Mile.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could tell it's the third year for us, because things have
gone much smoother,'' Johnsen said. ``I felt good about the
enthusiasm in the crowd. Texas pride is what it's all about here.
Our fans take pride in our racetrack like fans take pride in a
sports team, and that separates us from some other tracks.''
</P>
<P>
   Desert Air, owned by the Houston-based Mt. Brilliant Stable,
started the parade of Texas victors by leading from start to finish
to win the 1 1/16 mile Premiere by 2 3/4 lengths under jockey Corey
Lanerie.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Three Sox finished second, and Best Dressed Truck was
third.
</P>
<P>
   Desert Air set a fast pace and was weaving in and out through
the stretch, at one point drifting out in the path of Chief Three
Sox. But he had enough left to prevail as the odds-on favorite in
1:44.85, and paid only $3.40 to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was hoping there wouldn't be a \Rsteward's\S inquiry,''
Lanerie said of the stretch run. ``He just got there. He was the
best horse tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Winning trainer Mike Stidham said he hoped Desert Air's victory
was a harbinger of good things to come for his strong stable, which
also sends out Desert Air's full brother, Desert Demon, in Sunday's
Lone Star Derby. Sure enough, Stidham struck again in the fifth
race with Autumn Dancer, another heavy betting favorite.
</P>
<P>
   Desert Air could have run against Real Quiet in the Texas Mile,
Stidham said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But my philosophy has always been to try to put my horses
where they can win,'' he said. ``I thought he could win here, but I
didn't know if he could win that other race.''
</P>
<P>
   Lone Star's reworked one-mile dirt surface, which includes an
influx of a fir-bark additive, met with good comments from the
jockeys.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lot better,'' said Ronald Ardoin. ``It's staying
together better. It's not as powdery and `cuppy' as it has been. So
far, it's staying tight.'' / nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
