<HEADLINE>
MAVERICKS EXTEND WINNING STREAK TO 2
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Two nights after dumping the San Antonio Spurs, the
Mavericks had to struggle just to beat a Minnesota Timberwolves
team playing without starters Kevin Garnett and Terrell Brandon.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Finley didn't have to fend off Garnett's long arm, and
as a result his season-high 34 points paved the way for the
Mavericks to eke out a 101-95 triumph over Minnesota last night at
Reunion Arena. The Mavericks will take a two-game winning streak
into tonight's game against the Phoenix Suns at America West Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Finley scored 26 of his points in the second half. In the first
two games against Minnesota, both losses, this season, he scored a
total of 17 points, with Garnett mostly shadowing him.
</P>
<P>
   But with Garnett back in Minneapolis with the flu, Finley had a
field day.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're missing your best offensive player and one of your
best defensive players, we have to use that to our advantage,''
Finley said. ``We weren't going to roll over and play passive just
because he wasn't playing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew without him they might have come out with a little
more energy. So our main thing was just to get a win, with or
without Kevin.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks (13-25) led by 14 points in the first half, but
squandered it all and nearly let the game slip away. A Joe Smith
hook in the lane got Minnesota within 97-95 with 19.3 seconds
remaining.
</P>
<P>
   But Finley drilled two free throws shortly thereafter, A.C.
Green intercepted James Robinson's inbounds pass, and a pair of
free throws by Hubert Davis with 11.2 seconds left closed out the
scoring.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody knows what Kevin means to this team,'' said Smith,
who scored 21 points and grabbed nine rebounds. ``But we have 10 or
12 other players that can go out and play.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks are 2-17 against the top eight teams in the
Western Conference. Plus, this is just the sixth time the Mavericks
have scored 100 or more points in game this season, and they are
5-1 in those instances.
</P>
<P>
   ``Give \Rthe Timberwolves\S a lot of credit,'' Mavericks coach
Don Nelson said. ``They really hung in there tough and made it very
difficult for us. Thank goodness we found a way to win it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy to get two in a row at home against two pretty good
teams.''
</P>
<P>
   This was the first game of a three-games-in-three-days set for
the Mavericks.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota lost despite collecting 18 offensive rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could have played better,'' Gary Trent said. ``We won the
game, but we didn't play as good as we should have played. ]
</P>
<P>
   ``That's exactly why we have so many close losses. We get a team
down, and we get them on the ropes, and we don't knock them out. We
give them breathing room to recover to where they get back in their
stance and make it a game again.''
</P>
<P>
   Trent finished with 22 points and nine rebounds, Steve Nash had
11 points and six assists, and Shawn Bradley collected 10 points,
nine rebounds and four blocked shots.
</P>
<P>
   Former Mavericks forward Dennis Scott, who played for the
Mavericks from Sept. 24, 1997 until Feb. 18, 1998, scored 18 points
on 7-of-12 shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Scott was 3-of-4 from 3-point range, and shot from beyond
halfcourt. But it was waved off because he released the ball a
split-second after the end of the third period.
</P>
<P>
   worse than starting a six-game, eight-day trip with a loss,''
Nelson said. ``I'm just real pleased to somehow scratch that win
out.''] / nn
</P>
</TEXT>
