<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CLAIBORNE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUESS WORK FOR CLAIBORNE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The NFL draft is nearly here, but instead of
winding down and relaxing a little bit, Chris Claiborne is busier
than ever.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday morning, he was still fielding calls from teams and
coaches via cell phone, and just trying to stay abreast of the
latest news.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marshall Faulk just got traded,'' Claiborne said, aware that
the Indianapolis Colts had traded their top tailback, and would
probably select Texas running back Ricky Williams with the fourth
pick in the draft.
</P>
<P>
   There had been plenty of speculation that the Colts would take
Claiborne, but as the former USC linebacker has learned, nothing
seems certain when it comes to the draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``New developments every day,'' Claiborne said.
</P>
<P>
   This much is certain: Claiborne will be one of the day's highest
picks, expected to go anywhere from sixth to 10th in Saturday's
draft.
</P>
<P>
   Wherever he gets selected, Claiborne will simply be relieved
that the hectic process that started in January, when he declared
he would turn pro, finally concludes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been work. A lot of work,'' Claiborne said. ``I didn't
know what to expect.''
</P>
<P>
   He has worked out for teams, had doctors pull and tug on his
body, taken mental tests and been grilled by NFL coaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``They ask you stuff about your background and family. Things
they might have heard. It's more like a rumor-mill thing,''
Claiborne said.
</P>
<P>
   The endless questions might have bothered Claiborne, but he did
so many interviews at USC this season, it's become second-nature to
talk about himself regarding virtually any subject.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the best thing about going to SC. All of the
exposure,'' Claiborne said. ``It prepares you for this. I don't
mind it.''
</P>
<P>
   As numbing as it can be to have NFL teams scrutinizing every
detail of your life, it hasn't changed Claiborne's mind about
whether he made the right decision to turn pro.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to go to the league and play ball,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Just in case, however, USC coach Paul Hackett wouldn't mind
having him for another season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would take him back,'' Hackett joked this week. ``Can you
back out of that? Is there some legal thing you can do?''
</P>
<P>
   There were similar sentiments among USC fans who congratulated
Claiborne during last Saturday's spring scrimmage, when he came to
watch his former teammates.
</P>
<P>
   But the sideline is about as close as he'll get to being a
Trojan anymore, so Hackett will have to be satisfied with the
Butkus Award he keeps on his desk. It's a reminder that Claiborne
was considered the top college linebacker last season, not to
mention the top linebacker in this year's draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel he'll be an impact player for the next several years,''
said Bears director of player personnel Mark Hatley.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago has the seventh pick, and Claiborne is one of a handful
of players the Bears have on their short list of potential
selections.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, Claiborne doesn't really care where he goes, but
he spends as much time as possible scanning mock drafts on the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I spend a lot of time. A lot of time. Everybody says you're
going to go here or going there,'' Claiborne said. ``I look at
everything. I listen to (sports-talk radio).''
</P>
<P>
   He's learned not to worry about the mock draft projections,
though, taking advice from one of his best friends, former USC
cornerback Brian Kelly, who went through a similar experience last
year before being selected by Tampa Bay.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `You're just going to go where you're going to go,'''
Claiborne said.
</P>
<P>
   Claiborne wouldn't mind being the eighth pick, which would make
him an Arizona Cardinal. He likes the idea of living in Phoenix,
which would keep him close to his mother in Riverside, and his
father, a Marine gunnery sergeant in Japan who is about to be
transferred to Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what he will do with his first paycheck, Claiborne said,
``(Buy my mom) a house and another car.''
</P>
<P>
   While Claiborne was a unanimous All-American and claimed
virtually every individual honor possible, he also knew that some
NFL teams would ask him about the Sun Bowl, where USC lost to Texas
Christian University, 28-19.
</P>
<P>
   Claiborne seemed a step slow in the game, and admitted afterward
he had gained too much weight during the month of December. But he
said he has allayed fears about that performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``They asked about the game, but I had 13 tackles,'' Claiborne
said. ``I played middle and outside linebacker in that game, so I
showed I can play two positions.''
</P>
<P>
   As for his size, Claiborne said he is back to his optimum
playing weight of 250 pounds, and even added a little muscle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just toned up. I'm 250 pounds,'' he said. ``I've been
working out at Gold's Gym.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, all he has to do is collect the gold.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
