<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-HATCHER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS PREPARE FOR DEFENSEMAN'S SUSPENSION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Colin Campbell, the NHL's director of operations
and chief disciplinarian, has scheduled a 1 p.m. meeting today in
New York with Stars captain Derian Hatcher and general manager Bob
Gainey _ a sign Hatcher could receive a suspension of four or more
games for a hit that broke the jaw of Phoenix Coyotes center Jeremy
Roenick on Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   In NHL protocol, players are typically called in for
face-to-face meetings only when suspensions are for four games or
more.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I know is he's not going in there for a holiday,'' Stars
coach Ken Hitchcock said of Hatcher. ``We're preparing to play
without him on the weekend.''
</P>
<P>
   If suspended four games, Hatcher would miss the Stars' return
match with the Coyotes at 3 p.m. tomorrow in Phoenix, and the
regular-season finale on Sunday at Colorado. Hatcher would also
miss the Stars' first two playoff games against Edmonton.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars argue Hatcher shouldn't be suspended, even though
Roenick likely will miss the remainder of the playoffs with a
broken jaw and a broken thumb. Coyotes general manager Bobby Smith
said yesterday Roenick would take months to recover from jaw
surgery and added that a slash by Stars defenseman Craig Ludwig
earlier in the game resulted in a broken thumb that alone would
keep Roenick out for three to four weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars contend the hit on Roenick was no worse than a hit
Roenick delivered to Mike Modano in a March 23 game in Phoenix,
causing the Stars center to leave the game with a lacerated eyelid.
Roenick wasn't suspended at that time because Modano returned to
play the next game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty much been clarified I didn't hit him with my
elbow, I hit him with my shoulder. I guess the unfortunate thing is
I did come off my feet a bit,'' Hatcher said of his hit on Roenick.
``It's a play that happens throughout the course of the game, and
it happens in a lot of games.''
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes contend Hatcher's hit was worse because it was a
premeditated attempt to get even for the hit on Modano.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no premeditation,'' Hatcher said. ``If you can find
me a quote in any paper that says we were going to get Jeremy or
that said I was going to get him, then find them and show them to
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock said the lack of a suspension of Roenick was
disappointing, but said his team was not out to even the score.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt strongly, very strongly that there should have been
closure right after the hit on Modano,'' Hitchcock said. ``That
upset a lot of people.''
</P>
<P>
   Hatcher has a history concerning suspensions, which Campbell
might take into consideration. Hatcher was suspended four games
during the 1998-99 preseason for punching St. Louis Blues
defenseman Chris Pronger in the back of the head. Hatcher also was
suspended two games in the 1992 playoffs for breaking the jaw of
the Detroit Red Wings' Kevin Miller in a stick-swinging incident.
</P>
<P>
   The decision likely will be the biggest Campbell has faced since
he replaced Brian Burke as the league's chief disciplinarian over
the summer. Burke shied away from suspensions that cost any player
time in the playoffs, including not suspending San Jose's Bryan
Marchment after a hit that knocked the Stars' Joe Nieuwendyk out of
last season's playoffs. However, Campbell has been more aggressive
with his suspensions after an edict handed down by Commissioner
Gary Bettman to reduce hits to the head.
</P>
<P>
   On Nov. 23, Campbell issued a 12-game suspension to Los Angeles
Kings' forward Matt Johnson for a blow to the head of Rangers
defenseman Jeff Beukeboom. It was the longest suspension in the NHL
since 1994.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Campbell issued the statement: ``The league has
made it clear that deliberate blows to the head _ particularly
those which cause injury to the head of an opponent _ will be
treated severely.''
</P>
<P>
   The loss of Hatcher might compound problems on defense for the
Stars. Defenseman Richard Matvichuk is struggling with a sore groin
that has kept him sidelined for 14 of the past 15 games. Defenseman
Sergei Zubov is expected to miss tomorrow's game in Phoenix with a
bruised wrist. The Stars have recalled defenseman Petr Buzek from
the Michigan K-Wings on an emergency basis so they can be sure to
have six healthy defensemen for tomorrow's rematch with the
Coyotes.
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock said Matvichuk and Zubov will be ready to play when
the playoffs begin on Wednesday or Thursday against the Edmonton
Oilers at Reunion Arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to look at it as an injury, just like any player,''
Hitchcock said of Hatcher's possible suspension. ``We'll take
whatever happens and move ahead. It's no different than Pat Verbeek
or Roman Turek being injured.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
