<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS NOT ASKED TO FUND FACILITY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Dodgers representatives met with members of the Fort
McDowell Indian Community just outside of Scottsdale on Thursday,
but Yavapai tribal members didn't ask the Dodgers to help fund the
proposed $30 million spring training facility.
</P>
<P>
   Questions were raised in a published report that said tax money
raised with a county surcharge on rental cars would be exhausted,
possibly until 2017 instead of 2010. Such a surcharge would be used
to help pay for the construction costs.
</P>
<P>
   But Fred Coons, the Dodgers' director of business development,
said the subject was never broached during the day-long meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``My guess is they could probably self-fund this entire
package,'' Coons said. ``But at the same time, if they can get some
public funding ... they could get a better return on their
investment. ``I think they're looking at all the financial
packages. It's how can we put our heads together and see what's
available at the city, county and state level. I think everything
is OK. It's just a question of timing of the funds.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yavapai tribe's original funding plan called for private
money, loans and public funding to be used. While the projected
loss of public funding changes how the spring training complex
would be funded, Coons said it shouldn't change the tribe's ability
to fund the project.
</P>
<P>
   Coons, Dodgers president and CEO Bob Graziano, the club's
secretary and general counsel Sam Fernandez and director of ticket
marketing Bob Wymbs met with Yavapai representatives, including
president Bernadine Boyd.
</P>
<P>
   Coons also said the Dodgers would be reluctant to help with the
funding unless the tradeoff was a more lucrative revenue split with
the Yavapai Tribe, which owns the land the proposed complex would
be built on.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our preference would be not to (help fund it),'' Coons said.
``The primary reason (to meet) was to get back together. We didn't
talk anything specifically about contributions.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Vero Beach (Fla.) and Indian River County continue in
their attempt to get $20 million worth of funding to keep the
Dodgers in Dodgertown, their spring training home for 51 years.
</P>
<P>
   The Florida legislative session ends May 5, and Coons said the
Dodgers may hear something from Vero Beach as early as April 26. He
said it would take a few weeks for the Dodgers to digest the
information, and then negotiations with Vero Beach and Fort
McDowell would heat up.
</P>
<P>
   Side work for Hundley: Dodgers catcher Todd Hundley and
third-base coach Rick Dempsey, a former big-league catcher, were
out on the field before batting practice working on Hundley's
throwing mechanics.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents have stolen 10 bases with Hundley behind the plate.
Hundley's thrown out no one.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Hundley) was standing up there a little bit back there,''
Dodgers manager Davey Johnson said. ``Instead of firing out and
staying low, his technique has been muscling.''
</P>
<P>
   It's something the Dodgers noticed in the spring, but Hundley's
workload was slowed because of his reconstructed right elbow. Now
that he's been able to catch more and is in the routine of catching
a few days in a row, the Dodgers are able to work with him on the
side.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a few small things,'' said Johnson, noting most of the
bases were stolen off the pitchers. ``Out of the 10, (Hundley had a
chance) on a couple.''
</P>
<P>
   Perez vs. lefties: Dodgers left-hander Carlos Perez said it was
merely coincidence he gave up four runs in the seventh inning in
both of his starts this season. The latest came Wednesday against
Arizona, and afterward Johnson said he was mistaken for not yanking
Perez sooner, noting Perez looked fatigued because he was getting
his pitches up.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said the same thing happened to Perez in his first
outing, when he allowed a three-run homer to left-handed hitting
Todd Helton. Against the Diamondbacks, lefty David Dellucci had the
game-winning single.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to start working more on my slider,'' Perez said.
``That's not good giving up hits to lefties. When the season starts
I used to lose my first two or three starts and then I go and win
five or six. Maybe it's the same thing this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Not including pitchers, lefties are 4 for 15 (.267) with two
homers and six RBI against Perez.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
