<HEADLINE>
BROWNBACK'S VIEW ISN'T OFF BASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Although Sen. Sam Brownback took predictable flak for saying
abortions contribute to Social Security's problems, the
conservative Kansas Republican was more on point than most
Americans realize.
</P>
<P>
   As a strictly economic matter, Social Security's long-range
funding problems have been exacerbated to the extent that abortions
have reduced the population below what it would have been in the
absence of these abortions. This is a fact of economic life because
Social Security's basic problem is that its pool of beneficiaries
is increasing while the relative number of taxpayers supporting the
system is shrinking.
</P>
<P>
   There are many explanations for economic problems. In Social
Security's case, the explanation is demographics. While the effect
of abortion over a generation's time can't be precisely measured,
it can be said with certainty that abortions have made future
funding problems more challenging than otherwise would have been
the case.
</P>
<P>
   The math is simple. A half-century ago, there were about 16
workers for each Social Security beneficiary. Today there are just
over three workers for each beneficiary, and within another
generation's time, the ratio will fall below two workers for each
beneficiary.
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, older Americans are living longer not only because
they're healthier, but also because of ready access to health care
made possible by Medicare, which incidentally faces the same
demographic problem as Social Security. This trend will continue,
which makes it remarkable that proposed Social Security solutions
don't focus more on the need to encourage population growth.
</P>
<P>
   Some may contend that Brownback's view overstates abortion's
effect because abortion doesn't thin the potential population
enough to be a significant factor. This sounds plausible, but it
doesn't take that many more babies to make a substantial
difference.
</P>
<P>
   A recent article by two leaders of the pro-family movement in
/{The Weekly Standard/}, a conservative magazine, estimated that an
additional 100,000 children born in any single year would
contribute an additional $24.3 billion in Social Security taxes
over a working lifetime. If U.S. marital fertility were to return
to 30-year-ago levels, they said, the additional births in one year
would add $274 billion to Social Security's future revenue stream.
</P>
<P>
   The irony of this insight, they noted, is how it traces its
intellectual roots to the work of Gunnar Myrdal. The Swedish Nobel
laureate economist, they said, understood how old-age benefits
socialized the long-term benefits of having children.
</P>
<P>
   Before governments became increasingly responsible for the
elderly's economic welfare, large families were the key to parental
old-age security. Nowadays, however, the need is for more and more
children to pay future taxes into a government-run pension pot.
</P>
<P>
   While noting Myrdal's sympathies toward socialism, the article
said today's conservatives might characterize policies promoting
larger families as ``supply-side'' family policy.
</P>
<P>
   The only other alternative, if benefits are to be maintained at
current levels, is to continue increasing Social Security taxes to
the point of devastating the economic fortunes of our children and
grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
