A0680 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STAY-RESOLVE-2TAKES-K     04-16 0665
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAY-RESOLVE-2TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE DEATH IN THE BALKANS COULD TEST PUBLIC'S RESOLVE, POLLSTERS
SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT CANON  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) _ They come, like war itself, in sporadic bursts _
events that at once mold American opinion even as they test U.S.
resolve for saving Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   First it was wave after wave of ethnic Albanian refugees. Next
were images of three captured and battered American soldiers. And
this week, NATO's own planes blasted Kosovar refugees on the run.
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, polls reveal, public opinion gradually has
mounted in favor of ever stronger action in Yugoslavia. Keep the
bombs coming, Americans tell pollsters. Send in ground troops to
wrap this whole thing up, they say.
</P>
<P>
   Still...
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't gotten to crunch time yet,'' said Martin
Sletzinger, the director of East European studies at the Woodrow
Wilson International Center for Scholars.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are almost guessing at their own opinions now.''
</P>
<P>
   So will America have the patience and stomach for months and
months of war in the Balkans?
</P>
<P>
   The test of American resolve, if it comes, pollsters say, will
occur when reserve forces are yanked from their civilian jobs, when
U.S. troops tiptoe through Serb mine fields, when flag-draped
coffins are flown back to the States.
</P>
<P>
   Casualties won't necessarily doom domestic support for overseas
conflict, pollsters say. Rather, public opinion will turn on myriad
factors, including how troops are killed, perceptions of the
chances that bombs and bullets can succeed and how Americans'
emotions are shaped by events yet to come.
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, polls attempt to gauge the country's willingness to
sacrifice lives to protect Albanian Kosovars.
</P>
<P>
   In a typical poll last week, ABC News tried to gauge the depth
of support for sending in ground troops. Nearly 60 percent
supported the move, but that figure dropped to 44 percent if ``some
soldiers would be killed.''
</P>
<P>
   It dropped again, to 37 percent support, if there were a chance
of up to 100 casualties, to 31 percent if there were a chance of
500 dead, and finally down to 26 percent if up to 1,000 soldiers
might die.
</P>
<P>
   ``But this is the military. They are soldiers. They sign up to
fight and die for their country,'' said Benjamin Barber, a
political science professor at Rutgers University. ``That's what we
have the military for.''
</P>
<P>
   Karlyn Bowman, who studies public opinion at the American
Enterprise Institute, is skeptical about polling on hypothetical
deaths.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course you might expect some drop-off in support with
casualties,'' she said. ``But we don't know how quickly the deaths
would come or how.''
</P>
<P>
   If, for instance, several soldiers were killed because they were
acting on foolish orders, she said Americans might become skeptical
of the Pentagon's ability to direct the war. But if U.S. troops
were tortured, Bowman and others said, that might ignite rage at
home and cement support for continued fighting.
</P>
<P>
   ``The conventional wisdom is that the American people have no
stomach for a war that lasts a long time,'' said Doris Graber, a
scholar of political communication at the University of
Illinois-Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``That overlooks the years and years we tolerated Vietnam before
frustration set in.''
</P>
<P>
   But this is not 1968.
</P>
<P>
   ``Times have changed since Vietnam in part because people don't
want to go through that again,'' said Lee Miringoff, director of
the Marist Institute for Public Opinion. ``Americans were also
spoiled with the Gulf War. It was quick and decisive.''
</P>
<P>
   Miringoff argues that Americans will not have much patience for
an extended, far-off war that holds still-uncertain objectives for
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything has to be quicker,'' he said. ``It's the times
we're in.''
</P>
<P>
   Pollsters agree most Americans hold still-pliable opinions about
the Kosovo conflict, but they also say it's hard to compare the war
to historical models. MORE
</P>
<P>
   historical models.
</P>
<P>
   Is this 1930s Europe, where delays might have allowed genocide
to proceed? Is it 1960s Southeast Asia, a quagmire with little
promise? Or is this the Middle East of the early 1990s, where
decisive action can force a despot into retreat?
</P>
<P>
   ``Americans generally either want to act decisively or get
out,'' Bowman said. ``People say that if we're going to be involved
then we have to win _ if we know what winning means here _ and get
out.''
</P>
<P>
   Americans haven't yet forecast the odds for Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have a clear understanding that there are Kosovars in
deep trouble and that we have an obligation to do something,'' said
Andrew Kohut, director of the Pew Research Center for the People
and the Press. ``They're less certain about what.''
</P>
<P>
   That uncertainty means that public opinion could prove fickle.
</P>
<P>
   Recent polls, for instance, show wide ranges on the issue of
whether to send in ground troops. Although support has been rising,
with 73 percent in one poll last week backing the move if it was
the only way to stop fighting, only 41 percent in a poll also taken
last week wanted Americans helping Europeans in a ground assault.
</P>
<P>
   ``This whole thing is just suddenly upon us, and that has people
confused,'' said Jean Johnson of the Public Agenda think tank
devoted to studying public opinion.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see this on foreign policy on issue after issue. People
are not going to think strategically like a foreign policy analyst
might. They just want to know: Is it the right thing to do? Is it
going to work?''
</P>
<P>
   People are learning as they go.
</P>
<P>
   In a Los Angeles Times poll conducted March 25, 63 percent of
respondents didn't know which side the United States is supporting
in the conflict. A Pew poll conducted the same week found that most
people couldn't name Kosovo as the Yugoslav province ``where there
is conflict between Serbians and ethnic Albanians.''
</P>
<P>
   But the showdown in Kosovo also has grabbed America's interest.
A continuing survey by the Pew Research Center of attention paid to
news events found in late March that 74 percent of Americans were
following the war ``very closely'' or ``fairly closely.''
</P>
<P>
   That's slightly more attention than was paid to the stock market
crash of 1987 and slightly less than the federal government
shutdown in 1995 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
   That hothouse of close scrutiny of an exotic subject, said
California pollster Don Dixon, nurtures a softness of public
opinion that could affect how President Clinton responds to the
crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just a few weeks ago Clinton was ahead of public opinion'' in
terms of proposing American military action. Now, with the call for
ground troops, ``public opinion is ahead of him.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But if he commits to a ground war and we're stuck in a
protracted guerrilla conflict,'' Dixon said, ``public opinion could
leave him very quickly.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-16-99 0119EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
