r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEC-BUSINESS-KAN &LR;      04-16 0855
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEC-BUSINESS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRUCTURE OF COMPANY IS VITAL TO SUCCESS, EX-PORSCHE CEO SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE STAFFORD  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Kansas City, Mo.) _ The car is pronounced POR-sha, not porsh.
Once he cleared that up, Peter Schutz could focus on his primary
business lesson.
</P>
<P>
   The former president and chief executive of Porsche-AG, who led
the automaker from a money-losing to a profit-soaring operation in
the 1980s, shared some of his turnaround tips this week with a
group of Kansas City area CEOs.
</P>
<P>
   Tops on his list was the admonition to scrutinize their
organizational structures. The right structure will help a company
compete and prosper in fast-changing environments, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Schutz, who operates Harris &AMP; Schutz Inc., a management
consulting company based in Florida, spoke to a chapter of The
Executive Committee meeting in Lee's Summit. TEC is a national
organization of CEOs from midsize companies. Members meet in small
groups once a month to share experiences and learn new strategies.
</P>
<P>
   According to Schutz, the functional organization chart, in place
at many companies, creates conflict. It burdens individuals with
conflicting job titles and conflicting responsibilities that aren't
possible to satisfy.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Schutz outlined a standard organizational chart:
CEO at the top and four vice presidents reporting to him or her:
VP-sales and marketing; VP-production and product development;
VP-personnel management and human resource development; and
VP-accounting, finance and information systems (and maybe legal,
too).
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime you see sales and marketing in the same job, you can
count on the fact there'll be no true marketing in that
organization,'' Schutz contended. ``What they call marketing will
consist only of sales support activities.''
</P>
<P>
   Schutz said sales was a production and administration function,
designed to sell current products or services and meet current
customers' needs. Managing sales well requires a full-time
commitment.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, Schutz said, marketing is an entrepreneurial
function, designed to anticipate customer needs. It must be ahead
of market changes, he said, instead of reacting to them.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Schutz said, managing daily production is a full-time
job that leaves no time to adequately address product development.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you ask a vice president of production to help change the
company, you'll get change through cost cuts and quality
improvement of existing products,'' he said. ``You will not get
innovation, because production is not an entrepreneurial
function.''
</P>
<P>
   Ditto for other job titles that mix running-in-place functions
with planning-for-the-future functions, Schutz said.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who have production roles in their codes have to take
care of daily business, of existing customers; therefore, they're
incapable of dealing with visions for change,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Schutz said such functional organizations had two big negatives:
They're slower to change and they lose their entrepreneurial-minded
people to competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Schutz said he had guided several client companies through
transitions from functional organizations.
</P>
<P>
   He cautioned the CEOs that such transitions took time and must
include better communication, more mutual respect among all workers
and a shared understanding of how to pull together. That's a big
change from many standard corporate hierarchies, which inhibit the
flow of information and foster turf-protection battles, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Companies that prosper will be the ones in which everyone
understands the common goal: to make money by being their niche
market leader.
</P>
<P>
   Schutz said there were several alternative organization charts.
One he suggested had a CEO at the top (because someone still has to
make final decisions) and four persons reporting directly to the
CEO.
</P>
<P>
   These people would have slightly different job titles and
responsibilities from the vice presidents in the old functional
organization chart. The new chart might include:
</P>
<P>
   A chief operating officer, who leads sales, production,
administration and personnel.
</P>
<P>
   A chief administrative officer, who leads accounting,
information systems and legal.
</P>
<P>
   A chief development officer, who leads marketing, product
development and financial.
</P>
<P>
   A human resource officer, who leads training and staff
development.
</P>
<P>
   The first two positions must be held by people who are excellent
at leading daily business demands. The latter two positions must be
held by forward-thinking individuals who see that diversity _
social and philosophical _ is the best tool a company has, Schutz
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``A CEO must focus his or her best people on making money in a
market niche and give them the freedom and authority to do what it
takes to meet that goal,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``A CEO must separate administrative and entrepreneurial duties.
No one can do a good job at both at the same time. If you're stuck
in a production and administrative organization, and change is
going on, your best people will be out the door, and you'll be out
of business.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
