<HEADLINE>
NATION'S DRUG CZAR PRAISES KC AREA TREATMENT PROGRAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE LAMBE  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Kansas City, Mo) _ The United States has made dramatic progress
against illegal drugs, but the struggle is constant and endless,
the nation's drug policy director said Thursday during a visit to
Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   Barry McCaffrey, director of the Office of National Drug Control
Policy, praised Jackson County for innovative efforts and called
for more prevention and drug treatment in the nation's communities
and prisons.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kind of things you're organizing here will actually
work,'' he told a gathering of prosecutors, police, court and
social workers at a Country Club Plaza restaurant. ``It takes
time.''
</P>
<P>
   McCaffrey said that in 1979 about 14 percent of the U.S.
population used illegal drugs. Now he said about 6 percent still
use drugs and he wants to reduce that to 3 percent in a decade.
</P>
<P>
   But that will mean stopping methamphetamine, which McCaffrey
called ``the worst drug to ever hit America.''
</P>
<P>
   Methamphetamine is plentiful in about a half-dozen states,
including Missouri. Meth and other drugs that users make at home
with toxic chemicals and legal precursor drugs will be big threats
in the next century, McCaffrey said.
</P>
<P>
   Prevention programs and treatment are important, he said, and he
praised Jackson County for such efforts as its anti-drug tax, Drug
Court and coordinated treatment efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Drug courts have spread nationwide since Jackson County's
started in 1993. It allows minor offenders to avoid jail if they
complete a year of drug treatment, counseling and job training.
</P>
<P>
   McCaffrey also called the county's new Family Drug Court ``bold,
creative new thinking.'' Drug-addicted mothers in the program must
complete treatment or risk losing their children to foster care.
</P>
<P>
   He also noted that the vast majority of those in prison had
abused drugs or alcohol and should be seeking treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri Corrections Director Dora Schriro told the group that
the state had increased prison drug treatment beds from a few
hundred to about 3,000 in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   A study this year showed that 15 percent of the state's rapidly
growing prison population were drug offenders. It also showed that
many judges were sending drug users with no prior records to
prison.
</P>
<P>
   Schriro said her department in one year has helped establish 154
treatment providers statewide. She said they will give rural judges
an option besides prison and help monitor drug use by parolees.
</P>
<P>
   But McCaffrey told the group that community efforts were the key
to cutting illicit drug use.
</P>
<P>
   ``We stay at it,'' he said. ``We do the kind of things this
group has put together.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
