<SLUG> BC-KMBA-CRACKDOWN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KANSAS CRACKING DOWN ON MORTGAGE BROKERS, HIGH-RATE MORTGAGE
LENDERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TED SICKINGER  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) _ Kansas legislators are putting new teeth into state
regulations for mortgage brokers and high-rate mortgage lenders,
hoping to curb minor infractions and outright lending abuses that
have proliferated with the growth of both activities.
</P>
<P>
   The measures recast the state's laissez-faire approach toward
the industry but stop short of protections adopted in other states
and those recommended by trade groups in Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1996, Kansas has required mortgage brokers to register
with the state bank commissioner's office, but little else.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you had $100 and could fill out a form, you could be a
mortgage broker,'' said A.W. Pickel, president of Leader Mortgage
and past president of the Kansas Association of Mortgage Brokers.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Bill 241, effective last week, places new bonding
requirements on brokers and gives the state banking commissioner
new powers to punish brokers who are in violation of the code.
</P>
<P>
   Mortgage brokers are independent contractors who can arrange
home loans through a wide variety of lenders. Because they offer a
wider choice of loan products, they can usually find the best and
cheapest loan to meet customers' needs.
</P>
<P>
   It's a booming business. Since the state registration statute
passed, more than 500 individuals and companies have signed up to
broker mortgages in Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   More than 67 percent of those registered, however, have no
office in the state, according to regulators. They are out-of-state
companies that solicit business through telemarketing, direct mail
or the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, because brokers had no formal licensing, educational
or certification requirements in the state, regulators had little
control over their activities.
</P>
<P>
   According to Kevin Glendening, deputy state bank commissioner in
Kansas, the bulk of consumer problems cropping up are relatively
minor. A broker might not be registered. Or a poorly organized
broker might fail to follow through on commitments to clients,
situations that are hard to remedy when operators have no financial
stake in the state.
</P>
<P>
   As the number of brokers has increased, however, so have
instances of outright consumer fraud. Problems include
``steering,'' where brokers automatically send customers to lenders
who pay the highest finder's fee; the arrangement of loans with
excessive interest rates and fees; and the improper disbursement of
clients' loan proceeds.
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas Association of Mortgage Brokers maintains that the
``few bad apples'' in the industry are primarily out-of-state
operations. Consequently, it has been a vocal proponent of beefing
up requirements, even to the point of mandatory education and
certification.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the Legislature adopted several amendments to the
1996 law, including requirements for out-of-state brokers to post
$100,000 surety bonds or meet a minimum net worth requirement of
$50,000, with lesser such requirements for in-state brokers.
</P>
<P>
   The amendments also give regulators the authority to fine
brokers for infractions of the code and issue cease-and-desist
orders to those doing business without a license. They also force
brokers to establish escrow accounts and keep more-detailed records
on the disbursement of clients' funds.
</P>
<P>
   The new regulations don't match the specific educational or exam
requirements in such states as Illinois, Ohio, Arizona and
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't eliminate the fly-by-night ... operator,'' said
Michael Richmond, president-elect of the Kansas Association of
Mortgage Brokers. ``There are plenty of big shops out there
treating consumers unfairly that would have no problem posting a
bond.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's a beginning to regulate our industry, to at some
point pass legislative powers for education requirements. This
keeps people from flocking into the state for a hundred bucks.''
</P>
<P>
   On another front, the House and Senate passed a bill last week
mandating new disclosures for consumers who get high-rate and high
loan-to-value mortgages _ those in which the interest rate exceeds
12 percent or the loan exceeds the value of the collateral.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Bill 301, which is awaiting the governor's signature,
also eliminates balloon payments and negative amortization on
high-rate loans.
</P>
<P>
   Both occur when consumers are left with a large lump-sum payment
at the end of their loan term _ sometimes higher than the original
loan amount _ that they are forced to repay in full or refinance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
