</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-CURVEBALL-DEMISE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CURVEBALL IS GOING OUT OF STYLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nolan Ryan could throw a fastball close to 100 mph, but always
insisted many of his 5,714 strikeouts came on the curveball.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hitters would be setting up for that fastball,'' former
pitching coach Tom House said. ``Then he'd break off one of those
curves. The hitter would see that ball coming at his head and
freeze, then all of a sudden it would break over the plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``See ya. We called it his Good Night, Irene.''
</P>
<P>
   There are other names for the pitch. The Hook. Snapdragon.
Deuce. Uncle Charlie. Lord Charles.
</P>
<P>
   It is has long been an American institution. What Little League
pitcher doesn't dream about throwing his first curveball and have
that hitter look bewildered?
</P>
<P>
   ``I was 11 years old when I first started throwing mine,''
Rangers pitcher Aaron Sele said. ``But it was under very tight
restrictions. I was allowed to throw one per game.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, the curveball may take on another name.
</P>
<P>
   Extinct.
</P>
<P>
   This great American pitch, famed in song and story, is going out
of style, replaced by other breaking pitches such as the slider,
sinker, split-finger fastball, cut fastball and knuckle curve.
</P>
<P>
   Only three pitchers on the Rangers throw a genuine curveball:
Sele, John Wetteland and Mike Munoz.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even that is unusual,'' Rangers third baseman Todd Zeile said.
``Most staffs you're likely to find only one guy who throws a real
curve.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Rangers pitching coach Dick Bosman: ``The number of people
who throw it is very low, and it's getting less and less. It's a
very difficult pitch to learn to throw. \RPitching coach\S Sid
Hudson, God bless him, tried everything he knew to teach me to
throw a curveball and couldn't do it. I don't even teach it unless
a guy comes to me first and wants to learn it.''
</P>
<P>
   The slider has become the preferred breaking ball of
major-league pitchers because it's easier to learn and easier to
control. It breaks tighter and sharper.
</P>
<P>
   The curveball goes from ``12 to six,'' starting out high and
dropping down low as it breaks. Because of the unusual angle of the
pitch, it's much more difficult to throw for a low strike,
especially with today's smaller strike zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to control both the distance and the direction,''
Sele said.
</P>
<P>
   Said Wetteland: ``It's a difficult pitch; you have to stay with
it constantly. The upkeep is huge. I have to throw mine a ton just
to get a feel for it. Once you start throwing a slider, your
ability to throw a curve lessens because the muscles it takes to
throw both are completely different.''
</P>
<P>
   There is also the danger if a pitcher throws a hanging curve, a
hitter is likely to deposit it somewhere in the outfield seats.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to have a good one or it gets hit hard,'' Zeile
said.
</P>
<P>
   The curveball can also be hard on an arm. Steve Stone won 25
games and a Cy Young Award in 1980 for the Baltimore Orioles but
was never the same pitcher again. He admitted he overused the curve
that year. Former Orioles reliever Gregg Olson had an outstanding
curve but started having serious arm troubles.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had flexor problems and forearm problems because of the way
he threw it,'' Bosman said. ``He got sore quicker and didn't
recover quicker, and pretty soon there were large concerns about
his health.''
</P>
<P>
   Olson averaged 32 saves per year between 1989-93 before having
arm troubles. He had 13 saves over the next four years. Olson made
a comeback last year with Arizona, saving 30 games, but has
struggled this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd guard against throwing a breaking ball pitch until you're
15 or 16 years old,'' Wetteland said. ``If your bones and muscles
aren't developed, you run the risk of certain types of calcium
deposits.''
</P>
<P>
   That's probably wise advice but also disappointing for so many
Little Leaguers who can't wait to throw their first snapdragon.
</P>
<P>
   ``They probably don't know the difference between a curve or a
slider,'' Wetteland said. ``They just want to see the ball break.''
</P>
<P>
   Naturally. / nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
