<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-16 01:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0698 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-RANGERS-ZIMMERMAN     04-16 0484
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-ZIMMERMAN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ZIMMERMAN RECEIVES PRAISE FOR EARLY WORK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Johnny Oates has seen Esteban Loaiza this spring. He
has also seen Jeff Zimmerman.
</P>
<P>
   After Zimmerman's first two major-league outings, Oates is
convinced the right-hander from TCU is no Loaiza.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't put his name and Loaiza's in the same sentence,'' Oates
said. ``He's passing some people right now. From what I've seen in
spring training and now, I'm impressed.''
</P>
<P>
   Oates was especially impressed after the Rangers' 9-6 victory
over Seattle on Wednesday at the Kingdome. Zimmerman replaced
starter John Burkett in the fifth inning and retired eight
consecutive hitters, putting a halt to the Mariners' attack and
allowing the Rangers to mount a comeback.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was in a perfect world,'' Oates said. ``He was able to get
us to our short guys... This is why we needed a 12th pitcher, but
little did we know how good he would be. He's pitching like he's
been here his whole life.''
</P>
<P>
   Zimmerman's only complaint was that the first batter he faced,
Jay Buhner, hit a sacrifice fly to give the Mariners a 4-3 lead.
But the Rangers came back, tying it in the sixth inning on Juan
Gonzalez's sacrifice fly and going ahead on Tom Goodwin's
run-scoring single in the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   That allowed Zimmerman to earn his first major-league victory
with the eventual help of John Wetteland's fourth save.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was kind of bittersweet,'' Zimmerman said. ``I came in with
a runner on base, and I didn't want to let him score. But I fell
behind Buhner and gave him something to hit, and he got it in the
air. I was disappointed I didn't do my job there, but it worked
out.''
</P>
<P>
   Zimmerman made his major-league debut Tuesday, throwing 12/3
scoreless innings in the Rangers' 15-6 victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't feel as good as I did the night before,'' Zimmerman
said. ``I don't think I had the same velocity, and I couldn't go
after hitters as much. I had to hit my spots and change speeds
more.''
</P>
<P>
   The bottom of the Rangers' order _ Todd Zeile, Lee Stevens,
Royce Clayton and Goodwin _ provided most of Texas' offense. They
were 8-for-16 with four walks, three stolen bases, seven runs
scored and four runs batted in.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at our order, we're batting at the bottom because
we have so many great hitters in the lineup,'' Stevens said. ``When
the big guys are not driving in runs, we're there to pick up the
slack. There's definitely a pride factor.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez, batting with the bases loaded, might have done more
damage with his sacrifice fly, a long drive to deep center. But Ken
Griffey Jr., raced back and made an over-the-head catch to hold the
Rangers to one run.
</P>
<P>
   The two teams combined for 28 hits and Zimmerman was the only
pitcher to go more than one-third of an inning without giving up a
run.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
