<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-CASSTEVENS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANYTHING IS POSSIBLE WHEN JOHNSON PITCHES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID CASSTEVENS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - They opened the roof for a reason at Bank One
Ballpark. With Randy Johnson pitching anything can happen.
</P>
<P>
   The sky's the limit.
</P>
<P>
   What's he liable to do?
</P>
<P>
   Pitch a shutout?
</P>
<P>
   Flirt with a no-hitter?
</P>
<P>
   How many will he strike out tonight _ 10, 12? Last start he
fanned 15 Braves.
</P>
<P>
   No pitcher in the game today stirs expectations and generates
more excitement than the tall lanky figure who stood on the mound
at Bank One Ballpark Thursday night, ball hidden in his left hand,
a scowl on his face, menace in his heart.
</P>
<P>
   What would happen?
</P>
<P>
   A big disappointment, that's what.
</P>
<P>
   After losing three in a row to the Diamondbacks the Dodgers took
out their frustration with an 8-1 victory that spoiled Johnson's
home debut.
</P>
<P>
   Two home runs. A triple. As the visitors merrily circled the
bases in the fourth, fifth and sixth innings the picture of the
dejected lefthander brought to mind something Buck Showalter said
the other day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Randy's not perfect. He's human. He's not a robot,'' the
manager reminded.
</P>
<P>
   Some games he will be overpowering.
</P>
<P>
   Some nights trying to hit Johnson's fastball will be like trying
to drink coffee with a fork.
</P>
<P>
   Other nights he will make mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the most part, I pitched bad,'' Johnson said flatly. He
smiled at the assembly of media huddled around his cubicle. ``No
point pulling the wool over you guys, huh?''
</P>
<P>
   The major league strikeout leader fanned 10. He struck out six
of the first 10 batters. But the Big Unit lasted only six innings
and when he walked with his head bowed to the dugout with his team
trailing 7-1 the only person who felt worse than he did was
Showalter, sick with the flu.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks didn't hit. They committed three errors.
Johnson's outing was the poorest of his three starts.
</P>
<P>
   This wasn't how he had envisioned his home debut. Pitching for
the first time at BOB meant more to him than pitching on Opening
Day when he threw seven strong innings against the Dodgers and left
the game with a 6-2 lead.
</P>
<P>
   He was keyed up. Perhaps too much so. His first seven pitches
were balls.
</P>
<P>
   The beginning of the end cameGf the fourth. Gary Sheffield,
waving his black bat like a windshield wiper, drove a pitch into
Diamondbacks bullpen to give the Dodgers a 2-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Next inning Eric Young lashed a triple over rightfielder Tony
Womack who stood there momentarily, as if he didn't see the ball.
Mark Grudzielanek then deposited a Johnson offering over the
right-centerfield fence, near the swimming pool.
</P>
<P>
   It is ironic that Johnson's first game at home came against the
Dodgers. Last July Lisa Johnson was in Seattle watching ``Oprah''
when a news bulletin crawled aross the bottom of the screen _
``like one of those storm warnings,'' her husband said at the time.
The station reported that Johnson had been traded from the Mariners
to the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   Frantic, Lisa reached Randy by phone just before he boarded a
plane in Baltimore. The TV report proved to be wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle traded Johnson to Houston where he put the Astros on the
cover of Sports Illustrated. ``Houston, We Have Liftoff.''
</P>
<P>
   This wasn't the launch Johnson had envisioned in Arizona. But
there will be better nights. `` I figure I'll get 34 starts and
half of them will be at home. If I pitch 15 bad games'' _ Johnson's
smile said that wasn't likely _ ``then I may be looking to pitch
for some other team.''
</P>
<P>
   No chance of that. He is one of the game's premier attractions.
A fastball pitcher with an attitude.
</P>
<P>
   ``The psychological edge you get when you're taking charge on
the mound is important. Let a fellow know you're mean and he's
going to be a little leary. The mound is no place for charity.''
</P>
<P>
   Randy Johnson could have said that, but he didn't. Former Dodger
Don Drysdale did. In 1960. &QL; 
David Casstevens can be reached at (602) 444-8635 or at
david.casstevens(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
