r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-COWBOYS-ISMAIL-TE     04-16 0879
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-ISMAIL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS SIGN ISMAIL, BUT IRVIN MAY BE ON TRADE BLOCK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Clarence E. Hill Jr. 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ The signing of free-agent Raghib Ismail was one
of several developments at wide receiver for the Cowboys yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   The Ismail deal, for seven years and $21 million, including a $5
million signing bonus, was completed when the Cowboys received a
signed contract from Ismail's agent, Jack Mula, about 5 p.m.
yesterday by fax, perhaps a fitting way to end the monthlong
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys owner Jerry Jones also announced that the team would not
match the $1.25 million offer sheet that restricted free-agent
receiver Patrick Jeffers signed with the Carolina Panthers, ending
the former Fort Worth Country Day star's stint with his hometown
team after one season.
</P>
<P>
   But the biggest news of all heading into this weekend's NFL
draft might be that league sources have confirmed that the Cowboys
are willing to listen to trade offers for Michael Irvin, the team's
all-time leading receiver.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys owner Jerry Jones denied that Irvin has been included in
any trade talk.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just not right,'' Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   Another team official also denied it, saying, ``What would we do
for receivers without Irvin?''
</P>
<P>
   Irvin, 33, a 12-year veteran, had little comment about the trade
talk, saying ``that's fine.'' Irvin is in the final year of his
contract, which comes after a frustrating 1998 season, when he led
the team in receptions for the eighth consecutive season with 74
passes but caught only one touchdown pass.
</P>
<P>
   Still, his loss would be a major blow to the Cowboys' offense,
considering he is the team's only proven star receiver and coach
Chan Gailey's penchant for multiple-receiver sets. Additionally,
it's unlikely that any of the top receivers in the 1999 draft would
be available when the Cowboys select at No. 22.
</P>
<P>
   The addition of Ismail came about, in part, because of the
Cowboys need for a speed receiver to help discourage opponents from
the double-team tactics used so effectively against Irvin last
season.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys' main off-season priority was to acquire a quality
speed receiver to make plays opposite Irvin. Ismail, a former Notre
Dame football and track star who will turn 30 on Nov. 18, became
the target after career-best numbers of 69 receptions for 1,024
yards and eight touchdowns in 1998. His previous season-best was 36
catches in 1997 with the Panthers.
</P>
<P>
   ``He limits the things opponents can do if they are trying to
take away one guy because he's a guy you have to double as well
because of his speed,'' Cowboys receiver coach Dwain Painter said.
``He's a home-run threat any time you put the ball up.''
</P>
<P>
   A six-year veteran in the NFL, Ismail began his professional
career in the CFL in 1991, playing two seasons with Toronto before
joining the Raiders in 1993. He has played with the Panthers the
past three seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Gailey said he was impressed with Ismail's attitude as well as
his athletic ability.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously he is a great talent,'' Gailey said. ``He has
excellent speed, and he will make big plays. Those are things we
look at, the speed, the big- play ability and his attitude. He
wants to come in and be a part of the process.''
</P>
<P>
   Why the process of signing Ismail took so long is still unclear.
The two sides say they are just happy to get it done.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very pleased,'' said Mula, who indicated that Ismail
probably wouldn't make it to Dallas until next week. Mula said
Ismail's wife, Melani, who is pregnant with their third child, is
not feeling well.
</P>
<P>
   Jones is happy the Cowboys were able to get the deal done in a
cap-friendly way. In 1999, Ismail's base salary is $400,000, and he
counts just $1.1 million against the cap.
</P>
<P>
   Jones has given out $21.5 million in signing bonuses to Ismail,
quarterback Troy Aikman ($13 million) and center Mark Stepnoski
($3.5 million) in the past week. However, he is not through, saying
``the push'' is on to complete a deal with linebacker Quentin
Coryatt before the draft begins tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to be working late to get something done,'' Jones
said.
</P>
<P>
   Regarding the Jeffers decision, Jones said it was simply a
salary-cap issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted him on the team,'' Jones said. ``We basically looked
at it with disappointment. We thought he could contribute for us
this year. But we felt that amount of cap room would be better used
on some other part of our football team.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeffers, who caught 18 passes for the Cowboys last season,
becomes Carolina's highest-paid receiver. However, he is expected
to be the Panthers' third receiver behind starters Rae Carruth and
Muhsin Muhammad.
</P>
<P>
   In other free-agent news, the Cowboys have shown interest in
former St. Louis Rams quarterback Tony Banks. The Baltimore Ravens
are also in the running for Banks.
ROCKET FUEL
</P>
<P>
   A breakdown of free-agent wide receiver Raghib Ismail's contract
with the Cowboys: $5 million signing bonus 1999 base salary:
$400,000 2000 base salary: $500,000 2001 base salary: $1.6 million
2002 base salary: $3.5 million 2003 base salary: $4 million 2004
base salary: $3 million 2005 base salary: $3 million The last two
years are voidable
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
