<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-MILLER-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILLER SHOWS HE'S AN IRON MAN  
 CATCHER QUIETLY PUTS IN OVERTIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD OBERT  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Damian Miller once went a stretch of catching 30-some
games, but never a game in which he caught 16 innings.
</P>
<P>
   He did that Tuesday when the Diamondbacks and the Los Angeles
Dodgers played into Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was way past my bedtime, so I don't remember what I was
doing,'' Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   Catchers are normally drained after nine innings, both
physically and mentally. In the later innings of the marathon,
Miller, while his team was at bat, put heat pads on tightened
hamstrings to loosen them.
</P>
<P>
   He was back behind the plate Wednesday for nine innings and
again Thursday night and went 1 for 3 in the Diamondbacks' 8-1 loss
to the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   Miller isn't complaining about the work load as Kelly Stinnett
heals from a deep quadriceps bruise suffered in Atlanta last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you get an opportunity to catch every day in the big
leagues, you're going to take advantage of it,'' Miller said.
``That's what I get paid to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to go out there and play as long as I can.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller is seizing his moment. He started the season as the
backup, providing relief for Stinnett on occasion.
</P>
<P>
   Miller came into Thursday's game with a .308 batting average
and, in a five-game stretch, hit .381 (8 for 21) with four doubles
and four RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just try to go out and get more consistent, take every
at-bat like it's my last at bat,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Catching coach Glenn Sherlock said if his catchers can provide
offense, that's gravy. Their primary job to defend and call the
games.
</P>
<P>
   Doing 16-inning games isn't in the job description, but Miller
survived.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just go out and dig a little deeper each inning,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Sherlock was impressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``He played hard every inning and it's so stressful back there
when the game is so close,'' Sherlock said. ``We knew he was
capable of playing this way and now he's getting the opportunity to
play on an every-day basis.''
</P>
<P>
   But Miller knows Stinnett will be back, perhaps as soon as this
weekend for the San Francisco Giants.
</P>
<P>
   Stinnett fielded bunts out of the crouch position Thursday and
said he felt the best he has since being kneed by Atlanta's Ryan
Klesko.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's some pain, but it's a good pain, the kind you have the
day after you work out,'' Stinnett said.
</P>
<P>
   Miller has been durable in Stinnett's absence.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's doing the job defensively and offensively,'' Sherlock
said. ``He's getting some big hits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I consider him more of a defensive catcher. But he certainly
has pop in his bat.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller was excited about catching Randy Johnson on Thursday
night. He did last Saturday in Atlanta when Johnson struck out 15
in victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a challenge,'' Miller said. ``He expects to go out there
and dominate every single time. I've got to go out there with my
`A' game.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson struggled this time and left after six innings, his team
trailing, 7-1.
</P>
<P>
   Except for Andy Benes and Omar Daal, Miller is catching a new
starting staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``Spring training sometimes is not long enough to get a feel for
a guy,'' Miller said. ``They just want me to go out there and help
the starters get through seven or eight innings, whatever they can.
That's my job.
</P>
<P>
   ``Offensively, what I do is a plus.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, it's been a big plus. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
