<HEADLINE>
D-BACKS STRIKE OUT LESS OFTEN THIS YEAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM  
 and RICHARD OBERT  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - One of the Diamondbacks' goals this season has been to
cut down on strikeouts, and thus far, they have made noticeable
progress.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona led the major leagues last season with 1,239 strikeouts.
Entering Thursday night's game against the Los Angeles Dodgers, the
Diamondbacks had struck out 53 times in nine games, 13 fewer than
at the same point a year ago. Eleven National League teams had more
strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   One player showing more patience at the plate has been third
baseman Matt Williams. Entering Thursday night's game, he had
struck out just twice and had not once since the second game of the
season, April 6 in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to give yourself the best opportunity to hit. Have
patience and not try to do too much,'' Williams said. ``By not
trying to do too much, maybe that's why we have more home runs,''
Williams said. Arizona led the majors with 20 entering Thursday's
game. &QL; 
Turf test &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The new Kentucky bluegrass turf at Bank One Ballpark is holding
up well after the first series, according to head groundskeeper
Grant Trenbeath.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still showing its (young) age, but it's a little more
resilient than what we had last year (with zoysia),'' Trenbeath
said.
</P>
<P>
   The only noticeable blemish was from when the Dodgers' Gary
Sheffield took a large divot out of the grass in left field in the
second game. &QL; 
Finding relief &QL; 
Before Thursday's game, the Diamondbacks' bullpen had allowed three
earned runs on seven hits in 11 innings. In the last nine innings,
it yielded no runs and just two hits.
</P>
<P>
   Quite a change from the first week of the season when the
relievers struggled to get outs.
</P>
<P>
   John Frascatore worked the last two innings of Wednesday's game,
allowing just one hit. It was a nicer ending than the extra-inning
affairs in Los Angeles and Atlanta, where the right-hander was
tagged with two losses. &QL; 
Moving up &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Left fielder Luis Gonzalez moved up to third in the batting
order Thursday against the Dodgers. He had been hitting mostly
fifth, but he's been swinging a hot bat. He came in with a .333
batting average. &QL; 
No panic attack &QL; 
Tuesday's 16-inning victory was huge for the Diamondbacks, but
Frascatore said that Wednesday's 6-2 win was bigger.
</P>
<P>
   ``Especially when you can come back the next day from that,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all settled in,'' Gonzalez said. ``We've got a bunch of
veteran guys. Nobody really panicked after we lost the first few
games. It's not a short sprint. It's a long race.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-16-99 0137EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
