<DOCNO> NYT19990416.0035 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-16 01:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0718 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-COYOTES-ROENICK-A     04-16 1020
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES-ROENICK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROENICK'S WIFE: `HE'S A MESS'  
 HATCHER'S PUNISHMENT DUE TODAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB McManaman  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - The day after the hit that knocked out Jeremy Roenick
for the playoffs, the Coyotes' star center was recovering from 5{
hours of surgery, his wife was suggesting he quit and the
perpetrator was still claiming innocence.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas Stars captain Derian Hatcher, who inflicted the injury
that sidelined JR on Wednesday, will meet today in New York with
Colin Campbell, the NHL's punishment czar, and is likely to be
suspended for at least five games.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars' No. 1 line of Mike Modano and wingers Brett Hull and
Jere Lehtinen won't have to worry about taking a similar hit
Saturday when the teams play in the regular-season finale at
America West Arena. Stars Coach Ken Hitchcock said before
Wednesday's game that the trio would be getting that day off to
rest for the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes, the No. 4 seed in the Western Conference playoffs,
and Stars, the No. 1 West seed, could meet again as early as the
conference semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   Roenick underwent surgery at a Valley hospital Thursday to
repair the jaw that was broken in three places from a crushing hit
he took into the boards from the 6-foot-5, 225-pound Hatcher.
</P>
<P>
   Roenick also suffered a fractured right thumb _ which alone
would have knocked him out of at least the first round _ a
split-second before the Hatcher hit when he was slashed hard by
defenseman Craig Ludwig, who may also face suspension.
</P>
<P>
   Usually, when a player is summoned to the league office for a
hearing with Campbell, the NHL's senior vice president and director
of operations, he receives no less than a five-game banishment. It
means Hatcher can expect to miss the Stars' final two
regular-season games and at least the first few games of the
opening-round playoff series against Edmonton.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the penalty, it won't appease Roenick's wife, Tracey,
who spent time in the hospital earlier this week with the couple's
daughter, Brandi, who underwent an adenoid procedure.
</P>
<P>
   ``They just wheeled him into the recovery room a minute ago, and
he's a mess,'' Tracey Roenick said Thursday morning, adding that
the operation took two hours longer than expected. ``I think it's
disgusting. It's absolutely disgusting. When he wakes up, I'm
saying to JR, `Retire, it's just not freaking worth it anymore.' ''
</P>
<P>
   According to his wife, Roenick had two steel plates fitted into
his jaw during the operation and an oral surgeon told her that at
least eight teeth likely will have to be replaced. He wasn't
scheduled to be released from the hospital until Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   A still-angry Coyotes General Manager Bobby Smith had little to
say about the Hatcher hit, which many in the organization viewed as
a premeditated attack as retaliation for a check Roenick threw at
Modano three weeks earlier in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are confident the league will deal with this
appropriately,'' said Smith, who suffered two broken jaws during
his NHL career.
</P>
<P>
   Asked after the game whether he thinks Hatcher faces a lengthy
suspension, Hitchcock said: ``Not at all. The original call was two
minutes. It's because there was blood there it went to five. It's a
normal part of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Stars General Manager Bob Gainey is preparing for the worst when
Hatcher meets with Campbell.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that (the Coyotes have) got a player badly injured is
something I think nobody can feel good about,'' he said. ``That is
not what the sport is about. In the normal course of the game or
the season, players do get injuries, but injuries shouldn't be the
result of things that are not right.''
</P>
<P>
   Hatcher repeated Thursday that he never singled out Roenick on
the hit, that he didn't even know it was Roenick until just before
crashing into him, and that he didn't use his elbow to make
contact.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unfortunate Jeremy broke his jaw,'' he said. ``I feel
bad, but there's nothing I can do about it now. . . . I hit him
with my shoulder. The bad thing about it is, I did come off my feet
a bit. It's a play that happens in a lot of games.''
</P>
<P>
   Tracey Roenick wishes the Coyotes would have decided to sit her
husband Wednesday night in Dallas. She said he told her the day
before he left that the Stars were going to target him, something
which ``The Arizona'' ``Republic'' and the ``Dallas Morning News''
each warned was possible in stories Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Hatcher claims he never said anything to the media that could be
construed as premeditation.
</P>
<P>
   ``No. If you can find me a quote in any paper saying we were
going to hit Jeremy, or for that matter, saying I was going to get
him, find them and show them to me,'' said Hatcher, who also ended
Roenick's season during the 1994-95 playoffs with a questionable
knee-on-knee hit. ``It wasn't even mentioned in the room before the
game.''
</P>
<P>
   Roenick can't say much of anything with the condition of his
jaw, but his wife said she is fairly confident he wouldn't rip
Hatcher for the hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``He probably hasn't seen replays of the hit, but knowing `J,'
he wouldn't say what I feel like saying,'' Tracey Roenick said.
``When Derian took out his knee (in 1995), Jeremy never bashed
Derian for that and I know he wouldn't today.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just so frustrating because of the timing with the
playoffs coming up. I feel sad not only for Jeremy, but for the
Coyotes, the fans, for hockey, for everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Might Roenick, 29, contemplate retirement? Maybe for a second,
but probably not. Tracey, however, wonders if it is time.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's making unbelievable money and that's great,'' she said,
``but he plays because he truly loves the game. But how much can
you love the concussions, the knee injuries and now, the broken
jaw? He has two young children. How much is it worth? He wants a
chance to play for the Stanley Cup but where is he today? He's in a
hospital bed.
</P>
<P>
   ``If (retiring) could make Jeremy happy, I'd back him 100
percent. . . . I don't want my husband crippled so he can't go to
my son's hockey games.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
