<HEADER>
A0734 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-187-APPEAL-2TAKES-LAD     04-16 0815
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-187-APPEAL-2TAKES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOV. DAVIS ANGER BOTH SIDES BY SEEKING MEDIATION ON PROP. 187
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY TERRI HARDY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO _ Trying to sidestep the politically charged debate
over Proposition 187, California Gov. Gray Davis angered both sides
Thursday by announcing he would seek a negotiated compromise
through federal mediation rather than pursue a court appeal in
support of the measure.
</P>
<P>
   Both opponents and proponents of the measure, which would block
public benefits to illegal immigrants, questioned the legality of
the unusual maneuver, despite the governor's claims that mediation
would be best for all.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this were a piece of legislation, I would veto it,'' Davis
said. ``But it is not. I have taken an oath of office to enforce
all the laws of California and all the laws of this nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe both the plaintiffs and proponents of Proposition
187 will act responsibly. But if I must _ to ensure the will of the
electorate is respected and that we get beyond this divisive issue
_ I will knock heads to reach an agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear how far Davis was willing to go in dealing with
the overarching concerns about illegal immigration that prompted
voters to pass the initiative in 1994 by a margin of 59-41. In
1995, U.S. District Judge Maria Pfaelzer of Los Angeles ruled key
portions of the initiative unconstitutional. Last year she issued
her final order forbidding enactment of those provisions, and the
state under Gov. Pete Wilson appealed that ruling. Davis faced a
deadline to notify the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in San
Francisco whether he would pursue that appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to a question on illegal immigration, Davis said,
``I'm against anything that's illegal.''
</P>
<P>
   Latino leaders adamantly contended Proposition 187 is
unconstitutional and renewed their calls for the state to drop the
case for its support.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the initiative said it reflects the will of the
voters, and they demanded Davis vigorously defend it in court.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, who personally opposed Proposition 187, repeatedly has
vowed not to overlook the voters' mandate.
</P>
<P>
   In his toughest decision since taking office, Davis said he
believes negotiation is the best way to reach agreement on the
divisive issue, and he said it will spare taxpayers a lengthy,
costly legal battle.
</P>
<P>
   Any settlement would be consensual and turned over to a 9th
Circuit judge for approval.
</P>
<P>
   Davis' announcement infuriated Lt. Gov Cruz Bustamante, the
first Latino to hold state office in more than 100 years.
Addressing reporters on the steps of the Capitol with jaw clenched,
he tersely said he was disappointed by the governor's decision not
just to drop the case for an initiative Bustamante considers not
``morally or legally defensible.''
</P>
<P>
   Bustamante said he listened with pride to Davis' inaugural
speech declaring an end to wedge-issue politics like Proposition
187.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think that meant that we were going to wait for a
federal judge to do our job for us,'' Bustamante said. ``I thought
it was about what we were going to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Assembly Speaker Antonio Villaraigosa angrily opposed Davis'
action.
</P>
<P>
   In the mediation process, Davis, represented by Attorney General
Bill Lockyer, will be in the position of supporting the initiative.
Also at the table will be a group of lawsuit plaintiffs who oppose
the initiative. Davis also said he would be seeking informal input
from Pacific Legal Foundation, a group which represented backers of
Proposition 187.
</P>
<P>
   Davis urged the lawsuit plaintiffs to come to negotiations with
an open mind. But lawyers representing illegal immigrants said,
while they will listen to any proposal from the governor, they are
far from open-minded.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can you have an open mind? There's no such thing when you
are an advocate,'' said Vibiana Andrade, the counsel on Proposition
187 for the Mexican American Legal Defense and Educational Fund.
``What the governor doesn't seem to understand is that for the
Latino community, (the initiative) was ground zero for the culture
wars.''
</P>
<P>
   Andrade said she realized that, since the initiative passed,
there have been new federal laws that address some of the same
concerns that prompted Proposition 187. For instance, now illegal
immigrants cannot receive Social Security or nonemergency
health-care benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know the legal landscape has changed,'' Andrade said. ``But
if the governor walks in and demands certain things, like the
denial of education for children, that's something we wouldn't
stand for.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharon Browne, an attorney for Pacific Legal Foundation, said
the governor couldn't be trusted to provide a good defense for the
initiative, even though it was approved by 59 percent of voters.
</P>
<P>
   (CONTINUED ON NEXT TAKE)
</P>
<P>
   X X X  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO: _ 59 percent of voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Governor Davis has said he doesn't believe in Proposition 187
and that if it came across his desk he would veto it. I think that
gives us a good idea of how vigorously he will defend it.''
</P>
<P>
   Manuel Klausner, a Los Angeles attorney, said he has grave
concerns because the Pacific Legal Foundation is not being given a
formal place in the mediations, and he questions how the process
will work.
</P>
<P>
   ``The judge could say no; he would not endorse it,'' Klausner
said. ``Would a 9th Circuit judge go along and validate the
results? That's a very interesting question.''
</P>
<P>
   Legal experts questioned the use of mediation for a
constitutional issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``My instinct is that mediation makes more sense not in matters
of principle, like Proposition 187, but in matters of fact,'' said
Evan Caminker, a University of California, Los Angeles,
constitutional law professor.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles County Supervisor Michael D. Antonovich blasted the
governor's decision and took a swipe at him in a prepared statement
that alluded to Davis' longstanding reputation as a publicity
hound.
</P>
<P>
   ``At a time when we needed a profile of courage, we had all
profile _ and no courage.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Rosenbaum, legal director of the American Civil Liberties
Union of Southern California, said the ACLU ``will accept no offer
that removes children from schools they attend or denies needy
individuals the necessary health care or social services to which
they are entitled.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The ACLU believes that the governor has both the
constitutional authority and the constitutional obligation to
dismiss the appeal in the Proposition 187 litigation,'' Rosenbaum
said. ``The governor's oath to uphold our federal constitution
accordingly requires that he cease to attempt to enforce all laws,
including Proposition 187, which he believes to be
unconstitutional.''
</P>
<P>
   After long delaying a final decision, Judge Pfaelzer ruled it
unconstitutional on the grounds immigration issues are federal
responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
   An appeal would be dropped under Davis' mediation plan,
preventing a definitive ruling by the U.S. Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   X X X  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
