<HEADER>
A0744 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-MARINERS-RANGERS-     04-16 0789
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-RANGERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARINERS LOSE IN 10 INNINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ It was a perfect day for baseball _ at Safeco Field,
perhaps. But not indoors at the Kingdome, not for Lou Piniella and
the Seattle Mariners.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Rangers finished off a three-game sweep Thursday with
a 4-3 victory in 10 innings. The Mariners ended their
season-opening homestand with a 4-6 record. It's early of course,
but Piniella's patience was challenged _ though that happened after
the game.
</P>
<P>
   On a day in which Ken Griffey Jr. did not play because of an
upset stomach, the Mariner manager was also churning inside.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your thoughts on how the game turned out,'' Piniella was asked
afterward.
</P>
<P>
   ``My thoughts on how the ballgame turned out?'' a puzzled
Piniella asked. ``What should my thoughts be?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably frustrated,'' came the reply.
</P>
<P>
   And then Piniella caught himself, just like Jeff Fassero did,
before damage ensued.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only good thing is that Fassero pitched well,'' Piniella
said.
</P>
<P>
   Entering the game with a 10.80 earned run average, the Mariners'
No. 1 starter gave up a single on his first pitch to eventual hero
Luis Alicea and a run-scoring double to Roberto Kelly. The
left-hander resembled a quality pitcher after that, going eight
innings, allowing three runs on seven hits.
</P>
<P>
   ``He threw his fastball on both sides of the plate (for
strikes),'' said catcher Tom Lampkin. `` ... He demonstrated he
knows how to pitch. He'll change people's minds about what kind of
season he's having.''
</P>
<P>
   In workouts this week with pitching coach Stan Williams, Fassero
changed a couple of mechanics. He took the ball out of his glove
earlier in the windup, resulting in better control and a more
downward trajectory toward the plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was jumping out front too quick,'' Williams said. ``His arm
couldn't catch up.''
</P>
<P>
   Fassero said that his recent poor outings had not affected his
confidence, but Williams offered another perspective: ``When you're
getting your brains beat out, it's hard to be positive without
positive results.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Piniella: ``He's worked hard, and it's starting to bear
some fruit.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not an orchard, but better than the cores Fassero produced
in his first two outings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had been terrible. We needed something out there,'' said
Fassero, who has been mentioned in unsubstantiated trade rumors for
the Yankees' Hideki Irabu. ``I can build on this.''
</P>
<P>
   Boldly and consistently, Fassero threw fastballs inside. When
the Rangers started looking inside, he changed up and painted the
other corner, resulting in harmless ground balls to the right side.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll tell you what, he pitched me tough,'' said Rusty Greer,
who went 1-for-4 against Fassero.
</P>
<P>
   Down 3-0 at one point, Fassero left with the score tied 3-3
after David Bell's two-run homer in the third and Butch Huskey's
RBI double in the fourth evened it up.
</P>
<P>
   That was it for Mariner punch. Rick Helling, another struggling
starter, allowed five hits, and Tim Crabtree and John Wetteland
finished up with an inning each of hitless relief. Every Ranger
pitcher was around the plate all afternoon and, consequently, the
Mariners were more apt to be on the dugout bench instead of the
basepaths. Seattle left just two runners stranded.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not the pitchers' fault,'' Huskey said. ``We needed five
runs to win the game. As hitters, we didn't get the job done.''
</P>
<P>
   Reliever John Halama suffered the loss after pitching reasonably
well. But a single, a sacrifice and double by Alicea gave Wetteland
the opportunity to record his fourth save.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just off the center, just above the belt,'' Lampkin
said of the pitch Alicea drove to right-center field. ``He was
trying to get the ball down to the inside of the plate. He didn't
get it there. He knows it, I know it and, if you saw the replay,
you know it.''
</P>
<P>
   In Piniella's final analysis, Texas simply has ``more horses,''
but the stampede has left town along with the Mariners. The search
for victories and an identity continues in Anaheim tonight.
</P>
<P>
   Although the results indicated otherwise, it was evident that
the sun's rays somehow found a crack in the concrete and shone on
Lampkin's locker.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without two of the best players in baseball (Griffey and Alex
Rodriguez), we stayed with `em for 10 innings,'' Lampkin said. ``At
least we didn't give up 10 and score 2. We were in that game until
the last out. How can you not take something positive out of
that?''
</P>
<P>
   But for those who remain cynical about the Mariners' hopes, it
was Lampkin who made that last out, swinging helplessly at
Wetteland's final pitch.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
