<HEADER>
A0745 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-KINGS-LADN     04-16 0590
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS SURPRISE DUCKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD _ For much of Thursday it looked as if the Mighty
Ducks might regain control of their playoff destiny. Phoenix was
leading St. Louis and Anaheim appeared on its way to completing a
six-game series sweep of the Kings before 14,669 at the Forum.
</P>
<P>
   But in a matter of minutes things turned completely around. The
Blues rallied to beat the Coyotes and the Ducks were being pushed
to the limit and eventually defeated by the Kings 4-3 on a goal by
Ray Ferraro at 2:21 of overtime with the Ducks two men down.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks not only failed to stay alive in the race for fifth
place _ they still haven't wrapped up sixth either.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the bad news on the scoreboard from Phoenix, the Ducks
were leading 2-1 when the final meeting of the year between the two
teams turned into a run-and-gun affair.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings, who had managed only five goals in the five previous
games versus Anaheim, tied a team record when they scored twice in
six seconds to take a 3-2 lead with 12:07 to play.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Bodger tied the game with 40-footer that beat a screened
Dominic Roussel shot at 7:47. The crowd was still going wild when
Luc Robitaille beat Dan Trebil to the net and shoved the puck
through Roussel's pads for his 39th goal of the season.
</P>
<P>
   The celebration was short-lived as Anaheim tied the game, 3-3 at
8:17, with the third goal in 30 seconds. Teemu Selanne did the
honors scoring his league-leading 47th goal off a nice setup by
Matt Cullen.
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim got a much-need boost going into dressing room when it
took the lead with 3.4 seconds left in the second period.
</P>
<P>
   Rucchin won the draw cleanly back to Selanne, whose slap shot
from the high slot was blocked into the right circle by Stephane
Fiset. Unfortunately for the Kings goalie, Ducks defenseman Fredrik
Olausson had jumped right to that very spot and flicked the rebound
over Fiset for his 16th goal of the year. It was only Olausson's
second goal in his last 27 games.
</P>
<P>
   But during intermission Anaheim's chances of finishing fifth
took another body blow. Phoenix was leading St. Louis going into
the third period, but the Blues rallied to win with four goals in
the third.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks, who started fast on Wednesday night and wound up with
nothing to show for it, took a quick lead Thursday when Tomas
Sandstrom deflected rookie defensemen Scott Ferguson's point shot
past Fiset at 2:12.
</P>
<P>
   Fiset was tangled up with Sandstrom in front of the crease and
argued for an interference call, but the Anaheim winger's 14th goal
of the season stood.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks' lead lasted only six minutes thanks to a quick goal
by the Kings' much maligned power play. Ranked 24th in the league
with the man advantage, the Kings got a goal from Ray Ferraro at
6:12, only nine seconds after Jamie Pushor was sent to the penalty
box. Ferraro was wide open at the right post to receive a nice
cross-ice pass from Donald Audette and score his 11th goal of the
season and first in 25 games.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks had several chances to regain the lead, but it was
their No. 1 ranked power play that let them down. The Kings took
two consecutive penalties late in the first and early in the second
and another midway through the period, but the Ducks generated
virtually no pressure on Fiset.
</P>
<P>
   A key to Anaheim's success all season the Ducks' power play unit
had converted only one of 16 chances heading into Thursday's game.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
