<SLUG> BC-BKN-CLIPPERS-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAZZ GETS EVEN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By RANDY HILL &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; Long Beach Press-Telegram &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Clippers may not need a bigger bandwagon.
</P>
<P>
   And they can wait to rotate the tires on their current model,
because the parade that was threatening to break out on their road
to nowhere has stalled on the course.
</P>
<P>
   The rig was pulled over Thursday by the Utah Jazz, who thumped
the feisty Clippers, 103-89, in front of 10,447 at the Sports
Arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's no embarrassment losing to the Utah Jazz,'' said Clippers
coach Chris Ford, who - at 6 up and 32 down - now knows the emotion
well.
</P>
<P>
   But the defeat did end the Clips' victory run at two laps in a
row.
</P>
<P>
   Utah (30-8) also accomplished a little pick-and-role reversal
from March 27, when the Clippers experienced a harmonic convergence
- and a 103-77 triumph - in Anaheim. This time, the Clippers were
bothered by hearing too many whistles while they worked.
</P>
<P>
   The Jazz hoisted 12 more free-throw attempts than they did, but
- to the young Clips - the timing of those calls was brutal.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, our Thursday Night Nitro rematch between Utah's Karl
``The Mailman'' Malone and Clipper Maurice ``Phonecrusher'' Taylor
(he never seems to get any calls) was as dry as, well, most of
Utah.
</P>
<P>
   Malone finished with 25 points and seven rebounds while working
the officials from the lost post, a place he has zoned as the whine
country.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like it when Karl Malone cries,'' Clipper Lorenzen Wright
said. ``It means we made him mad.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor, the other mad guy, was limited to 33 minutes by frequent
fouling, countering with 16 and six.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was horrible,'' Taylor said - among other things -- in
reference to the officiating.
</P>
<P>
   Utah's physical starting crew had Malone's back, with John
Stockton (nine assists) and Bryon Russell each checking in with 19
points, Greg Ostertag contributing 19 rebounds and 16 points, and
Jeff Hornacek on the board for another 15.
</P>
<P>
   Wright scored 15 points and grabbed 12 rebounds off the Clipper
bench. Point guard Sherman Douglas had 17 points and six assists.
</P>
<P>
   Utah started their payback campaign with a 12-4 lead.
</P>
<P>
   With three starters on the twilight side of their powers, the
Jazz still execute their schemes like the death squad from a YMCA
league. But the Clippers are harder to shake than a bad credit
rating.
</P>
<P>
   The Clippers, showing appreciable pluck, kept fighting and
trailed 46-44 at intermission. But Malone and Stockton - death and
taxes - scored nine and eight points, respectively, as Utah pounded
its way to a 75-61 advantage entering the final period. The
Clippers scrapped to within seven on a three-point play by Murray
with 3:56, but the wheels came off again.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
