<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRAWBERRY'S DRUG ADDICTION AN EDUCATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Sports stars have long leashes. When the 3-pointers
and touchdowns and home runs keep coming, the slack we are willing
to cut them is generous.
</P>
<P>
   But what happens when they betray that flood of trust and
adulation?
</P>
<P>
   The leash gets yanked. It gets pulled back hard. With a
vengeance. With anger.
</P>
<P>
   The internet, radio talk shows and baseball clubhouses are alive
across America right now with talk of Darryl Strawberry.
Overwhelmingly, the words are harsh, the sentiments stern.
</P>
<P>
   All these things were said Thursday, in the wake of news that
Strawberry, 37, was arrested in Florida on charges of sex
solicitation and cocaine possession:
</P>
<P>
   (begin italics) A selfish person ... He acts with no regard to
others or other people's feelings ... No more chances, he's out ...
Put the dopester in prison where he can rot ... It's not about
drugs, it's about irresponsible behavior ... No more sympathy. (end
italics)
</P>
<P>
   At the Kingdome, veterans who have been around the game and
Strawberry were dismayed to hear the news about the Yankees
slugger, whose battles with cocaine and alcohol abuse twice landed
him in rehab and once got him a 60 day suspension from baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Rafael Palmeiro said he feels bad for Strawberry's family, but
not Strawberry.
</P>
<P>
   ``We get talked to about all this stuff in spring training,''
the Rangers first baseman said. ``We have FBI agents brought in to
tell us we're targets. Things like that will happen if you put
yourself in that situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Jay Buhner said it was a shame.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't say I feel sorry for him,'' he said. ``I know that
sounds rude and harsh because we're all family in baseball. When
something like this happens, I have concern for Darryl the person,
outside of baseball. I worry about Darryl. He's got a family and
kids. He's a father.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's got to be the toughest, to know a kid might grow up and
have to say, `My dad was a druggie.' I couldn't look my kids in the
eye.''
</P>
<P>
   It is difficult to understand how a man with such athletic
gifts, who has had so many chances already, could just go out and
blow it.
</P>
<P>
   But maybe this is another round of public education on the
insidious nature of addiction. That is what the experts say, though
they are no less disheartened to hear such news about a man whose
private demons, failures and disease are a matter of public record.
</P>
<P>
   David Mactas is the former director of the National Center for
Substance Abuse Treatment, the United States' principal agency for
this problem. He is now president and CEO of Hazelton, one of New
York's largest abuse treatment centers. He said the news about
Strawberry was terrible.
</P>
<P>
   ``Terrible because he is human and because he had gone down to
Florida to try and win a job (back in the major leagues) and
because his wife stood beside him all during his plight with colon
cancer,'' Mactas said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But this is the nature of the disease. It's a chronic,
relapsing condition. It's not a requirement to relapse. It is not
part of the job description but it is quite common.''
</P>
<P>
   While the charges allege only that Strawberry had 0.3 grams of
cocaine and there was no evidence that he had been using, it opens
the question about what is so powerful about cocaine.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's exhilarating. It's seductive. It's viable. It's
affordable. It's addictive,'' Mactas said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Laboratory rats would sooner use cocaine than eat food or
drink water. So will humans. It is a very powerful feeling of
exhilaration and most seductive for people who too often feel they
are missing feeling terrific.''
</P>
<P>
   Research has shown that the brain's chemistry and structure
change with substance abuse. The neurotransmitters and receptors in
the brain, which pass along substances that create the sensation of
euphoria, can be affected.
</P>
<P>
   In some sense, addiction is a ``modified brain disease,'' Mactas
said.
</P>
<P>
   But in the glare of the bright lights of major-league sports,
the nature of Strawberry's illness is fractured. The charge will be
that Strawberry is extra-responsible for keeping up his end of the
bargain. The feeling is he has let everyone down. Straw is worthy
of scorn, not forgiveness, because he has used up his ration _
whatever that mysterious ration may be.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the pendulum swing of emotion against Strawberry now is so
thorough because eight months ago, Strawberry's battle with colon
cancer drew so many people's interest and sympathy.
</P>
<P>
   If fact, ever since Yankees owner George Steinbrenner decided to
act like Father Flanagan by inviting Strawberry into the Bronx
Boystown four years ago, Strawberry has been a solid citizen. He
has been a positive, contributing member of a very unselfish,
personable, compelling Yankee team.
</P>
<P>
   If Steinbrenner had to open the door for Strawberry with a
warning not to mess up, Strawberry had fulfilled his obligation to
his boss, to baseball and to the fans.
</P>
<P>
   At least he had up until the time of his arrest, which did us
the favor of reminding us that recovery is never-ending, that the
stigma of addiction is almost as bad as the disease.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
