<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS DECIDE TO WAIVE RODMAN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD _ The Dennis Rodman experiment, as intriguing as it
was combustible, finally fizzled out Thursday afternoon, just 23
games after it began.
</P>
<P>
   And not a championship banner or ticker-tape parade to show for
it. Just the usual trail of chaos left in Rodman's choppy wake.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers decided to give up on the talented but troublesome
rebounding specialist late in the afternoon, and he will be placed
on waivers today.
</P>
<P>
   The decision was made jointly by executive vice president Jerry
West, general manager Mitch Kupchak and coach Kurt Rambis, just
hours after Rodman again arrived late for practice.
</P>
<P>
   Rambis sent Rodman home, signaling that the end of the
38-year-old veteran's tenure here was near.
</P>
<P>
   Lakers owner Jerry Buss, who befriended Rodman in the offseason,
then insisted on signing him despite West's strong objections,
signed off on the decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this time we feel it's in the best interests of the Lakers
to end the relationship,'' West said in a prepared statement.
``This obviously didn't work out like we had hoped. But we would
like to thank Dennis for the contributions he did make to the team
and wish him the best of luck in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Team officials could not be reached for further comment, but
Kupchak is scheduled to speak with the media today. There was no
immediate word from Rodman's army of Hollywood agents and public
relations specialists.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers must pay the remainder of Rodman's one-year contract,
about $122,000. Rodman had an option for $1 million for next
season, but that provision has been negated.
</P>
<P>
   Rodman, who won five NBA championships with Detroit and Chicago,
ended his brief Lakers career having averaged a team-leading 11.2
rebounds, 2.1 points and 1.3 assists in 28.6 minutes. He played in
23 games, started 11, and the Lakers went 17-6 when he played. They
were 8-9 without him in the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Third-year forward Travis Knight, the starter until Rodman
replaced him, will be activated from the injured list to take his
roster spot.
</P>
<P>
   The beginning of the end came shortly after 11 a.m. Thursday,
when Rodman arrived a few minutes late to practice at Southwest
College. Rambis, exhibiting a new zero-tolerance stance, sent him
home.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made exceptions and special cases to accommodate him, but
in my mind, the accommodation period is over,'' Rambis said
afterward, but before the team decided to waive Rodman.
</P>
<P>
   The coach's declaration was the strongest stance the Lakers had
taken since signing Rodman on Feb. 23, when the club's official
policy was ``Dennis is Dennis,'' as Buss put it.
</P>
<P>
   But letting Rodman play by his own rules didn't work out as
planned. He added double-figure rebounds when he played, but his
energizing performances were too often interrupted by both on- and
off-court flare-ups.
</P>
<P>
   Numerous late arrivals. Four skipped practices. Four missed
games, and a trip to Las Vegas while the team was on a six-game
road trip. And four instances of refusing to re-enter a game, the
last one Tuesday, when he claimed elbow soreness and sat out the
second half of the Lakers' 113-86 loss to Portland.
</P>
<P>
   That history, combined with the Lakers' recent struggles on the
court, led Rambis to draw the line. Rodman's explanation didn't
help his case.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said he was looking for socks and shoes,'' Rambis said,
``and I told him practice was 11, and why don't you just go home.''
</P>
<P>
   Once, the Lakers had the luxury of indulging such antics. But
not after losing their past two games and four of their past seven,
with just 10 regular-season games left to prepare for the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's time that we really, everybody, jump on the same
page. You're either involved with the team, on the team, with the
team or you're not,'' Rambis said. ``I just feel that we have to be
more concerned with the team than individuals.''
</P>
<P>
   Shaquille O'Neal said he supported Rambis' decision to send
Rodman home, but added, ``I really didn't see him as a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodman's actions, O'Neal said, are ``not really OK, but the guy
does his job in the game most of the time.''
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of Tuesday's deflating defeat at Portland, and with
a tough road game at Utah on Saturday, Rambis is determined to do
whatever is necessary to pull his floundering team together.
</P>
<P>
   So after sending Rodman home, Rambis kicked all bodyguards,
security people and hangers-on out of the gym, and posted a
handwritten sign on the door: ``Practice is closed. NO ENTRY.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he put the team through a non-nonsense, 2{-hour workout and
afterward said the closed-practice policy _ players, trainers and
coaches only _ will continue for the rest of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to be more focused as a team, we have to be more
dedicated as a team and we have to know that when we're coming
here, we're coming to work,'' Rambis said.
</P>
<P>
   Derek Fisher welcomed the crackdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been up and down, and right now we're just down,'' he
said. ``You can't sit there and just allow that to continue.''
</P>
<P>
   Notes: Glen Rice (tonsillitis) and Derek Harper (sore back)
attended practice but did not participate. Rice, out the last two
games, said he hoped to be able to practice today and play
Saturday, but ``how much, I have no idea.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
