<HEADLINE>
HAWKINS' `3' BEATS KINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ At this point in the regular season, the
Sonics need victories like cars need gasoline.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to Hersey Hawkins, the rough-riding Sonics left ARCO
Arena full.
</P>
<P>
   Hawkins' buzzer-beating 3-pointer in overtime beat the pesky
Sacramento Kings Thursday night in a must-win game for the Sonics.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an incredible relief,'' Sonics coach Paul Westphal
said, who jumped around the court, exchanging high-fives with
players and his assistants. ``It was a stunning relief. This win
was huge for our team.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics trailed 96-93 with 1:30 left in the game when Detlef
Schrempf hit a 3-pointer to tie the score. Sacramento muffed two
trips to the foul line that could have sealed the Sonics' fate.
</P>
<P>
   Hawkins' game-winner came after the Sonics put the ball in play,
down 98-96 with 7.3 seconds left. Gary Payton drove the baseline
and passed out to a wide-open Hawkins.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Hawkins hurt his knee when he fell to the floor. He
could hardly run on the game's final play.
</P>
<P>
   ``The funny thing is Paul said to me as I walked by, `Go knock
down a three and let's get out of here.' It worked just like he
said,'' Hawkins said. ``If I had to run, I would have been in
trouble. But I'm happy for Paul. It's been a rough season. We
haven't had any breaks so it's really nice to get one.''
</P>
<P>
   Hawkins picked the right time to make his only jump shot of the
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to figure sooner or later it's going to go our way,''
Schrempf said. ``There's nothing sweeter than seeing a shot fall
through at the buzzer and running out with a win.''
</P>
<P>
   The victory put the 19-19 Sonics a half-game in front of the
Phoenix Suns for the seventh seed in the Western Conference playoff
standings. The Sonics also moved 2{ games ahead of the Kings
(17-22).
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics led 90-86 with 1:24 left in regulation. Kings rookie
Jason Williams scored a layup with 31.5 seconds remaining. The
Kings then missed two chances to tie the game _ and the Sonics
missed a chance to put the game away.
</P>
<P>
   Sonics center Olden Polynice went to the the free-throw line
four times, making just one of them. The Sonics clung to a 91-88
lead with 4.4 seconds left, giving Sacramento just enough time.
</P>
<P>
   Kings center Vlade Divac dribbled the ball past midcourt and
found Predrag Stojakovic wide open in the corner opposite the
Sonics' bench. Stojakovic's off-balance 3-pointer fell as the clock
expired and forced overtime.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics argued the shot came after the buzzer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the first time in the NBA you win two games in one
night,'' Polynice said. ``When did we start playing
doubleheaders?''
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics play New Jersey at home tonight and play the Suns for
a third and final time Sunday at America West Arena.
</P>
<P>
   After another slow start, the Sonics trailed 51-45 at halftime.
Westphal used eight players in the first half and got solid
production from most of them.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics needed a balanced attack considering Payton played
his worst half this season. The team's leading scorer made good on
just 1 of his first 10 shots _ four of which were 3-pointers.
</P>
<P>
   Vin Baker, Jelani McCoy and Dale Ellis kept the Sonics from
falling behind by more than six points. Baker had 10 points and
McCoy connected on each of his three shots.
</P>
<P>
   After falling behind 25-24, Baker's three-point play capped an
8-0 run the Sonics used to start the second period. The Sonics
stormed in front 32-25 and then got into a shootout with the Kings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
