<HEADER>
A0768 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-BRUINS-PENGUINS-B     04-16 0760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-PENGUINS-BOS </SLUG>

 &HT;    BRUINS BEAT PENGUINS
 &HT;    (For use by New York Times News Service clients) 
 &HT;     By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Bruins insist they don't care whom they face in the first
round of the playoffs. Good thing, because the potential opponent
keeps changing.
</P>
<P>
   When they woke up Thursday morning, they were slotted to face
the New Jersey Devils in a No. 1 vs. No. 8 matchup.
</P>
<P>
   As of this morning, on the strength of a convincing 4-2 victory
over Pittsburgh at the FleetCenter Thursday night, the Bruins
vaulted over both the Penguins and Buffalo Sabres into sixth place
and were looking at No. 3 seed Carolina as their possible foe next
week.
</P>
<P>
   With two games remaining _ Saturday against the Sabres and
Sunday against the Flyers in Philadelphia _ it's likely to be
scrambled again.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know we're going to the dance, we just don't have a partner
yet,'' said coach Pat Burns, who has been the most vocal in telling
his players and the media that it matters not one whit who stands
in their way of first-round success. ``If you play well, you've got
a good chance to win the game. If you do that, good things are
going to happen. If you worry about the next two or three games
down the road and where you're going to finish, you forget about
how you're supposed to play. I thought this was playoff hockey
Thursday night and we played it that way.''
</P>
<P>
   If Thursday night was any indication, the Bruins (9-2-3 in their
last 14 games) are prepared to give anyone a run for their money.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the first period got off to a very slow start, due
in large part to both teams being off since last weekend. The
Bruins struck first midway through as a result of their power play.
Hal Gill, who always seems to rise to the occasion against Penguins
star Jaromir Jagr, helped set up his team's first score when he
drew a penalty on Jagr for hooking.
</P>
<P>
   Darren Van Impe started the play with a shot from the right
point that goalie Tom Barrasso gloved. The puck popped out to Jason
Allison in the slot. Allison, who had one goal and two assists,
shoveled a short pass to Joe Thornton, who was positioned low in
the right circle. Thornton popped it over the downed goalie and the
Bruins were ahead, 1-0.
</P>
<P>
   Just over five minutes later, the Bruins made it a two-goal lead
on Allison's 23d tally. He beat defenseman Kevin Hatcher in the
right corner and took advantage of a pick set by teammate Anson
Carter on center Brian Bonin. Carter got position on Bonin, Allison
skated past and went right to left around the net and out front,
where he fired in a shot that sailed past Barrasso for the 2-0
advantage.
</P>
<P>
   The Penguins pulled to within 2-1 at 1:49 of the second. With
Pittsburgh on the power play, Bruins defenseman Ray Bourque tried
to clear the puck out of the zone. His clearing attempt ended up
right on the stick of center Alexei Kovalev, who teed up a slapper
from the point that blistered past netminder Byron Dafoe. It was
Kovalev's 22d goal.
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh came looking for more midway through the period,
during which the dangerous Jagr, a runaway for the Art Ross trophy
as the league's top scorer, skated around and around the Boston
net, doing everything but scoring.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after Jagr's shift, the Bruins made it 3-1 when Carter
fired home a slapper from the right circle at 9:08. Carter's goal,
his 23d of the year and first of two in the game, was unassisted.
</P>
<P>
   The Penguins came oh-so-close to tying it at 14:25 when they had
a goal disallowed. Right wing Alexei Morozov, positioned to Dafoe's
left, dished a feed through the crease for Kovalev, who was
charging the net. Kovalev arrived, though, a nanosecond too soon
and was ruled in the crease prior to the puck, nullifying the
score.
</P>
<P>
   Jagr broke through, making it 3-2 with 1:27 left with his 41st
of the year. In the season series, which finished with the Bruins
earning a 2-1-1 record against Pittsburgh, Jagr was limited to two
goals _ his only points.
</P>
<P>
   Carter closed it out with an empty-netter with 49.8 seconds
remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Wherever the Bruins end up after the regular season, no one
seems concerned.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a matter of us playing at our highest level and
not worrying about the opponent,'' said Dafoe, who picked up his
31st win. ``We've picked our road game up so much. To be honest,
the pressure's off you when you start on the road in the playoffs.
All you have to do is win one game there. It's the other team
that's expected to win both games. It will be a good situation for
us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
