<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-16 02:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0770 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-BRUINS-PENGUINS-B     04-16 0807
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-PENGUINS-BOS </SLUG>

 &HT;    BRUINS' 1-2 PUNCH KEY TO SUCCESS
 &HT;    (For use by New York Times News Service clients)
 &HT;    By Kevin Paul Dupont  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   Hockey here in the Hub hasn't been exactly the clearing house of
unbridled optimism the past few years. You noticed? It hasn't been
Antoine Walker bad, but there hasn't been the glow and excitement
around the game that we grew so accustomed to in the '70s and '80s.
</P>
<P>
   Now it's almost playoff time, and what's playing out on Causeway
Street is the best brand of Bruins hockey since they moved into the
Vault almost four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are playing well,'' said Jason Allison, after Thursday
night's 4-2 win over the Penguins, Boston's sixth triumph in the
last seven games. ``But I still don't think we're on top of our
game yet. It might be good to have that room to improve.''
</P>
<P>
   The playoffs will come down to many things: Byron Dafoe's
netminding; referee's calls (where they register, either ridiculous
or sublime), penalty killing, five-on-five play, the man-advantage
. . . all the subsets that get reviewed and dissected as the
postseason unfolds and once it is finished.
</P>
<P>
   But the key to Boston's success or failure will be rooted in its
first- and second-line offense. For the first time since leaving
the Garden behind, they'll actually have a first- and second-line
attack. They have two lines that can go out and present a viable
threat, make something happen with the puck, and that's whether the
opponent is Ottawa, New Jersey, or Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year in the playoffs, we had only one line going,'' said
Allison, who centered that line with Sergei Samsonov and Dmitri
Khristich. ``This time that's not going to happen. We have two
lines going. So it's not going to be like last year, especially
with Joe (Thornton) on top of his game like lately.''
</P>
<P>
   Thornton most often now has Allison's former No. 1 wingers as
his running mates. Allison plays the pivot with Steve Heinze and
Anson Carter, the latter of whom has become the hottest contributor
in a Black-and-Gold uniform the past 2-3 weeks. Carter potted a
pair of goals Thursday night and added an assist, improving his run
to 8-3_11 over his last seven games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anson has proven that how good he wants to be is all up to
him,'' said coach Pat Burns. ``I've asked him in practice, `How
good do you want to be? . . . because it's all up to you.' It
depends on how you are going to come to work everyday. He's
bettered himself in practice. He's big. He's strong. He's a great
skater. And he knows the game. I put him on the ice, no matter what
the situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter's last goal came with the Penguins pressing in Boston's
end, hoping to tie, goaltender Tom Barrasso pulled for the extra
skater. Carter burst out of Boston's end with the puck and
punctuated his night's performance with an open-net stuff.
</P>
<P>
   ``He could be a bonafide power forward in this league,'' said
Allison, who played with Carter briefly in Washington and came here
with him when the Bruins gave up on their old guys, Adam Oates,
Rick Tocchet, and Bill Ranford. ``He's got the size, the speed, the
strength. It's like any of us . . . Joe, me, Sergei (Samsonov) . .
. it's a matter of time for a lot of guys. This is AC's second full
year, playing regular, and he's developing that consistency.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruins captain Ray Bourque says Carter can be a ``scary
player.'' He likes his skating, his speed, his attack to the net.
</P>
<P>
   This is a rebuilding program that finally has come to blossom.
Will two lines carry the Bruins to the Cup finals for the first
time since 1990? No one knows. If they can make it out of the first
round, that alone will be heady stuff, considering that only 24
months ago they finished dead last with a dead-last product.
</P>
<P>
   The Penguins aren't what they were in the early '90s (Mario
Lemieux's retirement and a trip to bankruptcy court can be, well,
limiting), but they certainly represent a fair measuring stick for
what the Bruins could face against Ottawa or Carolina _ two of
their prospective first-round opponents. The murmuring around the
locker room is that New Jersey could be Boston's toughest foe, but
the consistency and the enthusiasm in the Boston room the last
couple of weeks doesn't make the Devils look like those late-'70s
Canadiens. New Jersey is good, but beatable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a lot of teams are wondering about us right now,''
said Dafoe. ``The last 20 games, we've been one of the better teams
in hockey. There's a lot of confidence. I've won five in a row, and
I expect to win every time I go out there. And it's not just me _
it's everyone in the room.''
</P>
<P>
   They're back. They're viable. They're not big scorers, but
they're respectable, and they can button down in the back end as
well as anyone. The Hockey Hub has a pulse again, finally.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
