r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-COYOTES-BLUES-AZR     04-16 0658
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES-BLUES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLUES' POWER PLAY TOO MUCH FOR COYOTES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By TIM TYERS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Was it a sign of impending doom? Whatever it was, it
was a perfect contrast of two teams going into the playoffs while
headed in different directions.
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes, the No. 4 seed in the Western Conference, are going
in without Jeremy Roenick, their leading scorer, and are operating
with a dark cloud above their heads and on a five-game losing
streak after surrendering five third-period goals in a 6-4 loss to
the St. Louis Blues.
</P>
<P>
   The Blues, on the other hand, have lost only one of six games in
April and captured the No. 5 playoff seed and a first-round date
with the Coyotes thanks to the comeback victory and Anaheim's 4-3
overtime loss to Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get it turned around with a win,'' Coyotes Coach Jim
Schoenfeld said. ``We have one more game (Dallas at home on
Saturday) and if we don't get that one, we'll win the first playoff
game and everything will be fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Veteran Blues defenseman Al MacInnis didn't disagree, saying,
``They've known where they're going to finish for quite sometime
and it's tough to get motivated when there's really not a lot to
play for.''
</P>
<P>
   With Roenick in a local hospital after undergoing a 5{-hour
surgical procedure to repair a jaw broken in three places on
Wednesday night at Dallas, Keith Tkachuk produced two goals, Rick
Tocchet one and Shane Doan a late goal, but it wasn't nearly enough
to offset the Blues third-period explosion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, we're upset at losing JR, but you have to put it in the
back of your mind,'' Tocchet said. ``We've got guys who don't play
as much who are going to have to play more and fill the role up the
middle. We can't sit around here everyday and say, `We wish we had
JR.'
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a better chance at winning the Stanley Cup with JR,
but right now we have to figure a way to beat the St. Louis Blues
and we have enough guys to do it, but we have to get more
disciplined.''
</P>
<P>
   As in eliminating the dumb penalties.
</P>
<P>
   As for filling the role up the middle, Schoenfeld experimented a
bit by playing Tkachuk at center with Greg Adams and Dallas Drake
on the wings.
</P>
<P>
   It was one of those rare games when the term ``power play''
actually meant something. The Coyotes, who scored two power play
goals for the first time in 52 games after scoring only five on
their previous 45 chances, and especially for the Blues, who scored
four.
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis took a 4-2 lead with almost 8:57 left on Scott Young's
second goal, and neither team had scored an even-strength goal. The
Blues capped off a four minute and four second span in which they
capitalized on three straight power play opportunities to make a
2-1 Coyotes' lead provided by power play goals from Tkachuk and
Tocchet a fleeting a memory.
</P>
<P>
   It goes without saying that the Blues fourth-ranked power play
was unimpressed with the Coyotes' third-ranked penalty killing
unit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to kill basically for the whole third period,'' Tocchet
said. ``Robert Reichel, myself, Dallas Drake were all sitting, so
you can't get an offensive thrust going and they get four power
play goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just wanted to play hard. We played hard (Wednesday) in
Dallas and we battled to the end tonight. Their special teams
outplayed our special teams today. I'd rather lose now than in
another week.''
</P>
<P>
   The sudden demise started when Coyotes defenseman Oleg
Tverdovsky was hit with a double minor for high sticking St. Louis'
Michel Picard at 6:42 of the third.
</P>
<P>
   The Blues' Geoff Courtnall knocked home the tying goal past
goalie Nikolai Khabibulin.
</P>
<P>
   It took only 93 seconds more for the Blues' Young score on a
slap shot.
</P>
<P>
   Coyotes defenseman Keith Carney picked up a penalty on the play,
and Al MacInnis, who possesses the NHL's hardest slap shot, scored
his 21st, tops among NHL defensemen.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
