<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAMMEUS-EVIL-$ADV18-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WE HAVE TO WRESTLE WITH OUR DEMONS EVERY DAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL TAMMEUS  
 c. 1999 KANSAS CITY STAR 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the mysteries of our civic life is how our most prominent
public sinner, Bill Clinton, is able to diagnose the human
condition with such consistent accuracy. Maybe it's because he's
had to confront his own iniquities so publicly. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A recent example of his insight is found in remarks he made
earlier this month when he asked Congress to extend federal hate
crimes legislation to cover gays and lesbians. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The old, haunting demons,'' he said, ``are hard to root out of
the human spirit.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   No matter what good people do _ and sometimes that good is
simply breathtaking _ the reality is that they also are
persistently infected by evil, by bad motives. They are, thus,
capable of cruelty, malevolence, savagery. Why else would we even
need hate crimes legislation? Why else would we need jails or
armies or police or, for that matter, any laws at all? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This, of course, is not a new phenomenon, unique to our bloody
century of Holocaust and surgical airstrikes that produce
``collateral damage,'' the kinder, gentler name we now use for dead
people. Rather, this condition is as old as holy writ. The King
James Version of Jeremiah 17:9 shouts this truth through the long
corridors of sad human history: ``The heart is deceitful above all
things, and desperately wicked: who can know it?'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This recognition of human failings caused some of the 16th
century theological reformers to adopt what is known as the
Doctrine of the Total Depravity of Humankind. Despite its overblown
name, it does not say there is no good in us or that we are
incapable of good deeds. But it does acknowledge what Bill Clinton
was conceding recently: We all sin and fall short not only of God's
mark for us but also of our best mark for ourselves. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Clinton _ who in his post-impeachment life can't say these
things without them seeming to drip with accusatory irony _ put it
this way: ``We should remember that each of us. . .wakes up every
day with the scales of light and the scales of darkness in our own
hearts, and we've got to keep them in proper balance.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The crucial insight in his words is that, this side of heaven,
we cannot rid ourselves of the darkness in our hearts. Rather, we
must wrestle with those demons every day, trying our best to keep
them from lashing out and injuring ourselves and others. And we
must take responsibility and try to make amends when, in our
weakness, we give in to their destructive urgings. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Despite all this, we continue dreaming of perfection. History is
full of efforts to create utopia, some golden age of righteousness
in which our all motives are pure, all our acts benevolent, all our
problems solved. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, our idealistic nation is dotted with failed utopias _
from the Ephrata Community in Pennsylvania to New Harmony in
Indiana, from Brook Farm in Massachusetts to the Oneida Community
in Vermont. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But what the utopian enthusiasts behind these naive efforts
either forgot or never knew is that when Sir Thomas More first used
the word utopia in the early 1500s, its roots were Greek _
(ital)ou(end-ital) for ``not'' and (ital)topos(end-ital) for
``place.'' So utopia, literally, meant nowhere. And even today that
is where we'll find utopia _ nowhere. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The implications of this are sobering. It means we are,
individually and collectively, called on to remember our weaknesses
and vulnerabilities and to support each other's efforts to suppress
the evil within us. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The stained human condition requires vigilance against the
twisted inclinations our pestilent hearts. And this, sad to say, is
a lifelong task. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Tammeus is a columnist for The Kansas City Star. This
article was distributed by The New York Times News Service. E-mail:
tammeus(at)kcstar.com.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (This column is for use Sunday, April 18, and thereafter.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
