<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SESURVEY-CHATTANOOGA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cities must develop 20-year plan by 2001
 &HT;    By Arthur Brice
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHATTANOOGA _ Some political leaders here look 100 miles to the
south and see a paradise called Atlanta, a land of silk and money
where jobs fall from trees like ripened fruit and the sun never
sets on opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, these politicians will tell you, they know about metro
Atlanta's traffic gridlock and dirty air and out-of-control sprawl.
But they think they can do better.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd like to have that problem,'' said Hamilton County
Commissioner Harold Coker. ``Twenty-five percent of the growth in
the Southeast in the next 10 years will be in Atlanta. Give us that
25 percent growth. We'll handle the roads and traffic.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Tennessee Legislature, determined not to replicate the
problems plaguing Atlanta and other urban sprawl areas, is not so
sure that local leaders can handle growth without some strict
guidelines. That's why last year the legislature passed the Urban
Growth Policy Act, mandating that each county and city in Tennessee
develop a 20-year plan for orderly growth. Failure to do so by July
1, 2001, could result in the loss of state grants and loans for
highways, community development and tourism.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on who's talking, the Tennessee law is either one of
the most progressive or one of the most restrictive in the nation.
Some people will say it's both.
</P>
<P>
   In the Chattanooga area, a builders' group bought radio ads in
January warning of jeopardy to ``the American dream of
homeownership.'' At the same time, a group of developers,
manufacturers, mortgage bankers and insurers disseminated a
four-page letter questioning whether the new plan would be so
restrictive it would stifle growth, drive up housing prices and
scare away employers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an awful lot of fear about taking this kind of step,''
said Ann Coulter, executive director of the Regional Planning
Agency, which handles planning for Hamilton County and all but one
of its 10 cities. ``Any change is fearful. We've never done this
kind of planning before, and that's really scary.''
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, the Tennessee plan dictates that each county and
the cities within that county must agree on urban growth boundaries
to guide development for the next 20 years. Each plan must detail
how compact and contiguous high-density development will be
handled. The Tennessee law says communities must protect
agricultural, forest, recreation and wildlife areas.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, counties and cities must agree on how to make their
growth plans work together, offering a unified master blueprint to
the state. In Hamilton County, that means that Chattanooga and nine
other municipalities must agree with county officials on the master
plan.
</P>
<P>
   A 20-member county Coordinating Committee started work in August
1998 to work out details of the plan. The panel expects to issue a
preliminary report by the end of May, said Coulter.
</P>
<P>
   After that, each of the local governments must hold two public
hearings before submitting proposed boundaries back to the
coordinating committee, which will then have three months to work
out differences. According to that ambitious timetable, the
comprehensive plan would be completed by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   But obstacles already are cropping up. Earlier this month, some
county commissioners said they want to take responsibility for the
growth plan away from the coordinating committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's quite a lot of upheaval about the fact that a
non-elected group is going to manage the land use,'' County
Commissioner Coker said. Coker also sees the growth plan helping to
develop Chattanooga at the expense of Hamilton County. Part of that
suspicion is based on the $355 million that Chattanooga has spent
on downtown redevelopment in the past 10 years, achieving notable
success with such ventures as the $45 million Tennessee Aquarium.
</P>
<P>
   Coker says Chattanooga Mayor Jon Kinsey is ``attempting to keep
everything downtown.'' ``That's not the case,'' Kinsey replied.
``We want growth in this area, in this region.'' That growth must
be planned, said Kinsey, a former developer, to provide for
infrastructure and other needs.
</P>
<P>
   This county vs. city conflict is not new, nor solely the result
of the growth plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've always had some of that, and I regret that,'' Coker
said.
</P>
<P>
   Coulter, the regional planning head, downplays any territorial
squabbles among the elected officials on the coordinating
committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are dedicated to their own jurisdictions, but I've seen a
tremendous amount of realization on their part that we're all in
this together,'' she said. ``They're doing a good job of keeping
their eyes on the goal.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton County Executive Claude Ramsey says he supports both
growth and the new plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to continue to see housing developed in unincorporated
parts of the county as well as incorporated parts of the county,''
he said. ``We're looking at orderly transition. I'm all for putting
in sewers and roads.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Ramsey said, he wants to be able to protect
the rights of private property owners, particularly in rural areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``A farmer should have the right to operate his farm that's been
there. Government shouldn't take that away from him,'' Ramsey said.
``And a farmer should have the right to sell his property. For a
lot of farmers, that's their retirement.''
</P>
<P>
   Coulter also wants to reassure property owners' concerns that
they will lose control over their land, particularly if they want
to sell or develop it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We already make decisions locally on a daily basis that affect
private property values,'' she said. ``This legislation does
nothing that is not already affected.''
</P>
<P>
   She sees the growth plan as a tool to catalyze growth rather
than inhibit it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I happen to believe this will create opportunity,'' Coulter
said. ``We can use good information to pinpoint places where growth
makes the most sense.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, though, she and most others working on the plan realize
they have much difficult work ahead, particularly getting all the
competing economic and political interests to agree on it.
</P>
<P>
   Not until then will anyone be able to judge the new law, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only time will tell how good it is,'' Coulter said. ``How we
approach it and implement it will determine how good a law it is.''
</P>
<P>
   quote: ``Twenty-five percent of the growth in the Southeast in
the next 10 years will be in Atlanta. Give us that 25 percent
growth. We'll handle the roads and traffic.''
</P>
<P>
   HAROLD COKER
</P>
<P>
   Commissioner/Hamilton County
</P>
<P>
   Arthur Brice writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
