<TEXT>
<P>
   DISPATCHES FROM DREAMSVILLE: A young girl gets her pony
</P>
<P>
   (''Dispatches from Dreamsville'' is an occasional series in
which readers share with Cox Newspapers senior writer Joe Murray
their memories of growing up in small-town America. Back then, or
at least the way we remember it, life was like a dream.)
</P>
<P>
   By Georgia Morgan
</P>
<P>
   Special to Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   As a young girl, I was crazy about horses. I begged my folks for
one. There was a slight problem, though.
</P>
<P>
   We lived in the city. No space for a horse, and probably against
zoning laws, as well.
</P>
<P>
   Too young to understand, I refused to accept that excuse. I saw
no reason why a horse couldn't be kept in our garage at the back
alley.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes on Sunday afternoons, our family piled into the car
for a drive through the country, where I pointed out every horse
along the way, determined that my parents wouldn't forget my wish.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever we went to a fair or amusement park, I headed first for
the pony rides.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes I was given extra rides free because I was a good
little rider, or perhaps the owner of the ponies thought it might
draw a crowd to see a little girl having such a good time and
handling the pony so easily.
</P>
<P>
   Round and round, the pony and I went in the little ring, both of
us bouncing fast all the way.
</P>
<P>
   If no pony rides were available, I settled for second choice,
the merry-go-round.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the ride stopped for my turn, I had scrutinized
every horse and chosen one that had the characteristics I wanted:
arched neck, flowing mane and black.
</P>
<P>
   I was very upset if someone else grabbed that horse first.
</P>
<P>
   The best times came in summer when I spent a couple of weeks at
my grandparents' farm. What a wonderful change from the confining
city!
</P>
<P>
   Roaming over the land, exploring everything, gave me an
exhilarating feeling of freedom.
</P>
<P>
   The barn was a favorite place to play, so huge and seemingly
mysterious to a little girl.
</P>
<P>
   Climbing the ladder to the loft, I jumped into the fragrant hay.
After a few jumps, I was covered with scratchy hay, all through my
hair and even inside my clothes.
</P>
<P>
   On the farm were lots of animals: milk cows, pigs, sheep,
chickens _ but best of all, two huge work horses: Dick, a dark
horse, and Lindy, a gray.
</P>
<P>
   When my grandparents had some extra time, which wasn't often
because they worked hard from sunup to sundown, Lindy would be led
from her stall and I would be hoisted up to ride bareback around
the barnyard.
</P>
<P>
   I perched precariously on top of her broad back, pressing my
legs as tightly as I could along her big, round sides.
</P>
<P>
   Lindy was in no hurry, so we plodded along, her huge hooves
marking circles in the dirt.
</P>
<P>
   Those vacation days sped by quickly, and too soon I was back in
the city, back to begging my parents for a horse.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, when I was about 10 years old, my parents bought a
house in the country with 10 acres and plenty of pasture for a
horse.
</P>
<P>
   They had no excuses left, so the search for a horse began.
</P>
<P>
   Daddy located an old horse trainer who from time to time
acquired horses and trained them for buyers.
</P>
<P>
   In his pasture lot was a beautiful, sleek black stallion with a
white blaze down the front of his head.
</P>
<P>
   After mounting him, I realized he was a lot of horse to handle,
but I hoped more training would settle him down.
</P>
<P>
   Off to one side, Daddy and the trainer had a discussion and the
deal was set _ or so we thought.
</P>
<P>
   Later we found that the trainer had sold the horse to someone
else for a better price.
</P>
<P>
   I was crushed and Daddy was angry, and he let the trainer know
it. To make amends, he gave us a good price on a lovely black and
spotted filly, nicely trained for riding and ready to come home
with me.
</P>
<P>
   What a thrill to be saddling up my very own horse and taking off
down the country road, the filly happily tossing her head and
occasionally snorting or neighing at some other horse in a nearby
pasture.
</P>
<P>
   The feel of her strong body moving under me and responding to my
every command was exhilarating.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually I found first an old buggy and light driving harness
and then a beautiful red sleigh with bells on the shaves in
neighboring farmers' barns and I trained my horse to pull them.
</P>
<P>
   What a wonderful horse I had! She and I learned to accommodate,
trust and respect each other, and we always remained friends.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Morgan lives in Springfield, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (If you have a story to share, send it to ``Dispatches from
Dreamsville,'' c/o Joe Murray, Cox Newspapers, P.O. Box 151108,
Lufkin, Texas, 75915. A photo of the writer is optional. If your
article is used, you will receive $25. Look for other Dreamsville
stories at http://www.geocities.com/SoHo/Bistro/7147/.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
