<SLUG> BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-$ADV22-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMEN, HOUSE CLEANING AND GUILT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Thursday April 22)  
 By SUSAN SWARTZ   
 Santa Rosa (Calif.) Press Democrat   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If there is common male resistance to asking a stranger for
directions, the female version is asking a stranger to clean her
house.
</P>
<P>
   The guilt. You can't clean that little house yourself? You have
money to spare, you should give it to the poor. Or save it for your
old age.
</P>
<P>
   Is it a frugal streak? Is it fear of appearing pretentious? Or
is it even sicker, like I want the world to think I can do it all,
including wax my own floors?
</P>
<P>
   Hardly. I am one generation removed from smiling women in soap
ads wearing shirtdresses and rubber gloves and while there might be
a descendant some day who will find satisfaction in clean cupboards
it will not be my legacy.
</P>
<P>
   I love the house and I love creating the mess and I understand
the need for order and sanitary conditions, but I don't want to do
it.
</P>
<P>
   So, this spring, or any season thereafter, I will not be doing
my own spring cleaning (like she ever knew the concept, some might
observe) but have acquired the services of a professional.
</P>
<P>
   My house deserves this. The people whom I invite to use my
bathtub deserve this.
</P>
<P>
   A friend absolved me by saying that she gives herself two
things, no matter the cost, to ensure her safety and happiness - a
car that runs and a clean house. That got me thinking. We don't
even try to do our own 80,000 mile overhaul, why should we clean
the house?
</P>
<P>
   In the same way I don't cut my own hair or give myself a
massage, fix my own computer or haul my own garbage to the dump.
</P>
<P>
   This should not be an embarrassing luxury. Some people pay as
much for a bottle of wine as I pay for a clean house.
</P>
<P>
   So, I drive off to the office, not trying to imagine her looking
around and thinking, ``My god, they live like pigs.''
</P>
<P>
   That's part of it. We think everyone but us is working
undercover for public health. We suspect we've got more mold and
fuzz than anyone else even though we bathe every day and change our
sheets once a week. Anyone who's been to a garage sale knows that
most kitchens produce the same cookie pans encrusted with black
gunk. My plumber says what lives under our sink is no more shocking
than others he's seen. And I'm told the spider webs that hang in
sticky loops and regenerate nightly are found in some of the best
homes.
</P>
<P>
   There are spotless houses, where you want to show up
unexpectedly just to see where they normally stack their New
Yorkers. The houses where you leave, asking each other, ``Where do
they keep the dog hair?''
</P>
<P>
   While it is true that there are intensely clean people, the
average person is kind of a slob. But a well-meaning slob. We might
try but we can't possibly hold to the standards of a trained
specialist.
</P>
<P>
   I've seen what this woman can do in a few focused hours. She's a
marvel. She has sandblasted the shower walls cleaner than they were
before we bought the house. The tea kettle gleams as much as the
windows. I've always said that if you keep the lamps low, light
candles and put flowers around no one will notice the wine stain
under the coffee table, but I'm so relieved that she is taking us
beyond.
</P>
<P>
   This is one of those issues that came up in the earlier days of
feminism. We were not going to let a clean house be the measure of
a woman. We had careers to manage, children to nurture, more
essential ways to prove ourselves than whether the guests could see
their reflection in the dining room table. Worrying over the house
didn't fit our new freewheeling image. We would be known for our
wit, not our stain-free stovetops.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, we asked, if someone really appreciated the real you,
would they even notice your clutter?
</P>
<P>
   It turned out the answer was yes, and to them you can say,
``You're right. We're hiring someone.''
</P>
<P>
   (Susan Swartz is a columnist for The Press Democrat in Santa
Rosa, Calif. Her e-mail address is sfswartz(AT)pressdemo.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
