<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-16 10:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1137 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LOFTUS-COLUMN-$ADV22-     04-16 0578
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOFTUS-COLUMN-$ADV22-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHILDREN AND ROTOVIRUS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Thursday April 22)  
 By MARY J. LOFTUS   
 Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I have one wish for all families of small children this spring,
when nature's using every crayon in the box for red cardinals
streaking across treetops and yellow buds popping up on fresh-cut
green lawns and blue cloudless skies.
</P>
<P>
   And that wish is ... may rotavirus never descend upon your
family as it has ours.
</P>
<P>
   There it is in my ``Portable Pediatrician,'' a small, seemingly
innocuous entry: ``This is the most common cause of wintertime
diarrhea in young children in the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Also called ``the daycare virus,'' it targets the small
intestine and usually lasts from three to eight days. Some children
are quite ill and run a fever. Other children, and most adults who
become reinfected with the virus, have no symptoms at all.
</P>
<P>
   You never realize how long eight days can be. Or how lucky those
``other children, and most adults'' are to be asymptomatic to the
plague that is rotavirus.
</P>
<P>
   Spring break started on a high note. We had an Easter egg hunt,
ate the lion's share of the chocolate, stuffed swimsuits, shorts
and sandals into suitcases, packed up the minivan and set off from
Atlanta to Florida for a week of Adventure Island and Universal
Studios.
</P>
<P>
   We got as far as Macon before my 2-year-old threw up all over
the van, and her brother.
</P>
<P>
   We stopped at a motel, since my early, optimistic interpretation
was this: Too much Easter candy, resume trip tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   By 6:30 a.m., however, we were headed back to our house, armed
with Gatorade and soda crackers.
</P>
<P>
   By the next day, we were at the doctor's office (not to be
confused with Disney World) and he was nodding sympathetically.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's lost two pounds, which is 5 percent of her body weight.
If it goes up to 10 percent, we're looking at getting her to an
emergency room to start on an IV. We'll know in the next day or
so.''
</P>
<P>
   Sarah laid her head listlessly on my shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   ``No doctor can treat rotavirus,'' he said, patting her back.
``We can just offer support to the parents, and hope dehydration
doesn't set in.'' He said it was one of the most contagious of all
viruses, and can live outside the body for hours.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next few days, Sarah's illness followed its insidious
course, with false improvements and rapid relapses. Luckily, my
8-year-old was outside the target age. (``By 4, most persons have
been infected with the rotavirus and acquire long-term immunity.'')
</P>
<P>
   So while dad stayed with Sarah for an afternoon, Adam invited a
friend to come to Stone Mountain with us.
</P>
<P>
   After the ferry ride, we had cherry icees. Adam had two sips
before announcing, ``I think I'm seasick.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed.
</P>
<P>
   From the rotavirus fact sheet: ``The incubation period is
usually two days. One-third of children infected with the virus
will become ill. Improvements in sanitation and hygiene do not seem
to affect the spread.''
</P>
<P>
   And so, another eight days began.
</P>
<P>
   To all of the 3.5 million families a year who have experienced
the dreaded rotavirus, my sympathies.
</P>
<P>
   But take heart: several Internet entries list rotavirus under
``new up and coming vaccinations.''
</P>
<P>
   Here's to cheerier springs ahead.
</P>
<P>
   (Mary J. Loftus is a New York Times Regional Newspapers feature
writer. She has master's and specialist degrees in marriage and
family counseling.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
