<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Friday, April 16, 1999      The Hearst News Service will file these stories for the weekend.
If you have questions, please call Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   ABORTION (Albany, N.Y.) _ Days before one of the largest
national anti-abortion protests of the year begins on Sunday, a
federal judge here has ruled that buffer zones around reproductive
services clinics in western New York should be expanded, holding
back potentially hostile demonstrators by up to 60 feet. By LARA
JAKES.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE (San Francisco) _ With a serendipitous combination of
mild weather and a tradition of spurning tradition, the San
Francisco Bay area has given rise to inventions and discoveries
that have shaken the world _ sometimes literally. Accomplishments
of the last 99 years have allowed humanity to transcend time, space
and conventional human limits in once-unimagined ways. By KEAY
DAVIDSON.
</P>
<P>
   PRESS-KOSOVO (San Francisco) _ President Clinton noted in a
speech to newspaper editors here the ``stark contrast between a
free society with a free press and a closed society where the press
is used to manipulate people by suppressing or distorting the
truth.'' But while U.S. journalists are not being found shot dead,
some of America's most prominent opinion-makers are accusing the
Pentagon of kidnapping the facts on the war in Kosovo. By ROBERT
SALLADAY.
</P>
<P>
   OLMOS-EDITORS (San Francisco) _ Edward James Olmos, the
52-year-old actor, producer and community activist, took on yet
another challenge this week as he charmed, goaded and provoked the
country's newspaper editors meeting in San Francisco, urging them
to wake up and see the diversity that is changing the world around
them. By ANNIE NAKAO.
</P>
<P>
   1906-QUAKE-RECALLED (San Francisco) _ Survivors of the April 18,
1906, earthquake might be the rarest people around San Francisco
and Ernest Latapie is the rarest of the rare: Not only was he alive
when the city collapsed and burned, but he remembers vividly the
horror of the moment. By MICHAEL DOUGAN.
</P>
<P>
   RADIOACTIVE-AMMO (San Francisco) _ Ask Dr. Michael Kilpatrick, a
top Pentagon doctor, about a new study that says radioactive
ammunition used during the Persian Gulf War isn't likely to cause
lung cancer or other health problems, and he says: ``It's very
reassuring.'' But an internationally known radiation expert
compared the new Pentagon-sponsored study with reports on nicotine
from the tobacco industry. By KATHLEEN SULLIVAN.
</P>
<P>
   BENEFITS-IMMIGRANTS (San Francisco) _ California Gov. Gray
Davis' decision to ask a federal appeals court to mediate the legal
battle over Proposition 187, the voter-approved initiative limiting
benefits to illegal immigrants, has met with skepticism from all
sides, casting doubt on whether a settlement can be reached. By
JULIE CHAO.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   WOMEN-PAY (Albany, N.Y.) _ A lack of pay parity for women in the
workplace remains a societal problem, says Ida L. Castro, head of
the Equal Employment Opportunity Commission. When women are
underpaid, children and their husbands suffer economic hardship,
Castro says. By JO-ANN JOHNSTON.
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-COLUMN (Undated) _ Reviews of the new Palm Pilot V and
Compaq Aero 2100 hand-held computers. By DWIGHT SILVERMAN.
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-HELPLINE (Undated) _ Advice on screen-savers, fonts and
3-D games. By DWIGHT SILVERMAN.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   WHEELED-BOOK-BAGS (Albany, N.Y.) _ In the old days, kids carried
their books to school by hand. Then came canvas sacks _ or for
nerdy students, briefcases. By the 1970s, students were toting
books in canvas military surplus bags. Since the 1980s, bright
nylon backpacks held sway. Now, the most fashion-forward students
are going mobile, using backpacks or small suitcases with wheels to
cart their books around. It's just starting, but the wheeled book
bag may be the next Big Thing for kids. By RICK KARLIN.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TV-TURNOFF (Albany, N.Y.) _ Every April brings the same thing:
the baseball season, taxes and children are urged to turn off their
television sets for a week. I have no problem with temporary
abstinence from TV. But turning it off completely denies children
and adults a window to the world. By MARK McGUIRE.
</P>
<P>
   DC-TALK (Houston) _ dc Talk is all about making good God music.
The talented trio _ Toby McKeehan, Michael Tait and Kevin Max _ is
ensconced in the Top 10 on Billboard's contemporary Christian music
chart. By RICHARD VARA.
</P>
<P>
   CELINE (Houston) _ Celine Dion is no ordinary diva. She proved
it before a Houston audience this week. By JOEY GUERRA &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-MOONWALK (Undated) _ In case you miss the metaphor
crashing into your head like a block of concrete, ``A Walk on the
Moon'' is about discovery. It's set in the summer of '69, which
means we get Neil Armstrong's ``giant step for mankind'' along with
Woodstock revelers in various states of nudity. Astronautical
discovery, sexual discovery. Get it? By AMY BIANCOLLI.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-LIFE (Undated) _ ``Life'' has every reason to be
funny. It stars Eddie Murphy and Martin Lawrence, two very amusing
guys. Its plot is a comic rehash of ``The Shawshank Redemption.''
And it has the absolute goodwill of the audience, who want it to be
a laff riot. And it is. Sometimes. A little bit. Off and on. By AMY
BIANCOLLI.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   DeBARTOLO (San Francisco) _ After months of silence and
inaction, San Francisco 49ers' co-owner Eddie DeBartolo has gone on
the offense, filing a $150 million federal lawsuit against his
estranged sister, Denise DeBartolo York, and vowing to regain
control of his beloved football team in less than a year. By SCOTT
WINOCUR.
</P>
<P>
   OAKLAND-A'S (San Francisco) _ Officials of Oakland and Alameda
County, Calif., have given a sports investment firm authorization
to sell the Oakland A's if a qualified bidder comes forward. By RAY
DELGADO.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ President Clinton, who redefined
the meaning of sex and the word ``is,'' now is degrading other
parts of the language, including the word ``degrade.'' The man who
dodged the draft has drafted ``degrade'' to replace ``destroy,''
which sounds too brutal in the modern American world of politically
correct warfare. By ROB MORSE.
</P>
</TEXT>
