<P>
   These columns for release Saturday and Sunday, April 17-18, 1999
are moving today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   All columns have moved, in the commentary (k) category. If you
have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the Cox News
Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   TEEPEN-COLUMN _ Skirmishing and random small-arms fire continues
around the church-state issue of posting the Ten Commandments in
courthouses and schools. (Tom Teepen is national correspondent for
Cox Newspapers.) MOVED THURSDAY.
</P>
<P>
   KLEINBERG-COLUMN _ It is not with just mild interest when I note
that the high school art teacher for Kurt Cobain retained some of
his paintings and sketches. Cobain, of course, is the rocker who
became near-deified after his suicide. Not only did the teacher
have the foresight to know that Cobain would turn into a cult
personality (rockers who either commit suicide or die from drug
overdoses have that effect on young people) but he also thought he
could fetch a pretty good buck for the stuff through a Christie's
auction. (Howard Kleinberg is a columnist for Cox News Service.)
MOVED THURSDAY. For Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   GLASS-COLUMN _ CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ Unlike Vice President Al Gore,
Tim Berners-Lee hasn't claimed to have invented the Internet. But
he did invent the World Wide Web, which has made the Internet truly
useful to people. He's still full of ideas. (Andy Glass is a
columnist for Cox News Service in the Washington bureau.) MOVED
THURSDAY. For Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   JOEMURRAY-COLUMN _ Dispatches from Dreamsville: As a young girl,
I was crazy about horses. I begged my folks for one. (Morgan, Cox
News Service) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   LATHAM-COLUMN _ MARSHALL, Texas _ A reader sent me an e-mail the
other day telling me that I had a ``hidden'' agenda. He was being
too kind, and I mean that sincerely. If only he knew the whole
truth it might make him shudder. No, for a fact, I once hid my
agenda but, like everything else, I forgot where I put the dang
thing. My agenda isn't hidden, it is lost. (Latham, Marshall News
Messenger) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   MINTER-COLUMN _ FAYETTE COUNTY, Ga. _ One of the hazards of
extended international travel is jet lag. Symptoms are numbness
below the waist, swollen feet, difficulty in arm movements,
inability to focus eyes and a persistent dull headache. The good
news is that you eventually recover. (Jim Minter is a former editor
of The Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
