<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEATURES-BJT17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE FEATURES BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These feature stories are moving today to clients of the New
York Times News Service. Stories are for release Saturday, April
17, 1999, unless otherwise embargoed.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   SMALLTOWN-DOC _ ARLINGTON, Ga. _ Dr. Robert E. Jennings took
care of the folks in this one-redlight South Georgia town of
Arlington for 39 years, delivering their babies, sewing up their
chainsaw wounds and even treating the occasional snakebit dog. When
his patients needed help after 5 p.m., they'd call him up at home.
Or drop by. ``People didn't go to the emergency room,'' says his
daughter Felicia Alexander. ``They'd just knock on the back door.''
For years the tall, broad-shouldered physician and his family lived
in a yellow-brick ranch house across the street from the hospital,
so finding the doctor was easy. Finding a replacement won't be.
Jennings died last fall at age 65, leaving the 1,200 residents of
Arlington in shock. Now they're naming Main Street after him, in an
attempt to make sure he's never forgotten. (Emerson, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTOS. For Sunday, April 18.
</P>
<P>
   HEALTH-MAGNETS _ Atlanta researchers are trying to prove magnets
have healing powers, and they're submitting data from testing to
the FDA. (Lore, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT-ARTS
</P>
<P>
   JAZZFESTIVAL _ NEW ORLEANS _ ``When we first started,''
remembers Qunit Davis, director of the New Orleans Jazz &AMP; Heritage
Festival, ``there were a lot of reasons people thought this thing
was a hopeless failure. They said, `You can't mix all these people
_ old people, young people, white people, black people, rich
people, poor people.' '' In 1970, the South had only been
integrated for a few years. Having black and white musicians play
for black and white audiences in the same location was still novel.
``But we had a theory,'' Davis said, ``that if you show people what
each other eats and what each other dances to, it'd be all right.
We were right, it works.'' (Konigsmark, Atlanta
Journal-Consitution). WITH PHOTO. For Sunday, April 18.
</P>
<P>
   SPOLETO-MAMBA _ NEW YORK _ Spoleto preview. Feature on ``Mamba's
Daughters,'' one of the major theater productions at Spoleto this
year. The play by DuBose Heyward (author of ``Porgy'') is set in
Gullah South Carolina and deals with the taboo subject of suicide
in the African-American community. Focusing on actress Heather
Gillespie; also talking to director David Herskovits about his
revival of a play that first opened in 1939 with Ethel Waters and
Alberta Hunter. The ravishingly beautiful, velvet-voiced Gilliespie
had barely arrived from her home in London before she picked up an
Obie Award and got a rave review in the New York Times. We take her
to dinner at the Southern restaurant Jezebel, then go to see
Matthew Bourne's ``Swan Lake'' on Broadway. Play, which is being
seen in Charleston for the first time, runs the entire fest, May
28-June 11. (Brock, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 35. WITH PHOTO
and LAYOUT. For Sunday, April 18.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   SPOLETE-GUIDE _ A guiide to the best events at this year's
Spoleto Festival USA. (Brock, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   CASSANDRA-WILSON _ Interview with Cassandra Wilson, jazz singer
and bluesy signifier, who brings her ``Traveling Miles'' tour to
Variety Playhouse April 22 and at UGA a few days later. We'll talk
about how she approached claiming this beautiful music, made by
notorious misogynist Miles Davis as her womanly own. (Dollar,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 25. WITH PHOTO. For Sunday, April
18.
</P>
<P>
   DELANY _ Review of Delany sisters' movie airing on TV Sunday
night starring Ruby Dee and Diahann Carroll. (Holloway, Austin
American -Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   HOME &AMP; GARDENFURNITURE-TRENDS _ HIGH POINT, N.C. _ What will
home furnishings be like as we enter the 21st century? Hold on to
your slipcovers because that's only a few months away. Already,
trend watchers forecast more contemporary looks, with the clean,
simple lines of Asian themes; an emphasis on French country,
especially gardening motifs; and as we close the book a century of
design, a nostalgic revival of the curvy shapes and sleek finishes
of Art Moderne. Those are just a few predictions as the world's
largest biannual furniture market opened in High Point Thursday.
Will be topped by comments from a panel of design experts,
including Bob Mackie, Vladimir Kagan and Jena Hall. Includes
comments from Atlanta manufacturers. (Flanders, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   WARNER-ON-WOOD _ Japanese vs. Western tools. (Warner, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGIONKOSOVO-CHAPLAINS _ ATLANTA _ As the conflict in and
around Kosovo continues simmering, the Military Chaplains
Association this weeks comes to Atlanta for its annual meeting. We
talk with members to gauge their reaction to recent events and
possible links to others in the combat area and attend several
sessions, including a workshop on ``Religious and Ethical Issues in
the Federal Chaplaincies.'' (GWhite, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (l) Lifestyle and (i) International categories.
</P>
<P>
   BUDDHISM _ The rise in Buddhism and Eastern religions among baby
boomers. Pegged to the Dalai Lama's visit. (Lomartire, Palm Beach
Post). 40. PRIESTS-COPS _ The man who founded the Georgia
Association of Chiefs of Police is not a policeman at all. He's a
Roman Catholic priest. And he was recently given an honorary
doctorate in criminal law for his work with police officers over
the last 45 years. In 1953, two young police officers responding to
a routine call at the Shrine of the Immaculate Conception invited
Monosignor R. Donald Kieran to ride with them. He did and he became
hooked. He is currently chaplain for the Georgia State Patrol, the
DeKalb County Police Department, the GBI and the regional office of
the federal Division of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms. We talk to
Kieran about his years of experience and his fascination with
police work, and with some of the cops he has befriended over the
years. (GWhite, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).BUDGET INFORMATION
</P>
<P>
   So specialty editors won't have to look at every day's budget,
Cox's features budgets have daily themes according tothis schedule:
</P>
<P>
   Monday for Tuesday: Technology
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday for Wednesday: Automotive
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday for Thursday: Food, CD reviews, video reviews
</P>
<P>
   Thursday for Friday: Movie reviews, travel, books, fashion, and
home &AMP; garden
</P>
<P>
   TODAY: Religion and science &AMP; health
</P>
<P>
   In addition, separate budgets move daily with spot news, sports,
business and commentary.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the category they're listed under. Stories
moving to duplicate categories are marked. An ETA is given if a
story will move after 8 p.m. Eastern.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   LOOK ON THE WEB: Stories marked as a CoxNet layout are available
for purchase in paginated form: www.nytsyn.com/pageexpress.
</P>
