<DOCNO> NYT19990416.0064 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-16 11:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1164 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LATHAM-COLUMN17-COX     04-16 0593
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LATHAM-COLUMN17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    At long last I'm revealing my hidden agenda
 &HT;    By Phil Latham
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARSHALL, Texas _ A reader sent me an e-mail the other day
telling me that I had a ``hidden'' agenda. He was being too kind,
and I mean that sincerely. If only he knew the whole truth it might
make him shudder.
</P>
<P>
   No, for a fact, I once hid my agenda but, like everything else,
I forgot where I put the dang thing. My agenda isn't hidden, it is
lost.
</P>
<P>
   Next time I make an agenda _ and I'm not planning on doing this
anytime soon _ I'm going to put a Clapper(TM) by Ronco on it. That
way, when I forget where it is, I can just clap my hands a couple
of times, it will start beeping and the sound will lead me right to
the spot.
</P>
<P>
   The last time I saw my agenda, it was lying under a stack of
yellowing newspapers that we were saving to help house-train the
dog. It seemed like all we did was train the dog not to use the
bathroom on newspapers. So, we
</P>
<P>
   gave up and just put the dog outside before I uncovered the
agenda. Come to think of it, though, I don't think ``house-train
the dog'' was ever on my agenda.
</P>
<P>
   I guess I could say that the dog ate my agenda, but, when I used
that excuse in grade school, it got me whacked on the rear. Of
course, the dog eating my agenda could explain why it hasn't been
feeling all that well lately. An agenda like mine could give even a
dog a nasty case of indigestion.
</P>
<P>
   Even when my agenda was under the newspapers, it was not so much
hidden as just lying there waiting to be picked up. Of course, with
four children, it could be said that everything that enters my
house, including living things, is eventually ``hidden'' under
something. Why should an agenda be any different?
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, try as I might, I cannot remember what was on my
agenda or even what I might have been hoping to accomplish when I
set it forth. You'll understand just how embarrassing it is not to
know your own agenda, all the more true when it is a hidden agenda
that you've forgotten to memorize.
</P>
<P>
   I'm pretty sure that it started out with a prayer _ all my
agendas, hidden or otherwise, start out that way. On the other
hand, I'm not sure my agenda called anything to order, or perhaps I
just hadn't made it that far down the list before I ``hid'' it
forever.
</P>
<P>
   I can't even remember what was Number One on my agenda. You
always hear people talking about Number One on their agendas, but
it beats me what was Number One on my agenda, or Number Five or
even if there was a Number Five.
</P>
<P>
   I am pretty sure that my agenda did not include promoting gun
control, rampant pornography or abortions on demand. Likewise, my
agenda almost certainly did not have items for saving whales, seals
or spotted owls.
</P>
<P>
   It is far more likely that my 11-point agenda went something
like this:
</P>
<P>
   1. Sit in recliner.
</P>
<P>
   2. Eat a Ding Dong.
</P>
<P>
   3. Sit back in recliner.
</P>
<P>
   4. Nap.
</P>
<P>
   5. Eat lunch.
</P>
<P>
   6. Sit back in recliner.
</P>
<P>
   7. Exercise by walking upstairs to bed.
</P>
<P>
   8. Nap.
</P>
<P>
   9. Think about hunting for that hidden agenda.
</P>
<P>
   10. Eat a Ding Dong.
</P>
<P>
   11. Start back at Number One.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, why worry about finding my hidden agenda anyway? The
one I just wrote is probably better than what I had before, anyway.
No more hidden agendas for me, even if they get eaten by the dog.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Latham is editor and publisher of the Marshall News
Messenger. His e-mail address is platham(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
