<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINTER-COLUMN17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jet lag's strange effects can take time to heal
 &HT;    By Jim Minter
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FAYETTE COUNTY, Ga. _ One of the hazards of extended
international travel is jet lag. Symptoms are numbness below the
waist, swollen feet, difficulty in arm movements, inability to
focus eyes and a persistent dull headache. The good news is that
you eventually recover.
</P>
<P>
   My Athens friend Dan Magill called to say he is nearly back to
normal after three weeks in China.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's encouraging,'' I told him. ``Exactly when were you in
China?''
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1983,'' he replied.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to physical effects, your mind goes away for at
least a couple of months. Acute jet lag was to blame last week when
I got the Southside Clack boys and their wives reversed. Jerry is
married to Barbara. His older brother Jim is married to Jeannette.
I wrote it the other way around and hereby offer a retraction and
apology.
</P>
<P>
   Such errors can be excused due to the extra burden I carried
through Australia, New Zealand and the Fiji Islands. In addition to
hauling my Marco Polo-related wife's bags laden with goods
sufficient to stock a medium-size department store and a couple of
souvenir shops, I had to keep an eye on Bobby Mobley, who, among
other mishaps, managed to get nipped on his rear by a camel.
</P>
<P>
   After saying goodbye to the world's largest crocodile and
purchasing a busload of native goods and trinkets mostly made in
China, we said goodbye to Australia and headed for New Zealand,
which has 3 1/2 million people, 85 million sheep and, according to
Furman Bisher, about that many golf courses.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody in New Zealand is either hang-gliding, bungee-jumping
or taking an afternoon stroll on a glacier. At my age, I was happy
enough to settle for watching a sheep shearer shear a sheep. (Try
to read that sentence while suffering from jet lag.)
</P>
<P>
   The biggest difference in touring Australia and New Zealand,
compared to Europe, is you don't have to visit two dozen castles
and cathedrals built 400 years ago. Australia and New Zealand are
younger than Fayette County and apparently have only a couple of
churches between them.
</P>
<P>
   Since Australia was settled by criminals shipped out from
England, you don't expect it to be an overly religious country, and
you don't brag about having relatives living there. I checked the
local telephone books hoping not to find any Minters. I discovered
Sydney full of Minters, likely descended from criminals.
</P>
<P>
   Fiji was different. Methodist missionaries got a foothold about
the time our great-grandpas were fighting Yankees in Virginia.
Natives, who 150 years ago dined on each other, greet tourists with
a cry of ``Boula! Boula!'' I thought we'd run into a bunch of South
Pacific Yalies, until our local guide told us that ``Boula'' means
welcome, have a good day, and a lot of other nice things.
Everywhere we went we got boulaed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably means `sucker' in Fiji language,'' Bobby suggested.
For a good ol' boy from Palmetto, he catches on fast.
</P>
<P>
   Back home in Fayette County, we decided to have our family to
Sunday dinner. Since the cupboard was bare, my traveling companion
had to make a late Saturday trip to the grocery store. Then, punchy
with jet lag, we staggered to bed. We overslept.
</P>
<P>
   In the kitchen, rushing to fix lunch and get off to church, I
offered to help. ``I'll put on the roast,'' I volunteered.
</P>
<P>
   I've been well-trained in roast preparation. First you put the
roast in a paper sack, add flour, pepper and salt, and shake. When
the roast is covered with flour, you pour several tablespoons of
vegetable oil into a Dutch oven, turn the eye to high, sear the
roast on all sides, add an onion and a cup of water, and pop in the
oven at 350. Simple.
</P>
<P>
   She had set the roast out on a counter. Beside the roast was a
plastic bottle with clear lemon-colored liquid inside, freshly
purchased on her shopping trip. I opened the bottle, poured some
into the Dutch oven and turned the eye to high. When I began to
sear the roast it didn't sear.
</P>
<P>
   ``You need more cooking oil,'' she advised.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hand me the bottle,'' I said, reaching over to receive it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can't you read?'' she exclaimed. ``This isn't cooking oil!
It's Pine Sol! For cleaning the bathroom!''
</P>
<P>
   It was not my fault, even considering the effects of acute jet
lag. Any reasonable person would assume that if she put the roast
on the counter she also put cooking oil on the counter.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, it was good to be back home for Sunday lunch with the
family. Turpentine-flavored pot roast isn't all that bad.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Minter is a former editor in chief of The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
