<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARNER-ON-WOOD17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tool choice is all about how you want to handle it
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Offcuts from good old rec.woodworking on the Internet:
``Anybody have a source for light blue wood?'' asks a turner who
wants to make ``Kentucky Wildcat'' pens.
</P>
<P>
   Some of my best friends are, unaccountably, Kentucky alumni, and
I consulted them on this matter. While neither woodworkers nor
arborists, they were of the general opinion that since God had made
both the Wildcats and the grass blue, He must have made a tree to
match.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, I believe the pen maker will do better to use
aniline dye on a white or neutral-colored wood like maple or birch.
</P>
<P>
   Another woodworker asks if he would be better off with a
Japanese dozuki saw or a European back saw for cutting dovetails.
</P>
<P>
   This, of course, is a question impossible to answer. One can
only tell him what works best for oneself. The two saws are as
different as day and night.
</P>
<P>
   The chief difference, of course, is that the back saw is
heavy-bladed, with a brass stiffener on its back, and it cuts on
the forward stroke. The dozuki is thin, whippy, and cuts on the
pull stroke.
</P>
<P>
   If one is accustomed to using larger saws that cut on the push
stroke, then one is likely to be more comfortable with the back
saw. However, if the buyer is a novice and has no commitment to
either technique, then I recommend trying the dozuki.
</P>
<P>
   As with all Japanese tools, one can pay $25-$30 for a perfectly
useful dozuki with a replaceable blade, or one can pay several
hundred dollars for one with ineffable mystique and a
nonreplaceable blade. Since mystique, effable or otherwise, doesn't
cut wood, the cheaper tool will satisfy most of us.
</P>
<P>
   The back saw has to be stiff and heavy, or the blade would bend
and cramp on the push stroke. The dozuki, however, can be so thin
as to cut a hairline kerf because the act of pulling the blade
through the wood serves to tension it. It will cut almost
effortlessly.
</P>
<P>
   Again, however, it's really a matter of taste, like the
never-ending argument over whether to cut the pins or the tails
first.
</P>
<P>
   My pleasure in Japanese saws does not extend to Japanese planes,
except for specialty types like the ones meant for working concave
surfaces. Their planes, not surprisingly, are built to be pulled
rather than pushed, too. Pulling a saw blade is a natural enough
motion, since the stroke is more or less the same for any cut.
Pulling a plane isn't unnatural either, if you're working on a
piece of wood only a couple of feet long.
</P>
<P>
   But on a long plank, it requires not just pulling, but backing
up your whole body. With western planes, one strides forward to
accomplish this. I would much rather take a step or two forward
than move the same distance backward and blind.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Warner writes about woodworking for The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
