A1176 &Cx1f; tad-z
a a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEDICARE-HEALTH-0420-     04-16 0715
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICARE-HEALTH-0420-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MOST MEDICARE PATIENTS DON'T GET NECESSARY PREVENTIVE CARE
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (a) general news categories
 &HT;    For release Tuesday, April 20.
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Most elderly Americans do not receive important
preventive health care services paid for by Medicare, according to
a report issued Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The Dartmouth Atlas of Health Care 1999 also found wide
variations in the levels of Medicare services provided from one
geographic region to another.
</P>
<P>
   The report looked primarily at the impact of Medicare's
fee-for-service program on the 27.7 million elderly enrolled in
1996. It generally did not count those enrolled in Medicare managed
care plans or the nearly 4 million disabled in the Medicare
program, which covers about 38 million Americans. And it did not
analyze the reasons behind the findings.
</P>
<P>
   The report looked at medical resources -- such as the number of
hospital beds, doctors and nurses -- as well as medical conditions
and the range of care provided to patients.
</P>
<P>
   One area where better quality can be achieved -- and Medicare
patients' health improved -- is in preventive services. The report
found fewer than one out of three women aged 65 to 69 received a
mammogram during 1995-96, and in some parts of the country the
ratio was one out of eight women.
</P>
<P>
   Fewer than one out of eight Medicare beneficiaries received a
colorectal examination for cancer and fewer than half were given an
eye examination to detect the onslaught of diabetes.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors recommend that the elderly receive a pneumonia
vaccination at least every 10 years, meaning 10 percent of the
elderly should receive the shot each year. The study found that
only 4.3 percent of beneficiaries were vaccinated in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should be striving for close to 100 percent use of these
specific preventive services considering what we know about
prevention and detection,'' said Dr. John E. Wennberg, director of
the Center for the Evaluative Clinical Sciences at Dartmouth
Medical School and the Atlas' principal investigator.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Jonathan T. Lord, chief operating officer at the American
Hospital Association, said ``physicians and other providers should
see these data as an opportunity to make improvements and to work
together with their patients to make sure everyone is receiving
what are often life-saving preventive services.''
</P>
<P>
   The AHA subsidiary Health Forum publishes the Atlas, which
showed residents of some areas were 10 times more likely to undergo
certain surgical procedures than people elsewhere with the same
illness. For example, surgery to remove the prostate was nearly 10
times more likely in Baton Rouge, La., than in Binghamton, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Such differences do not reflect illness rates, the study
concluded. ``Variations in the rates of the use of these procedures
reflect variations in practice style and in how physicians diagnose
and treat common clinical conditions,'' the report said.
</P>
<P>
   End-of-life treatment patterns also varied widely. In some
places, such as Miami, Fla., more than one-third of the Medicare
patients saw 10 or more doctors during their last six months of
life. In Bloomington, Ill., 1.3 percent of patients saw 10 or more
doctors.
</P>
<P>
   Hospital and medical resources also varied nationwide -- and so
did costs.
</P>
<P>
   In nine regions of the country, there were more than 4.5
hospital beds per 1,000 residents -- Minot, N.D., was highest with
5.1 -- while 11 regions had 1.7 or fewer beds per 1,000, with
Everett, Wash., lowest at 1.4.
</P>
<P>
   Austin, Texas, had two registered nurses per 1,000 residents --
eighth lowest -- while Chicago, Ill, had five nurses per 1,000.
</P>
<P>
   Dayton, Ohio, had about 148 doctors per 100,000 residents -- the
fifth lowest in the nation -- while White Plains, N.Y., had the
most with 333 per 100,000 residents.
</P>
<P>
   How much Medicare spent in each region also varied. While the
national average was $4,993 per patient, costs ranged from $9,033
in McAllen, Texas, to $3,074 in Lynchburg, Va.
</P>
<P>
   The cost was $4,890 in Atlanta, $4,053 in Grand Junction, $4,761
in Greenville, N.C., $4,597 in Dayton and $5,146 in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
