<HEADER>
A1209 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      04-16 0801
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MAN WHO REDEFINED `IS' GIVES `WAR' NEW MEANING 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The man who redefined the meaning of sex and the
word ``is'' now is degrading other parts of the language, including
the word ``degrade.''
</P>
<P>
   Degradation in the old sense is hardly possible after the events
of the past year. But President Clinton and the military have
drafted ``degrade'' to replace ``destroy,'' which sounds too brutal
in the modern American world of politically correct warfare.
</P>
<P>
   Make that politically acceptable warfare, where public opinion
polls have replaced strategy.
</P>
<P>
   The term ``end game'' has replaced that gory, old-fashioned word
``victory,'' and the phrase ``acceptable casualties'' means no
American casualties.
</P>
<P>
   Civilian casualties, on the other hand, are ``unfortunate'' but
``unavoidable.'' Enemy troops aren't killed but have their
capabilities ``diminished'' by planes that fly too high for their
video cameras to record blood.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, anyone who knows the history of air war from the
Battle of Britain to Vietnam knows that bombings mainly harden
resistance, and even the most technologically miraculous planes get
shot down.
</P>
<P>
   Newspaper editors should do a little editing, and stop repeating
Pentagonese outside of direct quotations. They also could provide a
Berlitz of blitz so readers can translate the utterances of
generals and White House officials.
</P>
<P>
   Newspapers also could stop using the word ``stealthy'' when
referring to the F-117, one of which got shot down. They could
continue calling it the $45 million F-117, because it sure looks
like a big financial blip on the screen at tax time.
</P>
<P>
   The press must take some responsibility for the way America
fights war nowadays.
</P>
<P>
   When the president launches cruise missiles and aircraft to send
messages _ a heck of an expensive form of e-mail _ we play into the
American myth of air power. We print drawings, bomb loads and
ranges of the cruise missiles and aircraft, and only when it's too
late do we mention the fact that no war has ever been won by air
power alone.
</P>
<P>
   When the first pilot is shot down, or the first three soldiers
are captured, we go into deep yellow-ribbon schizophrenia. We
simultaneously beat the patriotic drum, while asking ``Why are we
there?''
</P>
<P>
   It's no wonder that shooting off pilotless cruise missiles is
Clinton's favorite way of sending a message, not counting wearing
special ties. Now he's just about run out of cruise missiles and
options.
</P>
<P>
   While Clinton has been manipulating symbols, watching the polls
and playing Western Union with laser-guided bombs, President
Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia has been playing for keeps. Now it
looks like we have to send in troops _ not a pleasant prospect in
the Balkans _ and we are unprepared to do so. Clinton didn't have
them ready to go in case Milosevic didn't fold after the first two
nights of bombing. The president wasn't ready to fight a war, just
a degradation.
</P>
<P>
   It's deja dodging all over again. I don't mean draft dodging but
responsibility dodging. Many commentators in the press have noted
the ``irony'' of the draft-avoider president getting caught
committing escalatio on a small country, as some wag once said of
President Lyndon Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   The president rightly inveighs against Serbian genocide and
ethnic cleansing of ethnic Albanians, but he hasn't cared enough to
send them the very best, the Marine Corps, the airborne and the
armored divisions.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has always been neither here nor there. He's tried to be
neither here nor there in fighting Milosevic, just as he was
neither here nor there during the Vietnam War. He didn't enlist and
he didn't get very involved in the anti-war movement, except in
Britain, where no one liked the war anyway.
</P>
<P>
   He escaped the draft by signing up for ROTC, but when the draft
lottery saved him from the draft he wheedled his way out of ROTC
with a whiny, self-pitying, self-promoting letter.
</P>
<P>
   This week it is interesting to examine the key run-on sentence
in young Clinton's letter to Col. Eugene Holmes, director of ROTC
at the University of Arkansas: ``I am writing too in the hope that
my telling this one story (about supposedly writing a letter
volunteering to be drafted) will help you to understand more
clearly how so many fine people have come to find themselves still
loving their country but loathing the military, to which you and
other good men have devoted years, lifetimes, of the best service
you could.''
</P>
<P>
   The man who once held the armed forces in contempt now loves
them to death.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
