A1232 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WOMEN-PAY-HNS &LR;      04-16 0484
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOMEN-PAY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REGULATOR LIKES TO TALK ABOUT WAGE GAP FOR WOMEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JO-ANN JOHNSTON  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ A lack of pay parity for women in the workplace
remains a persistent problem in American society, according to the
head of the federal Equal Employment Opportunity Commission.
</P>
<P>
   A problem for everyone, not just women, EEOC chairwoman Ida L.
Castro said during a visit to the State University of New York at
Albany. When they are underpaid, women suffer economic hardship,
their mates are penalized monetarily, and their children may have
to endure whatever day care the family can afford, instead of
quality care, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The civil rights officer said she wanted to practice preventive
civil rights in the workplace, rather than just relying on lawsuits
to redress wrongs. So Castro uses every opportunity to talk about
ways to address the wage gap.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would rather that employees, and of course, the employer,
work together to resolve these concerns,'' Castro, 46, said
Wednesday during the university's Distinguished Women Speaker
series.
</P>
<P>
   People have to realize that wage discrimination still exists,
whether employers' actions are knowing or not, she said. Women, she
said, think: ```It's 1999. Who would do that?' Well, a lot of
people do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Pay studies still routinely show bottom-line pay discrepancies
``that cannot be explained in any other way other than gender,''
she said. Part of the problem is that individuals and companies
often lack the data that would point to inequities. Women who work
in unionized workplaces are often better off, she said, because
unions typically negotiate wage scales.
</P>
<P>
   But workers in some non-union settings can be fired for
discussing compensation, Castro said. In the best of situations,
she said, an employer will review pay data to see if there are
existing wage discrepancies and then cooperate with employees to
correct shortfalls.
</P>
<P>
   That recently happened at the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology. But employers may fear that if they do an internal
review and then detect problems, that the review may be used to
punish them, she said. Accordingly, she said she would like EEOC to
devise a management or accounting tool that companies, especially
smaller ones, can use for a ``self audit.''
</P>
<P>
   Castro was sworn in as chairwoman of the EEOC, a $125,000-a
year-job, last October. She has worked in other government jobs in
the employment field, including acting director of the Women's
Bureau at the U.S. Department of Labor.
</P>
<P>
   In past years, some critics said that the EEOC was too slow in
getting to complaints. Castro has said in other interviews she
wants to use more mediation services and concentrate legal actions
on companies that refuse to comply with the law and on cases that
would clarify employment law.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-16-99 1230EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
