<DOCNO> NYT19990416.0077 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-16 12:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1235 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JOURNAL-ISRAEL-0417-C     04-16 0542
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOURNAL-ISRAEL-0417-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    LETTER FROM ISRAEL: JUST WHAT TIME IS IT? HARD TO TELL IN
JERUSALEM
 &HT;    With Photo mug of Kaplow.
 &HT;    Moving in both International and Commentary categories.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Long divided over how to share their small land, the
rift between Jews and Arabs has recently jumped dimensions -- from
space to time.
</P>
<P>
   For two weeks, clocks in the Jewish homes of Jerusalem have been
an hour ahead of clocks, just yards away in some cases, in Arab
homes. Palestinians at work have been an hour ahead of their
children's classrooms.
</P>
<P>
   For foreigners, the time warp has posed some problems of
protocol. One European diplomat took to wearing two watches as a
light-hearted gesture to both ``Israeli time'' and ``Palestinian
time.''
</P>
<P>
   The discrepancy began when Israel went on daylight savings time,
but the Palestinian National Authority, which governs parts of the
West Bank and Gaza Strip, decided to stick with the old hour for a
couple more weeks.
</P>
<P>
   In solidarity with their neighbors, most Palestinians in
Jerusalem also stuck to the old time, even though the city is
governed by Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since the authority was formed in 1996, Israelis and
Palestinians have been choosing different dates to spring forward.
Palestinian clocks finally caught up Thursday night (local time).
But, for two weeks, the close proximity of those on different
clocks bordered on the absurd.
</P>
<P>
   Daylight savings time is based on the earth's general
orientation toward the sun. You would not expect different time
zones for Jerusalem's Jews and Arabs, who live in adjacent, though
segregated, neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   But, it figures. Their schedules have always differed according
to their religions, cultures and, as with daylight savings time,
their political allegiances.
</P>
<P>
   Weekends, for example, have never coincided. Palestinians take
their day off Fridays, when Muslims are expected to attend their
mosques.
</P>
<P>
   As Palestinians start the work week on Saturday, Jews are off
for their Sabbath. The minority of Christians rest on Sunday, when
everyone else is working.
</P>
<P>
   It is a sad fact that the time difference did not cause as much
confusion as you might expect. Unfortunately, Jews and Arabs in
Jerusalem have little direct contact. They share very few schools
and aren't likely to take a lunch together. The majority likely did
not even know that they have been on different times for two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   For those who were affected, like Palestinians whose children go
to public schools run by the Israeli government, they have
straddled the two time zones.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of Palestinians with jobs in Israeli businesses spent
two weeks crossing a time line between home and work.
</P>
<P>
   Appointments had to be clarified -- ``Do you mean 1 p.m.
Palestinian time or Israeli time?'' -- and a lot of meetings have
started late. Several donors arrived an hour early for a recent
meeting at the World Bank, which was on Palestinian time.
</P>
<P>
   Thankfully, everybody's watches are now synchronized. At least
until the fall, when Jews and Arabs are asked what time it is, they
can agree.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-16-99 1235EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
