<SLUG> BC-WHEELED-BOOK-BAGS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDENTS ARE ON A ROLL, BOOKS AND ALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RICK KARLIN  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ In the old days, children carried their books to
school by hand, or tied them with a piece of rope or an old belt.
</P>
<P>
   Then came canvas sacks _ or for nerdy students, briefcases. By
the 1970s, students were toting their books in canvas military
surplus bags. From the 1980s until today, bright nylon backpacks
held sway.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the most fashion-forward students are going mobile, using
backpacks or small suitcases with wheels to cart their books
around.
</P>
<P>
   It's just starting, but the wheeled book bag may be the next Big
Thing that students feel compelled to have.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just had one show up,'' Doug Parker, head of the middle
school at Albany Academy, said of the devices, which are like those
favored by airline pilots and flight attendants.
</P>
<P>
   Time will tell if these conveyances become fashion fixtures.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether or not it's a trend for your average kids, it's hard
to say,'' said David Teufel, spokesman for L.L. Bean, the Maine
catalog retailer that plans to roll out its own wheeled pack in the
fall.
</P>
<P>
   Some retailers say they've seen a slow but steady stream of
young customers seeking the packs, which cost $70 or more.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess they really are bringing home a lot of books. Maybe
they are getting more homework,'' said Gwen Hook, a saleswoman at
Tri City Luggage in the Albany suburb of Colonie.
</P>
<P>
   She's right. For several years now, parents and some physicians
have been concerned about the size and weight of backpacks that
pupils are carrying.
</P>
<P>
   Part of it is due to heavier homework loads, and part is due to
the sheer time pressures that students face. A recent survey from
the University at Michigan showed that students aged 6 to 8 saw
their nightly homework load rise from an average of 9 minutes to 25
minutes between 1981 and 1997. That's a lot more books to drag
home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids in many situations can't go back to their lockers. They
are on the go from 7 a.m. to 7 p.m.,'' said Lauren Osterweil, a
spokeswoman for Eastpak, a Lowell, Mass.-based backpack maker.
</P>
<P>
   Children were carrying so much weight through the halls of
Albany Academy, Parker said, that school officials recently cracked
down on heavy packs, wheeled or otherwise. One teacher uses a scale
to enforce a 25 pound weight limit.
</P>
<P>
   And at least one school has banned the wheeled bags for fear of
collisions and other hallway mishaps.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had that and we said no to it,' said Nancy Chase,
superintendent at the Hoosick Falls school system in upstate New
York. That decision came after one student was using his wheeled
suitcase to bash other students in the hallway.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was rolling it down the hall wildly and knocking it in to
people. We decided it wasn't such a good idea,'' Chase said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
