A1289 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-REVIEW-MOON-HNS &LR;      04-16 0685
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-MOON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A `MOON' FULL OF DISCOVERY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By AMY BIANCOLLI  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In case you miss the metaphor crashing into your head like a
block of concrete, ``A Walk on the Moon'' is about discovery. It's
set in the summer of '69, which means we get Neil Armstrong's
``giant step for mankind'' along with Woodstock revelers in various
states of nudity. Astronautical discovery, sexual discovery. Get
it?
</P>
<P>
   Sure you do. First-time director Tony Goldwyn (best known for
his acting roles, notably the skanky-yuppie killer in ``Ghost'')
has made a winsome film out of a few stultifying cliches, not an
easy trick. The worst you can say about it is that 70 percent of
the time you know exactly what's going to happen. The best you can
say is that 30 percent of the time, you don't. And in that 30
percent lurk enough lovely surprises to redeem (almost) the
ham-handed clunkiness in the rest of the film.
</P>
<P>
   At the center of ``A Walk on the Moon'' is Pearl Kantrowitz
(Diane Lane), a distracted Jewish mom with a swell husband (Liev
Schreiber), a twitchy teen-age daughter (Anna Paquin) and a young
son (Bobby Boriello). She also has needs that hubby apparently has
not met. In June of '69 they fill their car to bursting and drive
up to a Borscht Belt resort in the Catskills, where the kids cavort
on the beach while Mom hobnobs with the ladies over mah-jongg.
</P>
<P>
   She also spends time buying shirts from a traveling blouse
salesman, a hunky bohemian (Viggo Mortenson) with major sideburns.
The salesman flirts openly with his customers, Pearl included. And
when Pearl's husband drives back to his job in New York, leaving
Pearl to her sublimated yearnings, she makes a hasty beeline for
the Blouse Man.
</P>
<P>
   Why she does this is never fully explained; we know that Pearl
married young, that her husband won't ``experiment'' in bed
(though, give the guy credit, he does wear toy gats and a cowboy
hat) and that her face assumes a mien of tragic resignation while
she's chopping celery in the kitchen. ``Do you ever feel trapped by
life, Norma?'' she asks a friend, a rhetorical question if there
ever was one. The answer, which we are duly given, is: Yes, But
That's The Way It Is.
</P>
<P>
   Pearl doesn't buy this. Instead she sneaks off with the Blouse
Man to engage in trippy antics at Woodstock while Pearl's daughter,
who has snuck off to Woodstock with her boyfriend, observes them
through binoculars. And you ask yourself: Weren't there more than
400,000 people at Woodstock? And: Where'd she get those expensive
binoculars, anyway?
</P>
<P>
   Rest assured, not all of this is cliched. Pamela Gray's
screenplay may trade on stereotypes (see ``A Price Above Rubies''
for yet another film about sexual doldrums in a Jewish marriage),
but it takes a few unexpected, emotionally honest turns that keep
things interesting until the end. Goldwyn directs with compassion,
drawing a mature, carefully ruled performance out of Schreiber and
a crisp character turn from Tovah Feldshuh as Pearl's
mother-in-law. Paquin is intentionally annoying it's her job but
Lane, taking on her beefiest role in years, can't get much beyond a
basic mope. When Paquin screams ``I'm the teen-ager!'' at her
muddle-headed mom, she's voicing irritation for the rest of us.
</P>
<P>
   Yet some of the dialogue is marvelous. When Pearl scolds the
Blouse Man for giving candy to her children, she snaps, ``Just keep
your licorice sticks to yourself!'' (Here's an adolescent girl,
discussing her parents' rules on dating and diet: ``Guys I can
kiss. Bacon is another story.'')
</P>
<P>
   ``A Walk on the Moon'' works well, too, as nostalgic
slice-of-life; among its brightest details are Julie Kavner's
deadpan loudspeaker announcements (``Attention: The Knish Man is on
the premises'') and its brief scenes of rapt resort-dwellers
watching Apollo XI on television. Cloddish metaphor or no cloddish
metaphor, the movie neatly captures that first moonwalk, the
suspense that led up to it and the popular exhilaration that
followed.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, it gets a few things right.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
