</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-HOLLEY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDIANOPLIS THROWS A KINK INTO THE PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One dumb trade changed my plans. I was prepared to gloat this
morning. I was going to remind you that my status as king of the
cosmos allows me to see the sports future. Many skeptics doubt me.
But thousands of the Dalai Lama's fans refer to me as the Holley
Lama.
</P>
<P>
   Haven't we been over this before? I can see the unseen. Two
months ago, I told you that this was Edgerrin James's weekend to
become a Patriot. And the Pats might have acquired the University
of Miami running back if stupidity hadn't struck in the Midwest
Thursday. You know, it's hard to make a living seeing the future
when the Indianapolis Colts are a part of your present.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL draft is Saturday and the Pats need a running back.
Perfect. James would have been the man for them. He is 20 years
old. He ran the ball well at a school that is known for great
passers. At one point, he could have matched Ricky Williams in the
categories of quickness and dreadlocks. The test-happy NFL types
have said that James scored below average on their intelligence
tests. But since when did a football field become the 100-Yard
Think Tank? If he can answer two questions, he's all right with me:
</P>
<P>
   Can you locate the first-down marker in this picture?
</P>
<P>
   Can you find a hole when Max Lane and Todd Rucci don't always
produce one?
</P>
<P>
   But that's nearly moot. The Colts made it that way by throwing a
smoke bomb into the draft's top five, sending a few teams
scattering.
</P>
<P>
   How did they do that? They gave a Pro Bowl running back to the
St. Louis Rams. Dick Vermeil must have felt as if he were in the
NFL's version of Filene's Basement Thursday. The coach dangled a
second- and fifth-round draft pick to the Colts and they gave him
Marshall Faulk. For the fashion heads among us, this is akin to
giving someone a pair of dusty Lee jeans in exchange for a stack of
new Maurice Malones.
</P>
<P>
   This is the same Faulk who rushed for 1,319 yards, caught 86
passes for nearly 1,000 more and scored 10 times last season. The
Rams began the day with June Henley (313 yards last season) as
their starter and ended it by adding 1,000 yards and the
26-year-old Faulk. I think someone should introduce the Rams to
Maria Grasso, who recently went from babysitter to multimillionaire
in a couple minutes. Did the Colts, holding the No. 4 pick in the
draft, even ask for the Rams' first-rounder (No. 6)?
</P>
<P>
   As you might have guessed, none of this is good for the Pats.
That's because the Colts now have a jones for Williams and the
surprising whispers are that the Eagles do, too. The Eagles pick
second. So let's say the Colts can't move up in the draft and the
Eagles select Williams. You know what that means, right? The Colts,
with a hole in their backfield, would have to take James. In that
case, not only would the Pats' trade talks with the Redskins
(picking fifth) lose a little energy, the team would have to see
James in its own division.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe you are angry and confused. The Holley Lama is here to
soothe your pain. I will give you a free counseling session and
tell you whom to blame for all this: The Colts.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point,'' Colts owner Jim Irsay said in a statement
Thursday, ``the Colts have decided to take a different direction as
preparations continue for the 1999 season.''
</P>
<P>
   Has Irsay been spending too much time around his PlayStation
console? That's the only time you see trades like this. Now, just
think if you could do brain swaps. If you could place the brain of
the Colts into the cranium of the Redskins, you might be able to
order your own Pats ``JAMES'' jersey as early as next week.
</P>
<P>
   Despite their repulsive nickname (I can see that column in my
sports future), the Redskins are smart. The Pats called them last
week and asked about the No. 5 pick. Some people have speculated
that the Washingtonians asked for safety Lawyer Milloy. They
didn't. At least not at first. They first inquired about Ty Law.
Then they asked about Terry Glenn. The Pats politely declined. The
sides were able to resume discussions this week _ with Law and
Glenn not included _ but a chance of making a deal is unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday afternoon, I was convinced that Bobby Grier and
Pete Carroll were exaggerating their interest in moving up in the
draft. Since this is the time of year when NFL types lie the most,
I thought they were talking about moving up simply to excite their
fans. But they were serious about James. And Williams, too.
</P>
<P>
   Leland Hardy, Williams's agent, says he has been in touch with
New England representatives. But Hardy still believes his client is
going to the Browns, who pick first.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know (Browns owner) Al Lerner is in the credit-card
business, so I know he knows about risk minimization,'' Hardy said
Wednesday night. ``And it would seem to me that the ultimate
low-risk choice is to take the single most productive player in the
draft. A man who did the job for four years.''
</P>
<P>
   The agent said he was not concerned about the typical draft
questions. They emerge at this time each year. Someone is not smart
enough, big enough, or quick enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this age of Starr-esque investigations,'' Hardy said,
``that's par for the course.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe someone should investigate the Colts. Their questionable
intellect makes it difficult to see the sports future. I am tempted
to tell you that the Pats will not draft Boston College's Damien
Woody in the first round. I am tempted to add that they may
surprise everyone at No. 20 and select Tulane's Shaun King to back
up quarterback Drew Bledsoe.
</P>
<P>
   But the Colts have stripped me of my confidence. Now I have to
wait for the draft in suspense, just like everyone else.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Michael Holley is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
