<HEADER>
A1296 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-REVIEW-LIFE-HNS &LR;      04-16 0628
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-LIFE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH A LITTLE EFFORT, `LIFE' IS FUNNY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By AMY BIANCOLLI  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Life'' has every reason to be funny. It stars Eddie Murphy and
Martin Lawrence, two very amusing guys. Its plot is a comic rehash
of ``The Shawshank Redemption,'' which seems a little weird at
first, but hey, we're game. And it's charmed by the absolute
goodwill of the audience, who want a movie starring Eddie Murphy
and Martin Lawrence to be _ what's the expression? _ a laff riot.
</P>
<P>
   And it is. Sometimes. A little bit. Off and on. If you're in a
terrific mood, if you're washing down Goobers with two quarts of
caffeinated fizz, if you're not paying a baby sitter five bucks an
hour, and if you try really, really hard. Then it's hilarious.
</P>
<P>
   ``Life'' was directed by Ted Demme, whose last two feature films
were deadly serious (``Monument Ave.'') and half-serious
(``Beautiful Girls''). You have to go back five years, to ``The
Ref,'' to find another Demme comedy _ about bickering yuppies and
the exhausted cat burglar who holds them hostage. It was obnoxious
but entertaining, working hit-or-miss humor out of a nasty
scenario.
</P>
<P>
   ``Life'' is similarly uneven: It's flat at the start, dour in
the middle, funny in bursts throughout. But it leaves a sweet taste
in the mouth, and if the Murphy-Lawrence pairing never ignites in a
blaze of comic genius, at least they make a darn cute couple. You
couldn't find two more adorable life inmates of a Mississippi state
prison. (You couldn't find a more adorable prison.) And by story's
end, when Murphy and Lawrence are teetering oldsters with heroic
makeup jobs, the film has morphed from a lame buddy caper into an
endearing little portrait of cantankerous friends.
</P>
<P>
   The tale begins in 1932, in a Harlem speakeasy. In walk two
guys: One, Ray (Murphy), is a two-bit criminal; the other, Claude
(Lawrence), is a young dweeb with a new bank job. Fate throws them
together when they can't pay their bills _ and Ray promises a goon
named Spanky (Rick James) that a quick moonshine run to Mississippi
should settle the matter. So down they go. And there they bump up
against bad luck, getting arrested, convicted and thrown in the pen
for a murder they didn't commit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Life'' wastes 36 soporific minutes before sending its stars to
prison; once they get there, the film wakes up. Not surprisingly,
Ray and Claude encounter a full complement of stock prison
characters: the gruff-but-good-egg sergeant (Nick Cassavetes, who
directed ``She's So Lovely''), the enormous bully (Michael ``Bear''
Taliferro), the bemused observer (Obba Babatunde), the bespectacled
kid (Guy Torry).
</P>
<P>
   The movie also throws in an athletically gifted mute (Bokeem
Woodbine) and a bandana-capped cross-dresser (Miguel A. Nunez Jr.),
just for good measure.
</P>
<P>
   None of what happens is particularly surprising _ the
screenplay, by Robert Ramsey and Matthew Stone, follows a well-trod
course _ but the leads bungle their way through prison life with
charming wrong-headedness. Murphy goes on a few brilliant comic
tangents, one of them involving a pocket watch, one a slice of
cornbread (``I'm from New York City, dammit! Nobody takes no
cornbread from me!''). And Lawrence makes a disarming nerd.
</P>
<P>
   Demme's film is spotty. It's unimaginative. It brazenly rips off
``The Shawshank Redemption,'' ``The Bad News Bears'' and
``Spartacus.'' It uses way too much profanity for a film set
(partly) in 1932. It's ridiculous, weepy, cliched, manipulative and
rude. Then again, that's life.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Amy Biancolli is the film critic for the Albany Times Union,
P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. E-mail:
abiancolli(at)timesunion.com or call 518-454-5738.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
