<SLUG> BC-MARA-KENYANS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KENYANS TANUI AND CO. RIGHT AT HOME IN BOSTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHIRA SPRINGER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- The Boston Marathon does business on a first-name
basis.
</P>
<P>
   After all, Moses and Joseph and John and Juma and Ibrahim and
Cosmas and Gelindo and Uta and Elana and Tegla and Fatuma have
ensured Boston showcases the top marathoners from around the world.
Year after year, spectators who line the 26.2 miles from Hopkinton
to Copley Square watch the most competitive marathon fields.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, for the first time in the history of the sport, three
men broke the 2:08 barrier in the same race. Winner Moses Tanui
finished in 2:07:34, and fellow Kenyan Joseph Chebet crossed the
line three seconds later. South African Gert Thys placed third in
2:07:52.
</P>
<P>
   In return for such history-making performances, sponsor John
Hancock provides the elite runners with an unmatched reception that
extends from arrival at the Athletes' Village to race day and
beyond. The Boston Marathon's commitment to bringing in the best
regardless of nationality makes the race unique. But its commitment
to the athlete as an individual truly sets the event apart.
</P>
<P>
   ``People know who these athletes are when they come here,'' said
Mark Wetmore, managing director of Global Athletics and Marketing
and agent for three-time men's champion Cosmas Ndeti and two-time
defending women's champion Fatuma Roba. ``They have a lot of
respect for the athletes. I don't know if it's because Boston is a
rich sports town or because the Marathon is so big, but they know
who the elites are as they run by. In New York, they clap and say
great job whoever you are, but in Boston they knew who Juma was,
they know Cosmas, Ibrahim, Moses. They know all these guys and
that's something you don't see at a lot of other places. They cheer
for them by name and the athletes can hear that along the course.''
</P>
<P>
   But the support isn't exclusive to race day. During their stay
in Boston, the top runners are treated like celebrities with a
staff of volunteers ready to take care of their every need,
allowing the athletes to focus on the race. Schoolchildren in
Hopkinton squeal with delight on Kenyan Day when they are
introduced to each elite runner from the East African nation.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, Ndeti was greeted by a two-minute standing ovation when
he celebrated his victory by attending a Celtics game. The public
address announcer did not need to identify Ndeti as the reigning
Marathon champion and course record-holder. The crowd knew and
Ndeti's bald head was instantly recognizable.
</P>
<P>
   Ndeti and his countrymen have won the past eight Boston
Marathons. In 1998, they took three of the top five places. In
1997, Kenyans captured five of the top seven spots. And in 1996,
Kenyans swept the top five places and seven of the top eight.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, nine Kenyans will compete for the men's title, and
Catherine Ndereba hopes to bring home the country's first title in
the women's race.
</P>
<P>
   The Kenyan dominance of Boston during the 1990s has not sparked
concern on the part of Hancock officials and race organizers, but
has been warmly welcomed as the byproduct of an ultra-competitive
field.
</P>
<P>
   However, other American races have tried to limit the number of
Kenyan participants. Last year, the Bolder Boulder race in Colorado
drew criticism for its attempt to limit Kenyan entrants to three
with a team format. Other races have awarded prize money only to
Americans or no prize money at all.
</P>
<P>
   Some races are attempting to encourage American runners by
increasing prize money for US athletes, and using team formats that
restrict entrants by nationality while granting exemptions to
Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Some who finance US races do not want to provide Kenyan athletes
with tens of thousands of dollars while shortchanging Americans who
can't keep pace.
</P>
<P>
   Some sponsors want to stop the Kenyan dominance with new rules,
not competition. The perception is that American spectators have
trouble identifying with and relating to foreign athletes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I go to events and hear people talking that sponsors don't
want to see runners all from one country win races,'' said agent
Luis Posso, who heads Posso International Promotions and represents
elite distance runners from 30 countries. ``I don't think races
bring out the personalities in all these runners. There are a lot
of good stories behind every runner. The Boston Marathon is
different. John Hancock gets runners involved in the community.
They have a program for runners. They educate people about the
runners.''
</P>
<P>
   The Boston Marathon has proved to be the exception, inviting the
world's best regardless of nationality. And John Hancock breaks
down the perceived monolith by emphasizing and promoting the
individual through clinics and exposure the week prior to the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boston is a very old marathon and most of the people in Boston
know about sports and how to organize athletes,'' Tanui said.
``This is one of the most important things (the organization). For
example, when I am running (spectators) call my name all along the
course. It's a wonderful marathon to go to. Everybody knows almost
all the runners when they pass by. Everybody likes to help the
athletes and this is different from other marathons. With John
Hancock you feel like you are at home and you can concentrate on
the marathon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember last year they were talking about only three or
four Kenyans in some American races. But John Hancock decided to
run an international race. In an international race, it doesn't
matter where you come from so long as you are the best. I think
this has made Boston stronger. They have decided to take the
athletes that are stronger. To compete with three is not a
competition. This is also making Boston unique, inviting all the
athletes no matter where they come from.''
</P>
<P>
   And the big names keep coming.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
