<SLUG> BC-SKA-NARI-NAM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NAM MAKING A NAME FOR HERSELF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Her show music is apt. ``It's `Getting to Know You'
from `The King and I,' '' she says. We got a brief and brilliant
introduction to Naomi Nari Nam in February when she zipped across
the TV screen from the US figure skating championships in Salt Lake
City during Saturday prime time and left commentator Dick Button
nearly speechless.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, my heavens, isn't that stupendous?'', he marveled, as Nam
was taking Rachmaninoff to middle school and teaching him a layback
spin. ``What a moment!''
</P>
<P>
   Then Nam collected her unexpected silver medal, gave victor
Michelle Kwan a hug on the podium _ and was gone before we really
got to know her.
</P>
<P>
   That's why Nam has made sure that her website is filled with
stuff that America might want to find out. That she was born in
Anaheim, not far from Disneyland. That she has a younger sister
named Naomi Nami Nam (`My father liked the name Naomi,' she says)
and that they go by their middle names. That her favorite actor is
Leonardo DiCaprio, her favorite color is periwinkle blue, her
favorite animal the snow tiger. That she collects Beanie Babies.
That her grandfather, who used to skate to school in North Korea,
took her to the Ice Chalet when she was five and nobody could get
her to leave.
</P>
<P>
   We might have known all that sooner if Nam had been able to take
on the Russians at last month's world championships in Helsinki.
But she was too young to go and she'll still be too young next year
(the minimum age is 15) unless she can squeeze through the loophole
by winning a world junior medal.
</P>
<P>
   Nam is so young that her King and I is a movie cartoon. ``She
hasn't seen Yul Brynner yet,'' says coach John Nicks.
</P>
<P>
   But she isn't too young to hit the exhibition circuit _ she'll
be performing in Ice Chips in Boston through Saturday. She isn't
too young to have a fan club, or to have every rink denizen from
Chatham to Costa Mesa already labeling her ``can't miss'' for the
2002 Olympics in Salt Lake City.
</P>
<P>
   All Nam has to do is get her triple lutz down cold and polish
her artistry and find a way to get herself in front of
Olympic-level judges the way Sarah Hughes, her 13-year-old friend
and rival, did.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes would have been too young for the world championships,
too, but she got to go because she was a junior medalist. Nam, who
had finished two places ahead of Hughes in Salt Lake, got to watch
on TV as Hughes finished a startling seventh.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, I was rooting for her,'' Nam says. ``She did very
well. Sometimes you think, ohhh, I wish I was at Worlds. But Sarah
and I are really good friends and I'm so happy for her that she
could do all this.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, Nam says, she knew she couldn't go to Helsinki, even
though she thinks the rule is ``weird.'' This was a bonus year for
her, anyway. Nam moved up to seniors only because the Olympics are
just three years away and it made no sense to spin her wheels.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I thought I should move up sooner and experience the senior
level earlier,'' Nam says, ``instead of staying back in juniors
waiting.''
</P>
<P>
   Nam has never been much for waiting. She dashed up skating's
stair steps _ juvenile, intermediate, novice, junior, senior _ in
five years. She had the spins, she had the jumps. Why not? But
moving up to seniors wasn't so much a technical question as it was
artistic, and Nam knew that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to tell the judges that I'm not a little 13-year-old,
that I'm a senior lady,'' she says. ``So I wanted to go out there
and perform like a senior lady. I had to have mature music and
simple and elegant costumes. And I had to work more on presenting
to the audience and not looking down.''
</P>
<P>
   So Nam went with something sprightly (Cirque du Soleil) and
something sophisticated (Rachmaninoff piano concertos) and made a
stunning debut in Salt Lake.
</P>
<P>
   After crashing on her combination jump (``Well, it was supposed
to be a combination jump'') in the short program and whacking her
head on the ice, Nam shook it off and finished up. ``I was a little
confused,'' she confesses. ``I was wondering if I should go on or
go to the referee and stop. But I thought it was a really good
choice to go on.''
</P>
<P>
   Nam stole the show in the long program, then burst into tears
when she realized what she'd done. Just competing against Kwan was
a thrill, she said. Standing next to her on the podium was ``a
dream come true.''
</P>
<P>
   The last two months have passed in a blur. Nam skated in South
Korea, where her parents were born. She explained the Naomi-Naomi
sibling thing to Jay Leno on the ``Tonight'' show. She performed on
the Rockefeller Center rink and signed on with the Champions on Ice
tour for its West Coast swing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was expecting a relaxed year with nothing much happening,''
muses her coach. ``It didn't quite work out that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Naomi Nari Nam is zipping through town this weekend, but she'll
be back for the US championships at the FleetCenter in 2001. By
then, a few hundred million people will have gotten to know her.
And she'll have seen the Yul Brynner version.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
