<HEADLINE>
SOME SEE BARGAIN IN SECURITY DYNAMICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some value-oriented investors think they may have spotted a
bargain in Security Dynamics Technologies, a small company in
Bedford, Mass. For those who think value is an outdated concept on
Wall Street, it should be pointed out that there is also an
Internet angle to this story, so pay attention.
</P>
<P>
   Security Dynamics makes computer security software, presumably a
good business to be in at a time when people are using their
computers more and worrying whether the information they are
storing and sending is safe.
</P>
<P>
   Security Dynamics owns 2.6 million shares of VeriSign, an
Internet start-up that is also in the security business. VeriSign's
stock has climbed from 28 in October to 156, largely on the
strength of Internet fever.
</P>
<P>
   Even after Thursday's big Internet sell-off, Security Dynamics'
stake in VeriSign was worth about $400 million. On top of that,
Security Dynamics has about $200 million in cash. If you are doing
the arithmetic that is $600 million worth of assets _ less if you
take out the taxes Security Dynamics would have to pay if it sold
VeriSign.
</P>
<P>
   The total market value of Security Dynamics is about $650
million, which means the stock market is placing precious little
value on the rest of the company's business, which is both growing
and profitable. ``The market isn't doing the math,'' complains Nick
Moore, a money manager with Jurika &AMP; Boyles in California. ``There
is value here staring you right in the face.''
</P>
<P>
   Why is Wall Street so indifferent to Security Dynamics? And why
doesn't the company get much credit for its Internet link?
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say part of the problem is that Security Dynamics is
not a pure Internet play. If you are excited about VeriSign, why
not just buy VeriSign, they say. And then there is Security
Dynamics' credibility problem. In January the company reported
earnings that came in well short of Wall Street's expectations. The
stock dropped 25 percent in a day and hasn't recovered since. ``The
earnings shortfall was a significant blemish,'' says Paul Saunders,
an analyst with SoundView Technology Group.
</P>
<P>
   Management described the problem as a one-time goof. To speed
entry into new markets, the company offered generous incentives to
its sales force. The incentives worked too well. Sales went up but
commissions owed salespeople rose even faster. Security Dynamics'
executives say they have since made adjustments to the incentive
formula.
</P>
<P>
   They may be right. Security Dynamics Thursday reported
first-quarter earnings after the market closed. The numbers met
Wall Street expectations. Excluding special items, the company
earned $5.1 million, or 12 cents per share, compared to $5.7
million, or 14 cents per share, in the first quarter a year ago.
Revenue rose 21 percent to $48.7 million. Security Dynamics stock
closed at 16 1/2, down 2 for the day.
</P>
<P>
   Company executives and some money managers are bullish about the
firm's longer-term prospects. Security Dynamics is a leader in two
different kinds of computer security. One set of its products
handles authentication, computerese for how you prove you are who
you say you are when you log on to your computer. Another set of
products does encryption, the scrambling of data so outsiders can't
see what you have written.
</P>
<P>
   Starting this quarter, Security Dynamics will roll out a new
product line based on VeriSign technology. The new gear is aimed
directly at the electronic commerce market. It is widely agreed
that with better security, especially for financial information,
business on the Internet can grow even faster than it already has.
</P>
<P>
   ``This company is right in the wheelhouse of the electronic
commerce phenomenon,'' says Brian Stack, manager of Massachusetts
Financial Services' New Discovery fund.
</P>
<P>
   But Stack and others still have plenty of questions about
Security Dynamics. Will the company be able to handle the
transition from the old generation of products to the new ones?
Will management be able to avoid the kind of screw-ups that popped
up in the fourth quarter?
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to show that we can deliver,'' concedes Arthur
Coviello, president of Security Dynamics.
</P>
<P>
   Investors, of course, can't answer that question. But the value
players on Wall Street like the fact that there is so much value on
the company's balance sheet. ``To some degree it insulates you from
downside risk,'' says money manager Nick Moore.
</P>
<P>
   Put another way, it means there is some security for those
willing to buy stock in Security Dynamics.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Red Herring
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Japan and its potential as a market for mutual fund companies
was the subject of a Boston conference Thursday sponsored by the
National Investment Company Service Association and the Japan
Society of Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Recent regulatory changes have made it easier for the Japanese
to put their money into different investment vehicles. By year's
end, the Japanese government is expected to legalize defined
contribution plans.
</P>
<P>
   According to the consulting firm, PricewaterhouseCoopers,
Japanese savers have $7 trillion socked away in cash. If just a
sliver of that money finds its way into mutual funds, the
opportunity for Boston-based firms could be enormous, the audience
was told. Fidelity Investments and State Street Corp. are among the
local players with operations in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
