<HEADLINE>
KITARO REACHES AROUND DIFFERENT WORLDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Kitaro is the world-music star who combines serenely ambient
synthesizer journeys with sometimes wild bashings on ancient
Japanese drums, topped by a trippy light show worthy of Pink Floyd.
Some observers are still trying to figure him out, but meanwhile,
he's sold millions of albums around the world and been nominated
for six Grammy Awards.
</P>
<P>
   He has recorded with Grateful Dead percussionist Mickey Hart and
Yes vocalist Jon Anderson. He led 450 taiko drummers in the closing
ceremonies at last year's Winter Olympics in Nagano, Japan _ near a
house he owns when he's not living on his 150-acre spread in
Colorado. He recorded the soundtrack for Oliver Stone's ``Heaven
and Earth'' and the music for the touring circus Cirque Ingenieux.
</P>
<P>
   ``My point of view is just to keep going and follow my mission
to get as many different sounds as I can,'' says Kitaro, who
headlines Symphony Hall on April 29.
</P>
<P>
   For his new tour, besides playing drums and analog synthesizers
(which he prefers to digital synths because of their ``warmth''),
Kitaro is playing wooden flute, hammer dulcimer, and a
``waterphone.'' As he explains: ``The waterphone was created by a
California guy. It's a metal pot and you put water in the pot and
around the pot you have strings. And when you hit the strings, the
sound makes a kind of wave.''
</P>
<P>
   Kitaro has been making other kinds of waves with some of his
projects. One was the soundtrack to the Chinese film ``Soong
Siters,'' which is included on his new double CD, ``Best of Kitaro,
Volume II,'' on Domo Records. He recorded the orchestral soundtrack
two years ago for the movie (never shown in the United States),
which is a true story of two Shanghai daughters married to Chinese
political figures.
</P>
<P>
   The soundtrack won a Taiwan Film Award for best original
soundtrack, but Kitaro says, ``The Chinese government checked the
movie and cut some of it because of political reasons. All of a
sudden, that meant some of my soundtrack was gone, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Kitaro is renowned for the visual impact of his music _ and he's
carrying that one step further by compiling a book of his
photographs (taken at his 10,000-foot-high Colorado property) that
will be out this summer.
</P>
<P>
   For now, however, he's on the road with a new band. While he has
performed with musicians from all over the world on past tours,
he's honoring his Japanese roots by using an all-Japanese group for
the first time.
</P>
<P>
   ``So far, so good,'' he says. ``I wanted to take out these
Japanese musicians because they don't have experience performing in
other countries. They're mostly 25- to 27-year-old young people.
But everybody is educated and trained in classical music. I also
have one female violin player, a female percussionist, and a female
keyboardist.''
</P>
<P>
   He's also performing four or five songs on tour from a new CD
that no one has heard yet. It's called ``The Thinking of You,'' and
he wrote it on Valentine's Day. It has ``a little romantic theme
song that I'm looking to get on a soundtrack,'' says Kitaro, whose
list of projects never ends.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Getting Godsmacked: Local rockers Godsmack have made national
headway and been added to the Ozz Fest this summer, but they've
also had to fight for their right to party. Singer Sully Erna
recently jumped offstage and crowd-surfed at the ``X Fest'' in Fort
Myers, Fla. He crawled back up, but a security guard mistook him
for a fan and tried to boot him out. Erna threw a punch and knocked
the guard unconscious.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was surreal,'' says Lee Daniels, program director for
WJBX-FM, the Florida station that put on the show. ``Everyone's
collective jaw dropped as the security guard tackled the lead
singer. But I'll tell you, the band didn't miss a beat.''
</P>
<P>
   Other Godsmack news: Its major-label debut album, ``Godsmack,''
just went gold, signifying sales of more than 500,000.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Boston Music Awards: The Kahlua Boston Music Awards, set for
Thursday at the Orpheum Theatre, include a fresh, engaging list of
performances this year by Joey McIntyre, Godsmack, Jo Dee Messina,
Susan Tedeschi, Big Wreck, Jonatha Brooke, Buffalo Tom, Melissa
Ferrick, Martin Sexton, and Jude. Several have been hot on the
charts, especially Messina, the country singer who is the first
woman to ever score three consecutive, multiple-week No. 1 hits in
that field. (Some tickets still available for the show.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gathering of the Vibes: Neo-hippie nirvana is forecast for the
Gathering of the Vibes Festival in Seaside Memorial Park in
Bridgeport, Conn., June 18-20. Camping is available on the 370-acre
site, which can accommodate 10,000 fans. The band lineup boasts
Gov't Mule, moe, John Scofield, Strangefolk, Deep Banana Blackout,
and Percy Hill. The event was booked by Terrapin Presents Inc., and
has run annually since the death of Jerry Garcia in hopes of
keeping the Deadhead community together. Tickets begin at $55 for
the three days, including camping. For more info, check the Web
site www.ttapes.com/vibes99 or call Terrapin at 800-677-8650.
</P>
