<SLUG> BC-BBA-OAKLAND-A'S-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOSTON FIRM GETS GO-AHEAD TO SELL OAKLAND TEAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RAY DELGADO  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ Oakland and Alameda County officials have
given a sports investment company authorization to sell the Oakland
Athletics if a qualified bidder emerges.
</P>
<P>
   The Oakland-Alameda County Joint Powers Authority on Thursday
moved to allow Boston-based Game Plan LLC to evaluate any qualified
bids for the team, said Game Plan President Randy Vataha.
</P>
<P>
   The authorities here have until Wednesday to find a buyer or
face the prospect of losing the baseball team to another city after
the 2001 season.
</P>
<P>
   A qualified bidder must agree to provide a $12 million down
payment and pay at least $122.4 million for the team. The winning
bidder must also agree to keep the team in the Oakland Coliseum
through at least 2004.
</P>
<P>
   Two groups are expected to meet the criteria, Vataha said.
</P>
<P>
   One is a seven- to 10-member group led by former A's executive
Andy Dolich that includes clothier George Zimmer, San Francisco
advertising executive Jeff Goodby, Oakland restaurateur Raymond
Gallagher, the Oakland Tribune and Modesto grocery mogul Robert
Piccinini.
</P>
<P>
   The second is a three-man group that includes San Francisco
lawyer and former bank executive Michael Lazarus, Arizona banker
Lyle Campbell and former Baltimore Orioles pitcher Steve Stone.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are both legitimate buyers,'' Vataha said. ``They're
both interested. They both have attorneys working around the clock
to put together bids. If somebody puts up the money, this is
definitely going to go forward in a sale.''
</P>
<P>
   If no bids are received, however, the current A's owners _ Steve
Schott and Ken Hoffman _ would be free to move the team to a new
stadium after 2001. Schott said recently that he hoped to move the
team to a new state-of-the-art stadium in Santa Clara or San Jose
if there is not bid for the Oakland team.
</P>
<P>
   But Vataha said he was reasonably sure that at least one of the
two potential buyers would put their bids in before the deadline.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-16-99 1345EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990416.0104 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-16 13:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1317 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      04-16 0736
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHATEVER HAPPENED TO FRIDAYS? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have you noticed? How there were fewer cars on the road this
morning? How clogged the airports are on Thursday night? How not
exactly everybody shows up for work on Friday? For white-collar
drones, Friday _ just recently set aside for casual dressing _ now
seems reserved for casual attendance.
</P>
<P>
   Understandably, this is not a subject that personnel managers
are anxious to discuss. But it is a subject that America's leading
workplace authority, ``Dilbert'' creator Scott Adams, will talk
about. ``It is a badge of shame if you can't think of a way to
avoid work on Friday,'' he notes.
</P>
<P>
   What accounts for this trend? Theories abound. It's true that
more mothers with children have entered the work force, and some
arrange four 10-hour workdays to maximize their time at home. More
readily than private companies, government bureaucracies have been
experimenting with flexible hours. Millions of Americans use their
computers to ``telecommute'' to the workplace.
</P>
<P>
   But don't you think a lot of people are just plain goofing off?
</P>
<P>
   Logan airport tracks passenger traffic, and ``Thursday night is
known as the busiest night,'' says a spokesman, Jeremy Crockford.
``Everybody who's gone away on a business trip tries to get home by
Thursday, and we doubt they go to work on Friday.'' Cartoonist
Adams agrees. ``Work avoidance is more pronounced on Fridays than
Mondays, partly because so many people are gone on Friday that no
one is there to notice that you are gone too. No one wants to narc
anyone else out about Friday absenteeism because everyone covets
the same crime.''
</P>
<P>
   Passenger-car statistics also indicate that the traditional
Friday ``slide'' has migrated Thursday-ward. Just two years ago,
Friday was the peak call day for Cambridge's SmartRoute Systems,
which dispenses traffic information to customers by phone. Now
Thursday is the peak day, with Friday and Tuesday tied for second
place. SmartRoute manager Jeff Larson attributes the shift to
changing work habits: ``A lot of people in corporate America tend
to schedule their meetings around their personal convenience.''
</P>
<P>
   And it's not just in the workplace. Over the years, Friday night
_ ``The Man From U.N.C.L.E.,'' ``Burke's Law,'' ``Dallas'' _ was
appointment television night, when the networks could rely on
finding the nuclear family relaxed and at home. Now it's Thursday.
Two academics recently told me that students had gently warned them
that should they choose to teach on Fridays, their classes will be
lightly attended.
</P>
<P>
   All things considered, we are moving in the right direction. In
so-called civilized society, the weekend consisted of just one day
_ Sunday, the Sabbath _ from the Dark Ages through the 18th
century. If anyone had an extra day off, it was Monday, generally
reserved for fairs, festivals, and sleeping off hangovers.
</P>
<P>
   To enjoy their leisurely country weekends, the British
aristocracy pioneered the ``long'' weekend, leaving London on
Friday and returning on Monday. The working class wasn't so lucky.
Until the 20th century, workers had to content themselves with a
half-day holiday on Saturday, plus Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   According to Witold Rybczynski's book, ``Waiting for the
Weekend,'' the first American factory to adopt the five-day work
week was a New England spinning mill, which wanted to free both its
Jewish and its Christian employees to observe their holy days, in
1908. The five-day week is now set in stone, and _ de facto or de
jure _ the four-day week is rapidly encroaching.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of years ago, two New Hampshire-based high-tech
companies, Kollman Inc. and Sanders, instituted ``9/80'' work
weeks, meaning that employees would work 80 hours in nine working
days, rather than 10, with every other Friday off. More recently,
Illinois-based software purveyor HighTower Inc. started offering an
8/80 option, meaning employees had to work only four days each
week.
</P>
<P>
   HighTower's president Jeff Rosengarden says he has children the
age of his youngest employees, and he knows what they want: ``They
would rather have more time off than have extra money.''
</P>
<P>
   Smart kids. Let's follow their example. I'll be available to
write the ``Thank God It's Thursday'' column any time.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Alex Beam's e-dress is beam(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
