<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SELLING CHINA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   All politicians are in the heat transfer business. They take
heat, they give heat. Their success and longevity depends on how
they handle the heat.
</P>
<P>
   America's president, Bill Clinton, the fellow with the asbestos
underwear, has a PhD in heat-taking. Old Bill _ He's aged some in
the job, hasn't he? _ can calibrate the political BTUs better than
anyone.
</P>
<P>
   Which is why the president pulled the plug on the Chinese
government's 13-year push for entry into the World Trade
Organization. This is something that, on balance, should happen,
and the sooner the better, not only for China, but for the United
States and for the rest of Asia's struggling economies.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton couldn't stand the heat for giving China a big
prize. Clinton has a war going on in the Balkans. He's just off
impeachment. There was the flap over Chinese spying on our
missilery stockpile, and those embarrassing contributions to the
Democratic presidential campaign from shadowy Sino-sources, and the
predictable harrumping from the anti-China lobbies.
</P>
<P>
   The defenders of Chinese dissidents, Tibet, Taiwan, and other
causes were lining the streets to demonstrate aqgainst the
just-completed nine-day tour of Chinese Prime Minister Zhu Rongji.
Clinton, with that gigantic mainframe of a political calculator
that he has inside his brain, or his gut, decided at the last
minute to stiff Zhu on the WTO business. Or did he?
</P>
<P>
   There's the mysterious phone call Tuesday  &UR; afternoon &LR;  from
Clinton to Zhu. It seems the American businessmen who want to open
up the fabulous 1.2 billion-person Chinese market got to Bill. For
20 minutes Clinton yakked with Zhu, and Zhu told media moguls in
New York City the deal was ``99 percent complete.'' US Commerce
Secretary Bill Daley said China's admission to the Big Boys club of
the WTO ``is not a question of `if' but of `when.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The hostile burping of the backbenchers in the
Republican-controlled Congress delayed the deal, it appears.
Clinton is trying to come out of impeachment, run the Kosovo war,
keep the rest of the world at bay, and he apparently concluded he
couldn't take on the Republicans over Chinese spying, campaign
contributions, and sins in Tibet and human rights.
</P>
<P>
   To the US political spin-cycle in which 24 hours can be a
lifetime, Zhu brought the perspective of 5,000 years of trying to
govern the world's biggest population. ``No big deal,'' he cracked
on more than one occasion, when fielding questions about the
perennial sticking points like China's trade deficit, copyright
infringement (that means theft) of intellectual property rights,
clapping dissidents into the calaboose, grinding Tibetans down.
</P>
<P>
   We're getting there, he kept telling American audiences. Give us
time, we have a different society and different problems than
yours, lighten up, trade more, give us a crack at your computers
and communications gear, and we'll get more modern more quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Zhu has three things going for him which made him a far more
successful visiting fireman than previous Chinese top dogs. First,
he's an electrical engineer, who at age 68 has witnessed firsthand
the way technology yanked China from its medieval ways to the
present. Second, he was mayor of Shanghai, that rock-'em-sock-'em
piratical city where the timid or the foolish do not long survive.
Like the mayor of Moscow, Yuri Lushkov, who may become Boris
Yeltsin's successor in Russia, a savvy mayor who understands how
things really work can go a long way in a country desperate to
modernize.
</P>
<P>
   Third, Zhu has a combination of sly wit and willingness to be
blunt that goes a long way to persuading American audiences that he
knows what's up. In grad school back home, he told a friendly MIT
crowd, some of his texts were photocopies; ``Whether they were
pirated or not I do not know.''
</P>
<P>
   He made wordplay about secrets and the espionage game, even
played the droll straight man, saying that when Clinton told him
China has only a few dozen nuclear warheads, ``I don't know how he
knew that.'' Inviting American accounting types to apply for some
Chinese job openings, he poked America's reputation for materialism
right in the ribs: ``I will pay what you are paid here.'' Asked
about imprisoned dissident Xu Wenli, Zhu said he'd been asked so
often about human rights, ``I practically have blisters on my
lips.''
</P>
<P>
   Zhu went a long way in persuading Americans that, as in Margaret
Thatcher's appraisal of Gorbachev, ``he is a man we can do business
with.'' Clinton should damn the anti-China torpedoes and go full
speed ahead for WTO recognition. That's where we should end up. It
helps end Asia's economic swoon, helps American business, and opens
China to western values. So stop screwing around. Ignore those
isolationist birdbrains in Congress. It's time to get from ``no big
deal'' to ``get real,'' and bring China in from the cold.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Nyhan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
