<HEADLINE>
I LOVE YOU, MARIA GRASSO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MCGRORY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I have a confession to make to you, Maria Grasso, one that will
undoubtedly surprise and delight you so very, very much. I love
you. I really do. I love you from the core of my heart and with
every fiber of my otherwise worthless soul in a way I've never
loved anyone before.
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, consider me a helpless, hopeless puppy, wagging
my pathetic little tail every time you deign to look my way. For
that reason, consider this space today an ode to your essence.
Consider every thought I think, every action I take, every word I
write and speak for the rest of my life to be a tribute to an
intangible beauty that is uniquely and unquestionably yours.
</P>
<P>
   What is it I love about you? Wow. Well, there you go. That's
just one thing: Your modesty. But what else? My God, so many
millions of reasons that I'm not quite sure where to begin.
</P>
<P>
   But here goes. I love that exotic Chilean accent of yours, the
way the words roll off your tongue like a hand-polished Bentley
gliding down a winding country highway.
</P>
<P>
   Ahem.
</P>
<P>
   I love the way the klieg lights sparkled in your eyes Wednesday
as you stood on stage at Lottery headquarters in Braintree and
accepted a destiny that is so exquisitely ours. In retrospect, I
can't pinpoint exactly why, but just watching you on television in
that gorgeous, gold-flecked, navy blue dress, your dark hair so
perfectly coiffed, I felt a bond that has given significance to my
previously insignificant life.
</P>
<P>
   And best of all, seeing that delighted look on your face, I knew
then that you were thinking of me as I was thinking of you. It was
a moment of unparalleled magic. And just as you spent a sleepless
night with your lottery ticket by your bed, I spent a sleepless
night with your photograph by mine.
</P>
<P>
   Now steel yourself, my dearest, for there are cynics among us
who will suspect vice in our communion where we only seek virtue.
They are everywhere, these naysayers, always pointing out the worst
while we search for each other's best.
</P>
<P>
   They will no doubt notice our age difference. Yes, I know you
are 54, 17 years more experienced than myself. They will whisper
about our varying backgrounds, you harking from that wondrously
beautiful nation of Chile, me coming from right here in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   They may note the curious timing of our relationship, coming as
it does amid all this publicity. And they even may make mention of
the inconvenient fact that you and I have never actually met.
</P>
<P>
   But ours is a love that bridges, not divides, an almost cosmic
marriage of emotion and attraction that is so much larger than the
both of us combined. We must face one crucial fact, my princess:
This is a love we may never fully understand, so it's probably best
we not even try.
</P>
<P>
   Me? You want to know about me? I'm so flattered, I can barely
think. Well, I happen to be the founder of the recently formed
National Commission to Preserve the Chilean Sea Bass. By some
measure of coincidence, I am the president of the Committee for the
Best Possible Treatment of South American Nannies. I heard you say
Wednesday that you'll continue to care for those with special
needs. I can't believe this coincidence. People tell me all the
time that I always think my own needs are so special.
</P>
<P>
   I will shout our love to the angels from the highest rooftops of
our real estate portfolio. I will whisper our love to the lilies in
the man-made pond of our Tuscan manor. I will skip down Mount
Vernon Street, kiss ducks and bunnies on the forehead, release
bright pink balloons to the heavens in the name of our lifetime
together.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, I want us to share every part of each other's lives. I
insist. I would be willing to leave my job to spend more time with
you. I would accompany you on a round-the-world cruise on the Queen
Elizabeth II, if that's what it takes. I really would. I would
hurtle across time zones on the Concorde to meet you in Paris. I
would leave my home to live in yours. I would do anything _
absolutely anything _ for you.
</P>
<P>
   So let's meet. Let's meet at noon today at what will always be
our special place _ the service desk at the Fenway Star Market.
You'll be the woman of unimaginable beauty, hopefully _ wink, wink
_ unaccompanied. I'll be the guy with the collection of American
Tourister luggage, and the note from my mother saying, ``Don't wake
while sleepwalking.'' I can almost hear you say, ``Brian, I am
yours and you are mine.'' I can feel our hands clasp. I will tell
you that our love will be strong, now and always, forever and ever.
Mi bella Maria.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Brian McGrory's e-mail address is mcgrory(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
