<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-GOODBYE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LURID ZEST FADES IN `GOODBYE LOVER' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
GOODBYE LOVER 
Directed by: Roland Joffe 
Screenplay by: Ron Peer, Joel Cohen, Alec Sokolow 
Starring: Patricia Arquette, Dermot Mulroney, Ellen DeGeneres,
Mary-Louise Parker, Don Johnson, Ray McKinnon 
Running time: 115 minutes 
Rated: R (sexuality, language and violence) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Goodbye Lover'' is almost the edgy scheme-fest it wants to be.
Certainly it achieves the dark, slick, malignant look it's after.
Venal characters slink through it, putting a high gloss on their
double-crosses. But while the betrayals pile up energetically, they
reach a point of diminishing returns about halfway through. Even
though the precise alignments of the treacheries will keep you
guessing, they stop seeming to matter on even the most superficial
stylistic level, stranding the actors and forfeiting anything like
thrills.
</P>
<P>
   Too bad, because the actors show up ready to work and director
Roland Joffe, in his first foray into comedy, has a feel for spiky
comedic jabs as the film begins in a surge of sexual heat that
quickly is revealed to be little more than sexual smoke. And
mirrors. ``Goodbye Lover'' is big on mirrors, especially when
Patricia Arquette's temptress, Sandra, passes in front of them and
can't resist inspecting her combat-readiness. She doesn't need much
to tempt Don Johnson's libidinous ad exec named Ben into steamy sex
in dangerous locations, where the prospect of getting caught
presumably adds to the excitement.
</P>
<P>
   Ratcheting up the ante is the fact that she's married to her
lover's younger brother, Dermot Mulroney's Jake. He also works at
the ad agency, drinks too much, and is only kept on the payroll
because of Ben's intervention. When Jake learns what's going on, he
predictably explodes. A confrontation between Jake and Ben ends
especially badly for one of them. But that's only the first stop in
a maze of amoral plotting and alliances. Mary-Louise Parker, an ad
agency careerist who had her eye on Ben and plays an ace nobody
knew she had, deals herself in too, with results she never foresaw.
</P>
<P>
   They're all crooked. And as the bodies pile up, they try to
dodge the gimlet eye of Ellen DeGeneres's experienced, world-weary
cop, whose effectiveness is lessened by forced comic routines with
a doltish partner. The film has its moments. I laughed at the
playing of Arquette's cheerful amorality against bits of her
favorite musical, ``The Sound of Music,'' a trademark even funnier
than her stiletto heels. But ``Goodbye Lover'' can't sustain its
loopy outrage, and its lurid zest drains away as it becomes too
silly to be funny.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
