<SLUG> BC-FBN-DRAFT-CLOUD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER BC STAR CLOUD HOPES TO LAND WITH PATRIOTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- The question of Mike Cloud getting selected in
Saturday's NFL draft ceases to be a matter of if, but where and by
whom. Cloud, the All-America running back from Boston College who
ranked as the Big East's leading rusher and No. 3 in the nation,
will be drafted. That much is certain.
</P>
<P>
   What is not, however, is Cloud's ultimate NFL destination.
</P>
<P>
   And that has Ethel Cloud worried.
</P>
<P>
   It is, after all, only natural for a mother to worry about her
child's future. But Mrs. Cloud would love to know where the
youngest of her three sons will be going off to work. While she
says she is not a big sports fan, what little she knows about the
NFL draft is that her son will not have any control in deciding
what team he plays for, unlike college, where Mike had his pick of
schools from BC, Syracuse, and Clemson.
</P>
<P>
   That will be up to men hunkered down in NFL draft war rooms from
Pittsburgh, Baltimore, Miami, and, Mrs. Cloud is fervently hoping,
New England.
</P>
<P>
   ``First of all, I've got a bad back and I can't stand the
cold,'' Mrs. Cloud said, stating the reasons why she has not
watched any of her son's games in person. ``And I'm too darned
nervous to sit still and watch the games. When I see them hit him,
I get too, too nervous because of what happened to Kevin . . . ''
</P>
<P>
   Kevin is her second-oldest son. A running back with great
college prospects, Kevin Cloud suffered a serious neck injury
during a scrimmage in his junior year at Portsmouth High. He
suffered a cervical fracture that shattered his dreams of playing
in college and very nearly ended his younger brother's budding
career.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why I don't like to watch it,'' Mrs. Cloud said. ``I
just sit here and say my prayers. A lot of times, I'd go to his BC
games and I'd watch the game from his dorm room. But I've never
flown on a plane and I'm not looking forward to it in the near
future, either.''
</P>
<P>
   That is why Mike Cloud, like his mother, is hoping the Patriots
call his number on draft day..
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be somewhere close,'' said Cloud, who honored his
brother Kevin by wearing the same No. 21 in high school and
college. ``My mom doesn't like to fly. She's never flown on a plane
and never wants to. It's kinda like the old show the `A-Team,' when
they had to knock out B.A. Baracus to get him into a helicopter.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's something we'll probably have to do with my mom,'' he
added, with a laugh. ``She refuses to get into an airplane, so if I
end up somewhere far away, it's going to be tough for her to watch
me if the games aren't on TV. It's not going to be like an hour
ride from Rhode Island to BC, how it was before.''
</P>
<P>
   Unless, that is, Cloud lands with the Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would be a perfect situation for me, being local all
these years and having my career end up in New England,'' Cloud
said. ``It's something at this point that's a little far-fetched,
because on draft day decisions could change within minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, there is a slight chance he could wind up with the
Patriots, but that is very slight. The Patriots have stated their
intention to move up in the draft by packaging their two
first-round picks (20th and 28th overall) in an attempt to land
either Heisman Trophy winner Ricky Williams of Texas or Miami's
Edgerrin James.
</P>
<P>
   ``Out of all the pro days I've done, I think that was the best
one as far as my performance,'' said Cloud, referring to his
workout for the Patriots in Foxborough. ``I did real well there. I
think it was because I just felt more relaxed being around the
coaches from New England. Just because they always had great things
to say about me, and just because I knew some of the coaching staff
from meeting them at the Senior Bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   After rushing 308 times for 1,726 yards and 14 touchdowns in his
senior year at BC, Cloud backed it up with a strong performance in
the Senior Bowl, where rushed 12 times for 117 yards, good enough
to earn MVP honors and the long-distance award for a 55-yard run.
``It's tough in the Senior Bowl with four or five running backs all
sharing time,'' Cloud said. ``I think I only played a quarter and a
half and had 12 carries, but I took every play like it was going to
be my last play, because you never knew when they were going to
switch running backs.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite his MVP performance, scouts still had lingering
questions about Cloud, a 5-foot-10-inch, 202-pounder.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the major workout day we had here (March 15), the one
question they kept asking was: `Is he tough enough? Can he run
inside with the ball?' '' said BC coach Tom O'Brien. ``That was one
of the things that they asked. As I said to them, he carried it
during the middle drill two days a week for us, going up in there
against the defense, and he never had a problem that way. So I
don't see (that) that would be a problem for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why I told the scouts, `We gave him the ball enough
times; you guys can't figure it out watching tape.' '' O'Brien
added. ``He didn't take a lot of plays off. I mean, look at the
Pittsburgh game. He only got the ball about 10 times on the last
drive _ and they were all runs inside the tackles.''
</P>
<P>
   Cloud went to the NFL scouting combine in Indianapolis and,
unlike some of the other highly-touted backs, was one of the few
who didn't balk at going through all the rigors. He ran a 4.47 in
the 40-yard dash, but at a pro workout day at BC last month lowered
that time to 4.31.
</P>
<P>
   ``To not work out didn't make any sense to me,'' he said. ``A
lot of guys who didn't work out, in my opinion, were guys who had a
lot of hype on them and maybe they couldn't live up to it on that
particular day.''
</P>
<P>
   He has heard that he could be drafted anywhere from the mid to
late second round. But by whom? That is a question that won't be
answered until draft day. ``If I could choose, yeah, definitely it
would be New England,'' Cloud said. ``That would be so much easier.
The transition would be so much easier being close to home, being
local. In a perfect world, this was where I'd love to be.''
</P>
<P>
   So would his mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``She actually called my agent and was like, `Why are the
Patriots trading their first-round draft pick?' Like she has any
idea what that means or anything,'' Cloud said, chuckling. ``My
agent called me back, cracking up laughing. But she's a great woman
and she just wants the best for me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
