<HEADLINE>
DEFENSIVE LINE: NO RUSH FOR A SURE THING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The need for defensive line talent around the NFL seems to far
exceed this group's abilities, but with that said, somebody has to
eventually replace the Reggie Whites and Bruce Smiths, and the
class of 1999 has a player or two with the potential to at least
make a run at that.
</P>
<P>
   The best could be multitalented Jevon Kearse of Florida but most
people consider him a linebacker masquerading as a defensive end,
so for the purposes of this discussion, we'll leave him standing
upright and move on to the true defensive linemen.
</P>
<P>
   To show you how difficult it is to find a defensive lineman who
might have an impact in the league, 56 such players were drafted in
the first round of the nine drafts this decade and nearly half (22)
were taken in the top 10. Few went on to become stars and this year
it's unlikely any will go in the top 10 (excluding Kearse), yet at
least four and perhaps five will be included in the first round in
the hope they hit (quarterbacks in particular).
</P>
<P>
   The top spot has been debated for sometime between LSU's run-
stuffing defensive tackle Anthony McFarland and still developing
defensive ends Ebenezer Ekuban of North Carolina, Patrick Kerney of
Virginia and Lamar King of Saginaw Valley State College (honest).
That debate will continue right into Saturday afternoon but
McFarland seems likely to go first because, while he is not a great
pass rusher, what he can do is obvious _ stuff the inside run _ and
teams will pay someone well for that.
</P>
<P>
   Ekuban, Kerney, and King are three of the more interesting
players at this position because all are projections more than
proven commodities, with big upside potential but accompanying
question marks.
</P>
<P>
   Ekuban moved to the United States from Ghana as a kid and didn't
play football until his junior year of high school. He has great
size and exceptional quickness, which most coaches consider the key
to pass rushing, but seems to lack some of the basic instincts that
come from playing a sport all your life.
</P>
<P>
   Kerney is a lacrosse and hockey player turned quarterback chaser
who was a walk-on to Virginia's football team and became a guy that
walked over ACC offensive linemen, making 23 sacks the last two
seasons. He's worked hard to develop himself against long odds but
is what scouts call ``a light load of poles,'' meaning he's not as
strong as they'd like.
</P>
<P>
   In high school Kerney was 6 feet 3 inches, 160 pounds, during
his early hockey days and was cut from the varsity football team
his first season only to be brought back after his first game on
the JV. Virginia didn't want him anywhere but on the lacrosse field
at first, either, but he's a weight room warrior who built himself
into an All-ACC performer. A full-time weight program and his work
ethic all but guarantee that Kerney will become stronger still in
the NFL, but will he retain his quickness and continue improving?
Some team will seek to answer that question with a first-round
pick.
</P>
<P>
   King may be the biggest gamble among the top-rated linemen
because he did big things in a very small place. Nebraska was hot
after him but academic problems precluded his going to Lincoln so
he ended up at tiny Saginaw State, where he was a giant both in the
weight room and on the field. As one would expect, King dominated
at that level but can he do the same thing when the competition
becomes much stiffer?
</P>
<P>
   Those are the questions scouts and personnel gurus will face
this weekend when they survey this group. Likely to be among those
asking such questions is New England's vice president for personnel
Bobby Grier, who may well have Ekuban, King, and the likes of
Florida defensive tackle Reggie McGrew and Florida State defensive
end Tony Bryant to pick from when the 20th selection of the first
round comes his way. If coach Pete Carroll controlled the situation
he'd grab someone like Ekuban and worry about a second-tier running
back or a tackle to groom as Bruce Armstrong's eventual replacement
eight picks later, when the Patriots make the 28th pick.
</P>
<P>
   But Grier calls the shots in the draft room so the decision _
and the responsibility _ will fall to him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
