<SLUG> BC-TV-SPORTS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ESPN WELCOMES THE DRAFT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HOWARD MANLY   
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As Chris Berman tells the story, a lot of people thought
televising the NFL draft was about as interesting as reading the
Yellow Pages.
</P>
<P>
   They were probably right. When ESPN started its daylong coverage
in 1980, the draft was the only link the cable sports network had
with the NFL. Berman recalled his first year as host in 1981 when
he worked out of an Italian restaurant in New York City. The draft
was held on Tuesday mornings then and Berman, a diehard New York
Jets fan, learned that his team had made a foolish pick.
</P>
<P>
   Just as Berman started railing against the Jets, the power blew
out. ``It was as if my yelling overloaded the circuits,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ESPN won't have any similar technology problems this year. ESPN
and ESPN2 have 17 hours of coverage, starting Saturday at noon.
ESPN has live coverage from the headquarters of 27 NFL teams. The
network's usual suspects will be on hand to report the news and
give instant analysis. Berman, Mike Tirico, and Mel Kiper Jr. will
be stationed at Madison Square Garden. Joe Theisman, Chris
Mortensen, Jim Kelly, Boomer Esiason, and Marty Schottenheimer will
also be in New York. Solomon Wilcots will report from Foxborough.
ESPN also has a ``war room'' cam to watch Patriots coaches make
their first-round selections.
</P>
<P>
   One of the best parts about ESPN's coverage is the crawl
appearing at the bottom of screens, which detail the latest draft
selections.
</P>
<P>
   Don't worry about the 15-minute periods that teams have to pick.
ESPN has plenty of graphics, features, and talking heads to fill
with ease.
</P>
<P>
   The network also has prepared notable draft moments, including
the 1983 draft when John Elway refused to play in Baltimore and was
subsequently traded to Denver; the 1988 draft when ESPN spent the
day with Oklahoma State running back Thurman Thomas, who fell
asleep during the telecast awaiting the call from Buffalo late in
the second round.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first five minutes are scripted,'' said ESPN producer Jay
Rothman. ``The rest of the time we are flying by the seat of our
pants.''
</P>
<P>
   The news dictates the themes of coverage. With all the talk
about quarterbacks, ESPN has put together a feature on the Class of
'83, the year six signal-callers were selected in the first round _
Elway, Todd Blackledge, Kelly, Tony Eason, Ken O'Brien, and Dan
Marino. ESPN also will have a feature on Peyton Manning and Ryan
Leaf, the top quarterbacks drafted last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a sexy draft,'' Berman said. ``By that I mean there
are a lot of skilled players with the biggest names in this year's
draft. So one of the stories will be whether any of these
quarterbacks can turn things around on a bad team. Another story
will be whether Mike Ditka trades his entire draft to get Ricky
Williams.''
</P>
<P>
   ESPN has come a long way from its first draft day coverage. It
was lucky to even get to do that. In 1979, the NFL owners voted
against ESPN televising the event.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a way to get back into football before we dive
headlong into baseball,'' Berman said. ``The draft involves every
NFL team and is a way for college football fans to find out where
their favorite player will be going in the pros. It's a lot of fun.
It's exciting, and it's a lot of work.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-16-99 1356EDT &QL; 
