<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-$ADV18-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COUPLE'S FUND PICKINGS LACK IN DIVERSITY DEPARTMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, April 18, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. We are a couple, both 39, and we would like to retire at age
59. We feel we have made a good start at saving for this, but don't
feel our distribution is very well balanced. We currently have an
income of $120,000 a year; 10 percent of this goes into 401(k)
plans, and our employers match the contributions of 5 percent of
our salary. The savings are invested in Vanguard funds, with
$25,000 in Wellington, $165,000 in Windsor II, $5,000 in
International Growth, and $20,000 in Prime money market. Other
offerings available are the Total Bond Market Index fund and
Primecap. What would you suggest for an aggressive, more balanced
distribution? Second, what kind of yearly distributions might we
expect from our accounts once we reach age 59?
</P>
<P>
   P.P., Lunenburg, mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Well, I agree you're pretty heavily committed to large-cap
domestic stocks, but adding Primecap to the lineup wouldn't help
much _ it's a large-cap fund with a portfolio representing a blend
of growth and value issues, so it would be a little relief from the
value oriented large-cap portfolios of both Windsor II and the
stock side of Wellington. What you really want is offerings such as
Vanguard Mid-Cap and Small-Cap Index funds, or its Extended Market
Index.
</P>
<P>
   Nor would I suggest at your age that you move any substantial
amount of money into Vanguard's Total Bond Market Index _ not
because the fund doesn't do a good job, but because any significant
concentration in bonds will drag the portfolio over the long haul.
If it were my account, I would move from the money market fund to
Primecap, but if you insist that your portfolio have a fallback
position that's invested conservatively, you could move from the
money market to Bond Market Index.
</P>
<P>
   But the most important thing for you to do at this time is to
lobby your employer (or employers) for a broader menu of funds. You
could point out the substantial duplication of large-cap
investments in Windsor II, Primecap and the stock portfolio of
Wellington, and point out that offering a money market, one bond
fund and one international fund simply isn't sufficient to allow
you to build a well-balanced portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   As for where you should be in 20 years, if we presume 10 percent
average annual growth and ongoing contributions of $18,000 a year
between yourselves and your employers, the total would be
$2,524,465. The income stream you might generate from this would
depend on how you had it invested. My feeling is that for somebody
retiring early, there should be a very substantial amount of money
left in growth accounts after retirement, to provide capital to
help you cope with the effects on inflation in the later years of
retirement.
</P>
<P>
   If you achieved an average 6.5 percent yield on the fixed-income
side, that would mean a $97,500 income stream. That likely won't
seem so tidy in 20 years as it does now, given what inflation is
likely to do to the buying power of money. But on the other hand,
if you (and your employers) continue to put a set percentage of
your salaries into your 401(k)s, the affect of every raise you get
during the next 20 years will be to build the savings pool larger.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. A professional has recommended that I sell my holdings in
AARP GNMA and US Treasury and T. Rowe Price International Stock
funds. She says both have underperformed their peers. Do you agree,
and what would you buy to replace them? Would I increase risk
dramatically by buying a corporate bond fund with proceeds of the
AARP fund?
</P>
<P>
   C.K., Wellesley, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Well, they say the Devil was trained as a statistician. But I
can't find any set of figures which prove the claim that either of
these funds have significantly underperformed their peers.
</P>
<P>
   AARP GNMA and US Treasury fund has year-to-date, 12-month, and
3-year average annual returns of 1.1 percent, 6.61 and 7.1 percent.
In comparison, its peer group of short-term government securities
showed a median return of 0.8 percent, 5.5 percent, and 6.1 percent
respectively for the same time periods. If it wouldn't show a
cynical streak in me, I'd wonder aloud whether somebody was trying
to sell you some mutual funds. The AARP fund, rated above average
by Morningstar Mutual Funds, is a solid if unspectacular offering,
and if its investment category remains the right place for you to
be, I see no reason to change.
</P>
<P>
   You might make a slightly better argument that the T. Rowe Price
fund has underperformed its peers, but I think it's pretty thin.
Entering this week, the fund had a year-to-date total return of 3.7
percent, trailing the median 4.7 percent for its world stock peers.
But over a year the Price fund's 3.4 percent compares nicely to its
peer group median of 1.1 percent, and its average annual return of
10.6 percent trails its peer group median of 10.7 percent only very
slightly.
</P>
<P>
   I see no reason to buy anything from the person who has been
advising you.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am 50 and have no debts. I am looking to retire at age 65.
I recently got a government job and will soon begin to build a
403(b) account with Vanguard, to which I am able to contribute $500
a month. I also have a 401(k) from a previous employer amounting to
$80,000. Of this, 20 percent is in common stock, 28 percent in
Fidelity Contrafund, and the rest is divided evenly among Fidelity
Magellan, Fidelity Equity-Income, and Janus Worldwide. I also have
an IRA of $38,000, with the money evenly divided among Fidelity's
Contrafund, Value, Blue Chip and Low-Priced stock funds. Finally, I
have $10,000 in a money market fund and a similar amount in a
taxable account with Fidelity Value fund, and I add $100 a month to
each of these accounts. Is the distribution of my money
appropriate? How should I allocate money at Vanguard?
</P>
<P>
   (Anonymous)
</P>
<P>
   A. Well, since I tally that more than 85 percent of your money
is basically invested in domestic large-cap stocks, I do think some
further diversification is in order.
</P>
<P>
   Within the old IRA, I would move the Fidelity Blue Chip holding
to Fidelity Select Health Care and the Fidelity Value position to
Fidelity Puritan, a fund into which I suggest you start filtering
increasing amounts of money when you get to be about five or six
years away from expected retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Within the old 401(k), I would swap the Janus Worldwide position
for one in a fund entirely devoted to foreign stock (as opposed to
world stock) investments, such as Vanguard International Stock or
Fidelity Overseas. And in this account, I'd move half of the funds
now in Fidelity Contrafund to Fidelity Puritan.
</P>
<P>
   As for the new account with Vanguard, I'd suggest you use your
investments to continue broadening your diversification, with an
eventual target of getting to no more than 50 to 60 percent in the
large-caps. Good funds to take you in that direction would be
Vanguard's Extended Market and its Mid-Cap and Small-Cap index
funds.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Send letters, including your name, address and telephone
number, to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, Mass. 02107.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
