<HEADER>
A1366 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-CUNANAN-BOS &LR;      04-16 1055
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-CUNANAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANDREW CUNANAN'S TWISTED TRAIL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD DYER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
THREE MONTH FEVER 
The Andrew Cunanan Story 
By Gary Indiana 
Cliff Street Books/HarperCollins, 254 pp., illustrated, $25 
 
VULGAR FAVORS 
Andrew Cunanan, Gianni Versace, and the Largest Failed Manhunt in
U.S.  History 
By Maureen Orth 
Delacorte Press, 452 pp., $24.95 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For a few weeks in 1997 Andrew Cunanan commanded the attention
of the media, but it wasn't until after he gunned down the fashion
designer Gianni Versace, his fifth victim, that Cunanan became the
celebrity he'd wanted to be all his life. He had probably never
thought of himself as the kind of celebrity the media labeled him:
a sociopath, a serial killer, a high-priced male prostitute, among
other things. Cunanan's mainstream celebrity lasted a scant eight
days, until, trapped, he lay down on the black satin sheets in a
tacky houseboat and shot himself.
</P>
<P>
   Cunanan might be pleased to know that he enjoys a measure of
posthumous fame, as two complementary books about him appear
simultaneously: ``Vulgar Favors,'' by Maureen Orth, a reporter for
Cunanan's favorite magazine, Vanity Fair; and ``Three Month
Fever,'' by the essayist and novelist Gary Indiana. He would not,
however, be pleased by his characterization in either book, or by
the things his friends have said about him. At least in hindsight,
the grandiose edifice of lies he built on the level foundation of
his life never fooled anyone. One friend did say something
perceptive to Indiana, however, observing that Cunanan's tragedy
was not that he was a congenital liar, but that no one around him
ever told him the truth.
</P>
<P>
   Both books have a polemical edge. The subtitle of Orth's
``Vulgar Favors'' points to part of her mission, to expose the
overlaps, and gaps, in this country's jurisdictional systems. The
wonder is not that the manhunt for Cunanan failed, but that any
manhunt could ever succeed, given the turf wars, the political
pressures, the egos, the colossal unwieldiness of the system, and
the incompetence of individuals within it _ it is a sorry story
that Orth tells, pointing out that better mechanisms exist for
tracing a missing vehicle than for tracking a missing person or a
fugitive.
</P>
<P>
   Indiana, a renegade essayist and author of ``Resentment,'' a
hilarious and disturbing novel about the trial of the Menendez
brothers, finds Cunanan's story ``somewhat poignant and depressing
but fairly ordinary.'' What scares Indiana is not Cunanan, but the
force of the unleashed media, the willingness of people to sell
themselves to the media, and the willingness of the public to buy
into the process. Most of the coverage of the manhunt and the case
was lurid and homophobic because Cunanan represented everything the
heterosexual public loves to hate about gay people. Indiana, who
delights in paradox, argues that the glittering, money-fueled
fashion-and-media world of Versace is every bit as sociopathic as
everyone said Cunanan was.
</P>
<P>
   Orth is an indefatigable reporter who apparently thinks that the
indiscriminate piling up of detail will suggest verisimilitude
rather than bad writing and inadequate editing; almost every page
presents a litter of detail that needs hoovering. Orth is a tourist
in many of the worlds Andrew Cunanan called home. This means that
she can sometimes be fresh and even fearless: ``In Gay America, men
treat each other as objects in a manner that most women today would
consider blatantly sexist.'' She insists that Versace was
HIV-positive (the only major figure in Cunanan's saga who was),
despite the strenuous objections and denials of the Versace family.
</P>
<P>
   More often, when Orth aspires to the Vanity Fair smirk, the tone
of the knowing insider, she comes out sounding gaga, clueless, or
even prejudicial. Twice she may have been telephoned by Cunanan _
the giveaway, to her, was his ``gay voice,'' whatever that might be
(Liberace? Randolph Scott?). When it comes to explaining the
unexplainable, she resorts to psychobabble about the interaction of
drugs and pornography on Cunanan's unbalanced mind. Her book is
badly organized, repetitious, and much too given to the
portentously pat summary (``The unraveling had begun'').
</P>
<P>
   Indiana's effort is riskier and more successful. Much of the
book is narrated from inside Cunanan's mind; the rest is interview
material, Indiana's own assessments, or police and FBI material,
printed without comment, though never without effect. Indiana also
incorporates far more of Cunanan's sophomorically clever writing
than Orth does (Cunanan's postcards reveal more than they intended
to). For the rest, Indiana uses his experience and a novelist's
imagination to fill in the gaps in a way that almost always seems
persuasive and plausible.
</P>
<P>
   He is by no means a tourist in Cunanan's world and takes much
for granted that makes Orth gasp. His eye and ear are alert, and so
is his evaluating brain. Of Norman Blachford, who kept Cunanan for
a year, Indiana writes, ``His statements to police and FBI suggest
a serene detachment from the case, as if an appliance he had once
leased were now suspected of causing a warehouse fire.'' He
incorporates many of the same facts or factoids that appear in
Orth's narrative and appears to have interviewed many of the same
people; but many of his facts are different ones, or contradict
Orth's discoveries, or come with his own spin on them. ``What isn't
plausible,'' Indiana writes, ``is that Andrew sunned himself on the
Riviera and regularly fleeced little fortunes out of lonely
millionaires while managing a drugstore and living with his
mother.''
</P>
<P>
   Orth's book comes without illustrations, though there are
photographs of Cuananan's victims on the dust jacket and a wanted
poster on the frontispiece; Indiana has 16 pages of black-and-white
pictures, including a police photo of the dead killer. Both books
were completed in great haste, which sometimes shows; both writers
have paradoxically become subject to the same media pressures they
attack. Orth's Cunanan ends up as a cliche, a drug-crazed monster;
Indiana argues that the the media needed Cunanan to be a monster
and therefore made him one. The real monster slouching through our
society is something else.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
