<HEADER>
A1371 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-LIVE-BOS &LR;      04-16 0704
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-LIVE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MURPHY'S LATEST COULD USE MORE LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOAN ANDERMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
LIFE 
Directed by: Ted Demme 
Screenplay by: Robert Ramsey and Matthew Stone 
Starring: Eddie Murphy, Martin Lawrence, Nick Cassevetes, Obba
Babatunde, Ned Beatty, Bernie Mac, Miguel A. Nunez, Jr. Calrence
Williams III, Bokeem Woodbine 
Running Time: 109 min. 
Rated: R (strong language, some violence) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Eddie Murphy's on a roll _ straight downhill, on a crash course
with a legacy of comedic mediocrity. The opening scene of Murphy's
new film, ``Life,'' is set in a prison cemetery, as two inmates
shovel earth onto a grave. It's a fitting entree into a film that
feels like one more heap of dirt on Murphy's once-bright career,
which has been in an artistic free-fall for more than a decade.
</P>
<P>
   There are all kinds of things wrong with ``Life,'' beginning
with its aspiration to be equal parts comedy and drama. Racial
bigotry and wrongful imprisonment make a dicey foundation for
humor, especially in a mainstream vehicle for a broad-brush actor
like Eddie Murphy. Maybe this is Murphy's stab at distancing
himself from the bloated, arrogant persona he's cultivated since
his early '80s heyday. But if the shift is well-intentioned, it's
still a move in the wrong direction _ away from the edgy wiseguy
that made Murphy a star and toward a more layered concept that he
simply isn't dimensional enough to pull off.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Life,'' Murphy stars as Ray Gibson, a small-time New York
hustler in the '30s whose destiny becomes entwined with that of
aspiring bank teller Claude Banks (Martin Lawrence) when he lifts
Banks's wallet in a swank Harlem nightclub. Both wind up owing
money to Spanky, the club owner, who lets the pair pay off their
respective debts by going on a bootlegging run to Mississippi.
</P>
<P>
   While there, the two are framed by a white sheriff for murder
and are sentenced to life in a Southern plantation-style prison.
Following a bit of ditch-digging, however, Ray, Claude, and the
predictable crew of fun-loving criminals seem to spend most of
their time playing baseball, hosting barbeques for the locals, and
growing older _ 60 years older, in fact, during which time Ray and
Claude develop an ``Odd-Couple''-style friendship chock full of
cranky confrontations and old-biddy bickering.
</P>
<P>
   The brilliant work of famed Hollywood makeup artist Rick Baker
(the latex-wielding craftsman behind Murphy's ``The Nutty
Professor'') is the most believable feature of this lifelong
relationship, which strains unsuccessfully to expand beyond the
confines of tired jail-cell jokes and botched escape schemes. As
the film leaps decades in a single bound _ spanning 1932 to the
present via newsreels and hairstyles _ Ray and Claude are
transformed with phenomenal detail and clarity from young adulthood
to midlife to old age. But the pair's physical transformation isn't
matched on an emotional level. Which would be just fine, if
``Life'' wasn't striving to be something deeper than a kooky buddy
film. Murphy, however is utterly incapable of conveying the subtly
drawn tenderness that would have animated Ray's long and
complicated bond with Claude. One wonders why Lawrence's Claude _
who has the advantage of being able to react, in contrast to
Murphy, whose delivery is exclusively in-your-face _ even bothers
to maintain this friendship.
</P>
<P>
   Oddly, the human drama that ``Life'' aims to capture between
gags is supplied in fits and starts by the supporting cast: Bokeem
Woodbine as Can't Get Right, a young inmate who is unable to speak
and fathers a child with the superintendent's daughter; Miguel A.
Nunez Jr. as Biscuit, a gay prisoner who can't face his family upon
release; and Ned Beatty as the sympathetic prison superintendent.
And the whole motley crew does, over the years, become something
like one big, strange happy family.
</P>
<P>
   Something as simple as funnier jokes (how many times are we
expected to laugh at the burly lifer awkwardly coming on to the new
kid on the cell block?), or a glimmer of poignancy to mark decades
surviving a cruel fate, might have breathed some life into this
film. As it is, ``Life'' is DOA.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
