<HEADER>
A1394 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-DeBARTOLO-HNS &LR;      04-16 0861
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-DeBARTOLO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
49ERS OWNER FIRES BACK AT SISTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SCOTT WINOKUR  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ San Francisco 49ers' co-owner Edward DeBartolo
Jr. has gone on offensive, filing a $150 million federal lawsuit
against his estranged sister, Denise DeBartolo York, and vowing to
regain control of the football team.
</P>
<P>
   But what DeBartolo failed to say Thursday _ surrounded by his
family and 49er greats Joe Montana, Jerry Rice and Roger Craig _
might make people in San Francisco wonder if he was intentionally
omitting a crucial play from his game plan.
</P>
<P>
   DeBartolo, 52, continued to remain silent on the question of his
1997 promise to build a $200 million shopping mall adjacent to a
new football stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Pressed on the issue, a spokesman for DeBartolo from the Arthur
Andersen consulting company refused to engage in what he called
``speculation'' about the commercial center, which, like the
stadium, is on hold. City officials say the mall must be built if
the club is to receive $100 million in public financing authorized
by voters nearly two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was extremely telling that Mr. DeBartolo did not
deal with any of the key issues ... which would lead one to believe
he doesn't have the answers to some very good questions,'' said
York's spokesman, Sam Singer.
</P>
<P>
   According to Singer, York and her husband, 49ers vice president
John York, are committed to ``finding an economically sensible way
to build a stadium-mall project in San Francisco.''
</P>
<P>
   There was no immediate comment from Mayor Willie Brown, who
rallied support for some public financing for the stadium and
commercial development.
</P>
<P>
   National Football League spokesman Greg Aiello said the league
would not comment on the latest legal development in the running
dispute between DeBartolo and York.
</P>
<P>
   Capping a week of furious activity that included futile attempts
to resolve their differences at a meeting Tuesday in Youngstown,
Ohio, DeBartolo announced through spokesman Rick Rice that the
16-page lawsuit had been filed Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit accused York of repudiating two agreements giving
her brother control of the club, including an Aug. 14, 1998,
written pact to move ahead with a tax-free spinoff of the 49ers to
DeBartolo as part of a separation of their financial interests.
</P>
<P>
   DeBartolo, in return, was to give up all his shares in the
family company. The agreement would have required the approval of
the Internal Revenue Service and the NFL. For the purposes of the
spinoff, the club was to be valued at $350 million _ $333 million
more than it cost DeBartolo in 1977.
</P>
<P>
   DeBartolo claimed, however, that York and one of her attorneys
changed their minds in the wake of other football deals that
followed in which franchises were sold or offered for much greater
sums.
</P>
<P>
   He also alleged that York was concerned with a significant
devaluation of her immense assets in the Simon Property Group, the
nation's largest commercial property company, in late 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, DeBartolo claimed that, after years of having no
interest in the club, York was increasingly eager to hold on to it
because of a ``lucrative financing plan'' offered by the NFL to
owners who wished to build or renovate their stadiums.
</P>
<P>
   Because of all this, DeBartolo alleged, York had come to regret
her agreement to sell. ``She wanted to find a way out,'' the
lawsuit said.
</P>
<P>
   DeBartolo also alleged in the lawsuit that he continued to have
``total and complete power to make all decisions'' affecting the
franchise under terms of a 1986 agreement with the family company,
Edward J. DeBartolo Corp. of Youngstown.
</P>
<P>
   According to the lawsuit, that agreement transferred ownership
of the club to a subsidiary of the company in order to ``make
profitable use of tax losses from the team,'' which was running
``substantial deficits.''
</P>
<P>
   The federal lawsuit came on the heels of a lawsuit against
DeBartolo filed in San Francisco Superior Court last week by the
DeBartolo Corp., which DeBartolo and York co-own, but which York
controls. The $3 billion company _ named for their late father, one
of the nation's leading builders of shopping malls _ owns 90
percent of the 49ers.
</P>
<P>
   That lawsuit accused DeBartolo of reneging on a $94 million debt
and cutting a shady side deal with the likely developer of the
proposed mall. It called on him to repay the money and abandon any
financial interest in the mall.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to Thursday's federal lawsuit against her, York said
in a statement that her own lawsuit ``was necessary to maintain the
stability of the company my father created.'' She also said her
brother's lawsuit had ignored ``key facts,'' including his
indebtedness.
</P>
<P>
   DeBartolo has not been in an official club management post since
1997, when he voluntarily stepped down from positions in the
corporation and the club, following disclosure of his role in a
gambling-and-bribery case in Louisiana.
</P>
<P>
   In March, NFL Commissioner Paul Tagliabue fined DeBartolo $1
million and continued his suspension through the end of the
1999-2000 football season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
