<SLUG> BC-JACKSON-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO SAFE BET ON THE LOTTERY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DERRICK Z. JACKSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   No one would dare, nor should anyone dare, begrudge Maria Grasso
the $197 million that made the Chilean immigrant the biggest
individual lottery winner in US history. &UR;  &LR; Besides being a caregiver
to Beacon Hill millionaires Hilary and Chris Gabrieli, Grasso
worked with mentally challenged adults and children when she lived
in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one deserved it more,'' said Jan Miller, of United Cerebral
Palsy of New York State.
</P>
<P>
   ``She suffered. She had to go outside the country and help
support us,'' said Grasso's sister, Ana Luisa Becerra in Chile.
</P>
<P>
   ``There ought to be little miracles in life,'' said Lisa de
Roetth, a Beacon Hill neighbor. ``And there's magic in this.''
</P>
<P>
   With odds much better than 1-in-52 million that someone this
very moment is scripting a movie about her life, Grasso says she
will never work at hard physical labor again. But it is clear she
wants to work small miracles on behalf of others. Grasso said she
will fund programs for people with special needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always try to be low, down-key, and I'm going to continue
that way,'' Grasso said.
</P>
<P>
   This may be a genuine individual case of blessed are the meek,
but it does not change the fact that most of the meek shall not
inherit the earth through the lottery. It is not only to Grasso's
benefit that she already is coming off like a philanthropist. The
greater benefit goes to the lottery itself.
</P>
<P>
   It could have not have dreamed up a more disarming poster child
to distract us from its regressive underbelly. To make one humble
woman rich, the lottery first had to rob the poor.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, a Globe series on gambling found that residents
in working-class and low-income towns spent far more of their
disposable income on the lottery than people in wealthy suburbs.
While people in Weston bet a mere $63 per capita on the lottery, no
doubt because they are cleaning up in the stock market, people in
Chelsea spent $915 a year on the lottery.
</P>
<P>
   For Weston residents, the amount spent on the lottery was less
than two-tenths of 1 percent of income. For residents of Chelsea,
the amount was 8 percent of income.
</P>
<P>
   The same Massachusetts that preaches personal responsibility and
hard work in slashing welfare is also the pusher preying on their
meager wages, blitzing every possible bodega, liquor store,
check-cashing joint, gas station and restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   The same is true in the rest of the nation. Heavy players in
Virginia spend an average of $1,200 a year on the lottery, even
though one in six players had household incomes of less than
$15,000. In Maryland, heavy players (who spend at least $10 a week)
were heavily skewed toward high school dropouts and those making
less than $20,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   In Wisconsin, people in poor areas pay four times as much of the
earnings on the lottery than people in wealthy areas.
</P>
<P>
   In Colorado, the 32 counties that spend the most per capita on
the lottery are all below the per capita average for state income.
</P>
<P>
   In New Mexico, the three most impovershed counties are in the
top 10 for per-capita lottery sales.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, a 1995 study of data by Newsday found that people
in the poorest census tracts spent eight times more money on the
lottery than people in the highest income tracts.
</P>
<P>
   In that study, Robert Goodman, a professor at Hampshire College
in Amherst who studies gambling said, ``As you go down the income
scale, people perceive it as a form of investment. As you go up the
income scale, people do it as a form of entertainment. Government
is promoting an activity that is essentially a poor form of
investment for most people.''
</P>
<P>
   When you consider that in 1996, the lottery took in $35 billion
from 38 states, and when you are reminded that nationally, only 34
cents per each dollar spent actually comes back to the people in
the form of public services _ a return that would never be
acceptable in the world of mutual funds _ that is an incredibly
wasted ``investment.'' It is a tax.
</P>
<P>
   The $35 billion would place the lotteries at No. 20 in the
Fortune 500, between Merrill Lynch and Prudential. But while
Merrill Lynch's bull rampages through Wall Street, creating untold
wealth for the top 5 percent of Americans, all you see from the
typical player of the lottery is a scratch, a sigh and a toss of a
worthless card into the gutter.
</P>
<P>
   There never has been a good reason for the state to push
gambling, and it is even more insidious in an era when politicians
are otherwise so mean to the poor.
</P>
<P>
   The good fortune of Grasso does not change that one bit. It will
be nice if she gives some of her money to charity, but that is not
the way to spread the wealth. She is one beaming, highly publicized
woman who struck it rich. However, most players of the lottery,
when you catch them at the bodega counter, will readily tell you
they never expect to inherit the earth through their scratch
tickets. In fact, the state disinherits them every day.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Derrick Z. Jackson is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-16-99 1406EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
