<SLUG> BC-MARROW-TRANSPLANT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATIENTS STILL HOLD ON TO HOPE FOR A CURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDY FOREMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Barbara Brogna, a 44-year-old banker with breast
cancer, had a bone marrow transplant two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   When it didn't work, she was devastated. But she'd have another
if she had to, she says, her cheeks rosy and her face alight
despite ongoing chemotherapy: ``I am determined I will live with
this disease, not die from it.''
</P>
<P>
   Lucille Foster, a 57-year old dental receptionist, was in the
same clincal study as Brogna, but was randomly assigned to two
years of chemotherapy instead of a transplant. She's in remission:
``I go to bed praying and wake up praying.''
</P>
<P>
   As Brogan and Foster chatted the other day, Diane Zaniboni, 38,
listened, her eyes glued to their faces. She hasn't had to make a
decision yet about a transplant, but she may. ``There is a part of
me,'' she says, ``that will do whatever it takes to survive so I
can live to see my 8-year old daughter grow up.''
</P>
<P>
   Brogna, Foster and Zaniboni are but three of the thousands of
women every year who agonize over whether to have a bone marrow
transplant for spreading breast cancer. Since the mid-1980s, in
fact, 12,000 breast cancer patients have had the transplants,
despite a dearth of evidence that the procedures would help.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, the agony of their dilemma was intensified with
publication of five new studies that, overall, showed no clear
benefit of the transplants. The results were posted on the net
(www.asco.org) by the American Society of Clinical Oncology.
</P>
<P>
   In a bone marrow transplant, and a similar procedure called stem
cell transplant, patients are given near-lethal doses of
chemotherapy and radiation and then ``rescued'' by reinfusion of
their own immune cells taken from the blood or bone marrow. The
treatment not only causes symptoms like severe nausea and diarrhea
but puts the patient at considerable risk of infection until the
bone marrow regenerates.
</P>
<P>
   In theory, that high blast of cancer-killing therapy should be
more effective than lower dose therapy. But in four of the five new
studies, ``investigators found no statistically significant
difference in survival between patients receiving'' high dose
chemotherapy/bone marrow transplants ``and those receiving
lower-dose chemotherapy without transplants,'' said the National
Cancer Institute in a prepared statement.
</P>
<P>
   In the fifth study, from South Africa, there was a significant
difference in favor of transplanation. But overall, these
relatively-short term studies show that the higher-dose treatment
is not clearly superior to lower-dose therapy.
</P>
<P>
   That means that the decision to have a transplant becomes a
``very personal one for each woman to make,'' says Zaniboni, a
lawyer and legal secretary.
</P>
<P>
   At 37, while taking a shower, she found a ``humongous'' lump in
her breast. After surgery, chemotherapy and radiation, she's in
remission. If she needs a transplant, she'll go for it.
</P>
<P>
   But it's chilling to realize the transplants may not, as so many
women and their doctors had hoped, be the last, best hope _ and to
listen to other women for whom it hasn't worked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lurking in the back of my mind is the experience of a close
friend of mine who underwent a stem cell transplant last April,''
she says. ``It was unsuccessful.''
</P>
<P>
   But knowing of _ or even having had _ an unsuccessful transplant
should not be an automatic deterrent, says Brogna.
</P>
<P>
   When Brogna was diagnosed in 1993, her prognosis looked good.
She had six months of chemotherapy and was fine until 1996, when
she discovered the cancer had spread to her bones. She had six more
months of chemotherapy. Even so, the cancer spread to her liver.
</P>
<P>
   When her oncologist, Dr. John Erban, chief of hematology and
oncology at NEMC, where all three were treated, suggested that
Brogna join a study there comparing bone marrow transplants to two
years of chemotherapy, she was scared that she'd be randomized to a
transplant and die from it.
</P>
<P>
   Many other women in similar straits feared just the opposite _
that if they joined a randomized study, they might not get a
transplant. In fact, it's because of this fear that dissuaded so
many women from joining studies that it has taken years to get
much-needed data on the efficacy, or lack of it, for transplants.
</P>
<P>
   But Erban eased Brogna's fears and she joined, figuring it was
her ``only hope for a cure.'' She sailed through the transplant in
1996. But six months later, the cancer was still in her liver and
bones and she's been on chemotherapy ever since.
</P>
<P>
   Yet she is upbeat. ``I would recommend a transplant because I
know two other women for whom it left them cancer free. I'm
determined that we are going to beat this. The next two years in
breast cancer treatment are going to be pretty exciting and
encouraging. I look forward to that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
