r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RELIGION-JONES-COLUMN     04-16 0769
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-JONES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUTHOR TAKES ISSUE WITH END-OF-THE-WORLD THEOLOGY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM JONES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Grace Halsell took chemicals to darken her skin to do research
for her book ``Soul Sister.'' She swam the Rio Grande to cross into
the United States in gathering inside knowledge for another
bestseller, ``The Illegals.''
</P>
<P>
   Now she has plunged herself into end-of-the-world biblical
prophecy in researching her latest book, ``Armageddon:
Understanding God's End Game.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I find the Armageddon mind-set very dangerous,'' said Halsell,
who was in Fort Worth to receive a media ethics award from Texas
Christian University's department of journalism.
</P>
<P>
   Halsell, a native of Lubbock who now resides in Washington,
D.C., lived in Fort Worth for a time and was the first female
police reporter for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram in the late 1940s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then I left to write my way around the world,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She toured the British Isles on a bicycle, did free-lance
writing in Lima, Peru, where she visited the Incan ruins of Machu
Picchu, and wrote for newspapers in Hong Kong and Tokyo. Later, she
was a speech writer for President Lyndon B. Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Her latest book, which is to be released this year, expresses
her fears about the end-times theology of many Christians.
</P>
<P>
   Exponents of Bible prophecy believe that a powerful and gifted
leader, known as the Antichrist, will lead a world coalition in the
battle of Armageddon. The Antichrist will be defeated as Christ
returns with the armies of heaven.
</P>
<P>
   Many Christians, particularly those in more liberal mainline
churches, see Armageddon as merely a symbolic battle between good
and evil on Judgment Day. But many other believers see it as an
actual event that will take place in a valley near Megiddo in
Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Another of Halsell's books, ``Prophecy and Politics: the Secret
Alliance Between Israel and the U.S. Christian Right,'' published
in 1989, also explores her concerns about Armageddon theology.
</P>
<P>
   But on the eve of the year 2000, she wanted to look again at
what it means to be a Christian, and why some Christians, such as
the Rev. Jerry Falwell, look toward a violent end of the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Must we totally destroy this world in order to usher in a `new
heaven and a new earth?''' she asks.
</P>
<P>
   Halsell draws on experiences in 1983 and 1985, when she traveled
to Israel on tours led by Falwell. She encountered many on the trip
who are convinced the world will end in a bloody battle on the
plains of Megiddo.
</P>
<P>
   Armageddon theology is preached by much-admired evangelists,
such as Billy Graham and Luis Palau. But as the year 2000
approaches, Halsell said she is alarmed by end-of-the-world
comments being made by many, particularly Falwell and Pat
Robertson, president of the Christian Broadcasting Network.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their sermons are filled with scary stuff,'' Halsell said.
</P>
<P>
   Falwell and Robertson are among those who believe that biblical
signs are in place _ such as the emergence of Israel as a nation,
widespread immorality, numerous earthquakes, floods and other
disasters _ to indicate that the end of the world as we know it is
near.
</P>
<P>
   In her new book, Halsell explains many end-times theories, such
as ``the Rapture,'' a belief that true Christians will be caught up
into heaven by Jesus before the final tribulation, which includes
the Battle of Armageddon.
</P>
<P>
   ``People feel a need for certitude, and they like the idea of
being saved from all this tribulation by the `Rapture,''' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Halsell bases her views solely on her own research and
experiences as a professing Christian and not on any credentials as
a biblical scholar. She argues that those who preach Armageddon
theology replace Christ's teachings about universal love with a God
of war.
</P>
<P>
   They portray Jesus ``as a five-star general, astride a horse,
leading all the armies of the world,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   A better way to usher in ``a new heaven and a new earth,'' she
said, is to focus on revolutionary philosophies taught by Jesus,
such as loving one's neighbor.
</P>
<P>
   Halsell also finds it paradoxical that many Christian leaders,
such as Falwell and Robertson, are so cheerful even though they
preach that a terrible Battle of Armageddon is imminent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The world is coming to an end and they are still smiling,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   (Jim Jones is religion editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7707, or e-mail:
jimjones(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
