<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-16 14:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1434 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LABBE-COLUMN-TEX     04-16 0801
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LABBE-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COUNTING THE COST OF JOURNALISTIC INDEPENDENCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By J.R. LABBE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Slavko Curuvija died Sunday on the streets of Belgrade, a
casualty of war.
</P>
<P>
   But the bullets that ended the 51-year-old's life weren't fired
by NATO forces, or from a Kalashnikov rifle carried in the hands of
a Kosovar rebel.
</P>
<P>
   Curuvija was gunned down because he was a journalist who dared
speak the truth about Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic's
repressive government.
</P>
<P>
   Journalists in too many places around the globe are warriors in
the same battle that took Curuvija's life _ the struggle to provide
independent news reports about official corruption, repression and
abuse.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, we value the concept that the truth shall
set you free. In places like the Congo, Afghanistan and Colombia,
the truth can get you killed.
</P>
<P>
   In Belgrade, Curuvija was publisher of the Dnevni Telegraf, the
first private daily newspaper in Serbia. In a country where the
government controls the majority of the media _ state-run
newspapers and radio and TV stations _ stepping out as an
independent voice draws attention.
</P>
<P>
   As the old saying goes, the nail with its head sticking up is
the one that gets hit.
</P>
<P>
   During testimony at a December congressional committee hearing
in Washington, Curuvija told lawmakers that questioning Milosevic's
rule was tantamount to treason. Just days after a pro-government
newspaper accused Curuvija of supporting NATO bombing, the
publisher was fatally shot _ on a public street at 4:40 in the
afternoon _ outside of his Belgrade apartment building.
</P>
<P>
   Curuvija's name will be among those that appear on the 1999 list
compiled by the Committee to Protect Journalists to account how
press freedom is faring around the world. The sad reality is that
the prominent publisher will no doubt have plenty of company.
</P>
<P>
   The committee's 1998 report, released last month, documented the
slayings of 24 journalists who were killed because of their work.
Another 12 journalists died under circumstances that the CPJ was
unable to confirm as being directly related to their work. And on
New Year's Eve 1998, 118 journalists were known to be imprisoned
for trying to disseminate information that the powers that be in
various nations found unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
   Turkey _ a NATO ally that apparently doesn't embrace the same
democratic ideas about free speech as the United States does _ held
the largest number at 27. China and Ethiopia each held 12
journalists prisoner.
</P>
<P>
   CPJ's report included an accounting of the grisly statistics for
the past 10 years. From 1989 though 1998, 471 journalists were
confirmed killed in the line of duty. The most dangerous countries
for working journalists were Algeria, Colombia, Russia, Tajikistan,
Croatia, India, Bosnia and Herzegovina, Turkey, Rwanda, Peru and
the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
   The United States is not absent from the list.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since the widely publicized 1976 murder of Arizona Republic
reporter Don Bolles, at least 11 other journalists have been
murdered in the United States because of their work,'' the report
said. ``In all but one case, the victims were immigrant journalists
working in languages other than English. Seven of those 11
homicides remain unsolved.''
</P>
<P>
   American journalists become those immigrant reporters when
working in foreign countries. Philip True, the Mexico City
correspondent for the San Antonio Express-News, was found dead in
December at the bottom of a ravine, his body partially covered with
rocks to conceal it, after setting out on a 10-day trip to report
and photograph the Huichol Indians. The Jalisco State medical
examiner ruled that True had been strangled and had sustained a
head injury not attributable to a fall.
</P>
<P>
   Each time I write a column about the Second Amendment or private
gun ownership, I receive e-mail and letters from readers who remark
on the courage that it takes to air such unpopular opinions. Yeah,
right.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't take courage for an opinion writer to speak out in a
country that values a free press right up there with freedom to
worship as one pleases. It doesn't take courage when the law of the
land guarantees one's right to speak the truth _ or even to speak
just shades of the truth.
</P>
<P>
   True courage can be found in the pages of the CPJ report, where
men and women risked harassment, imprisonment, torture and death in
the effort to bring unfettered and unadulterated information to the
people.
</P>
<P>
   (Jill ``J.R.'' Labbe is senior editorial writer and columnist
for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. She can be reached via e-mail at
jrlabbe(at)star-telegram.com or by phone at (817) 390-7599. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
