<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DC </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DC TALK ROOTED IN FAITH, FRIENDS 

</HEADLINE>
 TALK-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By RICHARD VARA 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ dc Talk is all about making good God music.
</P>
<P>
   The talented trio _ Toby McKeehan, Michael Tait and Kevin Max _
is ensconced in the Top 10 on Billboard's contemporary Christian
music chart with its edgy, alternative rock album,
``Supernatural,'' which has sold more than 500,000 copies.
</P>
<P>
   The group broke into the Christian youth scene 10 years ago with
rap and hip-hop appeal mixed with good looks and slick shows that
attracted more than religious kids. They have won shelf-loads of
Dove Awards, three Grammys and have had two platinum albums and one
gold.
</P>
<P>
   ``Supernatural'' dropped a few jaws when it debuted at No. 4 in
the Billboard Top 200 hits last year, a sure sign of crossover
appeal. dc Talk is also distributed by Virgin, a major player in
the recording industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``dc Talk has always wanted to make music for the masses,''
McKeehan said in a phone interview. ``We never wanted to restrict
ourselves to making music just for people who believe the way we
do.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of the songs on `Supernatural' are about human
relationships, about the things we are going through with other
people,'' McKeehan said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's Killing Me,'' for example, is about breaking away from a
self-destructive friend while ``Wanna Be Loved'' is exactly that _
seeking love and meaning in life.
</P>
<P>
   While the trio, who composed the album, wants mass appeal, they
don't want it at the cost of their spiritual messages.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are three guys pursuing our faith,'' McKeehan said. ``We
want to cause people to think about spiritual things.''
</P>
<P>
   Their faith is not just hype. The group has a ``road pastor''
who tends to their spiritual life on tour and at their Nashville
home base. They spend an hour prior to performances reflecting and
sharing thoughts and experiences based on Bible readings.
</P>
<P>
   A top Christian group faces the same temptations that any pop
group faces, including greed, sex, drugs and other snares, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just standing in the spotlight all the time, you get used to
people serving and working for you,'' he said. ``It is important
that we remain servants.''
</P>
<P>
   The trio holds one another accountable spiritually.
</P>
<P>
   ``When one guy forgets his roots, the other guy is there to
remind him of it,'' McKeehan said. Spiritual principles and
friendship is what makes dc Talk go. ``We didn't come together
based on some recording company's marketing scheme,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The three met in the mid-1980s at Liberty University, founded by
the Rev. Jerry Falwell, in Virginia. ``We met just hanging around
and became friends,'' McKeehan said. The three played in different
bands before deciding to blend their talents. Although McKeehan and
Tait are from the Washington, D.C., area, the ``dc'' in their name
stands for ``Decent Christian.''
</P>
<P>
   They began to compose the popular beats and lyrical verses that
first appealed to teen-agers. But dc Talk grew along with their
audience and now can attract not only youth but their parents. They
appeal to sacred-minded listeners and secular audiences.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of their tracks get some play on alternative rock
stations,'' said Doug Hannah, program director for KSBJ, a
Christian FM station with a contemporary adult format. ``Their
(1995 `Jesus Freak') album had a few tracks we were able to play on
our station, and we are very adult in our music mix focus.''
</P>
<P>
   While the group has moved beyond the rap and hip-hop that put
them on the Christian music map, McKeehan said, dc Talk has not
forgotten its roots.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am still a lover of hip-hop,'' McKeehan said. ``I still
start most songs with a `loop' when I produce them.''
</P>
<P>
   The current tour also features a DJ who plays a mix of the rap
and hip-hop.
</P>
<P>
   McKeehan is surprised that the fans have stayed loyal to the
group even though they have moved to contemporary rhythms.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I think that people have stuck with us, it is amazing to
me,'' he said. ``They have been loyal not to Toby, Michael and
Kevin, but to what we are about _ our faith in God and to the fact
that we are honest about our struggles with faith in God.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
