<P>
   YUGOSLAVIA-KOSOVO CONFLICTKOSOVO-STRIKES _ WASHINGTON _ NATO
spokesman were offering scant additional information Friday
regarding the bombing of a civilian convoy in southwestern Kosovo
province earlier this week, despite demands for further explanation
_ demands that at times appeared to touch a nerve during the
briefing at NATO headquarters. The spokesmen maintained that
despite the incident, the U.S.-led NATO bombing campaign will go
on. Also, that the Kosovo rebels are apparently regaining strength.
Developing. (Deans, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REFUGEES _ BLACE, Macedonia _ The numbers of Kosovar
Albanian refugees crossing the borders of Macedonia and Albania
continued to grow Thursday as Serbian military forces cleared
remote mountain towns and villages and word of open borders spread
in southern Kosovo province. Developing. (Holmes/Kunstel, Cox News
Service). WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   REFUGEES-TRAIN _ BRAZDA, Macedonia _ When the Rustemi boarded a
train from inside embattled Kosovo province headed for the
Macedonia border Thursday, they thought salvation from Serbian
military forces and thuggish gangs was near. However, when the
train abruptly stopped and was ordered back they thought they were
dead. On Friday, they finally escaped and told the story of their
frightening two-day ordeal. Developing. (Holmes, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CHAPLAINS _ ATLANTA _ As the conflict in and around
Kosovo continues simmering, the Military Chaplains Association this
weeks comes to Atlanta for its annual meeting. We talk with members
to gauge their reaction to recent events and possible links to
others in the combat area and attend several sessions, including a
workshop on ``Religious and Ethical Issues in the Federal
Chaplaincies.'' (GWhite, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
