   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   DOOLITTLE _ Eighteen of 19 surviving Doolittle Raiders hold
their first reunion at the USAF Museum since the 1960s. The raiders
flew with Lt. Col. Jimmy Doolittle on a daring daylight bombing
raid on Japan on April 18, 1942. This will be their 57th reunion. A
media availability is scheduled for Friday at the Doolittle
Raiders' B-25 exhibit in the museum. Today (Saturday) they will
hold a memorial service at the museum that will be open to the
public and will include a a flyover by the restored B-25 ``Old
Glory.'' Press release will be in tickler. (Ali, Dayton Daily
News). WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   FREAKNIK17 _ ATLANTA _ Main news story on Black College Reunion
in Atlanta. Criminal activity and arrests have marked previous
year's events. (Longa-Good, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   URBAN-WARGAMES _ The black helicopters, and the
specially-trained U.S. Army troops they dropped across South Texas
for 10 days in February, are gone now. In their wake, they left a
trail of tales that will be told, retold, and embellished for years
_ the soldiers rappeling into cities, the explosions, the
accidental fire, the satchel full of cash to pay for damages. And
they ignited a new round of buzz among those who consider the
helicopters symbols of government oppression or a coming one-world
order. The training exercises by the Army's Special Operations
Command, dubbed Operation Last Dance, were the latest in a 10-year
effort to give America's elite troops real-world experience in
different urban environments. And in town after town, local leaders
remain divided over whether they would invite the soldiers back for
an encore. (Harmon, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   TRUMP _ PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Hearing continues on Donald Trump's
attempt to lift restrictions on his Mar-a-Lago Club.
Preservationists and residents oppose the proposals. (Sims, Palm
Beach Daily News)
</P>
