<HEADLINE>
SIZING UP PALM V, AERO 2100 PALMTOPS &HT;     

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   (Undated) Folks who like to use handheld computers _ a k a
palmtops or personal digital assistants _ are downright religious
about them.
</P>
<P>
   Not only can the devices help simplify and organize a hectic
life, but a user looks so darned cool when whipping one out.
</P>
<P>
   But here's the ugly truth about palmtops _ most of them end up
occupying space in sock drawers. While a lot of tech-savvy types
like the idea of organizing their contacts, appointments, notes and
even e-mail in a machine you can fit in a jacket pocket, usually
they are more trouble than they are worth.
</P>
<P>
   The undisputed leader of this genre is Palm Computing's line of
Palm organizers, which has won the passion of handheld users in a
way that was once the purview of the now-defunct Apple Newton.
</P>
<P>
   The Palm line is being challenged by a slew of devices that use
Microsoft's Windows CE operating system. But Palm is standing firm,
with well over 70 percent of the market.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a look at the latest, thinnest Palm organizer, and a
colorful challenger from Houston's Compaq Computer Corp.
</P>
<P>
   __ Palm V _ $449, 3Com/Palm Computing. The emphasis with Palm's
devices has always been on simplicity. From the earliest model, the
Palm Pilot, up to this slick, sleek entry, the focus has been on
making its use easy and intuitive.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with the Palm V, it's stylish, too.
</P>
<P>
   The Palm V is about half the thickness of the Palm IIIx, an
updated version of the Palm III, the company's mainstream product.
It's encased in a brushed metal case and sports a super-clear new
display with a higher resolution than past models.
</P>
<P>
   There are many nifty touches to its design, which is aimed at
style-conscious executives who are willing to pay for a digital
fashion statement.
</P>
<P>
   For example, there are grooves on the left and right edges of
the Palm V. You can place a stylus in one groove, and the spine of
a leather cover in the other.
</P>
<P>
   Because they are interchangeable, the Palm V can be configured
for either right- or left-handers.
</P>
<P>
   Those who are used to using Palm devices will be most struck by
the display, which is a dramatic improvement. Text and graphics are
crisper in plain light.
</P>
<P>
   But the handheld's backlight _ which renders everything a fuzzy
green _ still leaves a lot to be desired.
</P>
<P>
   The Palm V has 2 megabytes of memory, which sounds small but can
hold a lot _ 3,000 appointments, 6,000 addresses or 200 e-mail
messages. An optional 2-MB upgrade can boost the Palm V up to the 4
MB level of the Palm IIIx.
</P>
<P>
   One handy option is a modem designed just for the Palm V that
snaps onto the back of it. It makes the Palm V about the same size
as the Palm III series, and enables you to get your e-mail
wirelessly.
</P>
<P>
   There is excellent software that lets you enter information via
your PC, then synchronize it to the Palm device. A new feature that
comes with the software for the Palm V provides a direct
connection, or ``conduit,'' to Microsoft's Outlook contact manager.
</P>
<P>
   There are two big drawbacks to the Palm V. First is its reliance
on handwriting recognition. Palm uses a program called Graffitti,
first found on the Newton, that requires users to learn a
simplified set of letters.
</P>
<P>
   Although it improves handwriting recognition in general, it
still will frustrate those whose handwriting is less than
letter-perfect _ like mine.
</P>
<P>
   An onscreen keyboard is available, but it also can be
frustrating.
</P>
<P>
   Aero 2100 _ $449 and up, Compaq Computer Corp. The Aero
resurrects the name of a subnotebook computer that Compaq peddled
in the 486 processor era.
</P>
<P>
   Beset with problems, the original Aero died a deserved death
when the Pentium processor began migrating into notebooks.
</P>
<P>
   The Aero 2100 uses the Windows CE operating system, which uses a
stripped-down version of the Windows 95/98 desktop.
</P>
<P>
   The Aero also has an interesting active-matrix color screen,
which sets it apart from most other Windows CE color handhelds,
which use less-clear passive-matrix displays. The screen is
viewable even outside.
</P>
<P>
   The Aero 2100 is a bulky thing, certainly larger than the Palm V
and even bigger than the older Palm III design. It felt comfortable
in my hand, which is relatively large, but probably would feel
oversized in smaller paws.
</P>
<P>
   Taking its size into account, the Aero's designers have added a
rocker switch on its side that lets you scroll through lists by
moving it up or down. This makes it easy to get through data using
just one hand, such as when you're talking on the phone.
</P>
<P>
   There are several models, with either 8 or 16 MB of memory, and
it can hold up to 24 MB.
</P>
<P>
   It also has many more bells and whistles than the Palm line _
and you can take that literally. It comes with a built-in voice
recorder for making quick audio notes, and can work with audio
files downloaded from the Audible.com Web site at www.audible.com.
</P>
<P>
   The color, audio and other nifty features account for the
weight. And they also extract a price in battery life.
</P>
<P>
   While the Palm V can last for more than a week on a charge, the
Aero will give you about 10 hours of service.
</P>
<P>
   Send e-mail to dwight.silverman- &QL; 
(a)chron.com, or call 713-220-2000, access code 1001.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
