<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-HELPLINE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROGRAMS PROVIDE LOTS OF OPTIONS TO CREATE YOUR OWN SCREEN SAVERS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN  
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I would like to know how to create screen savers that change
as the day goes on _ maybe at regular intervals. I am a teacher and
thought the kids would think it was cool if their pictures came up
as screen savers. I have multiple students using the same computer
throughout the day.
</P>
<P>
   A. There are quite a few shareware programs that will let you do
this, and you can find many of them at the Winfiles.com site. Look
at this specific page: www.winfiles.com/apps/98/savers-tools.html.
</P>
<P>
   Another option is a slick little commercial program called
Create Screen Savers Quick &AMP; Easy, from Individual Software. This
$20 program lets you create slide-show style screen savers with
some interesting effects. Just drag and drop the images you want
into place, tell the program how you want them to be displayed and
presto! It generates a Windows .SCR screen-saver file. And, it
works on Windows 3.1 systems, as well as Windows 95/98.
</P>
<P>
   Q. I'm having a very strange problem with the fonts in some of
my programs. Some of the words in various windows are overlapping
each other, they've been put down on top of the other words. In
America Online, I can only see the first few sentences in
paragraphs on some of its opening screens. Some of the title bars
on top of the windows have strange characters where letters should
be. I've fiddled with settings until I'm blue in the face. What's
wrong?
</P>
<P>
   A. Windows 95/98 likes to fool you into thinking you've got more
choices for system font sizes than you really do. When you take the
bait, problems such as this can occur.
</P>
<P>
   Chances are, you have decided to go with a custom font size for
your system fonts. These are the typefaces Windows uses for basic
text display, such as the names under icons or for the titles of
windows.
</P>
<P>
   However, despite your having the ability to change the font
sizes, doing so is not a good idea.
</P>
<P>
   To fix this, right-click on the Windows desktop, choose
Properties, then Settings. Click the Advanced tab. You'll see a
dialog box that includes an item called Font Sizes. I suspect it's
set at ``Other,'' which means you've got a custom font size.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is, some programs don't know what to do with a
custom font size. They want one of the two generic options _ Large
or Small. Change the setting to one of those, and your problem
should go away.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Right now I am using a Voodoo2 card (a Diamond Monster II)
for playing games. I've been reading about the Voodoo3 that's
coming out that is just one card _ you don't need an add-on. But I
also have been reading about new 3-D graphics chips from ATI
Technologies, Matrox and nVidia. Is it worth upgrading?
</P>
<P>
   A. The next few months are going to be a 3-D gamers' dream. Or,
if you're an indecisive 3-D gamer, it might be a nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   Next-generation 3-D cards are already starting to appear,
ranging from the 3dfx Voodoo3, to cards built around nVidia's
UltraTNT2 chips, to ATI's new line of Rage 128 cards, to Matrox's
G400, to S3's Savage 4 ... and on and on.
</P>
<P>
   All these cards are very fast, can utilize the slick graphics
available through either OpenGL or Microsoft's DirectX, and will be
reasonably priced, coming in well under $200.
</P>
<P>
   Each has its own benefits and shortcomings. For example, the
Voodoo3 is wickedly fast, but it can only display colors in 16 bits
in 3-D mode _ most of the other next-generation cards can use
32-bit color.
</P>
<P>
   Your best bet is to wait until the full crop is out, probably
around fall, and then start reading reviews and scanning Internet
discussion forums to see how things are shaking out. Personally, I
think you should pay particular attention to the Voodoo3 and the
nVidia cards _ early reports on both look very good.
</P>
<P>
   Got a question? Send e-mail to dwight.silverman(at)chron.com, or
call 713-220-2000 and enter access code 1001.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
