A1512 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BENEFITS-IMMIGRANTS-H     04-16 0800
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BENEFITS-IMMIGRANTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOVERNOR UNDER FIRE FOR SEEKING MIDDLE GROUND ON IMMIGRATION LAW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JULIE CHAO  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ California Gov. Gray Davis' decision to ask a
federal appeals court to mediate the legal battle over Proposition
187, the voter-approved initiative limiting benefits to illegal
immigrants, has met with skepticism from all sides, casting doubt
on whether a settlement can be reached.
</P>
<P>
   Neither opponents nor proponents of the measure saw any room for
compromise, while Hispanic and immigrant groups, who had pressed
Davis to let the issue die, expressed outrage at Thursday's
announcement.
</P>
<P>
   Although Davis opposes the initiative, approved by 59 percent of
voters in 1994 and strongly backed by then-Gov. Pete Wilson, he
said he had no authority to decide on its constitutionality nor
could he go against the will of voters.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the provisions of the disputed law, which include
denying education and health care to illegal immigrants and their
children, have been ruled unconstitutional by a federal judge.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, a Democrat, could have sought to appeal that decision or
drop the issue. Instead, he took the middle road.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's both the wormiest and the most brilliant thing he
could've done at the same time,'' said Gregory Rodriguez, research
scholar at Pepperdine Institute for Public Policy in Los Angeles
County.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realize it's really politically tricky for him. But there's
nothing that doesn't say a very popularly elected governor could
not persuade the California electorate of the wrongness of this
proposition.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis spokesman Michael Bustamante said going to the 9th Circuit
Court of Appeals' mediation panel was a way to build consensus and
avoid costly litigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The governor has always believed that reasonable people should
sit down at a table and find a way to resolve conflicts,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   However, the parties involved saw no possibility of finding any
middle ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't see where there's any area for compromise,'' said John
Findley, a lawyer for the Pacific Legal Foundation in Sacramento,
which is representing Proposition 187's sponsor. ``Either the
initiative is constitutional or it's not. It's an all-or-nothing
situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Saenz, regional counsel for the Mexican American Legal
Defense and Education Fund, the group leading the effort to strike
down the initiative, said he saw no reason to make any concessions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are negotiating from a complete position of strength,'' he
said. ``If we were to continue with this appeal, despite the
tremendous cost in time and money, we would prevail. I'm not
prepared to offer up anything at this point.''
</P>
<P>
   Saenz added that he would not negotiate with the Pacific Legal
Foundation since the 9th Circuit has ruled it has no legal standing
to intervene in the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to sit in any mediation with any party who is
not a part of the case,'' he said. ``If the governor wants to
consult with anybody, he's free to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Bustamante said participation from the Pacific Legal Foundation
was necessary to reach any settlement. He hoped it would take no
more than four months to complete negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Proposition 187 has become one of the most significant issues of
Davis' administration as he tries to balance the views of the
growing Hispanic electorate with those of the conservative
Democrats and independent voters who supported him.
</P>
<P>
   Anamaria Loya, executive director of La Raza Centro Legale, a
San Francisco public interest law firm, said, ``It's completely
backtracking and denigrates the values of a community to say that
we're willing to negotiate away their human rights. I think he's
going to hear from Latino voters in the next couple of weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor was she persuaded by Davis' desire to respect the will of
the voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``The law is immoral,'' she said. ``To me, it does not matter
that it's anyone's will. At some point, Jim Crow laws and slavery
were the will of the people.''
</P>
<P>
   Ted Wang of Chinese for Affirmative Action in San Francisco also
was disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was an opportunity for Governor Davis to show that he's
different from Pete Wilson,'' Wang said, referring to the
Republican governor who preceded Davis. Instead, ``he's just
exacerbating the racial tensions and some of the anti-immigrant
bashing that occurred under the Wilson administration.''
</P>
<P>
   But Clark Kelso, a professor at the University of Pacific's
McGeorge School of Law in Sacramento, said he saw some possibility
of a compromise since Proposition 187 has so many provisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's an all or nothing,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
