<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABORTION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE EXPANDS BUFFERS TO PROTECT ABORTION CLINICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LARA JAKES  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Days before one of the largest national
anti-abortion protests of the year, a federal judge ruled that the
buffer zones around reproductive services clinics in western New
York should be expanded, holding back demonstrators by up to 60
feet.
</P>
<P>
   A top national anti-abortion advocate said the ruling, a major
victory for groups that favor abortion rights, was a ``ludicrous,
Draconian decision'' and an assault on free speech.
</P>
<P>
   Preparing for the weeklong ``Operation Save America''
demonstration that begins Sunday in Buffalo and Rochester, Attorney
General Eliot Spitzer recently filed an injunction to expand the
15-foot no-protest zones around 13 area clinics. On Thursday, U.S.
District Court Judge Richard J. Arcara granted the request, which
requires federal marshals to be posted at clinics during protests
and allows for up to four escorts to help patients enter and exit
the facilities.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates of abortion rights ``have shown by a preponderance of
the evidence that they will suffer irreparable harm if injunctive
relief is not immediately granted,'' Arcara wrote in the 18-page
decision. ``Nothing in this order shall be construed to limit
defendants and those acting in concert with them from exercising
their legitimate rights under the First Amendment.''
</P>
<P>
   The court case stacked up Spitzer and five abortion-rights
groups against dozens of religious organizations and abortion
opponents. Protest organizers have said they expect 60,000 people
at the weeklong event, held six months after the fatal shooting of
abortion docto Barnett Slepian at his Buffalo-area home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our intention in seeking this action is to ensure that law and
order is maintained during the ... protests,'' Spitzer said
Thursday. ``We have been working with the law enforcement community
to enforce the law and ensure public safety.''
</P>
<P>
   But abortion opponents said the ruling violates their rights to
free speech by not allowing them to talk, or give information, to
clinic patients.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is blocking the access of women seeking reproductive health
information that might enable them to choose life,'' the Rev.
Philip L. ``Flip'' Benham said of Spitzer. Benham is the national
director of the Dallas-based Operation Rescue National, which is
organizing the New York demonstrations. ``The only ones who can
give information to women now are on the pro-abortion side. This is
a ludicrous, Draconian decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he would try to diffuse any violence growing out of the
demonstrations, Benham said: ``There's violence there every day _
they kill children.''
</P>
<P>
   Abortion-rights groups also are planning to attend the
demonstrations in order to lend support to clinics, their staff and
patients, said Kelli Conlin, executive director of the New York
chapter of the National Abortion Rights and Reproductive League.
She also called Thursday for the state's passage of a clinic-access
law, which would increase penalties against people who intimidate,
harass or hurt those seeking or administering reproductive
services.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George Pataki and the state Assembly support such
legislation, which needs Senate approval to become law.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
