<P>
   POWERPOINT-IDEAS (Undated) _ ``Good Morning. The title of
today's presentation is: `The Effect of Presentation Software on
Rhetorical Thinking,' or `Is Microsoft Powerpoint Taking Over Our
Minds?' I will begin by making a joke. Then I will take you through
each of my points in a linear fashion. Then I will sum up again at
the end. Unfortunately, due to the unique format of this particular
presentation, we will not be able to entertain questions.'' Many
people believe that the ubiquity of prepackaged computer software,
which helps users prepare such presentations, has not only taken
much of the life out of public speaking by homogenizing it at a low
level, but has led to a kind of ersatz thought that is devoid of
original ideas. By Laurence Zuckerman. (1800 words)
</P>
<P>
   LA-INTELLECTUALS (Los Angeles) _ Intellectual life in Los
Angeles may sound like an oxymoron. After all, the notion that Los
Angeles has no brain is about as old as the city itself. Yet with
the city's public and private universities, a slate of Nobel Prize
winners, some of the country's most creative artistic talent, a
reservoir of scientific expertise at the Jet Propulsion Laboratory
and the California Institute of Technology, these stereotypes were
always more alive in the imagination, particularly on the East
Coast, than in real life. Writers and scholars are now saying that
a new influx of institutions and art museums has helped make
intellectual life more vital than in any other period in this
city's history. By David Hay. (1400 words)
</P>
<P>
   CONNECT-MATRIX (Undated) _ The world of the film Matrix, the
hacker myth and its dreams of cyber utopia. By Edward Rothstein.
(1000 words)
</P>
