<HEADER>
A1578 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN18-CO     04-16 0572
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: Shine that laser target on
Milosevic's forehead
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   America has no quarrel with the Serb people, we're repeatedly
told during televised war briefings. It's their leader, Slobodan
Milosevic, whom NATO is punishing.
</P>
<P>
   The Serb people just happen to have the misfortune of being in
the place where we happen to be bombing.
</P>
<P>
   One day, it's an errant missile taking out a passenger train.
The next day, our planes mistakenly bomb a convoy of refugees.
</P>
<P>
   I'm at the point where I hate to open the newspaper or turn on
the TV news, for fear of learning the latest results from this
one-sided war we're waging.
</P>
<P>
   The idea seems that if we bring enough destruction to Serbia,
then Milosevic will have no choice but to capitulate, if for no
other reason than to save his own people.
</P>
<P>
   Not gonna happen.
</P>
<P>
   Slobodan Milosevic is a no-good, rotten Slobodan Milosevic. He's
a tinhorn Hitler, the poster boy of everything that is evil among
the struggle of the Balkan people.
</P>
<P>
   Hitler never gave in, and neither will Milosevic. Meanwhile, in
the process of destroying the Serbian army's capacity to make war,
we're also destroying the Serbian people's homes and places of
work, their transportation system and their industry, their very
way of life.
</P>
<P>
   Better we should kill Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Forget bombing their cities. Simply assassinate their leader.
</P>
<P>
   If that strikes you as immoral, take another look at the results
of some of our bomb strikes.
</P>
<P>
   The CIA has the ways and means of assassination. What they lack
is the directive.
</P>
<P>
   Time was when foreign killings were a matter of routine policy
as a part of our cloak-and-dagger capability.
</P>
<P>
   Heaven knows how they tried to take out Castro, even entering
into a hit contract with the Mafia to do the job. Neither their
gang nor ours, as it turned out, could shoot straight.
</P>
<P>
   There are those who believe the Kennedy assassination was in
retaliation for what we were trying to do in Cuba. Of course, there
are those, too, who speculate that JFK may have been killed by a
jealous husband.
</P>
<P>
   Reforms changed all that, following the expose' of CIA outrages,
Watergate and such. Congress made it a law: The CIA shall not
assassinate.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's time to change the law back.
</P>
<P>
   It would be better on everybody. One bad guy, one bullet. And
let that be a lesson to others, that we're making a list and
checking it twice.
</P>
<P>
   Belarus President Alexander Lukashenko, who visited Belgrade
this past week in support of Milosevic, comes to mind. He's the
last of the old Stalinists, a terrorist against his own people, an
enemy of human rights. The tyranny in Belarus is perhaps second
only to that of China, but, then, we do a lot of business with
China.
</P>
<P>
   What's the worst thing that could happen?
</P>
<P>
   Well, our enemies could respond in kind, targeting our own
president. That, of course, would be a terrible, terrible thing for
America.
</P>
<P>
   But it wouldn't be as terrible as having our cities bombed.
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas)
Daily News, is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. E-mail address is
jmurray(at)lcc.net; mailing address, P.O. Box 151108, Lufkin,
Texas, 75915.; web page,
http://www.geocities.com/SoHo/Bistro/7147.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
