<SLUG> BC-GO-GO-REVIVAL-$ADV18-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILLENNIUM A GO-GO: FRUGGING TO 2000 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By FRANK DeCARO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The latest Gap ads, which had their premieres during last
month's Academy Awards telecast, have taken something far out and
made it totally in. Hold on to your feather boas, pop culture is
going ``a go-go.'' Again.
</P>
<P>
   Gap, the ubiquitous San Francisco-based retailer, whose ``Khakis
Swing'' ad last year helped to make the 1940s dance revival cool,
has now unleashed 15 sexy dancers who do the frug, the pony and the
jerk in a '60s-inspired spot called ``Khaki a Go-Go.''
</P>
<P>
   Choreographed by Marguerite Derricks, who gave Mike Myers his
groovy moves in ``Austin Powers: International Man of Mystery,''
these 30 seconds of rotating wrists and whirling ponytails manage
to make even the most humdrum pair of Gap chinos seem somehow
``shagadelic,'' as Powers would say.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, MAC, the Canadian cosmetics company known as much for
employing offbeat spokesmodels like RuPaul and K.D. Lang as for its
durable lipstick, is celebrating the opening of each new MAC
counter this year with department store parties called MAC a Go-Go.
These main-floor shindigs come complete with dancing girls in
bubblegum-colored feather bikinis, and go-go boys in hot pink
pailletted square-cut trunks and Lycra crop-tops. Talk about a
hullabaloo!
</P>
<P>
   Wait, there's more. On Broadway, ``Fosse'' features muscled
dancers doing the ``Rich Man's Frug,'' a 1966 show-stopper from
``Sweet Charity.'' Their clenched fists and knocked knees make this
go-go-inspired number one of the legendary choreographer's most
exciting dances. Retro but modern, the routine inhales the smoke of
a vintage Tiparillo and exhales the haughtiness of high fashion at
the end of the century.
</P>
<P>
   At home, a fellow can now practice his cool jerk to a new
British CD compilation called ``Land of 1,000 Dances,'' which
repackages the ``Hippy Hippy Shake'' and ``Monkey Time'' for a new
generation. If not that, he can tune in to the USA Network's new
Saturday night variety series ``Happy Hour,'' where the Bombshells,
a dance troupe modeled after Dean Martin's Gold Diggers, make its
hosts, Dweezil and Ahmet Zappa, look that much hipper. And coming
soon to a multiplex near you is ``Austin Powers: The Spy Who
Shagged Me,'' a sequel teaming Myers' secret agent with Heather
Graham. If it's a hit _ and even a ``Phantom Menace'' is no reason
to believe this latest James Bond spoof won't be big, baby _
there's no telling how far this '60s fascination could go-go.
</P>
<P>
   But why go-go now? Rebecca Weill, a Gap spokeswoman, says they
came up with ``Khaki a Go-Go'' after a lot of research, listening
to music and poring over magazines and movies, to see what struck a
chord.
</P>
<P>
   ``The juxtaposition of old and new makes for a combination
that's very appealing to a lot of people,'' she said. These ads,
like the MAC promotion, offer more than cute dancers and fun music,
they mine a universal nostalgia that many young consumers feel.
</P>
<P>
   At a time when the Playboy mansion is once again the vortex of
Hollywood hip, it's only natural to revive the bunny esthetic. But
what seems odd is that such kooky-sexy playfulness resonates most
strongly among those who either don't remember the originals or
who, like me, were in the earliest years of primary school when the
``Laugh-In'' cocktail party was the place to be every Monday night.
A go-go revival fills a longing to have been a part of things back
then. Maybe we are all destined to like best the era into which
we're born.
</P>
<P>
   But it could be something else entirely. It may just be, as some
contend, that the '60s were simply the most interesting decade of
the 20th century. Period. Andy Warhol used to wonder if more things
happened in the '60s because people were on drugs, or if people
took drugs in the '60s just to keep up with all that was going on.
I don't know the answer to the Prince of Pop's conundrum, but I am
inclined to believe that the flavors and fads of that decade will
delight audiences well into the next millennium.
</P>
<P>
   Even after the '70s revival gives way to a neo-'80s renaissance,
and the '40s swing craze dies, the '60s will be an era that forever
draws us back.
</P>
<P>
   A decade in which desire for social change and hopes for the
future ran as high as micro-mini hemlines is always worth reviving.
At least that's the way it seems today, as we appropriate '60s
styles without any of the political or contextual baggage.
</P>
<P>
   Many of us remember the go-go boots more clearly than the Tet
offensive. In fact, designs of the '60s, from fashion to home
furnishings, are beginning to be considered American classics.
</P>
<P>
   One of the greatest disappointments today is that the world at
the dawn of the 21st century doesn't look '60s enough. It doesn't
look as fabulously futuristic as it did in ``Barbarella.'' As it
turns out, we won't all be wearing Rudi Gernreich in the year 2000;
we'll be wearing khakis. But at least we'll be doing the frug.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
