<P>
   &UR; BOSTON MARATHON (s) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MARA-OLDEST (Boston) -- As the oldest continuous race of its
kind in the world, the Boston Marathon has long been accustomed to
its unique identity. By Barbara Huebner. 1900 words.
</P>
<P>
   MARA-KENYANS (Boston) _ The Boston Marathon does business on a
first-name basis. Especially when it comes to Moses Tanui and his
cohorts from Kenya. By Shira Springer. 1025 words.
</P>
<P>
   MARA-WHEELCHAIR (Boston) -- Franz Nietlispach has won the Boston
men's wheelchair division for two years. The Swiss racer could very
well make it three straight. By Bob Monahan. 570 words.
</P>
<P>
   MARA-TIMES (Boston) -- These are the times that try men's and
women's soles. By Allen Lessels. 1040 words.
</P>
<P>
   MARA-COURSE (Boston) -- The Boston Marathon isn't special in the
eyes of THE USATF because it doesn't fall within the parameters of
record standards. By John Vallente. 720 words.
</P>
<P>
   MARA-MORSE (Boston) -- Few believe that without the steady hand
of director Guy Morse at the helm, Boston could have come through
the centennial so well. By Tony Chamberlain. 1320 words.
</P>
<P>
   MARA-SPONSORS (Boston) _ Businesses say they like to sponsor the
Boston Marathon because, for them, the race is like a big
commercial show-and-tell. By Gregg Krupa. 900 words. (s and f
coding)
</P>
