<SLUG> BC-BALKANS-GROUND-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATESIDE GIS SAY THEY'RE READY FOR THE REAL THING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNDA GOROV  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAWTON, Okla. _ They have played the war games, pretended they
were hunkered down in the darkness of Kosovo. They've fired
missiles at Serb soldiers, although both the missiles and the
soldiers were pretend, too.
</P>
<P>
   But when they joined the US Army straight out of high school
three years ago, the three young soldiers never expected this: real
war, real blood, and the real possibility that they would be
shipped overseas to fight for reasons they can't quite comprehend.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are trained to fight, but we're just kids,'' said Spec.
Miguel Angel Nieves, 22.
</P>
<P>
   Added his breakfast companion, Spec. Ronald Fayson, 23, ``I
wasn't thinking about war when I signed up. It was just something
to improve myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, they said they are ready and willing to do the job they
are paid $1,209 a month to do, even if that's too little money for
extras, even if their equally young wives are already afraid.
Mostly, they want to see the job done right, done fast, and they
say that means sending in ground troops made up of novice soldiers
such as themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Their unit at Fort Sill, located on the outskirts of this flat,
wind-swept city in southwestern Oklahoma, has been told to be
ready, although others are expected to go first. For now, though,
the military build-up in the Balkans has consisted only of Air
Force aircraft and personnel, including a recent deployment from
the base in nearby Altus.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a very articulate man,'' said Nieves, originally from
Panama and married five years now. ``But we either go over and kick
their (expletive) or we should stay the hell out. We go in, we go
in all the way, you see what I'm saying. You can't go in halfway.''
</P>
<P>
   None of the three, who met in Lawton 3 1/2 years ago after basic
training, is itching to go, although Spec. Philip Morgan said he
does feel the tug when he sees the destruction on TV. They see the
war in human terms, from the ethnic Albanian refugees streaming out
of Kosovo to the friends they hear are being sent over from the US
base in Germany. The politics _ who's killing who and why _ is
harder to grasp, especially in a city of 100,000 where
international news is scarce for those who can't afford the cable
TV bill.
</P>
<P>
   Nieves, the talker of the trio, walked the table through the
history of the conflict as he understands it. He knows it goes back
500 years. He knows the people in some Yugoslavian provinces abhor
the people in others. But what he knows best _ and what he fears
most _ is what he has heard is a system of Serbian underground
bunkers where entire armies can hide out. Serbia is well-bunkered,
but with little to do but wait, the mythology has grown among the
young men and women walking around Lawton in green Army fatigues.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter your opinion is how we look at it,'' said
Morgan, 21, and from California, ``You could totally disagree with
it, and nobody wants to kill anyone and definitely nobody wants to
be killed, but if you're told to go, you go. You do your job.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Nieves, whose father served in Vietnam, ``We still believe
in our country and freedom for all. . .What my wife thinks, though,
is that it's not our business, it's not our problem. We're giving
up American lives and the European community doesn't give a damn
when it's in their own backyard. At least that's the way she sees
it.''
</P>
<P>
   And from Fayson, whose family is in Florida, ``It's always
America. NATO. We need your help.''
</P>
<P>
   If the friends are sent to Kosovo from Fort Sill, where about
20,000 soldiers are stationed, each will have a job distinct from
the others. Fort Sill is the field artillery center, and Morgan
works with the multi-launch rocket system, or MLRS, that the base
is know for worldwide. Fayson, a personnel clerk, expects to work
the radios. Nieves is a chaplain's assistant, and his primary job
would be to guard the chaplain, forbidden under the Geneva
Convention from carrying a weapon himself for protection.
</P>
<P>
   ``My job would be to improve morale, however you do that in a
war,'' Nieves said. ``I'd be there to comfort the dead and the
dying. But my main job would be to be the chaplain's bullet-proof
vest.''
</P>
<P>
   Just then, an elderly woman stopped by the table, laden with
eggs and pancakes, sausage and grits, to wish ``our boys'' well.
They listened politely, nodding throughout, as she blasted
President Clinton, blasted Congress, for putting a single US
soldier in harm's way.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Clinton or Congress had to go, if the jokers who declare
war have to go, we'd never have one, I tell you,'' she said,
declining to introduce herself by name after mentioning that her
husband served in both World War II and Korea. ``They're just
leading our boys to the slaughter. We've got a bunch of jokers who
never served and don't know nothing about running a war.''
</P>
<P>
   At another table at the International House of Pancakes, packed
with soldiers allowed to leave their stations after the wind
knocked out some power lines, three artillery officers were more
stoic about the situation. Older, in the Army longer, and able to
explain Balkan politics with ease, they said they don't bother to
worry about what they can't control. None has heard a frightened
word from a solder under his command either.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just go in every day and don't think about it,'' said one,
a captain from New Jersey who declined to be identified by name
without official Army clearance. ``It's not our place to say one
way or the other whether it's the right thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Added another captain, ``What I'm thinking about is an
omelette.''
</P>
<P>
   The younger soldiers say they are trying to turn their thoughts
to other things, too. They try to keep their wives from worrying,
since, as Morgan put it, ``mine would be upset if she knew I was
probably going to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the decision to send in ground troops is some time off,
if it comes at all _ leaving Nieves, Morgan and Fayson with a sense
of ambivalence that they know would evaporate the minute they
landed in a land that continues to confuse them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been setting up real-world scenarios so we'll know what
we're in for, mapping it out, like we're in Kosovo,'' Morgan said.
</P>
<P>
   Added Fayson, ``We've dug fighting positions, done gas attacks,
all of it. But it definitely can't compare with the real thing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
