</P>
<P>
   States News Service
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON WATCH VOTE CHART Questions regarding this
transmission should be directed to 202-628-3100, ext. 224.
WASHINGTON, April 16 -- The following chart shows how senators and
representatives voted on key bills and amendments within the last
week. A ``Y'' means the member voted for the measure; an ``N''
means the member voted against the measure; a ``?'' means the
member did not vote; and a ``P'' means the member voted
``present.''
</P>
<P>
   SENATE VOTES:
</P>
<P>
   1) BILL NUMBER: SEN BUD
</P>
<P>
   The Senate on Thursday approved, 54 to 44, the final version of
the $1.7 trillion budget for fiscal year 2000. The package, a
compromise between previously passed House and Senate bills, lays
out a blueprint for cutting taxes over the next ten years, uses the
projected Social Security surplus to either pay down the national
debt or reform Social Security and Medicare and increases spending
for defense and education. Supporters said the tremendous
non-Social Security budget surplus should be returned to the
taxpayers through the tax cuts rather than used for new social
programs, as proposed by President Clinton. Opponents said the
budget does not do enough to save Social Security and Medicare and
that there should be more spending on social programs instead of
tax cuts. A ``yes'' vote favors the bill.
</P>
<P>
   VOTE : 1
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
<P>
   SANTORUM (R-PA) Y
</P>
<P>
   SPECTER (R-PA) Y
</P>
<P>
   HOUSE VOTES:
</P>
<P>
   1) BILL NUMBER: HOUSE BUD
</P>
<P>
   The House on Wednesday approved, 220 to 208, the final version
of the $1.7 trillion budget for fiscal year 2000. The package, a
compromise between previously passed House and Senate bills, lays
out a blueprint for cutting taxes over the next ten years, uses the
projected Social Security surplus to either pay down the national
debt or reform Social Security and Medicare and increases spending
for defense and education. Supporters said the tremendous
non-Social Security budget surplus should be returned to the
taxpayers through the tax cuts rather than be used for new social
programs, as proposed by President Clinton. Opponents said the
budget does not do enough to save Social Security and Medicare and
that there should be more spending on social programs instead of
tax cuts. A ``yes'' vote favors the bill.
</P>
<P>
   2) BILL NUMBER: CENSUS
</P>
<P>
   The House on Wednesday approved, 223-206, the Local Census
Quality Control Act, which would allow cities and towns to
challenge Census Bureau data and demand a recount of contested
areas before the final numbers are released. Supporters said the
plan would provide a more accurate population count. Opponents said
the Census Bureau lacks the resources to investigate what may be
tens of thousands of likely challenges by local governments. A
``yes'' vote favors the bill.
</P>
<P>
   VOTE : 1 2
</P>
