<HEADER>
A1601 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEXICO-TRAFFICKER-$AD     04-16 1602
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-TRAFFICKER-$ADV18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EX-TEXAS COP-TURNED-MEXICAN DRUG TRAFFICKER COULD REVEAL
CORRUPTION SECRETS
 &HT;    With Photo of Salinas.
 &HT;    For Use Sat., April 17 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By SUSAN FERRISS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   REYNOSA, Mexico _ It is, by now, a familiar tale in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   A small-town boy becomes police officer and quickly succumbs to
the temptations of lucrative drug trafficking.
</P>
<P>
   The difference this time is the former cop is an American
citizen named Gilbert Salinas, a Donna, Texas native who is wanted
in Houston and Atlanta, and is in jail in Mexico on charges of
smuggling tons of Colombian cocaine into the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican authorities say Salinas, 41, is a ``key member'' of the
Juarez-Cancun drug cartel, a criminal ring that has relied on
extensive support from Mexican police -- and the former governor of
Quintana Roo state -- to smuggle cocaine from Mexico into the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Justice Department has requested Salinas' extradition
to face marijuana-trafficking charges.
</P>
<P>
   Sources say Salinas is a very valuable catch because he could
reveal explosive secrets detailing how corrupt law-enforcement
officials on both sides of the border are helping smuggle cocaine
up the Gulf Coast, through U.S. checkpoints along the Rio Grande.
</P>
<P>
   Salinas is said to be the architect of the cartel's Gulf
smuggling routes into the United States, which were based on trails
he blazed as a marijuana smuggler in his native Rio Grande Valley.
Under his guidance, cocaine was allegedly delivered to this Mexican
border city and shipped across the Rio Grande to McAllen, Texas,
before being moved to Chicago, New York, Los Angeles and other
cities.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a very significant dope trafficker,'' said one U.S.
official, who spoke on condition of anonymity. ``He'd be like the
vice president for transportation, if you wanted to structure it
out like a business.''
</P>
<P>
   Salinas is also believed to be a critical witness who has
already named high-ranking officials under investigation for
trafficking, including the former governor of Quintana Roo, Mexican
highway police and judicial police.
</P>
<P>
   Because of his knowledge, Salinas is ``in a very precarious
position,'' the U.S. official said. ``The Colombians will do
anything possible to get him out (of jail). And when they find out
they can't they'll do anything they can to kill him.''
</P>
<P>
   Other than to confirm Salinas' role in the cartel, spokesmen
from the Mexican Attorney General's office declined to discuss
Salinas, who some Mexican newspaper accounts claim is a protected
witness in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   John Trevino, a U.S. Drug Enforcement Administration agent in
Texas, said, ``I guess he's Mr. Big now.''
</P>
<P>
   Salinas' brief career as a South Texas police officer ended when
he was arrested in 1982 at a U.S. Border Patrol checkpoint with a
load of marijuana. He was convicted, did some time in jail and was
convicted again in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, while out of jail on bond, he disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1980s, Trevino said, Salinas was moving thousands of
pounds of pot from Mexico into the United States.
</P>
<P>
   He was indicted in Atlanta in 1990 for conspiracy to traffic
marijuana and in 1993 in Houston on continuing criminal enterprise
charges, which can carry a life sentence without parole.
</P>
<P>
   Trevino said authorities in McAllen would also like to question
Salinas about the unsolved 1996 killing of a doctor in that city.
</P>
<P>
   On March 11 of this year, the Mexican Embassy in Washington
issued a statement that Salinas would have to be tried in Mexico
before authorities could hand him over to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   While underground for almost a decade, Salinas used various
aliases, including Gilberto Garza Garcia, Gilberto Salinas Doria
and the nickname, ``El Guero Gil,'' or ``White Gil.''
</P>
<P>
   Salinas was arrested in October 1998 by Mexican authorities, who
believed he was Mexican-born Gilberto Garza Garcia.
</P>
<P>
   He was taken soon after his arrest to the resort city of Cancun
as part of an probe into the Juarez-Cancun cartel. United States
sources believe he escaped shortly afterward because he paid a
large bribe.
</P>
<P>
   The trafficker was recaptured after he was found in a luxury
resort on a Venezuelan island in January and deported to Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   He was identified as Salinas in February, only after the FBI and
other U.S. law enforcement officers matched his picture and
fingerprints with records at the Donna and Weslaco police
departments in South Texas, where Salinas worked in the early
1980s.
</P>
<P>
   According to three Mexican newspapers, Salinas described some of
the cartel's inner-workings to Mexican authorities in an affidavit
taken Oct. 8, 1998, after his first arrest.
</P>
<P>
   The affidavit was leaked to El Manana newspaper in Reynosa, and
Mexico City's La Jornada and El Universal newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   In his statement, Salinas is said to have described how the
Juarez-Cancun cartel paid off certain Mexican highway police to
protect cocaine shipments being trucked through Veracruz, Tampico
and Tamaulipas states along the Gulf.
</P>
<P>
   He said a highway police commander in Reynosa was paid $50,000
per shipment.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's nothing. (The commander) must have been down at the
bottom of the food chain,'' said a U.S. official, who confirmed
suspicions in press reports here that Mexico's federal highway
police are under investigation for protecting drug deliveries.
</P>
<P>
   It was in that October affidavit that Salinas is said to have
also implicated the former governor of Quintana Roo state, Mario
Villanueva, along with a former judicial police commander.
</P>
<P>
   In March, just as a Mexican Attorney General's investigation
into Villanueva was heating up, the governor disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   Villanueva became a fugitive on April 5, when the attorney
general issued a warrant for his arrest in connection with the
Juarez-Cancun cartel.
</P>
<P>
   The cartel, originally based in Ciudad Juarez, had moved much of
its operation to Cancun during Villanueva's term as governor,
according to Mexican authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Salinas is also said to have sketched out the cartel's shipping
methods in his October statement. Some of these methods have been
confirmed by Mexican law enforcement authorities.
</P>
<P>
   The trafficker said boats drop cocaine along the Belize coast,
which borders Quintana Roo. Once in Veracruz state, the drugs are
shipped through the Gulf Coast states in trucks fitted with tubes
to haul liquids.
</P>
<P>
   In Reynosa, Salinas said, cocaine is put in 30-pound sacks and
loaded onto trucks. He implicated an unnamed McAllen transportation
company and alleged that U.S. law enforcement agents have also
helped smuggle the drugs over the border.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, complicity in drug smuggling among U.S.
law-enforcement agents is in the spotlight right now.
</P>
<P>
   On March 30, the General Accounting Office released a report
detailing corruption among U.S. Immigration and Naturalization
Service (INS) and U.S. Customs Service agents stationed along the
border, from the Rio Grande Valley to San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   Between 1992 and 1997, 28 employees were convicted for helping
traffickers, who often relied on bribes and longtime friendships
with U.S. agents.
</P>
<P>
   Two immigration inspectors based in Hidalgo, a port of entry
adjacent to McAllen, were convicted of allowing marijuana and
cocaine shipments over the bridge into the Rio Grande Valley.
</P>
<P>
   An INS employee in Los Fresnos, also in the Rio Grande Valley,
conspired with two colleagues and a former colleague to transport
drug shipments past Border Patrol checkpoints in official INS
vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Another INS employee who was helping move drug shipments from
the Rio Grande Valley to Chicago recruited a longtime friend and
Border Patrol agent to wave shipments through a Falfurrias, Texas,
checkpoint.
</P>
<P>
   In Donna, Salinas' home town, five former law enforcement
officers, including two former police chiefs, were arrested in 1997
for taking bribes to allow marijuana shipments to be driven through
town.
</P>
<P>
   Donna, a mostly Mexican-American community of 13,000, is about
nine miles from the Mexican border and 12 miles east of McAllen.
</P>
<P>
   Much of Salinas' family still lives in Donna, Texas, where the
story of how he evolved from cop to trafficker -- and now potential
star witness -- has piqued the interest of people who remember him
as an ordinary kid.
</P>
<P>
   Salinas joined the Donna police force in 1979. He was hired as a
patrolman in Weslaco, an adjacent town of about 40,000 in May 1980.
</P>
<P>
   He was fired from the Weslaco job after an internal
investigation led to his arrest for trafficking marijuana, said
police spokesman David Molina.
</P>
<P>
   ``He comes from a decent family,'' said childhood friend Alfonso
Avila, a lieutenant in the Donna Police Force. ``I guess the
temptation was too much.''
</P>
<P>
   Avila said Salinas' father, a house mover, was strict and
well-known in town for his involvement in local politics.
</P>
<P>
   A member of Salinas' family is a distinguished military man and
Donna residents named a school after him.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a saying in Spanish, 'A family is like a hand. All the
fingers are different,''' Avila said.
</P>
<P>
   Some in Donna say the accused trafficker lived in Reynosa while
he was a fugitive, and that he slipped back into Donna dressed as a
woman.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Gilbert was here he wasn't all that important,'' said Joe
Perez, a Donna barber who was listening to Mexican ballads, or
corridos, while he trimmed customers' hair.
</P>
<P>
   ``They haven't written a corrido for him yet,'' Perez said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
