<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   RESERVE-UNITS (Washington) _ The 30,000 or more military reserve
units that the Pentagon is expected call up for duty in the Kosovo
crisis are likely to be drawn mainly from the Air National Guard's
aerial refueling personnel at 17 bases across the country. We list
where those facilities are. By ERIC ROSENBERG.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-POLLUTION (Houston) _ Alcoa's Rockdale plant, one of the
state's biggest industrial polluters, has said it will apply for a
voluntary reduction permit once lawmakers implement voluntary
emission reductions by industries grandfathered under tighter
pollution laws. The company has said the coal-fired aluminum
production plant might have to close if it is compelled to get a
mandatory permit with emission-reduction requirements. By BILL
DAWSON.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-VOLUNTEER (Alvin, Texas) _ Glenna Winn, 83, is the
volunteer of the year in Texas. By STEVE OLAFSON.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BKN-ROCKETS (Houston) _ The Houston Rockets discuss their
playoff viability in the wake of Thursday's win over Portland. By
JONATHAN FEIGEN.
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-COSTS (Washington) _ The costs of waging war, even an
undeclared one, are high. The United States has already spent
nearly $1 billion to end ethnic violence in Yugoslavia, and the
cost is rising by nearly $40 million a day, says an independent
accounting group. President Clinton has asked Congress to
appropriate an additional $3.5 billion for the effort, and the
Pentagon won't say if that's all. The daily expenses would grow
geometrically in a ground war. By STEVE LASH.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   ALBANIA-REFUGEES (Tirana, Albania) _ We take a look at the
impact of the refugee crisis on the poor country of Albania, where
many people have taken refugees into their homes. By DUDLEY
ALTHAUS.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   OCTUPLETS (Houston) _ The pink and blue balloons and streamers
in the yard announce something special inside the southwest Houston
home. But it's the city garbage can parked next to the curb that
tells the real tale. The container is bulging with empty infant
formula bottles, household trash and diapers. The story of the
world's first surviving set of octuplets is about multiples _ 60
diapers a day, 40 feedings taking a total of 14 hours. By LEIGH
HOPPER.
</P>
<P>
   DRAGGING-DEATH (Cooper, Texas) _ Russell Brewer never was the
pride of Delta County. He was a high school dropout, a layabout and
an inept burglar who targeted the homes of his own relatives. Many
considered Brewer the bad seed of a good, hard-working Christian
family. But last summer's accusation that Brewer had joined ex-cons
William King and Shawn Berry in dragging a black man to his death
startled most in this tiny farm town. By ALLEN TURNER.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   THOMPSON-COLUMN (Washington) _ When the bombing ends and peace
is restored, Kosovo will need a Marshall Plan like the one that
rebuilt Western Europe after World War II. A look at how that plan
came about 52 years ago. By ROBERT E. THOMPSON. (Filed Wednesday.)
</P>
