<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-16 16:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1625 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SLUG-2NDTAKE-NYT &LR;      04-16 1148
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SLUG-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: looking sexy.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The display of glamour and sex appeal seems for some artists to
be an exuberant expression of hard-won gains by earlier feminist
artists. For years, women, with few exceptions, tended to posture
like Jackson Pollock in gritty jeans, paint-smeared T-shirt and
cigarette dangling from their lips.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the beginning, it was so hard for young women,'' said Paula
Cooper, who opened her first gallery, on Prince Street, in 1968.
``All the guys were the serious artists. To be taken seriously,
women had to be grungy. They couldn't be gorgeous, glamorous and
feminine. There was no room for anything other than the macho
ideal. Now, women have been accepted. Some of the strongest artists
of the '80s and '90s have been women, so they're freer to do what
they please.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the Romantic period, the male artist perpetuated the myth
of the grubby creative genius, so preoccupied with the lofty ideals
of his art that he was unaware of the holes in his shoes. Yes,
there were exceptions like Barnett Newman, impeccably dressed in a
suit and gold watch chain, or Andy Warhol, in his platinum wig.
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't until the '80s, when the art market exploded and
artists' wallets began to fatten, that male artists seriously began
to abandon the boho ideal. Jean-Michel Basquiat had a soft spot for
Armani suits. Julian Schnabel developed the habit of painting and
partying in silk pajamas. David Salle, who may be the snappiest
dresser of them all, has been known to wear Richard James suits
tailored on Savile Row with a Gilligan's Island fishing hat and
J.P. Tod's loafers.
</P>
<P>
   While the myth of the tortured genius still shadows these men _
at times they have been criticized for placing style over substance
_ they have had it easy compared to female artists with designer
inclinations. To be taken seriously, women had to appear as if they
did not care about their looks, and they also had to play down
their femininity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before, as a woman photographer, if you took pictures of a
nude woman, it was looked down upon,'' said Ms. Feinstein, the
sculptor who wore the see-through skirt for her Yale interview. She
said the efforts of earlier feminist artists freed her generation
to make what she calls ``girlie art.''
</P>
<P>
   ``All of these '70s feminist artists had to break through this
territory in a violent way,'' she said. ``Now we can make stuff
about femininity and fashion.'' Ms. Feinstein, whose work is on
view at White Columns, constructs hokey-looking stage sets in candy
colors that recall Disney heroines _ Cinderella, Snow White,
Sleeping Beauty. In her personal style she is equally kittenish,
given to frilly frocks and a long, Rapunzel fall of blond hair. Her
seeming nonchalance about the reactions to her vixenish pose _ and
the nonchalance of others like her _ disturbs some members of the
art world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Money and fashion have entered the picture,'' said Robert
Rosenblum, a professor of fine arts at New York University who has
written about contemporary art since the 1950s. ``The financial
success of modern art can be read in terms of the way artists are
dressing. Now young artists have to dress right if they want to be
successful. They all look hip and expensive in their studios for
publicity photos. If they don't look rich, people aren't going to
pay a lot of money for their work.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It sort of irritates me that these women are promoted just
because they look like fashion models,'' he said. ``Often, the p.r.
has to do with photographs of them and not their work. Women
artists used to have to look anguished, bohemian. The last thing
they looked like was Vogue models.''
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, the current trend traces to Cindy Sherman, 45,
best known for her photographic self-portraits in which she
parodies Hollywood's bimbos and vixens. Ms. Sherman was one of the
first to take for her subject matter pop culture's images of
glamour, and many of today's fashion-mad artists look up to her.
From the moment she walked into ``Another Girl, Another Planet,''
she was a center of attention. But she is disturbed by the trend
among young women, who, she contends, are exploiting their sex
appeal without questioning feminine stereotypes.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's something uninformed about it that is creepy and scary
to me,'' she said. ``Young women who haven't learned they can have
intellectual power know they can open their shirt and attract 20
guys. It's enormous power. If I had a lithe young body, I would
dress like that. But I think you can play into the game and twist
it to educate the guy, who will see the real whore on the street.''
</P>
<P>
   The love affair between the worlds of art and fashion has been
consummated over the last several years. ``In the mid-'90s, artists
began working directly with the subject of high fashion,'' said
Bankowsky of Artforum. ``We all suddenly knew the names of the
supermodels; fashion became part of public consciousness because of
TV. Previously, it had been a rarefied world.''
</P>
<P>
   He cited Sylvie Fleury, who has created installations out of
Chanel shopping bags, designer shoe boxes and the glossy covers of
fashion magazines.
</P>
<P>
   And Janine Antoni has made paintings by batting her mascara-ed
eyelashes against paper and by dipping her long hair in dye and
sweeping it across the floor.
</P>
<P>
   Jessica Craig-Martin, 35, may be the symbolic love child of the
union of art and fashion. As a paparazzo, she chronicles celebrity
fetes, gallery openings and film festivals. Her pictures frequently
appear in Vogue. But right now, at the Maureen Paley Gallery in
London, Ms. Craig-Martin is exhibiting work meant to reveal a
darker side of the glittery world she circulates in.
</P>
<P>
   Focusing on the details of clothing or body language at a party,
frequently cropping out the faces of her subjects, Ms. Craig-Martin
aims to capture the pathos of trying to fit into glitzy company.
``One is never so naked as when dressed for a party,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   As for herself, Ms. Craig-Martin says her Prada and Gucci
uniforms are a ``means of subterfuge,'' allowing her to pass for a
party guest and to cross the velvet ropes, gliding by the waiting
horde of jostling paparazzi.
</P>
<P>
   Being celebrity-gorgeous may be the new condition for survival,
or rather success, of the art world's fittest. But the trend
carries many risks. Not every creative person is born with the
genes of a fashion model, or a shopaholic.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is what the art world expects of a woman artist,'' lamented
Ana Kustera, whose gallery is on Wooster Street. ``It doesn't hurt
to be attractive, and the work should not be politically motivated;
it should be influenced by the fashion world, it doesn't offend,
and it should represent the perfected image of what beautiful is. I
want women artists to be taken more seriously, but if they make
more serious work, it will be overlooked.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
