 SEXING UP THE ART WORLD  (For release Sun., April 18) 
Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By ELIZABETH HAYT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It was an early spring night. The air was chilly and
damp, but in the art gallery on 57th Street the scene was so steamy
all coats had been shed. Amid the crowd of 500 who flocked to the
opening of ``Another Girl, Another Planet,'' an exhibition of
photographs by and about young women, the dozen artists in the show
were as easy to spot as fireflies at dusk.
</P>
<P>
   Like young starlets at a trendy Hollywood boite, the artists
displayed the casually glamorous style of women who are used to
being in the limelight, even though none are marquee names in the
art world. With their tousled hair, bare legs, colorful stilettos,
sexy leather pants, Tracy Feith slip dresses and beaded vintage
handbags, they looked as if they had stepped out of the fashion
pages.
</P>
<P>
   Some of them had. For the past two months, Vogue has featured
artists-about-town in ``Talking Fashion,'' its photo feature about
high-fashion trends _ long the exclusive terrain of celebrities and
socialites. ``These artists have great style,'' said Alexandra
Kotur, a senior editor for special projects. ``They look as great
as actresses at a premiere.''
</P>
<P>
   James Reginato, the features director of W magazine, who
attended the opening, which was at Lawrence Rubin-Greenberg Van
Doren Fine Art, said: ``I definitely see women artists cropping up
on our pages more. Everybody looks like they're in a Prada or
Helmut Lang ad these days. It's OK to be glamorous. Suffering for
your art is passe.''
</P>
<P>
   A wave of young artists, it appears, would rather be seen in
nail polish than with paint beneath their nails, not to mention
spattered on their jeans. For some it is a declaration of power and
self-confidence. For others, exuding glamour or sexuality is an
extension of the themes in their work, the '90s being in a decade
when many artists have made images of high fashion their point of
departure.
</P>
<P>
   Today, women who might once have felt obliged to masquerade as
scruffy, macho types in order to be taken seriously in an art world
dominated by men, now flaunt the feminine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Serious women artists are presenting themselves as
conventionally fashionable in a way that they wouldn't have in the
past,'' said Jack Bankowsky, the editor of Artforum magazine.
``Women have begun to have parity in society and now feel
comfortable playing with the codes and conventions of fashion,
whereas previously enlightened women wouldn't want to buy into the
sexist biases that come along with fashion.''
</P>
<P>
   The trend is not merely about a generation of artists that has
found its way to Barneys. The development says much about the
self-image of artists in society, about the appeal of postfeminism
to a younger generation, and about the role of money in an art
market that, after a long dry spell, has heated up in Dow-fueled
Manhattan. And dressing like a seductress or fashion model arouses
plenty of controversy in the high-minded art world where it is
often assumed that there must be more to images than meets the eye.
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, when Rachel Feinstein, a sculptor who is now
27, went to Yale for a graduate school interview, she wore leg
warmers with garters and a see-through plastic miniskirt, which
revealed lacy underwear. She was surprised when the head of the
sculpture department, a conceptual artist, was offended. ``He
attacked me verbally,'' Ms. Feinstein said. ``He accused me of
being a third-wave feminist. He said I was a woman who forces her
sexuality on men. He thought I was doing this for theoretical
reasons, that I was trying to affront him with my girlhood. He
tried to get me to defend myself. Needless to say, I didn't go to
Yale.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Feinstein insists she intended no statement, political,
feminist or otherwise, by her outfit. And many other artists of a
similar mind-set defend their right not to be judged by traditional
notions of female artists.
</P>
<P>
   Cecily Brown, 29, a painter who wears makeup when she works and
has her hair blown straight at a SoHo salon before going out at
night, said: ``It's important not to feel bullied into dressing
down. It's the Madonna school of feminism. My generation was born
feminists. We don't have to keep proving it. I couldn't care less
if it seems shallow to care about my appearance. My work is taken
seriously regardless of how I look.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Brown's paintings _ vibrant Expressionist images of male and
female figures depicted in orgiastic abandon _ have been snapped up
by the blue-chip Gagosian Gallery, which is planning a show at the
end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Tracey Emin, 36, whose best-known work is a tent inscribed with
the names of all the people she has slept with, extends the
provocative themes of her art to her wardrobe. ``When I go out, I
show an amazing amount of cleavage because I've got really nice
breasts, and it makes me feel glamorous,'' Ms. Emin said. A
resident of London, she will have a show at the Lehmann Maupin
Gallery in New York next month.
</P>
<P>
   The other day, as she worked in her studio on a tapestry
emblazoned with the words ``Psycho Slut,'' she was dressed in a
low-cut lingerie top beneath an open red cardigan.``If I was in
denial about my sexuality, I'd be in denial about aspects of my
work, which deals with personal revelations,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Preening in daring decolletage, Ms. Emin may be one of the more
uninhibited of today's young artists. But others are also creating
sexually provocative, or insistently feminine, work that they say
reflects their personalities.
</P>
<P>
   Jenny Gage, 30, a former assistant to an editor at Vogue, wore
an Ann Demeulemeester skirt with Gucci bag to the opening of
``Another Girl,'' where her photographs are on view. In her work,
she depicts the stereotypical popular girl in high school _
beautiful, mysterious, full of potential, slightly dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   Katy Grannan, 29, another artist in the show, pays young women
$50 to pose any way they like. The majority chose a state of
undress, which Ms. Grannan attributes to a confidence in their
sexuality, rather than any misguided sense of exhibitionism. ``Like
strippers, they're making money and know what they're doing,'' she
said. ``Women today are much smarter. We get pleasure from looking
sexy.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
