<HEADLINE>
THIN IN A DEN OF FAT 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., April 18) 
(jt) 
 By AMANDA HESSER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``I feel testosterone surging through my veins,''
said Susan Sistrom, a doll-size woman engulfed in a swelling pool
of portly men at Sparks Steak House in midtown on Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like the Yankees are going to show up,'' said Patricia
Marx, also a pretty, tiny person.
</P>
<P>
   The two were waiting to be seated with six other small women at
this temple of beef _ where both portions and patrons tend to be
oversize _ for, of all things, a ``skinny dinner.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Sistrom and Ms. Marx, writers for The New Yorker (Ms.
Sistrom under the name Susan Orlean), conduct ``skinny'' meals with
groups of weight-savvy wits who gorge on bons mots, not bonbons, to
siphon their secrets for staying thin. A series of ``skinny
lunches'' are the basis of their new book, ``The Skinny'' (Dell,
$9.95), a guide to help women stay thin whatever their genetic
makeup.
</P>
<P>
   After 200 pages, their astonishing conclusion: eat less. Even if
that means Diet Cokes and cigarettes for the first 10 hours of the
day.
</P>
<P>
   At the table, the thunder of boisterous men and knives scraping
against plates was tuned out. Girl talk was tuned in. ``I'm
starving, may I be so bold to say?'' said Sara Nelson, an editor at
Self. As she nibbled on a roll, her face pinkened with pleasure.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Marx and Ms. Sistrom baited their guests with topics of
obsessiveness, from the merits of predawn workouts to food
poisoning: good or bad? No weight issue was ignored.
</P>
<P>
   They discussed pregnancy. ``You want to wear a sign that says,
`Pregnant, not fat,''' Ms. Nelson said.
</P>
<P>
   And how Frenchwomen stay thin. ``Cigarettes, small portions and
a lot of sex,'' Ms. Sistrom said. Ms. Marx added, ``Instead of
eating, they're putting expensive skin products on.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the unsavory subject of sticking your finger down your
throat. ``Since when did that become diagnosed as illness?'' asked
Cynthia Kling, a contributing editor at Harper's Bazaar, who had
oatmeal for breakfast and a sinus pill for lunch. ``We worship
you,'' Ms. Marx said.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, the women, in a room renowned for its salty
sirloins, had to order dinner. Ms. Sistrom asked for broiled shrimp
and lobster without the butter sauce. ``I can do it for you, but no
taste,'' the waiter said. They compromised on a dab of butter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Juice is stupid,'' said Irene Sax, a restaurant reviewer for
The Daily News. To which Ms. Kling added, ``You know, fat people
drink juice.''
</P>
<P>
   After a round of dry salads and asparagus, the main courses
arrived. Atop the white tablecloths and white plates was a lot of
white and green food: Chilean sea bass, trout and broccoli. Ms.
Sistrom eyed the steamed broccoli and spinach before Wendy
Sarasohn, a realty executive. ``I didn't know it was a la carte,''
she said. ``I'm feeling competitive.''
</P>
<P>
   As the women cleaned their plates, the confessions became more
difficult to digest.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I'm thin,'' said Ms. Sistrom, who stood up and modeled
her baggy blue schoolgirl Romeo Gigli dress, ``it makes me feel
powerful and strong and tough.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe you should carry a gun,'' Ms. Marx suggested.
</P>
<P>
   Powerful, skinny types do not linger. By 11 p.m., the women were
filing out.
</P>
<P>
   The waiter, seeming distressed, called out, ``The next time you
come, order dessert, ladies, and don't talk so much of fat.'' No
one flinched.
</P>
<P>
   Parting, Muffin Humes, an editor at Conde Nast Traveler,
complained to Ms. Sistrom that she hadn't had a chance to talk to
her. ``You were so thin you were invisible,'' she said to Ms.
Sistrom, who glowed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
