<HEADLINE>
CASH TRIBUTE SHOWS US THE MAN INSIDE THE ARTIST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
``ALL STAR TRIBUTE TO JOHNNY CASH'' 
On: TNT 
Time: Sunday, 8 and 10 p.m. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Johnny Cash, known to millions as the Man in Black, has scored a
unique triple crown. The twangy, socially-conscious singer is the
only artist to have been inducted into the Country Music Hall of
Fame, the Rock Hall of Fame, and the Songwriters Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   It is no surprise, then, that ``All Star Tribute to Johnny
Cash'' on TNT draws acts from many corners of the music industry.
Bruce Springsteen, Bob Dylan, Dave Matthews, Emmylou Harris, Willie
Nelson, Wyclef Jean, and Cash's old running mate, Kris
Kristofferson were some of the performers who traveled to New York
City for the live concert tribute.
</P>
<P>
   From his breakthrough rockabilly days in Memphis in the '50s, to
his daring covers of songs by Springsteen and Soundgarden in later
years, Cash, now 67, has never stood still. As Springsteen tells
him: ``You took the social consciousness from folk music, the
gravity and humor from country music, and the rebellion from rock
'n' roll, and taught all of us young guys that not only was it all
right to tear up these lines and boundaries, but it was important,
too.''
</P>
<P>
   The program was taped April 6 at the Hammerstein Ballroom _ an
ornate setting and staging for a simple, down-home legend like
Cash, but the performances are generally magical. After the stars
are through singing his songs, Cash appears for his first public
performance in 19 months since a spokesman revealed that he has
Parkinson's disease, a chronic progressive disease that affects the
nervous system.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hello, I'm Johnny Cash,'' says the legend himself, then he's
off and running with remarkable poise through his famed ``Folsom
Prison Blues'' and ``I Walk the Line,'' for which he's joined by
the entire cast. He personally walks around and greets each and
every one in a heartfelt gesture that speaks volumes. Cash then
tells them that he's ``astonished by the stretch of the lyrics''
and the great arrangements that these artists have given his songs.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, he's right. The show is a winner from the start when
Sheryl Crow and Nelson rock through ``Jackson,'' then are followed
by Chris Isaak doing early Cash nuggets ``I Guess Things Just
Happen That Way'' and ``Get Rhythm.'' The backing band throughout
is the Mavericks, and if you love country music, that should tell
you everything right there. Cash's songs are given the bite that
they deserve.
</P>
<P>
   MC Jon Voight looks out of place in a tuxedo and scarf, but he
skillfully introduces performers on a night that builds to a
festive celebration. Taped segments are sent from U2 (a performance
of ``Don't Take Your Guns to Town'' in a Dublin studio), Dylan
(``Train of Love''), and a solo acoustic Springsteen (an
awe-inspiring ``Give My Love to Rose'').
</P>
<P>
   In-house highlights are a Matthews/Harris duet on ``Long Black
Veil'' (not written by Cash, but often identified with him), Lyle
Lovett on the bluegrassy ``Tennessee Flattop Box,'' Wyclef Jean
with an edgy, hip-hop/country version of the dark ``Delia's Gone,''
and Kristofferson on ``The Ballad of Ira Hayes,'' about the
mistreatment of the Native American who helped raise the flag at
Iwo Jima.
</P>
<P>
   The song confirms Cash's social conscience, as does documentary
footage showing his support of battered women's shelters, a home
for autistic children, and a burns research center. (Luther
Perkins, Cash's original guitarist, died from burns received from a
fire in 1958.) So we see Cash the artist, but we also see Cash the
man _ and there's no hall of fame big enough to contain this side
of him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
