<SLUG> BC-JACKBULL-HBO-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WESTERN `THE JACK BULL' FINDS A HOME ON THE HBO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
(Tonight refers to Saturday, April 17)  
By ROB LOWMAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Except for when Clint Eastwood turns his attention
to the genre, as he did in the Oscar-winning ``Unforgiven,'' it
seems that westerns _ good ones, that is _ &UR;  &LR; have hightailed it to
cable. A while back we had the clever ``Purgatory'' on TNT, and
tonight we have the morality tale ``The Jack Bull'' on HBO.
</P>
<P>
   Starring John Cusack as horse dealer Myrl Redding, ``The Jack
Bull'' is the story of a man obsessed with extracting what he sees
as the justice due him when he is wronged _ and the consequences he
pays for it.
</P>
<P>
   Redding has run afoul of Henry Ballard (L.Q. Jones), the local
cattle baron who has been buying up property in the area fearing
that the Wyoming Territory's bid in the 1880s for statehood will
interfere with his commerce. Redding, who sees statehood as
inevitable, is indifferent at first, but when challenged by
Ballard, sides with those for statehood. This marks him in
Ballard's eyes, and later when Redding is taking his animals to
market, Ballard imposes a fee to cross his newly acquired land,
which is the shortest route.
</P>
<P>
   Lacking funds, Redding is forced to leave two of his beloved
stallions as collateral. When he returns to reclaim his horses,
Redding finds that they have been abused and that his Indian ranch
hand has been beaten up.
</P>
<P>
   After confronting Ballard, he refuses to take the horses back
until the animals are returned to their former healthy state. He
files a petition with the local judge about his case, but the
justice, who is in the pocket of Ballard, won't hear it. Like a
bull, Redding continues charging, until tragedy results and events
take on a life of their own.
</P>
<P>
   The handsomely filmed ``The Jack Bull'' was written by Cusack's
father, Dick Cusack, and is based on the German writer Heinrich Von
Kleist's novel ``Michael Kohlhass,'' which was originally a Saxon
legend. By setting ``The Jack Bull'' in a Wyoming on the verge of
statehood, political considerations come into play. Statehood
advocates such as the governor see the Ballard-Redding dispute as
an embarrassment, showing that Wyoming is not ready to join the
Union. Justice, eventually, is tinged with expediency.
</P>
<P>
   Directed by John Badham (``Point of No Return''), ``The Jack
Bull'' is a finely crafted, entertaining film with a strong cast.
Cusack is an actor who projects a likability with an edginess that
serves him well as Redding, an easygoing, honest man with a dark
intensity. And John Goodman is particularly notable as Judge
Tolliver, who eventually is given the case and tries to make
Solomonic sense of what has become a twisted affair.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
