A1675 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RADIOACTIVE-AMMO-HNS &LR;      04-16 0794
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RADIOACTIVE-AMMO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPECIALIST DOUBTS REPORT ON RADIOACTIVE AMMO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By KATHLEEN SULLIVAN  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Ask Dr. Michael Kilpatrick, a top Pentagon
doctor, about a new study that says radioactive ammunition used
during the Gulf War isn't likely to cause lung cancer or other
health problems, and he says: ``It's very reassuring.''
</P>
<P>
   But an internationally known radiation specialist compared the
Pentagon-sponsored study, released Thursday, to reports on nicotine
from the tobacco industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at all the reports that came out of the tobacco companies
_ and are still coming out _ that say nobody has ever proven
tobacco is harmful,'' said Rosalie Bertell, president of the
International Institute of Concern for Public Health.
</P>
<P>
   She said the Pentagon treats depleted uranium the same way.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want to use the stuff and they don't want people saying
it's hazardous,'' Bertell said.
</P>
<P>
   Ammunition containing depleted uranium was used for the first
time in combat in the 1991 Gulf War. It was fired by U.S. Air Force
jets and Army tanks, but the Pentagon did not warn American
soldiers that its dust and debris were radioactive and chemically
toxic.
</P>
<P>
   Depleted uranium is a byproduct of the process of enriching
uranium for use in nuclear weapons and nuclear power plants.
</P>
<P>
   Depleted uranium ammunition is made from a radioactive and toxic
metal that is twice as dense as lead. It rips through tanks, the
Pentagon says, ``like a hot knife through butter.''
</P>
<P>
   Many veterans worry that the illnesses that plague them today
may be linked to combat exposure to depleted uranium.
</P>
<P>
   The new 120-page report by the Rand Corp., an independent think
tank, said health studies on depleted uranium are ``scarce,'' and
called for more research.
</P>
<P>
   But the report says Gulf War veterans have little reason for
concern about inhaling depleted uranium dust, because there is no
evidence that uranium industry workers contract lung cancer or
suffer from any other health problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``If radiation exposure is not a problem with natural uranium,
it's not going to be a problem with depleted uranium, which is 40
percent less radioactive,'' said C. Ross Anthony, one of five
authors of the Rand report.
</P>
<P>
   The group based its findings on reviews of 215 documents,
including military reports, industrial medicine journals and
conference proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony said the risks posed by depleted uranium's chemical
toxicity _ it is nearly twice as dense as lead _ are identical to
the hazards posed by uranium.
</P>
<P>
   The report said the body is ``amazingly efficient at clearing
alien substances,'' such as depleted uranium.
</P>
<P>
   After an individual inhales depleted uranium dust, 75 percent of
the substance is exhaled, the report said. Of the 25 percent
retained in the lungs, most is cleared by the upper respiratory
system or excreted through the gastrointestinal tract.
</P>
<P>
   Only a fraction enters the bloodstream, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   The body's ability to expel depleted uranium was one of the
reasons why Kilpatrick called the report reassuring.
</P>
<P>
   But Bertell said health studies on uranium exposure aren't
relevant to a discussion of the risks of depleted uranium.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Pentagon has created a new toxic material,'' Bertell said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Depleted uranium dust is not the same as uranium dust. It
becomes a ceramic _ like a little piece of glass _ when it is fired
on the battlefield.''
</P>
<P>
   Bertell said a British study showed that depleted uranium is
retained in the lungs for two years _ twice as long as uranium.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is also stored in the lymph nodes, the liver, the kidneys,
the muscle and the bone,'' she said. ``It's radioactive. Anyplace
it is stored it can do damage.''
</P>
<P>
   In a pilot study last year, Bertell found depleted uranium in
the urine of several Gulf War veterans.
</P>
<P>
   ``To say depleted uranium sits in the body for eight years and
doesn't do anything is beyond belief,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Bertell also challenged Rand's focus on cancer deaths.
</P>
<P>
   ``The risk of a fatal lung cancer is the only risk they accept
as important,'' she said. ``What about looking at the risk of a
depressed immune system or of neurological damage? If they don't
look, they're not going to find them.''
</P>
<P>
   Bertell said researchers would probably have to wait 50 years to
find lung cancer deaths among Gulf War veterans. But they're likely
to find other disabling lung disorders much sooner.
</P>
<P>
   ``The majority will have fibrosis _ in which the lung tissue
loses the ability to stretch and contract, and hardens _ and
necrosis _ in which the tissue dies,'' she said. ``Those people
will be suffering from emphysema and other lung diseases.''
</P>
</TEXT>
