<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-16 16:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1690 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-CONGRESS-$ADV1     04-16 0862
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CONGRESS-$ADV18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CONGRESS DUCKS ACTION ON BALKAN WAR
 &HT;    For release Sunday, April 18.
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ More than three weeks after the first U.S. missiles
began exploding in Yugoslavia, Congress has yet to take a clear
stand on the escalating conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Following a pattern set only in recent history, President
Clinton has exercised his power as commander-in-chief without
asking Congress for permission to send U.S. forces into combat.
</P>
<P>
   And while lawmakers pummeled the administration last week with
complaints about the strategy and goals of the NATO air war, they
have been content to leave the war-making decisions to the
president, while promising to pay the bills later.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the Constitution's statement that ``the Congress shall
have the Power ... to declare War,'' House Majority Whip Tom Delay,
R-Texas, said of the Balkan fighting: ``It's the president's war.''
</P>
<P>
   That position is rich with irony. Just a few months ago, the
House voted to impeach Clinton, and half the senators voted for
removing him from office. Now both chambers have yielded the
president unchallenged power to conduct the biggest war in Europe
in half a century.
</P>
<P>
   One of the House managers in the impeachment trial, Rep. Steve
Buyer, R-Ind., recently urged Clinton to consider the use of ground
troops against Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   If Clinton does decide to use ground troops, that may provoke
formal consideration of the Balkan conflict on Capitol Hill.
Lawmakers are already planning for an emergency spending bill to
pay for the operation, estimated to cost $1 billion a month.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., said last week it was
``too soon'' to take up a full debate on the military operation,
however. Instead, congressional leaders sent a fact-finding
delegation to Europe this weekend to inspect military bases and
refugee camps.
</P>
<P>
   Such congressional reluctance to take a position on military
missions has long concerned former Rep. Lee Hamilton, D-Ind. Before
retiring in 1998, he tried, with little success, to force
colleagues to take a stand when troops were sent into hostile
regions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The actions of the Congress are no profiles in courage when it
comes to issues of war and peace,'' said Hamilton, a former
chairman of the House International Relations Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``They prefer to let the president make the decision. ... If the
president's decision turns out to be right, they applaud it. If it
turns out to be wrong, they criticize it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The consequence of all this is that Congress gives up its
power to the president,'' he continued. ``It says, 'We really don't
want to participate in it. We don't want the burden of it. We don't
want to make the tough decisions. We'll leave it to you.' So the
Congress over a period of years has ceded enormous power to the
president on the most critical issue that the nation confronts _
the war issue.''
</P>
<P>
   The rare exception was the Persian Gulf war. In that case,
President Bush ordered a huge military buildup, and then sought
authorization from Congress before pushing Iraq's invading army out
of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, Clinton has ordered an invasion of Haiti, a
bombing campaign against Iraq, and now the Balkan war, all without
formal authorization from Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Only a few members have raised objections.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Tom Campbell, R-Calif., last week dusted off the
long-ignored War Powers Act, under which Congress must either vote
authorization for keeping troops in a hostile region or require the
president to order them home. And Rep. Ron Paul, R-Texas,
reiterated his long-held position that ``Congress should assume
their constitutional responsibility, and that is, not allow the
president to wage war without congressional approval.''
</P>
<P>
   This position has few backers, however. Congress's
constitutional power to declare war has become a ``dead letter,''
said Hamilton, noting that the last time that happened was during
World War II. ``And we've had a lot of wars since then,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In a Senate Armed Services Committee hearing last week, Sen. Bob
Smith, R-N.H., locked onto Defense Secretary William Cohen. ``Are
we at war?'' he demanded.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are engaged in open hostilities with the forces in the
field of President (Slobodan) Milosevic'' of Yugoslavia, Cohen
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seems to me that's an act of war,'' Smith said. He posited the
idea of introducing a declaration of war in the Senate, although he
said the vote would be 100-0 against it.
</P>
<P>
   The next serious action on the Balkan operation will come when
Congress considers the administration's request for additional
funding. But even then, the lawmakers may skirt the issue of
whether they approve of the war. Some of the harshest critics have
declared they will vote for the extra spending as an expression of
support for the troops.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the big dispute over Clinton's planned $4 billion
supplemental request is whether it's high enough, since many
Republicans want to give the military a much bigger increase.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
