   OHIO-CENSUS-TAXES. As Ohioans scrambled to meet the IRS filing
deadline, they may have wondered how much federal money comes flows
back into the state. (Working.) By Sean Gorman
</P>
<P>
   WISCONSIN-DAIRY-REACT. The Wisconsin congressional delegation
has banded together to try to stop a bill that would reverse
changes to the milk pricing system proposed last month by the USDA.
Although Wisconsin lawmakers are not crazy about the USDA proposal,
they insist it is better than nothing, and incorporates the
preferences of lawmakers from other areas of the country. (400
words.) By Elizabeth Hurt
</P>
<P>
   WYOMING-NUKE-WASTE. When Baltimore Gas and Electric announced
plans to open a nuclear power plant on the banks of the Chesapeake
Bay in the 1960s, critics warned that it would put local residents
at risk and scare away tourists, damaging the area's anemic
economy. But in the 25 years since the Calvert Cliffs Nuclear Power
Plant began splitting uranium atoms to make electricity here,
precisely the opposite has taken place. The environment remains
pristine, tourism has increased and Calvert County has been
transformed from one of Maryland's poorest counties into one of its
richest. The story of Calvert County gives a taste of what Wyoming
might expect if lawmakers allow a group of Riverton businessmen to
proceed with the ``Owl Creek Energy Project'' near Shoshoni -- a
facility that would be the nation's first private storehouse for
the used fuel from nuclear power plants. (35 inches.) By Charles
Davant
</P>
