<HEADER>
A1726 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOTHEBY-WHITNEYSALE17     04-16 0816
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOTHEBY-WHITNEYSALE17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sotheby's to auction `extraordinary' Whitney collection
 &HT;    By Shannon Donnelly
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Some people know how to live.
</P>
<P>
   Jock and Betsey Whitney were two of them. Homes at the finest
addresses in Manhattan, Saratoga, London, and Manhasset; a
plantation/hunting lodge in Thomasville, Ga.; fine furnishings and
decorative pieces; and an assemblage of paintings and sculpture
considered by many experts to be the finest private collection in
the
</P>
<P>
   world.
</P>
<P>
   Property from the estates of Ambassador John H. and Betsey
(Cushing) Whitney will be offered by Sotheby's in two separate
sales, one later this month and the other in early May.
</P>
<P>
   Furnishings, decorative arts and fine art will be offered in a
six-session sale from Thursday, April 22 to Sunday, April 25. The
paintings and sculpture collection will be offered in a
single-session sale on Monday, May 10. Both auctions will take
place in Sotheby's New York salesroom.
</P>
<P>
   John Hay Whitney founded J.H. Whitney and Co., the oldest
venture capital firm in the United States, and the Whitney
Communications Corp. He was also was a social activist and
philanthropist whose John Hay Whitney Foundation was established to
combat discrimination based on race, gender and economic condition.
</P>
<P>
   He was a decorated World War II veteran and served as ambassador
to the Court of St. James from 1956 to 1960. After leaving
diplomatic service, he was editor-in-chief and publisher of the New
York Herald Tribune until 1966 and chairman of the International
Herald Tribune from 1966 until he died in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   Betsey Maria Cushing was one of a trio of fabled daughters of
neurosurgeon Harvey Cushing and Kate Crowell Cushing. The three
young women epitomized the beauty and style trends of their day and
were famous for making marriages to prodigiously wealthy men. Her
sisters, Barbara (``Babe'') and Mary, became Mrs. William Paley and
Mrs. Vincent Astor, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Betsey Whitney spent a lifetime collecting art, furnishings and
``objets'' with an impeccable eye.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mrs. Whitney had incredible taste and an extraordinary
collection,'' said Diana Brooks, chief executive of Sotheby's
Holdings. ``Was she a perfectionist? Of course she was. She had an
unusual ability to create beauty in her surroundings, placing
furniture and decorative objects imaginatively together. ... It was
effortless, welcoming and original.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of those furnishings and decorative ``objets'' will be
offered during the six-session sale. Highlights from that sale
include the 1794 illuminated ``First Book of Urizen'' by William
Blake, written, etched and colored by Blake himself (estimated at
$500,000-$700,000); and a Louis XV ormolu and patinated bronze
mantel clock from the mid-18th century in the form of a rhinoceros
($150,000-$200,000).
</P>
<P>
   At her death in March 1998 at age 89, Mrs. Whitney bequeathed a
$300 million portion of her art collection to the National Gallery
of Art in Washington, D.C., and to the Museum of Modern Art in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   A highlight of the May 10 art auction will be the sale of
Cezanne's Rideau, Cruchon et Compotier, a still life, circa
1893-94.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Moffett, co-director of Sotheby's Department of
Impressionist and Modern Art, called it ``one of the
</P>
<P>
   greatest still lifes by the greatest still-life painter of all
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Executed during the peak of the artist's career, it is one of
the most important Cezannes to be offered at auction in years. The
work, which has been in the Whitney family for more than 50 years,
is expected to sell for between $25 million and $35 million.
</P>
<P>
   Another offering, George Seurat's L'Ile de la Grande Jatte, is
the only major image relating to Seurat's most famous work that
remains privately owned. It is one of two large final works
preceding Un Dimanche a la Grand Jatte, Seurat's masterpiece, now
at the Art Institute of Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Executed over a five-year period beginning in 1894, the Seurat
also is expected to bring between $25 million and $35 million.
</P>
<P>
   The May 10 sale also includes two works by Picasso, both
acquired in 1968 from the collection of Gertrude Stein. Le Journal
was executed in 1912 during the high period of analytical cubism.
It is expected to bring $4 million to $6 million. Verre, Bouteille
Rhum Pailee, Compotier sur une Table, is an early synthetic cubist
work executed in 1914. It is estimated at $5 million to $6 million.
</P>
<P>
   Other highlights include Gustave Courbet's The Hound from ``The
Burial at Ornans'' ($1 million-$1.5 million) and Berthe Morisot's
Cache-Cache, one of the artist's most recognizable images ($1.8
million- $2.2 million).
</P>
<P>
   The pre-sale exhibition begins at 1 p.m. Saturday and continues
through noon on Thursday, April 22.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
