<HEADLINE>
DODGE DURANGO IS CALLED A MID-SIZED SUV, BUT IS IN A CLASS BY
ITSELF
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   You can't call it a midsize, because the Dodge Durango
sport-utility vehicle is nearly as big as the Ford Expedition, and
can seat up to seven adults.
</P>
<P>
   The folks at DaimlerChrysler want everyone to believe it's a
midsize, so they can say that it's the biggest, roomiest and most
powerful vehicle in the midsize SUV class _ competing with the Ford
Explorer, Chevy Blazer, Toyota 4Runner, Nissan Pathfinder, Isuzu
Rodeo, Mitsubishi Montero Sport and so forth.
</P>
<P>
   But just like the Chevy Suburban, the Durango really is in a
class by itself (although the Suburban finally is getting some
competition from Ford, which will begin selling an even bigger
sport-utility this fall).
</P>
<P>
   Although it really falls midway between midsize and full-size,
the Durango does compete more against the midsize models than the
bigger ones. That's probably due in part to DaimlerChrysler's own
marketing, but it's also because the Durango really doesn't measure
up as a full-size sport-utility, except in fuel economy, which is
among the worst in either the mid- or full-size class.
</P>
<P>
   What the Durango offers is a roomier alternative to the Explorer
and others in that class without having to go to a bigger, bulkier
vehicle that might not fit into your garage or into downtown
parking spaces.
</P>
<P>
   Built on the chassis of the Dodge Dakota pickup (which competes
in the compact pickup class, but is bigger than all of the rest ...
you get the picture), the Durango was introduced last year to
appease Dodge dealers who were clamoring for a sport-utility
vehicle. Until then, the former Chrysler Corp. had been satisfied
to let its Jeep-Eagle dealers sell its two sport-utility vehicles,
the Jeep Cherokee and Grand Cherokee, leaving Dodge dealers only
minivans and pickups in the truck segment.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, only a four-wheel-drive version of the Durango was
offered. But for 1999, DaimlerChrysler has introduced a
two-wheel-drive model for those who want or can afford only half a
truck. This is no slam at the manufacturer; there are people who
really don't care about four-wheel drive and don't want to pay the
roughly $2,000 extra to get it, and DaimlerChrysler is just meeting
market demand.
</P>
<P>
   Two-wheel-drive customers are common in Texas, where virtually
everything _ including the most remote farm roads _ is paved, and
there is rarely any snow on the roads. But you couldn't give one of
the two-wheel-drives away in Denver during a winter snowstorm.
</P>
<P>
   Our test vehicle for the week was the 1999 Durango SLT Plus
(base price $25,265 plus $525 transportation) with two-wheel drive
and the biggest engine in a less-than-full-size SUV (that's my
designation for the Durango).
</P>
<P>
   The vehicle's 5.9-liter Magnum V-8 ($1,085 extra) cranks out a
respectable 245 horsepower and a whopping 335 foot-pounds of
torque. Of course, you need all of that torque to get this vehicle
moving; it weighs well above two tons empty. Fill it with seven
adults and their ``stuff,'' and you've got a big load _ well above
5,000 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   There are two smaller engines available in the Durango. The base
powerplant is a 3.9-liter V-6 with 175 horsepower and 225
foot-pounds of torque. It has adequate power for most needs,
particularly if you don't buy the optional third seat ($550).
(Without the third seat in place, middle-seat passengers get an
extra two inches of leg room.)
</P>
<P>
   The midlevel engine is a 5.2-liter V-8, rated at 230 horsepower
and 300 foot-pounds of torque. That engine is more than adequate
for just about any need; the only reason you might want the bigger
V-8 is to pull a heavy trailer.
</P>
<P>
   You won't save a lot of gas buying the smaller V-8 or even the
V-6, however. Fuel-economy ratings are 12 miles per gallon in the
city and 16 mpg on the highway for the biggest engine, but that
improves only one mpg with the smaller V-8, to 13 city/17 highway.
And surprisingly, the V-6 is only slightly better at 15 city/18
highway.
</P>
<P>
   MORE nn
</P>
</TEXT>
