<P>
   MINN-VENTURA (St. Paul) _ In his first three months of office,
Governor Ventura, the former professional wrestler known for
fighting in a pink boa, has managed to offend, annoy and outrage
plenty of Minnesotans _ but win the cheers of most. ``For as much
feathers as I've ruffled in being politically incorrect,'' the
Governor said in a recent interview, ``I get 10 to 1 letters from
people saying that's why they like me.'' By Dirk Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   MASS-WELFARE (Boston) _ A year out, the vast majority of
Massachusetts people who get off welfare and stay off find modest
improvements in their earnings and are able to stay employed,
despite dire predictions that the early gains of the welfare
overhaul would not last, according to a report released Friday that
is the most detailed study of the effects of welfare in a state
with some of the toughest laws. By Carey Goldberg.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   NY-EMBRYO-MIXUP (New York) _ In a case of mixed-up embryos that
caused a Staten Island woman who underwent in vitro fertilization
to give birth to two sons of different races, a state inquiry has
concluded that the embryologist knew he had implanted the wrong
eggs but failed to tell anyone because he did not think the
fertilized eggs would develop. By JIM YARDLEY
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (will run on the ``f'' wire)
</P>
<P>
   GREENSPAN-TRADE (Washington) _ Alan Greenspan, the Federal
Reserve chairman, waded into the escalating debate over trade
policy today, denouncing protectionism and arguing that pockets of
workers sometimes had to suffer in order for the national economy
to grow stronger. Greenspan did not directly address the biggest
question on the trade agenda, the possible entry of China into the
World Trade Organization. But he cited rising protectionist
sentiment as one of the biggest threats to the long-term economic
health of the United States, and suggested that any steps to reduce
trade barriers, even if not fully reciprocated, would have
substantial benefits. By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
