<HEADER>
A1779 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CARS-WILLIAMS-COLUMN-     04-16 0592
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARS-WILLIAMS-COLUMN-2ndTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
UNDATED: city/18 highway. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This vehicle is roomier than the segment-leading Explorer, and
that could be a big plus for folks with lots of kids and soccer
equipment to haul. Seven adults can be seated adequately in the
Durango, although the third seat is more suited to kids.
</P>
<P>
   Ride and handling are trucklike, of course, but not unpleasant.
Unlike some of the competition, such as the Grand Cherokee and
Lexus RX 300 _ the Durango is, after all, built on a truck chassis.
On smooth roads, the ride isn't bad at all; it's when you take a
Durango off-road onto bumpy jeep tracks that you begin to feel
every bump.
</P>
<P>
   Modern amenities abound, giving the Durango a carlike appearance
inside the cabin.
</P>
<P>
   All Durangos come with air-conditioning, tilt steering wheel,
cruise control, power door locks with keyless entry, power
one-touch windows, AM/FM/cassette stereo, dual front air bags, roof
rack, tinted glass, power outside mirrors, 15-inch aluminum wheels,
power rack-and-pinion steering, and a full-size spare tire.
</P>
<P>
   (The remote control for the keyless entry system has
super-sensitive buttons that I kept hitting accidentally just
taking the control out of my pocket or putting it back in. I must
have hit the ``panic button'' accidentally a couple dozen times
during the week I drove the Durango, setting off a blaring horn and
flashing the lights.)
</P>
<P>
   The Durango has power-assisted front disc, rear drum brakes with
an antilock system that works only on the rear wheels. Most of the
Durango's competitors have four-wheel antilock brakes, an important
safety feature.
</P>
<P>
   Extras on our vehicle included and optional equipment group
($2,525), which added such items as fog lights, overhead console,
floor mats, 3.92 axle ratio, automatic day/night mirror,
AM/FM/cassette/compact-disc stereo with equalizer, and a
leather-wrapped steering wheel with integrated audio controls.
Also, we had power heated fold-away outside mirrors ($75), rear
air-conditioning ($430), and a trailer-towing package ($245).
</P>
<P>
   Total sticker, including transportation, was $30,640, which is
somewhat below several comparably equipped competitors.
</P>
<P>
   The fuel tank holds 25 gallons of gasoline, and regular octane
fuel is sufficient.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   At A Glance:
</P>
<P>
   1999 Dodge Durango SLT Plus sport-utility
</P>
<P>
   THE PACKAGE: Less-than-full-size, four-door, five- or
seven-passenger, Magnum V-8 powered, rear-drive sport-utility
vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   HIGHLIGHTS: New for 1999 is the first two-wheel-drive Durango.
The 5.9-liter Magnum V-8 has more power than most people will ever
need; interior is roomy; ride is comfortable on smooth roads; price
is competitive against smaller midsize SUVs.
</P>
<P>
   NEGATIVES: Abysmal fuel-economy ratings.
</P>
<P>
   MAJOR COMPETITORS: Ford Explorer, Chevrolet Blazer/GMC Jimmy,
Jeep Cherokee, Jeep Grand Cherokee, Isuzu Rodeo, Mitsubishi Montero
Sport, Toyota 4Runner, Nissan Pathfinder, Mercedes-Benz M-class,
Land Rover Discovery II, Lexus RX 300, Isuzu Trooper/Acura SLX.
</P>
<P>
   EPA FUEL ECONOMY: 12 miles per gallon city, 16 highway.
</P>
<P>
   BASE PRICE: $25,265 plus $525 transportation.
</P>
<P>
   PRICE AS TESTED: $30,640, including transportation.
</P>
<P>
   ON THE ROAD RATING: B-plus.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
