<SLUG> BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARMING CHILDREN TO FIGHT OFF ASSAULT OF MASS MEDIA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Age 10, with a TV IQ noticeably higher than average. That's
Abney, round-faced and pig-tailed, feisty and inquisitive. This
much is apparent the moment she opens her mouth, the moment she
begins to rattle off the television programming she digests on a
daily basis. How it excites her and intrigues her, saddens her and
angers her.
</P>
<P>
   She likes ``The Smart Guy'' for its easily identifiable
messages, ``Moesha'' for its gray-area approach to adolescence and
adulthood, ``The Hughleys'' for its comical musings on race and
class from a point of view she easily comprehends.
</P>
<P>
   She considers ``Clueless'' ``just entertainment,'' finds ``South
Park'' ``stupid'' and even offers her own take on why ``Friends'''
characters have no homeys who look like her. (''They don't want it
to be a black show.'')
</P>
<P>
   She finds local news ``depressing'' and reality TV shows like
``Cops'' funny but ``kinda sad. It's real people, you know?''
</P>
<P>
   We met recently at Morningside Elementary in Fort Worth, where
her encyclopedic knowledge of the tube was equal parts amazing and
unsettling. When she speaks of programming, it's with an
understanding rare among young minds. Kids may know what they like
on ``Jerry Springer'' (the fighting) or dislike (the fighting), but
most would fumble mercilessly articulating the whys.
</P>
<P>
   Abney explains them with glee. She watches more and knows more
and ``understands'' more. What an exception. Young minds often
digest television like a vacuum swallowing dust. No analysis, no
deciphering. They believe what they see and act accordingly. They
become sponges for messages from an influential medium where profit
responsibility cancels out morality.
</P>
<P>
   Trampled in the process are the young minds, not that they have
to be. I ask Abney about media literacy and whether she'd heard
about it, and the answer is no. It's one of those vague terms that
means to analyze and assess media messages so as not to be
manipulated by them, something Abney seems to be accomplishing
without knowing it.
</P>
<P>
   My time with the Morningside students, from curious
kindergartners to jaded fifth-graders, reminded me that young
viewers must arm themselves with critical observation tools to make
informed choices about media messages.
</P>
<P>
   I know it's a tricky area in an age of budget cuts and school
finance gone amok, particularly in financially struggling districts
that tend to linger at the bottom of the priority scale.
</P>
<P>
   That's not the case at Azle High School just northwest of Fort
Worth, one of the few schools nationally to add to its curriculum a
course titled ``Analysis of Visual Media.''
</P>
<P>
   Todd Marchand, a teacher turned ad man turned teacher, handles
the course. ``Media literacy,'' he says, ``is the ability to
assess, analyze, evaluate and produce media in a variety of
forms.''
</P>
<P>
   It means his students learn to read and interpret and evaluate
the images, words and sounds that make up our contemporary mass
media culture.
</P>
<P>
   Marchand's first step is cultivating awareness, followed by
teaching critical-viewing skills. His thing is that when we as
television viewers learn to ask questions about what we see, when
we recognize and defuse the effects of commercials and media
violence, and when we intentionally evaluate program content, we
are on the road to being media-literate.
</P>
<P>
   Marchand understands this because he spent a decade in
advertising and knows how messages are deliberately pieced together
for a desired effect.
</P>
<P>
   Marchand and other educators are saying it's not enough to read
and write; youth must be able to communicate in a variety of media.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's important to try not to present one side or
another,'' he adds. ``They need to understand that what we want to
give them is the tools to make their own analysis of the media
messages they encounter.''
</P>
<P>
   Marchand and his students recently took a look at the media
coverage of Kosovo, asking, among other things, about the
possibility of censored news. ``It was a pretty lively
discussion,'' says Marchand.
</P>
<P>
   Teacher knows some things will stick with students, some won't.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully,'' he adds, ``enough will stick that they will
become a more perceptive consumer, whether in general or on
specific issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Like the class discussion on the subject of stereotypes, using
Fox's ``The PJs,'' an animated half-hour about life in the housing
projects, as launching pad.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, yeah, ``The PJs.'' That's certainly one Abney could have
sunk her teeth into.
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins is TV critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7862, or e-mail:
kperkins(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
