<DOCNO> NYT19990416.0194 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-16 17:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1799 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REFUGEES-TRAIN-0417-C     04-16 0635
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REFUGEES-TRAIN-0417-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    REFUGEE FAMILY SIDETRACKED TO FREEDOM: 'I THOUGHT, 'OH NO, WE'RE
DEAD'
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-REFUGEES-0417.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRAZDA, Macedonia _ In a hot and crowded railroad car, the
Rustemi family waited for the doors to part and freedom from
Kosovo's terror to be just down the road in Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   But then, the train lurched and began to move, back into the
heart of southern Kosovo, back toward the burning cities and
villages the Rustemis and thousands more thought they had left
behind on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had high hopes. We were approaching the border and we were
going to be safe and sound,'' said Enver Rustemi, 41. ``But when we
stopped and they turned us back, I thought, 'Oh no, we're dead.'''
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, they and thousands more ethnic Albanians finally
escaped, again by train, and told the story of their frightening
two-day ordeal. Rustemi and his family sat on the damp ground at
Brazda refugee camp while waiting to be assigned a tent. They ate
U.S.-supplied rations, a civilian version of the army's MRE --
meals ready to eat -- their first in two days.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past two weeks, Rustemi, a gas-station operator, and
his family were on the run after being forced from their home in
Urosevac. They scurried from house to house, from village to
village seeking to elude Serb forces and their mass expulsions in
the embattled Yugoslav province that have created more than 500,000
refugees in Macedonia, Albania and Montenegro.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, low on food and traveling with six children, including
their 7-year-old daughter, Samire, and a close friend's
five-month-old baby, they decided to take a chance earlier this
week and return to their home in Urosevac.
</P>
<P>
   They made it to their house, but were trapped there. Serb
snipers fired from rooftops, and nearby homes were destroyed and
smoldering.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, masked men with automatic rifles came to the door
with a menacing question. They asked Rustemi how many women were in
his house, how many on the block?
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't intend to leave my house, but felt we had to . . . We
we're lucky to escape. We think they had this on their minds: Take
the women,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the darkness Wednesday night, they dashed to the home of a
friend. The following morning, they made their way to the train
station in Urosevac, abandoning their Yugoslav-built car and
joining the throngs clamoring for tickets for the 25-mile trip to
the Macedonian border town of General Jankovic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Better to leave the car there than my soul,'' Rustemi said.
</P>
<P>
   The presence of Serb forces was surprisingly light. But inside
the station, there was chaos, as thousands of ethnic Albanians
sought to board the 12-car train.
</P>
<P>
   People were pushed into the cars ``like matches in boxes'' the
Rustemis said. In the confusion, some children and parents were
separated, old people were shoved. ``It brought tears to your
eyes,'' said Rustemi. ``Children were crying, people had pale
faces, ready to collapse.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the train pulled away for the hour-long trip south.
Hopes soared until, without explanation, the train arrived at the
border and was turned back.
</P>
<P>
   Again, they rose earlier on Friday morning and headed to the
station. Again, they struggled with thousands more to get aboard
the train. By 10:30 am., they were again at the border. This time,
the doors opened and they were instructed to walk down the railroad
tracks the remaining half-mile to the Macedonian border.
</P>
<P>
   There, they boarded buses for the refugee camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was born for the second time,'' Rustemi said with a broad
smile. ``At least here I can have a meal and not hear the shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
