<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Saturday, April 17, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(bl) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Warm weather will embrace the interior West from the deserts of
the Southwest to eastern Washington and Oregon on Saturday as a
ridge of high pressure spans from Baja California to western
Canada. However, cooler Pacific air will come ashore along the West
Coast, though offshore breezes may keep cool ocean air at bay along
parts of the southern California coast, thereby allowing
temperatures to rise into the 80Us. Meanwhile, milder air will
spread eastward into the Rockies on the eastern flank of the warm
ridge.
</P>
<P>
   With the expansive warm ridge covering the West, a flabby trough
of low pressure will promote cool, unsettled weather over the
Middle West and East. The focus of unsettled weather will lie from
the Ohio Valley to interior New England, where variable clouds and
scattered, occasional showers will prevail. A few of the showers
will produce gusty, fitful winds and brief modest rains, but most
of the showers will be light and relatively tame.
</P>
<P>
   Showers and thunderstorms will develop in central Florida along
and just behind a front marking the leading edge of cool air
associated with the chilly trough over the East. Saturday's
combination of clouds, rain and drier air will bring a halt to the
tropical heat wave that occurred over much of the state the past
few days. Indeed, temperatures will fall into the 30s Saturday
night across parts of the panhandle.
</P>
<P>
   Low clouds, patchy drizzle and isolated showers will dull the
day over the high ground of southwest Texas as moist winds from the
east are forced to ascend the sloping terrain.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Opposite Extremes
</P>
<P>
   At Oceanside, Calif., a coastal town in the southern California
the mercury struggled to 55 degrees on Thursday setting a record
for the coolest April 15 on record. Meanwhile, at Escondido about
15 miles inland, a record high of 87 was reached. This striking
contrast of opposite extremes was a result of the vagaries of the
marine layer. The layer of cool and often foggy air in contact with
the cool Pacific waters drifts in and out near the shores of
California throughout the year. On summer days, the marine layer
makes 30 degree contrasts common around the California coast. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
