<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service plans the following articles
from the Style section for use Sunday, April 18, and thereafter. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WOMEN-ARTISTS (New York) _ Amid the crowd of 500 who flocked to
the opening of ``Another Girl, Another Planet,'' an exhibition of
photographs by and about young women, the dozen artists in the show
were as easy to spot as fireflies at dusk. With their tousled hair,
bare legs, colorful stilettos, sexy leather pants, Tracy Feith slip
dresses and beaded vintage handbags, they looked as if they had
stepped out of the fashion pages. By Elizabeth Hayt. Photo. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FASHION-CULTURE (New York) _ One Tuesday afternoon in mid-March,
a flock of junior stylists and fashion editors debarked from a
cloud of limousines and stepped into a gallery at the World
Financial Center. Gen Art, the nonprofit organization had convened
the young selection committee for an international fashion design
competition. Devoted to showcasing young talent, Gen Art was asking
the panelists to select the finalists _ culled from design schools
and other sources _ for a glitzy fashion show to be held three
weeks later. By Bob Morris.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GO-GO-REVIVAL (Undated) _ The latest Gap ads, which had their
premieres during last month's Academy Awards telecast, have taken
something far out and made it totally in. Hold on to your feather
boas, pop culture is going ``a go-go.'' Again. Gap, the ubiquitous
San Francisco-based retailer, whose ``Khakis Swing'' ad last year
helped to make the 1940s dance revival cool, has now unleashed 15
sexy dancers who do the frug, the pony and the jerk in a
'60s-inspired spot called ``Khaki a Go-Go.'' By Frank De Caro.  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NITEOUT-SKINNYWOMEN (New York) _ I feel testosterone surging
through my veins,'' said Susan Sistrom, a doll-size woman engulfed
in a swelling pool of portly men at Sparks Steak House in midtown
on Wednesday night. ``I feel like the Yankees are going to show
up,'' said Patricia Marx, also a pretty, tiny person. The two were
waiting to be seated with six other small women at this temple of
beef _ where both portions and patrons tend to be oversize _ for,
of all things, a ``skinny dinner.'' Ms. Sistrom and Ms. Marx,
writers for The New Yorker (Ms. Sistrom under the name Susan
Orlean), conduct ``skinny'' meals with groups of weight-savvy wits
who gorge on bons mots, not bonbons, to siphon their secrets for
staying thin. A series of ``skinny lunches'' are the basis of their
new book, ``The Skinny'' (Dell, $9.95), a guide to help women stay
thin whatever their genetic makeup. By Amanda Hesser. Photo. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BHANGRA-BLOWOUT (Washington) _ On a Saturday night in April at
Constitution Hall, young women in long braids and shimmering,
sequined outfits sashayed onto stage, carrying water jugs and
swinging their hips to Punjabi folk songs. Young men with sky-high
turbans, some with two-headed drums whirled, leaping and heaving
their shoulders in rhythm, their arms raised to the roof. Every now
and then, dancers clasped their legs around a partner's torso and
spun at breakneck speed. At other times, they climbed atop one
another's shoulders, building human pyramids. Welcome to Bhangra
Blowout, an annual intercollegiate dance competition in which teams
from a dozen schools perform their renditions of traditional
Punjabi dance in a bid for a $1000 prize. By Somini Sengupta.
Photo.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-COLUMN (Undated) _ There is much good to say about a
flower with a sunny disposition and a desire to please. In August,
when most perennials are in their summer sulk and the annual flower
garden looks a bit ratty, marigolds can be counted on to look
presentable. By Cass Peterson.
</P>
