<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-16 17:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1814 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FASHION-CULTURE-$ADV1     04-16 1175
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-CULTURE-$ADV18-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN SEARCH OF THE NEXT CALVIN KLEIN AND COCKTAILS 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, April 18) 
(DW) 
 By BOB MORRIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ One Tuesday afternoon in mid-March, a flock of junior
stylists and fashion editors debarked from a cloud of limousines
and stepped into a gallery at the World Financial Center. After
being ceremoniously greeted by some junior administrators and
helping themselves to grilled chicken sandwiches, they were
escorted to a long table, where there were tins of Altoids and a
score sheet and pencil at each setting.
</P>
<P>
   ``This looks like fun,'' Shyama Patel, the fashion-market editor
of New York magazine, said. ``I mean, I always wanted to be a
panelist when I grew up.''
</P>
<P>
   She had come to the right place. After all, being grown up is
what Gen Art, the nonprofit organization that had convened the
young selection committee for an international fashion design
competition, is all about. Devoted to showcasing young talent, Gen
Art was asking the panelists to select the finalists _ culled from
design schools and other sources _ for a glitzy fashion show to be
held three weeks later.
</P>
<P>
   Despite some reservations about what they saw, all the panelists
seemed delighted to have been asked to play Anna Wintour for the
afternoon. ``Who needs a car service?'' a Gen Art administrator
asked when it was time to depart. Of course, every hand in the room
shot up into the air.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1980s, being an art insider was a way to flash social
cachet. Now the art world _ after Hollywood and pop music _ has
been sucked into the gravitational field of fashion. The Guggenheim
Museum runs style forums; Herb Ritts, the celebrity photographer,
gets a museum show sponsored by Donna Karan, and next month,
Creative Time, a downtown avant-garde arts presenter, is mounting a
fashion exhibition under the Brooklyn Bridge.
</P>
<P>
   Forget the stage. These days, all the world's a runway. VH-1
produces a fashion awards show for television. Victoria's Secret's
shows are broadcast on the Internet. Absolut vodka, having moved in
on fashion from the art world, has been playing runway with its
promotional collection of designer clothes for years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mass market for fashion culture is at its height right
now,'' Sally Singer, the fashion editor of New York magazine, said.
``Still, fashion shows are fundamentally boring, so I expect that
in a while the general public will become as tired of them as the
editors and buyers are.'' At a moment when teen-agers distinguish
Chanel from Prada, however, she wasn't sure when that time would
come. ``You can't unlearn an awareness of fashion,'' Ms. Singer
said. ``It's like nuclear weapons: once you start you really can't
turn back.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though its original mission was primarily to showcase young
artists and filmmakers, Gen Art now devotes tremendous resources to
featuring young designers in dazzling corporate-like venues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fashion has definitely become our most successful area,'' said
Ian Gerard, who left his job as a lawyer last year to run Gen Art,
which he founded with his brother, Stefan, in 1993. ``It's the
industry we can have the most impact on.''
</P>
<P>
   The organization cites Rebecca Dannenberg and Pixie Yates as
some of the deserving talent it has presented in recent years at
well-received shows in both Los Angeles and New York. Shoshanna
Lonstein was among the ``fresh faces'' Gen Art featured in a major
runway event last fall. As a result, Ms. Lonstein, the former
girlfriend of Jerry Seinfeld, got a favorable review in Women's
Wear Daily for one of her first collections of lingerie-inspired
sportswear.
</P>
<P>
   Did she need the boost so early in her career?
</P>
<P>
   Does any young designer? The senior judges at Gen Art's big,
glitzy ``Styles for the New Millennium'' show of finalists on April
6 thought so. Polly Mellen, the creative director of Allure;
Russell Simmons, the hip-hop mogul, and Richard Martin, the curator
of the Costume Institute of the Metropolitan Museum of Art, all
felt good about judging Gen Art's show before a young audience of
1,000 at the World Financial Center. Even if it was, in typical
grown-up-fashion style, an hour late in starting.
</P>
<P>
   ``People like structure,'' said Hal Rubenstein, In Style
magazine's fashion editor, another judge. ``They also like
cocktails.''
</P>
<P>
   Advertising executives, lawyers, media movers and bankers, who
had paid $50 each to have an authentic runway experience, cruised
the party before the show. ``So let's face it,'' said Nelson Mui, a
sportswear and media editor at The Daily News Record, the men's
fashion trade newspaper. ``These people aren't here to see clothes.
They're here to get dates.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, it was time to begin. Under the glass roof of the World
Financial Center's Winter Garden court, models with their hair in
beehives for the millennium walked around for an audience that was
especially enthusiastic after the Absolut-sponsored cocktail hour.
But for all the hoopla, there was only one truly memorable dress _
made of broken record albums _ by Anne Hung, from Canada.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything else was so conservative,'' said Simon Doonan,
known for his outlandishly creative displays at Barneys New York.
``It's a drag to see that that's how young people are thinking.''
</P>
<P>
   Betsey Johnson was let down, too. ``Right now fashion's in a
down moment,'' she said. ``I think it's sad that design schools are
encouraging students to be so sales oriented.''
</P>
<P>
   Mui said: ``It's a weird phenomenon. Everyone's looking for the
next new thing. But there's absolutely enough fashion out there
already, and these people only submitted two outfits to get into
this show in the first place. They haven't really proved themselves
yet.''
</P>
<P>
   But that hardly mattered to the amateur arbiters whooping it up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to think I have good taste, and this stuff looked good
to me.'' Todd Roth, a real estate agent and Gen Art supporter,
said. Dino Markus, his friend, who is also in real estate,
especially liked a pair of leather pants one designer showed. ``You
just liked the girl wearing them,'' Roth said.
</P>
<P>
   Happiest of all at night's end were the founders of Gen Art.
Stefan Gerard was standing at the top of the marble steps
overlooking a mob of well-dressed young people wrapped in black
Absolut feather boas, holding gift bags and cocktails, and looking
each other over with the acquisitive eyes of shoppers at a sample
sale.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always felt that if I can get somebody out of a sports
bar and turn him into an art collector or a fashion investor, then
I've done something positive,'' Gerard, a strategic planner at
Young &AMP; Rubicam, the advertising agency, said. ``OK, an event like
this doesn't save needy children. Still, it helps all these people
get engaged in something above the mundane.''
</P>
<P>
   Closer to the Absolut bar, a woman asked Markus if he was a
model. He was pleased with the question. ``Usually if I want to
impress a woman at parties,'' he said later, ``I tell them I write
children's books.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
