<DOCNO> NYT19990416.0198 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-16 17:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1815 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LA-INTELLECTURALS-NYT     04-16 1234
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LA-INTELLECTURALS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE L.A.'S IMAGE, ARTISTS AND SCHOLARS ARE THRIVING IN A
HOSPITABLE ENVIRONMENT  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID HAY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Stanley Sheinbaum, the publisher of New
Perspectives Quarterly, was standing by the window lamenting the
lack of ideological commitment among Hollywood executives. ``They
give their money away purely for ego rather than because they
identify with any particular cause,'' he said, his black turtleneck
setting off his white hair.
</P>
<P>
   Jon Wiener, a history professor, was waiting in line for a
sandwich and arguing about loyalty and betrayal in Washington. At
another table a discussion was starting about whether Mike Davis'
apocalyptic book on Los Angeles, ``Ecology of Fear,'' was fair to
their hometown.
</P>
<P>
   These 45 Angelenos had ventured out for their newest biweekly
tradition: a meeting of the Los Angeles Institute for the
Humanities, a group of writers, academics and intellectuals who
meet at the Faculty Center of the University of Southern
California.
</P>
<P>
   On this warm Friday they got to eat ham and turkey sandwiches
and listen to Ronald Steel, a professor and author, discuss his
forthcoming biography of Robert F. Kennedy. Also seated in the
standard-issue college dining room were Dagmar Barnouw, a
historian; Russell Jacoby, who wrote a book on public
intellectuals; the conservative columnist Arianna Huffington, and
David Schweitzer, a theater director.
</P>
<P>
   This is Los Angeles' intellectual life.
</P>
<P>
   That may sound like an oxymoron. After all, the notion that Los
Angeles has no brain is about as old as the city itself. Not even
its residents tend to think otherwise. ``That this city is so much
more complex than `Baywatch' is a fact too infrequently experienced
by its own residents,'' said Steve Wasserman editor of The Los
Angeles Times Book Review.
</P>
<P>
   Yet with the city's public and private universities, a slate of
Nobel Prize winners, some of the country's most creative artistic
talent, a reservoir of scientific expertise at the Jet Propulsion
Laboratory and the California Institute of Technology, these
stereotypes were always more alive in the imagination, particularly
on the East Coast, than in real life.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, writers and scholars are now saying that a new influx
of institutions and art museums has helped make intellectual life
more vital than in any other period in this city's history.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the West Side of Los Angeles there is now an intellectual
and cultural life that is easily comparable to that of New York or
Boston,'' said Davis, the historian, whose book is causing a stir.
</P>
<P>
   Sandra Harding, the director of the Center for the Study of
Women at the University of California, Los Angeles, agreed: ``Los
Angeles intellectual life is thriving. At the same time it is less
elitist and no one is intimidated by the big names.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the seven-month-old Institute for the Humanities
there is the new Institute for Art and Cultures at the Los Angeles
County Museum of Art, which sponsors lectures. Over the past year
59 Americans and Europeans, like the cultural critic Elaine Scarry
and the video artist Bill Viola, have come to study at the Bel Air
campus of the Getty Research Institute for the History of Art and
the Humanities. The area's universities regularly attract visiting
lecturers like the European philosophers Jacques Derrida and Jurgen
Habermas.
</P>
<P>
   Informal seminars and literary gatherings are becoming frequent
fixtures. On a recent Sunday night more than 80 people came to a
monthly literary salon at Le Coloniale, a West Hollywood
restaurant. For $20 you could get a buffet dinner and listen to
four writers read from new work. On this night DeLaune Michel,
whose one-woman show ``Southern Gothic'' played here last year, was
one of the attractions. ``There's a real desire out there to be
part of some greater literary community,'' said Charlie Otto, who
directed the reading.
</P>
<P>
   Books are a growth industry here. Last April 110,000 people
bought tickets to the third annual Los Angeles Times Book Fair.
``The greater Los Angeles area is the No. 1 book market in the
country,'' said Joseph Tosney, the regional manager of Borders
Books and Music.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, even the intellectuals don't try to claim that
cultivating the body never takes precedence over developing the
mind, or that the Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences
doesn't generate more interest than the academy.
</P>
<P>
   As Davis explained, ``This city has always been dominated by a
dictatorship of the boosters who were duly intolerant of the
intellectuals.''
</P>
<P>
   The city's geography hasn't helped. UCLA is more than 40 miles
from the Claremont Colleges. Driving is not only time consuming,
but it also works against spontaneous meetings and discussions.
``There's a vast intellectual audience out there,'' said Ruth
Seymour, the general manager of KCRW, the National Public Radio
station in Santa Monica. ``But it's much more hermetically
sealed.''
</P>
<P>
   Some are simply learning to work around such drawbacks. ``We do
not compete with the big gorilla,'' said Michael S. Roth, the
director of the Scholars and Seminars Program at the Getty Research
Institute, referring to Hollywood. ``We are not trying to make
money on ideas. We're here to demonstrate that ideas have
consequences on their own accord.''
</P>
<P>
   For others, technology has helped. The Southern California
Science Writers Group, frustrated by failed attempts to meet in
person, now plan to hold meetings on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   To what extent the isolation and narrowness is self-imposed is a
matter of debate, however. Chon Noriega, the editor of Aztlan: A
Journal of Chicano Studies, said that in a city that is 43 percent
Hispanic and 10 percent Asian the big new, largely white
intellectual institutions on the West Side ``do not represent the
population changes that have already occurred in this city.'' He
continued, ``What were once called minority writers are now on the
front lines of the new thinking about Los Angeles because it's they
who are grappling with the greatest range of positions.''
</P>
<P>
   One subject that seems to interest those inside and outside the
intellectual establishment is Los Angeles itself. ``The city is as
self-conscious about itself and generating as much literature about
itself as any other city in the world, including New York,'' said
Davis.
</P>
<P>
   If the subject matter is different here, so is the style of
discourse. Davis said there was a ``much tougher intellectual
climate in New York'' that ``arises from that city's political,
Jewish and radical traditions. Without that, it's more difficult in
a place like Los Angeles to get a harsh, critical discourse
going.''
</P>
<P>
   Laurie Winer, a former drama critic at The Times, said, ``If you
get into an argument here, people's first instinct is to smooth it
over.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, smoothing over isn't necessarily a bad idea. So many
people showed up for a recent 40-minute lecture by the American
painter R.B. Kitaj at the Institute for Art and Cultures that 300
of them _ including three museum trustees and the actor Michael
York _ had to be turned away amid angry complaints.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the organizers figured out how to defuse the
lecture-hungry crowd: Pipe the lecture through a loudspeaker on the
plaza and pass out glasses of free wine. That's an idea that even a
New York intellectual could love.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
