r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-MITCHELL-COLUMN-     04-16 0688
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-MITCHELL-COLUMN-(1660-2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHN HUGHES TAPPED INTO TEEN ANGST LIKE NO OTHER FILMMAKER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like all great artists, John Hughes knew whom to steal from. But
that doesn't mean he didn't have talent. He treated the misery
hidden behind the styling gel and shoulder pads of the 1980s more
profoundly than any other filmmaker. You can't watch the current
plethora of teen movies, such as ``She's All That'' or ``Cruel
Intentions'' or ``10 Things I Hate About You'' _ or for that
matter, TV's ``Dawson's Creek'' _ and not luxuriate under the
comfort of trees grown on ground he plowed and seeded. But with the
exception of Kevin Williamson, creator of ``Dawson'' as well as
``Scream'' and ``The Faculty,'' not one of Hughes' imitators can
create ache as elegantly as he did in his protagonists. Even in
``Home Alone,'' with its comforting blanket of Three Stooges and
Tex Avery-flavored violence, melodrama swells while the cartoon
souffle rises.
</P>
<P>
   Who would have figured, while sifting through the pile of
scripts that became the movies ``Mr. Mom'' and ``National Lampoon's
Vacation,'' that the writer of those pictures _ Hughes _ would go
on to become the most successful, and influential, filmmaker of the
1980s? He has written more than 20 scripts, ranging _ if you'll
pardon the expression _ from ``National Lampoon's Class Reunion''
to ``Ferris Bueller's Day Off,'' from ``Planes, Trains and
Automobiles'' to ``Curly Sue.'' This Michigan-born boy, who moved
with his family to Chicago as a teen, made the Cook County suburbs
into the promised land. All those rich kids with triple-pleated
pants and Corvettes paid for by Daddy practiced a high-school
cruelty that was particularly American, and that every member of
Hughes' white audience understood.
</P>
<P>
   His willfulness and the combination of awkwardness,
resentfulness and sweetness first surfaced in Hughes' work for
``National Lampoon'' magazine _ specifically in the story
``Vacation '59,'' which became the movie ``Vacation.'' Although its
director, Harold Ramis, would continue to examine the anxiety of
the midlife crisis in his subsequent movies (of which ``Analyze
This'' is another example), Hughes moved in the other direction; he
made movies about younger and younger protagonists, eventually
going all the way back to the crib with ``Baby's Day Out.''
</P>
<P>
   Taking their plights extraordinarily seriously was Hughes' gift.
No one before him had created a body of work that treated
adolescent crisis as if it were a tragedy disrupting the world as
the millennium nears. Yes, it's true that much of his entire
filmography was influenced by ``Alice Adams,'' the Katharine
Hepburn movie in which the good-hearted but poor protagonist was
humiliated by her social superiors. (Only we noticed, after 90
minutes of exquisite suffering, that she was their better.) But
what did it matter? His balance of sophistication and cruelty,
scored with the smartest use of contemporary music a director has
ever brought to pictures on a consistent basis, played ever so
brilliantly to an audience that felt it had never seen its own
stories on the screen before. The gasp of recognition from the teen
audiences when Judd Nelson snarled, ``When you grow up, your heart
dies'' in ``The Breakfast Club'' could be heard across the country.
</P>
<P>
   As a filmmaker, Hughes has the hypnotic ease of an advertising
ace, a pro who actually believes in the products he's selling.
Which is true, because he got his start as an ad copywriter who
churned out free-lance work, including the ``National Lampoon''
stuff, during his off-hours. And like any good adman, he manages to
exploit his audience's neediness with a total lack of shame.
Because he has no shame _ the bruising sentimentality that he has
employed in over half of his pictures, including the best of them,
``Sixteen Candles'' and ``Pretty in Pink,'' is mounted with a
shocking simplicity. Those pictures were his best because his muse,
Molly Ringwald, with her pliant pout, gave simple, honest
performances.
</P>
<P>
   MORE  &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
