<DOCNO> NYT19990416.0203 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-16 17:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1820 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-MITCHELL-COLUMN-     04-16 0805
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-MITCHELL-COLUMN-2ndTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
UNDATED: simple, honest performances. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Three times in his career, Hughes found actors who gave him
exactly what he needed: Ringwald, the ambitiously geeky Anthony
Michael Hall, and one actor he seemed to have discovered at a
larval stage: Macaulay Culkin. (Culkin's first Hughes movie was
``Uncle Buck,'' in which he seems nearly unformed.) Given his
peculiar smoothness _ his directing debut, ``Sixteen Candles,'' has
the deep-dish confidence of a veteran _ he showed a talent for
actors. And an empathy for them as well: In ``Planes, Trains and
Automobiles,'' Steve Martin exhibited a wet-eyed sappiness that,
with the ``Father of the Bride'' movies, he turned into a second
career. Hughes could be one of those people who were born to make
movies. Nowhere else could his unique assemblage of gifts and
sensitivity and anger have connected on such a large scale. He's
like a combination of screwball-comedy master director Preston
Sturges, young-adult novelist Judy Blume and Steven Spielberg. As
in Spielberg's most successful mainstream films, there's a fear of
sex in his movies. This is why his instinct for using pop is so
important. Through music, he communicates the restless teen desire
for sex without actually ever having to show it.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes' love of music may be the most redeeming element of his
movies, and the thing that makes them the most idiosyncratic.
Several of his other films also take their names from pop songs,
such as ``Sixteen Candles'' and ``Pretty in Pink.'' He picks most
of the music himself, and his song scores scurry from little-known
R&AMP;B classics to up-to-the-minute pop and oddball gems that clearly
reflect his own tastes. Hughes' love of music briefly led to his
creating a label, although his tastes were so outside the
mainstream _ and his attention so divided _ that it died quickly.
</P>
<P>
   He was so prolific that he couldn't possibly have got around to
directing all of the movies he scripted. ``She's Having a Baby''
seems to depict a move toward self-destruction. A sequence in which
star Kevin Bacon, fearful of the death of his creativity because of
his marriage, hurtles into a wall while strapped to a rocket sled
looked like nothing more than spitting in the face of a studio.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes' tantrums probably helped him resurrect Chris Columbus'
career, which had nose-dived into a ditch. Hughes' combative
attitude and Columbus' damaged status led to Hughes' exploding the
deal at ``Home Alone's'' original studio, Warner Bros., over a
budget disagreement of less than $2 million. Undefeated, Hughes
walked the movie over to Fox. (The guy who asked if you wanted to
supersize that Big Mac might be one of the Warner execs who let
``Alone'' get away.)
</P>
<P>
   Much of the blame for the infantilization of mainstream movies
has been laid at the feet of Spielberg and George Lucas, who raised
the stakes of box-office success. But some of that blame has to be
laid on Hughes, too. He was the man who proved that you could
consistently program movies for the ages 12-24 audience. It was
that chunk of the market that streamed into Hughes' filmography,
because they wanted to see themselves and their suburban angst
again and again. And he kept giving those movies to them, until he
apparently burned himself out. No one could write that many
pictures on roughly the same subject and not finally drain the
well.
</P>
<P>
   He fell into a slump after ``Curly Sue,'' and though he
reclaimed some popularity by writing and producing the live-action
``101 Dalmatians'' and the ``Flubber'' remake, he didn't seem to
matter anymore. Probably because he never embraced hip-hop, the pop
of his world became increasingly irrelevant to his target
audiences. His movies seemed too white even in the age of Vanilla
Ice and Milli Vanilli, a world transformed by ``Yo, MTV Raps'' and
the Fresh Prince. (Will Smith, however, would have been the perfect
star for a Hughes movie.) Only now are things reversing, as the
audience that grew up on his work begins making its own movies,
e.g. Adam Sandler and his Hughes-like ``The Wedding Singer.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, what's lost on them is that Hughes, maybe unlike any
other director of his generation, isn't a film-school maven. His
pictures show a bigger sphere of tributes _ accumulated matter that
he picked up from a number of sources _ than any of those by young
directors who view his movies over and over while scribbling down
scenes they want to steal. Remember, his first movies were about
men feeling middle age beading up on their receding hairlines.
Maybe he'll have to come back and show his devotees how to do it
right.
</P>
<P>
   (Elvis Mitchell is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7614. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
