<SLUG> BC-1906-QUAKE-RECALLED-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SURVIVOR RECALLS THE FURY OF GREAT SAN FRANCISCO QUAKE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICHAEL DOUGAN  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL CERRITO, Calif. _ Survivors of the April 18, 1906, earthquake
might be the rarest people around San Francisco, and Ernest Latapie
is the rarest of the rare: Not only was he alive when the city
collapsed and burned, but he remembers vividly the horror of the
moment.
</P>
<P>
   Many of those who will be participating in commemorative
celebrations this weekend were too young to understand, or even
notice, the earthquake, and have no stories to tell. But Latapie,
who turns 103 on July 20, is not among them.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, he sat down in the kitchen of his comfortable,
well-tended El Cerrito home and told his tale one more time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember when my mother came running into my room and
snatched my brother and me out into the street,'' said Latapie, who
was 10 at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Latapie said the ground was still shaking when his mother yanked
him awake at 5:13 a.m. in their Western Addition home.
</P>
<P>
   The earthquake, with a magnitude estimated at 8.3 on the Richter
scale, triggered fires that destroyed the downtown and much of the
city's residential areas. More than 500 people died.
</P>
<P>
   Latapie's parents, two French immigrants who met and married in
San Francisco, operated a bakery that was attached to their home.
</P>
<P>
   He had no idea what was going on when his mother dragged her two
offspring into the predawn chill. ``I thought it was wintertime and
a storm was brewing. I did not know it was an earthquake. I had no
knowledge of what an earthquake was,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Then, he recalled, ``A man walked up the street. He said, `Oh,
you should see the church down on the corner.' It was St. Dominic's
Catholic Church at Steiner and Bush. Both towers of the church were
down. All the walls were down.''
</P>
<P>
   While their home was intact, the brick chimney over his father's
bakery oven was cracked.
</P>
<P>
   ``The horse-drawn fire engines were coming down the street, back
and forth. All the mains were broken. They just went back to their
stations and the city was left to burn,'' Latapie said.
</P>
<P>
   Crowds were pressing into his neighborhood, scurrying to escape
the conflagration. Later that day, large swathes of San Francisco
were dynamited to make fire breaks and control the spread of the
blaze.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fire kept coming west, and my father said, `Well, I guess
we're going to be burned out,''' Latapie recalled. ``So we had an
employee load mattresses and blankets and clothing into a wagon and
we were going to be refugees. We went down and stayed in what today
is Hunters Point. That was all country.''
</P>
<P>
   Rather than sleep in the fields like many of the suddenly
homeless, the Latapie family managed to rent a house there for a
week.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father, after the fire was out, brought us home,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Their house was still standing.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the meantime, he was baking bread for the refugees,''
Latapie said. ``I remember lines about a block long waiting to get
a handout of a loaf of bread for each one.''
</P>
<P>
   For Latapie and his friends, the ruins of San Francisco were a
place for adventure and entrepreneurism.
</P>
<P>
   ``Market Street was all ruined,'' he said. ``At my age, Fillmore
Street was the new main street of San Francisco. A few kids in the
neighborhood and myself went to Chinatown for souvenirs that we
could sell. The city was under martial law and anyone caught there
would be fired on. Several times the soldiers would shoot at us.
They didn't hit anything. They probably were just scaring us.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would sell these Chinese cups and things on Fillmore Street
out of a barrel,`` he said. ``Naturally, at my age, we were trying
to make a few dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, Latapie's family moved to Emeryville, on the
east side of the San Francisco Bay. He has lived in there since,
and in his current home 50 years.
</P>
<P>
   Latapie went on to serve in the Navy during World War I, to work
as a pharmacist for 20 years, then as a real estate broker and
finally, for 35 years, as owner of the Golden Bear Motel in
Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   His wife of 20 years, Lucille, died of breast cancer. They had
no children.
</P>
<P>
   Latapie frequently visits San Francisco. ``As I go over there on
the bridge, it's hard for me to fathom that in my early days it was
all in ruins,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
