<SLUG> BC-DNA-FREE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DENNIS FRITZ IS COMING HOME AFTER 12 YEARS IN PRISON FOR A MURDER
HE DIDN'T COMMIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MALCOLM GARCIA  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   After serving 12 years in an Oklahoma prison for a murder he
didn't commit, Dennis Fritz is coming home. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I was told before I went into the courtroom today (Thursday)
that I was going to be released,'' Fritz said in a phone interview,
``but I didn't want to get my hopes up until I heard it from the
judge.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fritz, who was born in Kansas City and attended high school in
Lee's Summit, plans to return to the area next week. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Equally excited was his daughter, Elizabeth, who was 13 when he
was sent to prison. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels great to have my dad back,'' she said. ``I never had
a dad growing up. I want to spend a great deal of time with him now
so we can get to know each other again.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, in Ada, Okla., District Judge Tom Landrith
dismissed the murder charges against Fritz and his co-defendant,
Ron Williamson. Fritz had been living in Oklahoma when Debra Sue
Carter was killed in 1982 but insisted he never knew her. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fritz, 49, had been sentenced to life; Williamson, 46, had been
sentenced to death. Both have maintained their innocence since
separate juries in 1988 convicted them in the slaying of Carter,
21, who was sexually assaulted and strangled. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fritz had trouble believing he was free. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, I'm numb. I'm still trying to get used to it. It
hasn't sunk in yet,'' Fritz said Thursday night by phone from his
Ada motel room where he was staying with his mother and daughter.
``I'm just going through the process.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fritz was represented by Barry Scheck, a former O.J. Simpson
attorney and co-founder of the Innocence Project. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To release ``bitter feelings,'' Fritz worked on his case while
he was in prison. He contacted the Innocence Project four years ago
after he heard about the organization from another inmate. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a purpose by getting involved in my own case and doing
all I could to fight back,'' he said. ``But at the same time it was
like rubbing an open sore.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fritz admitted he was still angry but ``not to the point it will
negatively affect me. I may seek some kind of light counseling
though.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He is considering suing Oklahoma for compensation for the 12
years he spent in jail. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Prison is an experience I don't want to go through again,''
Fritz said. ``When you're an innocent man doing time you can't
accept your incarceration. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``A guilty man has a little easier time to accept his
incarceration and resolve some issues and move on. I couldn't do
this. I was innocent.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Williamson described how it felt to be labeled a ``sex-slayer''
in his hometown and his experience in prison. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Living on death row, I can say...there's a lot of pain and
misery,'' he said. ``That's a miserable existence.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fritz plans to live with his mother in Kansas City and ``just
relax and get my priorities straight over the next few months.'' He
is thinking of studying law and ``doing everything I can to prevent
this from happening to someone else.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fritz moved to Oklahoma when he was 17 and held several
construction jobs while he earned a teaching degree at Southeastern
State University. Before his arrest he taught science at the junior
high school in Noble, Okla. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In 1987, while he was visiting his mother to help her paint her
house, Fritz was arrested by Kansas City police and extradited back
to Oklahoma for Carter's 1982 murder. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Carter was beaten, a washcloth was stuffed down her throat and
she was strangled, possibly with an electric blanket cord. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I never knew Miss Carter,'' Fritz said. ``I heard her name on
the news. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Three months after she was killed I was questioned a couple of
times. Just routine questions. After that I assumed I was
cleared.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fritz plans to do a lot of catching up. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to get used to little gadgets,'' he said. ``It feels
very odd. We used a card to unlock the motel room. At the time I
went to prison you used a key. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``At 4:15 I looked at my watch and thought, `It's time for lock
down.' That was the time I was locked down and now I'm free.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
