<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-16 18:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1826 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REFUGEES-AID-0417-COX     04-16 0599
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REFUGEES-AID-0417-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SECURITY CONCERNS SLOWING ALLIED AIRLIFT OF AID TO REFUGEES
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-REFUGEES-0417.
 &HT;    By JOSEPH ALBRIGHT 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   RINAS AIR FIELD, Albania _ The Western airlift of food and
bedding to 100,000 refugees in the mountain town of Kukes has been
crimped in the last three days by a decision by U.S. military
commanders to ground all American helicopter flights to that area
of Albania for security reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Off the coast of Albania, 10 giant U.S. Navy MH-53E Sea Dragon
helicopters on the U.S.S. Inchon are awaiting orders to resume
flights to the swelling crowds of refugees in Kukes, the largest
single concentration of refugees just across the border from
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   But the flights to Kukes by American helicopters have been put
off indefinitely because of intelligence reports of Serb
infiltrators and the risks of having more airlifted supplies seized
by crowds of refugees and resident Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   The refugees in Kukes are still being supplied by flights on
smaller Swiss and French helicopters, as well as by truckers
weaving their way up the tortuous 10-hour road trip from the
Albanian port of Durres. While daily food requirements of the
refugees are being met so far, U.N. relief officials at the border
have been unable to build up more than a few days' stockpile in
Kukes.
</P>
<P>
   That deficiency became painfully apparent Friday as thousands of
Kosovar Albanian refugees began pouring across the border into
Albania, a result of Serbian military units beginning to clear out
the most remote mountain villages.
</P>
<P>
   The suspension of U.S. helicopter flights to Kukes is the latest
frustration for the Clinton administration in trying to get a grip
on the Kosovo humanitarian crisis.
</P>
<P>
   On April 5, the Pentagon had ordered the Inchon diverted from a
mission in the Persian Gulf. The aim was to to triple the allies'
airlift capacity to stranded Kosovo refugees in Kukes and
</P>
<P>
   elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   The Sea Dragons on the Inchon are capable of hoisting more than
50 tons of food a day to the mountain refugee camps. But the giant
helos carried only about 20 tons of supplies to Kukes before the
flights were suspended late Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as we feel comfortable with the environment, we will
fly to Kukes again,'' said Maj. Tom Dolney, a spokesman for the
allied humanitarian operation based at the Rinas Air Field.
</P>
<P>
   Around the same time, the flights of the U.S. Air Force's
special purpose Pave Low helicopters from Rinas to the Albanian
border were also cancelled.
</P>
<P>
   One factor that led to the cancellations was an intelligence
report late Tuesday that Serb infiltrators armed with
shoulder-mounted SA-7 anti-aircraft missiles may have been
positioned on an Albanian mountainside near Kukes. The suspected
Serb position was within range of the landing zone where the Navy
Sea Dragons dropped food on Sunday, Monday and Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Another factor was a concern among U.S. Navy commanders of a
repetition of Tuesday's chaotic episodes in which crowds of
refugees and local Albanians stormed onto the Navy's landing field
in Kukes and made off with more than six tons of food and sleeping
bags.
</P>
<P>
   ``Security is an important issue for us from a safety
perspective,'' the Inchon's commander, Capt. Dick Gallagher, told
reporters visiting the Inchon late Friday. ``The last thing we want
to
</P>
<P>
   do is hurt some poor innocent hungry person who is just there
trying to get a box of food or a sleeping bag.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
