<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-16 18:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1829 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-SISTERS-REVIEW-NYT     04-16 0926
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SISTERS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.C. N.Y.)  
 `HAVING OUR SAY': A MEMORABLE DELIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Broadcast notes are at end of review. Time, channel are for
New York area. Check local listings.) 
(rk) 
 By RON WERTHEIMER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If the television version of ``Having Our Say'' had been only a
vivid history lesson, that would have been enough to justify what
is clearly a labor of love.
</P>
<P>
   But this film is more, an engrossing drama built on characters
who are at once exceptional and accessible. If you've already met
the formidable Delany sisters through their books and the play they
inspired, you'll be delighted to be in their presence again. If
not, you're in for a memorable surprise.
</P>
<P>
   Sarah L. Delany, known as Sadie, a retired teacher, and her
sister A. Elizabeth, called Bessie, who had been a dentist, were
both past 100 when Amy Hill Hearth, a writer, came to their door in
Mount Vernon, N.Y., in 1991. (She had to go to their door; they
never saw the need for a telephone.)
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for Ms. Hearth, the sisters were overflowing with
memories and opinions and were willing to share them. Fortunately
for everybody else, Ms. Hearth was able to distill that cornucopia,
first into an article for The New York Times and then in what
became a best-selling book, ``Having Our Say: The Delany Sisters'
First 100 Years,'' in 1993, followed the next year by ``The Delany
Sisters' Book of Everyday Wisdom.''
</P>
<P>
   That considerable wisdom had been earned during lives that took
them to the Harlem Renaissance from Raleigh, N.C., where their
father, a former slave who became the nation's first black
Episcopal bishop, ran a school.
</P>
<P>
   Emily Mann, who adapted the sisters' reminiscences into a
two-woman play that appeared on Broadway in 1995, has now expanded
it into the film that CBS is broadcasting Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   At its center are strong portrayals of these strong women.
Diahann Carroll, playing against type and encased in a distracting
quantity of makeup, is the gentle, thoughtful Sadie. Ruby Dee, who
defies type, is the blunt-talking Bessie. ``She has trouble
forgiving and forgetting,'' Sadie says of her sister. Bessie
doesn't deny it: ``Most of the people I'm still mad at are long
dead.''
</P>
<P>
   The film, directed by Lynne Littman, moves back and forth in
time without compromising its narrative. Ms. Carroll and Ms. Dee
embody the sisters in middle and old age. Their performances
occasionally threaten to glide into caricature but more often
capture the women's complementary strengths and frailties and their
extraordinary bond.
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Arrindell Anderson is cryptically lovely in the role of
Sadie as a young woman. Mykelti Williamson and Lonette McKee convey
little more than loving nobility as their beloved parents, who
reared 10 children, instilling them with a deep pride and a deeper,
if largely unrequited, love for their country.
</P>
<P>
   The smoldering heart of the flashbacks is young Bessie, played
by Audra McDonald without a chance to display her celebrated
soprano voice. When Bessie faces down a white drunk demanding sex
and in another scene in which she tearfully chooses her career over
marriage, Ms. McDonald displays a vulnerable strength.
</P>
<P>
   There is one more central character in the film, Ms. Hearth,
played by Amy Madigan. In the books she had her say, briefly, in
introductions, and then skillfully shone the spotlight on the
Delanys. In the stage play, the audience members play the role of
the visiting stranger, as much of the dialogue is delivered
directly to them. Here, however, Ms. Mann has elected to bring Ms.
Hearth into the spotlight, too.
</P>
<P>
   This enables Ms. Mann to explore how Bessie's initial distrust
of this stranger evolves into affection. ``Once in a while God
sends a good white person to me,'' Bessie says. ``I guess it's
God's way of keeping me from becoming too mean.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Madigan is called upon to portray Ms. Hearth's own
evolution. As her nervousness around the sisters gives way to an
easy admiration, she becomes a better person by absorbing their
advice (and wearing a hat they give her). Ms. Madigan is a game
participant, but her character is a distraction.
</P>
<P>
   When she exclaims, ``To tell you the truth, you two are the most
wonderful women I've ever known,'' the effect is to underline a
point that has already been indelibly made.
</P>
<P>
   The film ends with the sisters attending a performance of the
play they inspired and accepting a standing ovation. It is
gratifying to know that these courageous women lived to receive
such tributes. (Bessie died in 1995, Sadie earlier this year.) And
it is gratifying to see their story well told again. So watch the
movie. But if you haven't read ``Having Our Say,'' find a copy.
You'll be enriched by the sisters' unadorned eloquence. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BROADCAST NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `HAVING OUR SAY' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   9 p.m. ET Sunday on CBS
</P>
<P>
   Written by Emily Mann and based on the book by Sarah L. Delany,
A. Elizabeth Delany and Amy Hill Hearth. Lynne Littman, director;
Tony Amatullo, producer; Roseanne Leto, co-producer; Preston
Fischer, supervising producer; Frank Byers, director of
photography. Produced by TeleVest in association with Columbia
TriStar Television. Camille O. Cosby, Judith R. James and Jeffrey
S. Grant, executive producers.
</P>
<P>
   With: Diahann Carroll (Sadie Delany), Ruby Dee (Bessie Delany),
Amy Madigan (Amy Hill Hearth), Lisa Arrindell Anderson (Sadie
Delany in her 20s), Mykelti Williamson (Papa Delany), Lonette McKee
(Mama Delany) and Audra McDonald (Bessie Delany in her 20s).
</P>
</TEXT>
