<HEADLINE>
TEMPORARILY YOURS 
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 18) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y., S.C.)   (af)  
 By ABBY ELLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ten years ago, I took a job stuffing envelopes. It was a
necessity: I had just graduated from college and had no idea what I
wanted to do with my life, but the lenders who had financed my
college education weren't sympathetic to my existential crisis.
</P>
<P>
   The job came through a temporary-employment agency, which paid
me $7.25 an hour to cram manila envelopes with a company's pap. I
lasted one day.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the temp world has changed dramatically. According
to the National Association of Temporary and Staffing Services,
there are nearly three million temporary employees in the United
States, up from 500,000 in 1983. Today's temps are younger (50
percent are 20 to 34 years old) and smarter (30 percent have an
associate or bachelor's degree). &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  And the Bureau of Labor Statistics says they make an average
of $10.62 an hour. Experts expect the $57 billion temp industry to
nearly double its annual revenue by 2006.
</P>
<P>
   Temporary employment has grown in part because employers are
more cautious about committing themselves. ``They want to try
people out before hiring them,'' said James Essey, president of the
Tempositions Group of Companies in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Many companies also prefer temps because they may not have to
give them full benefits, or any benefits at all. &QL; 
 &UR;  &LR; But it is not only employers who are fickle. Many young people
engage in serial workplace monogamy, refusing to enter into serious
relationships until they have sowed their corporate oats.
</P>
<P>
   ``You test each other out, like a trial marriage,'' said Georgia
Ellis, a vice president at Fifth Avenue Temporary Services in
Manhattan. ``And it doesn't look bad on your resume, because it
doesn't look like you've jumped from place to place. You have an
excuse. You're a temp.''
</P>
<P>
   Kristin Robinson, 29, has morphed into what is known as a
``permanent temp'' _ one with a long-term assignment. For the last
two years, Ms. Robinson, who is also an actress, has had a
continuing temporary position as a graphics artist, three days a
week, at Andersen Consulting in Manhattan. She freelances the other
two days from connections made at other temp jobs. The freedom, she
said, is invaluable: ``I try to be respectful and give notice, but
if I need to leave I leave. And I don't take work home.''
</P>
<P>
   Most young corporate nomads, some of whom are actors, musicians
and writers, want to focus on their ``real'' careers without having
to ask, ``Do you want fries with that?'' They thrive on the
flexibility and often use their day jobs as floating office spaces
for managing the rest of their lives.
</P>
<P>
   In a full-employment economy, the competition among temp
agencies has intensified. Many offer benefits to attract workers;
employees staying six months may be eligible for vacation pay,
child-care reimbursement and the purchase of medical coverage at
group rates.
</P>
<P>
   But the life of a temp isn't all free Krispy Kremes. Stories
abound of demeaning treatment from employers and permanent workers.
For details, check Tempslave, a magazine, or the Temp24-7 Web site
(www.temp24-7.com), where temps can vent. Temp24-7 includes ``Temps
vs. Suits,'' a game in which temps can attack a virtual boss.
</P>
<P>
   A recent ``gripe of the week'' on the Web site told of how a
group of temps were all called ``Jane'' by colleagues who didn't
feel like learning their names. Elsewhere on the site, temps posted
stories of endless dry spells with nary a job proposition.
</P>
<P>
   Cyberwrath aside, most of today's temps have strong bonds with
bosses and agencies. Some employers are so fond of their
longer-term temps that, when they take time off, other temps are
hired to stand in.
</P>
<P>
   Once displeased, temps can also request transfers. Or walk away.
Suzanne Lynn, 27, said she left a Greenville, S.C., law firm for
lunch and, angry about being yelled at, didn't come back. Her
agency understood and handed her another assignment.
</P>
<P>
   With that kind of freedom and unconditional love, temporary work
might be the wave of the future. And even envelope stuffing, now
paying $10 an hour in New York City, might be a slightly more
profitable, if not enviable, experience.
</P>
<P>
   Abby Ellin is a Manhattan writer. Her column on starting out in
the world of money will appear the third Sunday of each month.
E-mail: preludes(AT)nytimes.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
