<P>
   YUGOSLAVIA-KOSOVO CONFLICT
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-STRIKES _ WASHINGTON _ NATO spokesman were offering scant
additional information Friday regarding the bombing of a civilian
convoy in southwestern Kosovo province earlier this week, despite
demands for further explanation _ demands that at times appeared to
touch a nerve during the briefing at NATO headquarters. The
spokesmen maintained that despite the incident, the U.S.-led NATO
bombing campaign will go on. Also, that the Kosovo rebels are
apparently regaining strength. Developing. (Deans, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REFUGEES _ BLACE, Macedonia _ The numbers of Kosovar
Albanian refugees crossing the borders of Macedonia and Albania
continued to grow Thursday as Serbian military forces cleared
remote mountain towns and villages and word of open borders spread
in southern Kosovo province. Developing. (Holmes/Kunstel, Cox News
Service). WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REFUGEES-AID _ RINAS AIR FIELD, Albania _ The Western
airlift of food and bedding to 100,000 refugees in the mountain
town of Kukes has been crimped in the last three days by a decision
by American commanders to ground all American helicopter flights to
Kukes for security reasons. (Albright, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   (For Texas papers): KOSOVO-COOK _ ABOARD THE USS INCHON OFF
ALBANIA _ Like about 60 percent of the seamen and women aboard this
helicopter carrier, Navy Cook David Spencer is a Texan. When
Spencer and the 1,064 others aboard the Inchon left their home port
in Corpus Christi March 1, they thought they were heading for the
Arabian Gulf for a mine-hunting exercise. Hunting and sweeping
mines is what the Inchon does best. On April 4, the Inchon was
anchored in the Eastern Mediterranean waiting to pass through the
Suez Canal. The next day, the ship was ordered by the Pentagon to
turn around and head for the Adriatic off Albania to use its 10
giant mine-sweeping helicopters to haul food to Kosovo refugees.
(Albright, Cox News Service). WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REFUGEES-TRAIN _ BRAZDA, Macedonia _ When the Rustemi
boarded a train from inside embattled Kosovo province headed for
the Macedonia border Thursday, they thought salvation from Serbian
military forces and thuggish gangs was near. However, when the
train abruptly stopped and was ordered back they thought they were
dead. On Friday, they finally escaped and told the story of their
frightening two-day ordeal. Developing. (Holmes, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL _ JERUSALEM _ Long divided over how to share their small
land, the rift between Jews and Arabs has recently jumped
dimensions _ from space to time. (Kaplow, Cox News Service). WITH
PHOTO (mug).WASHINGTON/POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-ODD-DC _ WASHINGTON _ If you've never seen the
7,000-pound, 21-foot, sandal-wearing bronze statue of Albert
Einstein, you haven't seen one of the most eccentric attractions
Washington has to offer. The same goes for the National Museum of
Health and Medicine, which boasts an exhibit of bone fragments from
Abraham Lincoln's skull, complete with a few strands of his hair
still attached. We have an entire museum dedicated to chess,
another to dolls, and a monument erected to the survivors of the
Titanic. (The ship, not the movie.) These are the best-kept secrets
in a town that has trouble keeping anything under wraps.
(Montgomery, Cox News Service). WITH PHOTOS. EDs: MOVED Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   TAILHOOK-SUIT _ Fired CNN Tailwind producer April Oliver files
wrongful termination suit Friday in Washington. (Brief) (Sherman,
Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   FLA-FIRES _ PORT ST. LUCIE, Fla. _ Damage estimates? Drama?
Still fighting? What's happening in the rest of the state? Jenny
will visit the fire area in the morning, gather some details then
return to STUART to anchor. Feeds from Brian Crecente, Jim Reeder,
Teresa Lane, Mary Ellen Flannery.
</P>
<P>
   FLA-FIRES-FIGHTER _ PORT ST. LUCIE, Fla. _ A firefighter was up
from 9 a.m. to 3 a.m. Thursday, then most of the day Thursday
fighting fires, some of which were threatening his home. (Lane,
Palm Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   DOOLITTLE _ Eighteen of 19 surviving Doolittle Raiders hold
their first reunion at the USAF Museum since the 1960s. The raiders
flew with Lt. Col. Jimmy Doolittle on a daring daylight bombing
raid on Japan on April 18, 1942. This will be their 57th reunion. A
media availability is scheduled for Friday at the Doolittle
Raiders' B-25 exhibit in the museum. Today (Saturday) they will
hold a memorial service at the museum that will be open to the
public and will include a a flyover by the restored B-25 ``Old
Glory.'' Press release will be in tickler. (Ali, Dayton Daily
News). WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   FREAKNIK _ ATLANTA _ Main news story on Black College Reunion in
Atlanta. Criminal activity and arrests have marked previous year's
events. (Longa-Good, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   URBAN-WARGAMES _ The black helicopters, and the
specially-trained U.S. Army troops they dropped across South Texas
for 10 days in February, are gone now. In their wake, they left a
trail of tales that will be told, retold, and embellished for years
_ the soldiers rappeling into cities, the explosions, the
accidental fire, the satchel full of cash to pay for damages. And
they ignited a new round of buzz among those who consider the
helicopters symbols of government oppression or a coming one-world
order. The training exercises by the Army's Special Operations
Command, dubbed Operation Last Dance, were the latest in a 10-year
effort to give America's elite troops real-world experience in
different urban environments. And in town after town, local leaders
remain divided over whether they would invite the soldiers back for
an encore. (Harmon, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   TRUMP _ PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Hearing continues on Donald Trump's
attempt to lift restrictions on his Mar-a-Lago Club.
Preservationists and residents oppose the proposals. (Sims, Palm
Beach Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE/MEDICINEAIDS-DRUG _ FDA has approved agenerase, the
latest protease inhibitor and the first to be approved in two
years. The drug becomes the 16th to be OK'd for use against AIDS.
(Kim, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
