<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIA-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TO RETAIN POWER, INDIA'S RULERS COURT SMALLER PARTIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By CELIA W. DUGGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW DELHI, India _ For the moment, small-time politicians are
kingmakers here.
</P>
<P>
   This week the coalition government, led by a Hindu nationalist
party, lost the 18 votes of its largest partner and with them its
majority in Parliament.So the leaders of the coalition have been
engaged in hectic horse-trading and arm-twisting for the support of
small parties that will decide whether the government survives a
vote of confidence on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Om Prakash Chautala, who leads a party that has four of the 545
members of Parliament, said on Thursday that he definitely favored
the ouster of the year-old government. But after leaders of the
Hindu nationalist Bharatiya Janata Party courted his support, a
beaming Chautala announced Friday that he had changed his mind and
would support the government.
</P>
<P>
   By day's end, the arithmetic had shifted in favor of the
incumbent government, headed by Prime Minister Atal Behari
Vajpayee. Not only did Chautala return to the fold _ he deserted in
February _ but another party, with six votes, also defected from
the opposition.
</P>
<P>
   And a third party, which represents lower-caste voters,
announced that its five members of Parliament would abstain, rather
than voting against the government.
</P>
<P>
   The threat to the government was set off when the leader of a
party from the state of Tamil Nadu, Jayalalitha Jayaram, announced
that she was withdrawing her support to the government. Ostensibly
she quit because she wanted the defense minister dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   But spokesmen for the Bharatiya Janata Party said she actually
wanted the government to dismiss her rival from office in Tamil
Nadu under powers granted to the central government by the
constitution.
</P>
<P>
   The other votes that the government gained Friday were from the
party of her archenemy in Tamil Nadu.
</P>
<P>
   Jayalalitha, who set off the frenzy, talked strategy on Thursday
with Sonia Gandhi, president of the Congress Party, which now
dominates the opposition, and for most of the last half-century ran
the country.
</P>
<P>
   It was the declining power of the Congress Party, which became
calcified and unresponsive in the later years of its rule, which
contributed to the rise of the regional and caste-based parties
that now have the votes to shape who governs.
</P>
<P>
   As usual, the Italian-born Mrs. Gandhi, who married into the
Nehru-Gandhi dynasty and who in the last year has become the
unquestioned Congress Party leader , has said little publicly about
her intentions.
</P>
<P>
   If Vajpayee's government falls, she would be the most obvious
choice as the new prime minister. But she has not disclosed who
would be in a new government nor who would lead it, a reticence
that the governing coalition has exploited.
</P>
<P>
   Vajpayee told Parliament on Thursday when he opened debate on
the future of his government, ``Let the opposition tell the nation
who its leader is and what its programs will be if the government
falls.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
