<P>
   DELTA-PILOTS _ In yet another sign of poor relations between
Delta and its pilot union, the union is demanding the airline not
use regional affiliate Comair on its Northeast Shuttle operation as
planned this summer. Union leaders passed a resolution at a special
meeting on the issue. They contend any Shuttle flying should be
done by Delta crews rather than lower-paid commuter pilots.
(Thurston, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   BELLSOUTH _ ATLANTA _ BellSouth is making a bid to compete with
the national wireless companies, offering one-rate plans that
charge no extra for long-distance or roaming calls. The plans ($90
for 600 minutes and $120 for 1,000) are an implicit recognition
that the company has lost some lucrative customers to the likes of
Sprint and AT&AMP;T. (Kanell, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   INDUSTRY-RECRUITERS _ Fifteen years ago, industry recruitment
for most communities was a simple equation: cheap land plus cheap
labor equals new industry. Just how much that equation has changed
is clear watching a class of more than 100 new economic recruiters
going through a sort of boot camp this week at Georgia Tech. These
days, a community courting industry has to be concerned with its
teen pregnancy rate, high school drop out numbers and historic
preservation. (Kempner, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   WHEELS-RANGERPICKUP _ Russ DeVault test drives the Ford Ranger
pickup. (DeVault, Atlanta Jourbal-Constitution). WITH PHOTO
</P>
