A1851 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NISSAN-EARNINGS-NYT &LR;      04-16 0623
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NISSAN-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NISSAN SAYS LOSSES WILL BE WORSE THAN EXPECTED 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Nissan Motor Corp., Japan's second-largest automaker,
reported a revised estimate of fiscal-year losses Friday that were
more than three times as bad as the company had anticipated. Nissan
also eliminated the shareholder dividend for the first time since
it became a publicly traded company a half-century ago.
</P>
<P>
   The car company, which recently sold a 36.8 percent stake to
Renault SA of France for $5.4 billion, said estimated losses for
the year ending March 31 swelled to 35 billion yen, or about $294
million, compared with a projected loss of 10 billion yen it had
made earlier. The larger loss was not surprising to many automotive
analysts, who had expected such a downward revision.
</P>
<P>
   Pretax profits plunged to 15 billion yen from an estimate of 70
billion yen, and sales slid to 3.3 trillion yen from the previously
predicted 3.4 trillion yen.
</P>
<P>
   On a consolidated basis, which includes the results of various
Nissan affiliates and subsidiary companies, the company stuck to
its previous estimate of a 30 billion yen loss.
</P>
<P>
   Nissan said it would eliminate the 5 yen a share dividend it had
planned to distribute, the first time since the company's shares
were listed in 1951 that it has not paid shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   Renault released a statement saying that the new forecasts were
within the range of estimates it used in completing the deal with
Nissan, which was signed March 27.
</P>
<P>
   Nissan's official results for the fiscal year will not be
available until May but they confirmed what analysts had suspected
ever since they started seeing sales figures for the month of
March.
</P>
<P>
   March can account for one-quarter of a Japanese car company's
domestic sales in the last six months of the fiscal year, according
to analysts, and Nissan's sales were down by more than 18 percent
in the first 10 days of last month.
</P>
<P>
   It ended the month selling 15.9 percent fewer cars than it did
in the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the domestic car market was down 11.2 percent in the
year that ended March 31, and Nissan is not alone in seeing its
sales here slide. But the magnitude of Nissan's slippage has
usually been greater than that of competitors over the last year.
</P>
<P>
   Despite deflation that is keeping a damper on prices, Japanese
consumers have been reluctant to spend, fearful of job cuts and
sharp reductions in wage increases, overtime and bonuses. Many
corporations are struggling through crises similar to Nissan's and
have sharply curtailed their purchasing.
</P>
<P>
   No one outside the government clearly sees any end in sight.
Nissan's president Yoshikazu Hanawa said he expected current
economic conditions to persist throughout this fiscal year,
although he did not give any estimates for the current fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given chances that the yen will be stronger this year and with
little chance of a big change in domestic sales, I expect fiscal
year 2000 to be worse for Nissan than the one that just ended,''
said Koji Endo, an auto analyst at Schroder Securities in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   Given the bleak sales outlook in Japan, Hanawa said Nissan was
considering working to decrease production to 1.5 million vehicles
by 2003, rather than the 1.7 million target it had previously set.
Nissan currently produces 1.9 million vehicles and has excess
capacity of more than 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But Hanawa shied away from saying the company would close a
plant or production line, saying it could also merely reduce
production at various plants. Many economists argue that Japanese
companies like Nissan must reduce production capacity for the
long-term good of the economy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-16-99 1825EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
