<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-16 18:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1852 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-QUEBEC-DION-BOS &LR;      04-16 0836
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QUEBEC-DION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPERSTAR DION A TURNCOAT, SEPARATISTS SAY, FUELING DEBATE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i and e coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLIN NICKERSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ So what do you call a singing superstar whose
recordings and concerts have enthralled hundreds of millions of
people around the world?
</P>
<P>
   Not a true Quebecer.
</P>
<P>
   That's the view of one of Quebec's top separatist politicians,
whose disparaging cracks about the French-speaking province's most
beloved daughter, Celine Dion, have touched off a Titanic-sized
controversy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her songs reflect nothing of what Quebecers experience,''
Parliament member Suzanne Tremblay, one of the more prominent
leaders of the Quebec separatist movement, recently said at a
government hearing on Canadian culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``In her soul, she is neither a Quebecer nor a Canadian,''
Trembly declared in remarks that became public last week. ``Celine
Dion has become an American or universal performer.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the sort of swipe that separatists routinely take at
high-profile Quebecers who refuse to spend their days beating the
drums of secession or condemning the rest of Canada.
</P>
<P>
   But this time, it appears that Tremblay has gone a rhetorical
blast too far.
</P>
<P>
   Outrage at Tremblay's utterances is reverberating through the
province, as newspaper editorials, callers to radio talk shows,
television discussion panel hosts, and ordinary Quebecers _
separatists and federalists alike _ rally to defend the singer they
call ``our little Quebecer.''
</P>
<P>
   The 31-year-old Dion, who became fluent in English in her early
20s, is perhaps most famous for her song, ``My Heart Will Go On,''
from the film ``Titanic.'' But other recordings have kept her at
the top of international pop charts for years, and her music _ in
French and English _ is wildly popular among Quebecers.
</P>
<P>
   ``People here are so stuck on Celine,'' said Montreal music
critic Laurent Saulnier. ``They adore her.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Quebec cultural historian Frederic Demers: ``What's a true
Quebecois singer? One who sings only of snow, separatism,
lumberjacks, and spruce beer?''
</P>
<P>
   Dion is of impeccably French-Quebecois heritage, born and raised
in the French heartland community of Charlemagne, one of 14
brothers and sisters in a musical clan.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's our little girl from Charlemagne,'' said Denise Dion,
one of Celine's sisters. ``She's the little Quebecer who succeeded
on the world stage. Everyone is so proud of her.''
</P>
<P>
   Dion's first recordings and early hits were sung in French, and
even after making a commercial decision to record some albums in
English _ the only way to break into the huge American and European
markets _ she stuck steadfastly to her Quebec roots, refusing in
1990 to accept a Canadian award for ``best anglophone artist of the
year,'' since the category implied that she was an English-speaking
Canadian.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am Quebecoise, and proud of it,'' she said at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Quebecers were thrilled in 1997, when Dion made her opening
remarks in French at the Grammy Awards ceremony in New York,
thanking her original fans back in La Belle Province for her
success on the world stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``For most Quebecers, she is exporting the Quebec identity,''
said Demers.
</P>
<P>
   But not to Quebec's separatists, who control the provincial
government and are dedicated to cutting political ties with Canada.
It has long been the view of hard-core secessionists that any
Quebecer who succeeds in the English-speaking world is a sort of
turncoat.
</P>
<P>
   Although Dion last year was inducted into the Ordere National du
Quebec, the highest distinction the provincial government can
award, some separatists have never forgiven the music artist for an
offhand remark she made to reporters in 1992. Asked what she
thought of Quebec leaving Canada, she responded: ``Appalling.''
</P>
<P>
   That seems to have been the first and last political comment she
has ever made in public, but separatist memories are long.
</P>
<P>
   Tremblay, who represents a Quebec district in Canada's
Parliament, is one of the more pugnacious firebrands of the Quebec
independence movement.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Celine Dion sings in `Titanic,' she's not singing
anything'' about Quebec, Tremblay more recently told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Tremblay's criticisms have exploded into headlines across
Canada, causing huge embarrassment for the separatists, who have
been forced to hold damage-control press conferences, professing
utmost admiration for Dion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Celine Dion is an artist of international caliber, and I think
it is possible to be that and a true Quebecer at the same time,''
Gilles Duceppe, leader of the Bloc Quebecois, Tremblay's party,
told reporters this week.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, columnists in French and English media are having a
field day.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's any doubt about the nationality of Celine's soul,
just consider that she spends most of her spare time in Florida,''
wrote Finbarr O'Reilly in the National Post. ``What could be more
Quebecois than that?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
