<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-UNEMPLOY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAY STATE UNEMPLOYMENT RATE AT 2.8 PERCENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Massachusetts' unemployment rate dropped to 2.8
percent in March, as the state reached a record for the number of
residents who were working.
</P>
<P>
   The 0.1 percentage point decline last month in the jobless rate,
down from 2.9 percent in February, continues a strong period of
growth for the Massachusetts economy, according to the monthly
report by the Department of Employment and Training.
</P>
<P>
   The unemployment rate is down sharply over the past year from
3.5 percent in March 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``You wonder sometimes that it can't keep on going this good,''
said Elliott Weiner, the state's chief economist, ``but it still
seems to keep going.''
</P>
<P>
   The boom keeps going, but there is evidence of a slight slowdown
in New England. The US Bureau of Labor Statistics reported this
week that job growth in the region slowed to 1.9 percent in 1998,
from 2.3 percent in 1997. A world economic slump, which hit
manufacturers particularly hard, was blamed for more moderate
growth.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts employment levels rose 1.7 percent last year, down
from 2.5 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   In March, Massachusetts employers added a total of 7,100 jobs in
the typically strong hiring period that begins when the weather
warms. Job creation was well above the average of 4,000 new jobs a
month that has been recorded over the last year.
</P>
<P>
   In March, most of the jobs were added by business service firms
and by retailers. Retailers _ mainly furniture and general
merchandise stores and restaurants _ reported the biggest job gains
among all industries for a second consecutive month.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, a record 3.2 million people were employed in
Massachusetts last month, according to the state's survey of
business payrolls. The jobless statistics are derived from a
separate survey of Massachusetts households.
</P>
<P>
   Good news was repeated as state unemployment rates fell around
the country, with sharp declines reported in Midwestern states.
Massachusetts had the nation's seventh-lowest jobless rate, and the
lowest among the 11 largest states.
</P>
<P>
   The only sector in Massachusetts that reported fewer jobs were
manufacturers, which shrank their payrolls by 700 jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Breimyer, chief economist at State Street Corp. in Boston,
said that he believes the worst is over for manufacturers, which
were hit by a slump in demand for their export goods in markets
from Jakarta to Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   With Brazil's troubles now apparently contained, manufacturers
problems are ``abating,'' Breimyer said. ``The maximum impact has
been registered, and it doesn't look like there will be negative
impacts going forward.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he added, ``You're not going to see a lot of vibrancy in
this sector.''
</P>
<P>
   All other sectors reported strong gains: Retailers added 2,800
jobs in March; services grew by 2,700 jobs, with 2,200 of those in
business services; construction gained 1,700 jobs in its ninth
consecutive monthly increase; and the financial and real estate
sector added 500 jobs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
