<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-16 18:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1857 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DRAGGING-DEATH-2TAKES     04-16 0908
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRAGGING-DEATH-2TAKES-$ADV18-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLUES OF BIGOTRY DON'T SURFACE IN DRAGGING DEATH DEFENDANT'S PAST 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (For release, Sunday, April 18, 1999) 
 
By ALLAN TURNER 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COOPER, Texas _ Russell Brewer never was the pride of Delta
County. He was a high school dropout, a layabout who swilled beer
atop a town water tank with his buddies and an inept burglar who
targeted the homes of his own relatives.
</P>
<P>
   Many considered Brewer the bad seed of a good, hard-working
Christian family, an affliction to his many kinfolk who populate
the hardscrabble country between the North and South Sulphur
rivers.
</P>
<P>
   But last summer's accusation that Brewer had joined ex-cons Bill
King and Shawn Berry in dragging a black man, James Byrd Jr.,
behind a pickup to his death startled most people in this tiny
Northeast Texas farm town.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought his chance of becoming a productive citizen
was too bright,'' said former sheriff's investigator Gary Thompson.
``But I was surprised that he got into trouble of such magnitude.''
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors contend Brewer, 32, played a key role in what is
arguably the most monstrous crime in recent Texas history.
</P>
<P>
   On the evening of June 7, they say, Brewer, his old prison
friend, King, and King's longtime buddy, Berry, accosted the
intoxicated Byrd as he walked along a Jasper street. They then beat
him, chained him to a pickup and dragged him. Byrd was decapitated
when his body struck a culvert.
</P>
<P>
   Brewer's DNA was detected on a cigarette and beer bottle found
at the crime scene. Byrd's blood was found on his shoe.
</P>
<P>
   With the approach of Brewer's May 17 capital murder trial in
Jasper, residents of Delta County are puzzling openly about how the
seemingly pensive, dark-haired, dark-eyed man could be implicated
in such unspeakable cruelty. Though Brewer's previous scrapes with
the law were numerous, they never were violent nor, apparently,
racially motivated.
</P>
<P>
   Like much of Texas, Delta County has a history of racial
violence. In 1913, a black man accused of murdering a white girl
was pulled from a courtroom and lynched on the town square. But in
recent years, race relations have been good. Delta County, one of
the state's smallest and poorest, is 90 percent white.
</P>
<P>
   ``Russell didn't hate blacks,'' said his maternal aunt, Carol
Gillham. ``We've never had any KKK in this family. We had blacks in
this family. Russell's cousin married a black man. They had two
kids. Russell married a Hispanic. They had a son.''
</P>
<P>
   Brewer's father, Lawrence Russell Brewer Sr., who brought his
wife and five children back to his native county when he retired
from the Army in the late 1970s, has commented that his son was
reared in a cosmopolitan military setting, associating with people
of all races since infancy. If Brewer learned hatred, the older man
said shortly after his son was arrested, he didn't learn it at
home.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall Roberts, the black concrete worker who for seven years
was married to Brewer's cousin, said the accused killer betrayed no
racial hostility at family gatherings or during chance encounters
on the street. Sylvia Nunes of Fort Worth, Brewer's wife of five
years, has declined to comment about her ex-spouse. But her mother,
Marina Nunes, told The Dallas Morning News that Brewer seemed
racially tolerant.
</P>
<P>
   Brewer, himself, eschewed racism when he first was processed
into state prison 12 years ago, telling authorities he had no
objection to sharing a cell with an African-American. By the time
he was released from the Beto I unit in the summer of 1997, though,
prison gang experts suspected Brewer had allied himself with white
supremacists.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors contend that Brewer and Bill King _ who was
convicted of Byrd's murder in February and sentenced to die _ were
members of the Confederate Knights of America, a KKK-related prison
gang. Upon being released, prosecutors said, they planned to form a
``free world'' chapter _ Texas Rebel Soldiers _ in Jasper, and
Byrd's murder was meant to attract recruits.
</P>
<P>
   Sheriff Benny Fisher, who grew up with Brewer's father in rural
Delta County, described the accused killer as ``just a country
boy'' and recalled nothing in his background that could engender
violent racial hatred.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Lawrence Brewers were a good family,'' he said. ``They
went to church. They weren't mean to the kids. ... Brewer had to
pick up (the hatred) in prison. When the boy went off to prison, he
fell in with the wrong gang. It destroyed his life as well as his
parents' lives.''
</P>
<P>
   The crime Brewer allegedly committed in Jasper, he said, ``was
worse than crucifying Jesus.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who recalled Brewer from his teen-age years in the Delta
County hamlet of Klondike, remembered an uncommunicative youth,
more feckless than malign.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was one of the loners,'' said Sam Fall, Brewer's high
school physical education instructor. ``He wouldn't say a word.
You'd never see him smile. I've watched kids for 30 years. He
seemed unhappy.''
</P>
<P>
   An unremarkable student who excelled in nothing, Brewer was ``a
guy who didn't stand out in your mind,'' said Cooper school
Superintendent Fred G. Wilkerson. Brewer, who dropped out of school
in the 11th grade, wasn't even a memorable discipline problem,
Wilkerson said. ``There was certainly no indication that he someday
would commit the most despicable act in history.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(MORE)
</P>
<P>
   Klondike residents said Brewer and his friends plagued the
community of 135 with petty crime. Once, the youths stole parts
from a vehicle on a used car lot, the owner contended. Sometimes
the criminally inclined teens perched on the Klondike water tank to
drink beer.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wasn't a real bad one,'' added former sheriff's deputy Glen
Stone. ``He was just another one who had too much time on his
hands. He was one of those into drugs _ marijuana _ and then he
started doing burglaries.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time of his first arrest in the fall of 1986, Brewer had
been linked to as many as 16 burglaries, many of them poorly
planned, almost desultory adventures in lawlessness.
</P>
<P>
   Often, Brewer and his accomplices targeted acquaintances or even
family members.
</P>
<P>
   Brewer occasionally expressed remorse for his crimes. ``I know
what I did was wrong,'' he told authorities after he was
apprehended for burglarizing the home of a relative. ``I'm sorry
for what I did and want to get right with the law.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm certain that he was sorry that he was in the situation he
was in,'' Delta County District Attorney Frank Long observed dryly.
</P>
<P>
   Brewer began serving a seven-year sentence for burglary in
summer 1987 at the Hilltop prison in Gatesville. Brewer was paroled
in February 1988, but returned to prison in May 1989 with a 15-year
sentence for possession of cocaine in Scurry County in northwest
Texas. Paroled in May 1991, he returned to prison a second time in
February 1994 for a technical parole violation such as failing to
report to his parole officer.
</P>
<P>
   Brewer was released from prison a final time in September 1997.
</P>
<P>
   During the slightly more than seven years he was locked up in
county jails or state prisons, Brewer was cited no less than seven
times for violating regulations. While held in the Beto I Unit at
Tennessee Colony, where he met Bill King, Brewer received ``major
punishments'' for refusing to work, being absent from his assigned
location and participating in a riot.
</P>
<P>
   Brewer's 1997 release under the state's mandatory supervision
program warranted the highest level of supervision, said Emmer
Gray-Mallard, a pardons and paroles spokeswoman. Had the Paris
parole office that was assigned to his case possessed the
equipment, Brewer would have been subject to electronic monitoring.
</P>
<P>
   Brewer's father declined to be interviewed for this story. ``I
just can't stand it anymore,'' he blurted in ordering a reporter to
leave his Sulphur Springs home. But last year, in a brief interview
with the Houston Chronicle, he admitted he had been appalled when
his son visited him after his last release.
</P>
<P>
   The younger man's arms and body were covered with prison
tattoos, including Nazi ``SS'' lightning bolts and a KKK emblem.
The elder Brewer advised his son that such adornment was ``a
sickness,'' and the ex-con departed in a huff.
</P>
<P>
   The next development in Brewer's story reveals how deeply his
life is rooted in Delta County.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lawrence Brewer,'' said Sheriff Fisher, ``took up with my
son's ex-wife.''
</P>
<P>
   For several months, Brewer lived with Tammy Perritt and her
young children and another woman, Kara Pruitt, in a battered mobile
home in the Hopkins County community of Como.
</P>
<P>
   Perritt and Pruitt declined to be interviewed, but in an earlier
interview with the Beaumont Enterprise, Pruitt described Brewer as
a ``loving'' individual who took good care of Perritt's children
and expressed no racist feelings.
</P>
<P>
   In late spring 1998, Como Assistant Police Chief Donald Meeks
made what he thought was a routine traffic stop.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the wheel was Lawrence Russell Brewer.
</P>
<P>
   ``He seemed extremely nervous,'' Meeks recalled. ``I asked him
why he seemed so anxious, and he said that he was just out of the
penitentiary and he was nervous around police.''
</P>
<P>
   Suspicious, Meeks asked, and was granted, permission to search
the car. ``We searched it bumper to bumper for drugs or weapons,
but it came up clean,'' he said. ``It looked like he had all his
earthly possessions in there, everything very neatly stacked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tammy had told me that she was kicking him out of the house
because he wouldn't work, so I wasn't too surprised. I asked him
where he was going. He said Houston. He was going to look for
work.''
</P>
<P>
   Brewer had told the same story to his father and his parole
officer.
</P>
<P>
   Whether he ever went to Houston is an open question.
</P>
<P>
   In any event, by late May, Brewer was a hell-raising resident of
a rundown apartment complex in Jasper, more than 100 miles from his
reputed destination.
</P>
<P>
   His roommate?
</P>
<P>
   Bill King.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
