<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-COSTS-$ADV18-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOSOVO BOMBING COSTS U.S. $40 MILLION PER DAY 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (For release, Sunday, April 18, 1999) 
 
By STEVE LASH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The cost of waging war, even an undeclared one, is
expensive.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has already spent nearly $1 billion in its
effort to end ethnic violence in Yugoslavia, and the price tag is
rising by nearly $40 million per day, according to an independent
accounting organization in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   If White House predictions are correct that NATO's bombing
campaign could continue for several more months, the United States'
cost of the allied operation could reach $4.6 billion by mid-July.
</P>
<P>
   In just the first 15 days of the nearly month-old conflict, the
United States spent about $500 million on the military operation.
That amount has since risen to nearly $950 million, the Center for
Strategic and Budgetary Assessments reported last week.
</P>
<P>
   And if the air campaign develops into a ground war, the
mission's expense would increase astronomically, said Steven
Kosiak, a CSBA analyst. But President Clinton has continued to
state publicly that NATO has no intention of adding ground troops
to the aerial bombardment.
</P>
<P>
   To handle the operation's escalating costs, Clinton will soon
ask Congress to appropriate $3 billion to $4 billion more for the
effort, Pentagon spokesman Kenneth Bacon said last week.
Congressional sources, however, said the request could be for as
much as $6 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Armed Services Committee Chairman John Warner, R-Va., a
leading congressional hawk, voiced support for any additional money
Clinton might seek to stop Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic's
displacement of ethnic Albanians in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is essential that the Congress act on that (presidential
request) and send a strong signal to Milosevic,'' Warner said
during a committee hearing last week on NATO's Operation Allied
Force.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty members of Congress, led by the Senate's assistant
majority leader, Don Nickles, R-Okla., are on a fact-finding
mission in the Balkans this weekend to weigh the financial needs of
U.S. forces fighting in the region. The delegation consists of 10
senators and 10 House members divided evenly between Republicans
and Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon has not disclosed how much the war has cost,
leaving the accounting center to calculate U.S. expenses based on
the price of the warplanes used and the munitions expended.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the United States lost $70 million in a matter of
moments when an F-117A jet crashed March 27 in Yugoslavia, perhaps
due to hostile fire, the center said. The pilot was rescued, but
the multimillion-dollar plane was destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   The United States also has spent $220 million in missiles fired
during the Kosovo conflict. These munitions include 100 Tomahawk
land-attack missiles, at $1 million each, and 60 conventional
air-launched cruised missiles, at $2 million a piece.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, CSBA estimated that a total of 600 unguided
munitions were fired at ground targets during 600 of the U.S.
aircraft sorties. At a cost of $50,000 each, the United States has
spent $30 million on those munitions.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. planes also have fired an estimated $70 million in
munitions in trying to destroy Yugoslav air defenses, the center
said.
</P>
<P>
   As for the flights themselves, CSBA said the United States has
spent more than $50 million on the more than 5,000 U.S. sorties so
far, based on a rate of $10,000 per flight, and there is no letup
in sight. NATO's military commander, U.S. Army Gen. Wesley Clark,
said last week that the United States plans to send an additional
300 aircraft to the war zone.
</P>
<P>
   The cost of the air war, however, pales in comparison to what a
land invasion would cost, said CSBA's Kosiak. Depending on the
scope of the ground war, the cost could escalate from several
billion dollars to tens of billions of dollars, he said.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the United States would sustain exorbitant expenses
if NATO were to opt for a decisive ground force to oust Milosevic
and occupy a large area of Yugoslavia while facing resistance from
Yugoslav soldiers, Kosiak said.
</P>
<P>
   Even a peacekeeping force of 4,000 U.S. troops, limited to
escorting refugees back to Kosovo, would cost several billion
dollars, Kosiak said. Maintaining that peacekeeping force in Kosovo
would cost about $1 billion annually, he said, noting that the
United States is spending about $2 billion per year to support
9,000 peacekeepers in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   But predicting the cost of a military campaign is difficult,
especially with regard to Yugoslavia, where the issue of whether
ground troops will become involved has not been resolved, Kosiak
said.
</P>
<P>
   Clark, the NATO military leader, conceded last week that the
financial cost of Operation Allied Force would be high. But he
added the costs of the air campaign ``will be far more substantial
for Yugoslavia.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
