<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-16 18:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1863 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MISSING-ATHEIST-$ADV1     04-16 1213
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISSING-ATHEIST-$ADV18-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MISSING ATHEIST ONCE COMPLAINED OF POLICE BIAS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, April 18)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN MacCORMACK  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Shortly before vanishing in September 1995,
atheist leader Madalyn Murray O'Hair sent an angry letter to her
followers about her troubles with the Austin Police Department and
with a former employee, David R. Waters.
</P>
<P>
   Waters, 52, had just plead guilty to stealing $54,400 from
O'Hair's atheist organizations the year before. He is now a prime
suspect in her disappearance.
</P>
<P>
   In a lengthy essay in the July 1995 edition of the American
Atheist Newsletter, O'Hair accused law enforcement officials in
Austin of bias against atheists in their handling of the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Mr. Waters had stolen this amount of money from any church,
or had invaded the home of any minister, he would have been
arrested within hours, tried and convicted within days, and would
even now be serving a term in the Texas state penitentiary,'' she
wrote.
</P>
<P>
   O'Hair had risen to prominence more than three decades ago in
the wake of federal court battles to remove prayer and Bible
reading from public schools. She later ran a cluster of atheist
organizations in Austin with her two adult children _ Jon Garth
Murray and Robin Murray O'Hair.
</P>
<P>
   In the years since O'Hair's disappearance, similar complaints of
police indifference have been raised by other atheist leaders and
O'Hair's surviving son, William Murray.
</P>
<P>
   The Austin police, however, discount any bias against atheists
and say they thoroughly investigated the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is regrettable that William Murray feels the way he does.
Austin Police Department detectives have put forth a great deal of
time, effort and energy into locating his family members,'' the
department said in a written statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Murray-O'Hairs were not reported missing for a year after
their initial disappearance, and evidence indicated they were in
San Antonio after they left Austin. No evidence of foul play in
Austin was ever uncovered,'' the statement said.
</P>
<P>
   O'Hair's angry newsletter came two months before she and her two
children disappeared after spending a month in San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   They vanished hours after picking up $500,000 in gold coins
purchased with atheist funds transferred from New Zealand. All
three are presumed dead, although no bodies have been found and no
one is charged with any crimes related to their disappearance.
</P>
<P>
   However, Waters is currently being held in lieu of bond on a
federal firearms offense, and the FBI is actively investigating him
as a suspect in the O'Hair case.
</P>
<P>
   Waters began working for O'Hair as a typesetter in February
1993. O'Hair's last newsletter provides a lengthy, if one-sided,
account of what went wrong after Waters was promoted in January
1994 to manage the office of American Atheist General Headquarters
in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Waters was a good worker, steady and reliable. He learned
quickly and seemed to manage office routines well,'' noted O'Hair
in explaining the promotion.
</P>
<P>
   When O'Hair family members traveled to San Diego to defend
themselves in a lawsuit in March 1994, Waters was left in charge
and also had keys to the O'Hair home.
</P>
<P>
   But when the three returned in early April, the staff had been
laid off, the office was closed and Waters was gone, leaving behind
only a cryptic message on an office answering machine, according to
the O'Hair letter.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had quit because he `could no longer tolerate the mystique
of the organizations,''' she wrote. The $54,4000 soon turned up
missing from atheist accounts and was traced to checks Waters had
written to himself. In May 1995, Waters pleaded guilty to stealing
the money.
</P>
<P>
   Despite prior convictions for murder, battery and forgery,
Waters was sentenced to 10 years' probation and was ordered to make
restitution to the atheists.
</P>
<P>
   O'Hair thought the punishment was inadequate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Waters has not even been asked what he did with the money,
or if he has any left. Now, if you stop and think about this deal,
wouldn't you be willing to get about $55,000 in cash and pay it
back in ten years at $500 a month with absolutely no interest?''
O'Hair wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ``After ... the judge declined to issue a restraining order
against Mr. Waters, although several of his `priors' involved
physical violence, it was decided that a seven-foot steel-link
fence must be erected around the General Headquarters building and
land,'' she noted.
</P>
<P>
   Waters has repeatedly denied any knowledge of the O'Hairs' fate.
He believes they are probably hiding overseas, living off funds
siphoned from atheist accounts.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For most of the past three years, the Austin Police have
subscribed to the same general theory, assigning a young detective
to the case, and treating it as a voluntary disappearance.
</P>
<P>
   Even after information was published last summer suggesting a
kidnapping and murder and another source provided specific leads
and names to the police, the department was unmoved.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing indicates foul play. There's nothing to indicate to me
they would not be alive. They are just missing,'' Sgt. Steve Baker
said in January. Baker worked the case until late last year.
</P>
<P>
   While critical of the police, William Murray doubts any
philosophical bias.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue was not my mother's atheism. She was just not a nice
person to deal with and I believe a lot of the indifference on the
part of the Austin police was a policy of good riddance,'' Murray
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Very early on I sent a fax to the police chief, asking her to
reassign the case. I got back a flippant response from some
underling saying that the most competent officers were involved,
but in fact the matter was being handled by someone who
investigates 14-year-old runaway juveniles,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In her last newsletter, O'Hair said the police were indifferent
to a series of disturbing events at American Atheist General
Headquarters in Austin in early 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The problems included the theft of a computer loaded with
proprietary files, the theft of $60,000 in bonds from an office
safe, and the embezzlement of $54,400 to which Waters later pleaded
guilty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, the police did nothing; the Murray-O'Hairs alone
traced Mr. Waters' every step and reported it to the police, piece
by piece,'' O'Hair wrote of the investigation of Waters.
</P>
<P>
   David Travis, an O'Hair employee, confirmed the account.
</P>
<P>
   ``The police were given all the particulars by the
Murray-O'Hairs. I forget what all they took down there, bank
records, canceled checks, but there was no doubt whatsoever who had
written and cashed all those checks. David had done it himself,''
Travis said.
</P>
<P>
   ``And the police didn't even bother to pick him up. He lived in
the same apartment then, and I was very surprised when he went down
and turned himself in,'' Travis said.
</P>
<P>
   The police, however, say they acted quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``The theft was reported April 9, 1994. Waters was charged with
theft by appropriation ... on April 13, 1994, when a warrant was
issued for his arrest. He turned himself in on April 29, 1994,''
the police statement said.
</P>
</TEXT>
