<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-16 18:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1866 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ALBANIA-REFUGEES-2TAK     04-16 1020
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALBANIA-REFUGEES-2TAKES-$ADV18-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALBANIA THROWS OPEN HOMES, WALLETS AND HEARTS TO REFUGEES. &HT;     

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (For release, Sunday, April 18, 1999) 
 
By DUDLEY ALTHAUS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   TIRANA, Albania _ As a solitary voice intones prayers to Allah,
Umer Hoxha joins about 30 other worshipers on the mosque floor,
touching his nose and forehead to the carpet, submitting himself to
the will of God.
</P>
<P>
   ``God is great,'' the muezzin sings in staccato Arabic, as Hoxha
and 30 other men go through their late-afternoon prostrations.
``God is great.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoxha, a Kosovar refugee, has much to relinquish to God's
wisdom.
</P>
<P>
   Though he, his wife and three children have reached safety,
Hoxha has no idea when they will be able to return to Kosovo. He
has no idea what has become of his home. He has no idea what has
happened to many of his friends, relatives and neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   Still, like thousands of other ethnic Albanians who have fled
Kosovo over the past three weeks, Hoxha, 45, says he has reason to
be thankful. He and his family found refuge in the basement of a
small mosque tucked into a working-class neighborhood shortly after
they arrived in the Albanian capital.
</P>
<P>
   For three weeks now, the mosque has provided Hoxha's family and
23 other Kosovars with food and clothing, putting a financial
strain on the hand-to-mouth congregation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will remember the mercy of these people for a long time,''
Hoxha says, as he and other refugees sit talking on the thick
carpets and mattresses in the basement of the mosque. ``We will
remember this kindness our whole lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Across Albania, a poor, disheveled country that is still
grappling for an identity eight years after the fall of its
hard-line communist regime, people have thrown open their homes,
wallets and hearts to the flood of refugees.
</P>
<P>
   About 60,000 of the estimated 300,000 Kosovars who have poured
into Albania since the bombing of Yugoslavia began on March 24 have
found refuge in tent cities and makeshift shelters set up by NATO
forces and private relief agencies. But four times that number have
been taken in by mosques, churches and families across the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are Albanians, and we are assisting them through
difficult times,'' says Hamet Balla, a clergyman at the mosque
where Hoxha and his family are staying. ``We are all one nation. We
have heard from our grandfathers _ and now we are seeing with our
own eyes _ that Serbia is the cruelest enemy of the Albanian
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Most Albanians, like the vast majority of Kosovars, are Muslim.
Yet the help offered to the newcomers cuts across religious lines,
many say.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one cares about religion. People don't even ask,'' says
Muharrem Loxha, a 45-year-old window-maker from the Kosovo town of
Peji. Loxha, a Muslim, is living in the Tirana apartment of an
Orthodox Christian along with his wife, three children and 17 other
refugees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Christians or Orthodox or Muslim, we are all Albanian,'' Loxha
says.
</P>
<P>
   Some Albanians say that the refugee crisis has galvanized their
country of 3.3 million people. Many of those providing refuge to
the Kosovars say they are motivated both by a sense of charity and
by a patriotic desire for a ``Greater Albania,'' which would unite
ethnic Albanian communities across the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   ``These people are our brothers,'' Eduart Emiri, an 18-year-old
student, says of the refugees, as he performs volunteer work in the
kitchen of a camp set up for the Kosovars outside Tirana. ``We hope
that someday Kosovo is part of Albania again.''
</P>
<P>
   That dream is shared by many Kosovars and feared by Albania's
neighbors. It is the sort of dream that has kept the region in
turmoil for centuries.
</P>
<P>
   Fear of Albanian nationalist aspirations has apparently played a
part in the harsh treatment of Kosovar refugees in neighboring
Macedonia. Ethnic Albanians account for as much as 30 percent of
that country's population of about 2 million people. Some people in
Macedonia fear that hundreds of thousands of Kosovar refugees could
tip the scale in the Albanians' favor.
</P>
<P>
   For now, though, the resurgence of nationalism in Albania has
taken a back seat to the problem of handling the crush of refugees.
Already the poorest country in Europe with a per-capita income of
$830 a year, Albania must find a way to absorb a flood of newcomers
equal to a 10th of its population.
</P>
<P>
   Relief officials warned Friday that tens of thousands of
additional refugees could cross the Yugoslav border this weekend
because of a renewed Serbian offensive in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   NATO governments and aid agencies have been providing shelter,
food and other basic necessities to Kosovars living in refugee
camps. But proposals to give food rations and cash subsidies to
Albanians who have taken refugees into their homes remain in the
discussion stage.
</P>
<P>
   The refugees' Albanian hosts are largely on their own, at least
for now. And because many Kosovar families do not want to be
separated, Albanians who open their doors to the refugees often
find 10, 15 or 20 strangers living in their homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is our duty to share what little we have with those who
need it,'' Balla says.
</P>
<P>
   Since communism collapsed in Albania in 1991, the transition to
a free-market economy has been frenetic.
</P>
<P>
   As investment money poured in and Albanians went on a buying
spree for consumer goods, economic growth averaged 10 percent a
year for much of the decade. But feckless government policies,
rampant corruption and the collapse of pyramid investment schemes
that promised interest rates of 60 percent or more a year combined
to scuttle the good times.
</P>
<P>
   The economy crashed in early 1997, bankrupting many Albanians
and sending a wave of desperate job seekers sailing for Italy and
other countries.
</P>
<P>
   An economic recovery is under way, but unemployment has hit 30
percent, and even good jobs pay less than $5 a day. Many Albanians
eat only because of money sent home by relatives working in other
European countries or in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   And now come the Kosovars. &QL; 
 &QL; 
(MORE)
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be hard,'' says William Garvelink, an official
with the U.S. Agency for International Development who is directing
the organization's relief efforts in Tirana. ``You add this many
people into a country, the entire social infrastructure _ not to
mention the physical infrastructure _ is overloaded.''
</P>
<P>
   Carried from the Yugoslav border in buses, flatbed trucks and
farm wagons pulled by tractors, Kosovar refugees bounce over
Albania's deeply potholed roads, past gutted factories, fallow
fields and half-built villas whose owners went bust in the 1997
crash.
</P>
<P>
   Like Easter eggs hidden in a yard, small concrete bunkers pepper
the hillsides and pastures. The former communist government,
fearing invasion from a host of real or imagined enemies, ordered
700,000 of the bunkers to be built.
</P>
<P>
   Skeletons of hundreds of cars, the casualties of Albania's early
fling with modern consumerism, flank the road that links the border
to Tirana.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the vehicles were smashed in accidents. Forbidden to own
cars under the communists, most Albanians only recently learned to
drive, and traffic remains dangerous and chaotic.
</P>
<P>
   But most of the cars lining the road were simply abandoned.
After the collapse of communism, motion-craving but cash-poor
Albanians bought up Europe's jalopies. When those cars broke down,
their owners simply abandoned them.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Albania is swimming in a sea of Mercedes Benzes and other
luxury vehicles, many of them reported stolen in Germany and other
countries.
</P>
<P>
   The abundance of stolen cars reflects the larger problem of
organized crime. The country is rife with gangs, many of them based
on old clan relationships that re-emerged after the fall of
communism.
</P>
<P>
   Crime is considered such a problem that U.S. troops taking part
in the refugee relief operation at the Tirana airport have been
restricted to their base.
</P>
<P>
   How the refugees will ultimately affect Albania depends on how
long they stay and on how much international help is sent, some
experts says.
</P>
<P>
   Valdete Sala, the program manager of a Tirana foundation, says
the influx of refugees has created ``such an emergency, that all we
can do is react to it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No one is thinking about what will happen tomorrow,'' cautions
Sala, whose organization funds projects aimed at strengthening
civil society. ``To take in seven people or 15 people _ no family
in Albania can do that for a long time. This will have a great
impact.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the talk of unity, Albania remains sharply divided
between people living in the northern mountains and those residing
along the coast and on the central plains. Social tensions have
been stoked since 1991 by the migration of hundreds of thousands of
northerners to Tirana and other Albanian cities.
</P>
<P>
   Garvelink and other foreign relief officials warn that unless
the Albanian people receive aid along with the refugees, the
current charitable mood could turn bitter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to look for all the world that the refugees are
getting everything,'' Garvelink says.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some Albanians express hope that the refugee crisis will
force many people here to re-evaluate their lives and change their
country for the better.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now is the resurrection of Albania, both spiritually and
culturally,`` says Pellumb Vorpsi, a music composer and a prominent
member of the mosque where Umer Hoxha and other Kosovar refugees
are staying. ``If people believe in God, all the other problems
will be resolved.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
