<HEADER>
A1868 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZ-PROFILE-MARTINEZ-     04-16 0989
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-PROFILE-MARTINEZ-ART-$ADV18-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEPPING BACK, TO GO FORWARD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Mass., N.Y.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 18)  
 (af)  
 By JULIE FLAHERTY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   STOUGHTON, Mass. _ In 1998, the National Basketball Association
players were locked out and buyers of athletic shoes went on
strike. Hurt by changing fashions, foreign recessions and the job
dispute that gave the league's shoe spokesmen a collective bad
name, shoemakers saw their earnings plunge. As a result, Reebok,
for one, lost more than half its stock market value last year.
</P>
<P>
   So in December, Reebok called in its ace: Angel Martinez. He had
pulled Reebok out from Nike's shadow in the 1980s, when he created
the aerobic-workout shoe. And as chief executive of Rockport,
Reebok's street shoe subsidiary, the last four years, he even
managed to convince younger shoppers that their grandfathers'
clunky brown shoes could be sexy.
</P>
<P>
   Now Reebok is waiting to see what magic Martinez, as its new
marketing director, can create for its flagship brand. Should he do
well, he could position himself to eventually succeed Paul Fireman
as chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez says he wants to put the humanity back into Reebok and
its products. Instead of sitting grimly at computers, he says,
employees should spend more time jamming, both on the company
basketball court and in a company jazz band he hopes to revive.
</P>
<P>
   He talks of making customers feel good not only about their
shoes, but also about the workers who made them _ under more humane
conditions than past industry practice _ and of the benevolent
athletes who promote the products. While some analysts say Reebok's
foreign factories treat workers better than most in those
countries, some human-rights groups call for far higher wages.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez, from Reebok's headquarters in this suburb south of
Boston, announces the end of the hype. ``Yes, we did go through
that period where you had to have the athlete with the giant
contract slam-dunking in the NBA or doing incredible things in the
Olympics to sell any shoes,'' he said. ``And that's not who we
were. All we're doing now is going back to our roots.''
</P>
<P>
   Way back. It is hard to remember when this corporate giant was
not spending more than $140 million a year on advertising,
promoting gimmicks like shoes that inflated. But if there's a model
for the down-to-earth company that Reebok now strives to be, it is
Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   A 43-year-old with close-cropped dark brown hair and a goatee,
he wears a collarless dress shirt and a pair of the black Rockports
he helped glamorize. He spoke frankly about the mind-set that
brought Reebok to its present state.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had an industry on steroids,'' he said. ``It's been an
industry that convinced itself that the average consumer out there
was going to go from nine pairs a year of $100 shoes to 12 pairs a
year of $100 shoes. And the consumer decided that no, maybe two
pair a year was all they need.''
</P>
<P>
   No longer a strong challenger to Nike _ which has about 45
percent of the athletic footwear market, to Reebok's 10 percent _
the company is depending on its new chunky DMX design for serious
runners, a strong seller since it was introduced last year. But
even as he discusses its virtues, Martinez freely acknowledges that
the garish blue-and-chartreuse DMX in his hand is no thing of
beauty.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first reaction was: `boy, that is ugly,''' he said. ``But
you know what happened? It happened for the Volkswagen Beetle,
right? People buy it despite it being ugly. It feels so good that
they buy it anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street remains skeptical. John Shanley, an analyst with
First Security Van Kasper, doubts that customers are looking for
the softer side of Reebok. ``We're talking about teen-age males,
who have almost no sense of humanity,'' Shanley said. ``They are
basically looking for whatever is new, whatever is hottest.''
</P>
<P>
   Style was crucial when Martinez was a Reebok marketer in the
1980s. It was the start of the aerobics craze, and he saw that his
wife, Frankie, would rather go barefoot to class than wear
sneakers. ``She didn't want to wear bulky, ugly-looking running
shoes,'' he said. He convinced Fireman to promote a sleeker, yet
very comfortable shoe just for women, and sales took off.
</P>
<P>
   After marketing Reeboks for 14 years, he was sent by Fireman to
head up the stagnant, tradition-bound Rockport in 1994. Linda Lewi,
now Rockport's senior vice president for marketing, said Martinez
had encouraged his workers to ``get the hairballs out of the
plumbing.'' Whether it was coming up with new styles or using less
expensive materials, ``he would be the evangelist for that idea,
and really, people would want to suspend their disbelief and join
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Fireman, 55, confirmed that the Rockport success had helped
groom Martinez as his possible successor. Only one thing has
changed about Martinez in 20 years, he said: ``He gained weight. I
knew him when he was running track and field and he was skinny. Now
he's normal.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez came to America from Cuba when he was 3, to live with
his grandmother's sister in the Bronx. He remembers saving nickels
to buy a $5.95 pair of Converse Chuck Taylors and walking home on
the sides of his feet to keep the soles from getting dirty. Now he
can afford toys like a Harley-Davidson and the Fender Stratocaster
he might play in that company band.
</P>
<P>
   Still, getting employees to loosen up at a headquarters where
100 colleagues were laid off last year is another matter. But
Martinez says he's not kidding when he tells them to shun e-mail in
favor of real chat. ``People weren't talking to each other; nobody
was picking up the phone,'' he said. Pointing to his computer, he
added, ``I almost threw this thing out the window.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
