<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-16 18:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1877 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OCTUPLETS-2TAKES-$ADV     04-16 1127
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OCTUPLETS-2TAKES-$ADV18-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUSPENSE AND JOY FOR SEVEN SURVIVING HOUSTON OCTUPLETS 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (For release, Sunday, April 18, 1999) 
 
By LEIGH HOPPER 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ The pink and blue balloons and streamers in the yard
announce something special inside the southwest Houston home.
</P>
<P>
   But it's the city garbage can parked next to the curb that tells
the real tale. The 90-gallon container, so full of plastic bags the
lid won't fit on top, is bulging with empty infant formula bottles,
household trash and diapers.
</P>
<P>
   And diapers, diapers and more diapers.
</P>
<P>
   On April 8, two more of the seven surviving Houston octuplets
were discharged from Texas Children's Hospital, bringing the number
of babies at home to five: Sisters Chidi, Chima, Ebuka and Echerem,
and brother Jioke. Ikem, a boy, and Gorom, a girl, are expected
home by the end of the month.
</P>
<P>
   The story of Nkem Chukwu's grueling pregnancy, miraculous
delivery and the babies' robust survival is one of suspense and
joy.
</P>
<P>
   But ultimately it's about multiples _ in every sense of the
word.
</P>
<P>
   Twelve daily diaper changes, multiplied by five infants, equals
60. A skilled person can finish the task in about a minute, so at
least one hour of each day is occupied with baby bottoms. Eight
feedings a day times five is 40, and each feeding takes a minimum
of 20 minutes: a total of nearly 14 hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``From morning to night, night to morning,'' said the babies'
grandmother, Janet Chukwu, who takes only short breaks from infant
care to nap or shower.
</P>
<P>
   Five new cribs, store tags still attached, are lined up along
one wall of the dining room, which has been converted into a
nursery. The family is moving into a 5,300-square-foot home,
donated by the giant mortgage company Fannie Mae, in May. The home
is in League City, a suburb southeast of Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Four chairs and a sofa accommodate the steady stream of
volunteers, many of them from the surrounding neighborhood. A sign
posted on the front door tells first-time visitors, ``Please no
pictures yet. Wash your hands B/4 picking up.''
</P>
<P>
   At any given time, two or three babies are awake and sucking on
bottles, being bathed or cuddled, or getting a diaper changed.
Inside the house, all furniture is shoved against the walls as if
to make room for a large party. A newsletter from the Bellaire Area
Mothers of Multiples sits on a table, unopened.
</P>
<P>
   Yet despite the staggering task at hand, the atmosphere in the
Chukwu household is one of drowsy bliss.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never gone over there and felt frazzled or felt like it
was impossible. It's been fairly smooth,'' said next-door neighbor
Karen Fish. ``We do have times when there are two or three crying
at a time, and you just do the best you can. I've held two babies
at a time, I've seen Grandma (Chukwu) hold three at a time.''
</P>
<P>
   Chima and Chidi's arrival home was celebrated with Nigerian
religious music and a rousing blessing by the family's pastor,
Gabriel Nwuba of Bible Believers Christian Church. Chukwu, husband
Iyke Louis Udobi, her mother and friends sang and danced _ with a
German TV crew filming _ the babies, each cradled in an adult's
arms, slumbered on.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd dispersed and Chukwu, tired after spending most of the
day at the hospital, simply sighed, ``Hallelujah.''
</P>
<P>
   The babies, conceived with the help of fertility drugs, were
born Dec. 8 and Dec. 20 at St. Luke's Episcopal Hospital. It was
the first time a woman had given birth to eight living babies and
the feat thrust Chukwu and Udobi into the international spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   Chukwu, 29, and Udobi, 42, are both Nigerian-born. They married
five years ago, after Udobi met Chukwu during one of his annual
trips home to Nigeria. Udobi, who has lived in Houston more than 20
years, works two jobs as a respiratory therapist.
</P>
<P>
   Chukwu is described as a gregarious woman who loves having
people around. She was intent upon having children.
</P>
<P>
   Chukwu saw Dr. Brian Kirshon, a specialist in high-risk
pregnancies, when she was nine weeks pregnant. At that time,
doctors could see only six fetuses in her womb. She was informed
about the risks for high-order multiples, which include learning
disabilities, cerebral palsy, vision problems or death.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors offered to reduce the number of fetuses in her womb in
order to improve the remaining ones' chances of survival. The
procedure, called ``selective reduction,'' involves injecting some
of the fetuses with a drug that stops their heartbeat.
</P>
<P>
   Chukwu refused. The couple had lost triplets the year before,
and Chukwu was determined to have all the children her womb would
bear. She didn't tell her husband, who had been distraught over the
earlier loss, how many babies she was carrying. ``I needed to keep
it to myself,'' she said. ``That was the way I felt then.''
</P>
<P>
   Starting at 15 weeks, Chukwu was put on complete bed rest. For
the last month of the pregnancy, she was confined to a hospital bed
tilted at a steep angle to keep pressure off her cervix. Doctors
wanted to get the babies to 28 weeks, but she went into labor at 25
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 8, Ebuka, a girl was born. Her parents have said she is
the generous baby, because she left the womb early to make more
room for her siblings. Doctors saw for the first time there were
seven more. It was uncommon, though not unheard of, for one
multiple to be born while her siblings stayed inside.
</P>
<P>
   Chukwu's pregnancy continued. She was taking powerful drugs that
gave her daily nosebleeds. She coughed blood. All the while she
stroked her swollen belly and said, over and over, ``You will not
die, you will live. You will not die, you will live, to testify to
the goodness of the Lord, in this land of the living.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They heard everything,'' Chukwu said.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks later, an ultrasound showed one baby was being pressed
against the side of the uterus by the other siblings. The womb was
too crowded. Kirshon decided to perform an immediate Caesarean
section.
</P>
<P>
   One by one, the newborns were taken from the womb, wrapped in
blankets and handed off, bucket-brigade style, to medical personnel
who brought them to the neonatal intensive care unit at Texas
Children's Hospital. The babies were so small their combined weight
was just over 10 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   The delivery was a success, but the drugs Chukwu had been taking
prevented her blood from clotting. After the birth, she began
hemorrhaging. Kirshon told interviewers on a recent ``20/20''
special that Chukwu lost so much blood _ 12 pints _ that she nearly
died.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nearly died? Nearly died?'' Chukwu said recently. ``God saved
me. I wasn't going to die. I believed that in my soul, my heart. I
will live.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(MORE)
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   One week after the Dec. 20 delivery, the condition of Odera, the
smallest baby and the one who had been pressed against the wall of
the uterus, began to deteriorate. Her lungs never developed as
fully as the others, and on Dec. 27 she died.
</P>
<P>
   In the coming weeks, the remaining babies underwent surgeries
and fought off infections. In the medical community and in the
media, a debate raged over whether the birth of octuplets was a
miracle or a mistake, a signal that fertility medicine should be
regulated somehow.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a nightmare,'' Kirshon told ``20/20.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to see some form of control to prevent this
catastrophe. I think there has to be a lot of admiration for her,
... but it's not something that should be repeated.''
</P>
<P>
   In early January, doctors examined an ultrasound view of each
babies' brain, to look for signs of bleeding. Brain bleeding,
common among babies born so early, is a precursor to cerebral
palsy. To the doctors' surprise and delight, the infants' brains
appeared normal.
</P>
<P>
   Ounce by ounce, they began to thrive.
</P>
<P>
   Since the birth, the family has been showered with presents _ a
house, a van, $1 million in baby furniture, an unlimited supply of
infant formula and diapers. They've also been inundated with
requests for interviews, video footage and photographs. Chukwu and
Udobi turned publicity over to Chukwu's brother in Massachusetts,
who in turn looked to the McCaugheys of Iowa, who had septuplets in
1997, as a model for how to handle the media.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from brief appearances at press conferences held at the
hospital or in front of their new home, the family granted no
interviews until after a special about them aired last month on
``20/20.''
</P>
<P>
   Udobi explained: ``We refused to give interviews until our kids
were out of the woods. And our kids are now out of the woods. We
can talk to people.''
</P>
<P>
   Watching a recent broadcast, Udobi is more amused than offended
when the TV reporter says that some people believe the family has
turned the birth of the babies into a ``commercial bonanza.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think so, I don't think so. It's not commercial, ''
Udobi said. ``I have insurance, but there are some things that are
not covered. I have to take care of the kids. I don't have
scholarships yet. I have to take care of them. I work hard. I'm a
hard-working man.''
</P>
<P>
   The family has been careful about how they answer questions
regarding two troubling, or at least puzzling, aspects of their
story. In September, Udobi was charged with hitting his
mother-in-law with a chair. (In February, he pleaded no contest to
the misdemeanor and received a probated sentence.) In addition,
Udobi, who has been married twice before, was not present when the
seven babies were delivered Dec. 20.
</P>
<P>
   Those issues fueled speculation about the family's stability and
whether they could handle the tremendous job of caring for their
brood. But with Udobi playing host, offering soft drinks to
visitors, the domestic scene now is one of hospitality and
tranquility, muted by the exhaustion common to all new parents.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbor Fish, who barely knew Chukwu before the birth but is
now a central organizer of the babies' care, describes the
September assault as an out-of-character flare-up. She is the one
who called 911 at Chukwu's request after Chukwu came over that
night, upset that her husband was hurting her mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the whole incident was stress-related,'' said Fish.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know she was really distraught over losing those (triplets).
That seemed to be a priority in her life, having a child. I don't
know what caused it, it seemed out of character for Iyke. Things
like that just happen sometimes. They're very loving toward each
other. He's taking part in caring for them. I think the misdemeanor
probably was frustration on his part. It's hard to live with your
mother-in-law.''
</P>
<P>
   On a recent afternoon, while grandmother Chukwu and neighbor
Rose Okorocha looked after the infants, who now weigh a sturdy
seven or eight pounds each, Chukwu and Udobi sat holding hands in
the living room.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are excited, we are very excited. The other two will join
them in no time,'' Udobi said. ``We get sleep whenever we can. ...
God has been so wonderful to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Udobi explains that he was not present at the Dec. 20 delivery
because the Caesarean section was emergency surgery and he could
not be located in time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was at work and I was incommunicado because I have two jobs.
They didn't know where I was working that afternoon,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   So, Udobi explains, that is why he learned about the astonishing
birth when a friend reached him on the phone and told him to turn
on the television. As he watched the news on CNN, his hands began
shaking.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they got me a relief, I left,'' he said. ``Again, I
wasn't expecting the babies to be delivered. I was asking God for
(the pregnancy) to be extended.''
</P>
<P>
   From the beginning, the babies' care has combined deeply
religious and highly practical concerns. Yemi Adekunle, pastor of
Vineyard Christian Ministries International in southwest Houston,
said he ``made it a point of duty'' to visit Chukwu in the hospital
when he learned of Chukwu's decision to carry all eight babies.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing in life that God can't give to us,'' he would
pray. ``There's no problem that prayer cannot undo. There's nothing
that prayer cannot change.''
</P>
<P>
   Around 11 p.m. on the day that Chidi and Chima came home from
the hospital, Fish said she and another woman were alone in the
nursery with the babies while the rest of the family slept.
</P>
<P>
   Then the Rev. Nwuba and the Rev. Adekunle arrived. Fish said the
men went into the darkened living room where, for more than an
hour, they sang songs, read Scripture and prayed, just the two of
them. Afterward, Nwuba came into the nursery and asked for the
fussiest baby. He raised the baby up and said a prayer, then stayed
until 1 a.m. soothing the infants.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tears were just streaming down my face,'' Fish said. ``I was
just amazed. It brought to my realization that those babies have
been covered with prayer from day one, and so had Nkem.''
</P>
<P>
   Chukwu and Udobi said they are not worried about losing their
support network when they move to League City. Fish, already lining
up a second string of volunteers, is hoping friends infused with
the volunteer spirit will be willing to make the 30- to 45-minute
drive.
</P>
<P>
   Even though much of the help has come from Houston's substantial
Nigerian community, much of which is concentrated in southwest
Houston, Chukwu took note of the throngs of children and adults who
came by for punch and cookies when the family toured the new house
in March.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say they love kids,'' she said. ``I don't expect any
problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Adekunle spoke well of the future neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want to be part of their life,'' he said. ``I don't think
that should be a problem. ... (In Africa) we believe in this kind
of extended family. Those kids are blessings from God, and God will
provide for them.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
