<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-16 19:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1881 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ITALY-TELECOM-NYT &LR;      04-16 0978
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ITALY-TELECOM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TELECOM ITALIA IS SAID TO DISCUSS MERGER WITH DEUTSCHE TELEKOM 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JOHN TAGLIABUE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ Telecom Italia SpA, trying to thwart a hostile takeover
bid by its main domestic rival, Olivetti SpA, is discussing a
possible merger with Deutsche Telekom AG, Italian officials and
others close to the companies said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   An agreement is far from certain, but such a combination would
create one of the world's biggest companies, with a a stock market
value of $216 billion and annual revenue totaling $63 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The discussions, between Telecom Italia chief executive Franco
Bernabe and Ron Sommer, his counterpart at Deutsche Telekom, have
been going on for a while, but a note of urgency was injected after
shareholders foiled Bernabe's plans to deflect a $65 billion
hostile bid by Olivetti, Italy's No. 2 phone company, when they
turned out last Saturday for a shareholder meeting in insufficient
numbers for a quorum.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever form a deal might take, it is sure to be complicated.
It would be contingent, in part, on Deutsche Telekom's withdrawal
from a global alliance it has formed with France Telecom and Sprint
Corp., people close to the companies said. It would also have to be
approved by both the German and Italian governments, which continue
to hold shares in both companies, and would face close scrutiny by
the European Commission.
</P>
<P>
   The deal could also face resistance from some of Deutsche
Telekom's current partners, including France Telecom, which has a
reciprocal 2 percent stake in Deutsche Telekom, and is a partner
with Deutsche Telekom and the Italian energy utility Enel SpA in an
Italian phone company called Wind.
</P>
<P>
   Investors reacted skeptically to the talks, which were reported
Friday in The Wall Street Journal and The Financial Times of
London. In Frankfurt, Deutsche Telekom's share price was virtually
unchanged at 38.15 euros, or $40.43, while on the Milan exchange
the price of Telecom Italia rose 3 percent, to 9.88 euros, still
below the price of 11.50 euros Olivetti is offering.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said skepticism was based largely on the political
hurdles any such deal would face.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is plain there are obstacles, and they are mainly
political,'' said Robert Grindle, who follows telecommunications at
HSBC Securities in London. The Rome government, he said, would balk
at surrendering control of Telecom Italia, the former national
phone monopoly, to Deutsche Telekom, which remains 72 percent owned
by the German state. Moreover, he said, European Commission
antitrust officials would scrutinize any proposed deal closely,
``all the more so because the Italian regulatory environment is a
benign one.''
</P>
<P>
   Italian Finance Minister Vincenzo Visco said that Bernabe had
informed the Italian Treasury on Thursday of the discussions. But
Visco said any such deal would face ``notable technical problems.''
Given the German government's share in Deutsche Telekom, he said,
it would be tantamount to ``selling Telecom Italia to the German
state.''
</P>
<P>
   Italian Prime Minister Massimo D'Alema telephoned German
Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder to discuss the proposed merger, his
office said in a statement, but no details were disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   Bernabe began discussing possible deals with a range of European
and U.S. phone companies, including British Telecommunications,
Deutsche Telekom and SBC Communications Inc., not long after he
took over at Telecom Italia late last year in a management
shake-up, one person close to Telecom Italia said. But Bernabe's
assumption was that while merging Telecom Italia with a U.S. phone
company would be politically unacceptable to the Italian
government, this person said, a deal with Deutsche Telekom was
``more palatable because it is European.''
</P>
<P>
   The major concern of Italian officials, people close to Telecom
Italia said, was the potential loss of jobs and the surrender of
control over what Italy continues to regard as a strategic national
industry. To remain competitive, Telecom Italia is expected to have
to shed as many as 40,000 jobs in coming years, regardless of whom
is in control.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at Telecom Italia declined even to confirm that talks
with Deutsche Telekom had taken place. Ulrich Lissek, a Deutsche
Telekom spokesman in Bonn, said DT had no comment on any possible
acquisitions by Deutsche Telekom, which he said were fueled by the
company's announcement on Thursday that it would sell as much as
$12.7 billion in stock to finance acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   Should a deal succeed, it would go a long way to redesigning the
landscape of the European telephone business and provide Deutsche
Telekom with ammunition against its fiercest domestic competitor,
Mannesmann AG. In part because of strong competition from
Mannesmann, a steel pipe company turned phone service provider,
Deutsche Telekom's share of the German fixed-line phone business
dropped in 1998 to 76.5 percent from 81.5 percent the year before.
Moreover, Mannesmann would be a big winner if Olivetti won control
of Telecom Italia. If that happens, Mannesmann has agreed to
acquire Olivetti's current phone businesses in Italy for about $10
billion.
</P>
<P>
   To placate concerns of D'Alema's government, people close to
Telecom Italia said, Bernabe is seeking to frame a deal with
Deutsche Telekom as a merger of equals, even though Deutsche
Telekom is almost double Telecom Italia's size.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, any deal would be made contingent on a commitment by
the Bonn government to sell its remaining stake in Deutsche
Telekom, which would already be diluted by the merger with Telecom
Italia. The stock sale announced by Deutsche Telekom this week, in
which the German government would abstain, would dilute the German
government's stake to about 62 percent, Lissek said, and the
government intends further reductions. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
