<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-16 19:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1897 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BEIJING-HATCHBACK-BAN     04-16 1000
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEIJING-HATCHBACK-BAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEIJING ORDERS A VEXING DETOUR FOR HATCHBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By ELISABETH ROSENTHAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ All morning long, a steady stream of grumpy,
forlorn-looking drivers dutifully steered their cars out of the
flowing traffic on Changan Avenue, made a sweeping right turn and
landed in the far-as-you-can-see gridlock of the Second Ring Road.
</P>
<P>
   Young and old, prosperous and poor, the motorists had one thing
in common: the bad luck to be riding in a hatchback car.
</P>
<P>
   To help prepare for China's elaborate celebrations of the 50th
anniversary of the Communist state this fall, Beijing's city
planners on Thursday enacted what must be one of the world's
strangest traffic laws: a local ban on hatchbacks during daylight
hours.
</P>
<P>
   The central six-mile stretch of Changan, the central
thoroughfare that passes by Tiananmen Square, the Forbidden City,
the Great Hall of the People, and Zhongnanhai, the Chinese leaders'
housing compound, officially became a hatchback-free zone. From 7
a.m. to 8 p.m., hatchbacks will have trouble getting to the scores
of hotels, government offices and commercial buildings that line
this majestic eight-lane road.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is chaos,'' said Tian Fuhe, the driver of a hatchback
cab, who picked his way along side streets to avoid the forbidden
section of Changan.
</P>
<P>
   The new regulation also bans jeeps and station wagons. Cars must
have a trunk to pass. The new ban affects few government cars,
which are mostly sedans. But it does include some popular car
models and also, as angry commuters discovered, the omnipresent
tiny red hatchback Xiali cars, Beijing's dominant cheap taxi.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course it's terrible for my business,'' Du Ke said,
standing on a side street next to his idle Xiali, watching
competitors with sedans glide onto Changan. ``I can't take
passengers to the places they want to go. Some won't even get into
my car.''
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese government has nothing against hatchbacks. City
officials simply needed to reduce traffic on the normally congested
Changan Avenue by 20 percent to help beautification projects that
now line the street, according the Beijing Municipal Public
Security Traffic Management Bureau. Hatchbacks became the fall guy
because it happens that 20 percent of cars in Beijing are
hatchbacks, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   But Changan is the only major east-west artery in the heart of
Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   What was good for Changan proved a burden to the rest of
downtown Beijing, as drivers complained that the regulation
produced vast traffic jams on the smaller roads and pointed out
that their roundabout journeys were adding to the capital's air
pollution. ``Trunkless'' drivers who could not use the avenue found
crosstown travel times doubled on many routes.
</P>
<P>
   Government officials _ and some Beijingers _ are clearly
prepared to make sacrifices for Changan. The avenue will be the
stage for a military review and parade involving half a million
people on China's National Day, Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``This law will have a bad influence on my life, but I'll strive
to overcome it,'' said Yang Zhigang, a man in his 40s, who drives a
station wagon. ``It's an important day, and they're going all
out.''
</P>
<P>
   In the last few weeks, both sides of the avenue have been
transformed into a six-mile-long, 30-foot-wide construction site,
dotted with gaping holes, pyramids of pipes and bricks, and long
blue metal fences.
</P>
<P>
   Billboards have been dismantled according to government mandate.
Small stores and old homes have been leveled. Most of the old
sidewalk tiles, trees and curbstones have been removed, leaving
vast swaths of dusty rubble-strewn earth.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of workers from the Beijing Urban Planning Co. in
bright blue coveralls and orange baseball caps are busily sifting
dirt, spreading cement, and carting away branches and bricks from a
demolished courtyard home. Unemployed workers with pushcarts wait
to collect scrap metal as each building falls.
</P>
<P>
   The vast demolition job is the first step in a total facelift
that will widen and landscape Changan anew by October.
</P>
<P>
   With construction encroaching on sidewalks and even taking over
bike lanes, Changan's normal traffic problem has gotten worse in
recent weeks _ and that demanded an immediate and drastic solution,
some drivers said, not only because it interfered with the
renovations, but also because Chinese officials use Changan to go
to work.
</P>
<P>
   Officials defended their choice as fair: the new restrictions
cut across the vehicular class system, they said, including cars
that are expensive and those that are cheap, cars owned by the rich
and the poor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm upset, but at least I feel better that it was unbiased,''
said Yang, the station wagon driver. ``If they said Cherokees could
go on Changan but cheaper Citroens couldn't, there would be
conflicts. Companies would complain. This makes things easy.''
</P>
<P>
   Beijing car owners have grown accustomed to the city's
ever-changing driving restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   For many months private cars could drive into town only every
other day, depending on their license plate number; that ended.
Then the city announced that the most common type of van, a cheap
tinny vehicle called a miandi, could no longer drive within the
city center on weekdays; the miandi was supposedly singled out
because of its extremely polluting exhaust.
</P>
<P>
   Officials say the hatchback ban is temporary, though it might
not end ``until the end of the celebration activities'' in October.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mei banfa!'' _ ``It can't be helped!'' _ was the day's refrain
as the ban went into effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't make me happy or unhappy _ we're used to this kind
of thing,'' said Du, the taxi driver. ``It's like this: for years
you use one tool to fix something. And then you're told you can't
use it anymore. You find another way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
