<HEADER>
A1904 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WARSH-COLUMN-$ADV18-B     04-16 1254
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARSH-COLUMN-$ADV18-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO ROADS DIVERGED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, April 18, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID WARSH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Long before history books are written, there are ``lifetime
achievement awards:'' the first rough guides to events that have
transformed our lives. When the National Venture Capital
Association gave a pair of them _ only its second and third _
during its annual meeting in Boston last week, the presentation
began with a little slide show.
</P>
<P>
   While Louis Armstrong's famous voice rasped ``You're the Top,''
the projector in the darkened ballroom flashed photographs of
Boston's Peter Brooke, 70, and San Francisco's Thomas Perkins, 67.
</P>
<P>
   The choices could't have been more different _ or more
illuminating.
</P>
<P>
   There was Brooke in his tweeds and and tie. There was Perkins
sans socks with polo shirt. Perkins in his state-of-the-art
sailboat. Behind the wheel of his fancy car. With his new wife,
writer Danielle Steele. There was Brooke in his office. In his
suit. In his academic gown and overseer's top hat at a Harvard
graduation.
</P>
<P>
   These two shapers dominated the venture capital industry in its
early years in their respective states.(Who won the first lifetime
achievement award? David Morgenthaler, who galvanized the
association to push the capital gains tax cut in 1978 that ignited
the current boom.)
</P>
<P>
   Today California's economy is roughly the size of Germany's.
Massachusetts is still a small state in New England. But Boston
remains headquarters for an impressive fraction of the world's best
brains/most advanced research and development. Brooke's and
Perkins' stories show why.
</P>
<P>
   Legends of Yankee high-tech ingenuity go back to colonial days.
As the historian Daniel Boorstin says, who else ever turned stone
and ice into export crops? Railroads, telephones, and electricity
found their first funding in Boston. But a convenient point from
which to date the first glimmer of the venture capital industry
might be April 1926.
</P>
<P>
   That was when the First National Bank of Boston hired a refugee
from the Russian revolution named Serge Semenenko straight out of
the Harvard Business School. It was Semenenko who discovered in the
early 1940s that he could make money backing motion picture studios
_ a practice as profitable as it was radical.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of World War II, Gen. George Doriot was teaching a
course at Harvard Business School in what today is delicately
called ``private equity,'' the art of providing capital to
scientists and entrepreneurs in exchange for a big piece of the
hoped-for action _ a heretical idea in an age of giant
corporations.
</P>
<P>
   His gospel: know as much about the business as the entrepreneur
himself. Brooke enrolled in the course in the early 1950s, then
impetuously walked out. After graduation in 1954 and a hitch in the
Army, he headed for the First National Bank of Boston.
</P>
<P>
   It was there that Brooke learned his first lessons in high-tech
lending, staying up late at night to study the Standard Industrial
Classification Code manual in hopes of discerning which new
electronic specialties were growing and which were not. By day, he
knocked on doors of dusty warehouses where the new tinkerers were
at work, offering loans against government contract receipts
instead of personal collateral.
</P>
<P>
   Having founded a high-technology lending group at the Boston
Bank, Brooke moved briefly to Bessemer Securities Corp. in New
York, to make private investments for the Phipps familty, then
returned to Boston to do the same thing for the old Boston
brokerage of Tucker, Anthony &AMP; RL Day. In 1967, he formed TA
Associates. It quickly grew to become the largest venture capital
firm in the US.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Perkins, meanwhile, had enrolled in electrical engineering
at MIT in 1949. Afterward, he went to Harvard Business School,
graduating in 1957, then straight to California, where he went to
work for a fledgling enterprise known as Hewlett-Packard Co.
</P>
<P>
   In Cupertino, the restless Perkins launched Hewlett-Packard's
computer business in 1965, then started a business of his own after
hours, buildinng shock-proof lasers with funding from the Bank of
America. When he sold the company after a few years, he was rich.
In 1972, he and Eugene Kleiner founded Kleiner &AMP; Perkins (now
Kleiner Perkins Caulfield &AMP; Byers.)
</P>
<P>
   The 1970s were kind to TA Associates and Kleiner &AMP; Perkins; by
the 1980s, the firms were fabulous mnoney machines. Most of
Boston's venture capital industry was formed by alumni of TA (the
notable exception is William Elfers' Greylock Management Corp.,
which grew out of the Doriot branch;) Kleiner Perkins spawned a
host of imitators in San Francisco and along Sand Hill Road in Palo
Alto.
</P>
<P>
   In each case, the key was access to innovators working in
universities _ Harvard and the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology in the east, the University of California at Berkeley
and Stanford University in the west. And in the 1980s, the
communities around them looked superficially the same.
</P>
<P>
   Then California took off. The decision not to appoint Robert
Noyce to a faculty position after he graduated from MIT in 1953
turned out to have been the key _ Noyce went briefly to
Philadelphia, then in 1956 to the Shockley Semiconducter Laboratory
in Mountain View, Calif., in 1956. The future development of
semiconductors moved with him. It was in 1959 he invented the
integrated circuit, now known as silicon chip.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1980s, Brooke turned his attention overseas,
forming Advent International in 1985 to spread the techniques of
venture capital to more than 30 countries around the world. He
stopped doing deals and devoted himself to the development of an
international network self-consciously modelled on the Marshall
Plan.
</P>
<P>
   Not that Boston lost out on brains. The Internet had its early
development in Boston, at Bolt Beranek Newman and MIT's Laboratory
for Computer Science. Biotech in Cambridge got a jump on
California, thanks to Boston's teaching hospitals' proximity to
Harvard and MIT.
</P>
<P>
   But California had become the preeminent center for
manufacturing and marketing the new electronic technologies. New
England's old mill towns, which only a few years before had been
bursting with minicomputer activity, began emptying out again.
</P>
<P>
   Stanford Business School even surpassed Harvard in attracting
the very most promising students. Harvard Business School has been
preparing an onslaught to recapture its lead and last week Stanford
Business School named a new dean to cope with the threat. He is
Robert Joss, 57, a Stanford PhD who helped build San Francisco's
Wells Fargo Bank and since 1993 has headed Australia's second
largest bank.
</P>
<P>
   At the lifetime achievement ceremonies at Boston's Ritz-Carlton
Hotel it scarcely mattered. Boston was rich, California was richer,
Brooke had been honored by a dozen foreign governments and Perkins
had his wife, his boat, his cars -- and his companies. Among his
directorships: Tandem Computer, Genentech, Spectra Physics, Corning
Glass Works, Collagen Corp. and LSI Logic Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Best of all, it was still dawn in the venture capital industry,
according to Perkins. The proof, he said, was that in a business
famous for preference _ at least in its early days _ for spreading
the risk among many partners, ``Peter Brooke and I have never done
a deal together.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (David Warsh writes about economics for The Boston Globe. His
e-mail address is warsh(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-16-99 1906EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
