u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MALAYSIA-ANWAR-NYT &LR;      04-16 0840
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MALAYSIA-ANWAR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALAYSIA'S DEPUTY PRIME MINISTER GOES TO PRISON; WIFE FORMS
POLITICAL PARTY  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By MARK LANDLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia _ For 75 days, she sat in the gallery of
an austere courtroom here, bearing silent witness to the trial of
her husband, Anwar Ibrahim, the ousted deputy prime minister of
Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Anwar was found guilty of corruption and sentenced
to six years in prison. Now his wife, Dr. Wan Azizah Wan Ismail,
has been thrust into the center of Malaysia's gathering political
storm.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Anwar was arrested, I realized I had to do something,''
Azizah said in an interview here after her husband's verdict rocked
this southeast Asian country. ``If not, he would just fade away.''
</P>
<P>
   So Azizah, a soft-spoken 46-year-old ophthalmologist, formed a
political party to topple the man who has ruled Malaysia with a
tight grip for 18 years, Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad. Unlike
her husband, Azizah is not a born politician. On some days, she
confides, the crusade seems a crushing burden.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are times when the stress is unbearable,'' Azizah said,
as her suburban house echoed with the sounds of aides' chatting on
cellular telephones and two small children scampering to peer at
their mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to head this party _ my husband is behind bars _ I have
children at home,'' she said wearily. ``But there is this
tremendous overwhelming support from the people, and I think I
can't let them down.''
</P>
<P>
   Anwar's unexpectedly harsh sentence has uncorked a fresh burst
of anger in Malaysia, which has been roiled by anti-government
protests since he was charged with corruption and sex crimes in
September.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of students demonstrated on Wednesday and Thursday in
the old city, lighting bonfires, burning the flag of Malaysia's
governing coalition and clashing with red-helmeted riot troops.
About 400 students demonstrated again Friday, though witnesses said
they dispersed peacefully after 90 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Anwar, 51, has vowed to lead a campaign from his prison cell to
topple the government. But with his wife allowed to see him only
once a month, he has to rely on her to be his proxy and field
commander of the campaign against his former boss and mentor.
</P>
<P>
   Mahathir's coalition has two-thirds of the seats in Parliament.
hough many people here were outraged by Anwar's trial, Mahathir, a
73-year-old physician, still commands respect among Malaysians, who
credit him with turning this former British colony _ with its mix
of Malays, ethnic Chinese and Indians _ into a modern, harmonious
country.
</P>
<P>
   ``Moral outrage does not translate into electoral victory,''
K.S. Jomo, a political economist at the University of Malaya here,
said. ``It will be an uphill battle for Azizah and company.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Azizah acknowledged that before her husband's downfall she
rarely questioned the political culture propagated by Mahathir. In
fact, Anwar was a prime beneficiary of that system, a Muslim
student leader who rose rapidly in the party and government as the
prime minister's protege.
</P>
<P>
   ``The system worked,'' Azizah said. ``But now the flaws are so
much that you have to change things.''
</P>
<P>
   As she prepares for parliamentary elections, which are to be
held before June 2000, she is touring the country with a message _
justice, for her husband and for the dispossessed, who have
suffered through a deep recession brought on by the collapse in
Asian currencies.
</P>
<P>
   Political experts said her best chance for victory was to stitch
together a coalition of opposition parties, including the
Democratic Party, which is supported by the ethnic Chinese, and the
Islamic party. Her status as Anwar's wife cuts both ways with the
politically ascendant Muslims.
</P>
<P>
   At a mosque frequented by young supporters of Anwar, some said
Azizah was indispensable as the living symbol of their imprisoned
leader. But Mohd Fadil, a 32-year-old Muslim who designs oil
equipment, said: ``I can't see her as prime minister. In a Muslim
culture, we would choose a man.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, some experts said, Mahathir was more vulnerable now than
at any time in his tenure, both because of the fierce reaction to
the verdict and because of his health. He was just released from
the hospital after a lung infection.
</P>
<P>
   Such calculations seemed far from Azizah's mind as she talked
about consoling her six children _ five girls and a boy ranging in
age from 6 to 19 _ after their father was led down a stairwell in
the court on Wednesday and driven to a high-security prison outside
the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, they miss their father terribly and want him
home,'' she said. ``My son says he will be 20 by the time his
father gets out.''
</P>
<P>
   Azizah herself has little time to grieve. On Wednesday evening,
hours after have bade Anwar farewell, she spoke at a raucous rally
of more than 10,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   ``My husband told me,'' she said with a thin smile, `` `Don't
cry, be strong, don't be sad. It is part of the struggle.' ''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
