<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KODAK-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EASTMAN KODAK REPORTS 9.3 PERCENT EARNINGS RISE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By CLAUDIA H. DEUTSCH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Eastman Kodak Co., buoyed by six months of steady growth in film
sales, announced Friday that its net profit in the first quarter,
excluding one-time charges, rose 9.3 percent, to $259 million, or
80 cents a diluted share, from $237 million, or 73 cents. Sales
rose 6.5 percent, to $3.1 billion from $2.91 billion. The company
also said it would buy back $2 billion in stock over the next four
years.
</P>
<P>
   Investors reacted positively to the news, sending shares of
Kodak soaring $6.4375, or 9.67 percent, to $73.
</P>
<P>
   The delighted reaction was a bit startling, in that as recently
as February analysts had been predicting that Kodak would earn 89
cents a share. In fact, the stubbornly high expectations worried
Kodak so much that on March 29 it warned investors that its
earnings for the quarter would not top 80 cents. It indicated that
the earnings might even drop as low as 73 cents. But most analysts
figured that was a low estimate, and the consensus settled at 76
cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   Now analysts say it was not the earnings numbers, or even the
promise of a stock buyback, that drove the share price up. Rather,
they say, it was the indication that Kodak's sales were finally
growing again.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key is that the revenues were stellar,'' said Jonathan
Rosenzweig, an analyst with Salomon Smith Barney.
</P>
<P>
   That the stock has long traded at less than 15 times earnings
helped as well, added B. Alexander Henderson, an analyst with
Prudential Securities. ``You put together a cheap stock with
significant improvement in revenues, and you're going to get this
kind of movement,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kodak's sales growth came from various places. Film sales in
China, Brazil and a few other economically troubled markets were
surprisingly strong, as were sales of low-end digital cameras in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   But film sales in America provided the happiest surprise. The
nation's entire consumer film market was up 10 percent this quarter
from the first quarter of 1998, after rising 9 percent in the last
quarter. Kodak did even better, with the number of rolls of film
sold rising by 17 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sales were a lot stronger than even we had expected,'' said
Kodak chief financial officer Harry Kavetas.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, unit sales were up even though neither Kodak nor its
archrival, Fuji Photo Film, slashed prices this year. ``They're all
finally realizing that it is marketing, not price, that makes the
difference,'' said Ulysses Yannas, an analyst with Mercer, Bokert,
Buckman &AMP; Reid.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, no one expects film sales to keep growing at a
double-digit clip. ``It seems unlikely that the very strong growth
in consumer markets that's been observed in the fourth and first
quarters will persist,'' warned Michael Ellmann, an analyst with
Schroder &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   Even Kodak president Daniel Carp tempered his glee. ``It's been
quite a while since I've seen two back-to-back quarters of such
strong industry growth,'' he said. ``But industry numbers do bounce
around a lot as the year goes on.''
</P>
<P>
   And pricing may yet put a damper on profits. Kodak promised its
retailers aggressive price cuts on films and single-use cameras in
May and June, the time when film sales normally start to heat up.
``They sell the most film in the second and third quarters, which
means they've yet to establish what the really important prices for
the year will be,'' said Jack Kelly, an analyst with Goldman, Sachs
&AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Kodak's sales of consumer digital cameras keeps
growing, which may not be such a blessing. Kodak still loses money
on every unit it sells. And if enough consumers embrace digital
cameras, it could be bad news for films. ``Digital sales aren't
negatively impacting film sales yet, but that will be a
front-and-center issue by Christmas 2000,''said Henderson of
Prudential Securities.
</P>
<P>
   There were more immediate tarnishes on the quarter's shine as
well. Kodak brought its costs down by only $80 million, possibly
jeopardizing its chances to deliver the $470 million in cuts it had
promised for the year. Kodak executives, however, insisted the
company was on target.
</P>
<P>
   It has delayed its much-anticipated project to electronically
deliver processed photos to America Online's 17 million customers.
Its sales of motion picture film, long a steady growth area for the
company, were sluggish at best.
</P>
<P>
   The company's Eastman Software subsidiary, which lost $65
million last year, continued to lose money. And Kodak wrote off
losing bets on some inkjet technologies and retail photo kiosks.
Those three troubled areas resulted in a combined charge of $68
million against the latest quarter's earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Still, for the first time since June, the good news in a Kodak
quarter handily outweighed the bad. ``I know that one quarter does
not make a year,'' Carp said. ``But we are very pleased with where
we are right now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
