<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOREIGN BRIEFS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   PAKISTAN: BHUTTO PARTY URGES STRIKE
</P>
<P>
   Benazir Bhutto's Pakistan People's Party called for a strike
Saturday in her native Sindh province to protest her conviction on
corruption charges. She says the judges, who sentenced her to five
years in prison and barred her from holding public office, were
politically motivated. In downtown Karachi, more than a thousand of
her supporters, shouting anti-government slogans, marched in
protest at the conviction.
</P>
<P>
   _ By Celia W. Dugger
</P>
<P>
   PHILIPPINES: REBELS FREE GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   Communist rebels released an army general and a captain they had
held for 58 days on the southern island of Mindanao. Only one
captive now remains from five hostages the rebels had held. The
general, Victor Obillo, was the highest-ranking officer ever
captured in the now-weakened 30-year insurgency.
</P>
<P>
   _ By Seth Mydans
</P>
<P>
   MYANMAR: LAUREATE'S SON VISITS
</P>
<P>
   Kim Aris, 21, the younger son of the opposition leader and Nobel
laureate Daw Aung San Suu Kyi, arrived from London to visit her,
nearly three weeks after her British husband, Michael Aris, died of
cancer. The military junta, which denied her husband's request to
visit before he died, issued a statement wishing him ``an enjoyable
stay'' and both of them ``A very happy Myanmar New Year.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By Seth Mydans
</P>
<P>
   SINGAPORE: FOREST FIRE ALERT
</P>
<P>
   A light white fog and the sweet scent of wood smoke hung over
Singapore, the first hint this year of the thick haze from
Indonesian forest fires that has blanketed Southeast Asia in recent
years. Regional environment ministers issued a statement saying
satellites had monitored ``hot spots'' on Sumatra and warning of
severe smog later this year.
</P>
<P>
   _ By Seth Mydans
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA: REBEL REVOKING CALL TO ARMS
</P>
<P>
   The imprisoned East Timorese rebel leader Jose Alexandre Gusmao
told a visiting U.S. State Department official he would rescind his
recent call for separatist soldiers to resume their armed conflict.
The official, Stanley Roth, said, ``He made it clear that he was
favoring peace and reconciliation and that he would instruct his
commanders to once again cease any military operations.'' Renewed
clashes between soldiers and pro-independence guerrillas left three
people dead.
</P>
<P>
   _ By Seth Mydans
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN: PINOCHET RE-ARRESTED
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Augusto Pinochet, under house arrest in England since
October, was re-arrested by Scotland Yard officers at his rented
suburban mansion under a new warrant reflecting Britain's decision
to let an extradition case against him go forward. Spain is asking
that the 83-year-old former Chilean dictator stand trial in Madrid
on charges of crimes against humanity.
</P>
<P>
   _ By Warren Hoge
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY: 2000 BUG COULD CLOSE MARKETS
</P>
<P>
   Worried about the possibility of computer crashes as a result of
the so-called millennium bug, European finance ministers agreed in
principle that Europe's financial markets should be closed on New
Year's Eve as a precautionary measure. The move, decided at a
meeting in Dresden, reflects a shift from disinterest to alarm in
Europe that many systems will malfunction because they will not
recognize dates with the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   _ By Edmund L. Andrews
</P>
<P>
   LATIN AMERICA
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL: DIPLOMATIC CUTBACK
</P>
<P>
   As part of an effort to slash government spending, required by
the fiscal austerity agreement signed with the International
Monetary Fund last November, the Foreign Ministry is closing its
embassies in Cameroon, Kuwait and Tunisia, and 12 consulates.
Included in the ``temporary deactivation'' are the consulates in
Atlanta and San Juan.
</P>
<P>
   _ By Larry Rohter
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL: AMAZON DECREE LIFTED
</P>
<P>
   The government has revoked a decree that banned all new permits
for clearing land in the Amazon River basin. The action was taken
after loggers and ranchers agreed to new regulations aimed at
slowing the pace of deforestation in the world's largest rain
forest. In return for promises of faster handling of applications,
landowners pledged to limit the use of fire and to restrict
activities in areas that are already damaged.
</P>
<P>
   _ By Larry Rohter
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: POLITICAL FIGHTING
</P>
<P>
   In-house bickering is becoming increasingly public in the
opposition Party of the Democratic Revolution. A presidential
hopeful, Porfirio Munoz Ledo, has said the party's leading
presidential candidate, Mexico City Mayor Cuauhtemoc Cardenas
should pull out of the race. Munoz Ledo accused Cardenas of failing
to fight for his perceived victory in the 1988 presidential
election, which PRD members believe was stolen by Carlos Salinas
from Cardenas by fraud.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
