<HEADLINE>
KINGFISHER ACQUISITION WOULD CREATE LARGEST RETAILER IN BRITAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By   ALAN COWELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Kingfisher PLC, Britain's sixth-largest retailer, will
buy the supermarket chain Asda Group PLC for $9.6 billion in stock,
the companies announced Friday. Such a merger would create the
biggest British retailer, with the ability to expand through
acquisitions into Continental Europe.
</P>
<P>
   The merger has the potential to create stores selling everything
from food to toiletries to clothing, creating a platform to compete
with Continental European megastores. The new entity would have
combined sales of $22.4 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Based on Kingfisher's closing price on Thursday of 875 pence,
the proposed deal, offering 0.2263 Kingfisher share for every Asda
share, implied a 12.2 percent premium for Asda stock, valuing it at
198 pence, or $3.16 a share.
</P>
<P>
   Asda shares rose 22.24 pence (36 cents), or 12.6 percent, to
198.75 pence after the announcement, while Kingfisher fell 35
pence, or 4 percent, to 840.
</P>
<P>
   The deal would give Kingfisher shareholders 66.33 percent of the
equity in the new company, which is expected to be called
Kingfisher. Asda holders would control the rest.
</P>
<P>
   The companies said Sir Geoffrey Mulcahy, chief executive of
Kingfisher, would hold the same position in the new company. Allan
Leighton, Asda's chief executive, would be deputy chief executive
of the new company and chief executive of its food and general
merchandising division.
</P>
<P>
   Kingfisher's holdings include the B&AMP;Q home improvement business,
Woolworth variety store, Superdrug health and beauty chain and the
Comet electrical goods group. Though Asda sells mainly food and
clothing and is Britain's third-largest food retailer after Tesco
and Sainsbury, there are broad similarities.
</P>
<P>
   The companies said the merger would provide ``enhanced
opportunities for growth in the U.K., continental Europe and
internationally.''
</P>
<P>
   Kingfisher has already begun buying in Europe, taking stakes in
Darty, a French electrical retailer; Castorama, a French home
improvement chain, and companies in the Netherlands, Belgium and
Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts described the merger as a defensive ploy to thwart
ambitions by the Wal-Mart Stores chain of the United States to
penetrate Britain's retail market through acquisitions. But others
saw it as a reflection of retailers being forced to seek profit
from mergers because of increased retailing competition and lagging
consumer spending in Britain.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement Friday gave no details about possible job
losses among the 130,000 employees. Only a few weeks ago,
Kingfisher said that it planned to open 100 new stores, mainly in
Britain, providing 4,800 new jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The companies promised to divulge further details of the deal on
Monday. According to Merrill Lynch, Asda's financial advisers in
the deal, heavy trading in stock that pushed prices up by 20
percent over the last week persuaded the company to make a
preliminary announcement Friday.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
