<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-BALKANS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON SEES LONG ASSOCIATION BETWEEN US, BALKANS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROSEVILLE, Mich. _ Just as the United States led the effort to
rebuild Europe after World War II, President Clinton said Friday,
the nation could face a lengthy struggle to ensure a lasting peace
in the Balkans after the military conflict ends.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, speaking to humanitarian relief agencies at a small
community center outside Deroit, did not estimate how much the
United States might spend _ or how long it could take _ to
physically and politically rehabilitate the Balkan region. But he
made a firm commitment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must do for southeastern Europe, including the Balkans,
what was done for central Europe after the Cold War and for the
battleground nations of Europe after World War II,'' the president
said.
</P>
<P>
   As protest groups on opposite sides of the Kosovo issue
demonstrated outside, Clinton told more than 300 relief workers
that the postwar effort in the Balkans would be crucial to
preventing ``another decade where people carry around all this
hatred in their heart.''
</P>
<P>
   The president, returning to the fund-raising trail for the first
time since the NATO airtrikes on Serbia began, addressed the relief
groups between high-priced events in Dearborn, Mich., and Weston,
Mass., aimed at bolstering Democratic campaigns for the House and
Senate. A luncheon for 250 donors in Dearborn raised $500,000,
while a lamb-and-potato dinner for 80 Friday night at the Weston,
Mass. home of Alan Solomont was expected to bring in $800,000.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton seemed particularly affected by a crowd of about 200
protesters ouside the Dearborn fund-raiser who waved Serbian flags
and placards denouncing the NATO bombing. ``Serbian blood is red,
too!'' several placards said.
</P>
<P>
   At the luncheon and relief event later, Clinton warned against
anti-Serbian fervor rising in the United States. The NATO fight is
not against the Serbian people, he reiterated, but their president,
Slobodan Milosevic. ``I ask you to help me in making sure that in
this difficult period we do not diminish the humanity of any groups
of Americans, including the Serbian-Americans,'' he said in
Roseville.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who privately met after the speech with 30
Albanian-Americans, said he also had directed the Defense
Department Friday to build a refugee center in Albania to handle an
additional 20,000 refugees from the Kosovo conflict.
</P>
<P>
   In their meeting with Clinton, the Albanian-Americans asked the
president to postpone plans to transfer as many as 20,000 Kosavar
refugees to a US base at Guantanamo.
</P>
<P>
   A White House official who attended the meeting said the group
cautioned that Milosevic would claim the removal of Kosovar
refugees to American territory as a victory in his campaign to rid
the Yugoslavian province of ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   The Albanian-Americans also questioned the US role in the NATO
bombing effort, asking if ``we are in it to win it,'' the
administration official said. Clinton was said to have affirmed his
commitment to achieving NATO's military goals.
</P>
<P>
   In praising the relief agencies, Clinton also appealed to the
public to continue contributing to the humanitarian effort. The
Federal Emergency Management Agency has received 31,000 calls over
the last days from prospective contributors, officials said, and a
public service announcement was released Friday featuring an appeal
from Hillary Rodham Clinton for additional aid.
</P>
<P>
   ``The heart of America has been engaged by this,'' the president
said.
</P>
<P>
   Expanding on his rationale for the US role in the NATO
operation, Clinton also cited the racially divided environment of
his youth. ``I grew up in the segregated South,'' he said at the
Dearborn fund-raiser. ``I grew up with people who were taught not
to like people who were different from them.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``After all the work we've done in America to get
people to live together across racial and religious lines . . . how
would you feel if I had come here to give this speech today and the
headlines were full of all those people being killed and all those
people being thrown out of the country, and we were having to
explain to people why we couldn't lift a finger to do anything
about it?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
