<TEXT>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-16-99 1915EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990416.0260 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-16 19:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1918 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VENEZUELA-OIL-ART-2TA     04-16 0898
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VENEZUELA-OIL-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
  
 CARACAS : state coffers. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   That has led to speculation that the Venezuelan government,
hungry for cash to finance the ambitious social programs Chavez has
promised, might sell all or part of the Citgo unit, whose
acquisition was completed in 1989 for $1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   But many oil experts here argue that such a step would be a huge
mistake. With oil markets in a volatile state, they maintain, not
only would Venezuela not get the best price for the company, but
the country's heavier, high-sulfur grade of crude, which requires
special processing, would probably lose ground in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Citgo investment was tailor-made to be able to process
Venezuela's peculiar crude, and if we didn't have that guaranteed
outlet, it's quite possible that Saudi Arabia or Mexico would take
advantage,'' said Angel Olmeta, a former company board member who
engineered the original deal.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, some of Chavez's advisers are now urging him to increase
the company's refining capacity in the United States and to add to
its overseas assets, recently valued at $9 billion, of which about
$7.5 billion are in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Last year the company bought half of Mobil Oil's refinery in
Chalmette, La., and the Amerada Hess Corp.'s plant in the U &UR; . &LR; S &UR; . &LR; 
Virgin Islands, and it is said to be interested in other properties
available as a result of recent industry mergers.
</P>
<P>
   But with Venezuela mired in its worst credit and budget crunch
in decades, others here have even suggested that Chavez sell off
the state oil company, formed when the government nationalized
foreign oil holdings 23 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   An independent assessment conducted in 1997 put the company's
value at more than $80 billion, but disposing of its assets appears
to run counter to the president's nationalist instincts.
</P>
<P>
   ``PDVSA is not privatizable, and we're not going to talk about
that,'' Chavez said in a recent speech. While his government
respects all existing contracts and recognizes the need to
``stimulate private investment,'' he said, the goal is to make
Venezuela ``a global energy power'' in control of its own assets.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, predicted Paul, president of the local industry
trade group, the debate over selling at least some parts of the
company ``is a discussion that is going to continue, that is out
there on the table and at some point is probably going to be
resolved in favor of privatization.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Rodriguez, the Minister of Energy and Mines, suggested
that the company ``could sell some assets and acquire others'' as
part of the cost-reduction campaign Chavez has ordered.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The uncertainties over oil policy come at a time when the
company's own corporate culture is in flux. Last year, it revamped
its traditional structure, merging its three major divisions into a
single entity and setting off a factional struggle for dominance.
</P>
<P>
   One of Chavez's first steps after winning the election was to
announce he would dismiss Luis Giusti, the highly regarded
executive who had led the oil company since 1994. Replacing Giusti
is Roberto Mandini, who had been executive vice president at
Citgo's Tulsa headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Mandini declined a request for an interview. But Rodriguez said
he was chosen for the job in part because he had successfully
consolidated several smaller oil companies when he was head of the
company's Corpoven division. The other two main divisions were
Maraven and Lagoven, all derived from the separate organizations
acquired at the time of nationalization.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Mandini can make use of that experience to mold three
cultures into one,'' Rodriguez said.
</P>
<P>
   Oil analysts here predicted it would be more difficult, however,
for Mandini to resolve contradictions inherent to the company's
multiple roles as holding company, driller, exporter and retailer.
Not only does the state oil company regulate the foreign oil
companies that were invited back into Venezuela, but it is also
their partner in some ventures and their rival in others.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is all tangled up,'' said Pedro M. Burelli, an
investment banker who resigned from the board last year. ``There
are 70 different companies in Venezuela always operating in
association with PDVSA, and that is a tough challenge for any
company in the world, particularly a somewhat insensitive and
massive state monopoly.''
</P>
<P>
   The state oil company's most persistent problem, however, may be
the Venezuelan government's habit of viewing it as a cash cow whose
assets can be tapped without regard for its balance sheet. Even
when oil prices were in free fall last year, for instance, the
company was forced to pay an emergency $1 billion dividend to its
sole shareholder, the government.
</P>
<P>
   That left the company squeezed for cash, so it is now seeking
$900 million in new credits.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez has also vetoed any increase in domestic gasoline prices
that might improve the company's revenue.
</P>
<P>
   ``PDVSA's most baffling problem is that it is dealing with a
country that doesn't understand it or the complexities of the oil
industry in general,'' Burelli said. ``There are only two really
solid state institutions in this country, the military and PDVSA
One is in favor, one is not. One uses money, the other makes most
of what the state, and country, require.''
</P>
</TEXT>
