<HEADLINE>
AIR NATIONAL GUARD TANKERS, CREWS TO GET CALL UP FOR KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The 33,000 military reservists the Pentagon is
expected to call up for duty in the Kosovo crisis are likely to be
drawn mainly from the Air National Guard's aerial refueling
facilities at 19 bases across the country, military officials said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Up to 25,000 Air National Guard personnel who help operate
KC-135 tankers used to refuel combat jets in mid-air could be
activated as part of the call-up, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The pressing need for tanker specialists stems from NATO's
recent decision to dramatically expand the air campaign against
Yugoslav forces by adding more than 300 U.S. aircraft _ nearly a
third of which are likely to be refueling airplanes _ and 24 Army
Apache helicopters. The additions will bring NATO's total sky
armada to nearly 1,000 aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   About 100 tankers from the Air National Guard and the Air Force
Reserve are already taking part in the NATO missions. Those units
volunteered for service and were not called to active duty by the
president.
</P>
<P>
   The refueling tankers allow combat jets stationed in the United
States and dispatched to the Balkans to fly across the Atlantic
without stopping. In addition, the tankers allow jets sent on
bombing runs to stay aloft longer.
</P>
<P>
   The 19 Air National Guard facilities where the aerial tankers
are stationed are located at or near the following cities:
</P>
<P>
   Bangor, Maine; Portsmouth, N.H.; Niagara Falls, N.Y.;
Pittsburgh; Philadelphia (McGuire, N.J., Air Force Base); Columbus,
Ohio; Knoxville, Tenn.; Birmingham, Ala.; Meridian, Miss.; Chicago;
Milwaukee; Lincoln, Neb.; Forbes, Kan.; Salt Lake City; Phoenix;
Moreno Valley, Calif. (March Air Force Base); Fairbanks, Alaska
(Eielson Air Force Base); Spokane, Wash. (Fairchild Air Force
Base), and Honolulu (Hickam Air Force Base).
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Air Force Reserve operates tanker units at the
following facilities that might be activated: Grissom Air Force
Base (outside Indianapolis), Tinker Air Force Base (outside
Oklahoma City), Seymour Johnson Air Force Base (outside Goldsboro.
N.C.), Selfridge Air National Guard Base (outside Detroit) and
Beale Air Force Base (outside Yuba City, Calif.).
</P>
<P>
   Defense Secretary William Cohen declined Friday to provide the
exact number of reservists who will be called. ``I think it'll be a
significant number,'' Cohen said, adding that he will present the
request to President Clinton next week.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Richelle Dowdell, an Air Force spokeswoman at the Air
Mobility Command headquarters at Scott Air Force Base, Ill., near
St. Louis, Mo., said the service is preparing for activation
orders. Scott is the command center for the tankers.
</P>
<P>
   Dowdell added, ``As of right now, we are not sure what is going
to get used and who is going to be called up,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   As in the 1991 Persian Gulf War, the military is relying heavily
on aerial tankers during the air strikes against Yugoslav forces
that began March 24.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tremendous advantage to be able to refuel in the skies
as opposed to taking time to land and then get back into the
fight,'' said John Goheen, a spokesman for the National Guard
Association, which represents members of the Air National Guard.
``It's a much more efficient use of time and weaponry.''
</P>
<P>
   Retired Gen. Merrill McPeak, who was Air Force chief of staff
from 1990 to 1994, said the Kosovo operations are ``air-refueling
intensive.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Over Kosovo, our pilots have to loiter and find out what's
moving on the ground,'' he explained.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
