<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-NUMBERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNCERTAINTY OVER NUMBER OF KOSOVARS COMPLICATING RELIEF EFFORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLUM LYNCH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ Uncertainty over the exact number of ethnic
Albanians in Kosovo is complicating UN and NATO efforts to cope
with one of the worst European refugee crises since the second
world war.
</P>
<P>
   Most planners cite the 1991 census figure of 1.8 million in
estimating the size of Kosovo's population. But nobody is sure.
</P>
<P>
   The UN High Commissioner for refugees, the lead refugee agency,
claims that some 550,000 ethnic Albanians have fled the country for
refuge in neighboring Montenegro, Macedonia, and Albania since NATO
launched its war against the federal Republic of Yugoslvia. General
Henry H. Shelton, the chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, said
Friday that as few as 700,000 Albanian Kosovars remain displaced in
the country.
</P>
<P>
   If you account for the estimated 200,000 Serbs who live in
Kosovo, that leaves more than 500,000 people. The discrepancy,
according to UN officials, is due to the fact that nobody knows how
many people really lived in Kosovo before NATO began its March 24
bombing campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since Serbia tighten its grip around the renegade province
of Kosovo in the late 1980s, tens of thousands of the country's
ethnic Albanians have been fleeing the country for a better life in
Europe. And tens of thousands more, facing Serbian repression, have
flooded across the border into Albania, Macedonia and Montenegro
before NATO launched its war against the federal Republic of
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   The result, according to some Congressional critics of the
relief effort, has been confusion. For the moment, UNCHR said it is
planning for a total of 650,000 refugees. Mark Kirk, a
Congressional staffer with the House International Relations
Committee, says that's not enough. ``As far as Congress is
concerned,'' said Kirk. ``We would urge the administration to plan
upwards of 1.2 million refugees.''
</P>
<P>
   Kirk said that key State Department planners have privately
acknowledged that they need to plan for a flood of more than a
million refugees. But he said that they are reluctant to announce
it publicly out of fear that some of the key host governments in
Albania, Macedonia or Montenegro, will shut their borders.
</P>
<P>
   In the past 24 hours, some 16,000 Kosovars have crossed their
borders. UNHCR spokesman Ron Redmont said 100,000 thousand new
refugees are on their way to join them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The expulsions, which were put on hold or slowed down over the
past two weeks, have now resumed with full force,'' said Kris
Janowski, a spokesman for UNHCR.
</P>
<P>
   UN officials and humanitarian aid workers, meanwhile, have begun
warning that the hordes of homeless ethnic Albanians inside Kosovo
are in danger of perishing if they don't receive assistance.
</P>
<P>
   Carol Bellamy, the director of the UN Children's Fund (Unicef)
testified before Congress on Thursday that displaced children and
the elderly are in peril of dying if they relief doesn't reach
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are indications thousands of people are hiding in the
forests and icy mountain areas in central and southern Kosovo,''
Mary Robinson, the UN's Commissioner of Human Rights said Friday.
``Kosovo Albanians express great concern at (their) lack of food
and security...and have urged the international community to assist
them.''
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials are reluctant to mount a humanitarian
intervention in Kosovo without a political settlement.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration urged other countries, including
Greece, to use their influence with Milosevic to gain access to the
internally displaced. Kirk said that the administration has
promised to provide air cover to any country willing to conduct a
humanitarian airdrop over Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever country can use its relationship with people inside
Serbia to get access to the people at risk, we want to help them,''
said Rubin. ``But again, President Milosevic continues to use the
people of Kosovo in pursuit of his evil designs: as hostages, pawns
or victims.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
