<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-ADVISORY-NYT </SLUG>
  
(gm) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times plans three pages of stories, photos and
graphics on the continuing crisis in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MILITARY (Washington) _ In what NATO claimed as one of
its most successful 24 hours in the air campaign against
Yugoslavia, NATO pilots destroyed 57 targets in Kosovo, including
several tanks and artillery sites. The pilots also gathered new
photographic evidence to back up reports of mass killings, NATO and
Clinton administration officials said today. By Philip Shenon.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-SCENE (Urosevac, Yugoslavia) _ The scene in the province
of Kosovo as seen from 12 hours of riding around on a bus escorted
by Yugoslav Army, with a few stops and interviews. By Steven
Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Brussels) _ The confusion about whether NATO
accidentally bombed civilian refugees fleeing Serbian attacks in
Kosovo reflects the novelty of the first real air war the alliance
has ever fought and the determination of its American military
commander to control everything NATO says about air strikes even
while he runs the war. By Craig R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-COHEN (Washington) _ Secretary of Defense William Cohen
today complained of an ``Orwellian twisting of language and logic''
under which NATO leaders are finding themselves trying to explain
the bombing of a refugee convoy on Wednesday, while Serbian
President Slobodan Milosevic ``is not allowing his people to see
the kind of horrific damage that he is causing to hundreds of
thousands of people.'' By Joel Brinkley.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MACEDONIA (Brazda) _ The flow of ethnic Albanians fleeing
Kosovo into Macedonia surged again today with more than 6,000
refugees pouring out of the Serbian province including families
that had been forced by Serbian forces to turn back more than a
week ago and had gone into hiding. By David Rohde.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-ALBANIA (Kukes) _ There is growing concern here in the
Kukes area, where there are 100,000 refugees, that the city will be
hit by a Serbian attack. On Thursday, Serbs shelled a nearby
encampment of the Kosovo rebel group, the KLA. By Anthony DePalma.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-VOICES (Undated) _ The Times talks again to a dozen
people who live and work in White Plains, N.Y., who have been
interviewed several times since March 24, when NATO first bombed
Yugoslavia. By Susan Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   With photo (NYT 19 of 3-29-99).
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-EXPEL (Geneva) _ The United Nations refugee agency today
accused Yugoslavia of trying to expel the entire ethnic Albanian
population from Kosovo, where Albanians had made up 90 percent of
the population. By Elizabeth Olson.
</P>
