<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-RIGHTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. GETS NO SUPPORT FOR CHINA RESOLUTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA, Switzerland _ The United States submitted a resolution
criticizing China's human rights record to the main United Nations
rights body Friday, but it was unable to get any other country to
sign on as a co-sponsor.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials insisted that the absence of publicly declared
support did not mean that the resolution was headed for defeat at
the 53-member U.N. Human Rights Commission, which is expected to
vote on it next week.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration, under pressure from both houses of
Congress, which voted unanimously in favor of submitting a
resolution critical of China, has been circulating a draft for nine
days in hope of attracting co-sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   The draft resolution criticizes ``severe restrictions'' on a
range of democratic rights, including freedom of expression,
assembly and religion, and harsh sentences for those seeking to
exercise those rights.
</P>
<P>
   The measure, which U.S. officials described as balanced and
fair, calls on China to release political prisoners, including
those jailed for ``nonviolent counterrevolutionary activity,'' and
to protect the ``distinct cultural, ethnic, linguistic and
religious identity of Tibetans.''
</P>
<P>
   In March, European Union foreign ministers said they would avoid
censuring China's rights record, despite noting that they were
``dismayed'' by China's actions against pro-democracy activists.
</P>
<P>
   This left the administration without its staunchest ally in the
procession of resolutions critical of China, which have been
introduced in the human rights body every year but one since the
violent suppression of pro-democracy protests at Tiananmen Square
in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the loneliest resolution in the history of China
resolutions,'' said Joanna Weschler of Human Rights Watch, the
advocacy and monitoring group based in New York, which supports the
U.S. move.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, at a House
subcommittee hearing Friday, acknowledged that the measure faced
``an uphill battle.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No other country has agreed to co-sponsor the resolution,
which is depressing to say the least,'' Albright said.
</P>
<P>
   China, which has already mounted a vigorous public campaign to
defeat a vote, is also seeking support for a motion of its own to
take no action on the U.S. resolution. This has been the means by
which Beijing has defeated formal votes on all but one of the
previous measures against it.
</P>
<P>
   If passed, the no-action motion means that the resolution never
comes up for a vote in the rights commission, which meets for six
weeks annually to review human rights violations worldwide. In
March 1995, countries voted down the no-action motion, and China's
human rights record was debated. The resolution, sponsored by the
United States and the European Union, lost by one vote when Russia
cast its vote in opposition.
</P>
<P>
   This was the closest China has come to defeat. In 1996 and 1997,
China once again blocked votes on critical resolutions when
countries backed the preliminary no-action motion. Asian and
African countries have generally supported China on grounds that
such resolutions are undue interference in domestic matters.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, buoyed by improvements in Beijing's treatment of
dissidents, and its promise to sign onto an international accord
guaranteeing those rights, the push to criticize China ran out of
steam. Both the 15-member European Union and the United States
declined to offer a resolution.
</P>
<P>
   But in March the Clinton administration said the recent
crackdown on pro-democracy activists would prompt a renewed effort
to rebuke China. In December, three founding members of the banned
China Democracy Party were sentenced to lengthy prison terms for
acts against the state.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the European Union's stand, several prominent Chinese
dissidents in exile turned up in Geneva to lobby for the U.S.
resolution. Referring to the European Union countries, Wei
Jingsheng, who spent 18 years in jail, said at a news briefing,
``We believe they will vote for the resolution.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
