<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Council yet to lift limits on Trump club
 &HT;    By Tim O'Meilia
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ No beach parties for kids older than 12. No
cabanas higher than the next door neighbor's house. A wider tunnel
beneath State Road A1A.
</P>
<P>
   Those are just some of the demands being sought from Donald
Trump's Mar-a-Lago Club by his neighbors' lawyers and town
officials in exchange for approval of a beach-side pool, 14
cabanas, a 608-seat pavilion and ending membership and traffic
limits on the club.
</P>
<P>
   After two days of hearings, the town council is not close to
making a decision on the private club's requests. The hearing will
resume Tuesday at 9:30 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   The focus of debate is lifting limits of 500 members (the club
has 360 now), the 390 persons per special event and 313 car trips
per day to the club. The limits were set when the council approved
the creation of the club in 1993 on the 18-acre landmark estate
built by Marjorie Merriweather Post.
</P>
<P>
   The Preservation Foundation, the Palm Beach Civic Association
and beachfront neighbor Alyne Massey complained that a Celine Dion
charity concert Feb. 27 attracted more than 800 spectators each and
snarled traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Mar-a-Lago Club attorney Ray Royce apologized for the Dion
problem and said a Beach Boys appearance two weeks later was
handled much better.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we have here is not just a private club but an ongoing
business that rents itself out for profit,'' said attorney Ron
Kolins, representing Massey. ``You certainly shouldn't expand a
commercial use when it doesn't belong there in the first place.''
</P>
<P>
   More than a dozen club members said the beach additions would
allow more family enjoyment and the pavilion would cut down noise
because it would replace a temporary tent used for large events.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
