<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHEELS-RANGERPICKUP17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Four-door Ranger more carlike
 &HT;    By Russ DeVault
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Extra doors are the big deal these days for trucks and
vans, and Ford has taken that concept to the max with the '99
Ranger compact pickup. Just add $660 to the purchase price, and the
hot-selling Ranger becomes a four-door vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   The added utility is so obvious it seems an idea whose time
should have come decades ago. No matter whether transporting people
or cargo, the third and fourth doors soon seem so natural it's easy
to forget that not all trucks have them.
</P>
<P>
   ``More doors means more utility,'' says Drew Cook, brand manager
for Ranger. ``Utility is what today's customer demands.''
</P>
<P>
   That's hardly earthshaking news, but it does mean Ford, along
with other manufacturers, is well aware that trucks _ particularly
the compacts _ are regarded by many buyers as personal
transportation vehicles that can be workhorses.
</P>
<P>
   Other features, too, are becoming more carlike, as are prices.
The test Ranger Sport Supercab with a no-effort, switch-on-the-go
two/four-wheel drive system had about everything that can be added
except a sunroof and leather seats. It totaled $24,450, but the
other end of the market isn't forgotten. A two-door,
two-wheel-drive Ranger with very basic standard features is
available for $12,295.
</P>
<P>
   Additional proof that compact trucks are primarily for people
and not cargo is the cabin size. Cabs keep growing, and cargo boxes
keep shrinking.
</P>
<P>
   The Sport has 39.2 inches of headroom and 42.2 inches of
legroom, and there really is enough space overall to justify Ford's
claim that buyers who stick with the standard bench seat can ferry
around five people.
</P>
<P>
   The two in the rear aren't going to be very comfortable, of
course. The folding jump seats aren't very large or body-fitting,
and there's really no place for adult legs. Even for children, the
novelty of riding in the rear quickly wears off.
</P>
<P>
   The driver and front passenger can be sitting pretty, however,
with the addition of the cloth bucket seats ($360). The manual
adjustments provide a good range of positions, and the shape will
suit most bodies.
</P>
<P>
   Ford offers both four- and five-speed automatic transmissions,
in addition to the five-speed manual, but the engine choices aren't
as pleasing. The base 2.5-liter four-cylinder makes a mere 119
horsepower, while the 3.0-liter V-6 produces 150 and the 4.0-liter
V-6 manages a 10-hp boost to 160. The test Sport's 4.0-liter six
had good acceleration, but using full power to merge with traffic
and for travel with a load in the 72-inch-long cargo box was a
noisy process.
</P>
<P>
   Locking out overdrive improved the performance notably in loaded
and unloaded situations. Left alone, the five-speed automatic
quickly went to overdrive and created the sensation of an abrupt
loss of power.
</P>
<P>
   But except for seeming underpowered, the Ranger Sport is a nifty
little pickup. The ride, loaded and unloaded, is good, and the
handling characteristics are rather remarkable compared with
yesteryear's pickups. The evolution to carlike dashes and control
placement also boosts the ease of driving. The test Sport's cabin
had the same quality of materials _ plastic included _ that is
expected in cars.
</P>
<P>
   Test vehicle: 1999 Ford Ranger Sport Supercab two/four-wheel
drive pickup
</P>
<P>
   Price as tested: $24,450 (includes discounts not always
available)
</P>
<P>
   Safety features: dual front air bags, side-impact beams, power
anti-lock brakes with front discs and rear drums
</P>
<P>
   Drivetrain: optional 4.0-liter V-6 engine (160 horsepower,
$675), optional five-speed automatic transmission with overdrive
lockout ($1,130)
</P>
<P>
   Other options on test vehicle: four-door feature, $660; power
windows, locks and keyless entry system, $535; fog lamps and
16-inch aluminum wheels, $495; cruise control and leather-wrapped
tilt steering wheel, $395; cloth high-back bucket seats, $360;
trailer hitch, $215; upgraded stereo with CD player and four
speakers, $100
</P>
<P>
   EPA figures: 16 mpg regular unleaded city, 20 mpg highway
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
