<SLUG> BC-FRANCE-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEADER OF CHIRAC PARTY QUITS, CITING FRENCH RIGHT'S DISARRAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MARLISE SIMONS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ The leader of President Jacques Chirac's Gaullist party
resigned unexpectedly Friday, indirectly accusing Chirac of
undermining his position and throwing France's conservative
opposition into fresh disarray.
</P>
<P>
   The party leader, Philippe Seguin, 55, who has himself long
harbored presidential ambitions, set out to unite the conservative
opposition when he took over the party, Rally for the Republic,
after the Socialist victory in parliamentary elections in May 1997.
Friday, however, the opposition is more divided than ever.
</P>
<P>
   Seguin's resignation, accompanied by a bitter statement,
nonetheless took French politicians by surprise.
</P>
<P>
   Complaining that he found himself in a situation ``where
loyalty, clarity and transparency are no longer cardinal virtues,''
Seguin said he was also withdrawing as his party's leading
candidate in elections for the European Parliament on June 13.
</P>
<P>
   Although he did not mention Chirac by name, he clearly felt
snubbed Thursday when the president received the leader of a
competing center-right coalition, Francois Bayrou. Moreover, Seguin
complained that one of the president's top aides had publicly
expressed sympathy for a Seguin party dissident. He said the entire
rightist opposition was being weakened by ``suicidal strategies''
promoted by Elysee Palace.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the turmoil on the right stems from the
nonconfrontational way that the conservative president is managing
his ``cohabitation'' with the Socialist government of Prime
Minister Lionel Jospin. This approach, while damaging the right,
has allowed Chirac to increase his popularity and improve his
chances of re-election in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   But without clear leadership the mainstream opposition has
splintered, and three different groups of rightist candidates are
now competing in the coming European elections. Seguin, who opposed
French ratification of the Maastricht Treaty on European Union in
1992, had formed a pro-European ticket with former Finance Minister
Alain Madelin, who runs his own dissident movement, Liberal
Democracy. The Maastricht Treaty aligned members' policies more
closely in several areas.
</P>
<P>
   Former Interior Minister Charles Pasqua, a lifelong Gaullist who
campaigned with Seguin against Maastricht, remains opposed to
European integration and has been joined by Philippe de Villiers,
leader of another rightist party. The Union of French Democracy, a
loose of coalition of center-right parties now headed by Bayrou, is
running a pro-Europe ticket.
</P>
<P>
   In his statement Friday, Seguin said that the president of the
Association of Friends of Jacques Chirac, Bernard Pons, had
indicated that all three groups represented the president's
interests.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is clear that I no longer belong at the presidency of the
Rally for the Republic or at the head of a European candidates'
list intended to champion the president's policies,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Seguin's abrupt withdrawal from the political scene may be
only temporary. Some commentators said that if the right did poorly
in the European elections, as polls currently predict, Seguin would
avoid blame. And if Chirac's popularity weakened before the 2002
presidential elections, Seguin might be well placed to mount a
challenge as an independent Gaullist.
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, though, his resignation has prompted new calls
for unity within the opposition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sincerely hope we will use this test to form a single,
united opposition list,'' said Jean-Louis Debre, the Gaullist
minority leader in the National Assembly. This was endorsed by
Madelin, who added that unity behind President Chirac was all the
more important during the current crisis in Kosovo. Pasqua,
however, congratulated Seguin on his ``courageous decision.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
