<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAPECOD-CHIPS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MASS. POTATO CHIP MAKER SOLD TO N.C. SNACK COMPANY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn.: N.C.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN WILMSEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cape Cod Potato Chip Co., maker of extra crispy, extra salty
chips that have become a legend, is being sold _ again.
</P>
<P>
   Lance Inc., a Charlotte, N.C. snack company, said it bought the
Hyannis, Mass. company for an undisclosed sum Friday, a move Cape
Cod executives said was a must in the bare-knuckle world of chip
sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end of the day, it's really tough for a small company
like us to compete with the giants,'' said Vincent Fantegrossi,
president and chief executive officer of Cape Cod Potato Chip.
</P>
<P>
   That may be so, but it's the second time the brand with the red
lighthouse on the bag tried to go long with a snack-food mammoth.
Last time it was Anheuser-Busch, which bought the company from
founder Stephen Bernard in 1985. Under Anheuser-Busch's Eagle
Snacks subsidiary, Cape Cod was driven to the brink of destruction
in what became known as the Great Potato Chip War _ a prolonged
battle for shelf space and profits that ended in 1995 with
Frito-Lay the victor.
</P>
<P>
   For months, Cape Cod chips were absent from store shelves. And
with the brand threatened with extinction, Bernard bought the
company back with the help of SMS Brands, a venture capital firm
that buys distressed snack companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we took it over, there were no sales, no shelf space, no
distribution,'' Fantegrossi said. ``Our plant had been shut down
for a couple months. It was exactly at ground zero.''
</P>
<P>
   Cape Cod hired back some of its old employees, and in five years
built the company back up, claiming more than $30 million in annual
sales and distribution network that spanned the country, Canada and
Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Still, when Lance executives floated the idea of an acquisition,
Cape Cod executives said they couldn't refuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first we didn't know what to make of it,'' Fantegrossi
said. ``But after we met with them, we saw this thing really makes
sense.
</P>
<P>
   With the acquisition, Cape Cod Potato Chips will have the
benefit of Lance's fleet of 2,000 trucks, 65,000 vending machines
and 1 million square feet of manufacturing space, Fantegrossi said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The building they repair their vending machines in is bigger
than our plant here on the Cape,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The trucks and vending machines translate to a doubling of Cape
Cod Chips' distribution capacity and could mean sales growth of 15
percent to 20 percent a year.
</P>
<P>
   And despite that kind of potential growth, Fantegrossi assured,
``it'll still be the same old chips.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-16-99 1933EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
