<DOCNO> NYT19990416.0277 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-16 19:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1944 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEWIS-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      04-16 0739
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWIS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: ENGINE FOR CHANGE
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By ANTHONY LEWIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BILBAO, Spain _ ``Optimism is the engine for change,'' Nerea
Abasolo said. ``In a climate without hope _ which is where we were
in the Basque Country _ even people with money won't invest. But
when you see things are happening around you, you want to join
in.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Abasolo is communications director of the spectacular new
Guggenheim Museum in Bilbao, and she was talking about the effect
of the museum on this city and region. It is a transforming effect:
economic, psychological, perhaps even political.
</P>
<P>
   What makes it worth the world's attention is that the real
engine for change, the spark for optimism, is a work of art: Frank
Gehry's museum building. Everyone has seen the pictures of the
exterior _ the curved and angular titanium-clad shapes flowing into
each other, changing color from silver to gold with the light. But
nothing prepares you for the thing itself.
</P>
<P>
   The interior is as extraordinary as the much-photographed
exterior. At its heart is an atrium half again as high as Frank
Lloyd Wright's snail-shaped Guggenheim Museum in New York. Glass
and steel and limestone soar in lines and curves to unexpected
intersections. There are galleries of traditional shape for more
traditional works, like a current show of drawings, and of
unpredictable shapes for unpredictable modernity.
</P>
<P>
   It is the great building of the 20th century, I think. And it is
attracting visitors and supporters in amazing numbers. Before it
opened, in October 1997, experts predicted that 450,000 people
would visit it the first year. The actual number was three times
that, 1.36 million. They added $160 million to the Basque Country's
economy.
</P>
<P>
   But the intangibles are more important than the figures. That is
what Nerea Abasolo meant in her comment about optimism.
</P>
<P>
   The Basque area of northern Spain used to be a center of heavy
industry, notably steel and shipbuilding. As those industries
declined in the 1980's, it became a depressed region, further
troubled by the decades-long terrorist campaign of the Basque
separatist group ETA.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991 the Basque regional administration decided that the way
out of its slough of despond was culture. It agreed with the
Guggenheim Foundation to build a museum, at a cost of $100 million,
to be managed by Guggenheim _ and to pay the running expenses
thereafter. Within a year an architectural competition had been
held and Gehry selected.
</P>
<P>
   The site was a rust-belt classic: a former factory and parking
lot on the Nervion River, just down from the old port. A green
metal highway bridge bisected it. The competing architects proposed
walling off the bridge. Frank Gehry incorporated it in his design,
with one huge wing stretching under the bridge and a tower rising
behind it.
</P>
<P>
   Almost all the construction work was done by Basque companies
and individuals, so the success of its advanced technology is in a
sense a tribute to Basque skill. For example, the building has
300,000 steel beams _ in 250,000 different sizes. A
three-dimensional computer program was used for the design and then
for the fabrication of the steel and other materials.
</P>
<P>
   Basques are understandably proud of the museum. And Bilbao has
undertaken other major projects with such international architects
as Sir Norman Foster and Cesar Pelli.
</P>
<P>
   Last year the ETA announced a unilateral cease-fire, which
continues to hold. It can only be speculation, but the optimism to
which the museum has contributed may play a part in the turn away
from violence.
</P>
<P>
   The museum is significant in still another respect. In the
developed world today, people want at the same time to be part of
the global society and to be attached to local roots. The museum is
a symbol of both: an institution of international standing with a
strong local attachment.
</P>
<P>
   But for me the inspiring part of the Guggenheim Bilbao story is
the function of art _ of architecture. From ancient Athens to
Angkor Wat and the great cathedrals of Europe, architecture has
expressed the highest aspirations of the human spirit. Here in
Bilbao is a glimpse of what it could be for us today.
</P>
<P>
   Inescapably, too, it speaks of the extremes of human behavior.
In another corner of Europe, people are dying because of one man's
lust for power. Here they live more fully because of an architect's
genius for beauty.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
