<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-VOLUNTEER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
``VOLUNTEER OF THE YEAR'' DOESN'T MINCE WORDS AT AGE 83 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE OLAFSON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALVIN, Texas _ At 83 years of age, Glenna Winn would just as
soon no one make a fuss over her.
</P>
<P>
   But when you have tea at the Governor's Mansion and are
recognized as a ``Volunteer of the Year'' by the Texas Commission
on Volunteerism and Community Service, it's hard to be a
wallflower.
</P>
<P>
   She will accept the award gracefully, but she worries that the
people who make her program work _ some 25 volunteers, most of whom
are older than 70 _ might be forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   For her efforts in coordinating the ``Are You O.K.?'' Program in
Alvin, Winn on Monday will be recognized at the 1999 Governor's
Volunteer Awards as the state's top volunteer of the senior
division.
</P>
<P>
   That's when she'll have tea at the guv's house.
</P>
<P>
   Big deal, right?
</P>
<P>
   Well, when the governor's secretary called her at her home on
Friday to go over some last minute details about Monday's ceremony,
Winn seemed unimpressed.
</P>
<P>
   She's not ungrateful. She just wants to remind everyone she
alone doesn't make the ``Are You O.K.?'' Program successful.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have 25 volunteers in back of me.''
</P>
<P>
   The volunteers make daily contact with 175 elderly, handicapped
and homebound residents in the town of 20,000 who otherwise might
be left to fend for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   They deliver fans in the summer, heaters in the winter and help
some people with their electricity bills _ all on a budget of about
$4,000 per year.
</P>
<P>
   The program has been copied in 10 other towns with Winn's
assistance.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, many of the people her organization serves are
younger than Winn, who turns 84 on the 4th of July.
</P>
<P>
   With a deadpan sense of humor that belies her age, Winn can be
disarmingly blunt when offering opinions on anything from TV, which
she refuses to watch because of the ``trashy'' content, to
bureaucrats, who she believes hinder more than help programs that
assist the needy.
</P>
<P>
   Winn joked that she would like to use a baseball bat on a
certain bureaucrat at the county courthouse whom she feels slighted
her program's clients last year.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, she doesn't worry about whom she might offend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like when you're as old as I am _ what can they do to
you?'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   A widow who still drives her 1989 blue Buick Regal around town,
Winn also doesn't shrink from criticizing the elected leaders of
Alvin for what she calls their stingy ways in aiding the ``Are You
O.K.?'' program.
</P>
<P>
   ``The city of Alvin is not economical _ they're just plain
cheap,'' she said. ``They're the cheapest bunch of people you'll
ever run into.''
</P>
<P>
   With no government subsidy, she must raise money as well as run
the volunteer program, which was begun in 1992 by Police Chief Mike
Merkel.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key to her success has been her energy and her
enthusiasm,'' said Merkel, an unabashed fan. ``I love her.''
</P>
<P>
   Winn, who grew up in Centralia, Ill., as the daughter of a
railroad man, came to Texas in the 1940s to attend the University
of Houston.
</P>
<P>
   She moved to Alvin 35 years ago when she and her husband
William, dead now 20 years, decided to open an office supply
business.
</P>
<P>
   She wasn't crazy about leaving the city for the small town.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was pitiful back then,'' she said of the Brazoria County
town's slow pace.
</P>
<P>
   Today, taking another look at her town, Winn believes the
program she has coordinated has made Alvin a more comfortable place
for seniors.
</P>
<P>
   Just 10 days ago, she said, an Alvin woman who had undergone a
double mastectomy followed by chemotherapy found herself home alone
late one night believing some ice cream might make her feel better.
</P>
<P>
   The woman, who is served by the ``Are You O.K.?'' program, she
called the police dispatcher to see if an officer could bring her
some, Winn said.
</P>
<P>
   The dispatcher calmly explained an officer would come by as soon
as possible.
</P>
<P>
   Soon enough, he did, with a quart of ice cream in hand.
</P>
<P>
   Winn relates the story with a twinkle in her eye. It's the kind
of story that makes her think back 35 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the time, I couldn't imagine living in Alvin, Texas,'' she
said, ``but now I'm glad I did.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
