<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PENTAGON-GROUND-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOGISTICS OF KOSOVO GROUND WAR POINT UP DIFFICULTIES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i and w coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRED KAPLAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ There are solid reasons why NATO nations are
reluctant to send ground troops into Kosovo. As Defense Secretary
William Cohen told the Senate this week, many alliance soldiers
would die.
</P>
<P>
   For NATO leaders worried about maintaing political support, that
alone poses a major obstacle.
</P>
<P>
   But military analysts who have studied the terrain and tactics
have another reason for concern: Mounting and sustaining an
invasion, they said would be more difficult than it might look at
first glance.
</P>
<P>
   Still, as NATO's bombing intensifies and Slobodan Milosevic's
troops stand their ground, more and more people, especially in
Congress, are talking about sending in the troops.
</P>
<P>
   What might a ground war in Kosovo look like? How do the troops
get there? What do they do, once they are in?
</P>
<P>
   Cohen this week referred to Pentagon studies, estimating that
30,000 to 75,000 combat troops would be needed to push the 25,000
Serbian forces out of Kosovo. As many as 200,000 might be needed if
the aim were to take control of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   The map shows several ways into Kosovo, but only a few are
practical. The easiest would be from the north, across central
Europe and through Hungary. But this makes sense only if an
invasion of all of Serbia is the object. That would include
conquest of the capital, Belgrade, a step that probably exceeds
NATO's wildest ambitions.
</P>
<P>
   If the goal is to liberate Kosovo, then the troops must come in
through Albania from the southwest or Macedonia from the southeast,
preferably both.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to break in from both routes simultaneously,'' said
Barry Posen, professor of strategic studies at the Massachusetts
Institute of Technology. ``You want to maximize pressure on the
Serbs, make them wonder where we're coming from, rattle their
cages.''
</P>
<P>
   Although 11,000 NATO troops are currently stationed in
Macedonia, and more on the way, the leaders of the newly
independent republic oppose letting NATO use their territory as a
staging area for an invasion. If NATO respects Macedonian wishes,
an invasion would be much harder.
</P>
<P>
   Two roads cut into Kosovo from Albania, though only one of them
is firm enough to support vehicles bigger than a four-wheel truck.
Even the one useful road runs into hills, mountains, and forests
just over the border, and it has just two lanes, which would allow
only a one-way column of military vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Really large forces are going to fall all over themselves,''
Posen said. ``There will be bottlenecks,'' which could make an
assault vulnerable even to beleaguered Serbian defenders.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Posen said NATO troops would eventually push their way
in, possibly after a few days of quite intense fighting.
</P>
<P>
   After this push, the terrain opens up to plains, ideal for tanks
and other armored vehicles, assuming the roads and bridges up to
that point can support such heavy machines.
</P>
<P>
   However, a few miles farther north, the plains break up into
smaller basins surrounded by more hills, mountains, and forests.
</P>
<P>
   A Pentagon official, who asked not to be identified, said units
in one of these basins could not easily support or reinforce units
in other basins. He also expressed concern that Serbs could take
potshots from the many hiding places all around.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kosovo is like a medieval fortress,'' the official said.
``There are exit walls, interior walls, and compartments. Once you
penetrate the wall, you have to clean out the compartments.''
</P>
<P>
   British defense minister George Robinson, speaking at Harvard
University's John F. Kennedy School of Government Friday, made the
same point: ``I would remind you that Kosovo was last successfully
invaded in 1395, because of its unique geography.''
</P>
<P>
   If NATO were to attempt an invasion anyway, attack helicopters,
such as the 48 Apaches that are being sent to the region, would be
vital. They could fly across the geographic barriers and provide
additional firepower where necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Air-cavalry brigades, including larger helicopters to transport
infantry troops, would also play a major role.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Serbs are still believed to have a large arsenal of
antiaircraft weapons, including shoulder-fired surface-to-air
missiles. Much of NATO's bombing campaign is designed to destroy
the Serb antiaircraft threat, but many of the weapons are small and
portable.
</P>
<P>
   US officials have said the bombing could go on for weeks or
months. Mobilizing an invasion, which involves transporting troops,
weapons, and supplies to the area, as well as expanding bases and
staging areas in the region, would itself take a month or two.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts contemplate a different approach _ a bold airborne
assault-and-landing on the one airfield in Kosovo, just south of
Pristina.
</P>
<P>
   John Pike, a military specialist at the Federation of American
Scientists, a private organization, calls this tactic ``kicking the
door down.'' Just before such an assault begins, Pike speculated,
NATO attack planes would clear the area with a continuous barrage
of cluster bombs, forcing any Serbs around the airport to clear out
or take cover.
</P>
<P>
   Then transport planes _ carrying armored vehicles, weapons, and
troops _ would fly in, land at the airport, and set up an operating
base in the heart of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would take a week to get a brigade on the ground,'' Pike
estimated. A brigade consists of roughly 5,000 troops. Once the
base is secure, many more could fly in.
</P>
<P>
   Around Pristina, the terrain is fairly wide-open, and many roads
head wherever a commander would want to go.
</P>
<P>
   Pike noted such an operation would be ``challenging,'' likening
it to the Inchon landing in the Korean War.
</P>
<P>
   The whole scheme _ like any scheme for a ground war _ assumes
that weeks of NATO bombardment will have reduced the Serbian forces
to a tattered, immobilized shadow of their former selves.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, half the Serbs in Kosovo are army draftees, the other
half are security police. One group may not have the stomach for a
serious fight, the other may not have the training. But other
analysts worry that all these scenarios may underestimate the
Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon official points to an early-1950s US Army study of
the Yugoslav resistance to the Nazi juggernaut of World War II.
Hitler's generals threw well over 100,000 troops _ at one point,
over a half-million _ into Yugoslavia. For two years, until the
Allies conquered Italy, the resistance was on its own. The
partisans took heavy losses _ two-thirds of the country's males
between age 15 and 55 were killed or wounded _ but enough retreated
to the mountains or forests and returned to fight another day.
</P>
<P>
   Going back to the 14th century, Posen said of the Serbs, ``Their
whole mental construct involves fighting great powers.''
</P>
<P>
   Today's Serbs, he added, may not be the fearsome warriors of
olden times, nor is today's Yugoslavia as big as it was back then.
Kosovo is tinier still _ a diamond-shaped province about 80 by 80
miles.
</P>
<P>
   Still, even those who are optimistic about the results of a
ground war say NATO troops are bound to suffer a fair number of
casualties _ no one would guess how many _ especially in the
battle's first days, when the Serbs can be expected to haul out
everything they can muster to try to bog the Westerners down.
</P>
<P>
   This is why some analysts, particularly the military officers
who would plan an invasion, would prefer to pour in as many troops
_ and make the assault as overpowering _ as possible.
</P>
<P>
   Another reason for an all-out approach is that, even if NATO
restricted the invasion to Kosovo, commanders would want at least
to threaten Serbia _ to keep Milosevic's troops bottled up, unable
to reinforce or resupply those trapped in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Posen said one brigade might be poised on the border between
Macedonia and Serbia for this purpose. A Marine amphibious force
could anchor just off Yugoslavia's western shores, in the Adriatic
Sea, as a further threat.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the ground-war option in Senate hearings this week,
Gen. Henry Shelton, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, said,
``It would be a long and drawn-out proposition'' _ which is why,
for the moment, within the NATO alliance, ``there's no political
support to carry it out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
