<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-16 19:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1951 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GREENSPAN-TRADE-NYT &LR;      04-16 0807
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GREENSPAN-TRADE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREENSPAN DENOUNCES PROTECTIONIST PRESSURES IN TRADE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Mich.)  (mk) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Alan Greenspan, the Federal Reserve chairman, waded
into the escalating debate over trade policy Friday, denouncing
growing protectionist pressures and arguing that pockets of workers
sometimes had to suffer in order for the national economy to
strengthen.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech in Dallas, Greenspan did not directly address the
biggest question on the trade agenda, the possible entry of China
into the World Trade Organization. But he laid out a broad case for
knocking down trade barriers and warned that attempts to halt the
development of a more global economy are futile and harmful.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan's influence could be of substantial help to the
Clinton administration as it seeks to complete a deal with China
and win congressional approval for the pact.
</P>
<P>
   But Greenspan criticized the administration for framing the
benefits of trade in what he called the wrong way. The point of
expanding trade is not to create new jobs, Greenspan said, directly
contradicting Clinton's main argument for why the United States
should be battling to open new markets. Rather, Greenspan said,
trade forces the United States to become more competitive, and to
use its resources _ people, technology and money _ in the most
productive way.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed chairman also took the administration and Congress to
task for taking what he called an overly narrow view of trade
relations, saying the benefits of trade to one country do not come
at the expense of another.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am concerned about the recent evident weakening of support
for free trade in this country,'' Greenspan said in a speech to
business executives and foreign ambassadors. ``Should we endeavor
to freeze competitive progress in place, we will almost certainly
slow economic growth overall and impart substantial harm to those
workers who would otherwise seek more effective longer-term job
opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan spoke after 10 days of debate within the
administration and throughout Washington over how hard to push for
a deal that would bring China under the internationally agreed
rules of trade.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Clinton backed away from a deal with China's prime
minister, Zhu Rongji, despite sweeping concessions from the Chinese
on a variety of trade issues. Clinton concluded that he would not
be able to win approval from Congress at a time when many members
of both parties are particularly unhappy with China because of
accusations that it has violated human rights, spread nuclear
weapons and spied on American weapons programs.
</P>
<P>
   But after criticism from business leaders, Clinton restarted
talks with China, and White House officials hope a deal can be
concluded swiftly.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin and other administration
officials who advised the president to go for a better deal,
Greenspan does not have to worry about marshaling votes for his
position. There are factions within both parties that oppose
further trade deals as unfair to American workers, and even among
those who are supportive there is a strong sense that other nations
too often fail to play by the rules.
</P>
<P>
   The House recently passed legislation that would restrict steel
imports from Russia and Japan, among other countries. And Clinton
has been unable to win stronger trade negotiating authority from
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of a deal with China said Greenspan's influence could
help in Congress, if business leaders and other groups who can
explain how more trade will help ordinary Americans also speak up.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question that we have to hear from people like
Greenspan and major CEOs, as well as the president of course,''
said Rep. Robert Matsui, D-Calif.
</P>
<P>
   But even some free trade supporters said Greenspan's absolutist
position _ he also criticized tactics like anti-dumping rules as
``simple guises for inhibiting competition'' _ failed to take
account of the effects that changing trade rules can have on
companies and workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main issue is not free trade versus protectionism,'' said
Rep. Sander Levin, D-Mich. ``The question is the structure in which
free trade will operate, which has become an especially salient
issue as globalization integrates evolving economies.''
</P>
<P>
   As seen by Greenspan, the effects of trade on workers and
companies is part of an all-but-unstoppable cycle of ``creative
destruction.'' In his view, a vibrant economy remakes itself
constantly by giving up on activities that some other country can
do more cheaply, and takes advantage of new opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be a great tragedy were we to stop the wheels of
progress because of an incapacity to assist the victims of
progress,'' Greenspan said.
</P>
</TEXT>
