<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-16 19:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1952 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-0417-     04-16 0981
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-0417-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ANGUISHED KOSOVAR ALBANIANS FLOOD OVER BORDERS OF ALBANIA AND
MACEDONIA
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-STRIKES-0417.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES and MARCIA KUNSTEL 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MORINA BORDER POINT, Albania _ Day and night Kosovo refugees
stumbled out of their country Friday, describing tens of thousands
following them in the wake of an increasingly brutal and systematic
Serbian-led Yugoslav campaign of ethnic cleansing.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly international aid agencies here realized Friday they
are ill-equipped to help.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shelter is a big problem, and hygiene and health,'' said Paul
Martin, coordinator here for the United Nations Children's Fund
(UNICEF), as he worriedly watched tractor caravans brimming with
close-packed bodies clear registration procedures at the border
checkpoint Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to mobilize. After the low numbers last week, I think
people weren't geared up for this.''
</P>
<P>
   Aid officials in Macedonia had the help of NATO troops who were
erecting thousands more tents at camps in anticipation of continued
waves of refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Well more than half of Kosovo's 2.2 million population -- 90
percent which are ethnic Albanians -- is estimated to have fled
already, but that still leaves around a
</P>
<P>
   million potential refugees should the Serb juggernaut continue.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're talking at the very least tens of thousands and
possibly in the hundreds of thousands. We have no way of knowing,''
said Ron Redmond, a spokesman for the United Nations High
Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) in Skopje, the capital of
Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   By midnight Friday about 10,000 had entered through the single
main Albania border crossing, tripling the entries of Thursday. At
least 6,000 crossed three border points into Macedonia, equalling
the number on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   They face troubling situations, especially in Albania.
</P>
<P>
   As of Friday morning, when the surge of refugees already had
begun crossing this border checkpoint, there were virtually no
available tents in the nearby city of Kukes where they will stay.
And many if not most of these new exiles were coming on foot,
without a car to shield them from rain or even a blanket to dull
the nighttime mountain cold.
</P>
<P>
   At a meeting of relief groups, water systems were reported to be
taxed to the limit in Kukes, where water already is being rationed
to a few hours a day to the permanent population.
</P>
<P>
   Agencies also reported almost no vacant, available land for
refugees coming in cars or the ubiquitous tractor-drawn wagons that
carry 15 to 40 people each.
</P>
<P>
   Many of those who crossed the borders Friday came in tears and
anguish.
</P>
<P>
   They told of killings, of girls being grabbed and kept by
Serbian police and army, of family separations, beatings, theft and
the conflagrations they say Serbian authorities made of their homes
back in Kosovo when they chased them out.
</P>
<P>
   Some had walked for five days and literally staggered over the
border with the help of family into the arms of waiting medics. Old
people were pushed across in wheelbarrows, sometimes by spouses
just as old. Cars sputtered and died, as their last fumes of fuel
evaporated.
</P>
<P>
   The first cases of malnutrition were seen, according to Angela
Walker, spokesperson for the World Food Program in Kukes.
</P>
<P>
   The sudden influx was attributed to the rigorous ethnic
cleansing campaigns refugees said the Serbs conducted Thursday and
Friday in cities including Urosevac in southeast Kosovo and the
Mitrovice metropolitan area in central Kosovo, where as many as
180,000 Kosovar Albanians had lived.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only the army is left now in Mitrovice, and the police,'' said
Maser Rixhebi, 40. He was driving a tractor hauling 27 people
including his family from the Mitrovice area, which he said the
Serbs have destroyed and totally depopulated of ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   Except for those who may try to hide in forests or mountains,
all the people from Mitrovice will be heading into Albania and
Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   Refugees arriving in Macedonia described a two-week-long
campaign of attacks on villages by Serbian army forces, police and
masked paramilitary gunmen.
</P>
<P>
   Serb forces are deliberately setting fires in the woodlands near
villages in an apparent effort to flush out hiding refugees, the
new arrivals said.
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials believe more than 400,000 ethnic Albanians in
Kosovo could be in hiding. But they are running low on food and
could fall victim to malnutrition and disease.
</P>
<P>
   About 3,000 refugees arrived Friday at the Macedonian border by
train from Urosevac, where they were allowed to pass freely by
Serbian forces.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those who came to the city, they are safe,'' said refugee
Arben Berisha, 40, who traveled with his family. ``We're worried
about our relatives and friends. There is no shelter. There is no
food, and now there are the fires. We pray for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Border scenes here in Albania were heart-breaking.
</P>
<P>
   Relatives who dragged along a teen-aged boy scarcely able to
walk said they had been hiding in the mountains for two weeks. They
described the ashen-faced boy as sick and exhausted, then rushed to
follow the medics who were taking his collapsed body for treatment
at a first aid tent.
</P>
<P>
   Zade Radce, a 50-year-old woman who looked like she could have
been 70, limped across the border with the aid of a cane. She had
been walking for five days and bore puss-filled abrasions on her
nose, cheek and upper lip, the souvenir of Serbian troops who she
said pushed her to the ground and stomped on her back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've gotten lost. I've gotten lost,'' she cried, holding the
hand of her 14-year-old stepdaughter, who clutched only a blanket.
She didn't know what had become of her husband.
</P>
<P>
   (Kunstel reported from Albania and Holmes from Macedonia.)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
