<DOCNO> NYT19990416.0287 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-16 19:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1956 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YUGOSLAVIA-BOS &LR;      04-16 1279
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALBANIAN REFUGEES POUR OUT OF KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH AND SUSAN MILLIGAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A new wave of thousands of Kosovar Albanian
refugees poured across the border Friday and a United Nations
official estimated as many as 100,000 could soon cross into
Macedonia. US officials reported fresh evidence of mass killings in
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   At least 5,000 refugees crossed into Macedonia on Friday, and
another 8,000 arrived in Albania by late afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   NATO, meanwhile, claimed one of its most punishing nights of
bombing Yugoslav targets Friday, even as the alliance faced new
questions about its accidental attack on a civilian convoy in
Kosovo and its true rate of success in destroying military sites.
</P>
<P>
   With a warning from Defense Secretary William Cohen that the air
campaign could last months, the Clinton administration Friday
prepared to call up 33,000 reservists and send Congress a request
for $5.9 billion to pay for the war effort and humanitarian relief.
</P>
<P>
   NATO's admission that a pilot accidentally bombed a civilian
convoy in Kosovo Wednesday continued to reverberate. Serbian
authorities charged that a second NATO attack killed civilians in
Kosovo, but NATO officials said they had no confirmation.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen, rebuffing any suggestion that the civilian deaths would
make NATO retreat, said: ``If anything, we are more solidly
determined to continue the air campaign and to start inflicting
more and more damage upon (Yugoslav President Slobodan) Milosevic's
forces . . . in the coming weeks and months, if necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   NATO's Thursday night bombing raids struck oil refineries,
airports, and other facilities, officials said. NATO planes also
attacked sites in the Yugoslav republic of Montenegro, where
President Milo Djukanovic expressed dismay at being targeted even
though ``Montenegro has contributed neither to the making nor to
the escalation of the Kosovo problem.''
</P>
<P>
   These other developments occurred Friday:
</P>
<P>
   --Ibrahim Rugova, an ethnic Albanian leader, met with Yugoslav
government officials. The Yugoslavs said Rugova discussed a peace
plan with them, but State Department spokesman James Rubin said
Rugova is being held against his will and should be allowed to
travel freely.
</P>
<P>
   --NATO officials said the Kosovo Liberation Army, made up of
ethnic Albanians, are contributing more to the fight against the
Serbs in Kosovo. A NATO spokesman said the KLA has risen ``like a
phoenix'' and is helping to put the Serbs ``in something of a
vise.''
</P>
<P>
   --President Clinton appealed to an audience in Michigan, home to
many people with roots in Serbia and Kosovo, to support his policy.
While acknowledging some protests by Serbian-Americans, Clinton
said ``our quarrel'' is with Milosevic, who ``believes it is all
right to kill people and to uproot them and to destroy their family
records and to erase any record of their presence in a land simply
because of their ethnic heritage.''
</P>
<P>
   Cohen confirmed that he is requesting the president call up a
``significant number'' of reservists, many of them from Air Force
Reserve and Air National Guard units that are trained in aerial
refueling and airlift. Army Reserve specialists in civil affairs
are also expected to be activated.
</P>
<P>
   State Department officials said they had new evidence, which
they did not immediately provide, of ``mass killings'' in Kosovo.
``We are developing evidence that is rather compelling...that in
west central Kosovo, west of Pristina, there is evidence of mass
killings and graves associated with those mass killings,'' Rubin
said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton administration officials continued to say publicly that
there was no intention of starting a ground war. But Senator James
M. Inhofe, Republican of Oklahoma, said the deployment of ground
troops into the combat zone had already begun. He cited the
announcement that 4,800 soldiers are going to staging areas in
Albania and that reserve troops are being called up.
</P>
<P>
   ``For all practical purposes, the debate over ground troops is
over,'' Inhofe said in a statement. ``President Clinton has always
wanted US ground troops in Kosovo, they always knew that air power
alone would not work, and now the initial deployments are going
on.'' Inhofe called the move illegal and mistaken.
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials said the air attacks were proving successful,
especially Thursday night. ``In fact,'' NATO spokesman Jamie Shea
said, ``it was one of the best nights thus far in our campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Pentagon Friday, officials continued their daily practice
of showing video footage from NATO aircraft of successful bomb
attacks.
</P>
<P>
   After the films were run, a reporter asked the Pentagon briefer,
Major General Charles F. Wald of the US Air Force, why he wasn't
showing footage of bombs that missed their targets. A number of
military analysts have said that NATO may have a low rate of
destroying targets.
</P>
<P>
   Wald, after promising to show more videos of misses, said the
Gulf War experience showed an average of ``80 to 90 percent hits.''
Wald said he did not know if that applied to the air campaign over
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   President Djukanovic had harsh words for NATO attacks on
Montenegro, which is part of the Yugoslav federation but has been
relatively pro-Western.
</P>
<P>
   ``The consequences of the bombing are horrific,'' Djukanovic
said at a press conference. ``Montenegro has contributed neither to
the making nor to the escalation of the Kosovo problem. However, as
a republic of Yugoslavia, it is suffering drastic consequences of
the NATO strikes.''
</P>
<P>
   Military targets in Montenegro were bombed Thursday evening; no
casualties have been reported. An airfield in Montenegro has been
``extensively targeted'' because Yugoslav aircraft based there
posed an increasing threat to NATO forces in Albania, said Brig.
Gen. Guiseppe Marani, a NATO spokesman in Brussels.
</P>
<P>
   Air raid sirens blared Friday afternoon in Montenegro, and there
was a small but heated anti-NATO demonstration in front of the old
American Center offices, but no bombs fell.
</P>
<P>
   Djukanovic has been walking a thin line in the conflict, trying
to keep from provoking either the West or Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   But Montenegro has nonetheless been subjected to bombing, has
accepted more than 100,000 refugees, and is in an increasingly
tense situation with the Yugoslav National Army, which has 20,000
troops spread throughout Montenegro.
</P>
<P>
   Djukanovic dismissed the possibility of a much-rumored military
coup against him. But he said he was sure Milosevic would continue
to try to inject upheaval into Montenegro ``to ensure an overthrow
of the government here.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as Mr. Milosevic is in power, and I hope that it will
not be for much longer, there will be an ongoing attempt by his
side to repress democracy,'' Djukanovic said. Djukanovic said the
army had a ``legitimate right'' to defend Montenegro from a NATO
assault and said he would never approve of the sending of NATO
ground troops from Montenegro to be used in neighboring Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   Britain's defense secretary, George Robertson, speaking at
Harvard's John F. Kennedy School of Government Friday, called the
NATO campaign in Kosovo ``a defining moment in the aftermath of the
Cold War.'' Democratic nations, he said, ``have to draw a clear
line against the notion that the solution to ethnic conflict is to
shift populations around as though they were worthless counters in
some elaborate board-game.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Milligan reported from Montenegro, with contributions by John
Yemma of the Globe staff. Wire service material was used to prepare
this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
