   GREENSPAN-TRADE (Washington) _ Alan Greenspan, the Federal
Reserve chairman, waded into the escalating debate over trade
policy today, denouncing protectionism and arguing that pockets of
workers sometimes had to suffer in order for the national economy
to grow stronger. Greenspan did not directly address the biggest
question on the trade agenda, the possible entry of China into the
World Trade Organization. But he cited rising protectionist
sentiment as one of the biggest threats to the long-term economic
health of the United States, and suggested that any steps to reduce
trade barriers, even if not fully reciprocated, would have
substantial benefits. By Richard W. Stevenson.
