<HEADER>
A1958 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NH-TAX-BOS &LR;      04-16 0766
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NH-TAX-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHAHEEN CALLS FOR INCOME TAX BILL _ SO SHE CAN VETO IT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RALPH JIMENEZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, N. H. _ In an angry message to the Democratically
controlled Senate she worked hard to elect, New Hampshire Gov.
Jeanne Shaheen Friday implored senators to pass an income tax bill
to help end the state's school funding crisis. Then, she said, she
could swifly veto it.
</P>
<P>
   Shaheen has consistently said the giving New Hampshire its first
ever income tax is not the way to fund public schools. But, two
weeks after a court-imposed deadline passed, lawmakers have yet to
find the money, and Shaheen blames income-tax advocates for the
stalemate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is now April 16. Many teachers have been pink slipped, our
bond rating is in jeopardy and our communities face grave financial
uncertainty. The income tax stranglehold must come to an end,''
Shaheen said.
</P>
<P>
   Her blunt words reflect the deep frustration that has settled on
Concord. In the past week angry educators have bombarded
legislators with letters and calls; the state's capital city has
threatened a lawsuit of its own; an $825 million tax plan with
Shaheen's backing was pulled back while under attack and the mood
in the State House is uglier than anything veteran lawmakers can
remember.
</P>
<P>
   And while their debate moves in circles, Wall Street bond rating
agencies are hinting heavily that city and state credit ratings
could be downgraded, raising interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``They still have time,''said Gary Mescher, a Moody's Investors
Service vice president and the company's chief New Hampshire
analyst, but ``the clock is ticking.''
</P>
<P>
   The current crisis is another step in a nationwide fight over
what critics charge is inequitable school funding. In New
Hampshire, which has until now relied mostly on local propert taxes
to pay for schools, tax rates vary by as much as fifteen-fold
between poor and wealthy communities. New Hampshire is one of 36
states where a lawsuit has challenged the old system, and one of 20
where the lawsuit was successful.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of that lawsuit, the court gave lawmaker until April
1 to find a new source of funding.
</P>
<P>
   But finding a solution has proved especially complicated here
because the state has long resisted enacting a broad base sales or
income tax. The court's decision, and the ensuing political crises,
has encouraged those who want an income tax because it would make
the state's tax structure more progressive. According to a ranking
in Congressional Quarterly, the state is among the least
progressive _ 45th of 50 _ in the union.
</P>
<P>
   Yet an income tax proposal died in legislative maneuvering. And
none of the many other proposals has emerged from the fray.
</P>
<P>
   The impasse has left school districts who are trying to plan
their next year's budgets, and hire teachers, stymied. In Franklin,
the high school is on academic probation and the school boiler
won't last another winter, said school board member Donna Gilbreth.
</P>
<P>
   ``They still hold classes up in the gym but they can't put too
many people in it because then the asbestos starts flaking off and
falling down on the people below,'' Gilbreth said.
</P>
<P>
   Though their paychecks will not stop until July, teachers are
finding that even a pink slip sent as a formality can have serious
repercussions.
</P>
<P>
   ``One teacher told me that she was asked to sign for a college
loan for her child but couldn't get a letter from her school
district saying that she had a guaranteed income. Another teacher
told me that he couldn't close on his mortgage,'' said Dennis
Murphy, spokesman for the state's largest teachers union.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in Concord, tempers were so short on Thursday that
Speaker of the House Donna Sytek gave members of the finance
committee a long weekend to cool off. The House is not scheduled to
meet again until next Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the Senate will consider Shaheen's exasperated
request to pass on the income tax proposal. Senators will also
consider a plan crafted late Friday by 12 Democrats which would
include a capital gains tax and statewide property taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Still, with tax plans, alliances and meeting schedules changing
almost hourly anything could happen next week.
</P>
<P>
   Or nothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the biggest dysfunctional famly I've ever seen,'' said
Gordon Allen, an economist and former house finance committee
member who is tracking progress for a citizens group. ``The turkey
is burned up. The family is drunk and several of the uncles are
having a fistfight in the backyard.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
