<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CATHOLIC-PRIESTS-450&AMP;ADD-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLIGHT RISE IN NUMBER OF MEN STUDYING TO BE ROMAN CATHOLIC
PRIESTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo and graphic are being sent to NYT photo and graphic
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.) 
(rk) 
 By GUSTAV NIEBUHR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a sign that a long downward trend in enrollment may be
ending, the number of men studying at the nation's graduate-level
seminaries to become Roman Catholic priests has risen to the
highest level in five years, according to a study by a Catholic
social science research center.
</P>
<P>
   The study, by the Center for Applied Research in the Apostolate,
at Georgetown University, found that 3,386 men in the United States
were enrolled in graduate-level theological work for the priesthood
in the current academic year, up by 228 from last year and the
highest figure since 1993-94.
</P>
<P>
   Catholic officials concede that even the current numbers of
seminarians at the graduate level _ the level from which candidates
for the priesthood are ordained _ are not enough to replace the
priests who retire or die each year, a circumstance that helps
account for the sharp rise in the church's need for people to enter
lay ministries.
</P>
<P>
   But the center's findings suggest that a precipitate falloff in
the number of men preparing for the Catholic priesthood has abated
significantly.
</P>
<P>
   ``This reflects a general stability in enrollment,'' said Bryan
T. Froehle, the center's executive director.
</P>
<P>
   Froehle and others who have studied the issue attribute the
development to the expansion of two-year pre-graduate-level
programs, largely for older men considering the priesthood; a
slight rise in the number of college-level seminarians, and
stepped-up recruitment efforts by bishops.
</P>
<P>
   But the Rev. Raymond F. Collins, dean of the school of religious
studies at the Catholic University of America, in Washington, said
he thought that the trend toward enrollment stability was not
evenly spread among seminaries and instead reflected an increase in
enrollment at conservative institutions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's one major factor,'' Collins said. ``It's hardly
a uniform trend.''
</P>
<P>
   Immigrant Catholics also account for an important share of
seminarians. The Rev. Timothy T. Reker, executive director of
vocations and priestly formation at the U.S. Catholic Conference,
said 24 percent of the men scheduled to graduate from seminaries in
1999 were born outside the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing that we certainly notice this year is 5 percent were
born in Vietnam,'' Reker said. ``The next-highest would be Mexico,
3 percent this year.''
</P>
<P>
   The study also found that the number of lay people enrolled in
professional-level training programs for church work like religious
education, youth ministry or parish administration had risen to
29,137 at present from 10,500 in 1985. These figures are a sign of
the church's growing demand for workers as the number of priests
declines while the Catholic population rises.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Rev. Thomas J. Reese, editor of the Jesuit magazine America,
whose April 10 issue includes an article detailing the church's
need for lay staff, said, ``We're seeing today a tremendous
increase in the number of lay people involved in direct ministry in
the church, either as volunteers or paid staff people.''
</P>
<P>
   Reese attributed that increase not only to the importance that
the Second Vatican Council placed on the laity's role but also to
the decline in the number of the nation's Roman Catholic priests:
from over 60,000 to under 50,000 in the last three decades, during
which the Catholic population in the United States has risen above
61 million.
</P>
<P>
   That drop in the number of priests is reflected in the long
downward trend in seminary enrollment. The number of young men
enrolled in graduate level, college and high school seminary
programs topped 30,000 in the late 1960s, more than five times the
current level. ``The attrition,'' Froehle said, ``was always
greatest in the high schools and colleges,'' which fed seminarians
to the graduate level.
</P>
<P>
   What has helped bolster the graduate-level ranks, Froehle said,
is the expansion of ``pre-theology'' programs directed at older
men, college graduates who do not have the training in philosophy,
theology and spiritual direction needed for a graduate-level,
four-year seminary.
</P>
<P>
   The number of students enrolled in such pre-theology programs,
who were counted in the new study, has risen fourfold since 1980,
to 635. (Some say, on the other hand, that the larger number of
older candidates for the priesthood means that the church is
relying on men whose active service will be shorter, perhaps by a
decade or more, than the customary candidate who enters the
seminary straight from preparatory study in college.)
</P>
<P>
   Reker said this year's increase among graduate-level seminarians
was also at least partly a result of a greater involvement by
American bishops in talking to men about entering the priesthood.
</P>
<P>
   And, he said, anecdotal evidence from seminaries suggests that
there is ``a great deal of hope'' for enrollments next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``My sense is a corner has been turned,'' he said, ``and the
outlook is more positive again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
