<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-WELFARE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WELFARE REFORM STUDY   PAINTS ROSY PICTURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JORDANA HART  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Massachusetts' first long-term study of life after
welfare, released Friday, indicates former recipients have higher
incomes now, and feel better about themselves.
</P>
<P>
   A year after leaving welfare in early 1997, about 71 percent of
those families who responded to the survey had full-time members
earning an average gross monthly wage of $1,400, more than double
the typical $579 cash grant on welfare.
</P>
<P>
   Three months after leaving welfare in 1997, nearly half of those
who had jobs also reported having health insurance through their
employer. And after a year, half of those who responded to the
survey reported that the state was still subsidizing their child
care.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the study showed about 18 percent of the households
interviewed had returned to welfare within three months after
leaving, and about 21 percent had gone back on the rolls within a
year.
</P>
<P>
   Welfare reform critics pounded the study Friday, saying the
results were skewed by small interview samples of people who left
welfare before they were forced off by time limits. Those people,
critics say, were better prepared to work and do not represent the
hard-core welfare cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``The study has rose-tinted glasses on,'' said Mac D'Alessandro,
coordinator of the Family Economic Initiative, a coalition of
advocates and organizations working with poor families.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, even state officials balked at statistics showing
that only one in five eligible families was receiving federal Food
Stamps three months after leaving the rolls, even though more
families reported going hungry right after they left the welfare
rolls.
</P>
<P>
   ``The transition is not easy for everyone,'' said State
Department of Transitional Assistance Commissioner Claire McIntire
Friday. ``We have to, and will, do a better job of making former
recipients aware of their availability.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, McIntire called the study ``encouraging,'' and said it
bolstered the department's philosophy that jobs are the key to
ending dependence on government aid.
</P>
<P>
   ``This certainly reinforces our philosphy that full-time work is
a critical step in escaping the clutches of poverty,'' McIntire
said.
</P>
<P>
   But Deborah Harris, a lawyer with the Massachusetts Law reform
Institute, said the survey response was inadequate.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 647 randomly selected cases, only about half of them
responded to the first round of surveys. By the fourth round of
surveys, participation had dropped to about a third of those
households.
</P>
<P>
   Harris argued that many of those who answered all three rounds
of the surveys were those families who were still doing well.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are more likely to respond if they're feeling good,''
she said. ``People feeling hostile are less likely to respond.''
</P>
<P>
   Sifting through the numbers, advocates for welfare families said
that only 56 percent of all families who were interviewed a year
after leaving welfare actually had a member who worked.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the best of the bunch,'' said Randy Albelda, a labor
economist at the University of Massachusetts/Boston, who studies
poverty. ``These aren't folks forced off. This is the best face of
the impact of welfare reform.''
</P>
<P>
   Albelda, the co-author of a May 1998 study of welfare time
limits, pointed out that, even by the survey's own data, families
of four making $1,399 a month earn just slightly more than $16,450
a year _ the current federal poverty level.
</P>
<P>
   Since the state's welfare reform legislation was signed into law
in February 1995, the rolls have dropped from 102,993 families to
53,818 families, according to state figures.
</P>
<P>
   In Dec. 1, 1998, 5,100 families _ each typically consisting of a
mother with two children over age 2 _ began to see their cash
benefits run out. Of those families, 2,800 applied for last-minute
extensions because they could not find a job or child care.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, of the 2,220 extension requests reviewed so far,
state officials had approved only about 12 percent, making
Massachusetts one of the strictest in the nation in adhering to
time-limited cash aid.
</P>
<P>
   The results of the new survey were gleaned from two sets of
interviews of 341 families who left welfare in the first half of
1997. Welfare workers conducted one set of interviews three months
after the families left welfare, and the other was done a year
after, with 210 of the same families interviewed for both.
</P>
<P>
   In other survey findings:
</P>
<P>
   _ Thirty-three percent of those who had jobs said they were a
little better off since leaving welfare, while 26 percent said they
were much better off.
</P>
<P>
   _ Some 95 percent of those surveyed said their children had
MassHealth or some other kind of health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   _ Nearly half of all the families reported using friends and
relatives for child care, instead of licensed centers or family day
care.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
