<SLUG> BC-TELEMARKETER-CON-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TELEPHONE CALL WAS A CON GAME FROM JAIL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By NEIL MODIE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ One of the nice things about telemarketing is that you
can do it from home _ even when home is the King County jail.
</P>
<P>
   Lowell Nelson, a retiree who lives near Burien, a suburb of
Seattle, said Thursday that a telemarketer called last Saturday
night with this pitch: earn $25 by accessing a casino's Internet
Web site and completing a survey there about gambling preferences.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson declined. But after hanging up, he noticed his phone's
caller ID said the pitch came from a jail inmate telephone.
Puzzled, he notified authorities, who traced it to a phone
accessible to 64 inmates at the Kent Regional Justice Center.
</P>
<P>
   Jailers noted that one of those inmates gave his occupation as
``telemarketer'' when he was booked March 31 on two counts of check
forgery in Tukwila, Wash. He has a 10-year record of arrests for
other forgeries, burglary, theft, possession of stolen property and
other crimes.
</P>
<P>
   But the inmate denies making the call, and his former employer
says he wasn't continuing to make calls on any of its accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Center Commander Ray Coleman said Thursday that
investigators can't prove which inmate was involved. And while
telemarketing from behind bars may be tacky, it's legal. Coleman
said the casino Web site seems legitimate, though the investigation
continues.
</P>
<P>
   The silver lining in the incident, Coleman said, is that it
proved the jail's sophisticated caller ID system works _ sort of.
To protect crime victims and witnesses from harassment, anyone
receiving a call from a jail phone hears a recording saying where
the call is coming from and what inmate is making it.
</P>
<P>
   The telemarketing inmate, however, got around the recording by
going through a third party, a jail rule violation punishable by
loss of privileges. But at least caller ID gave the inmate away,
Coleman noted.
</P>
<P>
   And lest there are any doubts, Coleman emphasized the jail ``is
in no way conducting any telemarketing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-16-99 1955EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
