<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-16 19:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1964 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZ-JIM-NAPLES-ART-$A     04-16 0931
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-JIM-NAPLES-ART-$ADV18-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MANAGER WHO MOVED FROM INNINGS TO ARIAS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif., N.Y.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 18)  
 (af)  
 By LAURA PEDERSEN-PIETERSEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When a headhunter called him in 1986 to ask if he
wanted to become house manager for the Met, James H. Naples Jr.
immediately thought of shortstops at Shea Stadium, not coloraturas
at Lincoln Center. At the time, Naples, then 35, was in charge of a
staff of 900 as manager of Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   If the offer was out of left field, the destination wasn't. The
recruiter told him that the Metropolitan Opera House had gone
through 22 house managers in 20 years and that ``anyone who can
last 10 years with George Steinbrenner can do this job.''
</P>
<P>
   Naples accepted the offer and, like legions of other workers in
an age of ever-changing career paths, demonstrated that his skills
were indeed portable. Economists note that despite low unemployment
today, the labor force is still churning with workers losing,
changing and gaining jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Skills are becoming increasingly transferable from job to job
and industry to industry,'' said Paul Saffo, a director of the
Institute for the Future, a forecasting and research firm in Menlo
Park, Calif. ``While expertise may be limited, an individual's
skills may be very transferable.''
</P>
<P>
   Naples developed many skills in his Yankee Stadium job. In
addition to overseeing all home games, he was in charge of
high-pressure events like four World Series, the 1976 championship
fight between Muhammad Ali and Ken Norton and a Mass celebrated by
Pope John Paul II in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   For that one, Naples remembers praying for a logistical miracle;
he had to coordinate communion logistics for 80,000 people _ 23,000
more than the stadium usually holds.
</P>
<P>
   The job, of course, had rewards. At the Mass, he escorted the
pope onto the field as they chatted. After-hours during baseball
season, he passed the time with the likes of Billy Martin, the
often fired and rehired manager. The most memorable night was at
Jimmy Weston's restaurant in Manhattan, talking baseball with Frank
Sinatra.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his love of the game, Naples eventually heeded the
recruiter. Managing Yankee Stadium required up to 100 hours a week.
Having married two years earlier, he had a 1-year-old daughter whom
he hardly had time to see. Working for the Yankees was ``a dream
job for someone who's single,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Offered a better compensation package and a more sensible
schedule, Naples traded himself to the Met, where he has stayed 13
years. He manages 13 departments and 250 people, who work under
several labor contracts he helps to negotiate. He is in charge of
the building, security, the box office, the cleaning crews and the
ushers. And not just during the opera season, since the Met plays
host to groups including the American Ballet Theater and the Kirov
Ballet.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's actually not that different from my old job,'' he said.
``There we were presenting baseball and here we're presenting
opera.'' His workweek, however, is more manageable; he works about
50 hours.
</P>
<P>
   But how does a guy who was a pre-law student at Canisius College
in Buffalo _and who never took a business class _ become a
businessman, manager and negotiator?
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned about people from my father,'' he said. ``He owned a
bar in Buffalo where I worked as a kid, and you figure out pretty
quick who is real and who you want to emulate and, conversely, whom
you don't want to be like.''
</P>
<P>
   That's how Naples got to know Steinbrenner, who was a frequent
patron of the bar in the late 1960s, when he traveled to Buffalo on
business for his family's shipping companies.
</P>
<P>
   Steinbrenner later took control of the Yankees. In 1976, after
the renovation of Yankee Stadium, he asked Naples, then 25, to
oversee the ball park's concessions and luxury suites at a starting
salary of $16,000. After a year, Naples became assistant stadium
manager; in 1980, he became manager and in 1984 he received the
additional title of vice president.
</P>
<P>
   Naples also relied on lessons learned from watching an uncle,
Max Margulis, a Buffalo nightclub impresario, handle not only his
staff but also stars like Mel Torme and Aretha Franklin.
</P>
<P>
   What about his own management techniques? ``I'm in touch with
all department heads almost daily and my door is always open,''
Naples said. ``The minute I get to work there are eight people with
eight problems. Solving them is like winning, and I love winning.''
</P>
<P>
   He has learned his negotiating skills on the job. Steinbrenner
and Joseph Volpe, general manager of the Met, ``are not only
visionaries in their respective fields but sagacious negotiators,''
Naples said. ``I've learned from them how to make both sides feel
like they've accomplished something.''
</P>
<P>
   A recent surge in matters operatic has not hurt Naples's career.
The Met has added performances, television broadcasts and
recordings; attendance has risen and deficits have vanished. A
survey by the National Endowment for the Arts shows that opera
attendance rose 12.5 percent nationwide between 1992 and 1997.
</P>
<P>
   And in saying goodbye to World Series rings and hello to
Wagner's, Naples has found more time to spend with his wife, Nancy,
and their children, Nicole, 14; Jimmy, 11, and Gavin, 5. Though he
hasn't chatted with the pope recently, Naples talked with President
Clinton at opening night last fall.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
