<HEADER>
A1965 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZ-GROWERS-CO-OPS-AR     04-16 1049
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-GROWERS-CO-OPS-ART-$ADV18-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW TOO MUCH PURPLE COULD MEAN LESS GREEN
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 18)  
 (af)  
 By CONSTANCE L. HAYS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, Mass. _ At first glance it seems pretty simple. A food
processing company with a strong brand in a relatively narrow niche
finds the competition toughening and the niche's sales trend
flattening.
</P>
<P>
   To grow, it needs to extend its brand to new product categories,
to make acquisitions, or both. That calls for a big financial
commitment, which most companies can raise by tapping capital
markets.
</P>
<P>
   But Welch Foods isn't most companies: it is owned by a farmers'
cooperative, the National Grape Cooperative Association. And that
makes meeting its competitive challenges anything but
straightforward.
</P>
<P>
   With roots in 19th century agrarian socialism, co-ops can seem a
quaint counterpoint to the unbridled capitalism energizing most of
the economy. But they play a huge role in American agriculture. And
the value-added co-ops _ the ones like National Grape that process
members' produce into consumer products rather than just handling
bulk commodities _ own more well-known supermarket brands than many
consumers realize.
</P>
<P>
   Co-ops help farmers by assuring that each year's harvest will be
bought at predictable prices and by sharing profits, expertise and
purchasing muscle. But the ownership structure can also be a
significant competitive handicap.
</P>
<P>
   By definition, a co-op cannot sell stock or use it to pay for
acquisitions, or even build a war chest of cash from retained
earnings; profits must be distributed to the members each year. So
co-ops often have a difficult time financing major expansion,
unless they borrow or merge with other co-ops, as many dairy co-ops
have been doing.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, National Grape has managed to find steady if
unspectacular growth by aggressively marketing the Welch's line of
juices, jellies and related products, whose sales topped $600
million in 1998. But against increased competition from publicly
traded companies with formidable marketing and financial strengths,
Welch's now needs to look further afield.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have the capability to get beyond the billion-dollar mark
in sales,'' said Ted Dardani, a principal with BT Capital Partners,
a unit of Bankers Trust, who has worked with Welch's on acquisition
and joint venture ideas. ``They have done a very good job of
building their brands back. The point now is, how can Welch's take
all that brand equity and expertise and do some other product lines
that make sense?''
</P>
<P>
   Welch's now finds its longtime strength, an undistracted focus
on jelly and juice, turning into a shortcoming, as ever more rushed
Americans skip eating a traditional breakfast and demand sags.
</P>
<P>
   For decades after the co-op acquired it in 1945, Welch's did
well by remaining steadfastly grape-centric and conservative. It
shunned new product development and avoided advertising spending
like a bad grape disease. But by 1983, that strategy was flagging,
and the co-op was in danger of reneging on its promise to buy 70
percent of its members' ever-growing harvests, according to Daniel
P. Dillon, the president of Welch's, who joined the company around
that time as a vice president.
</P>
<P>
   Welch's management overcame initial resistance from the growers
and shifted gears, stepping up marketing to rebuild demand through
new TV advertising and a revival of the cartoon-character jelly
glasses that were a 1960s hit.
</P>
<P>
   The company paid for and trumpeted a study that concluded,
somewhat controversially, that white grape juice is better than
apple juice for babies and toddlers suffering from diarrhea because
it is lower in sorbitol. It seized on studies in France finding
that red wine helps control cholesterol, hoping that they would rub
off on grape juice.
</P>
<P>
   And it stretched the juice line any way it could, with new
blends like pineapple-banana, frozen smoothies, concentrates that
don't require refrigeration and, briefly, kosher grape juice. A new
research center tests innovations like a plastic can for frozen
juice that can be thawed in a microwave. And there are plans for
more single-serving items, an area where Ocean Spray (another
co-op) has made great strides.
</P>
<P>
   ``To really push ahead in the juice business, you have to
deliver more than one kind of juice,'' said Kevin Murphy, chief
operating officer of Ocean Spray, which recently bought a big stake
in Nantucket Nectars. ``I don't think Welch has been aggressive in
that regard. They've really tried to stretch grape juice out.''
Murphy questioned whether Welch's should use scarce resources to
chase growth in a shrinking category like frozen concentrate.
</P>
<P>
   But moving beyond grape juices means tangling with the likes of
Pepsico's Tropicana, Coca-Cola and Cadbury-Schweppes, a league in
which Welch's is at a distinct disadvantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``My competition isn't the local cooperative down the road,''
said Joe Falcone, a National Grape board member and
fourth-generation grape farmer. ``It's Nestle, and Pepsi, and big
companies like that,'' which can raise capital faster and more
flexibly. Still, co-ops can take advantage of low-interest loans
from the National Cooperative Bank, a $19 billion entity that lends
only to them.
</P>
<P>
   Much of what has kept Welch's intact can also hold it back. With
grape farmers for owners, ``it's a conservative environment,'' said
Rex Green, a managing director at Advest, a Boston investment bank
that has advised Welch's. ``These are men and women of the soil,
rather than day traders. They look at their company and their
stewardship of Welch's in the long term.''
</P>
<P>
   The next step for Welch's seems to be acquiring or pursuing
joint ventures with companies that make other kinds of consumer
packaged foods. Executives were quiet about specific plans.
</P>
<P>
   Approaching such ventures slowly works in Welch's favor, Green
said. ``They have an excellent record of not launching failed
products,'' he said. ``They can't afford to invest the capital, and
then not have it work. That absolutely reflects being in the
environment of a co-op.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
