<HEADER>
A1966 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIDS-DRUG17-COX     04-16 0462
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIDS-DRUG17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SCIENCE/HEALTH: Latest AIDS treatment gets FDA approval
 &HT;    By Lillian Lee Kim
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Food and Drug Administration on Friday approved a
new AIDS drug, the latest in the class of powerful medications that
has revolutionized HIV/AIDS treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Agenerase, also known as amprenavir, received the FDA's approval
in an accelerated process aimed at getting new AIDS drugs onto the
market as quickly as possible. Discovered by Vertex Pharmaceuticals
and licensed to Glaxo Wellcome, the leader in HIV drug development,
Agenerase brings the total number of approved AIDS drugs to 15.
</P>
<P>
   The drug belongs to the class called protease inhibitors, named
for the way in which they cripple the reproduction of HIV, the AIDS
virus.
</P>
<P>
   Agenerase has an advantage over the other five protease
inhibitors on the market: It has no food restrictions and has to be
taken only twice daily, compared to three times for the others.
With eight capsules per dose, it's still a cumbersome medication.
</P>
<P>
   ``The chemistry of the molecule required that we have a very
sophisticated formulation that would facilitate absorption of
amprenavir into the body,'' said Mike Rogers, Glaxo Wellcome's
project leader for Agenerase.
</P>
<P>
   More than three years ago, when protease inhibitors were
introduced, they dramatically improved the life expectancy and
quality of life for many with HIV. Terminally ill patients made
deathbed recoveries.
</P>
<P>
   Within a few years, that optimism was tempered by the
realization that protease inhibitors weren't as effective long-term
as researchers had hoped.
</P>
<P>
   Many patients developed resistance to the drugs, as HIV swiftly
mutated into less vulnerable forms. All AIDS drugs have severe side
effects, but those accompanying protease inhibitors proved to be
the harshest: diabetes, life-threateningly high cholesterol levels
and a bizarre condition called lipodystrophy, in which body fat is
redistributed to the stomach and back.
</P>
<P>
   Short-term results from extensive human trials of Agenerase
indicate it is fairly well tolerated.
</P>
<P>
   Another major selling point of Agenerase is that it doesn't
appear to be cross-resistant with other protease inhibitors,
providing a new, much-needed option to patients who already have
developed drug resistance. Like other AIDS drugs, Agenerase is
extremely costly: $16.80 per day, or $6,132 per year. Protease
inhibitors range in price from $5,220 to $7,344 per year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's actually at the low end _ not that I'm endorsing the
price, because all of them are priced too high,'' said Dan Dunable,
the treatment resource specialist at AIDS Survival Project in
Midtown.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
