<DOCNO> NYT19990416.0298 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-16 19:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1967 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ATL-HEALTH-MAGNETS17     04-16 0542
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATL-HEALTH-MAGNETS17 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SCIENCE/HEALTH: Magnet pain relief attracting more patients
 &HT;    By Diane Lore
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Browns' vacation was less than ideal.
</P>
<P>
   Although they were in picturesque Hilton Head Island, S.C.,
Charles Brown spent most of his time on a couch _ the result of
pulling his back while playing golf.
</P>
<P>
   ``And although we can laugh about it now,'' said his wife,
Leigh, ``it really was not much fun at the time.''
</P>
<P>
   But when they came home, the Browns bought two therapeutic
magnets from Smart Solutions, a home health equipment store, and
within a day, they were off to Panama City _ for a much better
round of relaxation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was unreal how fast they worked,'' said Charles Brown.
``Now we use them all the time, and we loan them to friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Therapeutic magnets have been around for more than six decades
in Asia and Europe. In Japan, the No. 1 therapeutic magnet company,
Nikken, has gross sales of more than $10 billion. In the United
States, however, the Food and Drug Administration has not approved
their use, but it hasn't banned them either. Instead, they've been
treated as a harmless form of fringe treatment _ up there with
herbal remedies.
</P>
<P>
   But in the past five years, doctors and biophysicists have been
giving magnets another look, especially since companies selling
magnetic products are finally subjecting the treatment to rigorous
clinical studies. At Vanderbilt University Medical Center in
Nashville, Tenn., and Baylor College of Medicine in Houston,
doctors testing magnetic products for pain relief are convinced
that magnets are producing dramatic results.
</P>
<P>
   At Baylor, for instance, researchers found magnet therapy eased
the pain in 76 percent of patients with post-polio syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   Magnetherapy Inc., founded in 1995, reports $25 million in
sales. It plans to submit several clinical studies for FDA review
this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that we have some good double-blind studies, this is what
we can safely say: Magnetics can reduce pain. If you've got an achy
joint or lower back pain, magnets could help,'' said Dr. Arthur
Pilla, director of the Bioelectrochemistry Laboratory at the Mount
Sinai School of Medicine in New York. Pilla also is the chairman of
the scientific and medical advisory committee for Magnetherapy Inc.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, how it works is a mystery. Magnets may somehow
trigger the healing action of cells at a molecular level, changing
the oxygen and nutrient level of the tissue.
</P>
<P>
   Pilla said that magnets may merely trigger the body to do what
it's supposed to do. ``These magnetic signals are very weak,'' he
said. ``But it might be like a pacemaker, which triggers the heart
muscle to pump but doesn't provide the energy for the action.''
</P>
<P>
   Several factors, however, are still unknown. For example, most
therapeutic magnets fall within the range of 50 to 1,000 gauss, the
measure by which magnetism is calculated. A refrigerator magnet has
a power of about 50 gauss. But doctors don't know if that range is
really the most effective or not, because few scientific studies
have been done on the health benefits of magnet therapies.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-16-99 1957EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
