<HEADER>
A1971 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZ-NONPROFIT-ART-$AD     04-16 0850
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-NONPROFIT-ART-$ADV18-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANAGING WHEN PROFIT ISN'T THE GOAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y., Conn.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 18)  
 (af)  
 By TODD COHEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nonprofit organizations, long known as an invisible sector in
the economy, have grown rapidly over the last two decades, now
accounting for 8 percent of the gross domestic product.
</P>
<P>
   To meet the rising demand for trained leaders for these groups,
a number of universities are offering graduate programs in
nonprofit management.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not enough to only want to do good; you have to do good
well,'' said Michael Seltzer, acting chairman of the master's
program in nonprofit management at the New School University in
Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   The number of charitable nonprofit groups grew from 82,000 in
1975 to 181,000 in 1995, the most recent data available, according
to the Internal Revenue Service.
</P>
<P>
   And in the last decade, the number of American universities
offering three or more graduate courses in nonprofit management has
grown from 17 to 82, say researchers at Seton Hall University,
which offers a program of its own. Other universities with big
nonprofit programs include Auburn, Boston University, De Paul and
Notre Dame.
</P>
<P>
   The programs do have their critics, who contend, among other
things, that they have too narrow a focus for students who may
switch fields later.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the surge in degree programs reflects rising competition
for support from foundations, corporations and government, which
increasingly expect nonprofits to be more professional, said Alan
J. Abramson, director of the Nonprofit Sector Research Fund of the
Aspen Institute in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   People who move to nonprofit work from business or government
jobs may have leadership experience, Abramson said, but they may
want more training in nonprofit issues.
</P>
<P>
   Consider Jeff Aulenbach. Two years ago, he worked for the mental
health department in New York City, managing contracts with
nonprofit groups. He wanted to work for a nonprofit, but lacked the
skills he thought necessary. So he enrolled part-time in the
master's program at the New School.
</P>
<P>
   A year later, while still taking classes, he landed a job as
executive director of the Variety Boys and Girls Club of Queens.
``I could not have gotten the job without the program,'' Aulenbach
said.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, he moved to a larger organization, as assistant
executive director of the Gloria Wise Boys and Girls Club in the
Bronx. He expects to finish the New School program next year.
</P>
<P>
   Aulenbach said classes on topics like financial planning and
marketing taught him ``every issue that an executive director needs
to deal with.'' At Gloria Wise, he applies lessons of his
leadership class to help program directors work together after a
string of mergers.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the students are nonprofit managers who take classes
part-time, with assignments often focusing on their real jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because I was in classes with nonprofit managers all the time,
I understood what the day-to-day challenges of working in a
nonprofit were like,'' said Armanda Famiglietti, a 1993 New School
graduate who manages grants for the Carnegie Corp. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone is impressed with a nonprofit-management degree.
Peter Dobkin Hall, director of Yale Divinity School's program on
nonprofit organizations, called the credential ``a degree of
unproven and dubious value,'' explaining, ``there is no such thing
as generic nonprofit management.'' His program focuses on research
rather than on teaching management skills.
</P>
<P>
   To accommodate job-switching, he said, ``you want to give people
portable skills, skills that are as applicable to the public sector
as to the business sector or the nonprofit sector.''
</P>
<P>
   Pablo Eisenberg, senior fellow at the Georgetown University
Public Policy Institute, said nonprofit graduate programs tend to
focus on internal issues like fund-raising and accounting, not on
external issues like collaboration with business and government.
``Most of them are really creating technicians, '' Eisenberg said.
The programs do not address a ``crisis of leadership,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents like Seltzer of the New School say the curriculum is
guided by student demand. This semester, he is teaching a course in
advocacy, public policy and social change. This fall, he plans to
begin training nonprofit managers to make better use of computers
and the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The field of nonprofit studies is still relatively young. But
some pioneers who have built their careers on such training now
recommend it to others.
</P>
<P>
   Dale Needles, now vice president for finance and administration
at the Hispanic Scholarship Fund, has used the skills he learned at
the University of San Francisco to manage organizations in the
arts, international development and education. ``Having that degree
definitely helps in opening doors,'' he said. ``Going through a
program like that gave me a sound footing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
