<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON PERSONAL BUSINESS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 18) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Perhaps Only Death Is Really Inevitable &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Predicting where its business will be expanding, the Internal
Revenue Service projects that the number of dead people who pay
taxes will rise more than seven times as fast as the number of
living taxpayers. Part of the reason may be that living Americans
are not using opportunities to make gifts to children and
grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   The IRS projected that the number of individual tax returns
would grow to 135.2 million in 2005 from 120.7 million in 1997, an
increase of 12 percent. But estate tax returns, which apply only to
the richest 1 percent or so of those who die, were expected to grow
to 195,000 from 102,000, a 90.5 percent climb.
</P>
<P>
   The increase is projected despite a federal law that gradually
increases the amount one can leave without owing estate taxes to $1
million in 2006, from $600,000 in 1997. Assets are growing faster
than the exemption because of the run-up in stocks and a rebound in
housing prices.
</P>
<P>
   Living taxpayers are not moving swiftly, however, to pass along
their wealth. From 1997 to 2005, the IRS foresees only a 40 percent
increase in gift tax returns, filed when taxpayers make gifts of
more than $10,000 ($20,000 for married couples) to individuals. No
tax is actually due unless the total amount given exceeds the
taxpayer's estate tax exemption, and using trusts can further cut
the obligation.
</P>
<P>
   David Cay Johnston &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Digging for Scholarship Gold &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There is a new addition to the many Web sites for high school
seniors and college students seeking scholarships for the fall
semester. While Collegenet (www.collegenet.com) does not have the
largest data base of scholarships, it also does not sell
demographic information to finance its operations, as some sites
do. The search portion of the site, called Mach 25, has information
on 7,000 scholarships and a simple series of filters to narrow the
visitor's search.
</P>
<P>
   A search of categories yields groupings like academics,
ethnicity, business, age and sports, and these have their own
sub-categories. A keyword search can narrow the selections quickly
_ and turn up some obscure awards. Students who loved glass-blowing
at summer camp, for instance, can find two arts scholarships by
entering the word ``glass.'' Sometimes the awards may be too
specific for most students. To qualify for the $1,200 scholarship
from the Northern Virginia Handcrafters Guild, for example,
applicants must live within a 60-mile radius of Merrifield, Va.
</P>
<P>
   Shelly Freierman
</P>
</TEXT>
