u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-GRETZKY17-COX     04-16 0723
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-GRETZKY17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gretzky makes it official
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Wayne Gretzky asked everyone to view it as a
celebration _ but the constant pauses and the way his voice cracked
indicated that even he didn't buy that part.
</P>
<P>
   Saying goodbye to a game he revolutionized and a league that
owes him as no other league owes an athlete, Gretzky officially
announced Friday his retirement from hockey, although his legend
will live for years in NHL record books.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have highs and lows in life,'' Gretzky said in a packed
theater adjacent to Madison Square Garden, where he will play his
final game Sunday with the New York Rangers against the Pittsburgh
Penguins. ``Unfortunately sometimes we go to funerals. Fortunately,
sometimes we go to weddings. To me this is a party, it's a
celebration. I look upon the next few days as something to really
enjoy. ... Obviously, today I'm officially retired.''
</P>
<P>
   And that was the first time Gretzky had mentioned the ``R'' word
since news first broke of his impending decision earlier in the
week. Gretzky had serious thoughts before the season that this
might be his final year and had pretty much decided by Christmas
that 1999 would be it for No. 99. In recent weeks, he withstood
attempts by his wife, Janet, long-time agent Michael Barnett, coach
John Muckler and several friends and teammates to talk him out of
it.
</P>
<P>
   Gretzky, who struggled this season, conceded that he ``started
to feel the fatigue mentally and physically that I've never felt
before. I started to question myself about it.''
</P>
<P>
   The 38-year-old, who always said he would play as long as hockey
was still enjoyable, then added, ``From the mental standpoint, I
just didn't have the passion anymore to put in the two hours a day
it would've taken to get ready for next season. I knew it at the
beginning of this year; I knew it all during the year. This
decision wasn't made this week.''
</P>
<P>
   Gretzky holds 61 NHL records, including career marks in goals
(894), assists (1,962) and points (2,856) in 20 NHL seasons. His
legendary achievements include three 200-point years in a row,
eight consecutive seasons with 50 or more goals, a 92-goal season,
nine MVP awards, 10 scoring titles and four Stanley Cup rings, all
with Edmonton, his first of four teams.
</P>
<P>
   Often, opponents seemed in such awe of him that they couldn't
bring themselves to body check him. Others who tried to knock him
off the puck couldn't; it was like checking a ghost. He was great
not because he skated or shot a puck at warp speed but because of
his vision. He saw the ice as no other player in history. He
anticipated where teammates _ and opponents _ would be even before
they did. He anticipated open spaces. The only thing more dangerous
than Gretzky in front of the net was Gretzky behind it. The keys to
his success were the same as that of any in the martial arts:
balance, focus and intelligence.
</P>
<P>
   Off the ice, the trading of Gretzky from Edmonton to Los Angeles
in 1988 helped the growth of the NHL in the Sunbelt. NHL
commissioner Gary Bettman turned to him early in the news
conference and said, ``No person has done as much for their sport
as you have for ours.''
</P>
<P>
   This year's highlight was limited to MVP of the All-Star Game.
This season, Gretzky missed more games (11) with a neck injury than
he had goals (nine).
</P>
<P>
   He required two steroid injections in his neck last month and
probably will need another this summer. The hits he used to
anticipate and avoid became prevalent, and the wear and tear took a
toll. Equally contributing to Gretzky's decision was that the
rebuilding Rangers have missed the playoffs two seasons in a row
and are at least two years away from competing for the Stanley Cup,
the primary reason Gretzky would extend his career. But he had no
desire to play elsewhere nor for a ``farewell tour'' next season.
``That wouldn't be fair to my teammates,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can always say, `Just one more year.' But I'm at peace of
mind. This was the right time.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked his feelings about his eventual induction in the Hall of
Fame, Gretzky smiled and said, ``I try to never get too
egotistical. But I guess it's safe to say I'll probably get in
there.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
