</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-DRAFT-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS NEED TO FOCUS ON CORNERBACK, RUNNING BACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ In the past two drafts, the Patriots have
addressed their areas of most critical need _ cornerback and
running back _ on the first round, using three No. 1 picks to solve
those problems. So what do they need most in the draft?
</P>
<P>
   A cornerback and a running back.
</P>
<P>
   Those are not good signs for the future because that part of
their future was supposed to have been taken care of. Because it is
not leaves New England with many drafting options in a year when
they have 11 picks, including three of the first 52 and five of the
top 91. But it also means they have more holes to fill than they
should have.
</P>
<P>
   The most glaring of the moment is running back, and that problem
was simply a case of bad luck. Nothing the Patriots could have done
short of locking Robert Edwards in his room could have prevented
the likely career-ending knee injury he suffered on a beach in
Honolulu in February. But it serves to highlight the consequences
of not taking care of the little things they did have control of
the last two years. If they had, when the inevitable struck _
unexpected disaster _ management could have reacted far differently
than now.
</P>
<P>
   New England has made 19 selections in the last two drafts and
thus far netted only one starter, and he is on crutches. What makes
matters worse is that New England retained 18 of those players (the
list is now down to 17 with Scott Rehberg having been selected by
Cleveland in the expansion draft) and most of them have watched
more than played.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, the Green Bay Packers, New England's opponent in
the Super Bowl three years ago, has made 16 selections over the
same time period, retained only seven but netted three starters,
which is a strong testimony to Ron Wolf's growing legend as a
selector of talent.
</P>
<P>
   Because of that, Patriot personnel guru Bobby Grier knows he
cannot gamble on players with the infamous (and oft overused)
``upside potential'' this year. When he picks at 20 and 28, Grier
needs to come away with players coach Pete Carroll can put on the
field now because every team in his division has gotten stronger,
most noticeably Miami and Indianapolis, while the Patriots have not
kept pace. That is why Grier will continue to try and trade up with
St. Louis or Chicago in hope of landing Miami running back Edgerrin
James.
</P>
<P>
   The trade Thursday of Marshall Faulk to the Rams actually has
made that possibility more likely because it means Colts general
manager Bill Polian is sure quarterbacks will go in the first three
slots in the draft, leaving him free to take Texas running back
Ricky Williams with the fourth pick and allowing St. Louis to
ignore James.
</P>
<P>
   The belief here is Washington will grab Champ Bailey if it has
an ounce of sense (which is open to debate) even though head coach
Norv Turner's offense could use a productive back. The Rams will
then come back and take North Carolina State receiver Torry Holt
despite all their talk of now going for defensive help, leaving
James still available when the Bears are ready to make their
selection.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago has many ways to go with that No. 7 pick and surely will
talk with both New England and New Orleans, although the Saints are
nowhere near as interested in James as they were in Williams and
may stand pat at No. 12 and hope to get a receiver like Ohio
State's David Boston there.
</P>
<P>
   The Bears are rumored to want out of the seventh spot if they
can't get one of the top three quarterbacks and with all their
problems would look favorably on a New England offer of both its
ones plus perhaps a two and a three. This would allow Grier to make
his move but would also put all his eggs in one basket, which is
always a gamble.
</P>
<P>
   It's a gamble New England should take and will if the
possibility is there but failing that (and one must remember a lot
more trades are talked about than made), the Patriots will stand
pat, make their two picks and go on with life. If the draft board
falls the way most projections go, they could stay there and solve
a serious but less-talked-about problem with their first pick by
grabbing LSU defensive tackle Anthony McFarland.
</P>
<P>
   Of all the defensive linemen available, McFarland is the most
ready to play in the NFL, a point of some import to a staff that
knows it has to win this year if it wants to be in position to be
picking anything next April, and he would fill a need on the inside
that has never been fully taken care of.
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina's strapping defensive end Ebenezer Ekuban and
Tennessee's Patrick Kerney are also possibilities, as would one of
the top linebacker prospects if they slide this far, but Ekuban is
a project and the Patriots already have a playroom full of such
young players with Tebucky Jones leading that class, and they
really can't afford to do that again if they are wise.
</P>
<P>
   They could also go for an offensive lineman here, either BC
center Damien Woody or someone with the potential to replace
perennial All-Pro left tackle Bruce Armstrong down the road. That
would eliminate a player such as Aaron Gibson if he's still
available because he'll never be a left tackle in the NFL but would
make Lonnie Shelton or John Tait attractive. Only problem is both
those players are so attractive they won't be around when the
Patriots select.
</P>
<P>
   Unless there has already been a run on most of the top offensive
linemen (which is unlikely), New England will go for defensive line
help first and work under the assumption they can still get a solid
offensive lineman such as Georgia's Matt Stinchcomb, West
Virginia's Solomon Page, or Michigan's Jon Jansen with the 28th
pick.
</P>
<P>
   If they do that, you say, where's their running back? On the
second round, which is where all the guys behind Williams and James
belong. New England makes the 52d pick then and should still have
its choice of several backs who could help (although not as much as
James would), including West Virginia's short but sturdy Amos
Zereoue, Michigan State's Sedrick Irvin, BC's Mike Cloud (forget
about it) and if they are lucky perhaps James Johnson or Kevin
Faulk.
</P>
<P>
   It's almost impossible to believe both Faulk and Johnson would
be there but if New England wants one of them, it could still try
to work a trade up to the top of the second round. Either way,
that's most likely where the Patriots' running back will come from,
failing a deal to get to the sixth or seventh spot in the first
round.
</P>
<P>
   After that, New England still needs a young cornerback because
its entire secondary's contracts run out at the end of this season
and they can't posibly re-sign Ty Law, Lawyer Milloy, Steve Israel,
and Willie Clay and there is little reason to believe Chris Canty
(who had to be browbeaten into coming to the offseason workout
program by Carroll) or Chris Carter (who is back in college and
that's frankly where his future lies) will help much there. Jones
remains a wild card in that area but if he doesn't end up as a
safety rather than a corner there will be a lot of shocked
personnel people and scouts throughout the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   That's not the only weakness left to address, however. The
Patriots could be tempted early by Woody at No. 20 in hopes of
plugging the hole left by Dave Wohlabaugh's defection. That would
allow Heath Irwin to shift to guard and compete with Todd Rucci and
Max Lane, one of whom's salary will not be around by September.
</P>
<P>
   If those needs can be taken care of they would then search for
an outside linebacker with speed and size in case undersized Tedy
Bruschi proves he isn't capable of playing full time in place of
departed free agent Todd Collins and every team is always searching
for some kind of pass-rushing prospect with the proverbial ``upside
potential'' New England has fallen in love with the last two
drafts.
</P>
<P>
   If the Patriots solve half of these problems they will have done
a good job but if they don't find a back early that they can put on
the field and a lineman who can open holes for him, the rest of
this draft may not matter much in the long run to Grier or Carroll
because they won't be around to watch these guys play.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
