<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DO THE RIGHT THING, JERRY, LET LOOSE OF LETT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Say goodbye, Leon. And make it your final goodbye.
</P>
<P>
   You will tell him just that, right, Jerry Jones? Tell Mr. Lett
to take his stupidity, his drug problem, and his days of
embarrassing the organization, and be gone immediately. Never to
return.
</P>
<P>
   And this is not even remotely about the NFL substance-abuse
program catching Lett once again with his nose packed. Nor is it
about another league-ordained suspension of one year, minimum, if
Lett's feeble appeal fails, which it will.
</P>
<P>
   If Jones has been shooting straight, he will beat the league
office to the suspension punch. That means going beyond the
harshest penalty the NFL can hand down _ an indefinite suspension
of at least a year for a third-time offender.
</P>
<P>
   Jones will slap a lifetime Valley Ranch ban on Lett.
</P>
<P>
   In his well-documented clean-up-the-Cowboys campaign that began
two years ago, Jones has sent both subtle and strong signals about
being serious. A nobody named Kendall Watkins defied the team ban
on a local bar, and was booted. There is also suspicion that when
Shante Carver suddenly disappeared from Valley Ranch, it had to do
with him being a repeat offender of the new Jones law.
</P>
<P>
   But Jerry delivered the hammer a year ago when the Cowboys
allowed receiver Randy Moss to slide by in the draft.
Football-wise, it was a huge mistake. But credibility-wise, Jones
came across as a standup guy. Moss' reputation did not fit the
clean-up-the-Cowboys campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Now, however, comes the ultimate credibility test with Lett,
although maybe not as ultimate as Lett's football credentials
suggest. Once considered among the league's premier defensive
tackles, Lett was a shadow of his old self last season. Lett being
voted to the Pro Bowl was a joke.
</P>
<P>
   Suspensions and personal problems appear to have finally caught
up with Lett, who at age 30 should be in the prime of his career.
</P>
<P>
   But even if star-status with Lett was still prevalent, Jones set
up the new team guidelines to be strict when it comes to violations
of character and doing right.
</P>
<P>
   Lett no longer qualifies for Valley Ranch membership under those
guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, he now faces at least another full-season suspension, and
at best won't play again in the NFL until a month or so before his
32nd birthday.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, it was known within the Valley Ranch walls that Lett
had failed another drug test and probably would not be available
for the 1999 season, if ever again.
</P>
<P>
   When Jones refused comment on the Lett situation yesterday, his
choice to remain mum was wise. Jones reached a low point three
years ago when he was caught lying about an upcoming Lett
suspension.
</P>
<P>
   But there were league-wide whispers yesterday about the Cowboys
having spent the last several weeks preparing for Lett's bye-bye.
</P>
<P>
   At least two other coaches from NFL teams said the Cowboys have
been attempting to set up a scenario for today's college draft
where they land LSU defensive tackle Anthony McFarland.
</P>
<P>
   In most mock drafts, McFarland is projected as middle of the
first round. Dallas has the 22th pick. There has been speculation
McFarland could slide to the Cowboys, but that's doubtful.
</P>
<P>
   If the Cowboys want McFarland to serve as a Lett replacement,
they will probably have to trade up to at least the 15th spot.
</P>
<P>
   One source from another NFL club said the Cowboys will have a
team representative ``baby-sitting'' today at McFarland's home. But
that also will happen with several players expected to go in the
middle of the first round, including receiver Troy Edwards of
Louisiana Tech.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive tackle, however, has suddenly become a depth hole for
the Cowboys. Remember that both Hurvin McCormack and Antonio
Anderson were lost in the expansion draft. Even a fading Lett was
easily the team's best at the position. The other starter, Chad
Hennings, had his worst season from a production standpoint.
</P>
<P>
   None of this excuses the fact Lett must be removed quickly and
permanently from Valley Ranch.
</P>
<P>
   In vowing to put the ``Evil Empire'' days behind the franchise,
Jones couldn't promise the organization would be trouble-free. But
he did give a blood oath to react swiftly if the image of the team
was again soiled.
</P>
<P>
   This is your chance, Jerry. Don't blow it.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
