<SLUG> BC-INVEST-COLUMN-ART-$ADV18-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE INSTALLMENT PLAN CAN BE A BAD DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic of dollar cost averaging into a Standard &AMP; Poor'
500 index fund is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 18)  
 (af)  
 By MARK HULBERT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Almost every guarantee of investment performance isn't worth the
paper on which it's printed. But there is an exception: the
guarantee that comes with the strategy called dollar cost
averaging. People who use this approach know that in at least one
respect, they will always do better than average.
</P>
<P>
   With dollar cost averaging, you don't invest all at once.
Instead, you invest gradually _ in equal amounts at regular
intervals. There is no single formula; you can choose the number of
installments you want.
</P>
<P>
   Many people use dollar cost averaging out of necessity. They may
have only $100 a month to invest, for example, so they sign up with
a mutual fund to have that amount drawn directly from their
checking accounts every 30 days. But some people use dollar cost
averaging when they already have a big chunk of money in hand.
</P>
<P>
   Say you have $30,000 and want to invest it in IBM stock in three
$10,000 installments over the next year _ today, six months from
now and 12 months from now. Let's further assume that six months
from now, IBM is trading at $220.625 a share, up from $170.625 last
Friday, and at $270.625 a year from now. The average of those three
prices is $220.625 a share. Yet your average purchase price will be
$212.94, or $7.69 less.
</P>
<P>
   Those numbers might look like strange alchemy, but they aren't.
That's because dollar cost averaging lets you buy more shares when
I.B.M. is trading at $170.625 and fewer shares when it is at
$270.625. The same goes for all variations on the strategy: Your
average purchase price will always be lower than the stock's
average price.
</P>
<P>
   It sounds wonderful, but it doesn't mean you should use dollar
cost averaging for all your investments. The guarantee of
below-average prices notwithstanding, you often can do better by
investing in a lump sum.
</P>
<P>
   Under what circumstances should you invest in one leap, instead
of intervals? Of course, the answer can be known only in hindsight;
it depends on whether the value of the asset rises or falls over
the period in question. If it rises, you will be better off buying
in a lump sum at the outset.
</P>
<P>
   Again using the IBM example, let's say that instead of
averaging, you make your entire investment today; the average
purchase price will be $170.625 _ far better than the $212.94
average above. The only scenario in which dollar cost averaging
comes out ahead of lump-sum investing is when the asset declines in
value over the investment period.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, dollar cost averaging is an implicit bet on such
a decline over the time you invest. That may come as a shock to
proponents of the strategy, who typically portray it as an
alternative to market timing. But at its core, dollar cost
averaging is little more than a bearish market-timing judgment.
</P>
<P>
   That isn't necessarily a criticism. There is nothing wrong with
being a market timer per se, or with being bearish. But if you
think that an asset is going to decline, why buy any of it now? Why
not wait?
</P>
<P>
   I concede that I'm not being entirely fair in my analysis. We
don't know in advance how an investment will perform in the
short-term. Many people probably use dollar cost averaging simply
because of that uncertainty _ and want to reduce risk.
</P>
<P>
   It is true that the strategy reduces risk over the period in
which you invest. Yet even as a risk reducer, dollar cost averaging
in any form comes up wanting, according to a recent study by Moshe
Arye Milevsky, a professor of finance at York University in
Toronto, and Steven E. Posner, vice president in charge of
quantitative modeling at Marsh &AMP; McClennan Securities.
</P>
<P>
   In all likelihood, they found, you will make more money, with no
more risk, by simply investing about one-half of a lump sum right
away and placing the rest in cash until the end of the period over
which you would otherwise be dollar cost averaging.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, dollar cost averaging is an expensive way to
reduce risk. If that's your goal, don't wait: Take half of what you
plan to invest and buy the asset today. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mark Hulbert is editor of the Hulbert Financial Digest, a
newsletter based in Alexandria, Va. His column on investment
strategies appears every other week. E-mail:
strategy(AT)nytimes.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
