<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-COHEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COHEN BERATES MILOSEVIC FOR REMARKS ON CONVOY BOMBING 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JOEL BRINKLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Secretary of Defense William Cohen accused Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic on Friday of an ``Orwellian twisting
of language and logic'' to describe the bombing of a Kosovo refugee
convoy on Wednesday, while ``not allowing his people to see the
kind of horrific damage that he is causing to hundreds of thousands
of people.''
</P>
<P>
   Cohen _ speaking after a Pentagon ceremony Friday morning with
the Italian defense minister, Carlo Scognamiglio _ was responding
to questions from reporters who asked why the Pentagon and NATO did
not release more information about the attack, including videotape
footage from the Air Force jet that may have been involved.
</P>
<P>
   Since the bombing of Yugoslavia began last month, NATO forces
have been reluctant to make public detailed after-action reports of
the sort that the public grew accustomed to seeing during the
Persian Gulf war.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, in fact, during Pentagon and NATO briefings,
officers and officials have declined to say how many attack
missions have been launched, how many have been completed, how many
bombs have been dropped or what the bombs may have hit.
</P>
<P>
   In recent days, the situation has improved somewhat. On Friday
afternoon the Pentagon showed videotape from half a dozen attacks
on Thursday night and announced that the allies had launched more
than 400 aircraft overnight, although many of them flew support
missions and not all of the attack aircraft completed their
missions.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, detailed information of that sort was not made
public. But Cohen argued that the refugee convoy was a special
case. For now, at least, he would not make any new information
public.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most appropriate thing,'' he said, would be to complete
the investigation of the incident before releasing new information.
</P>
<P>
   On the day after the attack, Pentagon and NATO officials offered
several conflicting accounts of what had occurred. ``I think that
the most important thing to do is to get our facts straight so that
there is not conflicting statements coming out of one source or
another,'' Cohen said. ``We have an obligation to be answerable to
the American people and to our NATO allies, and indeed we will.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no consideration given to trying to conceal
anything,'' he added. ``We want to make sure we don't get hammered
by the press as such, for putting out different conflicting
statements as to what happened. And we are trying to avoid that
because we think it is important that we be accountable and we be
accountable based on the facts.''
</P>
<P>
   But Cohen clearly felt that it was illogical _ or worse _ to
respond to accusations from the Yugoslav president about the
attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has the audacity to stand up and say that NATO has
deliberately targeted innocent civilians,'' he said. ``It is a
calumny; it is an outrage. It is a grotesque indulgent practice of
his.
</P>
<P>
   ``For anyone to accept the notion that allied forces would
deliberately target the very people that we are trying to save, I
think, can only be a testament to the kind of manipulation of
language and of logic that Milosevic, as a dictator, can engage
in.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
