<HEADLINE>
VALUE IS SUDDENLY LOOKING NIFTY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Mo.)   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 18)  
 (af)  
 By GRETCHEN MORGENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For years, stock market investors have resembled the
fellow Oscar Wilde once described as knowing the price of
everything and the value of nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, value suddenly mattered again to investors.
</P>
<P>
   For anyone in value stocks, a rally has been a long time in
coming. These companies have severely underperformed compared with
their growth-stock brethren since the middle of 1994.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, however, the trend turned. Assets flew out of stock
market darlings like Pfizer, Wal-Mart and Dell Computer and headed
directly for former duds like Caterpillar, DuPont, even Eastman
Kodak.
</P>
<P>
   After peaking on Monday, the Standard &AMP; Poor's Barra Growth
index lost 6.2 percent by week's end. But the S&AMP;P Barra Value index
gained 1.9 percent for the week.
</P>
<P>
   The about-face was all the more remarkable in that it was not
caused by a market correction. Byron R. Wien, United States
investment strategist at Morgan Stanley Dean Witter, says it
usually takes a market fall to shock investors into value havens.
</P>
<P>
   So what scared investors out of growth stocks? Wien cites two
events: the European central bank's interest-rate cut on April 8
and Compaq Computer's warning last Monday that its first-quarter
earnings would be half what analysts were expecting. ``Compaq's
announcement reminded people that there can be disappointments even
in technology,'' Wien said. ``And the ECB cutting interest rates
reminded people that policy makers are determined to keep the world
on a growth path.''
</P>
<P>
   Before they celebrate, value investors may be wondering whether
the sudden shift is just a cruel head fake to an already
beleaguered bunch.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas R. Cliggott, United States equity strategist at J.P.
Morgan Securities, thinks the value story has staying power. One
reason is an upswing in global earnings that he expects during the
next 6 to 12 months as economies around the world emerge from the
doldrums.
</P>
<P>
   That, he said, will help value stocks stay strong. When world
economic growth is falling, Cliggott noted, growth stocks win. ``In
periods of slow economic growth, earnings growth is scarce, so
those companies that can demonstrate growth tend to get very high
multiples put on those earnings,'' he explained. As growth
accelerates, paying up for earnings makes less sense, and value
shares typically rally.
</P>
<P>
   It is perhaps not surprising that the value rebound is happening
now. Such sentiment shifts often occur after the last diehard
investor _ in this case a value type _ has thrown in the towel.
This year, 98 percent of net inflows into equity mutual funds have
gone to growth managers.
</P>
<P>
   To investors who think that growth stocks always bounce back,
Alan F. Skrainka, chief market strategist at Edward D. Jones in St.
Louis, says history shows the perils of such faith.
</P>
<P>
   Harkening back to 1972, the last time that a small group of
growth stocks _ the Nifty 50 _ so dominated the investment scene,
Skrainka looked at the performance of that era's four top
technology stocks: Texas Instruments, IBM, Xerox and Polaroid. The
shares, he found, fetched 40 to 95 times earnings in 1972.
</P>
<P>
   But then the bear market of 1974 hammered them. And by 1982, the
former leaders had not yet recovered; their average annualized
returns for the 10-year period ending in 1982 were well below that
of the S&AMP;P 500.
</P>
<P>
   Market leadership, once it has been unseated, can take a long
time to return.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
