<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-SENIORS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHRISTY O'CONNOR JR.   PLAYS THROUGH THE ROUGH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM MCCABE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH GARDENS, Fla. _ The shot was struck nearly 10 years
ago, a 2-iron that was so splendid, so stunning, that he still gets
asked about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't let you forget, on either side of the water,''
said Christy O'Connor Jr., with a smile. It is a wonderful sight,
this smile that belongs to one of golf's great characters. Sadly,
it is a smile seen less frequently than in days gone by, for
O'Connor is a man living with an agonizing pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm after a dreadful tragedy. My son was taken from us,
unfortunately,'' said O'Connor. ``That's really the worst thing
now, to be honest with you. I find it very, very difficult to even
play.''
</P>
<P>
   For months, he couldn't. But he has decided to return to
competition, taking advantage of an invitation to play in this
week's PGA Seniors' Championship, his first as a member of the
over-50 crowd. Every day is a new test of strength. O'Connor
three-putted four times on the back side in Thursday's 76 and he
shook his head. He returned with a spring in his step Friday, shot
71, and easily made it into weekend play.
</P>
<P>
   This spirited Irishman, whose approach to the 18th at the Belfry
in 1989 stunned Fred Couples and will live forever in Ryder Cup
folklore, had grand plans in anticipation of his 50th birthday last
August.
</P>
<P>
   ``My whole plan was to bring my son over here (the United
States) and hopefully get him a scholarship.'' And it would afford
O'Connor the chance to make his debut as a senior golfer. ``We
would have him here with us. Anyway, that was our plan.''
</P>
<P>
   The trip never came to be. Darren O'Connor was just 17 when he
was killed last September in a car crash not far from the family
home in Galway. He had recently been crowned Ireland's junior
champion and had nearly won the under-21 title, too. He was a
2-handicap with impeccable golfing genes _ his father was a legend;
his father's uncle, Christy O'Connor Sr., was a notch above legend.
He was simply Himself.
</P>
<P>
   But that was golf, so unimportant in the face of this reality:
Darren O'Connor was the youngest of three children he adores. Stand
over a putt with that in the back of your mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find that very hard, to be honest with you, on the golf
course,'' said O'Connor. ``I can't stop thinking about it. I feel I
shouldn't be out there. I feel I'm neglecting the others . . . it's
stupid, I know, but that's how I feel.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor is a man saturated in charisma, a lively spirit who has
been known to lead a sing-a-long and join in celebratory affairs
after a round of golf. For close to 30 years he has been putting
his golf talents on public display in Europe. He is a national
treasure in his homeland and if America's only knowledge of him is
that 2-iron in 1989, that's quite a way to be remembered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right place at the right time,'' said O'Connor, again flashing
that smile from beneath his trademark cap. ``My lie was a tight
one, which I like, seeing that it was like a seaside lie. The green
had three tiers and I was going in low with a 2-iron to run up to
the hole.''
</P>
<P>
   It was one of those brilliant moments in golf, when the shot
came off perfectly. O'Connor, all square in his match against the
heavily favored Couples, watched as his shot from 221 yards came to
rest some 2 feet from the pin. Standing 60 yards down the fairway,
a 9-iron in his hands, Couples was in shock. He blew the easy shot
way right and never had a chance to make par. The pro-European
crowd was wild as Couples conceded the birdie that gave the match
to O'Connor and was the key to Europe's 14-14 tie that retained the
Ryder Cup.
</P>
<P>
   If there is regret, he said, it is that people overlook the fact
``that for 17 holes before that I hit a lot of good shots.'' He
would have had a medal score of 66 that day and as a way of
vindicating his stirring victory, O'Connor points with pride to his
Dunhill Cup match a few weeks later. His foe? Couples.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was really nice. I think if I had lost that match everyone
would have said, `Well, the first one was sort of a fluke.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Only the ignorant would consider his win over Couples a fluke or
his only career highlight. ``Because of intense pressure, the Ryder
Cup is something special, watched by millions of viewers
world-wide,'' said O'Connor. ``But I won the Kenya Open (1990) in
front of all my family. The British Masters (1992). It was
beautiful. The Irish Open (1975), winning at home is a fantastic
thrill.''
</P>
<P>
   He is far from home right now, but his infectious Irish
character has attracted a loyal gallery. O'Connor said he is
committed to giving senior golf a try. He has an exemption into
next week's stop in Charlotte, N.C., where his wife will join him,
and he may try Alabama the week after that. He is without status,
of course, and sponsor's exemptions are like gold. ``I understand
it's very difficult, because there are so very few invites
available.''
</P>
<P>
   He would be a natural for the BankBoston Classic in August,
someone suggested. ``I would love to be there,'' said O'Connor,
``because Boston is like being home.'' His eyes had a glitter to
them and he smiled. Again.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
