<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-16 20:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1991 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-GRETZKY-BOS &LR;      04-16 1099
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-GRETZKY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRETZKY MAKES IT OFFICIAL: HE'LL RETIRE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Magician, craftsman and master of the unexpected,
Wayne Gretzky for once in his career did what everyone anticipated
Friday, announcing that he will make Sunday the last game of his
illustrious career.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people have been asking me why,'' said the
38-year-old Gretzky, owner of virtually every offensive record in
the National Hockey League, without question the game's icon around
the world. ``It's a gut feel, something I believe is right.
</P>
<P>
   ``My heart, my gut is telling me this is it -- it's time. I'm
done.''
</P>
<P>
   Word began circulating last weekend that Gretzky, hindered this
season by a bulging cervical disk, would end his 20-year NHL career
when the Pittsburgh Penguins faced his Rangers at Madison Square
Garden. Gretzky all but confirmed the speculation after the
Blueshirts' game Thursday night in Ottawa, where he said, barring a
miracle, he would announce his retirement the next day.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after 4 p.m., inside Madison Square Garden's packed
Parmount Room, the Great One said goodbye. But earlier in the day,
he phoned home to Brantford, Ontario, and threw Phyllis Gretzky one
last deke.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mom,'' said the world's greatest hockey-playing son, ``it's a
miracle! I'm not retiring. ... April Fool's.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Wayne,'' said his mom, ``you're a (jerk).''
</P>
<P>
   Flanked by his wife, two sons, NHL commissioner Gary Bettman and
a string of Ranger and MSG officials, including his long-time coach
John Muckler, Gretzky spent some 50 minutes explainining why it was
time for him to walk away. It wasn't injury, he said. It wasn't any
one thing, but more a concert of feelings, all adding up to the
inevitable conclusion that it was time to give up the game he
loved. He told his Ranger teammates before Thursday's game that his
mind was made up. He called his long-time teammate and cohort, Mark
Messier, and broke the news to him after the game in Ottawa.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `Good for you, if that's your decision,' '' said
Gretzky, whose final game, televised in the United Stats via the
Fox network, will undoubtedly draw the highest-rated viewership in
hockey history. ``I hate to be repetitive about this. ... I love
the game ... but it's just part of it. Life goes on.''
</P>
<P>
   The scene inside the Paramount Room was eerily funereal at the
start. A bouquet of flowers fronted the podium, the predominant
colors orange and yellow, far more autumn than spring.
</P>
<P>
   Moments before the somber-looking Gretzky appeared, all his
Ranger teammates shuffled silently into the room and dutifly took
seats in an area that had been cordoned off from reporters and
photographers. Dressed in their best road suits, many of them
multimillionaires, they added to a scene that conjured images of
paying last respects at St. Patrick's Cathedral.
</P>
<P>
   ``In sports, you go through all these highs and lows,'' Gretzky
began, his voice quaking slightly, his eyes glistening.
``Unfortunately, sometimes you go to funerals. Fortunately,
sometimes you go to weddings. To me, this is a celebration, I hope
you understand that.''
</P>
<P>
   As he did his whole career on the ice, Gretzky maintained his
composure throughout his farewell address and the followup session
of questions and answers. He never once bristled. He answered every
question, thoughtfully, graciously, and with humility when
required.
</P>
<P>
   When he pulls off his skates, where will they go?
</P>
<P>
   ``As a kid, when I was 12 and 13 years old,'' he reminisced, ``a
guy at the Hall of Fame used to let me go in, and I'd just stand
there for hours and stare. If the NHL wants (the skates) for the
Hall of Fame, that's where they'll go.''
</P>
<P>
   It's widely considered that Gretzky will be immediately inducted
into the Hockey Hall of Fame in Toronto, the customary three-year
waiting period to be waived.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess it's safe to say, that I'm probably going to get in
there -- now that I'm retired I can say that,'' he said, again
flashing his humility. Asked what team sweater he would prefer his
likeness to wear in the Hall, he added, ``Somehow, some way, I will
be part of all of those teams in the Hall of Fame, but I'll always
be remembered that I retired a Ranger.''
</P>
<P>
   Gretzky began to make up his mind about retiring at mid-season
and told his wife, actress Janet Jones. She told him to wait, be
certain, and he said he fought off a temptation to make his
decision public after a mid-winter stop in Edmonton, the city where
he won his four Stanley Cups with the greatest offensive team ever
assembeled.
</P>
<P>
   Some three weeks ago he called his long-time agent, Mike
Barnett, and told him that he thought it was time to retire. When
the two met, Barnett realized there wasn't much to discuss.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was more a case of me listening; his mind was made up,''
said Barnett. ``I saw it in his eyes. I heard it. His inner voice
served him well, as it has throughout his career. Just as that
voice always told him to jump to the hole, to shoot the puck, go
for the wraparound ... that same clear voice was there again and he
wasn't going to go against it.''
</P>
<P>
   Fatigue was a factor, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just started to feel fatigue -- mentally and physically --
that I never felt before,'' said Gretzky.
</P>
<P>
   Gretzky had another year under contract with the Blueshirts, for
which he would have earned $5 million. He will collect what amounts
to a $500,000 retirement bonus. He said he will remain involved in
hockey, but he won't begin to formulate post-career plans until
after at least a one-year rest. He has played professionaly for 21
years -- including a first season with Indianapolis in the World
Hockey Association -- and he has been living the dream of playing
since age 3.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't sound as if he'll join Barnett as an agent with IMG.
``No, I don't think so,'' said Barnett. ``He'd more likely buy
IMG.''
</P>
<P>
   Team ownership could be in the Great One's future.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's so intelligent,'' said Barnett, asked if the high cost of
an NHL club might be beyond even Gretzky's means. ``He knows he'd
be better to have strategic partners than do it on his own. That
opportunity will present itself, I'm sure.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, Gretzky is going home, although he's not sure what that
means, because he doesn't know where to call home. He has loved his
time in Manhattan and his three children -- Paulina, Trevor and Ty
-- like their schools and have their friends. He said he didn't
know if home eventually will be in the United States or Canada.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
