<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON PEOPLE AND PERSONALITIES  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 18) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I Love Your Work, Now Get Outta Here! &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For the second time, Richard D. Parsons, president of Time
Warner, has succeeded in recruiting Deborah C. Wright away from
himself. New York's Carver Bancorp, the nation's largest bank
controlled by blacks, announced last week that she would become its
new chief executive June 1. She is now president of the Upper
Manhattan Empowerment Zone, a community development group where
Parsons is chairman.
</P>
<P>
   About five years ago, when Parsons was running the Dime Savings
Bank, he planned to hire Ms. Wright, an investment banker by trade,
to run a new unit for local projects. But when Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani named Parsons, his former law partner, to manage his
transition team, Parsons instead asked her to take charge of the
city Department of Housing, Preservation and Urban Development.
</P>
<P>
   Parsons is one of those who fault Carver for not reinvesting
deposits in the inner city. He wrote Ms. Wright a recommendation of
several single-spaced pages and then spent hours persuading board
members that they needed someone experienced in community
development rather than commercial banking.
</P>
<P>
   ``Debbie has the skills, commitment and vision,'' Parsons said.
``She has a sense of how to put money out into the community that
Carver serves.'' Her other backers included Henry Kravis, who has
also become a promoter of inner city investment. As for Parsons, he
is now hunting for a new empowerment-zone &QL; 
chief.
</P>
<P>
   Allen Myerson &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Keeping It Private at Andersen &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With even Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co. going public, executives at other
private partnerships are often asked when they will follow suit. At
least for Andersen Consulting, the global techology giant, selling
shares is not in the plans.
</P>
<P>
   George T. Shaheen, the firm's chairman, told journalists in New
York last week that going public might make his partners just too
fat and happy to care about the business. The consultants would end
up buying toys like yachts and two-seater Mercedes, he said, and
then go gallivanting about. Pointing to a colleague, Shaheen said,
``He's going to get divorced, and he's not going to come to work.''
</P>
<P>
   Melody Petersen &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sonnet in Gross National Product &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A talent for economics and a way with words coexist as rarely
as, say, welfare states and low taxes. During their single meeting,
Franklin Delano Roosevelt was nettled by John Maynard Keynes'
failure to communicate clearly, accusing the century's greatest
economist of sounding like a mathematician. Nobel Laureate Wassily
Leontief claimed that Keynes' influence was due largely to prose
that required deciphering by legions of disciples.
</P>
<P>
   But last Thursday, Jagdish Bhagwati, a member of the profession
who is already recognized for his rigor, was also honored with a
writing award, Columbia University's Eccles Prize for Excellence in
Economic Writing.
</P>
<P>
   Bhagwati, who teaches at Columbia, won for his latest collection
of essays, ``A Stream of Windows'' (MIT Press). Bhagwati has long
been a Nobel prize contender for his contributions to the theory of
international trade _ contributions leavened by apt metaphors,
clear examples and even poetry. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sylvia Nasar &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   My Dinner With Ross &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Richard H. Brown, the new chief at Electronic Data Systems, has
recruited a secret adviser with an EDS past. A few weeks ago, he
met with Ross Perot, the company founder, for a dinner lasting
several hours in the private back room of a Dallas restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   Perot Systems, the computer services company Perot currently
runs, is an EDS competitor. But Perot, no fan of the executives who
were deposed to make way for Brown, was evidently flattered to be
asked for tips on turning this struggling company around.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a lot of people who will explain EDS to me,'' Brown, a
telecommunications industry veteran, told him. ``So talk to me
about change.''
</P>
<P>
   Turns out that Brown and Perot have a lot in common: bluntness,
notorious impatience and contempt for bureaucratic procedure. Brown
loves to annoy the EDS security force by hitchhiking around the
company's campus and holding impromptu parking-lot conferences.
</P>
<P>
   Allen Myerson
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
