<HEADLINE>
BURNS LOOKS TO KHRISTICH FOR THAT SOMETHING EXTRA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Everyone can agree the Bruins have been playing very
well of late. However, with two games left in the regular season,
including Saturday's matinee against the Buffalo Sabres, and the
playoffs looming, coach Pat Burns said one player he needs more
from is right wing Dmitri Khristich. Khristich is the
second-leading scorer on the team with 71 points, true. But
Khristich has only one goal in his last eight games and a total of
four points.
</P>
<P>
   According to the coach, that just isn't enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very disappointed and I think he knows I'm disappointed,''
said Burns. ``When he's skating and on his game, he's been a
productive player. He's been a strong player for us all year but in
the last while, he hasn't been there for us. If we intend to go a
long way in the playoffs, Dmitri Khristich has to stand up and be
counted.''
</P>
<P>
   Burns has been a master at pushing his players' buttons in the
two seasons he's been here. From Jason Allison to Joe Thornton to
Sergei Samsonov, Burns always seems to have the right thing to say
to light a fire under whatever player happens to be slumping. In
this case, Burns said his fervent hope is to stop Khristich from
standing still.
</P>
<P>
   Burns said that unlike Steve Heinze, who is widely considered a
streaky offensive player, he wouldn't consider Khristich streaky.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can be a steady, steady player if he wants throughout the
year and probably get a lot of points and he did,'' Burns said.
``When he's on his game, I'll put him in a defensive situation and
make him kill penalties but when he's not skating, he's not getting
that. Forget it.''
</P>
<P>
   Khristich has been playing with Samsonov and Thornton of late
and Burns said he doesn't buy that he misses Allison as his
centerman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joe's been playing great lately,'' said the coach. ``We're not
here to say, `I want to play with this guy or that guy.' We're
going to play the guys together we feel are going to make a winner
or make the team better. There's not a player who's going to come
in and say, `I don't want to play with him.' Goodbye. That's not
the way it works. Everybody has to have some kind of contribution.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Dmitri is on his game, he plays center, he plays on the
wing, he gets tons of ice time. When he's not skating, he's not
going to get the ice time.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Allison, who played a terrific game against the Penguins
Thursday and tallied one goal and two assists, Burns said he had
one word for him, ``Shoot!''
</P>
<P>
   At one point in the game, Allison had a two-on-one break with
Anson Carter and passed up the shot to try to force the puck to
Carter.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's always trying to make the pass,'' said Burns. ``If I was
a defenseman, at 48 years old, I'd take 15 two-on-ones against him.
I'd just go to the other guy. Let him go because he's not going to
shoot it. I understand he doesn't always want to shoot it. When
he's skating and making the right decisions, like he did behind the
net (that led to his goal), he's a horse. He's a strong man. Dmitri
is a strong man on skates. In today's game, if you don't skate,
forget it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Center Tim Taylor stayed off the ice at Friday's practice in
Wilmington because of a groin strain, suffered in the first period
of Thursday's game against Pittsburgh. Taylor played the entire
contest, keeping his shifts short against the Penguins, and said he
will play Saturday ... Shawn Bates also missed the skate because of
a hamstring pull and won't be in the lineup against the Sabres ...
Burns' club is 0-4-0 against Buffalo this year and they will try to
change that in their final meeting Saturday. ``They've been a
puzzle to us,'' said Burns. ``They play hard. I thought (former
UMass-Lowell goalie Dwayne Roloson) had a great game against New
Jersey. They play tough, close, tight, in your face. They're a
tough team to play.''
</P>
</TEXT>
