<SLUG> BC-FBN-RBACKS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILLIAMS, JAMES AT THE TOP OF MANY WISH LISTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ricky Williams and Edgerrin James. By now the names have been
heard, seen, and read ad nauseam. That's because in Saturday's
draft they are the filet mignon of running backs _ two very
talented young men whom the Patriots would give a small fortune for
and may indeed try to position themselves to select.
</P>
<P>
   There's supposedly a great dropoff in talent after those two,
but experience says that the success of running backs is much too
difficult to predict. Prime examples of that include sixth-rounder
Terrell Davis, third- rounder Curtis Martin, fourth-rounder Jamal
Anderson, etc.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, according to New Orleans Saints coach Mike Ditka, is
``the next Earl Campbell.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams, who also doubled as a baseball player in the
Philadelphia Phillies organization, gained an amazing 2,124 yards
and scored 27 touchdowns his senior year. He started his career at
Texas as a fullback, but it was soon evident Williams had the
talent to be the featured back, and the 5-foot-11-inch, 235-pounder
went on to rush for 6,279 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Williams runs a 4.5 40-yard dash, sheds tacklers, runs through
people, can turn the corner, and leave defenders in the dust. He
has great balance, body control, and a general knack for getting it
done.
</P>
<P>
   James, at 6 feet, 216 pounds, is a smoother runner, running for
1,416 yards at the University of Miami. He has deceptive 4.4 speed
and is elusive. James drew major attention after gaining 299 yards
and three touchdowns against UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond Williams and James, among those to watch are Mississippi
State's James Johnson, LSU's Kevin Faulk, West Virginia's Amos
Zereoue, Michigan's Sedrick Irvin, Tennessee's Shawn Bryson, Boston
College's Mike Cloud, and UNH's Jerry Azumah. McNeese State's Cecil
Collins might be the third best runner in the draft, but he comes
with much personal baggage, which has gotten him kicked out of two
schools and facing two felony charges.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots, if they chose not to move, may very well settle
for Johnson, a 6-1, 227-pound runner who will be 24 by summer camp.
Johnson spent three years in the Navy and is a very mature kid who
could develop into a solid runner. If the Patriots want more flash,
they'll take a chance on Faulk, who is only 5-8, but weighs 201
pounds and could be an effective returner. He gained 1,282 yards on
247 carries with 13 TDs and is considered an excellent receiver. He
may be too small to be the every-down back.
</P>
<P>
   Zereoue is also short on size at 5-7 1/2, 203 pounds, but many
describe him as a young Joe Morris, with a low center of gravity
and able to move his feet quickly in close quarters. Irvin, who is
Dallas receiver Michael Irvin's cousin, is a little bigger at 5-11,
223, but he's not one of the faster high-echelon backs. Much like
his cousin, Irvin is a brash, cocky kid who might prove himself to
be a big-time player because of his attitude. Bryson is a tweener
at 6-1, 232, but is a very intriguing runner who runs hard and is
very tough.
</P>
<P>
   Cloud's status became clearer with his great Senior Bowl
performance. Patriots vice president Bobby Grier has watched
Cloud's career closely and loves his game. At 5-10, 202 pounds, the
Rhode Island native could be the Patriots' pick if they decide not
to take a back in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   Azumah, who had a record vertical leap of 43 1/2 inches at the
Scouting Combine, also enhanced his draft stature and may go in the
third or fourth round as a third-down back who can return. He may
be better than that, too.
</P>
<P>
   Other sleepers include Colorado's Marlon Barnes, Emporia State's
Brian Shay, Oklahoma's De'Mond Parker and Missouri's Devin West.
</P>
<P>
   Syracuse's Rob Konrad leads the crop of fullbacks. Konrad may
not be a pure fullback, as teams see him as a possible feature back
or even a tight end. Oklahoma's Jermaine Fazande, Nebraska's Joel
Makovicka, and Arizona State's Jeff Paulk are other possible
fullback choices.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
