A1998 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-LA-INTELLECTUALS-AR     04-16 1266
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-LA-INTELLECTUALS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE L.A.'S IMAGE, ARTISTS AND SCHOLARS ARE THRIVING IN A
HOSPITABLE ENVIRONMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (REPEATING to add photo note)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
may make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By DAVID HAY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Stanley Sheinbaum, the publisher of New
Perspectives Quarterly, was standing by the window lamenting the
lack of ideological commitment among Hollywood executives. ``They
give their money away purely for ego rather than because they
identify with any particular cause,'' he said, his black turtleneck
setting off his white hair.
</P>
<P>
   Jon Wiener, a history professor, was waiting in line for a
sandwich and arguing about loyalty and betrayal in Washington. At
another table a discussion was starting about whether Mike Davis'
apocalyptic book on Los Angeles, ``Ecology of Fear,'' was fair to
their hometown.
</P>
<P>
   These 45 Angelenos had ventured out for their newest biweekly
tradition: a meeting of the Los Angeles Institute for the
Humanities, a group of writers, academics and intellectuals who
meet at the Faculty Center of the University of Southern
California.
</P>
<P>
   On this warm Friday they got to eat ham and turkey sandwiches
and listen to Ronald Steel, a professor and author, discuss his
forthcoming biography of Robert F. Kennedy. Also seated in the
standard-issue college dining room were Dagmar Barnouw, a
historian; Russell Jacoby, who wrote a book on public
intellectuals; the conservative columnist Arianna Huffington, and
David Schweitzer, a theater director.
</P>
<P>
   This is Los Angeles' intellectual life.
</P>
<P>
   That may sound like an oxymoron. After all, the notion that Los
Angeles has no brain is about as old as the city itself. Not even
its residents tend to think otherwise. ``That this city is so much
more complex than `Baywatch' is a fact too infrequently experienced
by its own residents,'' said Steve Wasserman editor of The Los
Angeles Times Book Review.
</P>
<P>
   Yet with the city's public and private universities, a slate of
Nobel Prize winners, some of the country's most creative artistic
talent, a reservoir of scientific expertise at the Jet Propulsion
Laboratory and the California Institute of Technology, these
stereotypes were always more alive in the imagination, particularly
on the East Coast, than in real life.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, writers and scholars are now saying that a new influx
of institutions and art museums has helped make intellectual life
more vital than in any other period in this city's history.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the West Side of Los Angeles there is now an intellectual
and cultural life that is easily comparable to that of New York or
Boston,'' said Davis, the historian, whose book is causing a stir.
</P>
<P>
   Sandra Harding, the director of the Center for the Study of
Women at the University of California, Los Angeles, agreed: ``Los
Angeles intellectual life is thriving. At the same time it is less
elitist and no one is intimidated by the big names.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the seven-month-old Institute for the Humanities
there is the new Institute for Art and Cultures at the Los Angeles
County Museum of Art, which sponsors lectures. Over the past year
59 Americans and Europeans, like the cultural critic Elaine Scarry
and the video artist Bill Viola, have come to study at the Bel Air
campus of the Getty Research Institute for the History of Art and
the Humanities. The area's universities regularly attract visiting
lecturers like the European philosophers Jacques Derrida and Jurgen
Habermas.
</P>
<P>
   Informal seminars and literary gatherings are becoming frequent
fixtures. On a recent Sunday night more than 80 people came to a
monthly literary salon at Le Coloniale, a West Hollywood
restaurant. For $20 you could get a buffet dinner and listen to
four writers read from new work. On this night DeLaune Michel,
whose one-woman show ``Southern Gothic'' played here last year, was
one of the attractions. ``There's a real desire out there to be
part of some greater literary community,'' said Charlie Otto, who
directed the reading.
</P>
<P>
   Books are a growth industry here. Last April 110,000 people
bought tickets to the third annual Los Angeles Times Book Fair.
``The greater Los Angeles area is the No. 1 book market in the
country,'' said Joseph Tosney, the regional manager of Borders
Books and Music.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, even the intellectuals don't try to claim that
cultivating the body never takes precedence over developing the
mind, or that the Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences
doesn't generate more interest than the academy.
</P>
<P>
   As Davis explained, ``This city has always been dominated by a
dictatorship of the boosters who were duly intolerant of the
intellectuals.''
</P>
<P>
   The city's geography hasn't helped. UCLA is more than 40 miles
from the Claremont Colleges. Driving is not only time consuming,
but it also works against spontaneous meetings and discussions.
``There's a vast intellectual audience out there,'' said Ruth
Seymour, the general manager of KCRW, the National Public Radio
station in Santa Monica. ``But it's much more hermetically
sealed.''
</P>
<P>
   Some are simply learning to work around such drawbacks. ``We do
not compete with the big gorilla,'' said Michael S. Roth, the
director of the Scholars and Seminars Program at the Getty Research
Institute, referring to Hollywood. ``We are not trying to make
money on ideas. We're here to demonstrate that ideas have
consequences on their own accord.''
</P>
<P>
   For others, technology has helped. The Southern California
Science Writers Group, frustrated by failed attempts to meet in
person, now plan to hold meetings on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   To what extent the isolation and narrowness is self-imposed is a
matter of debate, however. Chon Noriega, the editor of Aztlan: A
Journal of Chicano Studies, said that in a city that is 43 percent
Hispanic and 10 percent Asian the big new, largely white
intellectual institutions on the West Side ``do not represent the
population changes that have already occurred in this city.'' He
continued, ``What were once called minority writers are now on the
front lines of the new thinking about Los Angeles because it's they
who are grappling with the greatest range of positions.''
</P>
<P>
   One subject that seems to interest those inside and outside the
intellectual establishment is Los Angeles itself. ``The city is as
self-conscious about itself and generating as much literature about
itself as any other city in the world, including New York,'' said
Davis.
</P>
<P>
   If the subject matter is different here, so is the style of
discourse. Davis said there was a ``much tougher intellectual
climate in New York'' that ``arises from that city's political,
Jewish and radical traditions. Without that, it's more difficult in
a place like Los Angeles to get a harsh, critical discourse
going.''
</P>
<P>
   Laurie Winer, a former drama critic at The Times, said, ``If you
get into an argument here, people's first instinct is to smooth it
over.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, smoothing over isn't necessarily a bad idea. So many
people showed up for a recent 40-minute lecture by the American
painter R.B. Kitaj at the Institute for Art and Cultures that 300
of them _ including three museum trustees and the actor Michael
York _ had to be turned away amid angry complaints.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the organizers figured out how to defuse the
lecture-hungry crowd: Pipe the lecture through a loudspeaker on the
plaza and pass out glasses of free wine. That's an idea that even a
New York intellectual could love.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-16-99 2024EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990416.0320 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-16 20:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1999 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOLLYWOOD-THEATER-LAD     04-16 1748
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLLYWOOD-THEATER-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR BETTER OR WORSE, SCREEN STARS FLOCK TO STAGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use Sunday, April 18 by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By REED JOHNSON  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ What overpriced coffee is to Seattle and windbag
speeches are to Washington, D.C., movies and television are to Los
Angeles. They're the fuel that keeps the whole show running.
</P>
<P>
   But for Hollywood actors, in this most caste-conscious of
company towns, opting to perform in a real, live play can be like
trying to sell abacuses in Silicon Valley. No one's going to stop
you, certainly, but you may get a few quizzical stares from
friends, colleagues and your agent.
</P>
<P>
   How, then, to explain the recent convergence of so many big-name
TV and movie stars on L.A. stages? A list of the marquee talent
that has graced local playhouses in the past year or so would
include Alan Alda, Debbie Allen, Christine Baranski, Annette
Bening, Carol Burnett, Jenna Elfman, Danny Glover, Kelsey Grammer,
Teri Hatcher, Jack Klugman, Frank Langella, Ian McKellen,
Christopher Plummer and Molly Ringwald.
</P>
<P>
   Still to come this season are Linda Lavin, who'll star in the
Geffen Playhouse production of Donald Margulies' ``Collected
Stories,'' opening next month, and two plays at the Mark Taper
Forum: Donald Sutherland in the U.S. premiere of ``Enigma
Variations,'' by the French playwright Eric-Emmanuel Schmitt, in
May and June; and Al Pacino, who'll direct and act in his Los
Angeles stage debut in Eugene O'Neill's ``Hughie,'' which opens in
June.
</P>
<P>
   Some performers, like Bening _ who cut her theatrical teeth in
New York and San Francisco in the early '80s _ are experienced
stage actors, returning to the boards after lengthy, klieg-lit
sabbaticals. Others like Hatcher, the slenderized half of TV's
``Lois &AMP; Clark,'' are taking their first plunge before a live,
seated audience. Still others, like McKellen, are seasoned stage
pros who've been shuttling between theater and film for years.
</P>
<P>
   Juiced up by celebrity wattage and buoyed by mostly good
reviews, some of these star-driven shows have been palpable hits.
Yasmina Rehza's internationally acclaimed ``Art,'' with a cast that
included Alda, Victor Garber and Alfred Molina, ran 12 weeks at the
Doolittle Theatre in Hollywood last winter. Bening's current
five-week run in the title role of Henrik Ibsen's ``Hedda Gabler''
at the 498-seat Geffen has become L.A.'s toughest ticket, with most
performances completely sold out, according to publicist Gary
Murphy.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, two-way traffic between Hollywood and the theater is
nothing new. Ever since New York vaudevillians began migrating west
to make silent films, Hollywood has been raiding theatrical talent,
whether it's Marlon Brando or Martin Short. Theater producers, for
their part, have been all too happy to boost their box office by
occasionally offering matinee idols to their subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   And in an increasingly fluid and inter-dependent entertainment
universe, the days have long since passed when (ITALICS
START)thea-tuh(ITALICS END) mavens could afford to look down their
noses at the studio philistines.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, some of those who've been doing theater here longest
say they've seldom seen so much prominent industry talent on
display in its own back yard.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not premeditated, but there is a sudden influx or
increase in the number of star performers, at least on the Los
Angeles stages,'' says Gordon Davidson, producing artistic director
of the Mark Taper Forum and the Ahmanson Theatre.
</P>
<P>
   What has brought so many prominent stars into alignment this
season? More significantly, what's to keep them _ not to mention
their audiences _ coming back to L.A. theaters in the future?
</P>
<P>
   Oddly, some producers say, the current star-crossed season
coincides with changing conditions that have made recruiting
Hollywood talent harder than ever. With today's year-round
production schedules and proliferating cable outlets and TV pilots,
the summertime ``hiatus'' that used to free up actors for a period
of a few weeks ``has essentially disappeared,'' says Davidson.
</P>
<P>
   Gil Cates, artistic director of the Geffen, says that when the
studio system prevailed, it was easier for actors to take time off
to work on plays. Now, few are willing to commit to a play for more
than six or eight weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's the conundrum,'' Cates explains. ``If we wouldn't
prepare a season, if we would just be going play by play, it'd be
easier to get stars. Because what would happen is we'd say, OK,
after we do `Collected Stories' let's do Arthur Miller's `The
Price.' Let's start rehearsing in June. Let's see who's available
in June. Maybe Dustin Hoffman's available in June, or maybe Al
Pacino. And you know something? If they're available in June, then
we got 'em.
</P>
<P>
   ``However, if you want to do a season you say, OK, we need him
available in March 2000. You go through two reactions. The first
reaction is usually from the representative: `Are you out of your
(expletive) mind?' And the second reaction is, `OK, but you know
you run the risk of something coming up.'''
</P>
<P>
   What's a theater to do? Some simply try to keep their industry
contacts open so stars will come to them with projects. The more
flexible a theater can be in scheduling, and the shorter a
commitment it requires, the better its chances of success. For
instance, the Reprise! series of staged concert musicals was able
to snag Kelsey Grammer for its recent production of ``Sweeney Todd,
the Demon Barber of Fleet Street'' by squeezing rehearsals into the
``Frasier'' star's television shooting schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Davidson is fond of quoting one Hollywood agent who told him,
``OK, my client wants to be in your show, but what if he or she
gets a job?''
</P>
<P>
   Davidson responded, `What do you think I've been offering? It's
a job!''
</P>
<P>
   Still, when Hollywood actors do show up, seats fill up a lot
faster. When the Mark Taper Forum added the Sutherland and Pacino
shows to the second half of its season _ both as replacements for
previously scheduled shows _ its midseason subscriptions shot up
``on the order of five or six thousand,'' about double the number
for a typical year, Davidson says.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's helpful, because we want to convert those people into
regular theater-goers.
</P>
<P>
   An old truism holds that theater-going in L.A. still is not an
ingrained cultural habit, as it is in New York or Chicago. Rather,
in an area where beaches and sunsets are pretty much free for the
taking, theater is simply one of a zillion entertainment options
clamoring for consumers' disposable income.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a special thing to go to the theater, whereas I think it
should be an everyday thing,'' says Jenna Elfman, who took time off
from her hit series ``Dharma &AMP; Greg'' last winter to perform in a
tiny Los Feliz theater in ``Visions and Lovers: Variations on a
Theme,'' a double bill of one-acts about modern relationships by
acting teacher Milton Katselas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think kids should grow up with theater and art, know that
there is more and know that they can create anything that they
want, as opposed to, `There's McDonald's' and `Let's go to Pic 'n'
Save,''' Elfman says.
</P>
<P>
   While established theaters like the Geffen, the Taper and the
Ahmanson get the lion's share of publicity _ both from local and
national media _ Los Angeles also is home to perhaps the largest
concentration of small and midsize theaters outside New York City.
Many of these are low-budget, storefront operations with fewer than
99 seats, producing everything from Shakespeare and Neil Simon to
experimental theater, gay theater and improvisational comedy.
</P>
<P>
   Some of these smaller theaters have expressed frustration at the
attention paid to the big Hollywood names and the theaters that
most consistently employ them. The Geffen, in fashionable Westwood,
is sometimes grumblingly referred to by less well-endowed rivals as
``Hollywood's community theater'' _ an epithet that, not
surprisingly, irritates Geffen staffers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a certain cynicism that is out there from people who
toil at the smaller theaters forever trying to build an audience,
and they do great work, but you've got to get an audience in the
seats,'' says publicist Murphy. ``But my theory is that what's good
for one is good for all, and that trickle-down theory should
work.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Murphy's boss, Gil Cates, says that while he's been
extremely pleased to present actors like Nicol Williamson and
Brendan Frasier at the Geffen, he has ``mixed feelings about having
the audience dependent upon stars to go to the theater.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's nice occasionally to have a star in a play that's
attractive to an audience,'' he says, ``but I think that to create
an audience that only goes to the theater because there's a star in
the play ... it's really playing with fire, in a way.''
</P>
<P>
   At times, dealing with Hollywood stars and their retinues of
handlers can be draining, some theater staffers confide.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's harder,'' says one staffer who asked for anonymity.
``It's people who've worked in a different world and have a
different expectation of how things operate. I think people who
work only in theater are more community-oriented.''
</P>
<P>
   But others believe Hollywood actors need more encouragement from
the theater community if they're going to perform here regularly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember Jon Voight, doing ``Streetcar'' in L.A.,'' says
playwright Katselas, ``and I thought critics and everyone should
welcome them (Hollywood stars who do theater) and really give them
a fanfare that really invites them and others to come in. I think
that it also is our duty as people who love theater to excite them
and pave the way for them _ not to tell them they're good when
they're not, but to aid them and help them.''
</P>
<P>
   What seems to be the consensus is that the more Hollywood actors
are willing to play to the hometown crowd, the more it will
legitimize L.A. theater in general and persuade more of their
colleagues to do likewise.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview shortly before ``Hedda Gabler'' opened, Annette
Bening said her Hollywood friends were ``all really interested,
very much so, very supportive'' of her return to the stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every once in a while somebody'll say, `What play are you
doing?' And when I say, `Hedda Gabler,' they'll kind of look at me
like, `What?!''' she said, laughing.
</P>
<P>
   ``But most people, of course, know the play, and they're like,
`Oh, wow, that's cool. Good for you.' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
