<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-16 20:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2000 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-RELIGION-COLUM     04-16 1101
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-RELIGION-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORAL LEADERS NEED TO ADDRESS THE WAR IN SERBIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (Skedded earlier as RELIGION-COLUMN)  
(DW) 
 By PETER STEINFELS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Charles W. Colson, once a proud tough guy for the Nixon
administration but for many years now a prominent conservative
religious leader, says NATO's air war against Serbia fails to meet
the traditional Christian criteria for a morally just war.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Land, president of the Southern Baptist Ethics and
Religious Liberty Commission, another conservative religious leader
who stands arm in arm with Colson on many public issues, cites the
same criteria for considering the same NATO campaign morally
justified.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, religious leaders and ethicists, both religious and
secular, are struggling with the question of a war, and once again
they disagree. That of course is neither surprising nor, in itself,
distressing. What is surprising is the new patterns of alignment in
the religious world as in the political one, of defenders and
critics of an American military venture.
</P>
<P>
   What is distressing is how often the moral pronouncements offer
only the surface of a position without following that line of
thought through to its logical conclusions or its rock-bottom
principles.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, people have to assess the facts for themselves and
consult their consciences. What they need from moral leaders is not
so much unanimity but clarity, and certainly not the same vague
generalities favored by politicians and diplomats.
</P>
<P>
   ``The NATO-led intervention,'' leaders of the World Council of
Churches and other international Christian groups declared in late
March, ``manifests the failure of the international community to
achieve a credible negotiated solution.''
</P>
<P>
   Did it take a conclave of religious leaders to notice that? Was
anyone arguing the absurdity that the resort to arms manifested the
success of negotiations?
</P>
<P>
   So what, really, is the point of that statement _ except to link
the words ``NATO-led intervention'' and ``failure'' in the same
sentence and to place responsibility for the horror on ``the
international community''?
</P>
<P>
   Many statements from religious leaders, either for or against
the current intervention, have been more nuanced and faithful to
the complexities than that one. To the extent that moral
conclusions may depend on facts that are swiftly changing or
obscure, whether in the Balkans, the planning rooms of NATO or the
corridors of diplomacy, one has to sympathize with those trying to
give moral guidance.
</P>
<P>
   But two dividing lines have emerged across the whole spectrum of
moral analyses. One has to do with the relative moral weight of
countering the systematic expulsion of the Albanian population in
Kosovo and of avoiding the destruction and destabilization of a
prolonged war. The other has to do with the leap into the unknown
that warfare almost inevitably entails. Is such a leap moral
foolhardiness, the historical equivalent of opening Pandora's box?
Or is it an unavoidable feature of a national life not doomed to
moral abdication?
</P>
<P>
   Both points of division could be addressed more directly.
</P>
<P>
   All participants in this debate, for instance, deplore both the
destruction of war and the Serbian policy of ``ethnic cleansing,''
and they are understandably reluctant to acknowledge which they
deplore more. But a choice may have to be made.
</P>
<P>
   It is fine for advocates of a cease-fire, like Pope John Paul II
and the leading Roman Catholic bishops in the United States, to
pray that an end to the bombardment might lead to a settlement in
which President Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia, having defied
NATO and achieved much of an Albanian-free Kosovo, would somehow
accept what he refused earlier. But if he does not?
</P>
<P>
   What if the choice gets down to this, as it very realistically
might: prolonging, even widening the war, or adding the Albanian
Kosovars to history's long list of permanently displaced
populations, to be aided and resettled but never to return to their
homeland? It is not unthinkable that these religious leaders truly
believe the latter to be the more moral outcome. Shouldn't they say
so candidly?
</P>
<P>
   A parallel question can also be put to those who clearly believe
that restoring the Albanian Kosovars and definitively punishing
Milosevic's systematic campaign of terror, murder and expulsion is
worth a prolonged and extended battle. Shouldn't they say how
prolonged, how extended? Shouldn't they give at least some rough
order of the magnitude, in numbers of casualties or years of
military presence, that they think the cause is worth?
</P>
<P>
   The other new divide in the moral debate turns on what moral
stance to take when uncertainty about those questions is great and
cannot realistically be narrowed. It seems clear that one basis for
the pope's and the Catholic bishops' preference for pursuing even
the most unlikely wisp of a diplomatic settlement, rather than
prosecuting the war, is their conviction that war has a terrible
momentum of its own and is enormously unpredictable in its
consequences. So when in doubt, don't.
</P>
<P>
   The opposing position is often more implied than articulated,
but it has been eloquently expounded by Leon Wieseltier in an essay
in the current issue of The New Republic. Wieseltier is writing
about the Kosovo conflict in a secular political rather than a
religious framework, but in terms that are none the less moral. He
vehemently criticizes the now conventional American demand for an
``exit strategy,'' which he says ``fundamentally misunderstands the
nature of war and, more generally, the nature of historical
action.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In the name of caution, it denies the contingency of human
affairs,'' Wieseltier says, adding: ``We cannot completely predict
or completely determine the outcome of our best endeavors, though
our ignorance of their outcome does not make them less necessary or
less just. No great deed, private or public, has even been
undertaken in a bliss of certainty.''
</P>
<P>
   The new threshold of certainty ``is a scruple about the use of
force itself,'' he says, something that the Vatican might agree
with. ``It rigs the discussion about military power,'' Wieseltier
contends, in a way that would have prevented the United States from
undertaking any of the military actions that have proved most
``essential to the protection of our values and our interests.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe religious leaders and moral thinkers only need more time
to clarify their views on Kosovo. Unfortunately, it appears that
they will have more time than anyone wants.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
