<HEADLINE>
U.N. AGENCY SAYS BELGRADE SEEKS TO EXPEL ALL ETHNIC ALBANIANS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ELIZABETH OLSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA _ The U.N. refugee agency accused Yugoslavia Friday of
trying to expel the entire ethnic Albanian population from Kosovo,
where Albanians had made up 90 percent of the population.
</P>
<P>
   At least 12,000 people had fled the province to Albania,
Macedonia and Montenegro in the previous 24 hours, said Kris
Janowski, a spokesman for the U.N. high commission for refugees.
</P>
<P>
   ``The expulsions, which were put on hold or slowed down over the
last two weeks, have now resumed with full force,'' Janowski said
at a briefing. ``The effort by the Serb authorities to expel the
entire ethnic population of Kosovo is again under way.''
</P>
<P>
   As recently as a few months ago, he said, ``it would have seemed
unbelievable to the civilized world that the Serbs would actually
expel the entire civilian population, but that seems to be the
reality now.''
</P>
<P>
   The commission estimated that more than 700,000 people had fled
Kosovo in the last year, with 70,000 going to Montenegro, the
smaller republic in Yugoslavia; 120,000 to Macedonia; 320,000 to
Albania, and 32,000 to Bosnia and Herzegovina. The rest have moved
on to other countries.
</P>
<P>
   Janowski said the commission did not know how many Albanians
remained in Kosovo, but estimated the number at 400,000. That
figure is hard to calculate because ethnic Albanians did not
cooperate with the most recent Yugoslav census in Kosovo and
because the registration of those fleeing is incomplete, he said.
The province had 1.8 million people before the recent exodus.
</P>
<P>
   The commission cannot offer any solution to aid those in Kosovo,
Janowski said, although it is clear from refugees' statements that
``terrible things are happening in Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Women are telling us stories about their men being tortured
and shot,'' he said. ``It's a brutal expulsion. It's completely out
of control and blessed, we have to assume, by the authorities in
Belgrade, whose duty it is to protect the civilian population.''
</P>
</TEXT>
