<HEADER>
A2005 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-VOICES-ART-2TA     04-16 0905
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-VOICES-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICANS VIEW ATTACKS WITH IDEALISM, AMBIVALENCE AND SOME ALARM
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Tenn.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.) 
(rk) 
 By SUSAN SACHS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For all the wrenching scenes of Kosovo refugees and burning
buildings, of starched military men talking damage assessment, of
monochromatic video clips of exploding targets, the bombing
campaign against Yugoslavia was beginning to fade to a remote
concern for many people.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the news that up to 33,000 reservists may be called up for
service in the Balkans, a portent of widening American involvement,
has brought the war back into sharp focus.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Clark, a Vietnam veteran who works for the Westchester
County government, is angry and fearful that each new escalation
will spawn another. ``We can supply them ammunition and planes and
everything, but why do we have to get more involved?'' he asked
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Martha McCauley, a retired office worker, was half-expecting a
call-up and even the deployment of ground troops, but is still
exasperated that no end to the war is in sight. ``That guy is never
going to give in,'' she said of President Slobodan Milosevic of
Yugoslavia. ``I wish somebody would go over there and take that guy
out.''
</P>
<P>
   Dilia Theodosakia, a former secretary who is starting a new
career as a nutritionist, is disgusted at what she has come to
regard as NATO's ruthless pummeling of Serbian cities. ``They keep
pounding these people, throwing all these weapons on them, and they
have no way of defending themselves,'' she said. ``It's the
powerful taking advantage of the weak.''
</P>
<P>
   A note of alarm has crept into conversations with Clark, Mrs.
McCauley and Mrs. Theodosakia. They are among a dozen people who
live and work in White Plains, N.Y., who were interviewed several
times since March 24, when NATO first bombed Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   The idealistic notion that the United States and its allies are
pursuing a just, moral course _ saving an ethnic minority in Kosovo
_ still captivates many people. But for those who had doubts about
the credibility of President Clinton in particular, the government
in general, and the news media overall, events of the past week
have only deepened their unease.
</P>
<P>
   David Gammons, a 59-year-old painter and retired art teacher,
kept the television tuned to CNN nearly all the time in the early
days of the air attacks. But he confessed that he is now feeling
more and more detached. ``I'm getting very fatigued with the
story,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The stories of ragged and frightened Kosovo refugees still stir
his sympathy. The policy debate has begun to sound repetitive, even
boring.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been listening to some of the argument about sending
ground troops and not sending ground troops,'' Gammons said. ``It's
getting to be like Monica Lewinsky. It goes on and on, and here I
am, disconnected, trying to paint and live my life.''
</P>
<P>
   At the start of the bombing, there was more wonder than fatigue
when Gammons spoke of the lack of connection between the easy
routines of his life and the drama unfolding at the borders of
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just like in the movies,'' he said last month, after a
few days of watching television reports on the exodus of ethnic
Albanians. ``There they are leaving these places _ there was one
elderly lady carrying a child on her back, papoose style _ and here
I sit.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, Gammons said, he started to ask himself whether he could
fairly judge the situation from so great a distance, in terms of
miles and personal experience. ``In my suburban mentality, yes, we
should help them,'' he said. ``A lot of us say, `Yes, go and bomb.'
But they're not bombing my house, my yard. We sit and watch it on
TV.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, he said, if NATO believes that Milosevic is the problem,
as allied leaders are constantly saying, then they should go after
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got angry one day last week,'' said Gammons, who is a native
of Tennessee. ``I was watching television, and there was Milosevic
at a very nice table in a suit and tie. And I surmised that he had
had two lovely meals and a home to sleep in at night and has no one
shooting at him, while somebody else from Kosovo is out there, is
dying.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why _ and maybe this is the hillbilly redneck in me _ why
doesn't somebody go and shoot the bugger?''
</P>
<P>
   The same question occurs to Mrs. McCauley, who retired from IBM
and now, at 69, volunteers as a teacher's aide.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see how we can get out of this thing unless they get
him to sign something or do something, or do something to him,''
she said. ``The problem is, they don't trust him.''
</P>
<P>
   She has been doggedly supportive of what the United States and
NATO are doing. Disabling the Yugoslav president, she said, is a
moral obligation for the United States, a mission as honorable as
the one her father carried out as an American soldier fighting Nazi
Germany in World War II.
</P>
<P>
   The other night, she went to the theater to see ``Camelot'' and
found herself defending that position when two of her friends
argued that the United States has no business being part of a war
on Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   ``They feel that we are always interfering in all wars,'' Mrs.
McCauley recalled. ``But I said to them all, `We don't want to be
embarrassed like after the Holocaust.'''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   For Mrs. Theodosakia, there is nothing clear-cut anymore in
connection with Yugoslavia and certainly no heroes. To her, the
Serbs have become more sympathetic, the Kosovo Albanians more
complicated and the NATO campaign more cruel as the weeks of
bombing passed.
</P>
<P>
   An avid reader of The New York Times and The Washington Post,
she has veered sharply away from her initial confident support of
the allies.
</P>
<P>
   At first, she saw the ethnic Albanians as absolute underdogs.
Then she read about the Kosovo Liberation Army, the separatist
militia that has been fighting the Serbs for years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a lot of problems with this bombing operation,'' Mrs.
Theodosakia said. ``Sometimes I feel it's the right thing because I
feel sorry for these poor people, these refugees, because they had
to leave Kosovo. Then you hear stories that they were fighting for
independence and were very pushy.''
</P>
<P>
   At first, she saw the Serbs as absolute oppressors. Then, the
other night, she watched ``CNN World Report,'' which featured a
report by Serbian television on the bombing from the Serbian point
of view.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so glad I listened to these people,'' she said. ``They
are so bitter about the U.S. They were talking about their capital.
They have beautiful, magnificent buildings that they kept beautiful
and they are so afraid that they will all be destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel sorry for the Serbians, too. They are people. And
that's their country.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite her reading and research, Mrs. Theodosakia, 57, who was
born in Puerto Rico, has come to trust more in her emotions on the
issue of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   A bitter turning point came when she saw that NATO did not pause
in its bombing last Sunday, Orthodox Easter. ``They didn't stop,
even though Clinton did that for the problem they had in Iraq,''
she said, referring to the debate within the administration in
December 1998 over whether to continue bombing Iraq during the
Islamic holy month of Ramadan.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Theodosakia said she can not help but feel an affinity for
the Serbs because she, too, is an Orthodox Christian, while most
Kosovo Albanians are Muslim.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't misunderstand me. I feel every religion should practice
what they believe in,'' she said. ``But this religion that the
Albanians practice _ we Americans have a lot of problems with these
people, too.''
</P>
<P>
   She also described herself as a political conservative with a
distrust of President Clinton that has only deepened as the bombing
continued.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to judge the president, because I don't know
what's going through his mind,'' she said. ``But I don't trust him
anymore. I don't believe him. Does he do this because he cares
about the people in Kosovo, or for his own ego?
</P>
<P>
   ``What about Rwanda? What did he do about those problems? I was
listening to the radio _ I don't remember which program _ but they
were asking, `Is it because the Rwandans were black that we didn't
help them?' What's the difference? Are we going to help every
nation or are we are going to pick the ones we want to help? Why
these people?''
</P>
<P>
   Clark, the Vietnam veteran, said he is just as disturbed by
reports of atrocities in Kosovo. But until the United States or its
interests are directly threatened, he added, American soldiers and
civilians should stay out.
</P>
<P>
   When he heard Friday morning that reservists might be called up,
the 58-year-old former Marine shed some of the courtly ambivalence
that he had shown in discussing the situation over the past six
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a good move,'' Clark said forcefully. ``I don't think
it's necessary.'' There is no threat to American interests in
Yugoslavia, he said.
</P>
<P>
   He recalled a trip he made to visit his family in Panama, where
he was born, after the U.S. invasion there in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said they hit strategic sites in Panama,'' he said.
``Yeah, strategic sites _ the neighborhood I grew up in. But that's
basically what goes on. Civilians get hit.''
</P>
<P>
   That is why, he added, news of a possible call-up upsets him so.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we send our civilians in there and they get killed, then
people are going to say we've got to really go in there in force
and get engaged,'' Clark said. ``And then they are going to send in
ground troops, and if they start to die, sooner or later you've got
to send more and then more, and it could end up being another
Vietnam.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
