<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-LEWIS-HOLYFIELD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEWIS AND HOLYFIELD OFFER DIFFERENT VIEWS ON THEIR DRAW 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By TIMOTHY W. SMITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Evander Holyfield and Lennox Lewis, the two
participants in last month's controversial heavyweight championship
bout at Madison Square Garden, gave testimony in Manhattan on
Friday before the New York state Senate Committee on
Investigations. About the only thing the boxers could agree on was
that legislative reforms were needed to clean up the sport.
</P>
<P>
   They disagreed on the issue that sparked this hearing. Each
fighter said he thought he had won the March 13 bout, which was
ruled a draw after one judge scored the fight for Holyfield, one
had Lewis winning and one said it was even.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield appeared with his lawyer Jim Thomas before state Sen.
Roy Goodman's committee, which is looking into reforms in boxing.
Holyfield said Lewis did not do enough to win the fight. Regarding
the fifth round, when Lewis hurt him with a shot to the back of the
head, Holyfield said Lewis should have tried to finish him off.
Eugenia Williams, one of the bout's three judges, called the round
in Holyfield's favor, differing from the other two fight judges.
</P>
<P>
   ``That great fifth round that Lennox had lasted 45 seconds,''
Holyfield said. ``In the fifth round, if I had been in trouble, he
would have been able to knock me out. The fact is that he did score
more and I will give him the fifth round.''
</P>
<P>
   Goodman asked Holyfield if he was surprised Williams gave him
that round. ``No, it's a matter of opinion,'' Holyfield said.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, whose testimony was presented on videotape, called
Williams ``clueless'' and said he thought he had clearly won the
fifth round and some other rounds that she scored for Holyfield.
Lewis said judges, in general, can be influenced by promoters and
sanctioning organizations, but that is difficult to prove.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can influence them by wearing the right type of jewelry
and clothes,'' Lewis said. ``They're definitely swayed by that sort
of thing.''
</P>
<P>
   And while Lewis was in favor of getting rid of the sanctioning
organizations, Holyfield was not.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be easy for me to say get rid of all the belts, but
the belts have allowed me to make $200 million,'' Holyfield said.
``And if I say all of a sudden, get rid of all the belts, then I'm
a hypocrite.''
</P>
<P>
   A rematch between Holyfield and Lewis has been scheduled for
Nov. 6 or Nov. 13, either in Las Vegas or back at Madison Square
Garden. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
