<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-16 20:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2011 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CASSANDRA-WILSON18-CO     04-16 1035
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CASSANDRA-WILSON18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wilson does legend proud in homage to Miles Davis
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, April 18.
 &HT;    By Steve Dollar
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ About 15 minutes into a telephone conversation from
her Columbus, Ohio, hotel room, Cassandra Wilson allows that
something else has been diverting her attention.
</P>
<P>
   She's been watching ``Days of Wine and Roses,'' the 1962 movie
starring Jack Lemmon and Lee Remick. More importantly, she's become
a little entranced by the film's theme song, written by those
``Moon River'' guys, Henry Mancini and Johnny Mercer. ``It's not
like these big Hollywood movies these days with these huge
orchestral pieces,'' says Wilson, a few days into a tour that
brings her to Variety Playhouse on Thursday. ``It's one tune that
you hear throughout.''
</P>
<P>
   It reminds Wilson, 43, of a comment someone once made to her.
``They felt I was singing the same song, that every tune I write
seems to be the same song.'' This was meant as a compliment, of
course: that the singer, whose contralto is so often described as
``smoky'' or ``sultry,'' brings coherence to her material, which
springs up from a consistent core of feeling. It's part of what has
allowed the Jackson, Miss., native to venture so far afoot from the
sometimes narrow expectations of a traditional jazz career.
</P>
<P>
   Spinning variations on blues and folk themes, steeping them in a
strong feminine identity infused with Yoruba spiritualism and jazz
lore, Wilson has been widely acknowledged as the next important
jazz vocalist _ a 1990s inheritor of Billie Holiday and Betty
Carter. Yet, she's also reimagined what that can mean. On such
recent albums as ``Blue Light 'Til Dawn'' (1993) and ``New Moon
Daughter'' (1995), and especially the new ``Traveling Miles'' (all
on the Blue Note label) _ a tribute to the music of Miles Davis _
the singer explores an expanded vocabulary of band arrangements and
song material that is beginning to sound exclusively her own.
</P>
<P>
   And like Davis, the mythic jazz trumpeter and band leader who
died in 1991, Wilson is fearless about experimentation, about
crossing musical boundaries, about messing with the rules. Yet, as
jazz scholar Robert G. O'Meally observed recently in The New York
Times, there is an even more explicit connection:
</P>
<P>
   ``The debt Wilson owes Davis is apparent in her singing: the
weight, and yet the delicacy, of her voice, the breathy flight
above and behind the beat, the insistence on melody in
improvisation and, most strikingly, the art by subtraction, the
creation of spaces between bursts of sounds.''
</P>
<P>
   Such creative kinship is a major part of what makes ``Traveling
Miles'' a rich and compelling project. The 12-track CD features
music from the chilled-out, acoustic Davis of the 1950s and '60s
but also prominent material from the '70s and '80s, when the
trumpeter's forays into a funk-driven electric sound sparked
controversy (and record sales). Except when the songs were already
borrowed (Cyndi Lauper's ``Time After Time,'' ``Someday My Prince
Will Come''), Wilson adds her own lyrics, and performs three songs
of her own. Though the vocalist insists she wasn't trying to claim
Davis' music, but rather honor it, she thoroughly succeeds in
personalizing it.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Miles' music was too heavy for some people, Cassandra's
arrangements have a quality that draws you in,'' says Regina
Carter, the violinist who performs on ``Traveling Miles'' and was
on the bandstand when the concept was staged last year by Jazz at
Lincoln Center. ``When she arranges, she thinks more of a scenario
or a feeling. We were working on a piece, and she told me to think
of when I was a little girl, and my music box was broken and it
played the same thing over and over. After I heard the tune, it
totally made sense. When you hear it, it's very fresh.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea came about two years ago when Wilson was invited by
Jazz at Lincoln Center to do a few concerts, following her
extensive tour with Wynton Marsalis and the JALC orchestra for the
slavery epic ``Blood on the Fields.'' But the project was clearly
something Wilson had been working up to her whole life. She
remembers being 6 or 7 years old and fishing out the Davis-Gil
Evans orchestral collaboration ``Sketches of Spain'' from her
father's record collection.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just the contrast between that and the rest of the
music that was in his collection,'' she says. ``I realized even at
that age that there was some sort of hybridization that was
happening on that album. It intrigued me. It was very evocative.
It's very broad, very expansive, the kind of music you can walk
inside of and actually inhabit. And for a child, it's a great place
for a fantasy.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson, whose current tour with a sextet offers yet another spin
on the ``Traveling Miles'' songbook, invited a string quartet to
join her at Lincoln Center, but otherwise has avoided anything
remotely as orchestral as ``Sketches.'' Instead, she's intensely
focused on the way stringed instruments, especially guitars, can
interact, creating a sound at once rhythmic and lyrical.
Noticeably, horns are absent from the album, save the first and
last cuts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I seem to be really preoccupied with guitar for some reason
these days,'' says Wilson, who grew up under the influence of her
jazz bassist father and the folk music of Joni Mitchell and Judy
Collins, ``and probably need to go see a therapist to understand
why. I had all kinds of visions about guitars, different kinds of
guitars and the textures they create.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's funny, I was just remembering my first experience with a
guitar, when I was very small and I used to play with the part of
guitar between the bridge and the endpiece. The string overlaps,
and it make this `ting ting' sound. Actually, that's the harmonics.
I used to play with that. And you wonder why you end up at certain
places in music. There's something in your childhood.''
</P>
<P>
   CONCERT
</P>
<P>
   Cassandra Wilson
</P>
<P>
   8 p.m. Thursday. $25. Variety Playhouse, 1099 Euclid Ave. N.E.,
Atlanta404-521-1786.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Dollar writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
