<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLASSICALMUSIC-NOTES18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLASSICAL MUSIC NOTES
 &HT;    Pulitzer win third for women composers
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, April 18.
 &HT;    By Judith Green
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   This year's Pulitzer Prize in music went to Melinda Wagner, born
in 1957 in Philadelphia. Her ``Concerto for Flute, Strings and
Percussion,'' commissioned by the American Composers Orchestra, was
premiered in Purchase, N.Y., in May 1998 by the Westchester (N.Y.)
Philharmonic.
</P>
<P>
   Wagner is the third woman to win the Pulitzer for music since
the award was instituted in 1943. The others were Ellen Taaffe
Zwilich of New York in 1983 and Shulamit Ran, an Israeli composer
teaching at the University of Chicago, in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   This year's jury for music was made up of composers Gunther
Schuller, Leslie Bassett and Wayne Peterson, all previous Pulitzer
winners; jazz-based composer John Lewis, who has worked with the
Modern Jazz Quartet; and Tim Page, Pulitzer Prize-winning music
critic for The Washington Post.
</P>
<P>
   Other finalists for the music prize were ``Persistent Memory''
by David Rakowski and ``Concerto for Orchestra'' by
composer-conductor Stanislaw Skrowaczewski, who teaches at the
Curtis Institute of Music in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview on the American Composers Orchestra Web site
(americancomposers.org), Wagner talked about commissioning programs
such as that of the ACO for giving young composers a chance to be
heard.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's going to make the next century possible for us,'' she
said. ``Before that, you had to have gotten your Pulitzer Prize to
get a major orchestra to play your work.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, now she has. And she gets $5,000, too.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  IN A NUTSHELL: This is positively the last thing you'll read
here about the $150,000 ``Rhapsody'' piano, a decorator instrument
_ midnight blue glossy finish embedded with mother-of-pearl stars _
that Steinway &AMP; Sons has created to honor the centenary of George
Gershwin.
</P>
<P>
   Pianist Marcus Roberts played ``Rhapsody in Blue'' on it last
weekend with the Atlanta Symphony Orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   The finest thumbnail description came from ASO artistic
administrator J. Frank Dans, who said: ``The perfect thing to play
on it would be `Le Tombeau de Liberace.'''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, that's a real piece, by camp composer Michael Daugherty,
who has written symphonies on such pop culture icons as Marilyn
Monroe and Elvis, as well as a mock homage to J. Edgar Hoover.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  NEW BATON: Julian Shew has been named director of university
orchestras at Georgia State University, succeeding interim director
Gregory Pritchard, who has held the job for the past academic year.
A native of Nanking, China, Shew holds advanced degrees from the
University of Missouri at Kansas City and the University of Kansas.
He comes to Georgia State from Gustavus Adolphus College in
Minnesota. He has a long track record with student and youth
orchestras in the United States and Europe.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  GLASS SLIPPERS: Atlanta Ballet will field three couples in the
lead roles for its May 6-16 production of ``Cinderella'': Christine
Winkler and John Welker, who are set to tie the knot in real life
on May 28; Julianne Kepley and Wei Dongsheng; and Hye-Young Kim and
Joe Roesner. There will be two truly homely pairs of stepsisters:
Jim Stein and Rodolfo Patella, and Xiao Chen and Damien Highfield.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  E-mail: jgreen(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Judith Green writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
