<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-16 20:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2013 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JAZZFESTIVAL18-COX     04-16 1035
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAZZFESTIVAL18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    In its 30 years, the New Orleans Jazz &AMP; Heritage Festival has
become one of the country's premier cultural events
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, April 18.
 &HT;    By Anne Rochell Konigsmark
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ Thirty years ago, 300 musicians performed for a
handful of people in a park on the edge of the French Quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Duke Ellington was there; so were Mahalia Jackson and Fats
Domino. Woody Allen took a break from filming ``Bananas'' to play
the clarinet with a Dixieland jazz band. Gospel music, propelled by
a piano plunked down in the grass, emanated from a small tent.
Local artists sold paintings and crafts, and 20 food booths served
regional specialties. Throughout the New Orleans Jazz &AMP; Heritage
Festival's first five days, performers outnumbered the audience.
</P>
<P>
   Also there was Quint Davis, a 19-year-old Tulane University
student hired by festival creator George Wein to scout out bands.
Davis, who had been working in the Tulane Jazz Archives, knew more
about the local music scene than anyone else.
</P>
<P>
   ''George's idea was to create a festival where New Orleans could
trumpet its birthright, its place in the cultural world and in
jazz,'' Davis said of Wein, a Bostonian who also founded the
Newport Jazz Festival. ''It would have night concerts and a
heritage fair. It had all the same elements the festival now has.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we first started,'' Davis remembers, ``there were a lot
of reasons people thought this thing was a hopeless failure. They
said, `You can't mix all these people _ old people, young people,
white people, black people, rich people, poor people.''' In 1970,
integration was still relatively new in the South; having black and
white musicians play for mixed audiences still seemed novel.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we had a theory,'' Davis says, ``that if you show people
what each other eats and what each other dances to, it'd be all
right. We were right; it works.''
</P>
<P>
   It didn't work right away. The first few years were such a flop
that the festival's board of directors tried to persuade Wein to do
away with the outdoor Louisiana Heritage Fair and just stage the
Evening Concert Series, with big-name acts. Davis' father, a
successful architect, kept his son's venture afloat.
</P>
<P>
   Davis never finished college. Instead, he stayed with Wein and
the festival, turning it into one of the most respected and
well-known cultural events in the country.
</P>
<P>
   The New Orleans Jazz &AMP; Heritage Festival, called Jazz Fest for
short, will be celebrated for the 30th time beginning Friday. While
it retains the same elements as that first year, it has become a
very different event.
</P>
<P>
   Some 10,000 musicians, artists and food vendors will descend on
the sprawling Fair Grounds Race Track, home of the gathering since
the early 1970s. Bands will play on 12 stages for seven days over
two weekends; 74 vendors will sell food. And if the weather is
good, attendance could total 500,000 before the festival ends May
2.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its size, the original spirit of this ``indigenous
self-celebration by a culture'' remains. Unlike other festivals,
where musicians, artists and food vendors are mostly out-of-towners
who travel around the country, Jazz Fest is primarily local.
Performers and vendors are chosen to reflect some aspect of New
Orleans or Louisiana culture, as are the folks who demonstrate such
traditional Cajun skills as boat-building and accordion-making.
</P>
<P>
   And although the festival always features big-name, out-of-town
bands _ this year's include Widespread Panic and Santana _ the vast
majority are New Orleans regulars. While Hootie &AMP; the Blowfish
entertain the masses May 1 on the largest stage, local heroes
Kermit Ruffins &AMP; the Barbecue Swingers will play classic jazz on a
smaller stage to a crowd more reminiscent of earlier festivals.
Other hometown favorites that day will include Nathan &AMP; the Zydeco
Cha-Chas, Ellis Marsalis and the Preservation Hall Jazz Band.
</P>
<P>
   Getting `pre-thrilled'
</P>
<P>
   Although crowds wouldn't come if the music and the food weren't
world class, what makes Jazz Fest special is harder to describe.
Davis recalls one year when tornadoes knocked down many of the
tents and the festival was closed for a day.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we were cleaning up, people started showing up,
festivalgoers, to rebuild,'' he said. ``That's something you never
forget.''
</P>
<P>
   While some critics charge that Jazz Fest has gotten too large
and that corporate sponsorship has ruined the grass-roots feel of
the early days, Davis brushes such talk aside.
</P>
<P>
   ``Corporate sponsorship is not a problem for us,'' he said.
``It's a form of security. The fact that we have a Sprint stage
allows us to have a great communications system we could never
afford, but they don't put singing operators onstage. They don't
interfere with the fest's integrity.''
</P>
<P>
   The nonprofit event costs $1 million a day to put on, and that
kind of price tag requires not only corporate sponsors, but also,
at least backstage, a corporate attitude.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a homemade, hand-built festival with a country fair
ambience,'' Davis said. ``But underneath it's complex and highly
polished.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked about his favorite moment during the last 29
festivals, Davis couldn't name one.
</P>
<P>
   ``The exciting moments, the thrilling moments, the memorable
moments are the ones that haven't come yet,'' he said. Thinking of
some of the acts he's most excited to see this year _ Dr. John, Ray
Charles and Fats Domino together for the first time; Fred Hammond
and Radical for Christ in the Gospel Tent; Hootie &AMP; the Blowfish on
one of the big stages _ he said simply, ``I get pre-thrilled.''
Davis is so devoted to music that he zooms around the fairgrounds
in a personalized golf cart, making it his mission to see every
band, at least for a few minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``There aren't many local musicians that Quint isn't on a
first-name basis with,'' said George Porter Jr., bass player for
the funky Meters and for Runnin' Pardners. ``I can't remember when
he wasn't a part of our lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Anne Rochell Konigsmark writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
