<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPOLETE-GUIDE18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    THE BEST OF SPOLETO
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, April 18.
 &HT;    By Wendell Brock
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Spoleto Festival USA, which runs May 28-June 13 in Charleston,
S.C., functions like a shopping mart for arts lovers. This year's
opera and theater offerings look particularly strong, while the
literary series is conspicuously absent. As always, the chamber and
new-music series are well worth a listen. Our guide to some of the
best options (tickets, 843-723-0402; brochures, 843-722-2764):
</P>
<P>
   CLASSICAL MUSIC
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Il Trittico.'' Director Nigel Redden won't even say how much
the fest is spending on this lavish triple bill of Puccini
one-acts. Count on about 3 1/2 hours of costume-drama overload and
gorgeous singing. May 28 and 31; June 5 and 11. $15-$75. Gaillard
Municipal Auditorium,
</P>
<P>
   77 Calhoun St.
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC THEATER
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Songs and Stories From Moby Dick.'' The performance artist
Laurie Anderson assumes a new persona: talking book. For her new
visual and aural meditation on the Melville classic, she'll use an
ensemble of musicians instead of the usual symphony of one. June
3-4. $10-$45. Gaillard Municipal Auditorium, 77 Calhoun St.
</P>
<P>
   THEATER
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Mamba's Daughters.'' With some 16 cast members, including
the mesmeric Heather Gillespie in the central role, this 1939 work
is the sort of old-fashioned melodrama that no one does anymore.
Set in Charleston and the surrounding islands, it's got big-voiced
Gullah spirituals and a heart-breaking Jerome Kern chestnut. May
27-31; June 2-6; June 8-13. $35. Dock Street Theatre, 133 Church
St.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Kwaidan.'' After its premiere last year at Atlanta's Center
for Puppetry Arts, Journal-Constitution theater critic Dan Hulbert
called this rendering of three Japanese ghost tales ``stage magic
at its most sublime.'' Directed by New York artist Ping Chong. June
4-8, 10-13. $30. Emmett Robinson Theatre, Albert Simons Center,
College of Charleston, 54 St. Philip St.
</P>
<P>
   DANCE
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Miami City Ballet. Dancing Balanchine classics and resident
choreographer Jimmy Gamonet De Los Heros' swingy ``The Big Band
SUPERMEGA-
</P>
<P>
   TROID,'' this impeccably trained company looks especially strong
these days. May 29-30. $15-$60. Gaillard Municipal Auditorium, 77
Calhoun St.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Quasar Companhia de Danca. This anatomically powerful
contemporary Brazilian company uses humor and body sculpture to
evoke lines that are as erotic as the tribal tattoos painted on
their chests. The kind of choreography that R.E.M.'s Michael Stipe
might dream up. May 29-31. $25. Garden Theatre, 371 King St.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Ron Brown/Evidence. Combining demanding physicality with
loosey-goosey technique, Brown is leading the pack of the younger
generation of African-American choreographers. A youthful, highly
energetic ensemble. June 10-13. $25. Garden Theatre, 371 King St.
</P>
<P>
   JAZZ
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Sonny Rollins. Always all over the place, the great tenor sax
player remains consistently in the groove, with a style that's as
well clipped as his salt-and-pepper beard. June 12. $10-$40. North
Charleston Coliseum, 5001 Coliseum Drive.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Denise Jannah. Critics, particularly the one who produced this
vocalist's first album, have made a big fuss over Jannah's
classical sensibilities _ comparing her to Sarah, Ella and Carmen
McRae. It's much too early for such lavish praise, but she's
awfully nice to come home to. May 29. $25. The Cistern, College of
Charleston, 66 George St.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Frank Emilio Flynn. Whether playing solo or with his
seven-piece Havana combo, the septuagenarian Cuban pianist never
loses his playful touch. Rarely heard in the States, he'll play
from Cuban composer Ernesto Lecuona's eponymous, Afro-Cuban bag of
tricks. June 4 at East Beach Conference Center, Kiawah Island
Resort; June 5 at the Cistern, 66 George St.. $25 each.
</P>
<P>
   _ Wendell Brock writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
