</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME&AMP;GARDENFURNITURE-TRENDS17- </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    At century's end, furniture styles take glance back
 &HT;    By Danny C. Flanders
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HIGH POINT, N.C. _ A new century, like a new year, presents a
new start, and if you're thinking of redecorating your home,
furniture designers say to think clean, casual and curvy.
</P>
<P>
   Clean as in the simple lines of contemporary. Casual as in a
less fussy French. And curvy as in 1920s, '30s and '40s modern.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until we close the book on this century and head into a new
millennium, there's going to be a lot of looking back to the past
for inspiration for the future. The important styles we thought had
been put to bed have been brought back to life as a punctuation
mark on the century,'' interior and furniture designer Jena Hall
said during Thursday's opening of the world's largest furniture
market.
</P>
<P>
   The 90th International Home Furnishings Market is a weeklong
wholesale preview of what should appear in stores by fall.
</P>
<P>
   Hall, along with designers Vladimir Kagan and Bob Mackie, says
the new emphasis will be on:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  French elegance that's less ornate and more casual.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Asian themes that are clean and contemporary.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  A nostalgic revival of art moderne's curvy shapes and sleek
finishes.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the biggest things we're seeing is what we're calling
the `French Evolution,' like a casual cottage look turning very
romantic and elegant,'' said Mark McMenamin, an editor for the
trade journal Home Accents Today. ``At the other end, formal French
styles like Louis XV are turning softer.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta-based Mary Bairstow Designs, a high-end manufacturer of
French furnishings, is introducing a line of hand-painted tables
and chairs called ``Colors of Provence,'' available exclusively
over the Internet. By selling directly to consumers, the company
eliminates the middle-man retailer, which typically doubles or
triples the wholesale price. The company's 18th-century
reproduction chairs are hand-painted in one of 10 finishes and
accented with a floral motif by two French artists in Atlanta. The
chairs are priced at $250 and the round pedestal table at $750.
</P>
<P>
   Lower-priced furnishings also target consumers aiming to mix new
pieces with other furnishings for an eclectic look, as the
Europeans blend traditional and contemporary. ``That way you get
the casualness everyone wants with a little elegance thrown in,''
Bairstow said.
</P>
<P>
   The same approach is making Asian-inspired furnishings,
headlining the past several markets, soar at this venue.
</P>
<P>
   What's different at this market is that manufacturers have
scaled down pieces to create cleaner, simpler lines, an Asian
minimalism that emphasizes ``less is more.'' High-lacquered
finishes and ornate Chinese chinoiserie will always be popular
among traditional high-end consumers, but modern and casual have
become the driving force, McMenamin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fabulous thing is you don't have to have all Chinese.
Oriental is so different that you can change the look of any room
by simply adding one or two pieces, just as accents,'' said Paige
Smith of PierceMartin, an Atlanta manufacturer of wicker, rattan
and iron.
</P>
<P>
   Cleaner, simpler lines also are returning in styles such as art
moderne _ the retro influence as designers close the books on a
century of design. Designer Larry Laslo has expanded his Moderne
Collection for Bexley Heath that recalls late-'40s France. And
Raphael Zenie has created the Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer Collection for
Classic Leather, which draws on the simple but glamorous
furnishings of Hollywood films.
</P>
<P>
   ``Retro is the most beautiful, modern things we've done in the
past,'' said Mackie, known for clothing Cher and Carol Burnett and
now designing furnishings.
</P>
<P>
   Make no mistake, like MGM, retro roars at High Point.
</P>
<P>
   NEW CENTURY COLORS
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Gray becomes the neutral in home decor, from pearl gray to
gunmetal, especially in paints.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Green, reflecting the gardening motif, shows up on fabrics in
shades of sage, spruce, kiwi and lime.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Honey-toned, weathered or crackled finishes remain popular in
accessories.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Deep, rich earth tones, such as burnished browns and paprika,
enrich leather upholstery.
</P>
<P>
   Danny C. Flanders writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
