<HEADER>
A2016 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PRIESTS-COPS17-COX     04-16 1077
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRIESTS-COPS17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A priest celebrates 50 years in the pulpit _ and nearly as many
in league with the law
 &HT;    By Gayle White
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ You can call the Rev. R. Donald Kiernan ``monsignor,''
the honorary title awarded by the Roman Catholic Archdiocese of
Atlanta for special service. You can call him ``captain,'' the rank
he holds with the Georgia State Patrol. You can call him
``colonel,'' his rank in the DeKalb County (Ga.) police department.
Or, you can call him ``doctor'' for the honorary criminal justice
degree he received from Georgia State University last year.
</P>
<P>
   On May 8, Kiernan will celebrate 50 years as a Roman Catholic
priest and 50 years as a Georgian. Both Kiernan's fellow priests
and his fellow police officers are looking forward to the
festivities.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's going to be a hell of a party,'' says Lt. Ric Clark of
DeKalb County's north police precinct. There will also be a Mass at
7 p.m. at the 3,300-family All Saints Catholic Church in Dunwoody
(Ga.), where Kiernan is pastor.
</P>
<P>
   He was ordained in Boston for the Diocese of Savannah (Ga.)_
which then covered all of Georgia _ in 1949. After half a century
in Georgia, he still maintains his Massachusetts accent.
</P>
<P>
   His record in law enforcement rivals his record in the church:
He was a founder of the Georgia Association of Chiefs of Police and
the organization's director and chaplain, and has served as
chaplain of the International Association of Chiefs of Police,
Georgia State Patrol, DeKalb County police department, Georgia
Bureau of Investigation, Atlanta office of the U.S. Treasury's
Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms, and Metropol, a
cooperative agency of local police and corporations.
</P>
<P>
   In the archdiocese, he has pastored churches in Savannah,
LaGrange (Ga.) and throughout North Georgia, was editor of The
Georgia Bulletin archdiocesan newspaper for 13 years, and now
serves as a member of the marriage tribunal, considering
applications for annulment.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's one of the most popular priests in the whole
archdiocese,'' says Archbishop John F. Donoghue. ``He's very
well-respected by priests and laity alike.''
</P>
<P>
   Kiernan won't give his age, but the archbishop lets slip that he
is the oldest active priest in the archdiocese.
</P>
<P>
   His relationship with law enforcement began in the early 1950s
with a call to Atlanta police about a prowler in the basement of
Atlanta's Shrine of the Immaculate Conception, where he was
assistant pastor. Two young officers, M.C. Faulkner and A.L. Posey
_ Kiernan remembers their names immediately _ responded and asked
the equally young priest to ride along with them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure 'nuff, the next night they came around and asked me
again,'' says Kiernan. And again, and again.
</P>
<P>
   Kiernan met sergeants, lieutenants and the then-Atlanta police
chief, the late Herbert Jenkins, who became a close friend.
</P>
<P>
   When assigned to a church in Cedartown, Kiernan realized there
was no state police academy to train officers in small towns. He
set up training for North Georgia officers, with help from Jenkins.
</P>
<P>
   In 1962, while pastor of St. Michael's Church in Gainesville, he
helped found the Georgia Association of Chiefs of Police because he
saw a need for heads of law enforcement agencies to be able to work
together and learn from each other.
</P>
<P>
   He's been a member of the International Association of Chiefs of
Police since the 1950s, riding to meetings held in the United
States because he will not fly.
</P>
<P>
   Maj. Gene Moss, commander of DeKalb County's north police
precinct, drove Kiernan to a meeting in Florida in 1997. ``There
were 16,000 people,'' says Moss. ``I may be exaggerating some, but
I really believe he knew 15,000 of them by first name. I have never
seen anybody know so many police officers.''
</P>
<P>
   Marietta Police Chief Bobby Moody met Kiernan shortly after he
became police chief in Covington in 1978 when he was 30 years old.
</P>
<P>
   ``He literally took me by the hand at a Metropol meeting, the
first one my wife and I went to, and introduced us to everybody,''
says Moody. ``For me, it was a bit of culture shock as a little
country boy from Covington to meet chiefs from Atlanta and Fulton
County.''
</P>
<P>
   As a Baptist, Moody said he also experienced a bit of culture
shock watching Kiernan play host and bartender in the hotel's
hospitality suite. ``I was mesmerized by this little priest running
around taking care of people,'' says Moody.
</P>
<P>
   Moody says he feels very close to Kiernan. ``I seek out the
monsignor when I need somebody I can just talk to,'' he says. ``We
play golf together. He's not the best golfer in the world and wants
to use an eraser on the score card, but as far as I'm concerned,
the monsignor gets any score he wants.''
</P>
<P>
   Kiernan's reputation extends even to officers who don't know him
personally. He tells this story on himself:
</P>
<P>
   Driving to Gainesville one day, Kiernan was pulled over by a
Gwinnett County deputy who began, typically, ``Do you know how fast
you were going?''
</P>
<P>
   ``83,'' said Kiernan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't clock you that fast,'' said the deputy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw the blue light and slowed down,'' said the monsignor.
</P>
<P>
   ``You sure are an honest man,'' said the deputy. ``What are
those antennas on your car?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm chaplain for the Georgia State Patrol,'' said the
monsignor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, you're the masseur, aren't you?'' said the deputy.
</P>
<P>
   Kiernan got off with a warning.
</P>
<P>
   Although Kiernan clearly enjoys his relationship with police
officers, some of his duties with them are deadly serious. He
accompanies officials to inform family members of deaths, performs
funerals for officers who are not affiliated with a church, and
counsels police struggling with family and spiritual concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Kiernan expresses great admiration for police officers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think any job in the world where you have to wear a
bulletproof vest to work should be better compensated,'' he says.
``In business today, you find dog-eat-dog. What attracts me to them
is they care for one another.''
</P>
<P>
   But Kiernan says he has no desire to be an amateur investigator
himself, in the tradition of fictional priest-detectives such as
Andrew Greeley's Father Blackie Ryan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got a parish and I'm busy,'' he says. ``I don't know how
Father Ryan has the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Gayle White writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
