<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON SURVEYS, RESEARCH AND NEW CONSUMER PRODUCTS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 18) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   An Unexpected Detour Into the Balkan War &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The errant phone calls are beginning to tail off, but he still
gets dozens a day, and Steve Penisten wonders what his next phone
bill will look like.
</P>
<P>
   Penisten owns Helco Manufacturing, a small company in Sioux
Falls, S.D., that makes fancy stainless-steel barbecue tools and
sells them mainly to distributors and to companies that want their
logos engraved on the handles.
</P>
<P>
   Though he rarely deals directly with the public, he has an
easy-to-remember toll-free number, (800) USA-CHEF, and that's where
the trouble started.
</P>
<P>
   When the Kosovo refugee crisis erupted, a toll-free line was
widely publicized that the public could call to contribute to
relief efforts: (800) USAID-RELIEF. But many people dial (800)
USA-AIDE-RELIEF by mistake, which works out to (800) 872-2433 _
Helco's number.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can tell right away when a caller is confused,'' said
Penisten, who said Kosovo-related calls still far outnumber calls
from his customers and often fill his voice mailbox to overflowing
overnight.
</P>
<P>
   He shrugged off the business disruptions, saying they were
trivial compared with the refugees' hardships and the perils for
American military personnel in the Balkans. He said he explains the
mix-up to callers and offers to mail catalogs to any who show
interest in his products.
</P>
<P>
   ``I might make a sale or two; you never know,'' he said. ``After
all, I am paying for the call.''
</P>
<P>
   Patrick J. Lyons &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Applied Whimsy &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Technology companies have long had a taste for fanciful names
like General Magic and U.S. Robotics that perhaps say more about
the founders' teen-age reading habits than about their businesses.
</P>
<P>
   An Austin, Texas, company, still in the venture capital stage
but presumably aspiring to an eventual public offering, would seem
to be in that category with its chosen name: Applied Science
Fiction. It develops digital image technology and licenses it to
camera and scanner makers.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, though, the name came from an offhand remark: One of
the founding engineers, trying to summarize for an early investor
what the company does, pointed to its chief scientist, Albert D.
Edgar, and said, ``He thinks of the science fiction, and we try to
apply it,'' according to Mary E. Browning, the company's director
of marketing communications.
</P>
<P>
   From her description, Edgar might be a science-fiction scientist
himself, from the eyeglasses held together with duct tape to the
homemade ink he whips up for his inkjet printer. (On weekends he
photographs weddings.)
</P>
<P>
   Do investors find such a nonserious name at all off-putting?
``Maybe 10 years ago they might have,'' Ms. Browning said. ``But
now? When there's a company called Yahoo?''
</P>
<P>
   Patrick J. Lyons
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-16-99 2036EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
