<DOCNO> NYT19990416.0336 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-16 20:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2018 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SMALLTOWN-DOC18-COX     04-16 1035
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMALLTOWN-DOC18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Five counties will pay tribute to beloved doctor
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, April 18.
 &HT;    By Bo Emerson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Ga. _ Dr. Robert E. Jennings took care of folks in
this one-red-light South Georgia town for 39 years, delivering
their babies, sewing up their chain-saw wounds and even treating
the occasional snakebit dog.
</P>
<P>
   When his patients needed help after 5 p.m., they'd call him at
home. Or drop by.
</P>
<P>
   ``People didn't go to the emergency room,'' says his daughter
Felicia Alexander. ``They'd just knock on the back door.''
</P>
<P>
   For years the tall, broad-shouldered physician and his family
lived in a yellow-brick ranch house across the street from the
hospital, so finding the doctor was easy. Finding a replacement
won't be.
</P>
<P>
   Jennings died last fall at age 65, leaving the 1,200 residents
of Arlington in shock.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a piece of this hospital is just broke off,'' says
Vivian Whitaker, director of nurses at Calhoun Memorial Hospital,
where Jennings was not only chief of staff but half the staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``This town like to have folded,'' says David Simpson, who runs
the Arlington Rexall Pharmacy. ``Everything that went on in this
town, he was a part of. It wasn't just medicine. He was a
counselor, a physician, a psychiatrist.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, patients and friends from throughout the farming country
of Calhoun, Early, Baker, Clay and Randolph counties will gather in
Arlington to pay tribute to the bearish doctor with the giant-size
heart. During the proceedings, the city will officially rename a
street and a clinic in his honor. Henceforward, Calhoun Memorial
Hospital's official address will be 209 R.E. Jennings Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want people to remember him when they ride down that street
in front of the hospital,'' says Peggy Pierce, Calhoun Memorial's
chief executive officer.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Kelly may remember Jennings every time he takes a breath. The
owner of Kelly Construction was experiencing an allergic reaction
to penicillin, and rapidly sinking into anaphylactic shock, when a
quick-thinking Jennings administered the antidote. ``He was just
about dead,'' says Kelly's wife, Ann.
</P>
<P>
   Coming to the rescue
</P>
<P>
   The town itself was in a similar medical emergency when Jennings
arrived in 1959.
</P>
<P>
   There was no doctor in Arlington. The hospital had closed. For
Arlington's 1,400 souls, the nearest physicians were nine miles
away in Edison and 20 miles the other way in Blakely.
</P>
<P>
   A state-funded scholarship brought Jennings, a native of
Atlanta, and Dr. Homer L. Lassiter to the rescue. As a condition of
the scholarship, after graduating from the Medical College of
Georgia, Jennings, then 26, and Lassiter, 25, were obliged to
practice in an underserved Georgia community of 5,000 or fewer
people.
</P>
<P>
   The residents of Arlington were overjoyed at the doctors'
arrival, and suspicious only of their youth. Arlington was a small
town where the peanut fields started just a few blocks from the
depot, and a small-town doctor has to handle every illness or
catastrophe that comes through the door _ which suited Jennings and
former partner Lassiter fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``He saved all kinds of lives,'' says pharmacist Simpson,
``especially heart attack victims that wouldn't have made it to
Albany.''
</P>
<P>
   Jennings would see between 28 and 50 patients a day and was on
call every other night. As his practice grew, so did his family. He
and wife Pauline had four children; they moved from the house
across the street from the hospital to one farther away, with a
pool and a pond. And Jennings joined City Council and even served
as mayor for a while.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was about the same as being a doctor,'' says Pauline of his
public service. ``They called on him for any little problem: My
water doesn't have pressure; there's a dog barking next door to me;
somebody's cow got out.''
</P>
<P>
   Additional stress came when Jennings and Lassiter, two very
different personality types, split up their practice in 1981. Two
years later, Robert and Pauline Jennings were divorced. A smoker
and a non-exerciser, Jennings also suffered the first of two heart
attacks around the same time.
</P>
<P>
   Calhoun Memorial nurse Susie Peterson accompanied Jennings
during his ambulance ride to Albany after his second heart attack,
praying all along that she wouldn't accidentally kill Arlington's
beloved doctor.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anything went wrong, I think I would have shot myself,''
Peterson says. ``I wouldn't have come back to this town, that's for
sure.''
</P>
<P>
   `Nothing you could do'
</P>
<P>
   Jennings survived. In 1993, he married Delores Fallin and bought
Clyde, a baby African Gray parrot, whom he fed through a syringe.
</P>
<P>
   Jennings and Clyde became inseparable, says Delores, and every
morning the two shared a cup of coffee. When the doctor napped on
the sofa after lunch, Clyde would nap on his shoulder, his head
under his wing.
</P>
<P>
   The Jenningses went out to dinner on Saturday, Sept. 19, and
returned that evening to be greeted, as usual, by their two
Rottweilers and by Clyde. In the early morning hours, the time when
Jennings had risen so often to treat emergencies or scrub for labor
and delivery, he died. Dr. David Wetherby of nearby Fort Gaines
says the cause was probably a heart attack.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday morning, the nursing staff assembled at the hospital,
not knowing why, except to mourn. ``We all came in crying, thinking
that if we could be together, it would go away,'' says Pierce, the
hospital CEO.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. David Kocherla of Albany has been taking care of Jennings'
patients. Lassiter moved to Albany last year, leaving Arlington
without a resident M.D.
</P>
<P>
   Jennings delivered Vivian Temple's daughter Wilma in 1963 and
her granddaughter April in 1980. And Temple, as she stood outside
the Arlington pharmacy talking about her favorite doctor, said
she's all for naming the street after him. ``They need to honor him
some way, and that would be a way that everyone could see. But
there's no kind of expression, no kind of nothing you could do,
that could ever match Dr. Jennings.''
</P>
<P>
   Bo Emerson writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
