<DOCNO> NYT19990416.0337 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-16 20:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2019 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPOLETO-MAMBA1STTAKE1     04-16 0844
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPOLETO-MAMBA1STTAKE18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Updated 1939 play of African-American women, from `Porgy and
Bess' team, gets its Charleston premiere
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, April 18.
 &HT;    By Wendell Brock
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Last year, an experimental downtown director gave a
gangly, unknown British actress a pair of 6-inch platform shoes and
cast her as the tragic heroine of ``Mamba's Daughters,'' a play
created for legendary Broadway belter Ethel Waters by the
Charleston, S.C., couple who wrote ``Porgy.''
</P>
<P>
   And to nearly everyone's surprise, the updated version of the
1939 play by DuBose Heyward and his wife, Dorothy, was everything
the original Broadway production was not.
</P>
<P>
   It got rave reviews in The New York Times and The New Yorker. It
won two prestigious Obies, the off-Broadway equivalent of the Tony,
for director David Herskovits and star Heather Gillespie. And now,
after a circuitous, 60-year journey, ``Mamba's Daughters'' is
coming to Charleston for the first time, as the centerpiece
theatrical event of Spoleto Festival USA, beginning May 27 at the
historic Dock Street Theatre.
</P>
<P>
   With a stellar lineup of opera, dance, music and theater, this
year's $5.5 million festival looks particularly exciting. A magnet
for music lovers of every stripe, Spoleto is boasting a costly,
original production of Puccini's three-part opera ``Il Trittico''
and the U.S. premiere of Kurt Weill's opera ``Die Burgschaft.''
Nigel Redden, the festival's general director, says that ticket
sales are up 50 percent over 1998. And some offerings _ including
the one-man show ``Ricky Jay and His 52 Assistants,'' directed by
David Mamet, and a 70th birthday tribute to chamber music
impresario Charles Wads-
</P>
<P>
   worth _ have already sold out.
</P>
<P>
   But it's the home-grown ``Mamba's Daughters'' _ a tragic tale of
three generations of African-American women who are nearly engulfed
by racism and their own internal conflicts _ that seems to have all
of Charleston on its ear.
</P>
<P>
   Why? Because DuBose Heyward and Catfish Row are to Charleston
what Margaret Mitchell and Tara are to Atlanta. Just down the
street from the Dock Street, at 76 Church St., is the home where
Heyward's autobiographical 1929 novel, ``Mamba's Daughters,'' on
which the play was based, was set. A plaque outside identifies it
as the DuBose Heyward House. And after a long and storied
theatrical career, including an affiliation with the Dock Street,
the Heywards were buried at nearby St. Philip's Episcopal Church _
he in 1940, she in 1961.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's one of the big immortals in South Carolina, because
`Porgy and Bess' really took Charleston around the world,'' says
Charleston literary historian Harlan Greene, remembering the
historic moment in 1970 when a ``60 Minutes'' crew turned up to
tape the local premiere of ``Porgy and Bess,'' the Gershwin opera
based on the play. ``He's up there with the gods.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Mamba's Daughters'' _ which pivots on the central
character, Hagar; her mother, Mamba; and her daughter, Lissa _
Herskovits has found a play that illumines the human condition, a
story that in some ways seems more alive today than when it was
written.
</P>
<P>
   ``The truth is that DuBose Heyward was not Eugene O'Neill,''
says Herskovits, artistic director of New York's Target Margin
Theater, which staged ``Mamba's'' revival last year as part of an
ongoing mission to present lost masterpieces. ``But I think it's
safe to say that his and his wife's work and its impact extend far
beyond `Porgy and Bess.' I hope we can bring what is interesting
and rich about that work back to the people. I think the people
need to know it.''
</P>
<P>
   That Heyward was a white man writing about a black man's culture
has been the subject of some debate. Yet it is his particular sort
of empathy that has endeared him to certain members of the black
intelligentsia _ from the poet Langston Hughes to Waters to
Gillespie, who plays Hagar.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, many people are eager to dismiss the contributions of a
person if he is writing about materials that are not readily of his
culture,'' says Gillespie, a fine-boned 32-year-old who speaks in a
lovely British accent that dances with the singsong rhythms of her
Jamaican ancestry. ``But I think you lose the point in taking up
these arguments. We love to pontificate on the question of race,
and really it's not a question of racism. It's a play about love,
or the scarcity of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Waters was already an established blues singer when she met the
Heywards at a ``Porgy'' cast party in 1935. As legend has it,
during a chance encounter she told Dorothy Heyward that she had
been gripped by the novel, a sort of upstairs-downstairs account of
a progressive, well-to-do white family and their servants. Right
then and there, the playwright declared to turn the novel into a
dramatic vehicle for Waters, focusing on Hagar.
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, 1939 would be a watershed moment for blacks in
the entertainment industry.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
