NYT-04-16-99 2036EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990416.0338 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-16 20:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2020 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPOLETO-MAMBA2NDTAKE1     04-16 0943
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPOLETO-MAMBA2NDTAKE18-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK: the entertainment industry.
</P>
<P>
   Hattie McDaniel became the first African-American to win an
Oscar, for ``Gone With the Wind.'' Marian Anderson was refused
entry to Washington's Constitution Hall by the Daughters of the
American Revolution, an event that began the slow thaw of
segregation. And though ``Mamba's Daughters'' failed to achieve
mainstream success, it became legendary in black circles _ not only
as Waters' first dramatic part, but as one of the first Broadway
productions to afford numerous major parts to a mostly black cast.
Waters said that Hagar represented ``all Negro women lost and
lonely in the white man's antagonistic world.''
</P>
<P>
   Assuming Waters' mantle was a source of both terror and joy for
Gillespie, who arrived in New York only four years ago and is much
better versed in the ways of London than the Lowcountry. But her
rewards came quick and fast.
</P>
<P>
   ``This man came up, and he had tears in his eyes,'' says
Gillespie, ``and I remember towering above him. And he said, `Ethel
Waters was my friend, and I know she was here tonight.' ''
</P>
<P>
   At 5-foot-8, Gillespie bears a much stronger resemblance to
supermodel Naomi Campbell than she does the ample-bodied Waters,
who took on the role at 38 and was known in her twilight years for
her animated rendering of ``His Eye Is on the Sparrow'' on the
broadcasts of televangelist Billy Graham. After Herskovits and his
costume designer dressed Gillespie in the thick-soled platform
shoes that became emblematic of her outsize performance, Times
critic Peter Marks wrote that she was ``in every sense the play's
walking monument.''
</P>
<P>
   The role was as demanding physically as it was emotionally,
Gillespie says. After opening night, ``I crawled into my bed
convinced I would die and not be able to do the play the next day.
I had given my blood and my bone. And for the first time in my
professional career, I was at the point where I wondered if I had
given too much.
</P>
<P>
   ``A girlfriend rang me up in the morning, and I couldn't hear a
word she was saying. She was screaming down the phone: `Times!
Times! Times! Review!' And then she said little excerpts of it over
the phone, and I said, `Could you just' _ this is so British _
`could you just hold the phone for a moment?' And I put down the
phone and I bawled my eyes out. I just cried, raged, because it was
the most painful thing I ever had to give.''
</P>
<P>
   When Redden saw the play, he was so blown away that he decided
to stage it at Spoleto.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whereas Ethel Waters is larger than life, in some ways Heather
Gillespie seems longer than life,'' says Redden. ``She's a tall
woman, and she seems to be walking on a tightrope throughout the
performance. She seems more in touch with life's dilemmas than any
other actress I can imagine doing that role.''
</P>
<P>
   Adds Herskovits: ``I think Heather is a genius. I really did
have the feeling of having discovered this person before anybody
else did. She was pretty much fresh off the boat from England, and
sure enough, she went out and won an Obie for the part.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Mamba's,'' which runs the gamut musically from authentic
Gullah spirituals to modern jazz added by Herskovits, Gillespie
sings the Jerome Kern ballad ``Lonesome Walls'' in a voice that is
more honey than husk. As Hagar, she is exiled to a sea island
plantation for committing a petty crime. Mamba, her mother, is left
to raise Hagar's daughter, Lissa. Alternating between innocence and
rage, Hagar is the emotional core of the drama.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to slow right down for Hagar, because I'm pretty
mercurial,'' says Gillespie, digging into spicy chicken, collards
and sweet potatoes at Jezebel, a Southern restaurant in the heart
of New York's theater district. ``I sliver all about the place, and
I operate on 10 planes of existence at the same time, and I live in
a multiple reality.'' Indeed, in a two-hour conversation, she
regales a listener with stories from enough past lives to do
Shirley MacLaine proud, and says it is that accumulated experience
that has enabled her to evoke parts as disparate as Josephine Baker
and the nurse in Shakespeare's ``Romeo and Juliet.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Gillespie admits to being absolutely mortified at the
thought of following in Waters' footsteps. ``I wanted to be a jazz
singer, and I sang jazz to get my Equity card (in London). But my
confidence in my singing is more in my interpretation than having
this amazing voice that can go up and down the scale and 'round the
house and through the back door and lie down in your bed,'' she
says, in one of her endlessly cascading, endlessly philosophical,
spoken riffs. ``I tell a story and that is my gift.''
</P>
<P>
   Herskovits says he'd like to see the play go full circle _ back
to Broadway, where it started 60 years ago. ``That's the funny
thing. We are a little experimental theater in downtown New York,
and we have brought back this play, which is a completely
mainstream drama with music.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly, I'd love to see it go to other places. I'd love to
see it go to Atlanta. I'd love to see it done everywhere,
especially in the South.''
</P>
<P>
   With 16 performances spread out over Spoleto's 18-day run,
``Mamba's Daughters'' is likely to be welcomed home to Charleston
like an old family member _ and in the end, the catharsis may
outjump the catfish.
</P>
<P>
   PREVIEW
</P>
<P>
   Spoleto Festival USA
</P>
<P>
   May 28-June 13 in Charleston, S.C. Tickets: 843-723-0402.
Brochures: 843-722-2764.
</P>
<P>
   Web site: http://www.spoletousa.org.
</P>
<P>
   Wendell Brock writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
