u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-CHILD-LABOR-2NDTAK     04-16 0286
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CHILD-LABOR-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
BRENTWOOD, N.Y.: like wildfire.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Free the Children hopes to raise enough money over the next two
years to build 100 schools overseas, one-room buildings costing
$2,000 each. The group has spent $200,000 to build and staff a more
ambitious school and rehabilitation center in India, where more
than 100 former child laborers each year learn a trade.
</P>
<P>
   As the chairman of Free the Children, Craig has visited Asia,
Africa and Latin America and has met with Nelson Mandela, Mother
Teresa, the Dalai Lama and the Pope. When he shows schoolchildren
slides from those trips, many are shocked to discover that child
labor exists, and many come away vowing to fight it.
</P>
<P>
   In the Brentwood library, Craig showed slides of Philippine
children scavenging through garbage piles to find things to sell,
and an 8-year-old girl in India whose job was dismantling a pile of
used syringes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked her, isn't she worried about getting AIDS from the
needles?'' Craig told the students. ``She gave me a blank stare.
She didn't even know what AIDS is.''
</P>
<P>
   When the slide show was over, one student, Malcolm Moore, stood
up and challenged Craig. ``How come you don't get involved in
fighting racism?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   After hesitating a few seconds, Craig responded that there are
many issues out there, and that he has chosen to focus on child
labor. He told Malcolm that if racism was his issue, then he should
stand up against it.
</P>
<P>
   Then, addressing the class, Craig said, ``If racism is important
to you, please stand up with Malcolm.'' Almost all the students
stood up.
</P>
<P>
   ``All you have to do,'' Craig continued, ``is have the courage
to ask people to stand with you.''
</P>
</TEXT>
