<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-16 20:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2023 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NUKE-LABS-NYT &LR;      04-16 0481
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NUKE-LABS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. LETS 3 LABS RESTART SECRET COMPUTER NETWORKS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By JAMES RISEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Energy Secretary Bill Richardson has authorized the
resumption of work on computer networks containing the nation's
most sensitive nuclear secrets, two weeks after he ordered them
shut down over concerns about lax security at weapons laboratories.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson gave the green light to restart the classified
computer networks at the three major nuclear-weapons laboratories
on Thursday night, after he was convinced that security and
counterintelligence programs at the laboratories had been
strengthened, he said in an interview Friday.
</P>
<P>
   He said the three labs, Los Alamos, Sandia and
Lawrence-Livermore, are carrying out new programs to improve
security training for employees, have developed new
electronic-security measures and are beginning to pay more
attention to counterintelligence than they have in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Systems that had been shut down are now undergoing a phased
resumption of operations, and will be fully operational again
within the next few days, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson's order shutting down the classified computer
networks at the labs was one of the most striking actions taken in
response to the furor over allegations that China had stolen
nuclear secrets from the labs. The administration has been under
fire for not acting more aggressively to tighten security.
</P>
<P>
   One of the longstanding security concerns about the laboratories
has been the possibility of transferring nuclear secrets from
classified computer networks into unclassified computers in the
labs. While the classified computer network is not linked to the
Internet, those unclassified computer networks can be reached from
outside through e-mail links.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the new security measures focused on electronic
security. By May 1, the labs are planning to install new systems
that will be able to scan the unclassified computer networks and
outgoing e-mail messages continuously to see if they contain
classified material, according to Energy Department officials.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of scientists and other researchers at the three labs
were affected by the computer shutdown; virtually no research work
related to nuclear weapons could be conducted. All the scientists
who have access to the classified network were ordered to attend
security training sessions while the systems were overhauled.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Bureau of Investigation is still analyzing
notebooks, computer files and other documents seized in the house
of Wen Ho Lee, a computer scientist who was fired from his job at
Los Alamos in March in connection with the investigation of
possible Chinese espionage. Lee has not been charged in the case,
and officials said there has not been any conclusion yet on the
significance of the files seized. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-16-99 2039EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
