s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INVEST-INSIGHT-Q&AMP;A-$A     04-16 0847
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-INSIGHT-Q&AMP;A-$ADV18-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACROSS ASIA, SIGNS OF SPRING  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 18) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Economics is not accounting, but the sense seems to be spreading
that Asia may be the FIFO region of the developing world: First in,
first out of recession.
</P>
<P>
   It has been nearly two years since bad times swept first through
Thailand and then the rest of East Asia. But now there are some
signs of life.
</P>
<P>
   Growth estimates in countries like South Korea, Malaysia and
India are being raised. Risk premiums on corporate and sovereign _
or government _ debt are shrinking. And equity markets are starting
to recover.
</P>
<P>
   In the last two quarters, Morgan Stanley's EMF Asia index, which
covers nine markets, has risen 48 percent. But it still has much
ground to make up, as do all emerging markets.
</P>
<P>
   Robert J. Pelosky Jr., global emerging markets strategist at
Morgan Stanley Dean Witter, took some time last week to discuss
signs of spring in Asia, as well as other exotic precincts of the
world. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. (italics)Some specialists in the emerging markets look at the
recovery in certain stock markets and see a dead-cat bounce. Is
that what you see?(end italics) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Our feeling is that emerging markets in general are turning
and that we are at the beginning of a new cycle for these markets _
one that has three stages. The value stage, which is where we are
today and have been for some time, is first.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is a growth phase, in terms of improved economic
activity and corporate profitability. The third stage is momentum,
which takes place as perceptions of risk decline, multiples improve
and a broader spectrum of investors return to the investment class.
</P>
<P>
   Asia had its dead-cat bounce a year ago, in the first quarter of
1998, when markets had a powerful rally and then petered out. The
big question we have about Asia now is if the region can stage a
broad-based recovery without a recovering Japan. We are
increasingly of the opinion that Japan is recovering. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. (italics)Aren't economic conditions improving in some
countries without a vibrant Japan?(end italics) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. It does seem that some parts of the region have started to
recover. We recently have raised our 1999 growth forecasts for
South Korea, Malaysia and India. And in terms of financial market
performance, South Korea, Taiwan and India have been doing well. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. (italics)What is the risk if Japan doesn't come back as
strongly as you hope?(end italics) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. In the late 1980s, Asia was a leveraged play on
developed-country growth because these countries were basically
export platforms to Europe and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, there has been an increase in inter-Asian trade,
which is where Japan comes in. If a Japanese recovery is generated
by an aggressive monetary policy, then the risk is the yen will
weaken. The question then will be if financial markets look through
the negative implications of a weak yen to the positives of a
Japanese economic recovery, one that would lead to greater demand
for Asian exports. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. (italics)A year ago, many were worried that China would do
further damage to the overall economic picture by devaluing the
yuan. At this point, how much harm would it do?(end italics) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. The possibility of a devaluation has already been discounted
by financial markets. But we feel the case for a significant
Chinese devaluation is just not that strong.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese exports are more demand-dependent than price-dependent.
Last year, the Chinese didn't lose a lot of market share even
though the currencies of their competitors in Asia fell sharply. If
the United States is going to continue to have growth of around 4
percent, if Europe is bottoming and if emerging markets are
bottoming, then demand for Chinese exports will pick up. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. (italics)It would seem that Latin America, which felt the
impact of the world financial crisis well after Asia, would take
longer to recover. Is that how it will play out?(end italics) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. We are starting to make the case that Latin America will
recover more quickly than people think because the shock there was
a secondary shock and because a lot of restructuring in that part
of the world has been going on since 1994, when the region was also
gripped with a financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that the American economy remains vibrant is a big
positive for Mexico. And the Brazilian devaluation, when it came,
was not a huge surprise. If interest rates in Brazil continue to
decline, then the region can recover more quickly than people
think. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. (italics)You mentioned the cycle that emerging markets are
entering. How long will it take?(end italics) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I would prefer to see a steady recovery rather than a big
spike upwards because volatility in these markets has been what has
kept most investors away. I think this is a one-to-three-year kind
of cycle. I think the growth stage will play out in 2000 and 2001,
with the momentum stage following after that.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
