<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-GORE-ENVIRON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON DEFENDS GORE TO ENVIRONMENTAL GROUPS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton sent environmental groups a
letter Friday that aggressively defends Vice President Al Gore's
record on their issues _ a highly unusual move that underscores the
president's commitment to boosting Gore's presidential prospects.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was responding to a letter to Gore earlier this week
from several environmental groups who accused the president and
vice president of breaking their pledge to reduce pollutants that
cause global warming. White House aides said they could not recall
a similar instance where Clinton felt so moved to publicly aid
Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one has done more over the past decade to mobilize action
against climate change than Vice President Gore,'' Clinton wrote in
the three-page letter. ``And no one can more effectively lead this
effort in the decade ahead. We must not allow our frustration over
the real obstacles we face to distract us from our common goals.''
</P>
<P>
   He continued, ``We must pursue sound strategies, not proposals
that risk eroding the support so vital to our success.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's effort demonstrates the degree to which he is
determined to help his vice president by trying to smooth relations
with environmental groups on what could be an important issue in
the presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The timing of Clinton's letter is particularly helpful; Thursday
will be Earth Day, a time when the administration will draw
significant publicity on its environmental record.
</P>
<P>
   The environmental groups' letter to Gore, who has long cast
himself as an environmental champion, was surprisingly combative.
``We are writing,'' it complained, ``to voice deep disappointment
with the lack of an administration proposal to require significant
reductions in global warming pollution. We are particularly
frustrated that the administration has not sought meaningful
emission reductions from either power plants or passenger
vehicles.''
</P>
<P>
   In his reply, Clinton recited the administration's environmental
accomplishments in the face of ``the most anti-environmental
Congress ever.'' Throughout the letter, he lauded Gore's ``vision
and leadership.'' He said Gore had ``led the charge'' on a number
of fronts. He also wrote, ``The vice president and I have sought at
every opportunity to highlight the mounting scientific evidence
that global warming is a threat to this and future generations.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kyoto treaty intended to reduce global emissions was
negotiated in Japan in 1997 and signed by the administration last
year. But it was not presented to the Senate for ratification
because it faced strong opposition from industry groups.
</P>
<P>
   Carl Pope, executive director of the Sierra Club, one of nine
groups that signed the original letter, said of the response, ``It
is a valid defense of what the administration has done to date. The
letter is fundamentally silent on the question of when the
administration will take the next step: insisting that the auto
industry and the public utilities start cleaning up their
greenhouse emissions.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Hansen, executive director of the Izaak Walton League of
America, another person who signed the letter, said, ``The
president makes a good point _ that we need to try to work
together.'' Even so, he said, it still does not take away from the
deficiencies in the administration's record.
</P>
<P>
   Another who signed the letter, National Environmental Trust
president Philip Clapp, said Clinton ``feels it necessary to cast
his and the vice president's inaction in the best political
light.'' He added: ``This is calculated to defend the vice
president from potential criticism between now and the election.''
</P>
<P>
   Hansen said he was disturbed that a colleague had given the
letter to the press. ``I'm extremely unhappy about that,'' he said.
``We thought this was an exchange of views _ not a political
stone-throwing contest.'' But Clapp insisted that ``this letter was
quite specifically a public letter.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
