<HEADLINE>
`THE WAR ON BOYS:' AN IDEOLOGICAL MISSION  
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes are at end of review. Time, channel are for
New York area. Check local listings.) 
(DW) 
 By WALTER GOODMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In a twist on the sexual harassment charges that
provide television with a steady stream of horror stories, the
participants in ``The War on Boys,'' Sunday's edition of ``National
Desk,'' make a case that boys are being maltreated by women. In
feminists' drive for ``gender equity,'' these cheer leaders for
masculinity charge, fundamental differences between boys and girls
are being ignored to the detriment of the boys.
</P>
<P>
   Shepherded by Fred Barnes, they maintain that while girls are
doing relatively well in classrooms, the misunderstood and
neglected boys are being driven to violence and crime, not to
mention suicide. These days, as one critic puts it, ``Masculinity
is politically incorrect.''
</P>
<P>
   Evidence to the contrary by groups like the American Association
of University Women is dismissed as ``advocacy research'' in the
service of an ideological mission. ``The War on Boys,'' which
invites suspicions of an ideological mission of its own, comes down
particularly hard on those who are quick to label restless lads as
suffering from attention deficit disorders and in need of quieting
drugs like Ritalin.
</P>
<P>
   The three-part program, supported by conservative foundations,
goes on in coming weeks to assertions that America's armed services
and college athletics are also being subverted by liberal social
agendas. Although the arguments could benefit from more rigor and
fewer anecdotes, they are presented with passion and can be counted
on to add fuel to battles over family values.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:  &QL; 
`The War on Boys' &QL; 
At 1 p.m. Sunday on PBS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A Whidbey Island Films production. Lionel Chetwynd, Conrad Denke
and Norman S. Powell, producers.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-16-99 2048EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
