<DOCNO> NYT19990416.0347 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-16 20:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2029 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-MACEDONIA-950&AMP;     04-16 1134
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MACEDONIA-950&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNWELCOME REFUGEES FLOOD MACEDONIA AFTER FLEEING SERBS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By DAVID ROHDE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRAZDA, Macedonia _ Ten days ago, thousands had suddenly
disappeared. After waiting days at a border crossing near here to
enter Macedonia from Kosovo, ethnic Albanians had been rousted from
their hillside camps, from their cars and their tractors and
ordered by Serbian forces back into the war zone they were trying
to flee.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, as the flow of ethnic Albanians into Macedonia surged,
they appeared again telling tales of being beaten, taking shelter
with strangers and waiting patiently for the right moment to
attempt again to flee Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the Albanians arriving here _ some 12,000 in 24 hours _
had been ordered away from the border last week and herded back
into Kosovo after President Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia had
announced a unilateral ``cease-fire.'' Many had been waiting at
border crossing here for days and then had vanished mysteriously
one night last week.
</P>
<P>
   Arriving at the refugee camp here Friday, exhausted refugees
told of expulsions that began three weeks ago in the three largest
towns in southeastern Kosovo and their frantic efforts to make it
to safety.
</P>
<P>
   Friday morning, on the final leg of their odyssey, fights broke
out among hundreds of people clamoring to board a train from the
town of Urosevac in Kosovo to the Macedonia border, refugees said.
</P>
<P>
   A haggard Qazim Hoti, 50, a physical education teacher who
arrived here Friday with his exhausted wife, two daughters and son,
said their flight from Kosovo began three weeks ago, after Serbian
paramilitary forces expelled them from their home in Pristina.
Driving to the Macedonian border in search of safety, they found a
mob of refugees already there.
</P>
<P>
   After spending six days and five nights camping in their Opel
sedan waiting to cross the border, Hoti and his family were among
the thousands ordered back into Kosovo after Milosevic declared the
cease-fire on April 6. Hoti said he was beaten by a Serbian
policeman in the chaos as the Albanians tried to reverse their cars
on the crowded roadway.
</P>
<P>
   ``They beat me and then let me get in the car,'' he said. ``Some
of the people from my neighborhood were there. I don't know where
they are.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Hoti said he followed orders to drive north but was stopped
at a Serbian checkpoint and told to turn east, away from Pristina,
his hometown. He then headed toward the small town of Shterpce near
the Macedonian border. Deciding it would be safest to follow local
villagers into the hills, he and his family abandoned their car and
hiked to the small village of Gocke.
</P>
<P>
   There, a stranger took the family into his home, he said.
Relative quiet ensued for the rest of the week as they waited for
the border with Macedonia to reopen. But early last week, gunfire
erupted in the village where they were hiding. In a series of
attacks described by other refugees, Serbian forces had begun
systematically expelling Albanians from the area.
</P>
<P>
   When word came that the border had reopened, Hoti and his family
decided to risk the journey. They walked first to Urosevac on
Thursday. Friday, they arrived at the railway station at 7:30 A.M.
hoping to take the daily train to the border, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But they found several thousand others already waiting to board.
As Serbian policemen stood by, chaos erupted when the train
arrived, with frantic people climbing into the train through its
windows and pulling each others from its doors.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were old women and kids being crushed,'' Hoti said.
``The people were not thinking of anything else, just getting on
that train.''
</P>
<P>
   Packed in so tightly that he was forced to stand on one foot for
the all of the 30-minute ride, he watched a landscape of
devastation roll by him where nearly every ethnic Albanian village
was deserted and partly burned. In one town, several hundred
Albanians waiting to get on the train were left behind because
there was no more room.
</P>
<P>
   Hoti said he did not know what became of the thousands of others
who were turned back at the border with his family 10 days ago. But
Miran Latifi, a 38-year-old lawyer who arrived Thursday from a
village near Urosevac with his wife and two sons, said several
thousand people from Pristina who were turned back at the border
were in villages in southeastern Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are hiding there and running out of food,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The sudden surge in arriving refugees suggests that a second
wave is heading for Macedonia, whose own fragile ethnic balance is
being sorely tested by the Balkan crisis. Another large influx is
likely to put even more pressure on a society where tensions are
simmering between ethnic Macedonians, who make up two-thirds of the
population, and the country's ethnic Albanian minority.
</P>
<P>
   Aid workers fear that the Macedonian government could again
resort to a de facto closing of the border or forced expulsions as
it did earlier to limit the number of Albanians entering.
</P>
<P>
   Macedonians, for their part, fear that Western countries will
fail to airlift refugees to third countries as promised and that
they will soon find themselves a minority in their own country.
</P>
<P>
   Tensions between refugees and Macedonian police continued to
rise here Friday. Refugees who said they were expelled from their
village in Kosovo four days ago and forced by Serbian policemen to
try to enter Macedonia from an unofficial border crossing bitterly
complained about the Macedonians.
</P>
<P>
   Hajredin Hajredini said 3,000 refugees spent three days this
week in a no-man's land on the border because the Macedonian police
refused to allow them to enter. ``They shouted at us and ordered us
to leave and go back to Serbia,'' he said. ``But we wouldn't
move.''
</P>
<P>
   After pressure from the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees, the
group was finally allowed to cross Thursday night.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Inside the refugee camps here, tensions between refugees and the
Macedonian police, who have been accused of beatings and callous
treatment of ethnic Albanians, have risen. NATO troops who built
several of the camps are scheduled to withdraw all but a skeleton
staff this weekend and many refugees fear that without a NATO
presence, the situation will worsen.
</P>
<P>
   Macedonian officials have defended the police conduct and say
that the complaints from refugees are exaggerated.
</P>
<P>
   But as the number of refugees in the crowded camps rises _ many
new arrivals are sleeping on the ground because of a shortage of
tents _ and the NATO presence in the camp recedes, both sides are
increasingly on edge.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will not accept it,'' said Sali Aliu, a 28-year-old
refugee. ``We are not safe with them here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-16-99 2050EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990416.0348 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-16 20:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
