<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-GRETSKY-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAYNE GRETSKY, HOCKEY'S ARTIST ON THE ICE, ANNOUNCES RETIREMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo and graphic are being sent to NYT photo and graphic
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In a sport often stereotyped for brute force and
violent intimidation, Wayne Gretzky was a hockey artist who used
his stick as a paint brush and his skates as dance slippers. With
grace and creativity, he became the National Hockey League's career
leader in points and goals, a nine-time most valuable player who
not only dominated his sport competitively but helped spread its
popularity past the borders of his native Canada to new markets in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   After 21 years as a professional _ the last 20 in the NHL and
the last three as a New York Ranger _ Gretzky announced his
retirement Friday afternoon in a news conference at Madison Square
Garden. His final game will be on Sunday afternoon at the Garden
against the Pittsburgh Penguins.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm done,'' Gretzky said, speaking from a dais, his family
alongside him, surrounded by photographs of himself in various
uniforms of several teams. ``It's just time. Of course I'm sad.
I've played hockey for 35 years, since I was three years old. I'm
going to miss it.''
</P>
<P>
   Gretzky was known as The Great One, and it was not just a pun on
his name. In his sport, he, Gordie Howe and Bobby Orr are generally
regarded as the very best players in its history.
</P>
<P>
   In comparison to other team sports, Gretzky will be remembered
at the level of Babe Ruth and Ty Cobb in baseball or Michael Jordan
and Wilt Chamberlain in basketball. He won 10 scoring titles, as
did Jordan, and his nine MVP awards are four more than Jordan won
in the National Basketball Association.
</P>
<P>
   In terms of marketing, Gretzky is often credited with stirring
interest in his cold-weather sport so that it was able to expand to
southern cities such as Tampa, Miami, Dallas and San Jose. When he
was dealt from Edmonton to Los Angeles in 1988 in a deal that
involved many players and much money, the move left Gretzky in
tears and was treated as a tragic day in Canadian history. But it
helped spur interest in professional hockey in Southern California,
and Gretzky's presence there at that time is widely thought to have
contributed to creation of the Disney-backed expansion franchise
called The Mighty Ducks of Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   He played one season as a 17-year-old in the World Hockey
Association, and his presence and potential with the Edmonton
Oilers helped spur a merger in 1979, officially called an
expansion, that created one major-league circuit.
</P>
<P>
   Slightly shorter and much more slender than the average player,
Gretzky nevertheless holds 61 NHL scoring records, and appeared in
18 All-Star Games. He won four Lady Byng trophies for
sportsmanship, the most recent in 1994. In NHL regular-season games
alone, he has scored 894 goals; Howe is second with 801. In
regular-season assists, Gretzky leads with 1,962; Paul Coffey is
second with 1,102. In total points in regular season play, Gretzky
leads with 2,856; Howe is second with 1,850.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, in both the National Hockey League and World Hockey
Association, Gretzky has scored 1,072 goals, just one more than
Howe scored in both leagues during both regular season and playoff
games. No player has scored more. Howe was Gretzky's idol when
Gretzky grew up in Brantford, Ontario. Soon, Gretzky is expected to
join Howe in the Hockey Hall of Fame. Gretzky recalled Friday how
he used to visit the Hall as a boy because a friendly worker would
let him in. He said he would stand around in awe, looking at the
pictures and the mementos on display.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess it's safe to say I'm going to probably get in there,''
Gretzky said. ``Now that I'm retired, I can say that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No person in sports has done as much for their sport as you
have been able to do for ours,'' NHL Commissioner Gary Bettman said
at the news conference.
</P>
<P>
   In a tribute that acknowledged Gretzky's status as a national
hero in Canada, Prime Minister Jean Chretien said in a statement:
``This is truly a bittersweet moment. One of the greatest players
ever to play our national game has decided to hang up his skates
... . But we can take heart from the endless, magical memories he
has given us.''
</P>
<P>
   Now 38 years old, Gretzky's announcement ended a dramatic week
of public and private speculation involving Gretkzy, his family,
his friends and his fans. He declined a contract offer to play one
more season for $5 million. His skills have been reduced by a
nagging injury to a neck disk and by age. In his best season for
goals, 1981-82 Gretzky scored an astounding 92 _ by contrast, this
year's leader has 47 _ but this season he has only 9. In his best
season for assists, Gretzky had 163, but this season has only 52.
In his best years, as an Edmonton Oiler, Gretzky dominated the
sport and led his team to four Stanley Cup championships in nine
seasons. He has had less success with the Los Angeles Kings, the
St. Louis Blues and the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   Although Gretzky insisted for most of this season that this
would not be his last, he revealed Friday that he began to
contemplate retirement around Christmas, when he ``started to feel
the fatigue, mentally and physically, that I've never felt
before.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the season, particularly in the second half, he was
hit harder by opposing checkers than had been the case in the past.
In his youth, checking Gretzky was like stopping a puff a smoke,
and he would materialize in open spaces like a mist rising from the
ice. This season, he was noticeably less elusive, and he rejected
pleas from his wife, agent, coach and general manager to continue.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my heart, I know I've made the right decision,'' Gretzky
said. ``This is the right time. I'm at peace of mind.''
</P>
<P>
   When people reminisce about the Gretzky era, as they surely will
for many decades, they will recall a playing style that was unlike
any other, even those of the other great ones. Howe, who began his
career shortly after World War II, was hockey's Paul Bunyan, a
mythic man, large for his era, tough for any age, a force through
several decades. Some thought he played for too long, retiring at
age 52 in 1980. Orr was a comet from the late 1960s and early
1970s, who played hockey the way Jimi Hendrix played guitar, with
elan that could not be copied.
</P>
<P>
   Gretzky was different and appropriate for his era. As his league
began importing increasing numbers of players from Europe, he
played what is now recognized as a European style. Although not
particularly speedy, Gretzky was a nimble skater who could stop,
collect a moving puck on his stick blade, look around and pass it
to an open teammate, seemingly in one motion, the components of the
flowing act not discernible as they are with most players. At other
times, Gretzky would carry the puck, stop suddenly and delay the
play a half-beat while letting others thunder by. Then he would
pass or shoot through openings, often against the grain, that only
he seemed to see.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
