<SLUG> BC-IRS-LONG-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATOR DERAILS AGENCY'S THREAT TO FIRE IRS WHISTLE-BLOWER 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DAVID IVANOVICH &HT;    c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Jennifer Long, the Internal Revenue Service agent
from Houston who blew the whistle on the agency during explosive
Senate hearings a year and a half ago, is fighting for her job.
</P>
<P>
   On April 15 _ tax filing day _ managers in the IRS's Houston
office handed the 15-year veteran a letter threatening to fire her
unless her job performance improved.
</P>
<P>
   In response, Sen. William Roth, R-Del., who chaired the Senate
hearings, accused the Houston office of retaliating against Long
for testifying about alleged abuses at the IRS.
</P>
<P>
   ``The actions of the IRS management in the Houston office are
outrageous,'' Roth said. ``They are a direct affront to Congress
and to the new IRS commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   ``How many taxpayers' calls and questions in Houston went
unanswered (Thursday) _ tax filing day _ because the IRS was busy
retaliating against its own?''
</P>
<P>
   The uproar prompted IRS Commissioner Charles Rossotti to
dispatch the No. 2 man at the agency _ Deputy Commissioner Bob
Wenzel _ to Houston to review the case. He also called on the
Treasury Department's inspector general for tax administration to
investigate, while Roth's office promised to focus on Houston in
future hearings.
</P>
<P>
   All of this prompted Long's managers to call her back in late
Friday to rescind the termination threat, Long said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just been the wildest thing you've ever seen,'' Long said
in a telephone interview. ``It was really cute _ April 15. That was
real funny. I couldn't believe it.''
</P>
<P>
   Long said she believes the quick withdrawal of the termination
threat means ``they are going to continue to do the same things to
me. ... I know this trick very well.''
</P>
<P>
   Rossotti, in a written statement Friday, said: ``I am extremely
disturbed that we may have taken an action that could be
retaliatory. As I have said before, I will not tolerate retaliation
against employees who came forward to testify before the Senate
Finance Committee or who come forward to report any allegations of
wrongdoing.''
</P>
<P>
   Houston IRS officials declined to comment beyond Rossotti's
statement.
</P>
<P>
   The action against Long may _ in one, fell swoop _ eradicate the
success the IRS has had rebuilding its image with the public since
the highly publicized Senate hearings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like the new-and-improved IRS that we heard so much
about this week is up to its old tricks again,'' said Rep. Bill
Archer, R-Texas, chairman of the House Ways and Means Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am appalled that the IRS would take such action against
someone who has served the public as Ms. Long has,'' said the
congressman from Houston.
</P>
<P>
   William Nixon, Roth's executive assistant and co-author of the
book ``The Power to Destroy: How the IRS Became America's Most
Powerful Agency; How Congress is Taking Control and What You Do to
Protect Yourself Under the Law,'' said a movie producer in
Hollywood would never consider a script like this one.
``Retaliating against a Senate witness on tax day when chaos reigns
around you just boggles the mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Long became something of a local folk hero in September 1997
when she publicly accused the IRS of abusing taxpayers. Long's
behavior was in sharp contrast to many of her colleagues, who
agreed to testify only if their identities were concealed.
</P>
<P>
   Long accused the Houston IRS office of singling out taxpayers
too poor to afford air conditioning and avoiding managers' friends
when selecting returns to audit. She also said she knew of five
taxpayers who had committed suicide, in part, because of pressure
imposed by the IRS.
</P>
<P>
   The testimony of Long, her colleagues and the agency's alleged
victims helped ensure passage of sweeping new legislation designed
to rein in the agency.
</P>
<P>
   A subsequent investigation by the Treasury inspector general's
office discounted many of Long's more spectacular allegations. But
the probe did raise concerns that supervisors could harass their
employees and then retaliate against any who protested.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Long was given a 13-page memo by group manager
Karie Gulley detailing her ``unacceptable'' performance and
threatening possible removal within 68 days if she did not improve.
</P>
<P>
   The memo _ a copy of which was obtained by the Chronicle _
criticized Long for failing to plan effectively, set priorities,
manage her work load, conduct audits accurately and fill out forms
completely.
</P>
<P>
   Long was taken to task for deciding to drive to a taxpayer's
location to conduct an audit, which required driving three to four
hours a day, which the manager described as an inefficient use of
her time.
</P>
<P>
   In one case, Long failed to fully investigate the assets a
taxpayer had in 11 different bank accounts.
</P>
<P>
   ``You looked at four of them and did not know what he was doing
at the other seven,'' the memo said. Long also was criticized for
working on more recent cases when an older case was still
outstanding.
</P>
<P>
   Gulley offered to help Long improve her job performance with
bi-weekly counseling sessions, planned to discuss each case Long
was working on and indicated she might make unscheduled visits when
Long was conducting on-site audits.
</P>
<P>
   Long described the problems as ``just nit-picky things'' and
violations of procedures that no one is used to because they have
been newly implemented.
</P>
<P>
   Roth noted that prior to testifying before the Senate hearings,
Long had received a grade of ``fully successful'' on her employee
evaluations.
</P>
<P>
   Nixon said he called half a dozen IRS employees in Houston about
Long after receiving word about the memo. Long's colleagues, he
said, insisted she demonstrated a strong work ethic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there are some in Houston who want to make her out to
be a difficult employee,'' Nixon said. ``But ... did she become
difficult the day after she testified before Congress?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
