<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-DRAFT-BENGALS17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bengals hope to gain a quarterback
 &HT;    By Chick Ludwig
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ After studying Oregon quarterback Akili Smith at a
workout before the East-West Shrine Game in Palo Alto, Calif.,
Bengals President Mike Brown made a telephone call before catching
a red-eye flight from San Francisco to Orlando, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `You're right. He is borderline special,''' recalled
Jim Lippincott, the team's director of pro/college personnel.
</P>
<P>
   Brown and offensive coordinator Ken Anderson then climbed aboard
that Florida-bound jet. Landing at 8 a.m., they went to watch
Central Florida quarterback Daunte Culpepper practice.
</P>
<P>
   That story, more than any, illustrates Brown's urgency to find a
player who can help turn the Bengals' franchise around.
</P>
<P>
   Unless he gets blown away by a trade offer, Brown will select a
quarterback with the No. 3 overall pick in the 64th NFL Draft
today.
</P>
<P>
   The Bengals have targeted the top quarterback prospects _ Smith,
Kentucky's Tim Couch and Syracuse's Donovan McNabb _ and aim to get
one.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland and Philadelphia pick first and second, respectively.
Barring any snags, they'll probably select quarterbacks too, and
decide who's left for the Bengals.
</P>
<P>
   Brown wouldn't reveal his order of preference Friday, but he's
excited about the opportunity to get the position resolved for the
Bengals.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a chance, and a good chance,'' Brown said. ``I'm not sure
I can quantify it in terms of percentage. The answer is: Nobody
knows. None of them are sure shots. Nobody ever is, or rarely is.
They all have a good chance at it, though, and that's a hard thing
to pass up.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's obvious when you can hit on a quarterback, you really can
make things work the way you want. You can hit on an offensive
guard. You can hit on a cornerback. You can hit on an offensive
tackle. All those things are helpful. But none are anywhere near as
helpful as if you hit on a quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the hub of the wheel ... like a queen on a chessboard.
These other guys are like rooks or bishops or other pieces that are
not quite as valuable. Some are more valuable than others. That's
just a fact.''
</P>
<P>
   Watching the offseason unfold, Lippincott noticed Brown's
renewed vigor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm starting my eighth year here and I've never seen Mike be
as aggressive at the all-star games as he was,'' Lippincott said.
``He saw Akili, took the red-eye from San Francisco to Orlando and
watched Culpepper practice. He's never done that. So the urgency is
exhibited right there.''
</P>
<P>
   It stems from having the worst record in the NFL since 1991 _
39-89 with no winning seasons since 1990; the fact that incumbent
QB Jeff Blake is entering the final year of his contract; and the
new Paul Brown Stadium will be ready in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Brown feels the dismal decade can be traced to the lack of a
franchise quarterback. The glory days of the late 1980s with Boomer
Esiason spilled into the frustrating 1990s with David Klingler,
Blake and Neil O'Donnell. Now it's someone else's turn.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you look at the NFL these days, the teams that have
productive quarterbacks all win,'' Brown said. ``Of the teams that
do not win, the thing they all have in common is quarterback
situations that are not productive. So everyone is looking to get a
quarterback. That's why teams run a risk in the draft to get one.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bengals also need a cornerback and help on the offensive and
defensive lines. Wide receiver Carl Pickens is threatening to sit
out if he isn't traded, so that position must be addressed. But
quarterback is the top priority.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Joe Montanas and the Kenny Andersons of the world aren't
out there anymore,'' head coach Bruce Coslet said. ``You don't see
'em. I see (John) Elway, Dan Marino, (Drew) Bledsoe, (Troy) Aikman,
Steve Young _ all high, high No. 1 draft choices. And the teams
that don't have those type of guys, they struggle. That's where we
are.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if you don't try; if ou don't take the chance; if you
say, `Oh, it might be David Klingler again,' well, do you want to
go through life just scared to death all the time? We've got to
take the chance. We've got to try.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
