A2034 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-DRAFT-BROWNS17-CO     04-16 0792
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-DRAFT-BROWNS17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    First pick still unknown _ even to Browns
 &HT;    By Sean McClelland
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ University of Oregon quarterback Akili Smith,
perhaps a trifle annoyed by the drama, said Thursday he was ``in
the dark'' about how the expansion Cleveland Browns plan to use the
first pick in today's NFL Draft.
</P>
<P>
   Join the crowd, Akili.
</P>
<P>
   If you believe the Browns, the hierarchy is huddled over
breakfast this morning sifting through last-minute data in hopes of
choosing properly among Smith, Kentucky quarterback Tim Couch and
Texas running back Ricky Williams.
</P>
<P>
   In all, the Browns have 14 selections this weekend as the
orderly reincarnation process continues nearly four years after Art
Modell snuck off to Baltimore with the original franchise. And now,
officially, they are on the clock.
</P>
<P>
   With three players deemed worthy of being chosen, the Browns
spent the past couple of days determining which one would sign a
contract with the least amount of struggle. They are said to be
offering a seven-year deal worth about $52 million, plus a $13
million signing bonus.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a number of teams remain interested in moving up. New
Orleans Saints coach Mike Ditka, for example, has offered the
Browns and the Bengals his entire draft for the No. 1 pick, with
which he would take Williams. Ditka tried a similar gambit last
year and was rebuffed in efforts to land quarterback Ryan Leaf, who
went to San Diego with the second pick.
</P>
<P>
   The poker-faced, bunkered Browns say they are keeping their
options open, but it looks like Ditka once again will go away
frustrated and that Williams will go fourth to the Indianapolis
Colts, who made room in the backfield Thursday by trading Marshall
Faulk to the St. Louis Rams for a second-round choice and a
fifth-rounder.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia drafts second, Cincinnati third. Both teams are
prepared to select quarterbacks.
</P>
<P>
   Based on television polls and radio talk shows, Browns fans
clearly favor Williams over any quarterback. The draft is
quarterback-rich, they argue, so a serviceable one _ Ohio State's
Joe Germaine? _ surely can be found in later rounds. If not,
there's always Warren Moon, currently a free agent.
</P>
<P>
   But the Browns want a franchise QB and, in this draft, only
Couch and Smith seem to match that definition in the mind of head
coach Chris Palmer. A well-respected guru of the position, Palmer
has developed Jacksonville's Mark Brunell and is credited with
helping the New England Patriots correctly decide on Drew Bledsoe
over Rick Mirer.
</P>
<P>
   The power-armed Smith caught Palmer's eye early, but Couch
rallied with last Sunday's workout in front of 11 members of the
front office, including owner Al Lerner. Today will end months of
suspense, speculation and analysis.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't anticipate making a decision on the pick until
Saturday morning,'' Browns spokesman Alex Martins kept saying all
week.
</P>
<P>
   At 24, Smith is older but less experienced than Couch, who is
skipping his senior season after thriving for three years in
Kentucky's wing-and-a-prayer offense. Smith, while undeniably
talented, is coming off his only full season of taking snaps at the
Division I level. ``From what I understand, Tim Couch didn't blow
them away with his workout,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Other areas the Browns hope to address are wide receiver,
defensive line, linebacker and overall team speed. Free agency and
the expansion draft yielded several pieces to the puzzle, including
linebacker Chris Spielman and an offensive line, anchored by former
Browns tackle Orlando Brown, that threatens to be respectable.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have so many needs,'' said Dwight Clark, director of
football operations. ``I would say defensive line and linebacker
would be the top two.''
</P>
<P>
   The old Browns had a rich history of draft-day blundering that
only the occasional first-round bonanza _ amazingly, Ozzie Newsome
and Clay Matthews both arrived in 1978 _ could offset. Who can
forget when coach Bill Belichick, unnerved by the New York Jets'
choice of tight end Kyle Brady, threw his hands in the air, gave up
and chose Ohio State linebacker Craig Powell. No linebackers are on
the Browns' short list of candidates for the No. 1 pick. There is,
therefore, no danger of another Powell, Mike Junkin or Clifford
Charlton, disasters all.
</P>
<P>
   That said, Clark will be looking to rehabilitate his image as a
talent-evaluator over the next two days. With San Francisco, Clark
orchestrated running back Ricky Watters' unpopular exit and
probably won't be forgiven anytime soon in the Bay Area for last
year's ill-fated decision to draft Jim Druckenmiller over Jake
Plummer.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
