</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FREAKNIK17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Freaknik comes to life, but slower than in years past
 &HT;    By Carlos Campos and Lyda Longa
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Freaknik showed signs of life Friday, as men with
video cameras, women with short skirts, and cars with stereos
blasting began filling Peachtree Street shortly after noon.
</P>
<P>
   But even before darkness fell on the first day of the annual
Black College Spring Break, some of its negative side could be
seen.
</P>
<P>
   Near Woodruff Park, a young man pulled down a woman's stretch
pants, and then quickly ran away.
</P>
<P>
   Two local girls who would not give their names said they were
skipping high school classes to stroll around Underground Atlanta
during Freaknik. They said they were 17 and 18 years old. But an
Atlanta police detective said truancy was not a serious problem on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Freaknik appears to remain a draw for college students.
Angie Pearson, a 21-year-old University of Florida student, said
she's heard ``the horror stories, how derogatory it is, the lack of
respect. But you never really know until you try it yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   Pearson and her friends were dressed relatively conservatively,
wearing blue jeans and sweaters as a chilly wind whipped past them.
Pearson's friend, Maneka Smith, 20, said the way women dress can
have an impact on how they are treated.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you carry yourself with a lack of respect, then that's the
way people treat you,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The women, almost in unison, said they came to Atlanta to
``party, get drunk, club and meet men.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Good, clean, wholesome college fun,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Technical school student Jay Scott, 20, of Detroit summed up
what Freaknik is all about for him and his friends in a few words:
``Females. We're just trying to see some females.''
</P>
<P>
   As they walked around Underground Atlanta, Mark McLaughlin, 18,
said ``It's boring. This ain't nothing compared to '97. It was way
live then.''
</P>
<P>
   Will Sims, 18, pointed his hand-held camcorder at some women
across the street, shouting, ``Say something for D-town!''
</P>
<P>
   ``We got a lot of fellas back home anticipating some pictures,''
Scott said.
</P>
<P>
   Downtown streets were thick with Atlanta police SWAT and Red Dog
teams.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta police set up an impromptu command center at Walton and
Peachtree streets and began stopping cruising drivers. Tow trucks
were lined up and waiting. Between 5 and 6 p.m. Friday, 15 cars
were impounded, said Lt. Larry Gilbert, assistant commander of
downtown's Zone 5 precinct.
</P>
<P>
   ``If cars stop, if their radios are too loud, and if anybody's
hanging out of a car, they're getting pulled over, cited and their
cars are being impounded,'' Gilbert said.
</P>
<P>
   One group videotaped a friend being arrested and handcuffed for
having no driver's license.
</P>
<P>
   Near Woodruff Park on Friday afternoon, 42-year-old Ernest
Maiden, of southwest Atlanta, filmed a woman shaking her rear for
his video camera. Maiden said he was gathering footage for a friend
of his who is a college student.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just like being part of the Olympics,'' Maiden said.
``But it seems like there's more policemen out here than people
enjoying the festivities.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked if he felt out of place among younger partygoers,
Maiden said, ``You're never too old to party. They have the Oscars
every year, and they put on fancy dresses and arrive in fancy
cars.''
</P>
<P>
   On Auburn Avenue, meanwhile, dozens of vendors were busy setting
up booths featuring African artifacts, handbags, watches, jewelry,
sunglasses and food.
</P>
<P>
   A festival planned along the historic black avenue is one of
only two events sanctioned by the city of Atlanta this year; a job
fair at the World Congress Center today is the other.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Pollard, 24, drove down to the festival from Columbia, S.C.,
to sell T-shirts and handbags. He sat alone in front of his table
Friday afternoon waiting for the crowds he said would pick up by
nightfall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess we'll just have to wait and see,'' he said. ``Last
year, we did great. Hopefully we'll do better this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the party doesn't truly kick into high gear until
Saturday, some of the traditional hot spots were quiet on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Traffic around Grant and Piedmont parks, as well as Greenbriar,
Lenox and West End malls was normal.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, many downtown office workers left early. Georgia
State University canceled classes after noon, state employees were
allowed to go home at 3 p.m., and the 11th Circuit Court of Appeals
offices were closed at 4 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Police in Gwinnett and Cobb counties said they did not stop an
unusually high number of speeders coming to Atlanta along
Interstate 75 and I-85 as they have done in past years. Officials
at both departments said they generally weren't stopping cars
unless they were going over 80 miles per hour or driving
dangerously.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's anywhere like it has been in the past,''
said Lt. George Hatfield, head of special operations for the Cobb
County Police Department. ``I don't think it's going to be that big
of a deal. Either that, or they're better behaved.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordy Wright, spokesman for the Georgia State Patrol, said, ``At
this time last year, we had at least seen some evidence of a
Freaknik. But this is probably the lightest traffic along the
interstate that I've seen since 1994.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
