A2040 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BELLSOUTH17-COX     04-16 0619
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BELLSOUTH17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BellSouth tries flat-rate plan for wireless service
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ BellSouth has begun bidding to compete with the
national wireless companies, offering flat-rate plans that charge
nothing extra for long-distance or roaming calls.
</P>
<P>
   The plans are an implicit admission that the company has lost
some big-spending customers to the likes of Sprint and AT&AMP;T, which
have similar one-rate plans pitched to travelers who are also heavy
wireless users. But the move is also something of a gamble, because
BellSouth could lose money providing service to travelers whose
phones are connecting to another company's network.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth offers 600 minutes of use for $90 a month and 1,000
minutes for $120. A customer who stayed within those time limits
would know in advance how much the bill will be, and would not pay
per-minute charges for ``roaming'' outside BellSouth's service
area.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth would still have to pay other carriers each time a
customer roamed _ almost certainly paying more than the customer on
a one-rate plan pays for an average minute.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the potential loss on roaming, the company needs to keep
those high-end customers, said Perry Walter, analyst for
Robinson-Humphrey. Although BellSouth can offer wireless
long-distance, it cannot yet offer long-distance to wire line
customers in its nine-state region. The loss of wireless customers
to national companies will threaten the company's ability to be a
complete carrier.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a defensive strategy,'' Walter said. ``They've got to
defend their turf in long-distance.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea of charging one rate for all wireless calls, regardless
of where they are made, got its first push from Sprint and Nextel,
then won the embrace of AT&AMP;T. BellSouth had long shrugged off the
suggestion that it needed a national wireless strategy, arguing
that most customers do not roam and if they do, they stay in the
Southeast.
</P>
<P>
   Less than one-quarter of BellSouth's wireless customers use the
phone outside the region, but they tend to be customers who use a
lot of telecommunications services. BellSouth users who traveled
have often found themselves paying exorbitant fees, and _ for at
least some users _ the one-rate drumbeat was apparently making a
difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our customers may have perceived that we were not as full a
provider as our competition,'' said BellSouth spokeswoman Kathy
Curtin.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth hopes that introduction of the flat-rate plans will
keep customers with the company, and persuade others to use their
phones more when they do travel.
</P>
<P>
   However, to use the plan, a customer needs a dual-band, dual
mode phone. The phone can work on a system that's analog or
digital; it can also work in the 800 megaherz bandwidth or in the
1,900 megaherz range. BellSouth is offering phones made by Nokia
and Ericsson, $99 to $199.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike BellSouth, the national providers can offer customers
phones that link to a network with one type of technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are using a single technology in 285 major markets,'' said
Sprint spokesman Dan Wilensky. ``We think that gives us an
advantage. I'm standing here in Nashville talking to you, and my
phone works the same as in Atlanta.''
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth officials scoffed at that idea, arguing that the
phones make the transition from one technology to another invisible
to the user. But, they agreed there would be a glitch if a customer
_ say in a car _ passes from a system using a high bandwidth to the
lower one or vice versa while on the phone. That call would almost
certainly be disconnected.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
