<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Delta's alliance with KAL suspended
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Delta Air Lines on Friday suspended its marketing
alliance with Korean Air Lines because of safety concerns
heightened by this week's crash of a KAL cargo plane in China.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta-based Delta, which has also been a safety consultant to
KAL since last fall, said it will conduct ``a thorough review'' of
the carrier's operations before deciding whether to renew the
alliance.
</P>
<P>
   Under the pact, Delta had booked passengers on KAL flights from
11 U.S. cities to Seoul and three other Korean destinations. The
arrangement, known as code-sharing, has become a common means of
service expansion among international carriers.
</P>
<P>
   The KAL suspension leaves Delta with only one minor alliance in
Asia. This winter it started a new code-share deal with China
Southern Airlines. Two years ago, Singapore Airlines jilted Delta
for a different alliance.
</P>
<P>
   Delta said it will make other travel arrangements for passengers
it had booked on future KAL flights. Delta will still carry KAL
passengers on some of its own flights.
</P>
<P>
   In this week's crash, an MD-11 freighter went down shortly after
takeoff from Shanghai for Seoul. Nine people were reported dead,
including the three-member crew and six people in an industrial
park where the plane crashed.
</P>
<P>
   KAL had suffered several other recent accidents, the worst a 747
crash on Guam in 1997 that killed 226 people. In March, a KAL MD-83
overran a runway at a Korean airport, injuring dozens.
</P>
<P>
   The carrier began a sweeping safety campaign after the Guam
crash and hired Delta last October to conduct a three-year, $20
million safety audit. Delta said that work will continue.
</P>
<P>
   ``KAL has made a major commitment to improving its operations to
world-class standards and has made substantial progress in that
work,'' Delta said.
</P>
<P>
   Delta, which has numerous European code-share alliances, booked
53 passengers on the Swissair MD-11 that crashed last summer near
Nova Scotia, killing all 229 aboard.
</P>
<P>
   Delta faces lawsuits from that crash but has made no changes in
its alliance with Swissair.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. CARRIERS' ASIA PARTNERS
</P>
<P>
   Delta: China Southern Airlines, Korean Air (suspended Friday)
</P>
<P>
   American: Japan Airlines, Asiana Airlines, China Eastern
Airlines, Singapore Airlines, Cathay Pacific (as part of global
Oneworld alliance)
</P>
<P>
   United: Thai Airways (part of global Star Alliance)
</P>
<P>
   Continental Airlines: China Airlines, EVA Air
</P>
<P>
   Northwest: Air China, Japan Air System
</P>
<P>
   US Airways: None
</P>
<P>
   KAL SAFETY VIOLATIONS
</P>
<P>
   Highlights of a report written by two Korean Air pilots chosen
to participate in an internal safety review. Airline officials said
the reports were exaggerated.
</P>
<P>
   During an airport approach, a co-pilot responded to air traffic
instructions intended for another plane and veered off course. The
captain responded by hitting him on the back of the hand.
</P>
<P>
   While planning an airline flight, crew members did not discuss
the expected weather or the amount of fuel necessary. Such
decisions, they said, should be made by the captain alone.
</P>
<P>
   In-flight newspapers were being reading by flight crews.
</P>
<P>
   Alternative landing sites were not approved for the size of the
plane.
</P>
<P>
   Arguments took place between a pilot and a dispatcher about how
much fuel to load for an ocean crossing.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
