<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELTA-PILOTS17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pilots urge Delta to drop Comair plans
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In another sign of chilled relations between Delta Air
Lines and its pilots, their union is demanding that the carrier
scrap plans to use regional affiliate Comair as part of the Delta
Shuttle operation in the Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   Air Lines Pilots Association leaders, after a special meeting on
the matter, passed a resolution threatening to sue Delta unless it
complies.
</P>
<P>
   Delta plans to add nonstop Washington-Boston flights June 1 to
its Shuttle operation, which now flies hourly between Washington
and New York, and New York and Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Ten daily flights will be flown by Delta jets, but another six
are to be flown by Comair, using small jets.
</P>
<P>
   Delta said it had to use Comair on the route because of
congestion at Washington-Reagan National Airport, where airlines
are limited to a certain number of flight ``slots.''
</P>
<P>
   Delta had only enough slots for two aircraft, but the airline
needed one more to have enough daily flights to compete with rival
US Airways, which is also expanding on the route.
</P>
<P>
   Delta asked Cincinnati-based Comair to use one of its slots to
provide extra flights temporarily, a Delta spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   Although the move isn't prohibited under ALPA's contract, the
union resolution said it violates ``the spirit and intent'' of its
pact.
</P>
<P>
   As a branded Delta product, the union said, Shuttle flights
should be operated solely by Delta pilots.
</P>
<P>
   The complaint reflects general concern among major airline
pilots that carriers can effectively outsource flying to lower-paid
crews through greater cooperation with their commuter affiliates.
</P>
<P>
   That concern is expected to be an issue in new contract talks
this fall between Delta and ALPA.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, Delta cut the number of Boeing 777s it's
buying, saying it feared having to park the big jets because of a
stalemate in talks with ALPA about pay rates for the planes.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-16-99 2107EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
