<DOCNO> NYT19990416.0358 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-16 21:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2045 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INDUSTRY-RECRUITERS17     04-16 0832
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDUSTRY-RECRUITERS17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Economic recruitment heads in new directions
 &HT;    By Matt Kempner
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Two decades ago, economic recruitment in the South
revolved around a simple equation: cheap land plus cheap labor
equals new industry.
</P>
<P>
   Just how much the arithmetic has changed became clear to the 115
economic developers who trained in a sort of boot camp this week at
Georgia Tech.
</P>
<P>
   Towns and cities ``recruit, recruit, recruit,'' but for many of
them economic prizes will never come, says J. Mac Holladay,
``because their product isn't any good if the community doesn't
look nice and the kids aren't smart.'' Holladay, the former chief
operating officer of the Governor's Development Council under
former Gov. Zell Miller, is now a private economic development
consultant.
</P>
<P>
   Many of those in attendance have been in their jobs only a few
months. They represent the latest generation of recruiters that
Southern chambers of commerce and economic development agencies
rely on to keep their business fires stoked.
</P>
<P>
   So, as you would expect, participants in the annual, weeklong
course heard about ways to court businesses.
</P>
<P>
   But they also heard about measuring their success through
reduced teen pregnancies, infant mortality and high school dropout
rates. A project manager from the Nature Conservancy told them to
protect the environment if they want to keep their economies
healthy. And she said they need to study wetlands regulations,
stream buffer laws and a host of other regulatory issues.
</P>
<P>
   They learned that recruiting traditional manufacturers is a bit
passe. Instead, they heard ideas for keeping existing businesses
happy, bolstering start-up companies, attracting high-tech firms,
tapping tourism and thinking about downtown development.
</P>
<P>
   Statements that would have been heresy just a few years ago were
tossed around all week in course seminars.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are people whose entire economic development program is
trying to attract Fortune 500 companies,'' Holladay says. ``That's
stupid!''
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been measuring the wrong things for a long time,'' he
says. ``It is about wealth creation for everybody. It's about
higher per capita income and lower infant mortality rates. It's
about things that make a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Other speakers echo the advice.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have the illusion that all you need to be worried about
are jobs,'' says Jack Bundy, a long-time chamber executive who now
heads Healthy Spartanburg!, an initiative tackling a range of
health and social issues.
</P>
<P>
   Recruiters didn't used to hear this kind of talk.
</P>
<P>
   ``For too long this field of economic development has been too
narrowly defined as new business attraction,'' said Rick Duke,
director of the economic development course at Georgia Tech and the
university's Center for Economic Development Services.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you go back to the late '80s and even early '90s, what we
now call economic development was called industrial development.
... almost everything revolved around industrial recruitment.''
</P>
<P>
   The South pursued manufacturers with the best it had to offer:
inexpensive land and plenty of unskilled labor willing to work
cheap. Economic developers often considered word-of-mouth referrals
their best sales strategy. The job wasn't easy, but neither was it
particularly complex.
</P>
<P>
   Manufacturers considering Southern communities often asked for
little information about the local work force beyond a head count,
said Bob Cassell, who started Georgia Tech's economic development
course 32 years ago and is now director emeritus.
</P>
<P>
   An evolving economy changed that. International markets grew
dramatically in importance. Technology changed the workplace and
reduced the economic significance of unskilled workers. Companies _
facing more competition and narrowing windows before product
equipment obsolescence _ are making location decisions faster and
demanding more from communities.
</P>
<P>
   All of this makes the job of the South's economic developers
increasingly complex. Yet Duke said the profession is still in the
midst of transition. Too many economic developers, he said, have
yet to recognize and react to the new demands.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some communities have thought, `If we acquire property, if we
run water and sewer and erect buildings, prospects will locate in
our community.' They have not thought broadly about the strengths
and weaknesses of their community.''
</P>
<P>
   They should be thinking about issues like schools, crime and
health care, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Many of those in attendance say they've already recognized the
new equation for economic development. ``You just don't sell one
little area,'' says Carmen Cole, a manager at the Liberty County
Development Authority in Hinesville. ``You sell the whole
community.''
</P>
<P>
   Visiting company executives ask detailed questions about the
quality of local schools and overall living conditions, Cole said.
But that's usually after officials are satisfied with more basic
infrastr
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-16-99 2109EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
