<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990416.0359 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-16 21:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2046 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-STRIKES-0417-C     04-16 1543
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-STRIKES-0417-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NATO GIVING GROUND TROOPS 'CONSIDERATION' FOR CREATING SAFE
CORRIDOR IN KOSOVO
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-REFUGEES-0417; REFUGEES-TRAIN-0417;
REFUGEES-AID-0417; KOSOVO-COOK-0417.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ NATO ground forces could be sent into Kosovo to
carve out a corridor of territory the alliance would control, under
one of three options NATO officials are considering to rescue
ethnic Albanians trapped inside the embattled Yugoslav province.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon spokesman Kenneth H. Bacon said Friday that NATO has
made no decision on the options, which also include air drops and
the insertion of humanitarian aid groups under NATO protection.
</P>
<P>
   Bacon stressed that all three choices are fraught with peril,
that there's no guarantee NATO would select any of them and that he
personally regards the corridor option as ``unlikely.''
</P>
<P>
   His announcement, however, marked the first time the Clinton
administration has formally acknowledged any active consideration
of inserting ground forces into Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no NATO plans to open a corridor. It remains an
option that's under consideration,'' Bacon said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously a corridor would require some sort of ground
placement,'' Bacon told reporters at the Pentagon, ``but NATO has
made no decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Bacon's remarks came as NATO's air campaign against Yugoslavia
stretched toward day 25 with fresh strikes early Saturday, and
humanitarian aid groups struggled to assist tens of thousands of
Kosovar Albanian refugees flooding the Albania and Macedonia
borders in the wake of an increasingly brutal and systematic
Serbian-led Yugoslav campaign of ethnic cleansing.
</P>
<P>
   Relief groups reported water systems to be taxed to the limit in
Kukes, where water already is being rationed to a few hours a day
to the permanent population.
</P>
<P>
   Agencies also reported almost no vacant, available land for
refugees coming in cars or the ubiquitous tractor-drawn wagons that
carry 15 to 40 people each.
</P>
<P>
   The influx, which is expected to increase over the coming days,
is putting even more pressure on NATO allies to find a quicker
solution that the daily drumbeat of bombs on Yugoslav forces and
other military targets.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. and allied pilots dropped laser-guided bombs, cluster bombs
and other munitions on 57 major targets -- including radar sites,
anti-aircraft missiles, bridges, fuel and ammunition supplies --
across Yugoslavia on Friday and Thursday, in addition to armored
personnel carriers, troop transport trucks and more than a dozen
tanks deployed inside Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Warplanes flying off of the U.S.S. Roosevelt aircraft carrier
near the Adriatic Sea attacked a military airfield in Montenegro --
along with Serbia, one of two states making up the rump Yugoslavia.
NATO officials said Yugoslav warplanes had been flying from the
field on quick missions into Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   As of Friday, U.S. and allied pilots had flown more than 8,000
sorties in the campaign -- designed to punish Yugoslavia for
repressive activities that have forced as many as 1.5 million
ethnic Albanians to flee their homes in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The NATO armada had risen to 653 aircraft, the Pentagon said,
including 463 U.S. warplanes, refueling tankers and reconnaissance
craft. The NATO supreme allied commander, U.S. Army Gen. Wesley
Clark, has requested 300 additional planes, and a Pentagon decision
on that is expected soon.
</P>
<P>
   With more than 22,500 NATO ground troops either posted near
Kosovo's borders or scheduled to arrive over the next week or so,
some analysts said that carving out a humanitarian corridor could
be a first step toward the launch of a ground offensive.
</P>
<P>
   ``A corridor is nothing more than an avenue of approach for
ground forces,'' said one military officer with extensive Balkans
knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you get 30,000 troops on the ground inside Kosovo and
they're NATO troops and they've got a staging area and it's
protected, it's obviously a place you could use to fly in more
military people,'' said Balkans analyst Michael O'Hanlon of the
Brookings Institution, a Washington think tank. ``You've also
crossed a certain policy line, in saying you're willing to put
troops on the ground in a non-permissive environment.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and the principals on his national security team have
repeatedly said there is ``no plan,'' or ``no intention'' to place
ground troops in Kosovo, except as peacekeepers permitted under an
agreement with Serbian leader Slobodan Milosevic, president of
Yugoslavia. Clinton has been careful, however, not to rule out the
use of ground troops altogether, in both his public remarks and his
closed-door consultations with congressional leaders.
</P>
<P>
   With up to 700,000 ethnic Albanians holed up in remote
mountainous regions with little or no food and shelter, NATO is
under pressure to augment its air war -- now in its fourth
inconclusive week -- with some direct assistance for the
beleaguered refugees trapped inside Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is something that NATO is addressing with some urgency,''
Bacon told reporters at the Pentagon. He made no prediction on how
soon a decision might come. ``The problem is, it's a big problem
and there is no easy solution.''
</P>
<P>
   Bacon's announcement came as 24 U.S. Army Apache combat
helicopters were scheduled to arrive by Monday in Albania, backed
by a ground force of some 2,500 U.S. infantrymen and 18 long-range
battlefield rocket launchers.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to those forces, roughly 8,000 troops from Italy and
other NATO countries are gathering in Albania over the coming week
or so -- many have already arrived -- and there are 12,000 NATO
troops on the ground in neighboring Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, those 20,000 troops are focused on providing
humanitarian assistance to refugees in those countries.
</P>
<P>
   They could, however, quickly be assigned to a combat mission.
The 12,000 NATO troops in Macedonia have been stationed there as
the forward force that would lead a larger NATO peacekeeping
mission into Kosovo, should Yugoslavia accede to the alliance's
demand that the force be permitted into the province.
</P>
<P>
   NATO spokesman Jamie Shea said Friday in Brussels that the
Kosovo Liberation Army, or KLA, has managed to carve out and
control a small pocket of territory in southwest Kosovo
</P>
<P>
   near the Albanian border.
</P>
<P>
   ``NATO has no contacts -- official contacts -- with the KLA,''
said Shea. ``Obviously we know that they have been operating along
the border between Albania and Kosovo. They have even been
successful at opening a corridor. And that may have helped, indeed,
many refugees to enter Albania that might have otherwise been
prevented from doing so.''
</P>
<P>
   Against that background, NATO is considering combining its air
strength with ground forces to carve out an area of control of its
own. Bacon would not say whether the plan envisioned building onto
the territory the KLA controls, but he said NATO's air strikes
against Serb forces on the ground have aided KLA efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the realities is that as the Serb forces become weaker,
the KLA forces will become stronger,'' Bacon said. ``And we've seen
evidence of that over the last two weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   Each of the three options being weighed by NATO's political arm
-- the North Atlantic Council, or NAC -- would pose enormous risks.
</P>
<P>
   Air drops would expose lumbering NATO cargo planes flying low
and slow to enemy fire. The food they might drop, moreover, could
wind up in the hands of the very Serb troops and police that NATO's
air campaign is targeting.
</P>
<P>
   Sending in so-called non-governmental organizations, known as
NGOs, is another option. The government of Greece has been in
intensive contact with Belgrade in recent days to try to win
Serbian safety guarantees for Greek-backed NGO convoys to ferry aid
into ethnic Albanians inside Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   NATO has doubts that Serbs would honor such guarantees -- Serb
forces compiled a long record of hijacking and other abuses of such
missions in the 3 1/2-year war in neighboring Bosnia. This option
would also further complicate what is already a very difficult NATO
air campaign.
</P>
<P>
   To facilitate aid convoys moving through Kosovo would require
NATO to suspend air strikes along those routes. That would, in
effect, create a safe zone in which Serbian forces might also have
room to maneuver, confounding NATO's military aims.
</P>
<P>
   The use of air power alone to try to protect NGOs from hostile
Serbs would be dangerous, said Air Force Maj. Gen. Charles Wald, a
combat pilot who flew similar missions to try to defend United
Nations-designated ``safe areas,'' in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would, personally, say that's not a great idea,'' said Wald.
``It didn't work that great in Bosnia.''
</P>
<P>
   That explains the corridor option.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the problems is that to get NGOs in there you probably
would have to open a corridor, so two of the plans might actually
conflate into one plan,'' Bacon said. ``There is a limited number
of options to deal with this problem, and as I've tried to stress,
no option is particularly easy and inviting.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
