<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRS-WHISTLEBLOWER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSTON IRS OFFICE TRIES BUT FAILS TO FIRE WHISTLEBLOWER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Del.)  (mk) 
 By DAVID CAY JOHNSTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As millions of Americans were filing their returns on tax day,
the Houston office of the IRS was in the process of firing the
first internal revenue agent to publicly blow the whistle about
agency abuses.
</P>
<P>
   The action was halted when the chairman of the Senate Finance
Committee, Sen. William Roth, R-Del., protested to the new tax
commissioner, Charles Rossotti, about retaliation against the
agent, Jennifer Long.
</P>
<P>
   Long, a career tax auditor and the daughter of two career tax
agency employees, was the star of hearings before the Finance
Committee in September 1997 that focused on accusations that
taxpayers were abused by the IRS. She was the only one of seven IRS
agents who did not sit behind a curtain and use a voice distortion
mask to hide her identity when she testified. Mrs. Long said the
agency preys on taxpayers it thinks are weak and lack the power to
fight an audit, while ignoring cheating by those with either the
resources to fight back or with friends in the agency.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Long, a career tax auditor who for 15 years was rated
``fully successful,'' said that on Thursday she was within an hour
of completing an audit when her manager, Karie Gulley, telephoned
and ordered her to return to the IRS office immediately.
</P>
<P>
   There Mrs. Long was served with formal notice that her work was
so bad that she had 60 days to straighten up or she was out of a
job.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're fired once they give you that letter,'' Mrs. Long said.
``They just have to give you 60 days' notice.''
</P>
<P>
   But on Friday afternoon, 23 hours later, the letter was
withdrawn after Roth intervened.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Keith, a spokesman in Washington for the tax agency, said
that Mrs. Long was served with the notice and then reinstated.
Beyond that, he said, ``by law, the IRS is prohibited from
responding.'' He added that managers in the Houston office were not
available to comment on the matter.
</P>
<P>
   Rossotti, who gave up a lucrative career as an executive to try
and remake the IRS into a customer-friendly organization, was said
by both his aides and those of Roth to be furious.
</P>
<P>
   After Rossotti learned of the firing, in a call from one of
Roth's staff, he assigned subordinates to call Michael Greenspan,
the acting director of the Houston district. Several hours later
Mrs. Long was called into Ms. Gulley's office and told that the
60-day letter was withdrawn.
</P>
<P>
   But, Mrs. Long said, the withdrawal of the letter was
accompanied by stern words from Ms. Gulley and her boss, a group
manager, Dianne Jones, and a load of work that was to be turned in
by Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
   The moves against Mrs. Long came one day after Roth, at a
followup to his two rounds of hearings on IRS abuses, had pressed
the tax commissioner for assurances that whistleblowers would be
protected and that errant executives and managers would be
punished.
</P>
<P>
   Rossotti noted that he had reprimanded 12 executives for
improperly rating IRS employees on the basis of how much money they
brought in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am extremely disturbed,'' Rossotti said in a statement,
``that we may have taken action that is retaliatory.'' He said that
on Monday the deputy commissioner, James Wenzel, will go to Houston
to pursue the matter and that he had ordered an inquiry by his
agency's inspector general.
</P>
<P>
   Roth, through his aides, said the letter to Mrs. Long amounted
to ``contempt of Congress.'' But after speaking by telephone with
Rossotti, the senator reiterated his ``complete faith in the
commissioner's sincerity'' and ability to remake the IRS.
</P>
<P>
   Roth's executive assistant, William Nixon, who with the senator
wrote a new book that is sharply critical of the IRS, ``The Power
to Destroy,'' said the firing of Mrs. Long showed how determined
many career IRS executives are to defeat the reforms Congress
ordered last year when it passed a law restructuring the agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's happened here,'' Nixon said, ``is really a pathology of
an ingrained culture. The IRS Houston district is a nest of
vipers.''
</P>
<P>
   He said Roth has collected information on at least a dozen other
auditors who are being harassed because they have either disclosed
improper actions, refused to act improperly or have been friendly
with those who are, like Mrs. Long, out of favor with management in
the Houston district.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Long was served with a list of 33 alleged shortcomings,
including both a failure to seek help from others and a failure to
be sufficiently independent. She was also criticized for driving to
conduct an audit three or four hours away from the office, an audit
that she said was indeed outside of the Houston district but that
was assigned to her by Ms. Gulley.
</P>
<P>
   A detailed list of improvements was included in the 60-day
notice, which specified precisely how Mrs. Long was to fill out her
appointment book, down to what shorthand she must use to specify
whether appointments with taxpayers were tentative or confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   She said that ever since her testimony she has been harassed and
her work subjected to picayune examination. ``On Monday when I came
to work every single manager was in my face with, `You're not a
team player,''' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think this is over,'' she said. ``But tonight I'm
going dancing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
