<HEADLINE>
ALCOA TO CUT EMISSIONS, BOOSTING BUSH'S VOLUNTARY PROGRAM 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BILL DAWSON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush's drive for a voluntary
program to reduce grandfathered air emissions gained support Friday
with a major new corporate commitment and a House committee vote.
</P>
<P>
   Alcoa said it would voluntarily acquire a new-style state permit
and cut emissions at its Rockdale, Texas, aluminum plant, the
state's largest source of grandfathered air emissions.
</P>
<P>
   In earlier legislative testimony, the company said it might have
to shut down the plant, about 50 miles northeast of Austin, if it
were required to get a traditional permit, which would mandate
bigger emission cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the House Environmental Regulation Committee approved
an amended version of a bill, already passed by the full Senate, to
let grandfathered industries acquire new-style permits and cut
emissions voluntarily.
</P>
<P>
   Grandfathered plants, accounting for about a third of industrial
air emissions in Texas, are older facilities exempt from
traditional emission permits since 1971. Permits generally require
stricter pollution controls and subject plants to greater
regulatory scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, backed by industry groups, advocates letting grandfathered
plants cut their emissions voluntarily, while environmentalists
support a mandatory end to their permit exemption.
</P>
<P>
   Scott McClellan, a spokesman for the governor, said the Alcoa
announcement, added to previous commitments from 48 other
companies, indicates Bush's voluntary initiative is working.
</P>
<P>
   A voluntary permit program, if approved by the Legislature,
would enlist still more grandfathered plants, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Ken Kramer, state director of the Sierra Club, said the
Alcoa announcement and House panel vote appeared ``carefully
orchestrated'' to rebut growing calls by environmentalists _ and
recent editorials in Texas' five largest newspapers, including the
Houston Chronicle _ for a mandatory end to the grandfathered
exemption.
</P>
<P>
   The action by the House panel came amid indications that
lawmakers will consider how to strengthen the pollution-reducing
potential of a voluntary permit program for grandfathered plants.
</P>
<P>
   The amount of emission reductions achievable through a voluntary
program, as currently embodied in pending legislation, has been a
major point of debate.
</P>
<P>
   The bill passed by the Senate and House panel would allow plants
getting new, voluntary permits to use pollution controls considered
``best'' 10 years ago. Traditional permits, required at new and
substantially modified plants, mandate controls that are now
considered the best technology.
</P>
<P>
   Alcoa made its commitment because of the flexibility that
provision allows, spokesman Jim Hodson said.
</P>
<P>
   The company cannot estimate the amount of emissions it will
eliminate with a voluntary permit, but there will be substantial
reductions in some pollutant categories, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Alcoa earlier said it would get a permit for part of its
Rockdale plant, and the Friday announcement extended that
commitment to the rest of the facility.
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Marquez, a Bush appointee to the Texas Natural Resource
Conservation Commission, said the company's expanded promise is
``very significant,'' because it means companies responsible for 63
percent of the state's grandfathered emissions have volunteered to
reduce them.
</P>
<P>
   Some of those companies will get traditional permits, while some
intend to apply for new-style voluntary permits that pending
legislation would authorize, Marquez said.
</P>
<P>
   None of the companies will erase its grandfathered emissions
entirely, he said, and reductions will vary from plant to plant,
depending on circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
