<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-16 21:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2058 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-ALBANIA-ART-86     04-16 1215
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-ALBANIA-ART-860&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REFUGEES NOT LEAVING ALBANIAN CITY DESPITE POSSIBILITY OF SERB
ATTACK 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo and graphic are being sent to NYT photo and graphic
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.) 
(rk) 
 By ANTHONY DePALMA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KUKES, Albania _ The shelling of the outskirts of this city full
of Kosovo refugees and the increasingly bold presence of the Kosovo
Liberation Army here have raised concerns that the city itself may
come under attack by Serb shelling.
</P>
<P>
   Five Serb rocket-fired cluster bombs presumably aimed at an
encampment of the rebel group west of Kukes fell on farm fields
four miles from the city on Thursday afternoon. A young goatherd
hit by shrapnel had to be hospitalized.
</P>
<P>
   The daylight bombing, along with a series of other cross-border
shellings in the last week in the cities of Tropoja and Kruma, has
the office of the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees working on
contingency plans to handle casualties if a bomb were to strike the
city, which is now home to more than 75,000 refugees and 20,000
residents.
</P>
<P>
   International monitors, who confirmed the attack, say they
believe that as many refugees as possible should be encouraged, or
even forced, to leave the city, which is only 10 miles from the
border, for safer exile farther away from the war front.
</P>
<P>
   The Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe
identified the bombs as 262-millimeter cluster bombs, self-guided
rockets that are not very accurate but that can be rigged to
explode in the air and shower the ground with many small explosives
or deadly mines.
</P>
<P>
   Kukes is within range of Serb rockets, and the European security
organization fears that the rebel encampment in the city will be
targeted sooner or later. ``It's a probability that can't be ruled
out,'' said Eugene O'Sullivan, a spokesman for the organization.
``The Serbians appear to be well informed about the movements and
actions of the KLA''
</P>
<P>
   Albanian farmers in the lakeside hamlet of Kolsh reported seeing
the rockets come over the mountains and head toward them around
5:30 on Thursday afternoon. Shaban Gika, 12, said he was playing
near his father's car when he heard the first rocket explode as it
hit the ground. The others detonated in the air, he said, and threw
out many small bombs that are now hidden in the underbrush on his
father's farm.
</P>
<P>
   His cousin Bilbil, 19, was tending his goats when he was hit in
the chest, arms and legs, by shrapnel from one of the bombs. He was
taken to a local hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby, Xhyle Doqi, a 40-year-old woman who lives with her six
children in an old stone farmhouse on a verdant hillside facing
Kukes, said she saw dark smoke after the first bomb fell and that
made her afraid.
</P>
<P>
   She said she knew that there was a rebel camp nearby, but, she
said, ``they are on the other side of the hill.'' She didn't know
how many members of the separatist militia were there, but she
thought there were many more men than a few months ago.
</P>
<P>
   The KLA, a disorganized and often undisciplined fighting group,
has sent out a worldwide call for volunteers. Many ethnic Albanians
who left Kosovo in the last decade for the United States, Canada
and a number of European countries have come flooding to Albania
with the intention of volunteering.
</P>
<P>
   Some of them end up in this area. The Organization for Security
and Cooperation in Europe believes that the encampment near Kolsh
is newly built but has expanded considerably since the NATO bombing
of Yugoslavia began on March 24.
</P>
<P>
   Within Kukes itself, the Kosovo rebel army has taken over an
industrial compound and is using it as a boot camp where young
recruits, and possibly men who are forced into volunteering, are
given uniforms, guns and some training before being dispatched to
fight.
</P>
<P>
   The local commander, a stocky man in fatigues who is referred to
only as Rushdi, came out of his office but refused to give any
details about the rebel operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have directives not to say anything to the press right
now,'' he said. ``Maybe in a few days, but not now.''
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations, which is coordinating a large part of the
relief effort for the 75,000 refugees who remain in Kukes, along
with 25,000 in the region and the thousands who stream across the
border every day _ (more than 9,000 Friday) _ has been aware of the
danger from the beginning.
</P>
<P>
   Antonio Kamil, the security adviser to the United Nations in
Kukes, said the organization's own guidelines call for settling
refugees at least 30 miles away from a war front. But there has
been little realistic alternative to using Kukes.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the very beginning we said the refugees should not remain
in Kukes because the area has a limited capacity and because of
security concerns for the refugees,'' Kamil said.
</P>
<P>
   But despite the clear danger, the United Nations cannot force
refugees to move on, even for their own safety. ``After all, the
refugees came by their own means and they can move if they want
to,'' Kamil said, ``but they don't.''
</P>
<P>
   There appear to be at least two primary reasons why so many
Kosovo refugees have remained in Kukes. Many believe they will
return to their homes in Kosovo, and want to remain close to the
border. And despite the language they share with Albanians, many
Kosovars feel lost in this country, with nowhere to go.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   That is the case even though almost any place would seem to have
more to offer than this city, with its questionable safety and
fragile network of services.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the soaring, snow-covered mountains that form a
picturesque background behind it, this city is harsh. Almost
nothing works. The potholes in the streets exceed the areas that
retain their asphalt. Garbage is rarely picked up, the streets are
scoured by dusty winds, and rainwater turns stagnant and evaporates
before it drains away.
</P>
<P>
   Adding almost 100,000 refugees and their thousands of tractors
has only made things worse. People live in the town park and around
the striking white Mosque of Salim Ben Mahfuz, which stands on the
edge of a cliff overlooking the river. Any stairwell or wall that
offers even the suggestion of privacy has been used as a toilet.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, despite the dreadful conditions, the dangerous presence of
the Kosovo rebel army, and the recent bombings that most refugees
saw, there is no rush to leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least here we are near Kosovo and if this is all settled we
can just go back,'' said Sevdie Rafshi, 41, who arrived here with
her family from Dulje in western Kosovo 10 days ago. They live on a
tractor that has been rigged with plastic sheets and old grain
sacks to keep out some of the rain.
</P>
<P>
   Many Kosovars rode on their tractors when they left their land,
and the thought of leaving them behind to go to Tirana, the
Albanian capital, or other places is simply unthinkable, even if it
means avoiding the danger of being bombed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We escaped from the war once and now the war is finding us
again,'' said Berisha Sagit, 24, who came from Peje on her family's
tractor. ``So we'll stay here, where we will be closer to Kosovo,
and if they bomb us it's nothing big because we're used to it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
