<SLUG> BC-OBIT-SACHS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROBERT SACHS, THEORETICAL PHYSICIST, DIES AT 82  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., Md., Mass.)   By ERIC NAGOURNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dr. Robert G. Sachs, a theoretical physicist who once served as
director of the Argonne National Laboratory near Chicago, died on
Wednesday at the University of Chicago Medical Center. He was 82
and lived in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was complications from surgery, the university said.
</P>
<P>
   Sachs was known for playing an important role in his field both
as administrator and policy maker, and as a theorist who,
especially in later years, tried to explain some of the more
mystifying behavior of subatomic particles.
</P>
<P>
   In 1946 and 1947, he helped to create Argonne, a research
laboratory owned by the government and managed by the University of
Chicago. He was a director at the university's Metallurgical
Laboratory, which in 1942 created the first controlled nuclear
chain reaction.
</P>
<P>
   Later, as associate director of Argonne from 1964 to 1968, Sachs
helped determine which scientists would be able to make use of the
lab's new particle accelerator, the zero gradient synchotron.
</P>
<P>
   Sachs returned to teaching in 1968. Although his early work had
been in nuclear physics _ his 1953 book, ``Nuclear Theory,'' was
considered a standard text for years _ he later devoted himself to
the study of particle physics.
</P>
<P>
   He was especially interested in developing theories about the
asymmetry between matter and antimatter in the universe, and the
physics of what scientists refer to as ``time reversal.'' In that
field, the behavior of subatomic particles is examined for clues
to, among other things, the nature of time.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists who study time reversal often use the example of two
billiard balls on a table to explain their theories. If a film is
made of the balls colliding, they note, a viewer would see nothing
amiss if it was shown to them running backward: the same physical
laws seem to apply, in other words, whichever direction time is
running.
</P>
<P>
   But scientists have known for more than three decades that with
certain particles, the rules appear different. It is as if two and
two were added together to make four, but when two was then
subtracted from the sum, the result was not the expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``One would like to have a theory of elementary particles that
essentially explains everything that they do,'' said Roger
Hildebrand, a physicist who worked with Sachs for decades. ``We
come very close to that. But there are some things that just don't
work.''
</P>
<P>
   Sachs' last book, published in 1987 by the University of Chicago
Press, was ``The Physics of Time Reversal.''
</P>
<P>
   He was also credited with creating a new division at the
American Physical Society, the principal professional society for
physicists, for scientists studying particles and fields.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Green Sachs was born on May 4, 1916, in Hagerstown, Md.
He received his doctorate in 1939 from Johns Hopkins University and
began teaching. Among his students was Hyman G. Rickover, who later
established the Navy's nuclear submarine program. After teaching
for three years, Sachs joined the Ballistic Research Laboratory at
the Aberdeen Proving Ground in Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   Sachs was hired by the University of Chicago in 1964, and
directed the Argonne lab from 1973 to 1979. He was also director of
the university's Enrico Fermi Institute from 1968 to 1973, and from
1983 to 1986, when he became professor emeritus.
</P>
<P>
   Colleagues said that Sachs, who was also a dedicated sailor,
remained active in his field until his death.
</P>
<P>
   Sachs is survived by his wife, Carolyn L. Sachs, of Chicago;
three daughters, Judith Crow, of Portola Valley, Calif., Rebecca
Norris, of Maynard, Mass., and Jennifer Sachs, of New York; two
sons, Joel, of Arlington, Mass., and Jeffrey, of Sunnyvale, Calif.;
three stepchildren, Jacqueline Wolf, of West Newton, Mass., Kate
Wolf, of Lincoln, Mass., and Thomas Wolf, of Brookline, Mass.; and
14 grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
