<SLUG> BC-ITALY-U.S.-JETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME MARINE FLIGHT TRAINING TO BE MOVED FROM ITALY
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With the United States strictly observing Italian
rules on low-altitude flights since a Marine jet severed a ski
gondola cable last year, killing 20 people, Italy is now unsuitable
for some essential training, an American admiral said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The admiral, Joseph Prueher, who disclosed part of a report on
new flight rules that he wrote with Lt. Gen. Leonardo Tricarico of
the Italian Air Force, said the United States is looking for other
training sites, including in Tunisia and Morocco.
</P>
<P>
   Italian rules require a minimum altitude of 2,000 feet above the
ground, and that is too high to practice ``terrain masking,'' or
sneaking into the battle theater between the mountains, the
technique that the EA-6B Prowler was practicing at the time of the
gondola accident, Prueher said.
</P>
<P>
   An Italian official, Brig. Gen. Giuseppe Bernardis, speaking at
the same briefing, said that his country, too, was looking for new
sites for low-level training; most of the Italian training is done
in Nevada, he said.
</P>
<P>
   A summary of the report, made public Friday, calls for a variety
of steps to improve adherence to Italian rules. The full report was
not released.
</P>
<P>
   The report contains information that conforms with previous
military investigations that say the primary cause of the accident
was error by the crew. The pilot and navigator testified that they
thought they were supposed to stay at 1,000 feet above the ground;
the cable they struck was at about 370 feet.
</P>
<P>
   But the report also faulted other officers, saying that ``the
primary guarantor of flight safety is unit/command leadership that
demands thoughtful, disciplined adherence to established
procedures.''
</P>
<P>
   The report said, ``Supervisory error occurred with the air
crew's chain of command.'' Prueher noted that the squadron
commander and safety officer had been relieved of command after the
crash, which occurred on Feb. 3, 1998. The pilot was acquitted of
negligence but faces charges of obstruction of justice; the
navigator was convicted of that charge and faces expulsion from the
Marine Corps.
</P>
<P>
   The recommendations, which Defense Secretary William Cohen and
Defense Minister Carlo Scognamiglio of Italy signed at a Pentagon
ceremony Friday morning and sent on to President Clinton and Prime
Minister Massimo D'Alema, would designate an American commander at
each Italian air base to assure that American crews were fully
cognizant of all local rules.
</P>
<P>
   The report does not call for fixing American navigation charts
that omit the gondola cables and scores of similar obstructions in
Italy, but Prueher said that such materials would be available to
crews, as part of improved briefing procedures.
 &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
