<SLUG> BC-HKN-GRETZKY-DAVIDSON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GREAT SCHMOOZE: DAVIDSON DIDN'T ASK 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ John Davidson, the Rangers' MSG Network and Fox
analyst, never asked Wayne Gretzky about retiring. Three times
since last week, Davidson told television audiences with increasing
certainty that the end was near for Gretzky's career. He said on
Fox last Sunday that retirement was an 80 percent possibility.
</P>
<P>
   But Davidson, the former Rangers goaltender who flies on the
team charter and usually sits with Gretzky, never directly asked
Gretzky the retirement question. Their relationship is not quite
journalistic; instead, it is a bond between a former and a current
player, a connection between two savvy National Hockey League
personalities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to put him on the spot,'' Davidson said Friday,
when he was host for Gretzky's retirement news conference at
Madison Square Garden. ``I thought it was an invasion of his
privacy to ask. I'm not sure when he became 100 percent. But it was
up to him to tell the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Each time Davidson aired his reports about the retirement, he
called Gretzky, who never warned him off.
</P>
<P>
   Davidson said the signals were evident. Gretzky's father,
Walter, said his son was considering retirement. Davidson watched
Gretzky crying on the bench in last Wednesday's game at Chicago. He
heard Gretzky was collecting pucks and sticks.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was throwing hints,'' Davidson said. ``A lot of people said
he was leaning toward retiring, including his father. I wanted to
alert people that the greatest player ever might retire. But I
wasn't looking for a scoop.''
</P>
<P>
   Davidson said Gretzky was unaware of how intense the coverage
would become once fans and the news media learned he was
considering retirement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to tell him, `If you're leaving, it's going to cause a
lot of interest,''' Davidson said. ``I don't think he understood
how big it would become.''
</P>
<P>
   Even on the charter flight home Thursday night from Ottawa,
where Gretzky played his final game in Canada, the talk was not
about retirement, but about Gretzky's elation about having played
well in the Rangers' 2-2 tie against the senators.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last night, he threw a pass to a winger that was one of the
best he'd ever made,'' Davidson said. ``No one could pass the puck
like him and still, there are very few who can pass the puck as
well as he does now.''
</P>
<P>
   The in-flight banter between Gretzky and Davidson centers on
hockey. ``We schmooze,'' Davidson said. ``When we're on charters or
on Tarmacs, we talk about hockey in this city or that, hockey
issues, rules changes, the stuff I pull off the Internet. And when
we play golf, we talk hockey.''
</P>
<P>
   Gretzky usually sits in the middle area of the plane, with the
broadcasters, public relations staff and the team trainer. The news
media following the Rangers do not fly on the charter, giving
Davidson access that no beat reporter possesses.
</P>
<P>
   Sam Rosen, Davidson's MSG partner, described the
Gretzky-Davidson relationship as very close.
</P>
<P>
   ``But he's been close to a lot of players,'' Rosen said. ``He's
respected as a former player and a top broadcaster. Players know if
there's something they say that they don't want getting out, he
won't say anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Davidson said during his conversations with Gretzky, he caught
himself starting to talk his friend out of retiring. ``But I caught
myself,'' Davidson said. ``Who am I to tell him or ask him what to
do? I could have said, `We could use you next year, and imagine the
farewell tour.' But that's not for him emotionally. He can still
play. He knows he's pretty good some nights, but not as good other
nights. It drives him nuts. It gets him frustrated.''
</P>
<P>
   Davidson was a Rangers goaltender when he first encountered
Gretzky, then a young Edmonton Oiler, in the early 1980s. ``I think
I played him only three times,'' Davidson said. ``He had some
assists. I remember one game in Edmonton, he was flattened on a
play, but came back and assisted on the game-winner. At that time,
I had a personal 10-game winning streak and that stopped that.''
</P>
<P>
   After his own retirement following the 1982-83 season, Davidson
got to know Gretzky and Mark Messier, his Edmonton teammate, when
he broadcast Oilers games for two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly two decades later, Davidson, along with Mike Emrick, will
describe Gretzky's farewell game. Tomorrow afternoon's
Rangers-Penguins game will be carried partly on the Fox-owned
Channel 5 (after the Yankees game ends) and in its entirety on MSG.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've done seventh games of Stanley Cup finals, the Olympics,
All-Star Games, the World Cup, but this may be the topper for me,''
Davidson said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
