<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NY-POLICE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: SOUND IDEAS FOR POLICE REFORM  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Saturday, April 17:
</P>
<P>
   The marchers at Thursday's rally on police reform in New York
City used the event to promote a 10-point plan for improving police
policies first proposed by a group of community and business
leaders last month. While we differ on some details, the plan is a
useful outline for change. Mayor Rudolph Giuliani should welcome a
serious dialogue on its principles, several of which were
recommended by a task force on police conduct that he himself
appointed after the attack on Abner Louima in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani has instituted part of the 10-point agenda, increasing
minority recruitment efforts and training for the Street Crime
unit. But in the past he has opposed or brushed aside other
elements that deserve support.
</P>
<P>
   A primary purpose of the agenda is to improve oversight of
police conduct and internal investigations, a departmental weakness
long evident to community leaders and criminal justice experts. The
plan rightly calls for the creation of an independent audit panel,
as recommended by the Mollen Commission, with full power to issue
subpoenas and investigate police corruption and brutality. The
Police Department would still have primary responsibility for
detecting and preventing corruption and misconduct, but the panel
would be a credible external monitoring force.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani has fought this idea, and has tied up City Council
legislation creating such a panel in two separate lawsuits. But the
lack of faith, particularly in minority communities, in the
department's ability to police itself makes an independent review
function more important than ever.
</P>
<P>
   The plan would strengthen and increase funding for the Civilian
Complaint Review Board, which would still be needed to investigate
individual misconduct complaints by members of the public. It also
proposes a special prosecutor for police brutality and corruption
cases, which should not be necessary if the independent panel can
refer findings of criminal activity directly to prosecuting
attorneys.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor's own task force had already recommended three
important elements of the plan. One would end the 48-hour rule that
now gives officers charged with violations of department rules two
days before they are questioned by investigators. That right, which
should be deleted from the next labor contract, makes it too easy
for officers to cover up misdeeds by giving them time to concoct a
story. A second would increase pay for officers.
</P>
<P>
   A third would impose a a city residency requirement, although
this would require a change in state law. Since that is likely to
be politically difficult, it may be more productive to provide
further incentives to entice officers to live in the city. In
addition, the plan appropriately urges periodic review of police
weapons and tactics, such as the use of hollow-point bullets.
</P>
<P>
   None of these proposals need diminish the mayor's power to run
the Police Department. Giuliani may well be able to improve on
elements of the plan, but it looks to be a sensible place to start.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-16-99 2130EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
