u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-SARGENT-NYT &LR;      04-16 0461
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-SARGENT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE GENEROSITY OF JOHN SINGER SARGENT  
DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Saturday, April 17: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In a room full of John Singer Sargent's portraits, a certain
augustness smites the viewer. The figures of Lord Dalhousie and
Lord Ribblesdale, of Sir Frank Swettenham and Madame X form a
striking assembly. They could not, at first glance, be more unlike
the casual crowd that wanders, in the loose clothing and
comfortable shoes of resolute sightseers, through the National
Gallery in Washington, where the Sargent exhibition is on display
until May 31. No matter how you dress, there is something a little
intimidating about Dalhousie, Ribblesdale et al., even if it is
nothing more than the height at which they hang from the walls, a
height that forces them to look down upon you.
</P>
<P>
   But Sargent does not seem to buy the augustness of these
figures. The faces and the postures are too revealing. It is as
though Sargent has caught each of his subjects in a mirror-image of
their own making, a moment when they are left alone to contemplate
themselves. Sargent seems to engulf these figures in his own
virtuosity, the disparity between the substance of these wealthy
men and women and their heirs and the imaginative power of mere
pigment and brushwork.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mrs. Carl Meyer and Her Children,'' for instance, is nothing
less than a fantasy on the premise of portraiture. The three faces
in this painting, which Sargent created in 1896, practically quiver
with identity. To everything else in the room _ the profusion of
satin Mrs. Meyer wears, the book flung beside her on the sofa, the
sofa itself _ Sargent has brought the intensity of his own focus in
brush strokes that, seen up close, look almost ephemeral, just the
residue of his touch. But that is Sargent. He appears to be a
genius of visage, when in fact he is a genius of light.
</P>
<P>
   This is the kind of exhibition where a viewer feels the loss as
each picture is left behind. That is especially true of several
paintings that are not portraits _ ``Capri'' (1878), ``In the
Luxembourg Gardens'' (1879), ``Carnation, Lily, Lily, Rose''
(1885-6), and ``Home Fields'' (about 1885). In these works the
viewer is allowed to stand within the light surrounding Sargent at
his easel, or more accurately the light filling Sargent's mind as
he put brush to canvas. It is not the light before you that you
sense but the light that would enfold you if the painting's horizon
reached behind you. These works evoke the quality that allows a
viewer to love even the austere facade of Ribblesdale or Henry
James. What we see, first and last, is the visual warmth, as well
as the insurrection, of Sargent's generosity. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
