<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-MEDIA-REPORT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ESPN TURNED DRAFT INTO GRIPPING TV
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID A. MARKIEWICZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ESPN's NFL draft TV marathon featuring Mel Kiper Jr. has proven
so popular with viewers that the network ought to consider a
spin-off sports program.
</P>
<P>
   Tentative title: The ESPN Major League Baseball Draft featuring
... who else? Duane Kuiper.
</P>
<P>
   The former Cleveland Indians and San Francisco Giants second
baseman doesn't have Kiper's hair, but he's got his name, or at
least one with the same pronunciation. He's broadcast-friendly,
too, having gone on to a sports announcing career when his playing
days were finished.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Kuiper can turn the baseball draft into the same sort of
edge-of-your-seat spectacle the football pickfest has become thanks
in large measure to Kiper and his know-it-all exuberance.
</P>
<P>
   Lest you think this a joke, be advised that back before ESPN
started its pro football draft coverage 20 years ago the event was
conducted on a Tuesday morning, and the only media present were the
local beat writers and a stray camera crew expecting a slow day.
</P>
<P>
   Today, when ESPN begins its coverage at 11 a.m., it will have a
nationwide TV audience, cameras inside the ``war rooms'' of four
NFL teams and video conferencing hook-ups with 20 other clubs.
</P>
<P>
   There also will be a benchload of ex-jocks around to do
player-by-player and team-by-team analysis in the New York and
Bristol, Conn., studios, plus field reporters reporting from
selected cities.
</P>
<P>
   With all that technology and staffing available, ESPN will need
hours and hours of air time to make full use of it. And they'll
have the time. Coverage on ESPN runs to 6 p.m. today, when it
switches over to ESPN2, which will run with the ball until 9 p.m.
ESPN picks things back up at 10 a.m. tomorrow and carries Day Two
of the draft until noon. ESPN2 takes it home to 5 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing ESPN's always been is thorough,'' understated
ESPN draft-day host Chris Berman. ``Technology's allowed us to
branch out.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be easy to go in there and sit down in a chair, roll
highlights and talk, then go to a commercial and come back and do
the same thing,'' said the show's producer, Jay Rothman. ``But our
viewers have an expectation. Our viewers have a thirst, really, for
who this player is and how \Rchoosing him\s affects their team.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys will get the video-conferencing treatment this
weekend, allowing for live, one-on-one interviews with Dallas
coaches and personnel. The network will not have a reporter on site
at Valley Ranch, however, or a war-room camera.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the Jerry Jones era, ESPN has been all over the
Cowboys on draft day with a war-room camera in place and reporter
Chris Myers on the scene. Myers, who had developed a comfortable
relationship with Jones and company, has moved on to Fox, though,
and the Cowboys have lost some of their luster thanks to a lower
draft slot.
</P>
<P>
   ESPN executives would like to have a camera in every team's war
room and a reporter at every draft site, but that's not
economically feasible.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really a matter of resources,'' Rothman explained. ``It's
really a financial or budget issue.''
</P>
<P>
   This year, war-room cameras will be located at draft
headquarters in Cleveland, Miami, Minnesota and New England.
</P>
<P>
   Why the Dolphins?
</P>
<P>
   Why, Jimmy Johnson, of course.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jimmy's the best,'' Rothman said. ``I think he might help us
in terms of where to place the camera. He's always made great
television for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Ever since those Valley Ranch days, that is.
</P>
<P>
   While some clubs enjoy the network's attention, others such as
the San Diego Chargers have asked for some peace and quiet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some teams obviously respond differently to it,'' Rothman said
of the attention.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, when you've drafted like the Chargers have in recent
years, you probably don't want anybody watching.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
