A2081 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOOLITTLE17-COX     04-16 0435
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOOLITTLE17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Doolittle Raiders hold first reunion
 &HT;    By Derek Ali
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ 1st Lt. James H. Macia never imagined the hero
status members of the Doolittle Tokyo Raiders earned after
successfully attacking Japan on April 18, 1942.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Macia doubted the squadron of 16 B-25 bombers would
survive _ seven men died on the mission and 12 more died before the
war ended.
</P>
<P>
   On their way, the U.S. fleet transporting the bombers sank a
Japanese ship and it was believed the ship sent out a radio message
warning the Japanese.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were thinking those guys knew we were coming,'' Macia said.
That thinking triggered a pre-mature launch of the B-25s, 200 miles
farther out than planned.
</P>
<P>
   The anticipated counterattack from Japanese fighter planes never
happened. The Raiders successfully attacked their targets and
brought hope at time when Japan appeared invincible.
</P>
<P>
   Macia and 17 of the 19 surviving pilots, gunners, navigators and
bombardiers who flew with Lt. Co. Jimmy Doolittle on the daring
daylight bombing raid are holding their first reunion at the USAF
Museum since the 1960s this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Raiders signed autographs and shared stories with the
curious in the Kettering Hall, near the museum's B-25 exhibit. In
honor of the 57th anniversary of the Raider's mission, the museum
is hosting a Day with Heroes, with a Memorial Dedication in the
museum's Memorial Park, at 10 a.m. today.
</P>
<P>
   Macia, a retired colonel, said he was the last of Doolittle's
Raiders to retire from active duty in 1973. However, Macia
continues to share stories with the inquisitive and hugs with
youngsters.
</P>
<P>
   Darke County's Kevan Dilworth, a 12-year-old flight fanatic and
benefactor of a Macia hug, said, ``I want to be a pilot later on. I
find it fascinating, the technology, what we're capable of.''
</P>
<P>
   Kevan counted his meeting with Macia and other members of the
Raiders as an historic event. ``I'm very excited about it. It's a
once in a life time experience and something you want to tell your
kids about. It's being a part of history.''
</P>
<P>
   Dave Thatcher, a staff sergeant who served as a gunner on the
bombing mission, was an active part of the history. After the
bombing, his B-25 crashed landed on the China coast. ``It took us a
month to get to Kung King.'' They traveled by train, sedan chairs
and rickshaw. ``The Chinese had blown up all the roads to slow the
advance of the Japanese. All there was was trails down through rice
patties.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
