<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MILITARY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO CLAIMS `ONE OF THE BEST NIGHTS' FOR BOMBINGS
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By PHILIP SHENON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ NATO pilots claimed one of their most successful
nights in the air campaign against Yugoslavia, destroying several
tanks and artillery sites and damaging a large air base on Thursday
night. The warplanes also gathered new photographic evidence to
back up reports of mass killings of Kosovo refugees, NATO and
Clinton administration officials said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   NATO said relatively clear skies over the Balkans from Thursday
night to Friday morning made it possible for the planes to attack
targets that included an SA-6 surface-to-air missile site near
Belgrade, an ammunition plant, the headquarters of several Serbian
army and policy units and a military airfield in Montenegro.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon reported that a total of 57 targets were hit
Thursday and Friday, suggesting that NATO planes were far more
successful than earlier in the campaign, when as few as 12 targets
were hit each night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last night we had some notable successes,'' NATO spokesman
Jamie Shea. ``In fact, it was one of the best nights thus far in
our campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's clear that life is becoming increasingly unpleasant for
Serb forces inside Kosovo,'' he added at a news conference at NATO
headquarters in Brussels.
</P>
<P>
   Late Friday, the Pentagon announced that Kosovar rebels had
seized a Yugoslav army lieutenant in Kosovo and that he was in
American custody as a prisoner of war.
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials acknowledged that despite success in the air,
they had received reports of new atrocities by Serb forces against
Kosovo Albanians uprooted from their homes.
</P>
<P>
   In Yugoslavia, President Slobodan Milosevic was another step
closer to what appears to be his ultimate goal in Kosovo, the
forced depopulation of the province of what had been its Albanian
majority. Thousands of refugees poured across the borders into
Albania and Montenegro Friday, putting the total number of refugees
reported along Kosovo's borders at more than 500,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trickle of refugees that had been going into Albania and
Macedonia has now become a flow,'' said State Department spokesman
James Rubin. ``This is something that greatly troubles us. There
may be up to 50,000 people who are backed up at the border.''
</P>
<P>
   Rubin said the renewed flood of refugees was explained in part
by reports of a new round of terror by Serbian forces. ``We have
developed new evidence, independently corroborated by refugee
interviews, about mass killings in west-central Kosovo,'' he said.
``This new information about mass killings is another example of
the fact that President Milosevic's policies are aimed toward
killing civilians.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Rubin would not describe the evidence in detail, other
administration officials said that photographs taken by American
spy satellites showed rows of freshly dug mass graves west of
Pristina, the provincial capital, and that refugee accounts from
the region suggested that Serbian forces had executed hundreds of
people there in recent days.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton rerouted Air Force One Friday on a Democratic
Party fund-raising tour to stop at Selfridge Air National Guard
Base, Mich., to meet 50 volunteer reservists who were scheduled to
leave Friday night for Europe to support the NATO effort.
</P>
<P>
   In Michigan, Clinton also met privately the family of Staff Sgt.
Christopher Stone, 25, of Smiths Creek, Mich., one of the three
American servicemen whom Serb forces took prisoner last month.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech Friday in metropolitan Detroit, a region where the
president noted that 40,000 Albanian-Americans lived, Clinton said
the United States should help rebuild the Balkans, much as it had
helped rebuild Western Europe with the Marshall Plan after World
War II.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must do for southeastern Europe, including the Balkans,
what was done for Central Europe after the Cold War and for the
battleground nations of Europe after World War II,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   NATO and Pentagon officials said that air strikes were being
conducted around the clock and that they were planning for the
heavy bombing of Yugoslav targets Friday night and early Saturday
morning, in an effort to beat the forecast of heavy clouds for the
region.
</P>
<P>
   The state-run Tanjung news agency in Yugoslavia reported that
the main Kosovo airport outside Pristina, Slatino, was hit Friday
night for the fifth time, along with mountaintop radio transmitters
northeast and south of the city.
</P>
<P>
   An wave of NATO attacks before dawn Friday focused on a military
airfield and airport just outside Podgorica, capital of Montenegro,
the smaller republic of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   The pro-Western Montenegro government has accused Belgrade of
trying to draw NATO attacks against Serb targets in Montenegran
territory.
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials said Friday that several Yugoslav naval vessels
docked in Montenegro ports had fired on NATO aircraft but that NATO
planes had not fired back so far.
</P>
<P>
   Also reported hit by NATO planes was the largest oil refinery in
Serbia and a bridge over the Danube southeast of Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   To cover the costs of the American part of the operation, the
White House is generally expected to ask Congress early next week
for $5.9 billion in emergency spending.
</P>
<P>
   The request, which covers projected spending through the fiscal
year that ends on Sept. 30, includes $5.5 billion for the Pentagon
and $500 million for the State Department, a senior administration
official said. Of that, $650 million to $700 million is focused on
relief aid.
</P>
<P>
   The official said the request was enough ``to sustain the
current forces through the rest of the year.'' That force, the
official said, includes the 48 Apache attack helicopters en route
to Albania, the 300 additional aircraft that Gen. Wesley Clark, the
NATO commander, has requested and the costs of calling as many as
33,000 reservists to active duty.
</P>
<P>
   The first Apache helicopters are now expected to reach Tirana,
Albania, this weekend. The full fleet is not expected to be ready
for combat for several weeks, the Pentagon said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Administration official said the appropriation request would not
cover the cost of ground forces, including 4,000 troops that the
United States has promised to a peacekeeping force that would work
in Kosovo under a negotiated settlement.
</P>
</TEXT>
