<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-POW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YUGOSLAV OFFICER, CAUGHT BY KLA, IS IN U.S. CUSTODY 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Albanian rebels in Kosovo have captured a Yugoslav
Army officer and turned him over to Albania, which Friday turned
him over to the U.S. Army in Albania's capital, the Pentagon
announced Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon immediately declared the officer a prisoner of war.
Eager to draw a distinction with Yugoslavia's treatment of three
American soldiers captured along Macedonia's border on March 31,
officials here emphasized that the officer would be treated in
accordance with the Geneva Convention.
</P>
<P>
   The officer, a lieutenant whose name was not disclosed, was
captured by fighters with the Kosovo Liberation Army near Junik,
Kosovo, late Tuesday or early Wednesday, a statement by the
Pentagon said. The rebels secreted the lieutenant across the border
to Albania and turned him over to authorities there.
</P>
<P>
   Evidently eager to transfer him to NATO's jurisdiction, the
Albanian government quickly alerted American military officers,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   A U.S. Army helicopter flew to an undisclosed spot in remote
northern Albania and returned the officer, evidently unharmed, to
Tirana, the capital, where he remains in American custody, the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
   At the nascent American base in Tirana, the officer was examined
by a doctor and ``found to be in good condition,'' the statement
said. The Pentagon said arrangements had already been made with the
International Committee of the Red Cross to visit him.
</P>
<P>
   ``In addition to the food, shelter and medical care being
provided, religious counseling is being coordinated for him,'' the
Pentagon said.
</P>
<P>
   The capture of a Yugoslav officer immediately raised the
prospect of a prisoner exchange, though it is not clear whether any
diplomatic channels exist for such discussions.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon's spokesman, Kenneth Bacon, said an exchange was a
possibility but added that it was premature to discuss it. ``The
rules of the Geneva Convention are pretty clear,'' Bacon said.
``He'll remain in our custody until the hostilities end. I don't
think it's time to speculate about anything else.''
</P>
<P>
   The three American soldiers have been held in Yugoslavia since
their capture in unclear circumstances along the
Yugoslavia-Macedonia border. The three _ Staff Sgt. Andrew Ramirez,
24, of Los Angeles; Staff Sgt. Christopher Stone, 25, of Smiths
Creek, Mich., and Spc. Steven Gonzales, 21, of Huntsville, Texas
_were among 350 American troops in Macedonia as part of a U.N.
observer mission.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after their capture, they were shown on Yugoslav
television, evidently beaten and bruised. After initially
threatening to submit them to a military trial, in violation of the
Geneva Convention, the Yugoslav government declared that it would
treat them as prisoners of war.
</P>
<P>
   An effort to free them by the acting president of Cyprus
collapsed a week ago when Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic
balked, citing the intensification of NATO's bombardment.
</P>
<P>
   The United States maintains that the three were illegally seized
by Yugoslav forces inside Macedonia, though officials concede that
they do not yet know all the circumstances of their disappearance.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon officials said the captured officer, who was born in
1978, commanded a unit of about 20 men. His unit _ identified in
Serbo-Croatian as the 1st Platoon, 2nd Battalion _ was part of a
larger force conducting operations near Junik, in a valley that has
been the scene of intense fighting throughout the yearlong
separatist insurgency.
</P>
<P>
   The officials said the Yugoslav force included 300 army troops
and 100 paramilitary police. It was not clear how the Kosovar
rebels managed to separate the lieutenant from the rest of his
platoon.
</P>
<P>
   The officials said it was likely he would be transferred out of
Albania as soon as Saturday, possibly to Italy. In a potentially
awkward legal complication, the Geneva Convention requires nations
to provide protections for prisoners, but makes no explicit
allowance for alliances like NATO's, one official said.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon's statement said the prisoner would have the right
to send and receive mail and ``communicate any complaints'' to his
captors.
</P>
<P>
   NATO and the Clinton administration have stepped up their praise
of the Kosovo Liberation Army, an organization harshly criticized
by the State Department only several months ago as ``terrorist.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Like a phoenix which rises from the ashes, the Kosovo
Liberation Army is able to mount a number of attacks still inside
Kosovo,'' NATO's spokesman, Jamie Shea, said Friday before the
capture was announced.
</P>
</TEXT>
