<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HALT FOR WAR OVER, CLINTON RESUMES FUND-RAISING 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WESTON, Mass. _ Ending his self-imposed moratorium on
fund-raising, President Clinton was back on the money circuit
Friday after 23 days, bringing in $1.3 million for Democratic
candidates at two events.
</P>
<P>
   The president, his party's top cash draw, suspended his
fund-raising activities March 24, when NATO's bombing of Yugoslavia
began. Now, with the war grinding through its fourth week, the
Clinton administration has decided that the image of the
president's raising money for political purposes is less
detrimental than any image of a president paralyzed in Washington
by a foreign policy crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president as president has an obligation to both manage
any foreign policy crisis that's going on as well as continue to
pursue his domestic agenda,'' said Joe Lockhart, Clinton's press
secretary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of what the president does is serve as the party leader,
and part of that process is to raise money,'' Lockhart added.
``He's fully able to execute his job as commander in chief
consistent with his duties as well as work on a domestic agenda,
and I think the American people expect the president to be able to
do both.''
</P>
<P>
   To that end, the president added several war-related activities
to his long-planned fund-raising schedule Friday. After speaking to
250 people in Dearborn, Mich., who paid $1,500 each for lunch with
him at the Fairlane Club, he remained in the Detroit area to
address about 300 officials of various refugee relief organizations
and also meet privately with seven Albanian-Americans who have
relatives in the war-torn region.
</P>
<P>
   And on his way Friday night to this Boston suburb, where he was
joined for dinner at the home of former Democratic finance chairman
Alan Solomont by 80 people who paid $10,000 apiece for the
privilege, he met with personnel at Hanscom Air Force Base in the
nearby town of Bedford.
</P>
<P>
   In his talks Friday, Clinton emphasized U.S. relief efforts
directed at helping the many thousands of refugees streaming out of
Kosovo. In his remarks to the aid organizations, he noted that the
Detroit area was home to 40,000 Albanian-Americans and to thousands
of Serbian-Americans, and said it was important that the nation not
blame Serbs for the war.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of them don't even know what has been done in their name
in Kosovo,'' he said, ``because the state-run media has covered it
up.''
</P>
<P>
   As he spoke, hundreds of demonstrators outside endured a steady
rain and a raw wind to hoist banners and chant against the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   Until the war began, the president had been on a fund-raising
spree, pulling in more than $9 million for the party in about two
months. As the headliner at two events in Washington on March 23,
the night before the bombing began, he raised more than $1 million.
Those were his last fund-raisers until Friday. He canceled three,
in Ohio, Nevada and California, that had been scheduled for March
25.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday he was in California, to speak to the American Society
of Newspaper Editors in San Francisco, but attended no
fund-raisers. He spent most of the day with his daughter, Chelsea,
who came up from Stanford University.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the situation abroad, the 2000 elections still loom,
and candidates still need to raise money for them. The Democrats
are determined to take back the House, and the cash that the
president raised Friday is to go to both House and Senate
Democratic campaign funds.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was joined at his fund-raisers Friday by several
prominent Democrats. In Michigan, most of the state's Democratic
congressional delegation attended, as did House Minority Leader
Dick Gephardt, who hopes to become speaker after the 2000
congressional elections. In Massachusetts, both of that state's
senators, Edward M. Kennedy and John Kerry, joined the president,
as did Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle.
</P>
<P>
   And in both Michigan and Massachusetts, Clinton was joined by
Rep. Patrick Kennedy of Rhode Island, who is spearheading the House
Democrats' fund-raising drive and is so eager for it to be
successful that he is opening his family's renowned compound in
Hyannis Port to big donors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
