<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-16 21:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2085 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REVLON-PERELMAN-ART-2     04-16 1218
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVLON-PERELMAN-ART-2TAKES-$ADV18-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WRINKLES UNDER THE SURFACE AT REVLON 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y.)   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 18)  
 (af)  
 By DANA CANEDY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The cover of Revlon Inc.'s latest annual report could easily be
mistaken for the front of a glamour magazine, with the model Cindy
Crawford and the actress Cybill Shepherd looking flawless in the
company's ``tawny'' blush and ``hot cocoa'' lipstick.
</P>
<P>
   But the image of Revlon's majority owner, the billionaire Ronald
O. Perelman, is anything but unblemished. A 1980s-style deal maker
with a passion for the high life, Perelman is known for bailing out
of ventures in the nick of time. There have been fiascos _ for
public shareholders, at least _ at Marvel Entertainment, Coleman,
Consolidated Cigar and Sunbeam, all of which lost money and
accumulated debt on his watch.
</P>
<P>
   Revlon, though, has been the crown jewel of his portfolio _
glamorous, with strong cash flow, a business that held his interest
and bore his fingerprints. Only weeks ago, it seemed inconceivable
that he would consider selling this, his core asset. But now he has
declared himself ready to unload it.
</P>
<P>
   What changed? Analysts, fund managers and industry experts say
Perelman has toted up Revlon's huge debts, gauged its slipping
competitive stance and concluded that the picture is unlikely to
brighten anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
   Winning a decent price for all or part of Revlon, they say, is
his best route to salvaging at least part of his reputation as
something more than a corporate raider. Saving face ``is his
biggest problem,'' said Andrew Shore, an analyst at Paine Webber.
``Everybody wants to see how he handles it. He's got a lot on the
line.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Perelman's closest confidants dismisses this reading of
his motives, saying the financier is simply frustrated by
investors' overreaction to the company's recent dismal performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't believe Revlon is too highly leveraged, but the
investing public thinks so,'' said Howard Gittis, vice chairman and
chief operating officer of Perelman's holding company, MacAndrews &AMP;
Forbes. ``That is why we are considering selling. You can't keep
fighting the marketplace.''
</P>
<P>
   For most of the time since Perelman bought it in a leveraged
buyout in 1985, Revlon _ whose brands include the Almay, Ultima II
and Revlon lines of blush, lipstick and eye shadow _ seemed to be
the exception to his investment pattern.
</P>
<P>
   Revlon dominated the cosmetics and toiletry aisles in drugstores
and discount chains. And until the second half of last year it was
posting respectable financial results, which management still likes
to characterize as spectacular.
</P>
<P>
   But then came the unexpected _ disappointments in earnings and a
decline in sales. Profits from continuing operations tumbled 83
percent in the third quarter and continued to fall in the fourth,
to $6.5 million from $36.6 million in the corresponding quarter a
year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The company blamed its reversals of fortune on weakened consumer
buying power abroad and on inventory cutbacks in American
drugstores; it expects the latter to continue into the second half
of this year. At the same time, management faces formidable new
competition, even as Revlon sags under so much debt that analysts
say there is too little cash left for a makeover.
</P>
<P>
   The interest on Revlon's $1.7 billion in debt exceeded its
operating income last year. By contrast, interest payments consumed
just 9 percent of operating income at Procter &AMP; Gamble, which is
fast emerging as a key Revlon competitor, and 6 percent at Avon.
</P>
<P>
   ``A company with less debt is by definition somewhat more
flexible in their ability to spend,'' said Heather Hay, an analyst
at Merrill Lynch. ``The industry in general is one that tends to
need a lot of resources to really be able to fund the business and
grow.''
</P>
<P>
   Just three months ago, after Revlon took a $50 million charge
against earnings for restructuring, the company had to ask lenders
to ease up on some terms of its credit agreements.
</P>
<P>
   But in an interview last week, George Fellows, Revlon's chief
executive, said too much had been made of the balance-sheet issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other people may be concerned that our level of debt may seem
to impair our ability to perform, but I can absolutely assure you
that it doesn't,'' Fellows said. Revlon, he added, remains a leader
in research and development. He pointed to its Colorstay line of
long-lasting makeup and the success of its ``age-defying'' skin
products, and he predicted another hit in a line of lipstick using
new technology and due out in June.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the last five years, we have represented approximately 50
percent of the growth in the color cosmetics category in the mass
market,'' he said. ``I will be perfectly happy to let the results
of this company through this year, once we get by this difficult
period, speak for themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   But even if Revlon's immediate problems were not enough to
prompt Perelman to consider bailing out, another largely overlooked
factor is probably adding to the urgency: Unless he finds a quick
fix or moves on, he could lose half his shares in the company.
</P>
<P>
   The reason is that more debt is lurking in Perelman's complex
corporate swirl. He issued zero-coupon bonds in 1998 through Revlon
Worldwide, the cosmetics company's privately held parent, that come
due on March 15, 2001 _ bonds that are secured by 20 million of his
shares. When the bonds mature, holders will be owed $770 million.
</P>
<P>
   So, analysts say, Perelman faces a choice: If he wants to roll
over the bonds, he must begin to clean up Revlon to attract new
investors. If he wants to pay off the bonds, he must raise money to
come up with the cash _ by selling all or part of Revlon or some
other holding.
</P>
<P>
   (Perelman could also reap millions from a federal judge's
decision this month ordering the government to pay $908.9 million
to one of the California savings institutions in which he is a
controlling shareholder _ although that money is bound to be tied
up in lengthy appeals.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Given his empire's fairly leveraged status, the fact that the
business isn't getting any less competitive at this juncture and
that the zeros additionally loom on the horizon, it makes sense
that he would approach this process earlier, as opposed to the 11th
hour,'' said Stephen Weiss, a director in the corporate bond
research group of Salomon Smith Barney. ``He's got to come to grips
with how to address that.''
</P>
<P>
   But Gittis said that raising cash to pay off the bonds did not
figure into the company's desire to sell the business. ``We've had
zeros out against Revlon stock now since the early '90's,'' he
added. ``That has never been a problem for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, by Revlon's own admission, the market does not hold the
company in high regard these days. So any move to refinance the
zero-coupon issue could get a chilly reception, said Terrence
Dwyer, a fixed-income analyst with KDP Investment Advisors. ``No
investor is going to touch it, whether it's a public or private
deal, unless they are certain that the cash flow will be there,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, Perelman faces more immediate challenges with
Revlon. The company manufactured its products in too much abundance
last year, at a time when drugstore chains were consolidating, said
Allan Mottus, an industry consultant who publishes The
Informationist, a trade magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Mottus said, Revlon has not had a big hit since the
introduction in 1996 of the Colorstay products _ which competitors
copied quickly.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, rivals with much deeper pockets are squeezing
in on the already crowded shelf space in the drugstores and
discount chains where Revlon competes.
</P>
<P>
   Fellows says that competition is nothing new to Revlon and that
it can hold its own. Still, in direct threats to its Almay brand,
Procter &AMP; Gamble is rolling out Oil of Olay cosmetics in the United
States and Johnson &AMP; Johnson is adding makeup to its Neutrogena
line of face-cleansing products.
</P>
<P>
   So Perelman, in opening Revlon's doors to suitors even as
management struggles to fend off new competition, is hardly
operating from a position of strength, Mottus said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the competition knows the status of your company as well
as these people do, they can make adjustments and load up on brands
to take market share,'' Mottus said. ``They realize the company is
wounded.''
</P>
<P>
   Burdened by its heavy debts, analysts say, Revlon has not made
the kinds of investments that have enabled other large cosmetics
concerns to prosper.
</P>
<P>
   Estee Lauder, for example, has become a global juggernaut by
using its stock and cash to diversify not only its product lines
but also its distribution channels. While it once sold makeup
almost exclusively in department stores, Lauder now generates more
revenues through mass-market stores and boutiques.
</P>
<P>
   And while it was once seen as selling products that appealed
strictly to the well-to-do woman, it now owns the trendy Bobbi
Brown line; the Jane line, geared toward teen-agers, and Origins, a
brand intended to project a wholesome image.
</P>
<P>
   Fellows says focusing on the mass market remains a smart
strategy; he believes that it will continue to grow, drug-chain
mergers or not.
</P>
<P>
   Gittis dismissed as ``quite off the mark'' any criticism that
Revlon's management might not be adequately committed to investing
in the business.
</P>
<P>
   After remaining silent for weeks amid speculation that it was
about to be sold, Revlon announced early this month that it had
hired Goldman Sachs and Lazard Freres to explore its options. Two
companies mentioned as likely buyers are Unilever, the Dutch
consumer products giant, and L'Oreal, whose chief executive said
last week that it was, indeed, seeking acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   Revlon stock rose more than 60 percent in just two days on
anticipation that the company might be put up for sale _ and an
additional 18 percent when it confirmed the rumors. The shares
closed at $25.375 on Friday, 55 percent below the price a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the run-up, analysts say, Revlon's name alone would
command a premium in a sale. But the company's highly publicized
problems, they add, are sure to hurt in negotiations, with bidders
likely to think that Perelman is desperate.
</P>
<P>
   Gittis said, ``If Ronald doesn't get a premium price he won't
sell it.''
</P>
<P>
   One mutual fund manager said Revlon was regarded as ``one of the
blue-chip credits in the high-yield market'' two years ago, ``but
it literally crashed in the second half of 1998.'' The manager, who
recently dumped Revlon's bonds, spoke on condition of anonymity
because his firm has a policy of not commenting on holdings it has
shed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The company has some real fundamental problems,'' he said.
``You have to throw on top of that the proverbial Perelman wild
card, which is always an issue when you're investing in his
companies,'' he added, in a reference to Perelman's spotty history
as a corporate manager.
</P>
<P>
   As if his Revlon problems were not enough, Perelman also faces
daunting challenges with some other holdings.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, he tried to shed one headache by selling the
money-losing Coleman Co., a maker of camping gear, to the Sunbeam
Corp. for stock. But within months, that deal left him the
second-largest shareholder of a company in the midst of an
accounting and management nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   Sunbeam, it turned out, had exaggerated its earnings by tens of
millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the investment problems, Perelman is in the midst of a
divorce battle that is playing out in the tabloids and could soon
leave him in need of more cash. He and his third ex-wife, Patricia
Duff, are arguing over issues like bodyguards and their 4-year-old
daughter's nap time as well as basics of alimony, child support and
child custody.
</P>
<P>
   But assuming, as his confidants do, that holders of the
zero-coupon bonds won't end up with half his Revlon shares _ and
that he will sell only at a premium _ it seems clear that Perelman
won't take a powder on any deal. But with the shares selling at
roughly the same price as at their initial offering three years
ago, and steeply below their peak, public investors will be looking
for a buyer to give Revlon a face lift.
</P>
<P>
   Veteran Perelman watchers are familiar with such circumstances.
He took Consolidated Cigar public in 1996 at $23 a share, or more
than 14 times his purchase price. The company was sold late last
year for $17.85 a share after trend-chasers moved on.
</P>
<P>
   Perelman bought Marvel Entertainment Group for $82.5 million in
1989, putting up only $10 million of his own money and financing
the rest with debt. Two years later, he took the company public,
but the business eventually collapsed, and by December 1996 it had
filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection. Perelman, though,
walked away with a $50 million profit, largely from selling bonds.
</P>
<P>
   Revlon executives talk of selling ``dreams in a bottle.'' Revlon
investors can only hope to wake up from their nightmare.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
