<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARKS-HAZE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON WEIGHS PARK   AIR MEASURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT ALLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   On a clear day, Cadillac Mountain in Acadia National Park may be
the single best place to view the rugged Maine coast. From the
highest seaboard perch in the Northeast, visitors can see across
the wooded islands of Penobscot Bay to the gentle Camden Hills 40
miles off.
</P>
<P>
   But when summer winds blows from the southwest, the scenery
disappears behind a haze of air pollution carried from Midwestern
coal-burning plants and distant cities. On those days, even Blue
Hill, just 12 miles away, becomes a faint blur in the sulfate-laden
mist.
</P>
<P>
   Now, President Clinton is weighing a controversial new rule to
gradually restore the view at national parks from Acadia to the
Grand Canyon in Arizona. Spurred on by environmentalists who see
the chance for a victory over the coal industry, the administration
may announce a plan next week that would virtually ban air
pollution in parks within 60 years.
</P>
<P>
   Though the timetable is uncommonly generous, the rule would
force states to begin addressing park visibility during the next
decade. Just as important, it would hand environmental groups a new
tool in their broader attack on big coal-burning power plants from
Pennsylvania to Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think the rule is far too weak, but it sets a goal to get
the parks back to pristine air quality, not just manageable air
quality,'' said Armond Cohen of the Boston-based Clean Air Task
Force. ``People think they are going to Acadia or Shenandoah or the
Adirondacks to get away from the dirty air.''
</P>
<P>
   Utilities that own coal-burning plants insist that they, too,
want a grand view from Cadillac Mountain, but they complain that
the Clinton proposal may be too fast, adding to the already
substantial cost of meeting rules to reduce other kinds of air
pollution such as smog and acid rain.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's okay to have a national visibility program. The question
is, what are the requirements?'' said Paul Bailey of the Edison
Electric Institute, a utility trade group in Washington. ``We would
like to see a program that leaves it essentially up to the states
along with the other stakeholders'' to decide how quickly the
cleanup should occur.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the White House and the US Environmental Protection
Agency aren't commenting, but sources say the White House is
considering an announcement next Thursday, on Earth Day, either by
Vice President Al Gore or Clinton himself.
</P>
<P>
   In a sense, the battle over America's scenic vistas is the
unfinished business from a 1977 act of Congress that called for
``no manmade impairment'' of visibility in national parks. At the
time, landmarks such as the Grand Canyon and the Great Smoky
Mountains in Tennessee often had worse air than many cities due to
winds that carried pollution hundreds of miles from its source.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, federal and state regulators have clamped down on
various air pollutants, including some chemicals that reduce
visibility in national parks. Most importantly, national releases
of sulfur dioxide released from coal-burning and other activities
have dropped by almost 25 percent since 1990.
</P>
<P>
   But summertime visibility remains up to 80 percent less than it
was 50 years ago in some national parks. At Acadia, where average
visibility is up to 50 percent below what it once was, park
officials say they have seen some improvement in recent years, but
the poor visibility days are as bad as ever.
</P>
<P>
   The trouble, explains National Park Service biologist Bob Breen,
is that the air over Acadia is full of sulfates, chemicals related
to sulfur dioxide that are produced from coal-burning and other
combustion. The sulfates readily combine with the moisture in
summertime air to create haze, usually accompanied by high ozone
that makes breathing difficult.
</P>
<P>
   And almost none of the pollution comes from the little towns
around Acadia, said Breen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We get the bad days . . . when we have prevailing winds from .
. . many of the pollution sources of the upper Midwest and the
Eastern seaboard upwind of us,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The poignance of air pollution at national monuments has played
nicely into environmental groups' crusade against coal-burning,
especially older coal plants that are exempted from many federal
pollution requirements and equipped with tall smokestacks to
disperse pollution over a wide area.
</P>
<P>
   And both the electric utilities and the coal mining industry
have found it impossible to oppose the goal. ``It's apple pie and
motherhood,'' Bailey of the Edison Electric Institute said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   But clearing the air at the 156 far-flung parks entitled to
pristine visibility under the 1977 law requires a national attack
that could touch power plants and coal mines everywhere. As a
result, industry groups as well as coal power states pressed for
more time to meet the law, with some industry officials advocating
a 200 year cleanup timetable.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are talking about what period of time is reasonable to
reach that goal,'' said Bailey who, along with states such as
Virginia, prefers no fixed cleanup timetable at all.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, environmentalists say they, too, are settling for
less, since they preferred a faster 50-year cleanup schedule. But
the suffering is relative, they admit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sort of like you order up an ice cream sundae and you get
just the ice cream,'' said Bruce Hill, a scientist at the
Appalachian Mountain Club in New Hampshire.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
