<SLUG> BC-OCTUPLETS-SIDER-$ADV18-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FERTILITY TREATMENT RESULTS `HARD TO PREDICT' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (For release, Sunday, April 18, 1999) 
 
By LEIGH HOPPER 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ When Nkem Chukwu's babies were born, people asked: How
did this happen?
</P>
<P>
   Last week, a doctor from her fertility clinic offered the first
public insight into that question.
</P>
<P>
   The answer is, no one could have predicted Chukwu's conception
of octuplets. Fertility treatment is, at its best, an imprecise
science, but even at that, doctors believe Chukwu's ovaries
functioned in a highly unusual way.
</P>
<P>
   Chukwu was receiving fertility treatment at MacGregor Medical
Association in Houston when she became pregnant with eight babies.
Chukwu and her husband refuse to discuss details, and a MacGregor
spokeswoman says the family requested that the clinic not give out
any information about them.
</P>
<P>
   But a fertility specialist with MacGregor, Dr. Milton McNichol,
talked in general terms last week about the type of treatment
Chukwu received.
</P>
<P>
   Two hormones are used, the first administered daily, through an
injection to the muscles near the hip, to stimulate the development
of eggs on the ovaries. The second hormone causes the eggs to pop
off the ovary and enter the fallopian tube, where sperm can
fertilize them.
</P>
<P>
   McNichol said the effects of the first hormone are closely
followed for several days by testing levels of estrogen and viewing
the ovaries by ultrasound. Based on what doctors see, the hormone
dosage may vary. A patient who has no results at first may respond
vigorously to the next level of dosage the following month.
</P>
<P>
   Before patients get the second hormone, doctors discuss the
number of mature follicles, each of which contains an egg, that are
present on the ovaries. They counsel couples on the odds of
conceiving multiples _ or not conceiving at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some patients who might have five follicles and they
don't get pregnant. We counsel them, you have a 25 percent chance
of having twins, a 5 to 10 percent chance of having three or
more,'' McNichol said. ``Perhaps the most common outcome is to not
get pregnant.''
</P>
<P>
   If there is a high number of follicles present on the ovary,
patients can forgo the second hormone or abstain from sex. McNichol
said if a woman has four or more mature follicles on her ovary
``that's a danger flag,'' partly because there is a slight risk
that smaller, less-mature follicles also present on the ovary may
ovulate as well.
</P>
<P>
   But patients often choose to proceed.
</P>
<P>
   ``To put it in perspective, a patient spends $3,000 to $4,000 on
medication before that second dose,'' McNichol said. ``For a couple
that's had a long history of infertility and invested lots of money
and time to get to that stage, it's hard to make a clearly
objective decision.''
</P>
<P>
   In Nkem's case, McNichol believes the unforeseen ovulation of
immature follicles was what led to her conceiving octuplets.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's informed medicine,'' he said. ``But it is hard to
predict.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
