<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUNDAY-FINAL-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service will move the following
entertainment/arts articles this week for release Sunday, April 18,
1999. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT &AMP; ARTS (Moved in `e' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FEATURE stories &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AMERICAN-ART-CENTURY (Undated) _ Art-wise, was this really the
American century? We take the cliche for granted because, well,
because we are so arrogant. Never mind that its just a catch phrase
cooked up in 1941 by Henry Luce, the most thoroughly
unreconstructed of American chauvinists, partly out of missionary
zeal and partly to sell his magazine. The American Century is the
title of what looks to be an immense two-part survey at the Whitney
Museum of American Art, the first part of which, covering the years
1900 to 1950, will open Friday. It's one of several century-ending
extravaganzas (the Modern is planning another). And no doubt they
all, to some degree, will confront the cliche of American
predominance in visual art, deciding what it means and whether it
really makes sense. By Michael Kimmelman. (Moved). Photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FILM AND VIDEO &LR;
</P>
<P>
   60s-FILMS (Undated) _ A whiff of incense mixed with marijuana
smoke drifts through two recent movies, ``Hideous Kinky'' and ``A
Walk on the Moon,'' both of which conjure an era that Hollywood, in
its devotion to snugly happy endings, has largely avoided. By
Stephen Holden. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DANCE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   JUDSON-DANCE (New York) _ In the not too distant past it was my
good fortune to chance upon the performance of an arresting,
unconventional work. A luminous fabric comprising music both vocal
and instrumental, literary fragments from varied centuries and
civilizations, and everyday movement functioning as dance, it
projected an irresistible aura of good will and celebrated the
wonderful power of artistic persuasion. And, for the best of
reasons, it reminded me instantly of the Judson Dance Theater, that
whirlpool of restless creative spirits performing at Judson
Memorial Church at Washington Square in the 1960s. Now, 37 years
after they first began enjoying Judson's hospitality, a group of
those formerly young would-be creators, who found performance and
exhibition space when they needed it most, are expressing their
gratitude in ``No Limits _ A Celebration of Freedom and Art to
Benefit Judson Memorial Church.'' Some 75 dancers/choreographers,
poets, painters and sculptors are expected to participate in events
that began at the church last Friday and will run through this
Saturday. By Allen Hughes. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   NOBREGA-DANCE (Undated) _ Antonio Nobrega, a Brazilian performer
who will be making his United States debut at the Kennedy Center's
American Dance Festival April 27 through 29, trots out a variety of
characters in ``Figural,'' the one-man show he will use to greet
North American audiences. The figures he conjures, through mime,
dance, music and acrobatics, are not simply creatures of the
artist's fancy but a string of types meant as a showcase for
Brazil's culturally rich northeast. By Diana Jean Schemo. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THEATER &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CANBY-THEATER (Undated) _ Theater reviews of ``The Iceman
Cometh'' and ``The Weir.'' By Vincent Canby. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   THEATER-NIGHTCLUB (New York) _ Coaxing nightclubs from
legitimate theaters is not unheard of. Florenz Ziegfeld found room
for one in 1915 atop his New Amsterdam Theater on West 42d Street.
Throughout the life span of Ziegfeld's ``Follies,'' the New
Amsterdam roof was the toniest nightspot in New York. But Joe's Pub
on Lafayette Street, is a much less lofty enterprise, carved as it
is from ground-floor back-office space at the theater. The $2.35
million club is the result, in part, of a construction and
renovation grant to the Public from city capital funds that
includes refurbishment of the Delacorte Theater in Central Park.
There were some doubters when the Pub opened in October about
whether the Public Theater could make a theater-night life alliance
work. Six months later, according to George C. Wolfe, the producer
of the Public Theater, Joe's Pub ``is actually doing better than I
thought it would.'' By Barry Singer. (Moved). Photo.
</P>
<P>
   CIVIL-WAR-MUSICAL (Undated) _ A wall of cannons atop a grassy,
open slope. Forty thousand men killed or wounded in three days near
Gettysburg, Pa. It was the numbers that got to Frank Wildhorn, the
composer of ``The Civil War,'' the new Broadway musical opening on
Thursday at the St. James Theater. At a time when Broadway is
devoted to revivals of American classics _ both straight plays and
musicals _ and imports from London, Wildhorn is one of the few
composers creating musicals that are new, American and popular with
audiences. By Roxane Orgill. (Moved). Photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CLASSICAL MUSIC &LR;
</P>
<P>
   GOERNE-MUSIC (New York) _ The German baritone, Matthias Goerne,
along with his new recital partner, the Austrian pianist Alfred
Brendel, will present Schubert's ``Winterreise'' on Thursday
evening at Carnegie Hall. By Matthew Gurewitsch. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   HISTORIC-RELEASES (Undated) _ Anyone who gets anywhere near a
record store or catalogue knows that ``historic'' releases are
coming from every direction. Legitimate enterprises like Nimbus's
``Grand Piano'' series and Philips's giant new survey of the
century's best pianists compete with pirate tapes of murky
legitimacy. By Bernard Holland. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   BOOMER-COMPOSERS (Undated) _ Going to a contemporary-music
concert in the 1970s to hear new works by young Americans could
often be a discombobulating experience. The composers were
baby-boomers who had grown up with Motown, rhythm-and-blues and 60s
rock. Yet from some of the music they composed, you would have
thought that they had been living in gas-lit garrets in Vienna
during the 1920s, completely in thrall to the radical 12-tone works
of Schoenberg, Webern and Berg. By Anthony Tommasini. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ART &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NY-ARTISTS (New York) _ What defines a New York artist at the
end of the 20th century? The question surfaced with the
announcement that the works to be exhibited at the next Whitney
Biennial would be chosen by a team of art professionals who neither
work at the museum nor live in New York. Maxwell L. Anderson, the
museum's director, spoke of giving the show a ``national
perspective.'' After 25 years of having New Yorkers select the
show, it could be interesting to reverse the gaze, as theorists
might say, and see what non-New Yorkers come up with. By Roberta
Smith. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TELEVISION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BROADWAY-THEATER-ARCHIVE (New York) _ A venture called the
Broadway Theater Archive will digitize the vast video library of
Public Broadcasting System's WNET (local Channel 13), chronicling
some 40 years of the best of the American stage. WNET will
rebroadcast some of the productions as ``Treasures From the
Archive'' in a new series ``Stage on Screen,'' to begin next
Saturday. By Ralph Blumenthal. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   TV-WILL-AND-GRACE (Los Angeles) _ Last fall, when ``Will and
Grace'' had its premiere, television pundits took up column space
debating whether America was ready for a show about the sometimes
touching and always complicated intimacy between best-friend
roommates, one of whom is openly homosexual (Will) and the other, a
love-hungry heterosexual career gal (Debra Messing's Grace). But
viewers pronounced the discussion moot by declaring their love for
Sean Hayes's role as Jack McFarland. After three episodes, the NBC
promotions department decided to use Hayes's breakout status to
hype the show by broadcasting a 30-second Jack spot, complete with
a fever-pitch montage of Jack footage and a goofy Jack theme song.
By Margy Rochlin. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ANTIQUES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CHANDELIER-ANTIQUES (Undated) _ The Age of Reason was also the
Age of Reflection. Chandeliers dripped with cut-glass lusters,
moldings glimmered with gold leaf. Mirrors were placed behind
blazing candles and opposite sunny, full-length windows. And
surprisingly, at least some chimney pieces of the day were
literally architectural jewels, studded, paved and highlighted with
paste diamonds (in other words, rhinestones). ``There was such a
need to magnify the light candles gave out,'' said William Jay
Iselin, a former Christie's associate who now works with the
eminent Paris antiquary Ariane Dandois. ``Anything that could
refract light, to up the candle power, so to speak, was embraced.''
Recently exhibited at the Palm Beach International Art and Antiques
Fair, one of Iselin and Ms. Dandois's most spectacular finds is a
formally carved, rhinestone-studded chimney piece, circa 1790. The
chandelier, which is about 12 feet high and 14 feet wide, is for
sale at $95,000. By Mitchell Owens. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   BESTSELLERS (Undated) (Moved.)
</P>
<P>
   PAPERBACKS (Undated) (Moved.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TRAVEL (`t' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-CHINA-NANJING (Undated) _ China's Yangshan stone tablet:
A relic of imperial aspirations. By Nicholas D. Kristof. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-SHANGHAI (Undated) _ A vessel for China's treasuries. By
Seth Faison. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-CAMBODIA (Phnom Penh, Cambodia) _ Cambodia, now at peace,
hopes for tourists. By Seth Mydans. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   CYBER-TRAVEL (Undated) _ Going, Going ... bidding for bargains.
By L.R. Shannon. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
