<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NY-JURY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: A LIMIT ON JURY SEQUESTRATION  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Saturday, April 17: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A new study by New York's Office of Court Administration
provides ample justification for abandoning the state's foolish
policy of requiring the sequestration of deliberating jurors in all
trials involving violent crimes. That policy, ostensibly designed
to insure the integrity of criminal proceedings, requires that
jurors be housed overnight and guarded round the clock even in
low-profile cases where there is scant danger of outside pressure.
</P>
<P>
   The study finds that a temporary law approved by the state
Legislature four years ago to allow jurors in lower-level felony
cases to go home during deliberations has saved the state $3.5
million in security and lodging costs without producing any
increase in mistrials or allegations of jury-tampering. It has
spared more than 14,000 jurors and their families needless
inconvenience, broadened the pool of jurors available to serve, and
significantly reduced the impetus for juries to rush their
decisions by sundown to avoid being kept overnight.
</P>
<P>
   With the temporary law due to expire on June 30, state court
officials are urging the Legislature to enact a permanent change
that would give trial judges discretion to forgo sequestration of
juries in all criminal trials, except in death-penalty cases. The
state's chief administrative judge, Jonathan Lippman, estimates
this overdue change would affect about 1,000 cases each year and
save $2 million annually.
</P>
<P>
   The court officers' union, not surprisingly, cherishes the
overtime the current rules compel. But at a time when other parts
of the justice system are starving for resources, the Legislature
should not waste money just to please a special interest.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-16-99 2140EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
