<DOCNO> NYT19990416.0385 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-16 21:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2094 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-EMBRYO-MIXUP-NYT &LR;      04-16 1064
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-EMBRYO-MIXUP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTIGATORS SAY EMBRYOLOGIST KNEW HE ERRED IN EGG MIX-UP  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By JIM YARDLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the case of mixed-up embryos that caused a white
Staten Island woman who underwent in vitro fertilization to give
birth to two sons of different races, a state inquiry has concluded
that the embryologist knew another couple's embryos had been
implanted but failed to tell anyone at the time or to act to
correct his error.
</P>
<P>
   The embryologist, Michael Obasaju, could have told Dr. Lillian
D. Nash, the physician, to stop the procedure immediately. Instead,
investigators say, he prepared a second batch with the correct
embryos and handed them to Nash for implantation. He said he
remained quiet about his original error because the wrongly
implanted embryos were ``lower grade in quality'' and he did not
believe they would grow. But when the Staten Island woman became
pregnant a month later, Obasaju confessed the error to Nash, who
immediately informed the two couples involved, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Donna Fasano, who is white, gave birth to the
two boys, one white and one black. Since becoming public last
month, the case has reverberated through the field of assisted
reproductive technology, raising a host of ethical questions and
serving as a vivid reminder that mistakes, though rare, do happen.
</P>
<P>
   While state officials said Friday that ``the real error here''
was made by the embryologist, the report also found that numerous
procedural violations had taken place at the Manhattan clinic where
the mistake occurred, and it cited Nash for failing to properly
oversee Obasaju. The possibility of any punitive measures against
the clinic, IVF New York, or against Obasaju or Nash is uncertain;
the clinic remains open and must provide a written report to the
State Health Department by May 14, explaining what corrective
measures have been taken.
</P>
<P>
   Diane Mathis, a Health Department spokeswoman, said that
punitive action against Obasaju was unlikely because the state does
not license or certify embryologists. ``They are able to work as
embryologists based on their education, training and experience,''
Ms. Mathis said. She added, ``Our oversight was limited to the
facility where the error took place and the director of that
facility.'' Officials at IVF New York have told state investigators
that Obasaju will no longer be allowed to work there.
</P>
<P>
   The state report, obtained under the Freedom of Information Act,
is the latest development in a case that became public last month
after the black couple involved, Deborah Perry-Rogers and Robert
Rogers,, filed a lawsuit seeking custody of the black child. The
Rogerses have said that the embryos wrongly implanted in Mrs.
Fasano belong to them. The suit also accused Nash, Obasaju, the
clinic, and another physician, Dr. Dov B. Goldstein, of
malpractice, negligence and breach of contract.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, lawyers for the Fasanos announced that the couple
would raise their biological child and allow the Rogerses to raise
theirs if DNA tests proved they were his biological parents. David
Cohen, a lawyer representing the Fasanos, said Friday that the DNA
tests of the Rogerses were complete, but he would not release the
results.
</P>
<P>
   Rudolph Silas, the Rogerses' lawyer, was not in his office
Friday afternoon and did not return telephone calls. But Cohen said
that lawyers for both couples were negotiating a visitation
arrangement so the boys would grow up knowing each other.
</P>
<P>
   Nash did not return a telephone message left with her office
answering service and another left on her home answering machine.
Obasaju could not be located last night for comment.
</P>
<P>
   The state report traces the beginning of the case to April 21,
1998, when Nash retrieved ova, or eggs, from both Mrs. Fasano and
Mrs. Perry-Rogers at IVF New York, also known as Central Park
Medical Services. Nash told investigators that the scheduling of
two patients on the same day was ``unusual'' but ``coincidental.''
She retrieved seven eggs from Mrs. Fasano and 25 from Mrs.
Perry-Rogers.
</P>
<P>
   Obasaju, who like most embryologists has a doctorate but not a
medical degree, told investigators that he placed the eggs from the
two women in separate dishes. Each woman's eggs were inseminated
with sperm from her husband. Each woman's dish was labeled with her
name, and the dishes were placed in an incubator for three days.
The report said that Obasaju removed both dishes from the incubator
on April 24 and placed them on ``a hot plate'' so he could
determine which of the embryos had the best chance of successful
development.
</P>
<P>
   He then placed four of Mrs. Fasano's embryos into a different
culture dish. But the report said he divided Mrs. Perry-Rogers'
embryos into three dishes. Of the 25 eggs that had been taken from
her, 20 were fertilized: he placed six embryos for use later in the
day in one dish; he put 10 embryos to be frozen into a second dish,
and he placed four ``lower graded embryos'' into a third dish to be
discarded.
</P>
<P>
   He then placed all four dishes back on the hot plate. When Mrs.
Fasano arrived for her procedure, Obasaju told investigators, he
place the four lower-grade Rogers embryos ``by accident'' into the
catheter used by Nash.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Mathis said that if Obasaju had announced his mistake
immediately, ``there is some kind of procedure'' that might have
been used to wash out the embryos.''
</P>
<P>
   On May 20, after Nash learned that Mrs. Fasano was pregnant,
Obasaju admitted his error to her. Mrs. Perry-Rogers had undergone
the procedure with her own embryos, but she had not become
pregnant.
</P>
<P>
   State officials noted that Obasaju is not the clinic's regular
embryologist; he works only with Nash. The report said that the
clinic did have written operating procedures, but that Obasaju did
not follow them. The report also cited officials of IVF New York
and Nash for failing to insure that the procedures were followed.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Mathis noted that Goldstein was ``not implicated in the
actual error.'' Goldstein, who operates a different clinic, had
agreed to store the Rogerses' additional embryos. His lawyer, Luke
Pittoni, said that he would file a motion next week to have his
client removed as a defendant in the Rogerses' lawsuit and as a
defendant in a lawsuit that has since been filed by the Fasanos.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
