<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-UPDATE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOSOVO UPDATE 
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   COMBAT
</P>
<P>
   -- With the NATO air campaign against Yugoslavia in its fourth
week, the alliance claimed one of its most successful nights of
bombing, destroying tanks and artillery sites in Kosovo and hitting
key sites around Belgrade. NATO also struck military targets in
Montenegro.
</P>
<P>
   -- Albanian rebels in Kosovo captured a Yugoslav army officer
and turned him over to Albania, which then turned him over to U.S.
military officials in Albania.
</P>
<P>
   -- NATO again acknowledged accidentally hitting a civilian
vehicle in Kosovo on Wednesday, but said it could not account for
the apparent bombing deaths of other civilians in the same area.
Serb officials said at least 75 people died in another NATO strike
on a refugee convoy the same day.
</P>
<P>
   REFUGEES
</P>
<P>
   -- A new stream of Kosovo refugees poured into Macedonia, and
foreign observers said they seemed to be the victims of another
mass expulsion.
</P>
<P>
   -- The U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees accused Yugoslavia of
trying to expel the entire Albanian population from Kosovo. The
agency now estimates the total number of Kosovo Albanian refugees
who have been forced from the province since March 1998 at 671,700.
This compares with a pre-conflict Kosovo Albanian population of 1.8
million.
</P>
<P>
   OTHER DEVELOPMENTS
</P>
<P>
   -- Russia's opposition-dominated lower house of Parliament
approved a resolution to allow Yugoslavia to join the loose
Russia-Belarus union.
</P>
<P>
   -- The Kosovo Albanian leader Ibrahim Rugova met with President
Milan Milutinovic of Serbia and Deputy Prime Minister Nikola
Sainovic of Yugoslavia in Belgrade, Serbian media reported.
</P>
<P>
   -- The Red Cross sent an envoy to Belgrade to discuss several
issues including the status of three American soldiers held by
Yugoslavia since March 31.
</P>
<P>
   -- Foreign Secretary Robin Cook of Britain directed a senior
Foreign Office official to gather evidence of suspected war crimes
committed in Kosovo for the War Crimes Tribunal in The Hague.
</P>
<P>
   ON THE WEB
</P>
<P>
   Continuous coverage of the conflict in Yugoslavia is available
from The New York Times on the Web: http://www.nytimes.com  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
