<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLUMBUS GAME HOLDS MUCH IMPORT FOR GALDERISI 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH _ The Revolution have only once defeated the Columbus
Crew in regulation time in a meaningful MLS game. In the 30th game
of the 1997 season, Alberto Naveda converted the game-winner on a
move set up by Giuseppe Galderisi and Alexi Lalas as the Revolution
qualified for their only MLS playoff appearance.
</P>
<P>
   Only Galderisi remains with the Revolution, but in an unofficial
role as assistant to player-coach Walter Zenga. Clearly, Galderisi
wants to stay with the team, and several key players have offered
support both with public statements and through in-person appeals
to general manager Brian O'Donovan.
</P>
<P>
   But no decision will be made until after Saturday's game against
Columbus, the second in which Galderisi will coach from the bench
without a contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter what happens, I am happy and proud to be with this
team,'' Galderisi said Friday. ``It's just so great to be able to
work with young players who want to improve and learn. Players like
Joe-Max Moore, who hasn't won anything in this league, still has
the ambition to win. With attitudes like his, this team can go very
far.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the older players to the youngest, they have the same
hunger to win and to learn.''
</P>
<P>
   Galderisi appears to be an excellent foil for Zenga, whose
coaching experience only began last August. They communicate well,
and Galderisi is among the few coaches who both has inside
knowledge of the league and commands Zenga's respect. In fact,
Galderisi actually won more Serie A championships in Italy than
Zenga as a player.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the same mentality,'' Galderisi said of Zenga. ``We
work in the same way. We realized it in Massa Carrara last month,
the players and the coaches, we committed to working together.''
</P>
<P>
   Galderisi and O'Donovan began negotiating last month while the
team was training in Italy. This week, Galderisi has been in the
middle of Revolution preparations, and Zenga seems to be under less
pressure after delegating much authority to Galderisi.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, Zenga is sticking to his policy of not informing the team
of the starting lineup until 90 minutes before kickoff. His choices
have been simplified because of injuries, but there seems little
future in playing Brian Dunseth out of position at right back and
Mike Burns in midfield. Dunseth, a central defender, has struggled
in the role, and Burns is better suited for the right back
position. But the Revolution have experienced some success in the
last two matches, so Zenga might not make major changes.
</P>
<P>
   Edwin Gorter, slated to be the team's midfield leader since
being recruited from Holland last year by former coach Thomas
Rongen, has not filled the role on a consistent basis. But Gorter's
presence late in last week's game against D.C. United, which the
Revolution lost in the shootout after tying, 2-2, in regulation
time, was encouraging.
</P>
<P>
   The primary objective will be to defend against the Stern
John-Brian McBride striking combination. Zenga tried to acquire
McBride in the offseason, and said McBride ``is the best striker in
the league.'' But John has been the best scorer, with 28 goals in
27 MLS appearances.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to keep those two to zero or one goal to have a chance
to win,'' defender Dan Calichman said. ``We can't give them any
room. McBride will win 99.9 percent of any balls in the air and
Stern John can turn on you at any time.''
</P>
<P>
   Columbus had a 3-0 record and an 11-2 goal advantage over the
Revolution in the first three games last year, before the
Revolution took a 2-0 victory after having been eliminated from
playoff contention.
</P>
<P>
   ``They give everyone in the league trouble,'' Calichman said.
``They have talented players all over the field. Everyone around
the league views them as a difficult team to beat, one of the best
teams in the league.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
