<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-16 21:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2098 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-DIALLO-PROTEST-NYT     04-16 1199
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-DIALLO-PROTEST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: A BIG STEP FROM DIALLO POSTERS TO POLICE POLICY 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JODI WILGOREN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ To underscore the message of their march, 10
politicians and community leaders led thousands of people across
the Brooklyn Bridge on Thursday with special signs slung around
their necks, each highlighting a specific point in their proposal
for police reform.
</P>
<P>
   The only problem was, from even a few yards away, the placards
were impossible to read.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that poster board lends itself better to sharp slogans
than substantive suggestions is an apt symbol of the challenge
confronting the Rev. Al Sharpton and his partners in protest: how
to transform the passion that marked weeks of demonstrations since
the police shooting of Amadou Diallo into policies that will
actually have an impact.
</P>
<P>
   ``They achieved a goal of focusing in on their issues in a
manner that is acceptable to most New Yorkers,'' said Norman Adler,
a political consultant. ``Now the question is, where do they go
from here? If I were they, I would be spending my time figuring out
how to go to step two, and that is how to create an organization
committed to the 10-point goals, an organization with a staff, and
a board, and with a budget, and with some strategies for achieving
your goals.''
</P>
<P>
   It has been three weeks since black and Hispanic political
leaders met with the heads of the city's major labor unions and
civil liberties groups to draft the 10-point plan, which they hoped
would turn the outrage over an individual incident into a movement
for systemic change. But neither Mayor Rudolph Giuliani nor Police
Commissioner Howard Safir has publicly addressed any of the
proposals _ indeed, a top Police Department spokesman said Friday
afternoon that the commissioner had probably not even seen them _
and even keen observers of city politics are hard-pressed to cite
half the list.
</P>
<P>
   During his radio show Friday, Giuliani concentrated not on the
substance of the placards carried by the 10 march leaders, but on
the slogans touted by many at the back of the pack. Citing a poster
that showed a swastika across the insignia of the New York Police
Department and others that compared the mayor to Hitler and the
department to the Ku Klux Klan, Giuliani invoked David Duke to
denounce, again, the tone of the demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just consider for one moment if David Duke came to New York
City, assembled 4,000, 5,000 or 10,000 people, whatever the number
you want to say the march was, and in that march there were 10
people that had signs with hateful, racist and anti-Semitic
language attached to it,'' the mayor said. ``And suppose a group of
politicians participated in that march, spoke to a group that had
signs like that. I think this morning a lot of tough questions
would be asked of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharpton and former Mayor David Dinkins, who wore point No. 1
around his neck at Thursday's march, expressed outrage at the
comparison to Duke, the former Klan leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``What he's objecting to is what he's doing,'' Sharpton said.
``While he's being critical of signs that are excessive, he's being
excessive.''
</P>
<P>
   As the mayor exulted in the lower-than-expected turnout at the
march on Thursday _ organizers had predicted 25,000, and estimates
ranged from the official police tally of 4,500 to about 12,000 _
Sharpton and his colleagues celebrated what they said was the
largest-ever demonstration against police brutality and plotted
their next steps.
</P>
<P>
   There was talk about putting a referendum on the city ballot in
the fall to implement the police-reform plan, though probably only
one of the proposals, to reconstitute and fully fund the Civilian
Complaint Review Board, could be addressed through that process.
Plans are also afoot for a new umbrella civil rights organization
that would meet every other month and, among other things, draft
10-point plans for other city departments.
</P>
<P>
   Sharpton is headed to Riverside, Calif., on Saturday night to
protest a police shooting there, and he is organizing a national
tour for Diallo's mother, Katiadou, when she returns from Africa in
May. Separately, leaders of civil rights organizations across the
country plan to meet about police brutality in the coming weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as I'm concerned as an organizer, we got the debate
waving in this city,'' said Bill Lynch, who was deputy mayor under
Dinkins and helped organize Thursday's rally. ``It took nine years
from the time that Rosa Parks refused to go to the back of the bus
before an accommodations law was passed. With technology, we don't
have to be that patient, but this is a long fight.''
</P>
<P>
   But where Lynch and others see momentum, some analysts say the
nascent movement could be in danger of stalling, with no logical
place to go next.
</P>
<P>
   It will most likely be many months before the four officers who
were indicted in the Diallo case return to court. Many in the City
Council and the state Assembly are supportive of the coalition's
cause, but with Giuliani running City Hall and his fellow
Republicans controlling the statehouse and the state Senate, at
least 2 of the 10 points _ proposals for a city residency
requirement for police officers and a special prosecutor for police
brutality and corruption _ seem unlikely to pass.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the 10 proposals, such as an affirmative action policy,
sensitivity training and an end to the use of hollow-point bullets,
are in the hands of Safir and Giuliani, who show no signs of acting
on the recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes after the clarity of the initial moment, then things
do get a little more confused,'' said Lee Miringoff, a pollster who
has surveyed people's reactions about the Diallo killing. ``As this
works its way through the courts, it loses some of its initial
energy.''
</P>
<P>
   Some believe that Giuliani himself will become the focal point,
as demonstrations give way to a get-out-the-vote campaign to block
his likely bid for a United States Senate seat in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``What these people want more than anything else is to defeat
Rudy Giuliani in 2000 and thereby end his political career,'' said
Phil Friedman, a consultant who works for both Democrats and
Republicans. ``However much of a tragedy this is in human terms,
politically speaking it is in some part a game, where opportunity
has afforded itself to turn an unknown person into a martyr, to
turn a martyr into a movement, and to turn a movement into turnout
on Election Day.''
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, Thursday's crowd was reminiscent of the coalition
that elected Dinkins in 1989 _ and failed to re-elect him in 1993.
But the group is hardly ready to coalesce behind a candidate for
mayor in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Bronx Borough President Fernando Ferrer, a likely mayoral
candidate, wore point No. 7 _ raise police officers' salaries _
around his neck Thursday. Sharpton, who wore No. 8 _ end the
48-hour delay before department officials can question New York
officers involved in a shooting _ has not ruled out another run.
</P>
<P>
   And Public Advocate Mark Green, who has all but announced his
candidacy, did not get one of the 10 signs but was, nonetheless, in
the crowd, marching.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
