<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-STRAWBERRY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL WANTS STRAWBERRY TO TAKE DRUG TEST 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ In the aftermath of Darryl Strawberry's arrest
Wednesday night on charges of cocaine possession and solicitation
of prostitution, Major League Baseball has sought to administer a
drug test to the New York Yankees outfielder.
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry has been subject to regular testing by the league
since the mid-1990s _ he underwent drug treatment while with the
Dodgers in 1994 and was suspended by baseball while with the Giants
in 1995 _ and he provided the league with a urine sample the day
before his arrest. What was unclear Friday was whether the latest
test sought by baseball had been previously scheduled or was in
response to the arrest.
</P>
<P>
   Under the testing program, all samples are divided in half, and
if a test comes back positive, then the other half is tested to
confirm the results of the first batch. It is unclear whether
Strawberry _ who is in Florida, according to two baseball officials
_ was actually tested in the last two days, but a refusal to
provide a sample would violate the terms of baseball's after-care
program and place Strawberry at risk of immediate suspension.
</P>
<P>
   George Steinbrenner, the Yankees' principal owner, who may
ultimately determine whether Strawberry will be given another
chance to play in the major leagues, maintained his public silence
on the matter Friday for the second consecutive day. He did not
return a phone message, and the Yankees offered no statement on his
behalf.
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry, 37, was arrested in Tampa, Fla., on charges of
possession of 0.3 grams of cocaine and the solicitation of an
undercover police officer who was posing as a prostitute. He awaits
arraignment, which is likely to occur in the next two weeks, and
even if his drug test does not reveal the presence of cocaine,
Strawberry is now in a web of law and baseball rules that clearly
endangers his baseball career. Among the many complications he
faces:
</P>
<P>
   _ Possession of cocaine carries a maximum sentence of five
years, and solicitation of prostitution could lead to a 60-day
sentence. Strawberry has maintained his innocence on both charges,
indicating to the police that the drug, wrapped inside a $20 bill,
might have belonged to his wife's uncle _ an assertion denied by
the uncle, according to the police report filed in Strawberry's
case.
</P>
<P>
   If Strawberry's lawyers attempt to arrange a guilty plea on the
possession charge in return for a reduced sentence, the plea would
be viewed by Major League Baseball as a violation of his after-care
program; Strawberry would be subject to immediate suspension,
according to a baseball lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   _ Because the Yankees wanted to avoid paying a luxury tax for
Strawberry's contract, they gave him a $2.5 million minor league
deal that contained a morals clause; according to the terms of that
agreement, Strawberry had to meet specific standards of conduct.
</P>
<P>
   But Strawberry has been advised by the Players Association that
this clause is unenforceable in relation to drug issues, according
to a baseball lawyer, because the Yankees' contract is superseded
by the terms of his after-care program with Major League Baseball.
But if Strawberry tests positive, pleads guilty or is convicted of
possession, then he is subject to suspension _ and given that he
was suspended for 60 days in 1995, and that penalties for repeat
offenders have escalated in the past, it stands to reason he would
be suspended for at least half the season. Officials for Major
League Baseball were researching applicable precedents Friday.
</P>
<P>
   _ If Strawberry beats the cocaine-possession charge, or if the
charge is dropped, his career could still be at risk because of the
solicitation charge. Strawberry has a minor league contract with a
provision that the club can terminate the contract if the player
shall ``fail, refuse or neglect to conform players' personal
conduct to high standards of good citizenship and good
sportsmanship.''
</P>
<P>
   And in this instance, the conduct clause in Strawberry's
contract would not be superseded by the terms of the drug
after-care program.
</P>
<P>
   After his last suspension, Strawberry was considered untouchable
by clubs other than the Yankees. If he is suspended for half a
season, he will have almost no chance to play the rest of this
year, even if Steinbrenner brought him back, because he would have
to work his way back into shape. If he does not return in 1999, he
will be 38 years old next year, recovering from colon cancer,
moving on a bad knee and coming off a season in which he had a
total of 26 spring training at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   Don Zimmer, the Yankees' interim manager, said Friday that
Strawberry's status is on his mind. ``It's in all our thoughts,''
said Zimmer, before adding, ``Life's got to go on.''
</P>
<P>
   Zimmer spoke Thursday about Strawberry's presence in 1998:
``This guy was as good a man as I've been around the last two and a
half years. He treated everybody great. To have this happen, it
hurts.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul O'Neill said: ``It's shocking. I think a lot of people in
here are shocked. It's the kind of thing you don't want to judge
until all the facts are in.''
</P>
<P>
   Derek Jeter said: ``You don't want to believe it. You're
stunned, obviously. I still don't want to believe it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
