<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-16 21:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2103 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-NATO-ART-NYT &LR;      04-16 1158
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-NATO-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: NATO NOT UNIFIED IN GIVING OUT INFORMATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.) 
(rk) 
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium _ The confusion about whether NATO
accidentally bombed civilian refugees in Kosovo reflects both the
novelty of the first real air war the alliance has ever fought and
the determination of its American military commander to control
everything NATO says about airstrikes even while he runs the war.
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, the truth is obscured in the fog between the
security-obsessed NATO military command center in Mons and the
civilian diplomats and bureaucrats of NATO's endless corridors here
in Brussels, an hour away. Brussels and Mons, it turns out, do not
always speak with one voice.
</P>
<P>
   The military commanders generally believe that the less the
civilian world knows about the tactics, intended targets and
weapons of allied planes, the less able their Serb adversaries will
be to shoot them down. So they want to disclose as little as
possible about those things in the daily briefings at NATO
headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   But the diplomats have to ensure political support for the war
on the home front, which means they need public confidence that
NATO is being forthright about its war aims and honest about how
well allied forces are carrying them out.
</P>
<P>
   The most fundamental goal of NATO's bombing campaign is
protecting the ethnic Albanian population of Kosovo from murder,
rape, and expulsion by the Serb authorities who rule the province,
so the charge that allied bombs actually killed Albanian refugees
cuts to the very heart of the rationale for the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   But the alliance's inability to answer the charge Friday led to
some sharp exchanges Friday afternoon between reporters demanding
more information from the military and the civilian spokesmen for
NATO, Brig. Gen. Giuseppe Marani of Italy and Jamie P. Shea of
Britain, who devoted a far greater part of their briefing time to
parrying questions than to answering them.
</P>
<P>
   According to NATO officials, Gen. Wesley K. Clark has made
himself the only authoritative military source of information on
the bombing, in part because he has apparently barred subordinate
officers who plan and run the operation in Germany and Italy from
giving press interviews
</P>
<P>
   Stung by earlier criticism about the paucity of military
information on matters such as the number of strikes flown by
allied planes, Clark on Tuesday gave the most extensive public
briefing since the bombing began, the third one he has done
personally.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, he briefed NATO ambassadors in private on an air
attack that, in NATO's version, destroyed a civilian tractor
traveling with two other vehicles on a road north of the town of
Djakovica at about 3 p.m. Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   But there was confusion, both in public and in private, about
two other air attacks on the road between Djakovica and Prizren, in
southwestern Kosovo, that Serbian state television said had killed
scores of civilians the same day.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the other incidents, they believe all they hit was military
targets,'' a NATO diplomat said. ``They are investigating, but the
normal debriefing process can take 24 hours, and these guys are
trying to take advantage of good weather and bomb military targets,
not spend all their time explaining the one attack that went
wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   What actually happened on the road between Djakovica and Prizren
is important because Clark and his commanders have been saying
since the bombing started on March 24 that they were doing
everything humanly possible to avoid civilian target.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that over time, we will be able to establish the
truth on this. But it may take time,'' Shea said Friday. ``We are
not going to be blown off course by side issues.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, amid extensive accounts from reporters who were taken to
sites where civilians were killed, purportedly by NATO bombs, and
from refugees who have since crossed into Albania, the alliance has
acknowledged only that a civilian vehicle was struck north of
Djakovica.
</P>
<P>
   Even earlier NATO statements about the bombing are now
apparently inoperative. For example, a confirmation by the military
command in Mons Wednesday night that NATO warplanes had made
attacks south of Djakovica has been withdrawn. Shea and Marani
refused to say Friday that there had been any NATO attacks on the
Prizren-Djakovica road Wednesday. ``I do not accept any blame for
any other incident except the one north of Djakovica on which we
briefed you yesterday,'' Shea said.
</P>
<P>
   Marani said: ``What we know about our air attacks, we told you
yesterday.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the civilian and military spokesmen often brief together,
they tend to speak with separate voices.
</P>
<P>
   Shea, who works for NATO's civilian secretary-general, Javier
Solana, has often found himself without much to say about the
bombing, which is left to Clark's own spokesmen.
</P>
<P>
   The military, for its part, has been loath to give detailed
accounts of its bombing, especially since the Balkans have been
shrouded by clouds for much of the past four weeks, limiting the
effectiveness of the attacks on Serb ground forces.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps half the Serb air defenses have been destroyed, one
allied ambassador said this week, but the command has claimed only
about a dozen tanks so far.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, Shea and his military colleagues do not even seem to
be reading from the same script. Shea, for instance, started off
Thursday's briefing with bad news first, saying, ``NATO deeply
regrets the loss of life to civilians from the attack yesterday on
a convoy traveling between Prizren and Djakovica.''
</P>
<P>
   He then turned to Marani, who proceeded to give an extensive
explanation of an attack in a different place, one on three
vehicles north of Djakovica. That, he said, was the only one NATO
knew of in which civilians might have been killed.
</P>
<P>
   The confusing NATO performance baffled the Pentagon's spokesman,
Kenneth Bacon, as much as it puzzled reporters here. ``I cannot
explain the NATO rendition,'' Bacon said late Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Clark's spokesman said the allies were preparing to
blast Serb television to stop it from broadcasting propaganda, but
Shea said no they were not, unless television towers were connected
to the military communications network.
</P>
<P>
   In an indication that the alliance realizes that it may need
professional public relations help, British Prime Minister Tony
Blair's office said Friday that his spokesman, Alastair Campbell,
had been asked by Shea and Solana to spend a day looking at their
media operation here.
</P>
<P>
   One of the things they discussed, an announcement from 10
Downing Street said, was ``how to counter the obvious disadvantage
of waging a conflict of this kind when the enemy has total control
of his own media.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
