<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-16 21:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2104 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT     04-16 0861
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: UNDER ALL THAT HAIR IS GLIMPSE INTO THE FUTURE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Texas, La., Pa., N.Y.)   (jw) 
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Experts are calling Saturday's National Football League draft
revolutionary, largely because the sport's most exalted position _
quarterback _ appears to be undergoing a fundamental change.
</P>
<P>
   Most likely for the first time in 28 years, three quarterbacks
will be taken with the first three picks. More than that, for the
first time in NFL history three African-American quarterbacks _
Daunte Culpepper, Donovan McNabb and Akili Smith _ are expected to
be drafted in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't revolution, but evolution. The need for better
players at all positions has overtaken the need to preserve the
myth of white dominance and heroism embodied by the quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   The revolutionary aspect of the NFL's 64th draft involves an
emerging culture and a new generation of young players: They are
more independent, more unpredictable, more artistic and less
grateful than previous generations. The revolution is embodied by
Ricky Williams, the running back from the University of Texas. Some
say Williams is the best player in the draft.
</P>
<P>
   He won't be the first pick. Not because he's a running back, but
largely because he is different.
</P>
<P>
   In the staid, conservative world of professional football
decision makers, where military order and ritual reign, Williams
potentially represents a challenge far more reaching than black
quarterbacks. Williams won the 1998 Heisman Trophy. He is the most
productive running back in Division I history, a runner with
bruising size and speed. He also has the longest braids in Division
I, is one of the few players to have his tongue pierced and is one
of many who are covered with tattoos.
</P>
<P>
   Last January Williams fired Woolf &AMP; Associates, which had
represented him, and in February he signed with No Limit Sports
Management. No Limit was formed in 1997 by Master P, who turned a
rap career into a $200 million empire that features a record
company, No Limit. He founded No Limit Sports in 1997 and vowed to
challenge giants in the field.
</P>
<P>
   Musicians and athletes historically have shared the same
creative spaces; now that is being manifested in a business
affiliation. Williams reacted to meeting Master P like fans react
to meeting Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``He walks into my room, and my jaw just drops,'' Williams said.
``I was like, `Oh, my God.' I couldn't even talk. He's going
places. He's come from nowhere to get to the top, and I really
respect that. That's one of the reasons I want to be part of this
company.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams received warnings from various elements of the sports
establishment that he had better drop No Limit or the NFL power
structure would exclude him from the club. One writer, on national
television, warned Williams that his stock was dropping because he
supposedly showed up at a workout with a posse. In fact, he showed
up with his lawyer; his agent, Leland Hardy, and an accountant.
Williams had gained weight, the effect of his post-Heisman
celebrity. ``I told him to enjoy himself,'' Hardy said. ``You only
experience that once in your life.''
</P>
<P>
   Hardy designed a six-city, three-day tour, visiting teams that
held five of the first six picks. Williams met with owners and
general managers. They sat down and talked, broke bread. The
Saints' owner flew in from the owners' meetings to have dinner with
Williams and Hardy. Beneath the hair and tattoos they found an
engaging 21-year-old with insights. With a love of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Williams burned off the extra pounds, and in workouts he showed
that under the hair and the tattoos is an extraordinary runner. ``I
think he's a special player who comes out once in a while,'' Saints
Coach Mike Ditka said. ``Like Earl Campbell, Walter Payton. Like
Tony Dorsett. Those are special players. That's exactly what I see.
I think he's the big difference-maker right away.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Williams is not like Earl Campbell, who preceded him
at Texas. Campbell, in the typical, conservative
don't-rock-the-boat mode of old, warned Williams to get rid of the
accessories and cut his hair.
</P>
<P>
   ``I may be being foolish,'' Williams said last week, ``but it
seems like because I'm the way I am and I do things the way I want
to do them and I'm not really a conformist, that people don't want
to see me succeed sometimes.''
</P>
<P>
   Hardy, 37, who was a heavyweight boxer, completed his MBA at the
University of Pennsylvania's Wharton School of business and earned
a master's degree in international relations. He maintains an
office in Harlem. He speaks four languages.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to challenge,'' Hardy said, referring to taking on
the giant sports agents. ``They have inertia, they have a lot of
clients. But they also see the writing on the wall.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a mild revolution going on around the NFL. Black
quarterbacks are a small part of it, but Ricky Williams is the real
harbinger of change: change of perception, challenging executives
and coaches to look beneath the surface, beneath the skin. In this
case, beneath the braids.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
