</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SCHOOL-FRAUD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIGURE IN 20-YEAR SCHOOL FUNDING SCHEME JUSTIFIES IT 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JACQUES STEINBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The rabbi at the center of a scheme that funneled
millions of public school dollars from a Brooklyn district to a
Jewish girls' school said Friday that he knew dozens of Hasidic
housewives were collecting paychecks and insurance benefits for
no-show jobs, but that he justified the arrangement in his own mind
because he believed it benefited the children who attended his
school.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're right to say, `The end justifies the means,''' the
rabbi, Hertz Frankel, said Friday, in his first interview since
pleading guilty April 9 to one count of conspiracy in the 20-year
scheme.
</P>
<P>
   The rabbi's comments came as investigators, and the rabbi
himself, shed new light on how a criminal operation of such
magnitude had gone undetected for so many years.
</P>
<P>
   The investigators said that the arrangement had flourished with
no interference, in part because the officials of Community School
District 14 who engineered and maintained the scheme were able to
exploit the school system's decentralized bureaucracy with little
fear of getting caught.
</P>
<P>
   The central Board of Education's bookkeeping was so lax, the
investigators said, that there was little chance that a central
administrator would notice if the Williamsburg district used city
and state tax money to assign 30 extra security guards to the
district office who never showed up for work _ one of the main
ruses that the conspirators employed to divert paychecks to the
Beth Rachel School for Girls in Williamsburg, where the rabbi was a
principal.
</P>
<P>
   Though perhaps one-third of the $6 million siphoned to the
Jewish school was from the federal Title 1 program, which pays the
salaries of remedial teachers in public and private schools, the
investigators said that it would have been difficult for auditors
to uncover the misuse of that money. That is because the girls'
school, given its poor population, was entitled to much of it.
</P>
<P>
   But instead of using the federal money to pay its remedial
teachers, investigators said, the school often gathered the
paychecks in one pool for any number of uses, including the
purchase of equipment and books, and the hiring of secretaries. The
teachers entitled to the money, investigators said, were often
given only a fraction of their salaries.
</P>
<P>
   Though investigators have been unable to account for a large
portion of the money, in part because the checks were often cashed
at street-front check-cashing services, they have uncovered no
evidence that Frankel, 68, derived any personal benefit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real crime here,'' said one official familiar with the
scheme, which lasted from 1973 until 1994, ``is that every year the
district siphoned off all this money, before they decided whether
they were going to be able to rehire all their teachers or buy new
books. They said, `This is for Frankel.'''
</P>
<P>
   Echoing a statement issued on his behalf on Thursday, the day
the scheme was first revealed by the special commissioner of
investigation for the city schools, Frankel said Friday that he had
been led to believe that the scheme was legitimate by two men who
are no longer in a position to argue with him. They are the
district's longtime superintendent, William Rogers, and his
successor, Mario DeStefano; they died in 1993 and 1996,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Frankel said that Rogers had conceived the scheme because he
believed that Hasidic children should be entitled to public money
even if they attended parochial schools. ``It was easy on my
conscience,'' said the rabbi, 68, ``that the man in charge of this
program said, `Don't worry, Hertz' _ and he used to call me by my
first name _ `I am responsible. I direct you. I want to help these
children. I want them to get as much as they possibly can.'''
</P>
<P>
   Though it was unclear what benefit Rogers received in return for
his largess, he was re-elected superintendent over an exceptionally
long period _ 20 years _ with the support of a critical, Hasidic
bloc on the community school board. Though Frankel denied holding
any sway over the members of the board, he acknowledged that he
played an important political role in the Satmar community. It was
he, for example, who arranged visits for the grand rabbi with
everyone from presidents to governors to mayors. And it was he who
did the translating.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how he could justify that dozens of women _ some of them
with 10 children each _ were able to enjoy health insurance
benefits for jobs they did not do, the rabbi said it was easy.
Though those women kept their benefits, they gave up their
paychecks to teachers at the school who had no benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``So it balanced,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
