u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TAX-PATAKI-NYT &LR;      04-16 0581
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAX-PATAKI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATAKIS RELEASE TAX RETURNS, REPORTING INCOME OF $246,417  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ore.)   By CLIFFORD J. LEVY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Gov. George Pataki and his wife, Libby, reported
income of $246,417 last year, a sharp drop from the previous year,
but the tax returns they released Friday also showed that Mrs.
Pataki has begun a new job in which she is paid to give speeches on
behalf of a medical products company, with a salary of $90,000 a
year.
</P>
<P>
   In New Jersey, Gov. Christie Whitman announced that she and her
husband, John, earned $1.4 million in federally taxable income last
year. As they have in the past, they filed for a four-month
extension to complete their tax forms, saying that they would make
a full disclosure in August.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki has suggested in the past that his family has difficulty
living on only his state salary, which in January rose to $179,000
from $130,000, and as a result, he gives speeches for fees of at
least $15,000 each. Last year, he earned $50,000 for three speeches
and $24,000 more for his autobiography.
</P>
<P>
   While the speeches have drawn criticism, Mrs. Pataki's
employment has also attracted scrutiny, and now, she, too, will be
paid to deliver speeches. In her new job as a consultant with an
Oregon-based company, Premier Heart, she will speak to groups about
being vigilant against heart disease, while promoting the company's
new testing device.
</P>
<P>
   This is not Mrs. Pataki's first foray into health education.
Since the governor took office, she has often talked publicly about
fighting breast cancer. Those speeches were not for fees.
</P>
<P>
   The work for Premier Heart is Mrs. Pataki's second consulting
job. In Pataki's first term, Ronald Lauder, the cosmetics heir and
benefactor to conservative causes, hired her to advise him on
expanding his television broadcasting business in the Middle East.
The governor's aides have said Mrs. Pataki has experience in
international business and family ties in Morocco. Lauder paid her
$80,000 last year, according to the returns.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Pataki's hiring by Premier Heart was arranged by a college
friend of the governor, Richard Hayden, who is a principal in
Premier Heart. Michael McKeon, a spokesman for the Patakis, said
Mrs. Pataki did not have experience in the medical field but was
hired for her marketing expertise.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is going to be helping to market whatever product it is
that they produce,'' McKeon said, adding that Mrs. Pataki would
have no contact with state government in her work.
</P>
<P>
   Hayden said in a telephone interview that he helped found
Premier Heart last year to market a diagnostic device called the
Cardiotron, which is similar to a sophisticated electrocardiogram.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were trying to figure out how to promote the product,''
Hayden said. ``Libby had done a lot of speaking on breast cancer,
quite effectively I thought, and we said wouldn't it be great to be
able to promote the fight against heart disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want her to do a heavy sell, but we are not going to
avoid mentioning the product.''
</P>
<P>
   He said Mrs. Pataki had no plans to speak on behalf of the
company in New York, but he would not rule it out. The governor's
aides, though, said she would not give such speeches in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The Patakis' income of $246,417 in 1998 was down from $337,455
in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The couple paid nearly $70,000 in taxes last year, and also took
a loss of $60,722 on real estate transactions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-16-99 2202EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
