<DOCNO> NYT19990416.0398 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-16 22:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2115 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-NFL-DRAFT-NYT &LR;      04-16 0745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFL-DRAFT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COUCH TO BROWNS IS LIKELY, BUT THE REST OF THE NFL DRAFT IS UP IN
THE AIR
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By MIKE FREEMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When quarterback Tim Couch worked out with the Cleveland Browns
for a second time last week, his passes had more zip and his step
had an extra bounce. The Browns' management saw enough to feel
comfortable with the fact that Couch could lead their team for the
next 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   But while it seems 90 percent certain that the Browns will take
Couch with the first pick in Saturday's NFL draft, all kinds of
machinations could affect their choice, including their contract
negotiations with Couch's agent, Tom Condon. If there are no snags,
Couch will most likely be a Brown.
</P>
<P>
   After that, all bets are off.
</P>
<P>
   Which players will go where depends on whom you talk to and
when. Last month, the draft order looked like this: Couch as the
No. 1 pick, then running back Ricky Williams to Philadelphia,
quarterback Akili Smith to Cincinnati, linebacker Chris Claiborne
to Indianapolis and cornerback Champ Bailey to Washington.
</P>
<P>
   A week ago, that completely changed, with the Browns talking
about Smith and Williams as candidates for the top spot. And
Friday, one top league executive had the first five picks as Couch,
quarterback Daunte Culpepper, Smith, Williams and Bailey.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, put on your seat belts, it's going to be a bumpy
draft.
</P>
<P>
   Expect a number of trades throughout the two days of the draft,
including several high-profile ones in the first round. While it is
hard this time of year to figure out what teams are really trying
to do _ they tell each other all kinds of lies _ several themes
were still developing late Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The New Orleans Saints continued to try to move from the 12th
spot overall into the top four to get Williams. The Saints are
offering all of their picks from this year's draft, plus several
next year and players off their roster. So far, they have not had
any takers.
</P>
<P>
   The Dallas Cowboys might lose Leon Lett, their star defensive
lineman, to a drug suspension, so they are almost certain to take a
defensive lineman with their pick, the 22nd. They want North
Carolina's Ebenezer Ekuban, a 6-foot-3-inch, 281-pound player who
is probably the most athletic defensive lineman in the draft. The
Cowboys are so enamored with Ekuban that they have had a
representative at his house recently, trying to negotiate a
contract.
</P>
<P>
   The Green Bay Packers, as they did last year, are trying to move
up from the 25th spot and have been talking with Seattle, which
picks 17th. Ron Wolf, the Packers' general manager, is one of the
best personnel men in the league and likes adventures on draft day.
If he does trade with Seattle, Wolf wants either a cornerback like
Antwan Edwards of Clemson or a defensive lineman.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Culpepper's stock has increased dramatically in the last
48 hours. Baltimore, picking 10th, likes him. Also, the Raiders
want Culpepper but do not think he will be around at No. 18 when
they select. If he is not, they are comfortable with UCLA
quarterback Cade McNown.
</P>
<P>
   And the most sure pick in the draft? Bailey, from Georgia, who
is considered one of the most versatile players in college football
history. He can play wide receiver, return kicks or fly the space
shuttle.
</P>
<P>
   Teams believe Bailey is the one player in the draft who is a
lock to succeed. ``Our scouts tell us the safest player on our
board is Champ Bailey,'' said Carmen Policy, president of the
Browns. ``They say he's an impact player who is going to contribute
right from the beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   ``So if we were going to go the absolute safest route,'' Policy
added, ``that's the player to take.''
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco 49ers' draft is being run by Bill Walsh, who
wants a quarterback in the first round. Yet he seems to be ignoring
the fact that the 49ers desperately need defensive players. They
may address that need in rounds three through five.
</P>
<P>
   The draft remains strong in terms of offensive linemen, with one
general manager saying a team can get a solid one through the third
round. The executive also said that talented defensive linemen go
only about five deep, that the linebackers over all have excellent
speed, and there is not a lot of depth at cornerback but there is
at wide receiver.
</P>
<P>
   Every year, the draft is interesting, because there are always a
number of surprises. This draft will have likely have its share _
and then some. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-16-99 2203EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
