<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-NOTES17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    McReynolds bids to buy Rudd team
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARTINSVILLE, Va. _ Larry McReynolds, crew chief for driver Mike
Skinner, submitted a bid to buy the Winston Cup team of veteran
Ricky Rudd.
</P>
<P>
   Rudd, a 25-year veteran and one of only four drivers on the Cup
circuit who owns his own team, is looking to make changes to the
struggling Tide-sponsored No. 10 Ford.
</P>
<P>
   Various media outlets reported that CART owner Chip Ganassi is
interested in buying the team, but Rudd denied those reports.
</P>
<P>
   Rudd, 42, says he might not sell the team altogether. In fact,
he says he may add a partner, which would allow him to add a second
car and become more competitive.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we could take in the right partner to make the team
stronger and better, and help me with the business side to expand,
that would be great,'' he said. ``We definitely need to be looking
at going with a multi-car team, whether it's now or next year. But
it's gonna take more than me handling that because it's become big
business.''
</P>
<P>
   McReynolds, who plans on leaving Richard Childress Racing after
this season to form his own team, says his offer to Rudd may not be
enough.
</P>
<P>
   Rudd is 35th in points going into Sunday's Goody's Body Pain
500. He entered this year with at least one victory in each of the
last 16 seasons. Around the track
</P>
<P>
   Darrell Waltrip qualified on speed for the third race in a row,
posting the 25th-best average speed at 94.153 mph. ... James Ince
resigned as crew chief for the No. 16 Ford team, citing
``philosophical differences'' with Roush Racing management and
driver Kevin Lepage. Ince was replace by Tommy Morgan, crew chief
for Jeff Burton's Busch team.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
