<HEADER>
A2119 &Cx1f; tad-z
u r &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-NASCAR-POLE17-COX     04-16 0525
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-POLE17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rookie Stewart first in fast field
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARTINSVILLE, Va. _ Rookie Tony Stewart raised quite a stir in
the first seven races of the Winston Cup season. He started on the
front row of his first Daytona 500 in February, and then posted
consecutive sixth-place finishes at Darlington and Texas last
month.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Stewart captured his first pole by breaking the track
record in first-round qualifying for Sunday's Goody's Body Pain 500
at Martinsville Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, whose No. 20 Pontiac was the 45th of 46 cars to run,
covered the .526-mile oval in 19.875 seconds, an average speed of
95.275 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, 27, was one of 24 drivers who broke Martinsville's
qualifying record of 94.129 mph, set by Ted Musgrave in September
1994. Stewart's speed also dismantled an all-Roush Racing front row
of Mark Martin and Jeff Burton, who will start second and third,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, a former champion in midgets and sprint cars from
Columbus, Ind., says he was even surprised by his fifth top-10
qualifying effort of the season. Less than two weeks ago, he
struggled in testing at Martinsville.
</P>
<P>
   ``I woke up (Friday) morning and really didn't want to get out
of bed,'' he said. ``On the other hand, I thought this was going to
be a true test of how my season is going to be. This is the first
place where I've really, really struggled in testing. I was really
dejected when I left. ... I thought for sure we'd be a second-round
qualifier and have to fight to get in the race.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Stewart will be trying for his first Winston Cup
victory. There have been only two Winston Cup rookies to win races
at Martinsville _ Earl Rossin 1974 and Morgan Sheppard in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   Burton, who earned his third top-5 start of the season, says he
won't be shocked if Stewart becomes the third.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was running against him in the Busch series, I was
really impressed by his ability,'' Burton said. ``Tony's going to
be a guy that we're going to have to race for a long time....
They're just doing a great job. They're a rookie team and they've
taken advantage of the tests that they've gotten. They deserve
every bit of credit that they get.''
</P>
<P>
   And Stewart is getting plenty of notice, including comparisons
to NASCAR's last phenomenal rookie, two-time defending Winston Cup
champion Jeff Gordon, who broke into the circuit full-time in 1993.
Gordon's average finish in his first seven races was 17th;
Stewart's was 16th.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, who has obviously benefited from driving for
established owner Joe Gibbs, as well as the steadying influence of
teammate Bobby Labonte, says he isn't ready to get ahead of
himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``The two goals we set at the beginning of the season are the
same ones we're going to carry all the way through the end of the
year,'' Stewart said. ``That's just to qualify in the first round
and get in the top 25 each week, and then try to finish as many
laps as we can on race day. Anything more than that was going to be
a bonus.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
