<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-16 22:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2123 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-DRAFT-FALCONS17-C     04-16 0530
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-DRAFT-FALCONS17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Two picks for Reeves on first day
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The start of today's NFL draft will look boring to
Falcons fans. Atlanta doesn't pick until 30th, some four or five
hours into in the first round. The Falcons will have just two picks
today, the next coming third-from-last in the third round _ about
10 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   No one is speculating that the Falcons will trade for a better
pick. When a team has traded away its second-round pick, gone last
year for wide receiver Tony Martin, and when its third-round pick
is so late, it doesn't have much to barter with _ unless it wants
to send a veteran packing.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're at the level we're at,'' coach Dan Reeves said,
``nobody wants to help you out.'' So don't be shocked if Atlanta
trades back to pick up later picks, especially if the Falcons can't
land a quality defensive end in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   Nineteen of 22 starters return from last year's team, and the
three other spots are all but spoken for, by newly acquired strong
safety Marty Carter and wide receiver Chris Calloway and by last
year's No. 1 draft choice, linebacker Keith Brooking.
</P>
<P>
   But 14 projected starters have contracts scheduled to expire
after next season. Ten are to become unrestricted free agents, and
three will become restricted free agents.
</P>
<P>
   Of particular concern is defensive end, the one position that
could force the Falcons to try to trade for a better choice. Only
starters Chuck Smith and Lester Archambeau have played in an NFL
game, and both have contracts that expire after next season.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta likes defensive ends Jevon Kearse of Florida, Virginia's
Patrick Kerney, Saginaw Valley State's Lamar King, and perhaps
Florida State's Tony Bryant.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we've got a defensive end we like, and there are three
teams we think are going to take a defensive end,'' Reeves said,
``we might get on the phone and try to trade picks with a team.''
</P>
<P>
   Three of the four teams immediately in front of the Falcons _
No. 26 Jacksonville, No. 27 San Francisco, and No. 29 Minnesota _
seem to be interested in defensive ends.
</P>
<P>
   Another NFC team might be reluctant to trade with the defending
conference champions. That would leave Buffalo at No. 23. The Bills
are interested in a cornerback, and there could be at least two
first-round caliber corners available at No. 30.
</P>
<P>
   If Atlanta stands pat, and those ends and defensive tackles
Anthony McFarland of LSU and Reggie McGrew of Florida all are gone,
the Falcons probably would select the best player available from
among cornerbacks Antoine Winfield, Fernando Bryant and Fred
Vinson, wide receivers Kevin Johnson, Troy Edwards and Peerless
Price and Georgia tackle Matt Stinchcomb. Syracuse fullback Rob
Konrad is a longshot.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons also have labeled 10-15 players as ``can't miss,''
and team officials expect them to go quickly. But if one of them
slips to No. 30, Reeves said Atlanta would choose him regardless of
position.
</P>
<P>
   Another possibility is that Atlanta would trade back into the
second round.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
