</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-DRAFT-NOTES17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Browns trying to sign Couch for right price
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The process that should culminate with the Cleveland
Browns taking Kentucky quarterback Tim Couch with the first choice
in today's draft began in earnest Friday afternoon. After days of
talking by telephone, agent Tom Condon and Cleveland salary-cap
expert Lal Heneghan initiated face-to-face negotiations aimed at
reaching a deal before the start of the draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``The truth is, this shouldn't be that hard,'' Condon said.
``But, hey, you never know.''
</P>
<P>
   It could be a negotiation rife with intrigue. Condon negotiated
a landmark contract last year for Peyton Manning and has hinted he
wants a deal that is about 8 percent more _ the increase of the
rookie pool over 1998 _ than the six-year, $38 million Manning got.
The Browns want to hold the line on the contract, and their
posturing the past few days indicates they will try to squeeze
Condon a bit.
</P>
<P>
   There also is talk that agent Leigh Steinberg, who represents
Oregon quarterback Akili Smith, is willing to undercut Condon's
figures in an attempt to persuade the Browns that his client should
be the first choice. Steinberg said Friday evening that there had
been no negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, there is the matter of Condon and Carmen Policy, the
Browns' team president. Condon works for Cleveland-based IMG, the
sports and entertainment giant that Policy thinks was heavy-handed
in its failed attempts to land the franchise's marketing deals.
Some club officials feel IMG was the source of a misinformation
campaign aimed at discrediting Smith's credentials.
</P>
<P>
   Falling star
</P>
<P>
   The NFL is prohibited from publicly discussing players under
scrutiny, but officials did privately confirm they are reviewing
the results of a positive drug test by Dallas defensive tackle Leon
Lett. Friday morning, Cowboys owner Jerry Jones informed his
coaching staff that Lett's availability for 1999 is uncertain. That
could dramatically alter the team's strategy in the first round.
Cowboys coach Chan Gailey had hoped Louisiana Tech wide receiver
Troy Edwards might fall to him at the 22nd spot. If Lett is
sanctioned, however, Dallas might be forced to look to a player
like Florida defensive tackle Reggie McGrew. The club is attempting
to trade up for a shot at LSU defensive tackle Anthony McFarland.
Lett has been suspended twice for violating the NFL's drug-abuse
policy. He could be suspended for a year if the recent test is
upheld.
</P>
<P>
   Maneuvering
</P>
<P>
   New England offered wide receiver Terry Glenn as part of a
package to St. Louis, hoping to get into position to select Miami
tailback Edgerrin James. ... Bengals coach Bruce Coslet would
prefer to trade out of the third spot, fall back and select UCLA
quarterback Cade McNown. But owner Mike Brown wants to stay put and
take Akili Smith. ... Detroit coach Bobby Ross is trying to
persuade Lions management to sign defensive end Marco Coleman,
which could affect the club's draft plans. ... The Saints made an
offer to Philadelphia that had Eagles officials thinking about
trading down from the No. 2 spot. It's believed the Saints included
defensive end Joe Johnson in the package. ... Rams officials still
aren't settled on whether they'll take North Carolina State wideout
Torry Holt or Arizona corner Chris McAlister with the sixth pick.
... Miami coach Jimmy Johnson was trying hard to move into the top
six picks. If he can't move up, Johnson wants to trade out of the
first round and draft McNeese State tailback Cecil Collins in the
second. ... Don't be surprised if the Falcons select Notre Dame
offensive lineman Mike Rosenthal in the third round. ... St. Louis
hopes to trade quarterback Tony Banks today to Dallas, Washington
or Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   Super sleepers
</P>
<P>
   Some players that fans don't know, but who could be off the
board by the end of today's action: DE/LB Joey Porter (Colorado
State), CB Anthony Parker (Weber State), DE Chike Okeafor (Purdue),
DT Cletidus Hunt (Kentucky State), OG Tony Coats (Washington), RB
Joe Montgomery (Ohio State), OG Randy Thomas (Mississippi State),
DE Roderick Coleman (East Carolina), WR Darnell McDonald (Kansas
State).
</P>
<P>
   The last word(s)
</P>
<P>
   Akili Smith on the workout the Browns had with Couch on Sunday,
a session in which the Kentucky star impressed Cleveland coach
Chris Palmer enough to secure the No. 1 spot: ``It was like they
said, `OK, we're going to give you a second chance at this.' Hey,
if they'd given me the chance to throw for Carmen Policy and
(owner) Al Lerner, I would have put on a show they'd never forget.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
