<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Get an eraser: Draft scenarios change rapidly
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Call Leland Hardy, the agent for Heisman Trophy
tailback Ricky Williams, and his answering machine greets you in
three languages.
</P>
<P>
   Given the uncertainty about today's NFL draft, such an eclectic
approach probably is appropriate. The final draft of the '90s is
shaping up as one in which pre-draft impressions probably won't be
lasting ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can do all the planning and be as diligent as possible
and, in a draft like this one, it might not matter,'' Tampa Bay
coach Tony Dungy said. ``There are going to be a lot of trades
evolving, and you're going to have to react and be able to think on
your feet. What seems to be happening one minute could be the
opposite a minute later. You'll just have to trust your judgment
and instincts.''
</P>
<P>
   The first half-dozen selections appear set: For the first time
since 1971, the first three choices will be quarterbacks. But
little is settled after that.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the confusion is that a few teams hope to maneuver up
toward the top, more wish to move down, and, typically, Miami coach
Jimmy Johnson is prepared to do both. By the time the first round
ends tonight, the NFL will have worn down plenty of erasers.
</P>
<P>
   Taking a cue from Johnson, some general managers, such as Ron
Wolf of Green Bay, placed more emphasis this spring on assigning
very specific values on prospects. Those teams know in what round,
and what portion of that round, they want to get a player. Because
this year's draft is viewed as average in most areas, teams want to
avoid reaching for a player and taking him at a spot higher than
his rating on their draft board.
</P>
<P>
   ``More than ever, you pay for your mistakes,'' Cincinnati owner
Mike Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, the quarterbacks will grab the spotlight
today. Only four times since 1970 have more than two quarterbacks
gone in the first round. Five likely will go today, the most since
the six of the celebrated Class of '83.
</P>
<P>
   Just as notable is that three of the quarterbacks are black,
equaling the highest number of African-American quarterbacks in the
first round.
</P>
<P>
   However, the offensive linemen are the ones lending depth to
this draft. Nine blockers are included in The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution's top 50 players, and 10 to 12 linemen could
be selected in the first two rounds.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
