<SLUG> BC-URBAN-WARGAMES17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Army `black helicopter' training goes boom in the night
 &HT;    By Dave Harmon
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The black helicopters, and the specially-trained
U.S. Army troops they dropped across South Texas for 10 days in
February, are gone now.
</P>
<P>
   In their wake, they left a trail of tales that will be told,
retold, and embellished for years _ the soldiers rappelling into
cities, the explosions, the accidental fire, the satchel full of
cash to pay for damages. And they ignited a new round of buzz among
those who consider the helicopters symbols of government oppression
or a coming one-world order.
</P>
<P>
   The Army Special Operations Command's training exercises _
dubbed Operation Last Dance _ were the latest in a 10-year effort
to give the United States' elite troops real-world experience in
different urban environments. And in town after town, local leaders
remain divided over whether they would invite the soldiers back for
an encore.
</P>
<P>
   In Alice, Police Chief Jack Compton said he would be honored to
see the units return.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was a damn well-run operation,'' Compton said of
the Feb. 12 exercise at a former poultry plant. ``For some of the
folks living in the area it was a big event. They sat on their
porches (to watch) and had a grand old time.''
</P>
<P>
   In Kingsville, Tomas Sanchez, head of Kleburg County's emergency
management office, said he and other county officials weren't
notified of the Feb. 8 operation _ city officials were _ and that
he would try to stop any future exercises.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you see a bunch of helicopters coming and a bunch of men
rappelling with no markings on their uniforms, and bang-bang,
boom-boom, you get a little concerned,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As much as a year before, Army representatives had quietly
approached officials in a number of Texas cities, seeking
permission to stage training missions in abandoned buildings. There
would be helicopters and explosions and small-arms fire, they said,
but the grenades would be weaker versions of the real thing, the
bullets would be plastic, and buildings would be prepared
beforehand to protect people and property.
</P>
<P>
   At Fort Bragg, N.C., home of the Special Operations Command, the
exercises are an essential part of training the Army's elite
forces, which number 27,000 active and reserve members, said
spokesman Walter Sokalski. Since the late 1980s, Sokalski said,
they have used populated areas to stage missions that serve as a
final exam for the soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   The initial homework takes place at bases around the country,
where soldiers practice in buildings erected to simulate an urban
environment, Sokalski said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then we move to a real-world environment where you have things
like telephone lines and different lighting, to see if they've
learned the skills they need to learn,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas exercises involved 65 soldiers and support personnel,
said Maj. Jeff Fanto, spokesman for the U.S. Special Operations
Command at Fort MacDill, Fla., headquarters for the nation's elite
military units. He said he knows of no civilian injuries or deaths
during an urban special operations exercise. Jamming 911 lines
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 8 in Kingsville, a city of 27,000 near Corpus Christi,
eight helicopters hovered over several downtown buildings in the
evening as local police cordoned off a three-block area. Dark-clad
soldiers with night-vision goggles slid down ropes, then muffled
booms and shots erupted inside the old Exxon building and the
former police headquarters. The blasts blew out windows at the
Exxon building, despite the plywood tacked up to contain damage.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor recessed a city meeting so local officials could
watch. But it looked all too real to those nearby residents who
hadn't been notified of the exercise _ including many who lived in
the Casa Ricardo retirement home across the street. Callers lit up
the 911 lines.
</P>
<P>
   Then a mishap. According to Kingsville Fire Marshal Lupe Garcia,
soldiers cutting through a door in the old jail with a blowtorch
started a fire that spread beyond their control. ``It gutted the
room pretty well,'' Garcia said.
</P>
<P>
   The fire department, which according to fire chief Coronado
Garza had less than two hours' notice before the exercise, put out
the blaze in less than 20 minutes. Sanchez, the county emergency
management chief, said Kingsville police weren't alerted soon
enough to notify all of the surrounding businesses and residents.
And although city leaders approved of the exercise, he said county
officials were kept in the dark.
</P>
<P>
   ``It caused a little bit of bitterness and friction,'' he said.
``It's not what they did, it's how they did it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Army wasn't asked to pay for the damage to the old police
building because it was going to be torn down anyway, said Police
Chief Felipe Garza. But he and other officials said the Army
promptly paid the police and fire departments for their time.
</P>
<P>
   ``They paid cash money,'' said Garcia, the fire marshal. ``They
had a satchel ready to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Fanto, the U.S. Special Operations Command spokesman, said he
isn't sure whether the Army reimburses local officials for police
and fire services. ``I really don't know anything about that,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Garza said more than 50 citizens called 911, most of them
``inquiring just what the hell the noise was.'' In the following
days, Garza said he got more calls, this time from talk-radio shows
around the country wanting him to go on the air live to talk about
the operation. Internet sites sizzled with stories of U.S. soldiers
invading a small Texas town.
</P>
<P>
   ``Man, I've been on more radio talk shows,'' Garza said. He said
he tried to knock down the conspiracy talk, but he's not sure it
did any good.
</P>
<P>
   ``The alarmists will continue to sound the alarm, the Chicken
Littles will still see the sky fall, and the anti-military and
anti-government types will still be against the government,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Mixed welcome
</P>
<P>
   From Kingsville, the soldiersmoved on to the Corpus Christi
area, where they staged several days' worth of exercises, and to
Alice and finally San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   After watching Blackhawk helicopters dart over a former water
treatment plant, a refinery area, and Harbor Island, across the
water from his city, Corpus Christi Mayor Loyd Neal said he was
proud that the area could help soldiers hone their skills for
dangerous missions.
</P>
<P>
   Some citizens expressed concern about the maneuvers, but Neal
said the Army sent the commanding officer and an Army operations
specialist to speak at a city council meeting after the operation
began to give residents more information.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just glad that Corpus Christi, with its rich military
tradition, was selected for one of these sites,'' said Neal, a
retired Army colonel. ``As I told them, we'd be glad to have them
come back.''
</P>
<P>
   Port Aransas Mayor Glenn Martin was less enthusiastic.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was somewhat disturbing, since we didn't know they were
coming,'' Martin said of the Army's maneuvers on nearby Harbor
Island. ``But we had no problems, no damage. In this area, we're
used to military exercises.''
</P>
<P>
   In Alice, a city of 20,000, an exercise in an abandoned poultry
processing plant at the edge of town generated only three phone
calls, said Compton, the police chief. But when the helicopters
reached San Antonio Feb. 18, an old controversy was waiting for
them.
</P>
<P>
   The Army finished its operation at Fort Sam Houston, a military
base just northeast of downtown. Mayor Howard Peak said the Army
chose the base because he and the police chief had rebuffed an
earlier request to stage maneuvers in the city.
</P>
<P>
   In early 1998, Peak said, Army officials approached him about
training in San Antonio, but he refused to give his consent because
the Army would not divulge the details of the operation. At that
point, he said, ``they tried to go around us and offer money to
people for their support, which was very unfortunate.''
</P>
<P>
   Peak said Army officials offered to make donations to a City
Council member's favorite charity in order to win his support. The
council member, Mario Salas, told San Antonio reporters he rejected
the offer.
</P>
<P>
   Fanto said there was no such offer. ``We do not do business by
bribery or those types of things,'' Fanto said.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Peak said, the operation at Fort Sam Houston went
smoothly. San Antonio has a strong relationship with the military,
he said, but he will never consent to operations within the city.
</P>
<P>
   And what about Austin? City Manager Jesus Garza said he has
never heard of a request from the Army to conduct such drills here.
He said such a decision would be made by the City Council, with
input from the city's police and fire chiefs and emergency
management office.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-16-99 2216EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990416.0410 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-16 22:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2134 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TURNER-WILDLAND17-COX     04-16 2468
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TURNER-WILDLAND17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ted Turner and the West `as it was meant to be'
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Ted Turner has dreamed of bigger game ever since he
kept salamanders in a jar as a 5-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   Young Ted lay in bed some nights picturing 1,000 bison crossing
a grassy plain that stretched to the horizon.
</P>
<P>
   Fifty-five years later, Turner has 17,000 bison roaming on nine
ranches in the American West. The massive, shaggy-headed beasts
represent more than the fulfillment of a childhood dream.
</P>
<P>
   They are part of an ambitious and controversial effort to
restore a trampled and overgrazed American West to the glory it
knew in the days when the Sioux dominated the Great Plains. And,
ever the wily businessman who turned an outdoor advertising
business into a multibillion-dollar media company, Turner wants the
effort to pay for itself, if not turn a small profit.
</P>
<P>
   Not since Teddy Roosevelt and John D. Rockefeller, who at the
turn of the century bought millions of acres of wild land, has
anyone tried to save so much of the country's natural habitat.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nobody doing land conservation on that scale that
Turner is,'' says John Sawhill, president and chief executive of
the Nature Conservancy. ``He's really leaving a legacy. His efforts
will make a difference in the landscape for future generations.''
</P>
<P>
   Turner's ranches are about something deeply personal,
representing a lifelong pattern of searching for things that are
fun, challenging and part of a larger crusade.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm bringing back the old West, saving key pieces of the world
from development,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm doing it because I enjoy it. It's that simple. At some
point I'm going to retire, and I'm a very active person. These
ranches will give me something pleasurable to do,'' says Turner,
vice chairman of Time Warner Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ``Besides,'' Turner adds with his trademark wink, ``I've always
been a collector and the buffalo nickel was the favorite in my coin
collection.''
</P>
<P>
   Turner has rarely discussed his plan with anyone outside a close
circle of friends and family. But, as his operations have grown, he
feels the need to explain his goals out West. That's why an Atlanta
Journal-Constitution photographer and reporter spent several days
at one of his ranches _ the Vermejo Park Ranch in New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   While Turner has his supporters, many Westerners are suspicious.
They see him as some ``Hollywood'' outsider who doesn't understand
the West.
</P>
<P>
   Most ranchers would shoot the coyotes Turner keeps on his land.
And they resent his removing the fencing that long divided the West
into individual cattle pens.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's still a lot of skepticism by other ranchers,'' says
David Vacker, general manager of Vermejo Park Ranch, Turner's
largest single property. ``But a lot of them are coming by at least
to take a look at what we're doing.''
</P>
<P>
   What visiting ranchers see are tens of thousands of acres burned
black to clear the way for the restoration of native trees and
grass. If they're lucky, visitors might also see the wolves,
black-footed ferrets, bison and other endangered native Western
animals Turner is trying to reintroduce on his land.
</P>
<P>
   A family affair
</P>
<P>
   Turner is no stranger to controversy. It has dogged him since he
helped launch the cable TV industry in the early 1970s. But unlike
that effort, which made him a multibillionaire, his ranches and
environmental effort are a family affair. Two of his sons, Teddy
Jr. and Beau, are heavily involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're doing is the right thing to do with our ranches,
the right thing for the family and the right thing for the
future,'' says R.E. ``Teddy'' Turner Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Teddy Jr. and Beau, Turner's second- and fourth-born children,
serve as their father's right and left hands in running his
ranches. They are as different as a sports jacket is from a fishing
vest.
</P>
<P>
   Beau, 31, is the fishing vest. A towering, lean figure and an
expert hunter and fly fisherman, Beau is partial to worn pants and
hiking boots. He's a naturalist by training, and preservation ideas
burble from him like a stream flowing in mountains.
</P>
<P>
   But Beau is no backwoods recluse. It's his job to oversee all
his father's land and scout out new purchases. He takes his job
very seriously, spending most of his time traveling among his
father's ranches.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stewardship is everything,'' says Beau. ``Heck, bison could
ruin the land just as much as cattle if not handled right.'' He
wants his family's land to set an example.
</P>
<P>
   At the ranches, Beau works to keep everyone from the kitchen
help to managers enthusiastic and on task. His chief tools are
traits he inherited from Dad. He's got Turner's gruff laugh,
flashing smile and winning enthusiasm. And, like Dad, he's got a
hearty slap on the back for anyone within reach.
</P>
<P>
   Beau works his father as deftly as he does the ranch hands. He
wants him to keep buying land, saving it from the rapid
urbanization engulfing large parts of the West. And to save the
bison, Beau needs ever more land to support expanding herds.
</P>
<P>
   His environmental preservation interests aren't limited to the
West. He has recently considered land for his father to buy in
Alaska and Maine.
</P>
<P>
   Too much?
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, 35-year-old Teddy considers land purchases as part
of a bigger business calculation and worries his father is buying
too much of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know Beau sees Dad's legacy as protecting the land,'' Teddy
says. ``But I worry that we'll get in over our head. We can't sell
all the bison meat we have now.''
</P>
<P>
   Teddy's business sense is hard won, sharpened after years of
working for his father at Turner Broadcasting Corp. He left the
company after Time Warner bought it three years ago and is trying
to make it as an entrepreneur.
</P>
<P>
   Teddy likes to joke that he's the only Turner who carries a
Republican Party membership card in his wallet.
</P>
<P>
   About a year ago, Turner asked his son to rejoin him in business
but this time outside the company. He wanted Teddy to handle the
sales and marketing of his bison.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Teddy runs U.S. Bison Co., the marketing arm of his
father's bison effort, from Jacksonville. There, Teddy is one step
removed from a strong-willed father and minutes from the ocean and
sailing. An expert sailor like his father, Teddy draws his
inspiration from the sea _ not land.
</P>
<P>
   Despite their differences in opinion and style, Teddy and Beau
are close and speak fondly of each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing when you think about it,'' says Beau. ``My
family's one big circus, but we all find a way to get along.''
</P>
<P>
   One way they get along is by turning to Dad to settle
differences.
</P>
<P>
   Turner is concerned about both issues raised by his sons, money
and business.
</P>
<P>
   But his biggest worry is time, or the lack of it, to oversee his
ranching operations. The ranches already employ 200 people, a
number that swells with temporary workers during the peak warm
weather hunting and fishing seasons.
</P>
<P>
   As for buying more properties, Turner quips, ``At some point
we'll either run out of suitable land to buy or money.'' But that
time apparently hasn't arrived. ``If ranches are for sale that make
sense for bison, we will consider them,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Vermejo Park
</P>
<P>
   There's no better place to grasp the scope of Turner's effort
than at his largest ranch, Vermejo Park in northeastern New Mexico.
Shaped roughly like Italy, Vermejo's 588,000 acres sprawl from the
top of snowcapped mountains to rolling grassland. That's an area
equal to three-quarters the size of Rhode Island.
</P>
<P>
   Beau first heard about Vermejo, which once was owned by the
Pennzoil Co. of Houston.
</P>
<P>
   He wasted no time in flying out to see the ranch. Even he, used
to spectacular wilderness vistas, was stunned by the breadth of
Vermejo's beauty. ``I told Dad he just had to buy it,'' he recalls.
</P>
<P>
   Turner took his son's advice, buying the property for $80
million nearly three years ago. He bought it without seeing it
himself _ a testimony to both his harried schedule and the trust he
places in his son.
</P>
<P>
   When Turner showed up to inspect Vermejo, Beau wasn't there. ``I
was scared of what Dad would think when he saw it for the first
time,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   He needn't have worried. Turner grasped Vermejo's potential
immediately.
</P>
<P>
   From the footsteps of the main house on the ranch, he could see
elk grazing in a nearby meadow.
</P>
<P>
   Rising above the elk were dark-green foothills stretching out as
far as the eye can see. And above them towered the snowy jagged
peaks of the Sangre de Cristo Mountains 30 miles north.
</P>
<P>
   All that Turner saw belonged to him as part of the Vermejo
ranch.
</P>
<P>
   Given its diversity in terrain and wildlife, Vermejo was a great
testing ground for ideas about conservation. If restoration worked
here, it might work on other Turner properties.
</P>
<P>
   Vermejo's diversity encompasses the best and the worst of the
modern West. The best was the wide variety of wildlife and
vegetation represented at Vermejo.
</P>
<P>
   The ranch has an estimated 10,000 elk, 183 different kinds of
birds and 10,000 prairie dogs. There also are coyote, bear and
herds of fleet-footed antelope that flash like white and brown
minnows across the ranch's grassy plains.
</P>
<P>
   The wildlife at Vermejo is surprisingly accessible. A herd of
elk graze within eyesight of Turner's main residence, a mansion
called Casa Grande that's made from the land's native yellow
sandstone. Mule deer nibble grass at Casa Grande's footsteps. They
are not pets.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the house, prairie dogs bark in an adjacent meadow.
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, there are the bison. About 2,500 roam 65,000
acres, an area roughly eight miles by 15 miles, in the grassy boot
of Vermejo. It's a 35-mile drive from Casa Grande to the bison.
</P>
<P>
   Vermejo ranch manager Vacker is a scholar cowboy who has learned
to read the landscape like an archaeologist deciphering
hieroglyphics. Wearing a worn cowboy hat stained white from salty
sweat, he studies the softly rolling foothills of the ranch. Every
hill has a story to tell, and at Vermejo not every story is a
pretty one.
</P>
<P>
   Vacker points to some rotting stumps of yellow-belly pine that
litter the hills.
</P>
<P>
   At one time these trees, which can reach heights of 80 feet,
dominated the ranch. Then the pines were logged by the tens of
thousands.
</P>
<P>
   In the rotting wake of the yellow-belly pines rose up smaller
blackjack pines, which now darken the hills like thick weeds.
</P>
<P>
   Next Vacker points to one of the gullied riverbanks that
crisscross the landscape like weathered crow's-feet in an aging
cowboy's face. The gullies tell how grazing cattle denuded the land
of the natural grasses that held back the soil.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've learned from people more how not to do things than how to
do them right,'' says Vacker.
</P>
<P>
   Land restoration
</P>
<P>
   Vacker's mandate from the Turners is simple, if daunting. He
must wipe the landscape clean of man's influence. ``It's becoming
rarer and rarer to find areas absent of evidence of man,'' says
Vacker.
</P>
<P>
   This is a job that requires Vacker to be both politician and
forest ranger.
</P>
<P>
   Since January, for example, Vacker has burned 35,000 acres at
Vermejo.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is to clean out weedlike trees and grasses, making
space for the native species to again take hold.
</P>
<P>
   Gone, too, are animals Vacker considers unnatural and
destructive, including 7,000 head of cattle that grazed Vermejo
before Turner bought the ranch.
</P>
<P>
   The hope is that, without the insatiable cattle, denuded
riverbanks will again reseed with natural grasses.
</P>
<P>
   When Vacker sent the cattle packing he began dismantling the
ranch's 500 miles of barbed wire fencing. He's taken down 200 miles
of it so far, giving Vermejo a more open feel.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to put in a resilient ecosystem that can support
itself,'' he says. Wildlife restoration
</P>
<P>
   Plant life is only half the environmental equation for the
Turners. They also want to reintroduce endangered animal species
that once thrived in the West. Again, Vermejo and its bison are a
case in point.
</P>
<P>
   Turner isn't breeding bison like cattle, fencing them in and
herding them from grass lot to grass lot.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he lets his bison roam free. There are few fences
blocking their grassy range.
</P>
<P>
   The bison are just the start of wildlife restoration at Vermejo.
</P>
<P>
   In a project funded by Turner's Wildlife Foundation, Vermejo is
trying to breed endangered black-footed ferrets. They live in what
looks like a low-ceiling circus tent of black netting within the
bison's grassy home. If breeding succeeds, the ferrets will be
released onto the ranch for help in reining in the prairie dog
population.
</P>
<P>
   And, in the most controversial move, Turner would like to
reintroduce wolves to Vermejo. To do so, Turner needs state
permission and it won't be easy to get. ``Wolves remain an
emotional issue here,'' says Vacker. ``They still represent
something dark and dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   To win local acceptance of wolves, the Turners will have to
manage the people living around Vermejo as much as the land _ and
they know that.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't own this much land and not effect the people living
around you,'' says Beau. ``We want to be good neighbors.''
</P>
<P>
   At Beau's direction, the Turner family's various philanthropic
foundations have given money to some nearby towns. For example,
Raton, a town abutting the eastern corner of the ranch, received
$100,000 for youth activities.
</P>
<P>
   Vacker has also ringed the bison's domain with electric fencing.
``Bison are thought by many to be mangy marauders who will break
out of the range,'' explains Vacker. ``Not a single bison has
escaped but the fencing makes my neighbors happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Turning a profit
</P>
<P>
   Turner is not relying alone on bison to support his land. He's
also counting on big-game hunting, fly-fishing and something called
ecotourism. In layman's terms, ecotourism is observing wildlife,
not shooting it.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, the big moneymaker at Vermejo is game hunting.
Visitors, largely wealthy executives and celebrities, pay $10,000
to hunt on Vermejo. Guests have included Atlanta Braves player Ryan
Klesko and ABC anchor Sam Donaldson.
</P>
<P>
   Long term, Turner would like bison and ecotourism to become the
financial base of his land. Neither is close to meeting that goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're 50 years away from making ecotourism pay,'' says Vacker.
By then, Vacker figures, so much natural habitat will be gone that
people will pay a lot to see one of the few remaining vestiges of
the Wild West.
</P>
<P>
   Turner agrees. ``We're not going to turn my land into another
Disneyland or Animal Kingdom,'' he says. ``But it will be a place
that people can come and see the West as it really was, as it was
meant to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
