<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALAXY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ZAMBRANO NOT POPULAR IN CHICAGO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Chicago is not Los Angeles Galaxy coach Octavio Zambrano's
favorite town. Nor is it his favorite team.
</P>
<P>
   Zambrano has been harshly criticized since he mocked the Fire's
unattractive approach to the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Fire, of course, got the last laugh by sweeping the Galaxy
in the Western Conference finals, then winning the MLS championship
on Los Angeles' home field at the Rose Bowl with a stunning defeat
of two-time MLS champion D.C. United.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight, Zambrano sends his troops to Soldier Field. The Galaxy
(2-2, two points) meets Chicago (3-1, six points) for the first
time this season at 5 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Zambrano has since called Chicago the class of the Western
Conference. But it doesn't matter much because the Fire's fans will
never let him forget the words that became Chicago's motivation a
year ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never had a problem in this league, but when I said
Chicago was a team that only defended, I got an incredible amount
of bad print from the Chicago press for it,'' Zambrano said. ``It
seemed like I was saying something sacrilegious.''
</P>
<P>
   Zambrano hasn't changed his opinion of the style of play Chicago
used last season, but wishes he hadn't voiced it -- not because he
doesn't believe it, but because he thinks it may have been unfair.
</P>
<P>
   ``I shouldn't have said, for example, that someone should never
pay to see this team play,'' Zambrano said. ``That's not fair
because what we perceive as beauty in this game is different.
Whether I like or dislike that type of soccer, it shouldn't matter.
I should have kept it to myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Zambrano would be hard-pressed to accuse Chicago of
defending this season, especially since the Fire has a
league-leading 10 goals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
