<SLUG> BC-PUFFY-ARREST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAP SINGER PUFFY ARRESTED ON ASSAULT CHARGE
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By NEIL MacFARQUHAR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Sean Combs, a 29-year-old rap performer and producer,
was arrested Friday and charged with taking part in battering an
executive at Universal Records with a Champagne bottle, a chair and
a telephone.
</P>
<P>
   Known as Puffy, Combs surrendered to police at noon and was
charged with second-degree assault and criminal mischief. Two
others are still being sought in the attack. The assault charge can
carry a sentence of up to seven years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Law enforcement officials said they could not confirm the motive
for the attack, although it apparently involved a dispute over a
music video that Combs did not like.
</P>
<P>
   Police said Combs was one of three men who entered the Manhattan
office of Steven Stoute, 28, a rap producer, at 1755 Broadway
around 4:30 p.m. Thursday, beat him with several objects from his
office and damaged the room. The attack was recorded by security
video cameras in the office, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Stoute may have suffered a broken left arm in the attack, and
had extensive cuts, bruises and swelling on his head, arms, legs
and back, said Barbara Thompson, spokeswoman for the Manhattan
district attorney.
</P>
<P>
   Combs did not enter a plea in an appearance before Judge Troy
Webber of Manhattan Criminal Court. The judge set bail at $15,000,
which Combs paid immediately. He left the courtroom without
commenting to reporters, and his lawyer, Nicholas Kaizer, did not
return telephone calls.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Thompson said Combs had a criminal record, having been found
guilty in 1996 of criminal mischief after threatening someone with
a gun. He paid a $1,000 fine for that incident.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Stoute nor Juanita Stephens, spokeswoman for Combs and
the vice president for publicity at Bad Boy Entertainment, Combs'
record company, would comment yesterday on the attack.
</P>
<P>
   The rap business has a reputation for bloody attacks by
performers feuding with others in the industry. An editor at Blaze
magazine, which focuses on rap, was beaten by four men in his
Manhattan office in November in a dispute over a photograph
published by the magazine.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
