</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-N.Y.-IMMIGRANT-SUIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUIT SAYS IMMIGRATION SERVICE REJECTS WAIVERS FOR DISABLED
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By SUSAN SACHS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The federal Immigration and Naturalization Service
was accused in a lawsuit Friday of arbitrarily rejecting the
applications of disabled immigrants who seek exemptions from the
English language and civics parts of the citizenship exam.
</P>
<P>
   The class action suit asked the U.S. District Court in Manhattan
to require the agency to follow its own published guidelines for
evaluating disability waivers and to reconsider all the
applications it rejected over the last two years.
</P>
<P>
   Immigration officials, the lawsuit added, are ignoring the
guidelines and second-guessing the immigrants' own doctors.
</P>
<P>
   Under a 1994 law, immigration officers are required to
accommodate legal immigrants who are disabled and whose doctors
attest that their disabilities prevent them from demonstrating an
understanding of English and civics.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates for immigrants have complained for years about the way
the immigration service handles medical waivers. A similar class
action lawsuit accusing the agency of arbitrarily rejecting waiver
requests was filed last year in Florida against the agency's Miami
district.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers in New York City have reported cases in which
immigration officers had scolded disabled applicants for asking for
waivers, rejected applications without seeming to read them and
misleading immigrants on how to apply for waivers.
</P>
<P>
   Immigration officials in Washington recently acknowledged that
they have had difficulty administering the waivers and have
repeatedly revised policy guidelines for field workers who handle
applications.
</P>
<P>
   The latest INS guidelines for its field workers require them to
contact an immigrant's doctor if they have questions about the
application. The guidelines also caution them against
second-guessing the doctor and oblige them to give a reason in
writing for denying an application.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want them to follow their regulations,'' said Constance
Carden, a lawyer for the New York Legal Assistance Group in
Manhattan, which filed the lawsuit with the Hudson Valley Poverty
Law Center in White Plains, N.Y. ``If they would follow their own
policies, we'd find our clients are being fairly treated.''
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit cited the cases of two people. One is a Ukrainian
woman, Musya Krukier, 73, who became paralyzed after a stroke. She
submitted medical records and statements by several of her doctors
that she cannot learn and retain information. Her applications were
repeatedly denied. The lawsuit maintained the rejections were made
by officers who made medical conclusions they were unqualified to
make.
</P>
<P>
   The second case involves Teresa Riascos, 69, from Ecuador, who
lives in Ossining, N.Y. The lawsuit says that her waiver request
was not accepted, but that she was never given an explanation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-16-99 2239EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
