<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS TRY TO MAKE EDISON FIELD DUGOUTS SAFER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM BARRERO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; ANAHEIM, Calif. _ They're back.
</P>
<P>
   The Anaheim Angels returned home from their first road trip to
find padded railings in front of both dugouts at Edison Field.
</P>
<P>
   In the team's season opener, first baseman Mo Vaughn sprained
his left ankle when he fell into the visitor's dugout chasing a
foul ball, mostly because he didn't have a feel for how close the
steps were. Vaughn hasn't played since.
</P>
<P>
   But manager Terry Collins said Vaughn's mishap was not the
reason for the return of the railings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mo had nothing to do with it, Collins said. ``Line drives into
our dugouts had everything to do with it.
</P>
<P>
   After Anaheim Stadium was renovated back to a baseball-only
facility for the beginning of last season, the railings were in
place early in the year.
</P>
<P>
   But complaints from the dugout about not being able to see the
field action along with an inability to effectively relay signs
from the bench to base coaches were cited as the reasons why they
were removed.
</P>
<P>
   Collins said during this season's first homestand, pitcher Omar
Olivares was hit by a line drive in the dugout and that there had
been several other close calls.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys are too valuable to get hurt, Collins said. ``We've
decided the safety of the players is what we have to concern
ourselves with.
</P>
<P>
   Collins said even if the railings had been in place last week,
it likely wouldn't have mattered in Vaughn's situation since they
don't extend completely to each end of the dugout.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look to where it ends, Collins said of the railings,
``there wouldn't have been anything there anyway.
</P>
<P>
   (BOX) With questions still lingering about when Jim Edmonds
might return, the team's fourth outfielder, Orlando Palmeiro,
certainly has done all he can to keep production at a high level.
</P>
<P>
   Palmeiro hit .333 on the recent seven-game road trip, including
four RBIs and his first major league home run after 415 at-bate.
Palmeiro had three hits in Thursday's game at Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's as good a fourth outfielder as any team needs, Collins
said. ``He's done a great job.
</P>
<P>
   Collins said Palmeiro would have been in the lineup even more,
but that he wanted to get backups Jeff Huson and Tim Unroe some
much-needed at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   (BOX) Because the team is missing three regular starters,
Collins said he was pleased with the 5-5 record heading into
Friday's game.
</P>
<P>
   On the road trip, the Angels batted .342 with 23 doubles --
including 10 in one game against Texas -- seven home runs and 47
RBIs, averaging 7.6 runs per game.
</P>
<P>
   The pitching staff also was sharp during the trip, especially
the bullpen, which did not allow an earned run in 20 1/3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've played three good teams so far, Collins said of the
Cleveland Indians, Texas Rangers and Oakland A's. ``A lot of our
guys have played really well, so I'm happy.
</P>
<P>
   (BOX) The double-A Little League Field at Orchard Dale School in
Whittier will be rededicated as Darrin Erstad Field in a ceremony
this morning.
</P>
<P>
   Erstad donated $50,000 for renovations for two baseball fields
and Angels Care contributed another $30,000 for the project.
</P>
<P>
   Other supporters included the East Whittier City School District
and the Whittier Boys and Girls Club.
</P>
<P>
   (BOX) Pitching matchups for the remainder of the series: Tonight
-- Ken Hill (0-1, 7.56 ERA) vs. Freddy Garcia (2-0, 3.65 ERA);
Sunday -- Steve Sparks (0-2, 7.20 ERA) vs. Brett Hinchcliffe (0-0,
5.68 ERA).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
