<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-16 23:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2325 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PLANE-COMBAT-KAN &LR;      04-16 1202
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PLANE-COMBAT-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSH OF COMBAT ADRENALIN PUNCTUATES `SURREAL' MISSIONS FROM
MISSOURI 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT CANON  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KNOB NOSTER, Mo. _ This is wartime for the B-2 pilot: Golf one
day. Bomb Belgrade the next. Order pizza for the family the day
after that. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And the kids don't even know Daddy's been to war. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sure, there are the serious tasks of traveling to the other side
of the planet and back, of avoiding ground forces that want to blow
you out of the sky and of surviving 30 or so hours in a space the
size of a Honda. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But life at the controls of the world's most expensive aircraft
is an almost antiseptic experience, a test of skills far removed
from the death and destruction on the ground below. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``One of those surreal events,'' in the words of one pilot. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Before the United States joined NATO in Operation Allied Force,
the B-2 stealth bomber was a bit of a hangar queen _ an enormously
sophisticated $2 billion airplane that the Air Force brass had been
unwilling to risk near live fire. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   All that changed last month when a pair of B-2s became the first
Allied jets to head into the hostile skies over Yugoslavia and dump
loads of ``smart bombs'' on the most heavily guarded targets in
Serb territory. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Since then, said Brig. Gen. Leroy Barnidge of the 509th Bomb
Wing, B-2s have headed into combat overseas ``most nights...and
performed beyond our expectations.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, for the first time since the bombing campaign began,
two stealth bomber pilots from Whiteman Air Force Base talked about
flying the bat-winged behemoth in combat and waging war across the
ocean without setting foot on foreign soil. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, they said, the trips to Eastern Europe resembled
scores of training missions they'd flown before. Planning sessions
were followed by equipment checks followed by in-air refuelings
before dropping bombs and repeating the equipment checks and
refueling on the way home. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But it /{was/} different. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``If you see missiles in the air,'' said a major, ``you know
it's combat.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   They can see, as well, the fiery damage below of war, and they
can hear the excited conversations of their comrades in other
airplanes dodging their way through combat. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``You hear the chatter,'' said a captain, ``and the octaves
change.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (The two pilots spoke only on the condition that they not be
named. When pilots of other aircraft spoke on television shortly
after the war began, their families were flooded by hate mail over
the Internet from around the world. And after an F-117 stealth
fighter was shot down over Serbia, the longstanding tradition of
having pilots' names written on the sides of their aircraft came to
an end.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Flying the B-2 is like piloting no other aircraft in the world.
It was built for secrecy, not for speed. So it has none of the
yank-and-bank qualities that test the pilots of fighter jets or
even B-1 bombers. Trainers tell new B-2 pilots that rarely will
they have a handful of plane, but they will often have a brainful. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``You're a systems manager,'' the captain said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And an enormous system it is. Parked on a football field, it
would stretch from sideline to sideline. It is packed with the
latest in computer-designed technology designed to befuddle enemy
radar. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It has the ability to take two persons and 16 bombs anywhere
around the globe. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For most of their flights, a computer does the steering and a
system of computers linked by satellites guides the bombs to their
targets. Only during landings, takeoffs and the four in-air
refuelings on the Yugoslavia trips do pilots grab the controls. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything else is programmed ahead of time,'' the captain
said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For these Yugoslavia combat flights, pilots have been told of
their missions about a week in advance. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys like us,'' said the major, ``we train our whole careers
to do this. They can't help but be excited.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The days leading up to the long-distance war pass however the
pilots want. They can study the flight plan, practice guiding a B-2
in a simulator and change their sleep schedules to adjust for the
marathon trip. The major ran errands _ picking up a child from
school, heading to football practice _ the day before his first
combat. The captain hit the links. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Research performed at the Air Force Research Laboratory in Texas
for long-range bombing missions has given pilots clues about how
best to get ready. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest problem the pilots have is fatigue,'' said Bill
Storm, one of the researchers who has designed methods for dealing
with the long flights. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Air Force times different tasks on a mission _ topping the
plane's fuel tank, or dumping its payload _ with considerations of
when pilots become most groggy. They also have detailed advice
about what to eat and when. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   B-2 pilots take turns sleeping on the mission, snoozing in the
cramped space between the two seats and the plane's small toilet. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Each pilot packs his own meals. The slim major said he drinks
water by the gallon and charges himself with a cup of coffee 15
minutes before refueling. The equally trim captain _ the two have
not flown together _ chows with more abandon. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a junk food junkie,'' he said. He's fought this war while
guzzling liters of Mountain Dew and Coke, wolfing down tortilla
chips and shoveling in Hot Tamales candy. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I work up a good sugar high and keep it going until I crash
for a while and then get up and do it again,'' the captain said.
The result? The captain slept seven hours on his mission, and the
major less than three hours on his. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As for the scenery, ``you'd figure during a war they'd have the
lights off,'' the captain said. ``But (Serbia) was lit up as big as
Dallas.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Each plane carries 16 satellite-guided, 2,000-pound bombs, which
are released in quick clusters _ an open bomb bay can show up on
enemy radar below. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Then, pumped with adrenalin, they head for Missouri. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``You feel good when you get out of there safe,'' the major
said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The pilots' wives get telephone calls from Whiteman officials
once their husbands have cleared enemy air space and wait another
half day or more to see them. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew she was scared,'' the major said. ``She told me that
after she got the call she slept well.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Research shows pilots get drowsiest on the drive home. Some pass
the time reading magazines. Others try to nap. Often they chat
about high school days, about their plans for the next day, about
sports. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We talk about anything you would talk about sitting down with
a guy at a bar,'' the captain said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Once the wheels of their jets finally touched down on same
runway they lifted off from about 30 hours earlier, the pilots
headed for a few hours of briefing and then to their own beds. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After his mission, the captain slept 21/2 hours before spending
an evening at home with his wife and child. The major slept five
hours, had dinner delivered from Pizza Hut, helped his kids with
their homework and played a few hands of Uno. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   His next orders? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife told me I had to mow the lawn.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-16-99 2312EDT &QL; 
