<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CATTLE-DRIVE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONCE AGAIN, DRIVE TURNS DOWNTOWN KC INTO COWTOWN KC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE PENN  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Radio personality Mike Murphy majestically raised his arm
Friday, signaling the start of his fourth annual cattle drive
through downtown Kansas City. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Head 'em up, move 'em out. Let's go!'' Murphy yelled at
precisely 12:20 p.m. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But the cattle apparently didn't know that _ at least for today
_ this was a cow town again. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it was the chill in the air. Or maybe the animals were
spooked by the crowd in the River Market area. Or it could have
been a case of cattle contrariness. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But for several minutes the livestock sort of mingled among
themselves, lacking any drive whatsoever. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A woman in the crowd yelled: ``Isn't that cute. They won't
budge.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Then one animal became amorous, much to the amusement of some in
the crowd and the horror of others. Finally, one cow decided it was
show time and took off. About 50 others ambled behind. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   State Auditor Claire McCaskill tried to keep up on horseback. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great,'' said McCaskill, one of the ``cowpokes''
participating in the urban cattle drive. ``It (horseback) beats the
back of a car any time.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As the cattle paraded through downtown, roughly 1,000 people
paused to stare. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bob Faulkner, the operator of Benjamin Ranch, said cool weather
actually makes the cattle lively. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Someone in the crowd asked Faulkner whether it was OK to run in
front of the animals, as participants do during the running of the
bulls. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't advise it,'' Faulkner said. ``This ain't Spain.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As the cattle rounded a grassy median at Ninth and Main streets,
several stopped to smell the roses _ and eat them. But a cowboy
with a lasso coaxed them back on the road. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jan McCain watched the spectacle from a window inside Commerce
Bank. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is amazing,'' McCain said. ``This is the first
time I've seen cows in a city. They don't do this in Memphis, where
I'm from.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Miranda Goodwin of London, who was in Kansas City visiting a
friend, took time to cheer on the cattle. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen lots of things,'' Goodwin said. ``But I've never
seen anything like this before in my life.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the drive, the cattle were herded into a pen. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Former restaurateur Carl DiCapo said the cattle drive had a few
critics four years ago when it started. But now, DiCapo said, the
idea is spreading to other cities. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Kansas City's a leader,'' DiCapo said. ``You just see. One of
these days, this will be compared to the American Royal Parade.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
