<SLUG> BC-NY-POLITICAL-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN PARTISAN BUDGET BICKERING, LITTLE THINGS COUNT BIG 
GAY RIGHTS BILL ADVANCES 
STATEN ISLAND SECESSION DRIVE WANES
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ First it was a luge run. Then the Harlem Boys
Choir. What next?
</P>
<P>
   In this year's state budget stalemate, the Capitol's hoary
tradition of holding up the opposition's pet projects has descended
to new levels of minutiae. Such skirmishes have little to do with
the budget, but they neatly illuminate the animosity between Gov.
George Pataki, a Republican, and the assembly speaker, Sheldon
Silver, a Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Another late budget means a series of emergency appropriations
bills to keep the state running, and Pataki likes to slip unrelated
items into them, a back-door way to get what he wants.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes it works. Two years ago, he won changes in a
vehicle-emissions law by attaching the amendments to an emergency
spending bill. But this year, nothing so substantive is at stake,
and Democrats say the governor is using the insertions to embarrass
them.
</P>
<P>
   Tucked into the governor's first two-week emergency bill was $10
million for a luge run and two ski lifts to be used during next
year's Goodwill Games at Lake Placid. He proposed taking the money
from an environmental fund, which he knew the Democrats opposed.
</P>
<P>
   Silver declared that this year, no emergency spending bill would
pass with any extraneous elements. Pataki accused the speaker of
putting the games at risk. Democrats said the governor could
readily find the money elsewhere (which he did this week). For a
few days, there was the threat of a government shutdown, if the
Assembly refused to pass an emergency appropriation because the
bill included money for the luge run .
</P>
<P>
   Then the governor blinked, removing the luge and lifts from the
bill.
</P>
<P>
   But if Pataki's own pet projects could not crack the speaker's
hard line, what about an item dear to Democrats? This week, in a
new emergency bill, the governor included $60,000 for a trip to
Israel by the Harlem Boys Choir.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats accused the governor of trying to divide black
legislators from white ones. ``To make the Boys Choir of Harlem
political pawns in this game is awful, and he should be spanked,''
Assemblyman Keith Wright, a Harlem Democrat and chairman of the
Black and Hispanic Caucus said of the governor.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki professed surprise at the reaction. ``If it's a problem,
I'll take it out,'' he said, and he did.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, throughout this byplay, no progress toward a budget
was made.
</P>
<P>
   Gay Rights Bill Advances
</P>
<P>
   The Assembly's annual passage of a gay rights bill can seem like
an exercise in futility, but this year there are signs that the
sands beneath the issue are shifting after a long stalemate.
</P>
<P>
   The Legislature's lower house recently voted 105 to 43 for the
measure, compared with last year's 87-53 vote. Seven Republicans
switched their positions. In particular, Republicans from Nassau
County voted unanimously against the bill last year, but voted 5 to
2 for it this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just a sense that this was the right thing to do,''
said Assemblyman Thomas Alfano of Franklin Square, one of those who
switched.
</P>
<P>
   For a decade, the bill _ which would ban discrimination in
employment, housing and other fields _ has languished in the
Republican-controlled Senate. Last year, for the first time,
supporters were confident it could pass, but Majority Leader Joseph
Bruno would not allow a vote. No one has been so bold as to predict
that Bruno will relent this year, but the bill's supporters took
heart from recent events.
</P>
<P>
   New York Republicans have a long tradition of tolerant social
views, in keeping with a state where a fiercer brand of
conservatism does not play well. Pataki, who says he would sign the
gay rights measure, is from that mold.
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans also keep a wary eye on New York's Conservative
Party, which opposes abortion, gambling and gay rights. Republicans
in suburban swing districts often move to the right on social
issues to avoid a Conservative challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Republican legislators say the Conservative Party applied no
pressure on the gay rights vote, nor did Nassau County's powerful
Republican chairman, Joseph Mondello. Gay rights advocates say that
bodes well for winning more votes in the Senate, adding to the
pressure on Bruno.
</P>
<P>
   Staten Island Secession Drive Wanes
</P>
<P>
   The fires of Staten Island secession have been banked, thanks to
years of attention and pork from a governor and a mayor, Rudolph
Giuliani, who owed their elections in part to ``the forgotten
borough.''
</P>
<P>
   Cityhood for Staten Island is the longest of long shots, opposed
by Silver, Giuliani and New York City Council Speaker Peter
Vallone. Recent polls have shown that a majority of Staten
Islanders no longer support secession, a sharp turnabout from a few
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But state legislators from the borough refuse to give up on the
idea _ in fact, they dare not. ``At any time, something could
happen to get people worked up about it again,'' said an aide to
one of those lawmakers. ``You don't want to be the guy who let it
drop.''
</P>
<P>
   Assemblyman Robert Straniere, a Republican, reintroduced a
secession bill this year, though it has no chance of passage.
</P>
<P>
   And the island's legislators appear to have saved the most
visible expression of the secessionist movement, the Staten Island
Charter Commission.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
