<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIR AND LIGHT: HELPING A CITY KEEP ITS SOUL 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By DAVID GONZALEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Fred Kent walked toward Seventh Avenue along West
43rd Street, pausing in midstride to enjoy _ nothing. He beheld the
intersection's southwest corner, where a building had been razed
months earlier to create _ for now _ an open space. Kent could see
the tip of the Empire State Building looming elegantly beyond.
Standing on 43rd Street, he could actually get an unusual panoramic
view of the buildings and billboards.
</P>
<P>
   Better yet, he could feel the space.
</P>
<P>
   ``It changes everything, doesn't it?'' he said. ``It doesn't get
any better than this.''
</P>
<P>
   Right on both counts. The space on the corner is as temporary as
it is serendipitous. Bulldozers and dump trucks are already
rumbling into it, as the foundation is laid for a new office
building for Reuters. The tower will join another building across
the street for Conde Nast magazines.
</P>
<P>
   This will attract thousands of office workers to the area, who
will have to cram themselves into the throngs of tourists who have
descended upon the sanitized Times Square.
</P>
<P>
   The construction and crowds bode well for the economy, but those
developments worry Kent. He is the president of the Project for
Public Spaces, a New York group that designs urban oases in parks,
waterfronts and squares.
</P>
<P>
   Often, creating people-friendly areas means making them
pedestrian-friendly. He thinks that notion has been lost in the
remade Times Square. As a result, even the unexpected open space on
43nd Street seems out of place.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seeing this is like, God, we need light and air,'' he said.
``We have it here, but we don't even plan to use it. Everything is
so damn crowded, you feed suddenly awkward, and you can't enjoy the
openness you feel when a building is taken out. If the street is
not changed to compensate for the excessive density, it's going to
lose its allure. The street has been transformed, but it has not
changed to handle all the pedestrians.''
</P>
<P>
   Taking his cue from planners in Zurich and Copenhagen, Kent
suggested reducing the traffic flowing through Times Square. Right
now, cars are almost always stacked up at a choke point near 46th
Street, as the eight lanes of Broadway and Seventh Avenue feed into
five lanes.
</P>
<P>
   Traffic usually eases after the cars pass through the choke
point. Kent suggested moving the point further north, which he said
would open up more space around the pedestrian islands that include
the always packed TKTS booth.
</P>
<P>
   Choke point is a fitting term for the crushing experience that
would make any sane person want to strangle the urban designers who
dreamed up the current layout.
</P>
<P>
   Like many of his fellow New Yorkers intent on dodging the
tourists, watch sellers and turbaned preachers on the sidewalk,
Kent walked in the street, close to the gutter. On one pedestrian
island, several dozen teen-agers posed for a class picture. He
walked past them, cutting diagonally across the street, where he
caught the attention of a police officer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't let him go that way,'' one officer yelled to his partner
as he tried to wave Kent back to the crosswalk. ``The sidewalk's
open.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe in some parallel universe. The one Kent tried to walk on
was filled with teeny-boppers shouting up to their idols in the MTV
studios. Not an inch was open. The street, in contrast, had few
cars and lots of open space.
</P>
<P>
   There is just too much excess capacity in the roadway here,''
Kent said. ``If we moved up the choke point, we could double the
size of the islands and widen the sidewalk. It doesn't take a
genius. If you look at this now, you know there's something wrong
with this picture. Traffic engineers don't think about it. They
think about moving cars through a given space. But is the role of
the city to absorb more automobiles, or to create wonderful public
spaces?''
</P>
<P>
   Weed out the traffic, widen the walkways and the square will be
there. He is trying just that in Astor Place, where he has been
enlisted by administrators at Cooper Union to revamp the public
spaces around the college. Some streets may be closed, others might
be redrawn to accommodate shoppers, markets and restaurants. He is
even talking about expanding the small park just south of the
college.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you put a park in a square, that's exciting,'' Kent said.
``You have quiet open space and active green space.''
</P>
<P>
   Then a space has a special place.
</P>
<P>
   ``It goes to here,'' Kent said, pointing to his heart. ``You're
talking about soul. Does a place have a soul?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
