<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATTORNEYS-ADS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWYERS GROUP MAKES TV ADS TO TOUT PRO BONO WORK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SCOTT SUNDE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Did you hear the one about the group that bought
$25,000 in television advertising to convince the public that
honorable, saintly lawyers walk among us?
</P>
<P>
   It's no joke.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning Monday and running through mid-May, a 30-second spot
that promotes free legal work done by members of the King County
Bar Association will appear. The advertisement will run 300 times,
mostly on cable TV programs.
</P>
<P>
   It's the first time the county bar group has tried this
approach, said Linda Strout, association president. And it may be
the first time that any bar group has taken to the airways to
polish the profession's image, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The bar group hopes the ads will spur more lawyers to take on
pro bono work. The lawyers' code of professional responsibility
urges them to offer free advice and work to the poor. About 1,200
of the bar association's 5,200 members did that last year,
providing $2 million in free services. That represents a small
percentage of the total billings lawyers had in King County last
year.
</P>
<P>
   But the group also wants to begin to change the public's
attitude about lawyers, Strout said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public has come away with an image of lawyers as being
very sleazy, self-aggrandizing and interested only in money,''
Strout said.
</P>
<P>
   After all, who hasn't heard a lawyer joke? (Why didn't the shark
eat the lawyer who fell in the ocean? Professional courtesy.)
</P>
<P>
   Television programs and movies portray lawyers as rapacious,
sex-crazed or addle-brained. One recent film even featured Satan
himself as a member of the bar.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems to us that more and more lawyers are portrayed in
negative ways,'' Strout said. ``And we know that isn't really true
and that lawyers are really good people. That side of the story
isn't told.''
</P>
<P>
   Focusing on pro bono legal work was easy. Such volunteer
programs are ``the heart and soul of the King County Bar
Association,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not a social club. We have been doing pro bono work for
years.''
</P>
<P>
   About 7,000 people received pro bono work from bar association
members last year. The clients have to have incomes that are no
more than 125 percent of federal poverty levels. The free work is
for civil legal problems. Poor people who face criminal charges get
lawyers provided at public expense.
</P>
<P>
   The ad is very different from the lawyer come-ons television
viewers are used to. There's no promise to exact revenge on the
driver who gave you whiplash or the boss who sent you up that
wobbly stepladder.
</P>
<P>
   This one uses the words of Seattle-area lawyers Rick Spoonemore
and Lisa Schuchman as ``voices of justice'' who talk about their
pro bono work. It was filmed in a courtroom in King County Superior
Court with a real judge portraying himself and Strout acting the
part of an attorney.
</P>
<P>
   Strout said she doesn't expect the ad will change people's
attitudes over night. ``We hope they might say, `The King County
Bar Association's pro bono program _ what's that all about?'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
