<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-16 23:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2337 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLA-FIRES17-COX     04-16 1710
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-FIRES17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    48 homes fell to blazes
 &HT;    By Teresa Lane,Brian D. Crecente and Jenny Staletovich/Palm
Beach Post Staff Writers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT ST. LUCIE, Fla. _ Nobody wanted to look when the sun came
up Friday.
</P>
<P>
   A night of wildfires had visited their neighborhood and marched,
in no particular order, across seven square miles, wiped out 48
homes and damaged another dozen. Returning home was like rolling
dice.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a bad dream and I haven't woke up yet,'' Juan
Echazabal, 43, said as he shoveled through ash that used to be his
house.
</P>
<P>
   Up and down the winding streets of this community, neighbors
returned to find a checkerboard of destruction in the worst fires
to burn St. Lucie County in memory. About 300 became homeless
overnight.
</P>
<P>
   Some houses stood intact. Some had lawns burned to within inches
of the front door. Yet others were simply flattened. A swingset in
one yard was untouched; the house was gone. In another lot, only
concrete lawn furniture, a hot-water heater and the charred frames
of metal kitchen appliances remained.
</P>
<P>
   Once woody lots, thick with pine and Brazilian pepper, became a
winter landscape, blackened like a film negative. Instead of snow,
ash blanketed the ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do you grab when your whole life is in that house?'' Don
Kranker asked. Weeping, he hugged his neighbor and explained that
when firefighters ordered him to leave, he stayed behind armed with
a garden hose to save his house. It survived.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had no defense. I just didn't think I was going to make
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Pete Bordon, the county's radio coordinator, after a tour
of the worst-hit streets: ``I see burned homes, burned property,
peoples' lives devastated by fire. People's memories, their days
here totally destroyed. It's unbelievable what I see.''
</P>
<P>
   Rescue workers, forest rangers and homeowners began the
monumental task of cleaning up and starting over as Gov. Jeb Bush
toured the area Friday evening. Bush said he will meet with
forestry officials today to determine how much money to request
from President Clinton. Property appraisers and Federal Emergency
Management Agency officials also began tallying the loss, but
probably won't have a total for several days, said County
Administrator Doug Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   What caused the fires remains unanswered.
</P>
<P>
   The first sign came about 3 p.m. Thursday when smoke was
reported near Gatlin Boulevard. Another fire burned the day before
off Gatlin Boulevard, prompting speculation that it was never
entirely extinguished and reignited. But Ron Parrish, spokesman for
the St. Lucie County Fire District, said Thursday's fire occurred
at least a half mile away, too far to be the same blaze. The
district, along with an arson strike force recently created by the
state, will investigate what they suspect was not caused by nature.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't have lightning here, so we have to look into the
many ways man can cause fire,'' said Division of Forestry spokesman
Gene Madden. ``Fire is one of the most difficult things to go to a
spot and say, `Ah-hah.' ''
</P>
<P>
   No matter how it started, fire officials know what kept it
going. And keeping up was like racing the wind.
</P>
<P>
   With gusts of 30 mph, no amount of equipment, either tractors
plowing fire lines or helicopters raining water, could control the
fire, said Senior Forester Dale Armstrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't even imagine the equipment you'd need to knock that
out,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For those who watched raging fires ignite parts of Volusia and
Flagler counties in the worst conflagration of last year's wildfire
season, Thursday's were eerily familiar. Eventually, 500,000 acres
burned last year and 370 structures were damaged or destroyed. Fire
officials had hoped the fires would provide a lesson, and help
fatten their budgets. But so far, that hasn't happened.
</P>
<P>
   No fire hydrants
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Agriculture asked Bush for a $125.2 million
budget hike, but the governor slashed its request to $223.4
million. The legislature is considering a bill that would provide
$13.2 million for helicopters, pilots, strike teams and other
equipment.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we need to put more in there, we'll do that,'' said Rep.
Ken Pruitt (R-Port St. Lucie), a House budget chairman whose family
was evacuated Thursday. Pruitt, and U.S. Rep. Mark Foley (R-West
Palm Beach) traveled with Bush on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not so much concerned about the direct amount as getting
the resources there now,'' Pruitt said.
</P>
<P>
   But Democrats spotted some irony, especially after Republican
leaders approved a whopping $1 billion tax break Thursday, the
biggest in state history.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are providing millions of dollars in big breaks to big
business while our citizens watch their homes burns,'' said Rep.
Les Miller (D-Tampa), whose side of the state ignited in March when
thousands of acres near Naples burned.
</P>
<P>
   But on Friday, the state continued to dump manpower and
equipment onto the Port St. Lucie fire. To help out the more than
60 county firefighters working the fire _ altogether 150 from the
county were on duty overnight _ the state sent five brigades with
15 fire trucks to the area. A National Guard Blackhawk helicopter,
carrying a ``Bambi bucket'' holding 750 gallons of water, continued
to patrol Friday morning. Two P-3 Orions airplanes from Brooksville
and Tallahassee were also on hand.
</P>
<P>
   In retracing their steps and trying to explain what happened,
county and fire officials said several elements factored into the
equation, the same elements that create every significant fire:
drought, wind and thick vegetation.
</P>
<P>
   Only one third of the 80-square-mile city is developed, meaning
many lots remain empty, but heavily wooded.
</P>
<P>
   ``For us to take care of all these lots, would be impossible,''
said Mayor Jim Fielding. ``If it was reversed, if 70 percent were
built out and 30 percent empty, we might have a better shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Add to that an absence of water and sewer lines that could
provide hydrants. The city had planned to install the lines, but
was delayed two years by lawsuits, Fielding said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope those people who stood up several years ago and fought
the city tooth and nail _ we don't need water, we don't need sewer
_ are reading the newspapers now,'' said Deputy City Manager Victor
Granello.
</P>
<P>
   County Commissioner John Bruhn, chairman of the county fire
district, who raised the issue several weeks ago, has asked the
county attorney to draft an ordinance requiring hydrants in the
area.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't believe they built a whole neighborhood without fire
hydrants,'' said Glen Abraham, who fought back flames with a garden
hose. ``It was very frustrating. The entire neighborhood was on
fire and we never saw any firefighters.''
</P>
<P>
   Ill wind blew no good
</P>
<P>
   That's because every firefighter was fighting a fire that blazed
across 2,400 acres, Parrish said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were very stretched as far as apparatus goes. I was getting
calls at the dispatch center from people standing in front of their
homes, watching them burn. It was very difficult. I was sitting in
the communications center and I kept thinking, `This is not us.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Still, while the lack of hydrants may have angered owners of
burning houses, Parrish said water really wasn't the issue. Wind
was.
</P>
<P>
   Several weeks ago, county officials declared a state of
emergency as drought conditions worsened. About two hours before
the fire, state officials warned them to be on alert. Anderson
said. Almost immediately after arriving at Thursday's fire,
firefighters called for help from Martin and Indian River counties.
Palm Beach and Broward counties soon joined. When foresters _
already on edge by weeks of fierce fire conditions _ arrived, they
called in air support, diverting helicopters working other fires in
South Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the past month, we've had several large fires around the
state. Some, as large as 10,000 acres. But they were in remote
areas,'' Madden said. ``This is the most significant in a while.''
</P>
<P>
   With wind gusts from the south and southwest spreading fires
rapidly, workers dug in. Communications quickly became a problem
because each agency involved _ county firefighters, foresters,
deputies, city police and Florida Highway Patrol troopers _ worked
off a different radio frequency. Still, even if everything had gone
as planned, controlling the blaze would have been futile, Madden
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``No fire department, no fire personnel, is going to be able to
get in front of (a wind-driven fire) and stop it. Mother Nature
started that and Mother Nature stopped it.''
</P>
<P>
   The fires weren't fully controlled until early Friday, said
Forestry Division ranger Craig Iversen. Only one small fire in the
area flared Friday. Several other smaller brush fires in the county
also ignited.
</P>
<P>
   That was no comfort to homeowners.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just finished building the house ourselves,'' Polly Trimble
said as she stood outside a Kmart she visited Friday morning to buy
new clothes and other items her family lost when fire razed her
house on Gabor Court. ``My husband slaved over it for a year and I
did the tile work. Now it's all gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Everywhere, people struggled to comprehend the destruction.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like Mount Saint Helens went through here,'' said
Chrystal Perkins as she drove down one particularly bad street.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's actually my anniversary and it will be six years because
we moved here when we got married,'' said Kathy Federico, whose
house was destroyed. ``We slept on the floor. We had nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   By afternoon Friday, 42 families had applied for disaster aid at
the Red Cross shelter in the city's community center. Businesses
and residents from four counties dropped off boxes of diapers,
toothbrushes and blankets. Others left money. So much food was
available that many carried cartons of bread, fruit and bottled
drinks home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got a stack of checks and cash _ enough that it makes me
uneasy,'' said the Red Cross' Hillery Brown. ``The community
outpouring has been overwhelming.''
</P>
<P>
   Staff writers Noah Bierman, Thomas R. Collins, Jim Reeder, Lady
Hereford, Mary Ellen Klas and David Lane contributed to this story.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
