<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MOB-GIGANTE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIGANTE'S LAWYERS SAY JURORS IMPROPERLY DISCUSSED HIS CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JOSEPH P. FRIED   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Lawyers for imprisoned Mafia boss Vincent Gigante say
they will seek to overturn his conspiracy-to-murder and
racketeering convictions because they have evidence that the jurors
at his 1997 trial improperly discussed the case among themselves
throughout the trial.
</P>
<P>
   The judge had instructed the jurors, who heard the case in U.S.
District Court in Brooklyn, not to discuss the testimony and
arguments until deliberations had begun, a standard instruction
that is intended to keep jurors from forming and exchanging
conclusions before all the evidence is in.
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer for Gigante said that to gather the evidence of juror
misconduct, his client's relatives hired a private investigator
who, several months after the trial had ended, secretly recorded
conversations with a private security guard who had been hired by
the government to drive jurors between their homes and the
courthouse. The lawyers said the driver, Alfred Santoro, was
recorded on tape saying that the jurors discussed details of the
case long before deliberations began.
</P>
<P>
   Gigante's relatives hired the investigator, Raymond Glynn, after
the lawyers learned that Santoro had described the jurors'
discussions to other people, one of the lawyers said.
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer for Glynn made available Friday what he said were
transcripts of some of the recorded conversations, in which Santoro
spoke with Glynn or with an associate of his.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the conversations, said to have taken place two and a
half months after Gigante was convicted in July 1997, Santoro says
the four jurors he had been driving each day told him that all 12
jurors, as well as the six alternate jurors, had discussed the
evidence during recesses throughout the trial, according to the
transcript.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is what they were telling me afterwards,'' Santoro says,
according to the transcript. ``Most of the 18 jurors were listening
to one of the alternates.''
</P>
<P>
   That alternate, Santoro says, ``was the one that spoke up and
spoke to the other 17 jurors, and everybody was agreeing with
him.''
</P>
<P>
   In the transcript, Santoro says he was told that this alternate
juror believed that the evidence was not sufficient to convict
Gigante, and that the other jurors and alternates were going along
with him. ``They were saying: `Yeah, you're right, John, you're
right. I agree with you on that, I agree with you on that point,''
Santoro says.
</P>
<P>
   Santoro says that when the alternates were dismissed just before
deliberations began, the alternate juror known as John was no
longer there to exercise his influence, according to the
transcripts, and Gigante was convicted.
</P>
<P>
   And in what was said to be a transcript of another conversation
_ on Oct. 23, 1997, three months after the conviction _ Santoro is
quoted as describing a conversation among the four jurors during
the third or fourth week of the trial.
</P>
<P>
   He said the conversation touched on a central question of the
trial: Had Gigante been mentally ill for a long time and incapable
of having been the boss of the powerful Genovese crime family, as
his defense maintained, or had he long been faking insanity,
employing a zombielike act during the trial, as the prosecution
contended?
</P>
<P>
   In the transcript of the recorded conversation, Santoro says:
``They looked at his face, the jurors in my car. One woman said,
`Jesus, his face, his expression, no expression.'''
</P>
<P>
   Santoro then describes the response of a male juror in the car,
quoting him as saying, `` `Sometimes I saw him and his eyes looked
like they, they were alert.''' He said the juror added, `` `He
looked like he was aware of what was going around him.'''
</P>
<P>
   Steven Kartagener, a lawyer for Gigante, who is 70 and is
serving a 12-year sentence in a federal prison in Minnesota, said
he would argue at a hearing on Thursday that Judge Jack Weinstein
should question all the jurors about what Santoro says was their
improper behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Dorsky, an assistant U.S. attorney in Brooklyn, declined
to comment, and Santoro could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Kuby, the lawyer for Glynn, the private investigator,
expressed concern that prosecutors would accuse his client of
wrongdoing as they try to ``defend Gigante's conviction.''
</P>
<P>
   Weinstein could order a new trial, could decide that Santoro or
the taped conversations are not credible, or could decide that even
if the jurors discussed the case as Santoro says, that did not
taint their verdict.
</P>
</TEXT>
