<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-TIGERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKS ARE MAULED BY TIGERS, 8-1 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Orlando Hernandez came to this country 13 months ago,
knowing little English beyond the names of baseball teams. He
conducted his first full postgame interview in his second language
Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``No control fastball,'' Hernandez said, shrugging his
shoulders. ``No control. Next time, maybe.''
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez was far more remarkable and accurate with his
splintered sentences than he had been on the mound in the New York
Yankees' 8-1 loss to the Detroit Tigers. It was the second
consecutive defeat for the Yankees, who once again performed
terribly on defense.
</P>
<P>
   Friday evening was not a total loss: Hideki Irabu, aided by an
adjustment in the way he uses his back foot in his delivery, threw
three perfect innings, striking out four, and Derek Jeter slugged
his fourth home run.
</P>
<P>
   The Tigers took an early and prohibitive lead by taking
advantage of Hernandez's wildness. Last Sunday, the Yankee pitcher
threw a perfect game for six and one-third innings against Detroit,
blowing on his hands before each pitch in the 44-degree conditions
at Yankee Stadium. The temperature in Tiger Stadium this evening
again was 44 degrees, but it seemed much colder; rain had fallen
here most of the day, and wind whirled within the high walls of
this aging park.
</P>
<P>
   With his breath leaving his mouth in clouds, Hernandez blew on
his hands before and after each pitch, even as the catcher Joe
Girardi flipped the ball back to him. Hernandez, who was raised in
Cuba's tropical climate, prefers warmer weather, and there were
suggestions that Friday night the cold may have gotten to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, it was no problem,'' Hernandez said.
</P>
<P>
   There was evidence to the contrary. Hernandez, who walked four
batters in his first two starts, walked two and hit another in the
first inning, giving up four runs, including an unearned run after
Jeter dropped a pop fly. Gregg Jefferies smashed a two-run homer in
the second, and in the fourth, Hernandez surrendered a triple, walk
and double, wrapped around a throwing error by Girardi.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez, Girardi said, ``Never really looked comfortable, from
the start.''
</P>
<P>
   In the first eight games, Yankee starters compiled a 1.51 earned
run average. But over the last two games, Roger Clemens and
Hernandez have been charged with 14 earned runs in eight innings.
</P>
<P>
   With the Tigers running away after five innings, the Yankees'
interim manager Don Zimmer attempted to salvage some good from the
evening by inserting Irabu. The Yankees now are at least exploring
the idea of trading Irabu, and after he allowed five runs in
one-third of an inning against Baltimore on Wednesday, club
officials kept him in the major leagues, where he can re-establish
his value in relief appearances.
</P>
<P>
   Irabu affected a minor change in his delivery in the last two
days: Rather than keep his back foot flat as he pushes off the
rubber, he perched high on the front part of his foot, as if he was
catapulting himself toward home plate.
</P>
<P>
   The game essentially was over by the time Irabu took the mound
in the sixth, and Irabu has always done well against the
free-swinging Tigers. Nonetheless, Irabu did throw the ball much
better, striking out Bobby Higginson and Damion Easley and two
others in his three innings. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
