<HEADER>
A2354 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-DEVILS-FLYERS-NYT     04-16 0623
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DEVILS-FLYERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEVILS SHOOT DOWN FLYERS, 3-2 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ALEX YANNIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ The New Jersey Devils' regular season
finale Saturday night in Nashville will have double significance. A
victory would capture first place in the Eastern Conference and
break Montreal's record for road victories in a season.
</P>
<P>
   This scenario was set up after Friday night's 3-2 overtime
triumph over the Philadelphia Flyers at Continental Arena put the
Devils (46-24-11) one point over the Ottawa Senators (44-23-14),
the team that eliminated the Devils in the first round of last
year's playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Terreri proved again why he has dominated the Flyers like
no other Devils' goaltender. Even though he made his first start in
seven games, Terreri displayed glimpses of brilliance, turning
aside 27 shots, including two in the overtime.
</P>
<P>
   ``T-bone played great,'' coach Robbie Ftorek said. ``He made
some big saves for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Terreri can be a pivotal man for the Devils in the playoffs. His
strength is coming off the bench after a long spell and still be
sharp. He played with inspiration Friday night and instilled
confidence in his teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt good out there,'' said Terreri, whose reord against the
Flyers as a member of the Devils is 18-5-2. ``I feel good playing
against them. this was an intense game from start to finish.''
</P>
<P>
   Terreri's cannot be blamed for Philadelphia's goals. He was
screened by Ken Daneyko on the goal by Keith Jones with 2 minutes
37 seconds left in the second, and he was left at the mercy of
Mikael Renberg's goal 6:38 into the third period.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Rolston scored the first goal for the Devils and Bobby
Holik scored twe last two goals, including the winner with 1:33
left in the overtime, when he took a pass from randy McKay,
streaked down the right wing and beat John Vanbiesbrouck between
the 5-hole for his 26th of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had more chances than they did and it always feels good in
the overtime,'' Holik said. ``We believe we're at a level we can do
things.''
</P>
<P>
   Captain Scott Stevens put in perspective the Devils' aspirations
of finishing first in the Eastern Conference and breaking
Montreal's record for most victories on the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have control of our own destiny,'' Stevens said. ``It's in
our hands, and it is an opportunity for us to finish first in the
conference and also break the road record.''
</P>
<P>
   After Ottawa's 2-2 tie with the Rangers on Thursday night, the
Devils have an excellent chance of finishing first in the Eastern
Conference and gain the home advantage throughout the conference
playoffs with a victory at Nasville.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not thinking in terms of winning the conference,''
Stevens said. ``All we've been thinking is try to finish as high as
we can.''
</P>
<P>
   Stevens appeared more concerned about breaking the record for
most victories on the road rather then finishing first in the
conference. The Devils finished first in the conference the last
two seasons, but they never came close to breaking the record for
most victories on the road.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that the Montreal Canadiens set the record of 27
victories on the road in their dynasty years in the late 1970s has
been extra motivation for the Devils to break the record.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good that we've tied them,'' Stevens said about the 27th
victory the Devils accomplished with the triumph in Buffalo two
nights ago. ``Now, we want to win it outright.''
</P>
<P>
   Stevens echoed the sentiments of the rest of the Devils about
their desire to break Montreal's record that was set in 1976-77 and
repeated a year later.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very hard to get to this point again,'' Stevens said.
``That's why we want to do it.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-16-99 2338EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
