<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATAKI-NH-KOSOVO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATAKI CRITICIZES CLINTON ON KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By RAYMOND HERNANDEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILFORD, N.H. _ Testing a foreign-policy theme in his second
political trip to New Hampshire in less than a month, New York Gov.
George Pataki criticized President Clinton's policies on Kosovo,
saying they had ``raised the risk of trouble in the Balkans.''
</P>
<P>
   In a warmly received speech at the Veterans of Foreign War Post
4368 here, Pataki said the president had failed to accomplish three
of his main goals in the region: protecting the people of Kosovo,
preventing the ``destabilization' of the Balkans and weakening
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   ``What have his policies done?'' Pataki asked a gathering of
about 75 people. `Instead of preserving the life and the shelter of
the Kosovars, we have seen hundreds of thousands forced out.
Instead of stabilizing the Balkans, his policies have created
instability in places like Macedonia, and raised the risk of
trouble in the Balkans. And instead of weakening Milosevic, he has
united the Serbian people around Milosevic.''
</P>
<P>
   Pataki added, ``I think it's tragic that we have not achieved
those goals, honorable as those goals were.''
</P>
<P>
   Pataki's appearance here Friday was part of a series of speeches
around the country in recent months intended to bolster his
national presence.
</P>
<P>
   As in his previous speeches, the governor, who has been
mentioned as a possible candidate for the Republicans' national
ticket next year, emphasized his credentials as an effective tax
cutter and crime fighter. But his comments tonight represented the
first time he has ventured into foreign policy on one of his
political trips.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's trip was his second to New Hampshire, the site of the
nation's first presidential primary. Pataki is among a growing list
of candidates who have traveled here to woo voters: this weekend
alone, two Republican presidential hopefuls _ former Vice President
Dan Quayle, and Rep. John Kasich of Ohio _ are swinging through the
state while Vice President Gore is scheduled to visit nearby Keene,
Salem, Bedford and Manchester.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
